<HEADLINE>
RANGERS STARTING PITCHERS ARE A SPRING EYE-OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Four Rangers pitchers combined to shut
out Baltimore yesterday, the latest in a series of pitching
performances that have helped pull this camp out of an early
malaise.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Oliver, Jeff Zimmerman, Ryan Glynn and Joaquin Benoit
combined on a three-hitter as the Rangers beat the Orioles, 2-0,
for their third consecutive victory after a 3-7 start.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have given up three runs in those three victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how your emotions can go up and down,'' manager
Johnny Oates said. ``Three days ago, I wasn't very happy. We
weren't throwing strikes, and we were making errors. Now we're the
best thing since sliced bread.''
</P>
<P>
   Darren Oliver pitched 41/3 hitless innings, indicating again
that the Rangers' starting pitching has been one of the best things
about the camp. The Rangers' starting five of Oliver, Kenny Rogers,
Rick Helling, Esteban Loaiza and Mark Clark has a combined
earned-run average of 2.63.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to see,'' first baseman Rafael Palmeiro said. ``It
gives you confidence when you have guys who can shut down the other
team like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Dick Bosman said: ``I like the attitude, and I
like the way they're throwing the ball over \Rthe plate\S. The
attitude is one of aggression. We're good, let's be good, let's act
like it, and let's perform like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, as good as the pitching has been, three nagging injuries
and three other issues need to be addressed before the Rangers
break camp in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The injuries of most concern are to relievers John Wetteland and
Mike Venafro, and outfielder Rusty Greer. Wetteland (strained
groin) and Venafro (strained ligament on his left middle finger)
have not pitched in an intrasquad game, and Greer (inflamed right
ankle) has been limited to 14 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Danny Wheat said Wetteland is improving but said,
``We're going to take an extra day or two just to be on the safe
side.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer is expected to return to the lineup Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Venafro has not even pitched batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I think about it, but I'm not worried about it,'' Oates
said. ``You want everybody healthy and throwing, but it takes
somebody better than I am. The trainers are working hard, and the
\Rplayers\S are working hard. Everybody has to deal with those
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates listed three major issues to be decided before the end of
camp: third base, second base and the batting order.
</P>
<P>
   Third base is up in the air between rookies Mike Lamb and Tom
Evans.
</P>
<P>
   Second base is Luis Alicea's job, but Frank Catalanotto is
bidding for more playing time with his spring performance.
Catalanotto is hitting .438 with two home runs; Alicea went 0-for-3
yesterday and is hitting .182.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luis is going to get a shot,'' Oates said. ``But if Luis
doesn't hit, Catalanotto will play second base. If Luis hits, we'll
find other places for Catalanotto to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Initial reports on Catalanotto included concern about his
defense. But Oates said: ``If Catalanotto is playing second base,
his defense will be fine. I don't think defense will keep him from
playing second.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
