<SLUG> BC-NY-PORTAUTH-CHIEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORT AUTHORITY CHIEF IS ACCUSED OF FRAUD IN REAL ESTATE DEAL
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The state attorney general Wednesday accused the
chief of the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey, a longtime
friend and fund-raiser to Gov. George Pataki, of fraud and other
misdeeds in a real estate deal, and state officials say he will
soon leave the authority because of the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Eliot Spitzer filed a civil lawsuit Wednesday
in state Supreme Court in Manhattan, contending that the
authority's executive director, Robert E. Boyle, 63, had illegally
profited in the early 1990s from real estate transactions with
Hudson Valley Hospital Center in Peekskill, where he was chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Boyle, a former head of the Jacob K. Javits Convention Center,
becomes the closest person to the governor, and the first
high-ranking member of his administration, to be tainted by
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, then a state assemblyman, served on the hospital's board
at Boyle's invitation from 1988 to 1992. There has been no
suggestion that Pataki was involved in, or knew of, any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The case against Boyle stemmed from the federal tax-fraud
indictment more than a year ago against Albert J. Pirro Jr., a
prominent lobbyist and real estate lawyer, and the husband of
Jeanine F. Pirro, the Westchester County district attorney, another
close friend and ally of the governor's.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment described a real estate deal that Boyle and Pirro
entered into with the hospital, though Spitzer's suit says that
Boyle's role in that deal was hidden.
</P>
<P>
   Pirro's indictment prompted Spitzer's investigation of Boyle,
which was kept secret until Wednesday. The attorney general decided
not to seek criminal charges against Boyle, but is seeking more
than $500,000 in restitution to the hospital under the civil
action.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's suit contends that Boyle defrauded the hospital and
its parent company, Westchester-Putnam Health Management System
Inc., by hiding his role, and accuses him of many violations of the
state's laws against self-dealing by the officers of a
not-for-profit corporation. It also says that his lies led the
hospital and the parent company to file false statements in their
annual reports.
</P>
<P>
   State prosecutors and administration officials said they
expected Boyle to leave the Port Authority because of the
accusations. He will either resign, they said, or simply not seek
reappointment by the governor when his term expires in April.
</P>
<P>
   Boyle's lawyer, Andrew J. Levander, released a statement
Wednesday saying that the suit was ``based on tired, inaccurate and
invalid allegations relating to events nearly 10 years ago.'' It
added, ``Mr. Boyle intends to move to dismiss this lawsuit in its
entirety.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyle's departure from the Port Authority would complicate
matters at an agency that has been paralyzed by a running dispute
between Pataki and Gov. Christie Whitman of New Jersey over how to
divide its resources between the two states. For more than a year,
that feud has held up approval of a crucial contract with the
country's two largest shipping companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
