<SLUG> BC-NJ-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIFTH REPUBLICAN ENTERS RACE FOR THE U.S. SENATE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH ARLINGTON, N.J. _ State Sen. William L. Gormley, who has
been seeking higher office for more than a decade, officially
entered the race Wednesday for the Republican nomination for the
U.S. Senate, saying his reputation for integrity and his record as
a tax cutter would win over voters.
</P>
<P>
   In a minibus tour from his hometown, Margate, on the Jersey
Shore, to Republican-rich suburbs to the north, Gormley, a
53-year-old former Marine captain, made character a central issue.
He described himself as a hardball fighter for his constituents who
was unafraid to take difficult stands, no matter the consequences.
``On matters of principle I will not waver,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley is the fifth Republican to declare his candidacy. His
chief rivals are two other moderates: Rep. Robert D. Franks, a
four-term congressman and two-time state Republican chairman, and
James W. Treffinger, the Essex County executive. Also running are
two conservatives, Murray Sabrin, a finance professor at Ramapo
College, and Brian T. Kennedy, a former state senator.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley and Franks have been dominating the early but important
organizational phase of the primary campaign, by amassing the
greatest number of endorsements from elected officials and party
leaders. One of the few densely populated counties still largely up
for grabs is Bergen, in northern Jersey; that is why Gormley
appeared here Wednesday at the home of Nick and Jeanne Mazzolla, a
couple active in the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley, who ran for governor in 1989, sought to distinguish
himself from Franks by recalling his own vote to ban assault
weapons. That decision, he said, prompted the National Rifle
Association to wage ``a vicious soft money campaign'' against him
in his 1991 re-election effort. By contrast, Franks, then an
assemblyman, voted against the assault weapons ban, Gormley told
reporters. And later, when other lawmakers sought to repeal the
ban, Franks failed to vote either way, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I refused to back down,'' Gormley said in his speech.
``Positions as important as a ban on assault weapons should not and
cannot change with the political tide, or bend to the pressure and
money of special interests. We who serve the public and run for
office must take a stand and stick to it. Excuses and double talk
simply do not cut it.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Smith, a spokesman for Franks, did not dispute his
Assembly voting record on the assault weapons ban. Instead, he
responded: ``Bob Franks is the only candidate in this race who has
voted for a federal ban on assault weapons, the 1994 crime bill,
and has consistently opposed any attempts to weaken or repeal that
ban.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Thompson, a spokesman for Treffinger, questioned Gormley's
credentials as a tax cutter, pointing out that his voting record in
Trenton had actually begun in 1977. ``Bill Gormley calling himself
a pro-taxpayer is simply not credible,'' Thompson said. ``He has
voted to raise income taxes, sales taxes and even gasoline taxes,
and overall, has voted at least 78 times to raise taxes or fees.''
</P>
<P>
   Gormley, who is known in the State House for a fiery temper and
flashes of anger, lightheartedly referred to such criticism in his
speech Wednesday. ``Some have called me intense,'' he said. ``Many
have said that I am tough and direct. It's true! Hopefully you will
see that these qualities can work for New Jersey.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
