<HEADLINE>
FAMILY SURVIVES TRAIN DERAILMENT...BUT PLANS TO FLY NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLINGER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARBONDALE, Kan. _ The Kemmerer family left Kansas City, Mo.,
just before midnight Tuesday on Amtrak's Southwest Chief No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later, the two Kemmerer children were huddled together
on top of their overturned sleeping car. Inside the dusty, dimly
lit car, their parents, Jacque and Jerald Kemmerer, struggled to
help passengers get out through a window.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are the odds that this would happen on our first train
trip?'' asked Jacque Kemmerer, of Overland Park.
</P>
<P>
   They were among 155 persons, including four crew members and 11
service employees, on board the Chicago-to-Los Angeles train when
it derailed at 2:05 a.m. Wednesday. Twenty-nine passengers were
injured, one woman seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the injured suffered minor cuts and bruises and were
treated at Topeka hospitals and released.
</P>
<P>
   While Amtrak officials were making other travel arrangements for
the passengers, investigators from the National Transportation
Safety Board were sent to the derailment just southwest of
Carbondale.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the derailment was still under investigation
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Workers for the Burlington Northern Santa Fe Railway were busy
Wednesday repairing the track and clearing the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   The westbound train with 27 cars and four locomotives left
Chicago at 3:20 p.m. Tuesday and stopped in Kansas City at 11:05
p.m. It left about 15 minutes later and went through Lawrence and
Topeka before derailing. It was traveling about 60 mph on straight
track after coming out of a gentle curve, the train's engineer told
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen cars left the tracks. Six were passenger cars: two
lounges, a diner, two sleepers and a coach. Five of the six came to
rest on their sides beside the track.
</P>
<P>
   Three passenger cars that were immediately in front of the
derailed cars stayed on the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The Kemmerers were just getting to sleep in one of the two
sleeper cars when they heard a loud, squeaking noise. Then the car
began shaking violently.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went backward once and then forward, almost standing up,''
Jacque Kemmerer said. ``We knew our daughter was on the bottom
(berth), and we were both hollering her name to make sure she was
OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Emergency lights came on, and the car was filled with dust from
sliding on its side. Gravel had spilled in through broken side
windows.
</P>
<P>
   Jerald Kemmerer reached a window _ now overhead _ and opened it.
The couple then lifted out Jerilyn and Jonathan, 12, and handed
blankets and pillows up to them.
</P>
<P>
   Other people were screaming and crying for help, Jacque Kemmerer
said, and she and her husband began letting them know they could
get through the window.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once people learned there was a way out, they started calming
down,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said her husband began hoisting people through the open
window. In a nearby cabin, a man yelled that he was trapped and
couldn't breathe. Jerald Kemmerer and another passenger pulled
debris off the man.
</P>
<P>
   Jerilyn said it was cold and dark on top of the car while
waiting for rescuers to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sat on mattresses, and my brother was bundled up in
blankets,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jacque Kemmerer said the couple never worried about fire. They
were too busy helping people out.
</P>
<P>
   Troopers from the Kansas Highway Patrol and deputies from the
Osage County Sheriff's Department arrived and began pulling people
from the train. Two helicopters circled overhead, bathing the
wreckage in light.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this rural area, it's pitch black,'' said Highway Patrol
Sgt. John Eichkorn, one of the first rescuers.
</P>
<P>
   Ambulances began arriving, and those who weren't hurt, including
the Kemmerers, were taken by bus to the Carbondale elementary
school.
</P>
<P>
   Victims began arriving at three Topeka hospitals about 3:15
a.m., said Amy Leiker, communications specialist with Stormont-Vail
Regional Health Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called in probably 30 additional staff,'' she said.
``Everything ran very smoothly.''
</P>
<P>
   LaVaughn Durkin, who lives a quarter-mile from the derailment,
said she gathered blankets and took them to the school gym in
Carbondale. Residents also brought in food and coffee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole community really opened its doors,'' Eichkorn said.
</P>
<P>
   From the elementary school, the passengers were taken to the
Days Inn Capital Centre and the Downtown Ramada Inn in Topeka.
Throughout the day, Amtrak officials worked at the hotels to get
passengers to their destinations.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Hare, an Amtrak spokesman, said most of the stranded
passengers would be taken to Kansas City to catch another train to
the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Some passengers were put on buses and airlines, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Kemmerers were headed to Flagstaff, Ariz., to see relatives
and the Grand Canyon. Jacque Kemmerer said Wednesday afternoon that
the family was trying to make arrangement to fly.
</P>
<P>
   Their luggage, however, was still back at the derailed train.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we got the two best packages out of that car we could
have,'' she said, referring to her children. ``That's all we care
about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
