<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-PLOT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOY, 12, AND GIRL, 14, CHARGED IN SCHOOL SHOOTING PLOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GORDY HOLT and RUTH SCHUBERT  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHIMACUM, Wash. _ Neighbors said it ``must be some kind of
misunderstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jefferson County prosecutors took another view, and
Wednesday charged a 12-year-old Port Townsend boy and a 14-year-old
female classmate from Shine, Wash., with conspiracy to commit
murder in a plot to shoot up Chimacum Middle School.
</P>
<P>
   They intended to kill classmates, teachers and school
administrators, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   As outlined by Deputy Prosecutor Michael Hass, the plot was the
boy's idea, but the girl refined it in a telephone conversation
with her alleged co-conspirator.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few minutes into the conversation, (the girl) ... made
suggestions for foolproofing the plan,'' Haas said. ``Specifically,
she suggested (that the boy) obtain silencers to use in the
massacre ... and to cut phone lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said the boy and a 14-year-old cousin attempted to
obtain guns from the cousin's gang friends in Tacoma, Wash. But the
plot came unhinged almost from the start.
</P>
<P>
   The boys abandoned a car they had stolen from their grandfather
when they spotted police. When they eventually did get to Tacoma on
Feb. 19, their friends were in jail. It's unclear whether the gang
had weapons.
</P>
<P>
   So the boys went home empty handed, only to be foiled by
overheard talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God,'' said Chimacum School District Superintendent Mary
Lynne Derrington.
</P>
<P>
   Derrington said word of the alleged plot leaked about two weeks
ago when a student overheard talk and reported it to a staff
member, who called police.
</P>
<P>
   The boy who was charged Wednesday told police he was angry at
classmates and teachers at Chimacum Middle School, and hatched the
plot to get even. He attended the school by permission because he
is a resident of Port Townsend. That permission to attend was
revoked two weeks ago. Derrington said two Chimacum Middle School
girls also were expelled because of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's cousin did not attend school in either district,
according to Port Townsend School District Superintendent Carol
Andreasen.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as we can tell, they wanted to (shoot) administration
people in general, one specific juvenile and one classroom,'' Haas
said. ``It did not appear that the female planned to take part in
the shooting, but there is an indication she planned to be involved
in cutting telephone lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Haas said the two students were not charged as adults. If the
students are convicted, prosecutors will seek to keep them in
custody until they are 21. The standard sentencing range for
juveniles convicted of the Class A felony is 15 to 36 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The boy was in custody Wednesday afternoon and the girl had not
been picked up, Jefferson County Prosecutor Juelanne Dalvall said.
Their names were not being released by prosecutors due to their
ages, Dalvall said.
</P>
<P>
   The far-flung Chimacum School District and its 1,740 students
stretches from the southern boundary of the Port Townsend School
District south down the Olympic Peninsula to Dabob Bay, and serves
a diverse socio-economic population.
</P>
<P>
   Its communities range from a low-income belt in and around
Chimacum and Irondale, south past the posh reaches of Port Ludlow
to Shine, a rapidly changing, old neighborhood of saltwater views
and double-wide housing. Three-car garages are now pushing out the
carports.
</P>
<P>
   Shine is where the girl, her parents and two sisters live, and
where two next-door neighbors, husband and wife, expressed shock
Wednesday. They stood on their front porch, a stunning view of Hood
Canal visible behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart's breaking for those people,'' said the woman,
stubbing out a cigarette. ``Must have been just a childish thing,
something to impress a boy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These are nice people,'' said her husband. ``Their girls mean
everything to them. They took them everywhere; to basketball games,
you name it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the girl suspect's house, blinds were drawn and a black dog
barked from behind a back fence. But no one answered the door.
</P>
<P>
   No one answered the door of the boy suspect's home on E Street
in Port Townsend, either.
</P>
<P>
   Across a side street, another neighbor would not identify
herself but said she knew the boy's grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think `murder' is a bit extravagent,'' she said of the
prosecutors' charge. ``But these days, you can't take a chance, can
you?''
</P>
<P>
   Chimicum and Port Townsend school officials would not talk in
detail about the suspects, citing privacy concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Part-time security officer Gary Ingersoll said the boy ``had had
problems in Port Townsend,'' before arrving at Chimacum.
</P>
<P>
   But Chimacum Middle School Principal Kathy Wales said her
district does not accept transfers without checking out
disciplinary problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do a pretty good check on interdistrict transfer
students,'' Wales said.
</P>
<P>
   History teacher Barb Aldrich, after saying that she didn't want
to violate the privacy of the students or the school, said that she
hadn't had any problems with the students allegedly involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing I can say that would shed any light on them,''
Aldrich said. ``I've had no disciplinary problems with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The indictments came as a surpise to many at the middle school,
which shares a campus with the town's elementary and high schools.
</P>
<P>
   Ingersoll, who said he often picks up rumors and complaints from
the students, knew nothing about the alleged plot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little surprised _ and for the first time a little
nervous about the whole situation _ simply because I didn't know,
it didn't get back to me somehow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although some teachers said they felt secure knowing that the
alleged conspirators are in custody, Ingersoll for one remains a
bit nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking at everybody and really making a point of getting
to know the loners this week,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Anglin, who manages a gas-and-feed store just south of the
Chimacum complex, said he had heard about the threats several weeks
ago but was shocked at Wednesday's news.
</P>
<P>
   ``You gotta feel for kids like that who can't cope,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
