<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-STARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOGILNY DEBUT IS SCORELESS ONE AS DEVILS LOSE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Alexander Mogilny is supposed to be the
sniper the Devils have been missing for years, but it will take him
awhile to display his scoring prowess for his new teammates. The
Russian right wing, who was acquired from Vancouver on Tuesday,
just before the trading deadline, showed little in his Devils debut
as New Jersey suffered a 3-2 loss to the Dallas Stars on Wednesday
night in a game between division leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Mogilny's best chances came moments apart in the second minute
of the third period while the game was tied. He was denied both
times by goaltender Manny Fernandez, the first time from close
range on the right and then on a backhander from the slot.
</P>
<P>
   Mogilny, who scored his 21st goal of the season for Vancouver
Monday night, had another chance with two minutes left and the
Devils trailing by a goal, but he was denied again by Fernandez,
this time at his right doorstep. Fernandez was playing in place of
Ed Belfour, who was at Continental Arena, but has missed the last
four games after being arrested last week on charges of assaulting
a hotel security guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been feeling better lately and started to put the puck in
the net,'' Mogilny said. ``I'm excited to be here because this is a
really good hockey team and coming into this team has increased my
confidence level. It'll take a little time to adjust because for me
it's a culture shock right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Mogilny said he planned to use his speed and his ability to take
defenders on one-on-one and go to the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a guy who is going to take it behind the net,''
Mogilny said. ``I'm going to take it all the way through, beat
three or four guys and score.''
</P>
<P>
   Mogilny likes to be around Russian friends, but that is no
longer one of his priorities. He said that the presence of
Assistant Coach Slava Fetisov and three other Russian players on
the team would not make him feel any more comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a big, big boy now,'' Mogilny said. ``I've been in this
league for 11 years now and I'm used to changes, but I still have
to make an adjustment with this team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars paid extra attention to Mogilny, and that allowed his
linemates, Scott Gomez on the left and Sergei Nemchinov at center,
to get plenty of room and create chances. But that came only after
the Devils fell behind on two goals 35 seconds apart early in the
first period.
</P>
<P>
   Both goals came during a four-on-four situation, with Jamie
Langerbrunner scoring first from close range on the right, and
Richard Matvichuk scoring on the fourth shot of the game for the
Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas dominated the rest of the first period, but the Devils
cut the deficit to 2-1 when Patrik Elias got his 30th goal of the
season with 4 minutes 36 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Elias is the first player with the Devils to reach the 30-goal
plateau since the 1993-94 season, when John MacLean, now with the
Rangers, had 37 goals and Stephane Richer, now with St. Louis, had
36.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Arnott tied it with his 19th goal at 5:51 of the second
period, after Elias, twice, and Petr Sykora had chances in the same
sequence. Elias' first attempt hit the post while the Dallas
defense was caught chasing the puck.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Modano scored the winner with his 33rd goal of the season,
at 5:50 of the third period, when he threw the puck into the crease
from the left side. Scott Stevens and Arnott were on top of the
puck but they failed to clear it from behind the fallen Martin
Brodeur after it hit Stevens' skate. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
