<HEADLINE>
TALENT SEARCH FINDS IT ON LONG ISLAND
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT WASHINGTON, N.Y. _ Theories are abounding here as to why
Paul D. Schreiber High School achieved a stunning victory in the
nationwide Intel Science Talent Search this year, producing the
first-place winner and two other finalists and stealing the thunder
of the highly selective New York City schools that have
traditionally dominated the contest.
</P>
<P>
   Viviana Risca, a Romanian immigrant who won first prize for
encrypting a secret message on a strand of DNA, surmised that since
Schreiber was smaller than schools like Stuyvesant in Manhattan and
the Bronx High School of Science, its students got more personal
attention from teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas Hanft, whose sociology experiment assessing political
learnings on Long Island and in New York City landed him among the
finalists, said that Port Washington must have had a ``particularly
excellent gene pool'' in 1982, the year that he was born.
</P>
<P>
   And Dr. Sidney Barish, the school principal, said a combination
of factors practically guaranteed that Schreiber students would
shine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we don't specialize in science but we've got bright
kids, supportive families and a school district willing to
invest,'' Barish said.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the main reason that Schreiber students excel in a
contest that rewards scientific research is that 15 years ago it
started a program to teach students how to perform sophisticated
research. School officials had noticed that several neighboring
schools were grooming students for what was then called the
Westinghouse Science Talent Search.
</P>
<P>
   Under the program, students apply to the program in their
freshman year and for the next three years they spend at least an
hour a day learning how to hypothesize, experiment and draw valid
conclusions. By their junior year, most of the students in the
program are paired with professional researchers.
</P>
<P>
   The school had its first semifinalist in the Westinghouse
competition in 1987. Thirteen years later, Port Washington _ an
affluent hamlet that was the model for East Egg in ``The Great
Gatsby'' _ has produced 72 semifinalists and 12 finalists.
</P>
<P>
   Hanft said that ``just about all the smart kids'' applied to the
research programs, even if they were not particularly interested in
science or math.
</P>
<P>
   Joshua Brandstadter, the 16-year-old sophomore who is
experimenting with the fruit flies, said it was ``nerve-racking''
to think about spending two more increasingly difficult years in
the research program. During a recent vacation, he had to come into
school every day to see if his flies had died _ ``a drag,'' he
said. But otherwise, Brandstadter said, he was happy to be a
scientist-in-training.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't start working this hard in high school,'' he
said, ``you're never going to be prepared for the real world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
