<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-KAZ-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRESHMAN MAKING MOST OF UCLA OPPORTUNITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Her UCLA teammates watch Nicole Kaczmarski on the
basketball court and forget she's just a freshman. She doesn't
behave like other freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``A.J.'s (Jalina Bradley) always late. Kaz isn't,'' senior
forward Maylana Martin said. ``(Natalie) Jarrett, she's goofy. She
always asks questions like a freshman.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior guard Erica Gomez chimed in: ``Jarrett, you want to reach
out and help her.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin continued: ``Yeah, but Kaz is in a different position.
She's more a sophomore now.''
</P>
<P>
   It's true Kaczmarski had to learn on the job and had no time to
ease into college life. Injuries to Gomez and Michelle Greco made
it impossible, so Kaczmarski started immediately, often at the
point.
</P>
<P>
   The results: Kaczmarski averaged 11.6 points a game, second
highest on the team, and earned All-Conference Freshman Team
honors. She likely will start when the Bruins meet George
Washington in an NCAA Tournament first-round game Friday at South
Bend, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell she doesn't feel like she doesn't belong,'' UCLA
coach Kathy Olivier said. ``She's confident out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaczmarski never has lacked confidence since signing with the
Bruins out of Sachem High on Long Island, where she was the
Gatorade National Player of the Year and a USA Today All-American.
</P>
<P>
   But here, so far away from home, she had to adjust like any
other freshman, going from the go-to player on her high school team
to just another role player on a senior-dominated squad. No longer
could her family watch her play, and the homesickness set in. With
it came rumors Kaczmarski would transfer to a school closer to
home, perhaps Rutgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a certain person like that, leaving home and getting
on a plane,'' she said. ``The first couple of weeks, I wondered
what did I do. . . . But no, I made this decision (to attend UCLA)
based on the program. I don't plan on leaving. I just got here.''
</P>
<P>
   Plus, she's playing. A lot. Averaging 29 minutes a game.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't supposed to happen, but Gomez began the season
recovering from shoulder surgery, so Olivier had little choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got thrown into it,'' Kaczmarski said. ``That was a little
bit of pressure. I was happy I got to play right away.''
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't easy. Seniors such as Martin and Janae Hubbard had
grown accustomed to Gomez getting them the ball. Kaczmarski didn't
know her teammates' tendencies and preferences, and the Bruins
struggled in wins over Pepperdine and Fullerton and in losses to
nationally ranked teams Tennessee, Connecticut, Rutgers and
Louisiana Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Kaczmarski tried to do too much and it showed in her shooting:
33 percent in her first nine games. Once she stopped (and once
players healed), she eased into her role as shooting guard/backup
point guard. In the last 13 games, she is shooting 45.4 percent and
has made 41 of her last 47 free throws.
</P>
<P>
   Her relaxed self was most evident when she sank 10 of 12
3-pointers in last week's win over Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Kaczmarski didn't say much this season, nor will she against
George Washington. But wait until next year, when she really is a
sophomore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 0022EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
