<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8370 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-FISCAL-NYT &LR;      03-16 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FISCAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSEMBLY DEMOCRATS PROPOSE BUDGET $1.3 BILLION BIGGER THAN
PATAKI'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Democrats who control the state Assembly on
Wednesday proposed a $78.2 billion budget, significantly more money
than Gov. George Pataki wants to spend, setting the stage for yet
another protracted budget fight.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed budget is $5.3 billion, or 7.3 percent, higher than
the one that the governor and the Legislature enacted last year. It
relies on the state's surging tax revenues to finance large
increases in spending for health care, public schools, and state
colleges and universities, as well as a smattering of new tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The budget we're adopting responsibly supports education, job
creation, tax cuts and health care,'' said Sheldon Silver, the
Democratic speaker of the Assembly. ``It responds to the real need
of the people of our state.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the Democratic plan would spend $1.3 billion, or 1.8
percent, more than the proposal Pataki released earlier this year.
The governor's $76.8 billion budget proposal is $3.5 billion, or
5.5 percent, larger than the one enacted last year.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, a Republican, has warned lawmakers that the state could
be headed for fiscal trouble if it does not restrain spending.
Indeed, independent fiscal monitors have cautioned that the state
could face huge budget shortfalls in future years because of the
anticipated cost of tax cuts and new benefit programs enacted in
previous budgets.
</P>
<P>
   But legislative leaders from both major parties are likely to
hold out for more money than the governor has proposed in a variety
of areas, largely because all 211 members of the Legislature are up
for re-election this year and eager to finance programs that are
popular with their constituents.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest difference between the Democrats and Pataki is in
education. The Democrats are calling for a $1.3 billion, or 10.3
percent, rise in state aid to schools, compared with the $355
million, or 2.8 percent, increase that the governor requested in
his budget.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's Republican allies in the state Senate have
already proposed a $900 million increase for public schools,
placing even greater pressure on him to move beyond the amount that
he has proposed.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic proposal restores $117 million in cuts that the
governor's budget makes to educational programs that largely
benefit New York City: one that raises the salaries of teachers in
urban school districts and another that provides such districts
money to undertake minor maintenance projects in aging school
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats would also pump money into a statewide program
intended to expand prekindergarten classes and reduce class sizes.
The Democrats called for providing $170 million more than the $20
million increase Pataki proposed for these programs.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also proposed providing $60 million for a handful of
other programs that the governor did not seek any increases for,
like expanding after-school offerings in relatively poor urban
school districts.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic leaders also unveiled a tax-cut package, saying it
would save New York taxpayers $750 million over the next four
years. The centerpiece of the package calls for raising standard
deductions for married couples who file income taxes jointly to
$15,000 a year from $13,000, saving taxpayers $180 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic plan also expands a state program that subsidizes
prescription drug purchases for the elderly, proposing to more than
double the number of people eligible for the coverage. The plan
calls for adding $308 million to the $148 million that the state
pays annually to provide prescription drug coverage for the
elderly. That would raise the number of people enrolled in the
program to 224,000 from 112,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 0026EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
