<HEADER>
A8373 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-WIRED-COMMUNITY-LADN     03-16 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIRED-COMMUNITY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DEVELOPMENT WILL BE WIRED INTO INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON Z. COHEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; Valencia, Calif. _ Newhall Ranch will be wired for speed under
a deal between its developer, The Newhall Land &AMP; Farming Company,
and SBC Communications Inc., the parent company of Pacific Bell.
</P>
<P>
   The project will encompass 30,000 homes and thousands of
businesses, making Newhall Ranch and parts of Valencia the first
communities in Southern California to be built from the ground up
with the infrastructure in place for high-speed Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to installing digital subscriber line connections in
every new home, Pacific Bell will install fiber optic voice and
data communications infrastructure in all of Valencia and Newhall
Ranch's new residential and commercial/industrial developments.
</P>
<P>
   Located about 30 miles north of Los Angeles, Newhall Ranch will
have new shopping centers along with more than 20,000 homes, making
the community bigger than most cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``That community could have the most advanced communications of
any community. They can maybe get fiber within 6,000 feet of every
customer,'' said Rex Mitchell, telecommunications analyst with Bank
of America Montgomery Securities. ``Being able to offer high-speed
digital services across the board to all of their customers is
their future.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, Pacific Bell will install high-speed DSL wiring
in each new house built at Newhall Ranch and in Valencia beginning
with the Bridgeport development.
</P>
<P>
   SBC and Newhall Land also will collaborate on Intranet for
Valencia, providing an online connection for neighbors linking them
to schools, clubs, local businesses and community information.
</P>
<P>
   Although the deal does not give Pacific Bell exclusive rights to
provide DSL in the community, it is a demonstration of the
company's ability to provide the latest voice and data
communications technology, Mitchell said. The revenue effect will
be minimal for SBC Communications, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For neighbors already developed, Pacific Bell officials said the
company plans to go back and install high-speed Internet access
service on a priority basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``There currently exists a fiber infrastructure out there, and
that certainly will be expanded as the commercial and business
development grows,'' said Pacific Bell spokesman Steve Getzug. ``We
plan to extend fiber further into the residential communities in
order that all of our customers can take advantage of DSL.''
</P>
<P>
   DSL gives customers Internet connections as much as 50 times
faster than regular dial-up service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our current residents and our future customers are very
interested in technology. They recognize it is a critical component
in their way of life, both from an individual and a business
standpoint,'' said Newhall Land and Farming spokeswoman Marlee
Lauffer. The deal ``ensures that Pacific Bell will prioritize
getting any current and new technologies to our communities.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 0032EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
