A8377 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-POLAND-AZR &LR;      03-16 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLAND-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENCY IS DENIED FOR POLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY JUDI VILLA  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Patrick Poland leaned forward and, in a shaking voice, spoke to
the families of the men he killed nearly 23 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to say I'm sorry. I've lived with this every day, and I
wish I could just go back in time,'' said Poland, 50. ``I hope
everyone can accept my apology, understand me and forgive me.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite Poland's remorse and passionate pleas to spare his
life, the Arizona Board of Executive Clem ency voted, 4-1, on
Tuesday to go ahead with Poland's execution.
</P>
<P>
   He is scheduled to die by lethal injection at 3 p.m. today at
the state prison in Florence for killing ar mored-van guards Cecil
Newkirk and Russell Dempsey in May 1977. Po land would be the 21st
inmate executed in Arizona since the state resumed capital
punishment in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel for Patrick Poland, and I hope he can truly repent for
what he did,'' Newkirk's grandson, Cecil III, said after the
hearing. ``I'm sure if he could go back, things would be different.
But, unfortunately, it can't be like that. He has to serve (his
sentence) for what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Poland's attorney, Tom Gorman, filed a last-minute appeal with
the U.S. Supreme Court on Tuesday night. A decision is expected
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's it. That's the highest court there is,'' Gorman said.
``We're hoping they will grant us a stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's eight-hour hearing was marked by tearful pleas for
mercy and heartbreaking stories of abuse that Poland suffered as a
child at the hands of his father. Three of his siblings, including
his twin brother, Jeff, and his two children spoke in his behalf.
So did two prosecutors and the FBI agent who once rallied to put
Poland on death row.
</P>
<P>
   All wanted Poland's death sentence reduced to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look in my father's eyes and I've got so much love for him,
and I feel like I'm 4 years old again,'' said Guy Poland, Patrick's
son. ``I love my father so much, I can't even imagine being here
without him.''
</P>
<P>
   Several times during breaks Tuesday, Guy and his sister, Stacey,
looked toward the enclosed chamber where their father sat, and
mouthed, ``I love you, Dad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were realistic and we knew it probably wouldn't happen,''
Stacey said after the board's decision. ``Ev erything that could
have been done has been done.''
</P>
<P>
   After the hearing, Guy and Stacey said their final goodbyes
through the glass of a visitation booth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love him; he knows that,'' Stacey said. ``And I told him to
give me a kiss.''
</P>
<P>
   Poland has asked that his family not witness his execution.
</P>
<P>
   He and his brother, Michael, posed as highway patrolmen to pull
over a Purolator Inc. armored van, steal $288,000 and kill both
guards. They then drove 250 miles to Lake Mead, wrapped Newkirk and
Dempsey in custom-made canvas bags weighted with rocks and dropped
them from a rented boat to a watery grave.
</P>
<P>
   Newkirk's widow said in a letter to the board that ``the Poland
brothers cheated my husband from many years of happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Does this man deserve to die?'' Lola Newkirk wrote. ``Yes, he
does! He must pay with his life! This will not bring back my dear
husband, but justice must be served.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 0035EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8378 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-INTERVIEW-TEXT-2     03-16 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-INTERVIEW-TEXT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERVIEW WITH BUSH ON CAMPAIGN ISSUES AND ELECTION STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN EDITORS: Papers without the space to run this in its entirety
may want to consider selecting excerpts from it for use as sidebars
with BUSH-NYT by Richard L. Berke and Frank Bruni)  
 (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ _ Following are excerpts from an interview
Wednesday with Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, as recorded by The New
York Times:
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is your reaction to Al Gore's statement that he had
asked the Democratic National Committee to refrain from running
issue ads financed with soft money?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: It's kind of a gimmick. He has no credibility, as far as
I'm concerned. I don't trust him. I don't trust him. I don't trust
him. He needs to stand up in front of the unions, to get all his
friends not to run issue ads. I don't trust the man. He has no
credibility, as far as I'm concerned, about campaign funding
reform. . . .
</P>
<P>
   You've got to understand my position: I don't trust him. I don't
believe what he says he's going to do. He needs to say the same
thing to the labor unions, to all the folks who are out there
getting ready to spend millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why not call his bluff?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: I'm running against a man that I believe will say anything
to get elected. I believe that. And I am amazed. Last week, it was,
we're going to ban all soft money. At the same time, in your
newspaper, you reported that President Clinton was out raising soft
money and Vice President Gore, the very same day or the next day,
in your paper, accurately reported by you all, was getting ready to
go raise $35 million and proud of it. So you can understand why I'm
somewhat skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   Q. As a politician/competitor, what do you think of him?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: I believe he'll say anything to get elected, that's what I
believe.
</P>
<P>
   Q. If he's willing to say and do anything, how do you not end up
having a whole bunch of the time in this campaign consumed by him
doing and saying things and you responding?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: It's very important for me to enunciate clearly where I
want to lead the country. In order for me to win, I need to talk
about my vision of reform and the ideas that are necessary to
achieve reform. There's no question about that. I hope to be able
to counterpunch quickly and move directly to where I want to lead
America. That's what Americans want to hear. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you think the public wants a president who desperately
wants it that badly?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: I think what the public wants is somebody who can lift the
spirit of this country. The public wants somebody who will bring
honor and dignity to the White House. This country's so great, and
the future's going to be incredibly positive. They want to hear
that. And I understand politics. I understand what goes on in a
political campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Wasn't that lost in fighting over tactics during primaries?
Can't that happen again if Gore acts as McCain did?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: First of all, Al Gore is no John McCain. Please don't lump
John into that category. Secondly, I think John McCain is a person
that basically wanted to elevate the discourse and had a reason for
running, rather than tearing somebody down.
</P>
<P>
   I know everybody said this was a dirty campaign. Compared to
many campaigns, it wasn't and the proof is that we had huge
turnouts in our primaries, huge, much bigger than the Democrats and
much bigger than the past. And the reason why was in spite of what
the punditry said, people were hearing positive things. They were
hearing positive things about education. They were hearing things
about the military.
</P>
<P>
   I know that some are saying that people aren't interested in tax
relief. I happen to think they are. And even if they weren't, I'd
still be talking about it, because I happen to think it's important
for the economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Polls say voters aren't demanding a huge tax cut and that
they trust Al Gore more on the tax issue. Is that not like
campaigning with weights around your ankles?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: May I make something really clear to you, once again, and
I hope this pleases you. I don't care what the polls say. I don't.
. . .I'm doing what I think what's wrong. I think it's right for
economic reasons. You've heard me talk about what's wrong with this
tax code. It's wrong for people who are making $22,000 a year to
pay a higher marginal rate on every dollar earned than someone
making $200,000 a year. That's wrong. And I hope this doesn't sound
blase: I don't care what the polls say. It's not going to change my
opinion about what I think should happen. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Q. How different from Bob Dole?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: It's different because one, I started early, and two,
there's a different budget projection. There's a different budget
picture. I'm still going to have to fight the same thing he fought
with an administration that's desperate to keep the money in
Washington. I mean, Al Gore spends most of the surplus on programs.
That's what he decided to do. Look at his budget numbers. That's
just a difference of opinion. It's a fundamental difference of
opinion. And it's very important for me to make clear that we can
have tax relief and tax reform and make the codes fairer without
affecting anybody's Medicare check.
</P>
<P>
   Q. The nation's economic outlook has changed since you laid your
plan out. The stock market has fallen and inflation is growing.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: That's another reason to have tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Does your plan take into account a new reality?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: It does. Absolutely. That's a reason, if the economy
begins to get shaky. By the way, there's a five and a half year
phase-in. It's going to address an economic slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   To me, it's justifiable on economic grounds, and necessary. All
the more reason to provide tax relief. I hope we don't slow down.
But you're right, it is a little more shaky now, in a brief
five-month period of time.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How critical is your tax plan to winning this election?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: It's a part of what's critical to my election. What's
critical to my election is a lot of things. One, that people trust
my judgment. Two, that people hear the call for reform. Three, that
people know that I can renew what I call the spirit of America.
Four, that people are comfortable with the types of people that
I'll bring into my administration. Five, whether people are happy
or not with the status quo. I readily concede that if people want
four more years of Clinton-Gore, I've got a tough road. I do. I
know what my position is. I'm the outsider, and I'm the challenger.
I'm coming from outside Washington, and I'm the challenger
candidate. People say, I hear them talking out of Washington, well,
he doesn't have enough experience. As if being the governor of the
second biggest state and having served as a CEO in the private
sector isn't experience. It's a Washington mentality. And I'm going
to have to battle it. I'm fully aware of the odds I'm going to
face.
</P>
<P>
   It's a well thought-out plan. And I'm going to have to battle.
I'm going to have battle with the polls. I'm going to have to
battle with a president who wants to keep the money in Washington.
I'm going to have to battle with a vice president who'll say risky
this, risky that. I understand that. But I believed it when I laid
it out and I believe it while I'm sitting right here today, after
having won some primaries and lost some primaries. This is right
for America.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Q. Has John McCain elevated your consciousness about reform? Has
he changed your views?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: No, he didn't change my views. He made me a better
candidate. He forced me to play to my strengths better. I needed to
make it more clear that I not only believe in reform, I've got the
record as a chief executive of getting reform done. There's nothing
like the humbling experience of getting whipped pretty bad in New
Hampshire to cause a man to re-evaluate. And I re-evaluated my
message and I re-evaluated how I was conducting myself as a
candidate. I wasn't doing as good a job as I could have explaining
where my strength is. And my strength is as somebody when, giving
the chance to reform, like education, I brought both Republicans
and Democrats together. That's what this country needs, when it
comes to Social Security, for example.
</P>
<P>
   When it's all said and done, I think America's going to turn to
me. I've got a record of doing it. The vice president is extremely
partisan. He's extremely partisan.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is there anything McCain brought to light for you or changed
your opinion on in any way?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: No, not really. We agreed more than we disagreed. That's
the great irony. You know, primaries are struggles, arguments over
shades of gray. And that's what makes primaries difficult. In my
case, I've known John a long time. And battling with John wasn't
all that pleasant, because I like him. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you see healing happen?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: Yes, I do.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What do you need to do to make sure that happens?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: Just remind him there's a lot of agreement. We agree on a
lot of things, starting with neither of us wants Al Gore to be the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What about Al Gore's public life do you dislike so much?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: I don't like the acrimony in Washington. I don't like the
zero-sum politics. I don't like pitting one group of people against
another. I don't like the way they've handled whether or not he
knew about raising money from the White House _ you know, iced tea
and all these kinds of excuses. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Q. You don't have to make concessions, but there are people out
there urging it and calling for it __
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: Who's saying that?
</P>
<P>
   Q. Intermediaries. Is there anything you need to do to win him
over? Any concessions you need to offer?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: No. I think what I need to do is explain to John that we
agree a lot more than we disagree. There's a lot of room for reform
in Washington, D.C. I look forward to working with him to achieve
the reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Q. You said initially you were going to stay positive in the
campaign. Any regrets about the way the primary went?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: No, I don't.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you regret the turn of the whole campaign?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: I regret being called an anti-Catholic bigot. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Q. You're comfortable with the negative tone?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: I didn't take the negative tone. The filter took the
negative tone. . . .
</P>
<P>
   The reason that the turnout was so huge is because I talked
about education reform and military reform and rarely did I attack
my opponents. As a matter of fact, I was the person being attacked
most of the time, early on in the primaries, and then coming down
the stretch, I felt I need to project a positive image, and that's
what I did.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How involved are you in the day-to-day decisions of the
campaign?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: This is important if you're trying to leap from here to
the presidency. I know the difference between being somebody who
sets the vision and sets the tone and enunciates the principles by
which decisions are being made and someone who is a micro-manager.
Being a candidate itself is a lot of work. I can't tell you all the
times when I say I'm not going to give this speech. It happens a
lot. I can be pretty stubborn.
</P>
<P>
   People make suggestions on what to say all the time. I'll give
you an example; I don't read what's handed to me. People say
``Here, here's your speech, or here's an idea for a speech.''
They're changed. Trust me. Last night's a good example. We could
have been a lot harsher in tone on Vice President Gore last night.
I chose not to. What I think is important is not to get mired in a
slugfest with this guy. That's what he wants. And last night one of
the drafts I got was pretty tough. I said I'm not going to talk
about him this way, because I wanted to talk about education.
</P>
<P>
   Q. When you look at some of the situations where the United
States is trying with mixed success to broker peace talks, do you
have sympathy for what Clinton is trying to do or do you blame him?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: Take Northern Ireland for example. I have been on the
record applauding the efforts to use our prestige to bring people
together. It's very important for Americans and elected officials
to be patient with the peace process. To be diligent and patient.
It's very important for a president not to impose a United States
solution on the peace process. So to the president's credit, it
seems to me on the Middle East he's working hard to bring people
together.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What would you do with the situation in the Balkans?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: I would have hopefully not gotten us involved in the first
place. I would hope my diplomacy would have allowed there not to
commit troops in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is it time to turn things completely over to the United
Nations?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: In the Balkans, I don't think so yet. But I do think it's
time to begin to say to our European allies, you're going to have
to be the peacekeepers. I think it's going to be very important for
us to trim United States involvement around the world from certain
peacekeeping missions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
