A8384 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CONN-LEGIS-NYT &LR;      03-16 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONN-LEGIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE AGENDA IN CONNECTICUT'S LEGISLATURE: REFORMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ As they hustle through this year's 12-week
legislative session, Connecticut lawmakers on both sides of the
aisle have been tossing around the R-word almost as often as their
parties' candidates for president have.
</P>
<P>
   For Democrats, who control both houses of the General Assembly,
reforming the state's campaign finance laws is a top priority.
Republicans, on the other hand, want reforms in the rules
controlling how the Democratic state treasurer invests the state's
$21 billion pension fund.
</P>
<P>
   And almost halfway through the session, both sides seem to agree
that the state's county sheriff system needs so much reform that it
should simply be abolished.
</P>
<P>
   Neither party has abandoned its core issues. For Democrats,
those include strengthening laws to protect air and water quality;
Republicans are intent on tax cuts, including a 7-cent reduction in
the gasoline tax.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats have seized on campaign finance legislation as the
political hammer with which to pound Republicans, who have been
forced to discuss the issue since Paul J. Silvester, a former state
treasurer and a Republican ally of Gov. John G. Rowland, pleaded
guilty to federal charges of money laundering and racketeering in
September for improperly investing state pension funds in exchange
for political favors or money.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Bill No. 1 would limit campaign spending by each party's
ticket for governor and lieutenant governor to $5 million, and
limit spending by each candidate for the five other statewide
elected offices to $750,000, beginning in 2002. It would also
finance up to half of the money those candidates spend through
voluntary taxpayer donations.
</P>
<P>
   But the bill's most provocative element _ the spending caps on
political campaigns _ has been disparaged as unconstitutional by
many lawmakers in both parties and by the state Elections
Enforcement Commission. A similar bill offered by House Democrats
proposes voluntary spending limits on campaigns for governor and
the five other statewide offices, but not on the 187 campaigns for
state legislative office. The General Assembly's powerful joint
Appropriations Committee is expected to vote on the Senate bill
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans oppose both campaign finance bills. They favor a
third bill, based on recommendations made by the Elections
Enforcement Commission, that would more strictly limit how much
special-interest groups could give candidates. At Thursday's
Judiciary Committee meeting, a group of Senate Republicans plans to
propose amending the two Democratic-sponsored bills to include a
ban on campaign contributions from all political action committees,
unions and corporations.
</P>
<P>
   For Republicans, though, this year's paramount issue is cutting
taxes. As gasoline prices in Connecticut surpass $2 a gallon,
Republican leaders are counting on public sentiment to fight
Democratic opposition to a proposal dear to Rowland: a 7-cent
reduction in the state's 32-cent-a-gallon gasoline tax.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying before the Finance, Revenue and Bonding Committee
last Friday, Marc S. Ryan, the governor's state budget director,
called the gas tax, the highest in the country, ``one of the last
remaining regressive tax structures we have'' and urged the panel
to pass the bill ``so we don't see individuals driving across
borders to purchase gas and other things.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats remain unconvinced, arguing that cutting the gas tax
might not result in lower pump prices and that the $90 million in
potential savings would be better spent on fixing roads and
bridges. But the Democratic co-chairwoman of the committee, state
Rep. Anne McDonald of Stamford, predicted that in an election year
most committee members would vote for the tax cut, despite concerns
about its effect on the state's healthy AA bond rating by Standard
&AMP; Poor's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it will come to a compromise, where there's a 3- or
4-cent reduction,'' McDonald said in an interview Monday. The
47-member finance committee has until March 28 to vote on the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   Other major items on the agenda this year include legislation
that would force fossil-fuel power plants in Bridgeport, New Haven,
Middletown, Norwalk and Montville to cut their emission levels of
nitrogen and sulfur oxides by 2003. The plants were built before
the 1973 federal Clean Air Act took effect, and emissions at all
five plants exceed current federal standards. A similar bill passed
last June on a 68-67 vote in the state House of Representatives,
but the Assembly's Energy and Technology Committee ignored the
proposal, effectively killing it. The owners of the five power
plants say that if the bill passes and is signed by the governor,
they will be forced to shut down for eight weeks to retool.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats both support another environmental
measure to eliminate a chemical additive to gasoline that reduces
toxic tailpipe emissions but that has polluted Connecticut ground
water. Several bills seeking to ban the chemical in gasoline sold
in the state are under discussion in legislative committees.
</P>
<P>
   State officials have sought the cooperation of other
Northeastern states to ban the additive, methyl tertiary butyl
ether, or MTBE. Two weeks ago, Rowland asked the state's
congressional delegation to propose a national policy on the
additive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
