<SLUG> BC-BKW_SCWOMEN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC MOVING ON UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Chris Gobrecht has been trying to turn around the
women's basketball program at USC for three years, and as recently
as early February, it appeared the Women of Troy were at least one
more season away from even limited success.
</P>
<P>
   The team was struggling with an 8-11 record and seemed destined
for a third straight finish in the lower half of the conference.
</P>
<P>
   It was especially hard on Gobrecht, who took Washington to the
NCAA Tournament nine times.
</P>
<P>
   USC was 19-35 in Gobrecht's first two seasons as head coach and
her competitive nature made it tough to endure the losing, despite
the fact injuries and a talent shortage were primarily responsible
for the losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had times of being really frustrated. I didn't know what
buttons to push any more,'' Gobrecht said. ``It's not so much you
doubt yourself (but rather) as you're humbled. You realize you
don't have all the answers.''
</P>
<P>
   The past five weeks have almost made up for those trying times,
however, as USC went 7-2 in the second half of Pacific-10
Conference play and earned a bid to the Women's National Invitation
Tournament; it will meet Santa Clara at 7 tonight in a first-round
game at Toso Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   USC (15-13) was arguably the hottest team in the conference by
the end of the season and possibly just a win away from making the
NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Among those most surprised by USC's late-season surge is
Gobrecht, considering the Trojans went 3-6 in the first half of the
Pac-10 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have thought we could go 7-2,'' she said. ``It
allows us to skip straight to our expectations. We have an
understanding of what it's about now. It's time to move up with the
big guys.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's NIT bid is seen as the first small step toward
rebuilding the program.
</P>
<P>
   Although USC loses three players, it has one of the nation'stop
recruiting classes, a class that features center Ebony Hoffman of
Narbone High in Harbor City, rated the No. 2 prospect in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   USC also signed Aisha Hollans of Berkeley High, whose team will
play against Hoffman's Narbonne team on Saturday in the State
Division I championship game, and guard Ryane Alexander of Copperas
Cove, Texas, USA Today's ninth-ranked team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we feel pretty good about being in position to be one
of the top programs in the Pac-10,'' Gobrecht said.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a turning point for this year's team, it probably
occurred in early February. USC was blown out by California 81-64
in what was unquestionably the low point in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our loss at Cal, that was an embarrassment,'' said senior
forward Danielle Golay.
</P>
<P>
   USC lost its following game at Stanford 69-59, but the players
believe that close contest boosted their confidence and helped
change the direction of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We grew up a little bit and matured,'' Golay said. ``From a
loss, we actually learned we were getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   After that, USC upset 20th-ranked UCLA, 15th-ranked Arizona and
completed a sweep of Pac-10 champion Oregon with a 69-63 victory at
McArthur Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning of the year, a lot of people were not doing
their part,'' Golay said. ``When that changed, we did win games.
Before you knew it, you looked at our record and it was like `Wow.'
I didn't even know we finished 7-2 until (Gobrecht) told us last
weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   A major reason USC has improved is sophomore guard Tiffany
Elmore, who averaged 8.8 points in the first nine Pac-10 games and
14.2 points in the final nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I needed to step up because at the beginning of
the season, I averaged like two points a game,'' Elmore said. ``I
wasn't as confident. There was a lot of stress and things
happening. But all of the hard work has paid off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
