<HEADLINE>
I SING THE PICKUP ELECTRIC  &HT;      
</HEADLINE>
   By SCOTT OSTLER  
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
We're flying down 101 around Hospital Curve, me and Electric Ray,
passing the internal-combustion losers right and left, and it
occurs to me what Ray's truck lacks:
<P>
   A loudspeaker.
</P>
<P>
   I once drove the Oscar Mayer Weinermobile and it has a
loudspeaker, an enormously handy feature, so much more highly
evolved than the horn. ``Honk'' is like  &LR; aloha,  &LR; it can mean
anything.
</P>
<P>
   Driving Electric Ray's pickup, I feel a need to communicate with
other motorists, although technically I am the only motorist on the
road, since gas cars are powered by  &LR; engines,  &LR; not motors.
</P>
<P>
   I want to say:
</P>
<P>
   ``Attention, blue Chevy! I am the future! Please get out of my
lane and let me through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yo, white Honda smogmaker, dinosaurs died for your
environmental sins!''
</P>
<P>
   I am driving Ray's Ford Ranger, which is powered by batteries. I
am developing an attitude: greener than thou.
</P>
<P>
   Electric Ray, also known as Ray Levinson, laughed when he read
the headline in Wednesday's newspaper, ``Gas Prices Rise to
Historic Highs.''
</P>
<P>
   And here's a secret memo to you other drivers: Gas prices not
heading south soon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; READER DAN MILLER &LR;  stopped at a Chevron station on San Jose Ave.
Wednesday and as he was pumping at $1.93 a gallon, an attendant was
changing the signboard to read $1.95.
</P>
<P>
   I'm telling you, smart people know that the $3 gallon is coming,
and they are draining their swimming pools and hot tubs and filling
them with gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   You're paying two bucks a gallon? Electric Ray is using about
two bucks worth of electricity to get the equivalent of a  &LR; full &LR; 
 &LR; tank.  &LR; And if he works it right, he can get charged for free.
</P>
<P>
   The man is stealing transportation. It's the ultimate way to bum
a ride.
</P>
<P>
   Ray can drive up to the front door of the Hyatt Regency at
Fisherman's Wharf, for instance, and tell the valet parking guy,
``Fill 'er up,'' and get a free charge from the Hyatt's charger. He
can charge up at Costco, even at some BART stations.
</P>
<P>
   Ray is the U.S. post office's environmental manager for
California and Hawaii. He has been hammering the P.O. to get
electric vehicles, and he figured he should practice what he
hammers.
</P>
<P>
   So he leased his pickup for $199 a month. His Ranger can range
only about 65 to 70 miles between charges, but other than that ...
no gas, no oil, no transmission fluid, no moving parts. It's a
flashlight on wheels.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; HE LET &LR;  me take it for a whirr. It has all kinds of zip. Careens
though the city, jumps onto the freeway, cruises at 65.
</P>
<P>
   Electric Ray is a former Los Angeles hippie. He went to work for
the post office because they hired freaky guys with long hair. He
rose through the ranks and is now Mr. Environment.
</P>
<P>
   Ray's hair is short now, but he still listens to his inner
hippie. His home has special watt-saving bulbs and bamboo flooring
(it's a grass; save the trees), and he composts.
</P>
<P>
   He has persuade the post office to order 500 EVs (electric
vehicles) from Ford. He became such a pest on the subject that his
co-workers call him Electric Ray.
</P>
<P>
   He is going to wind up on Saddam Hussein's hit list. One-third
of all U.S. oil consumption is for transportation, and the Mideast
oil boys need us to need them.
</P>
<P>
   Ray's truck is like a UFO. The motor (not an engine, please) is
stone silent. It's eerie. If you have some kind of need for stealth
driving, this is your ride.
</P>
<P>
   No transmission, so no shifting or lurching. This is not to be
confused with the hybrid engines that run on gas and electricity.
Screw the hybrids, this is the full Monty.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of OSTLER16 (7401 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  As I drive, I become acutely conscious of the fact that for the
first time in my life behind the wheel of a vehicle,  &LR; I am &LR;   &LR; not
polluting! &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; I AM  &LR; not belching carcinogens and hydrocarbons into the air my
children breathe, or at least my vehicle isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Zero emissions! Zilcho on the filth-o. No tailpipe, no oil
leaks. Should I fire up a big cigar to compensate?
</P>
<P>
   I feel as though I deserve a special reward, a candy bar, maybe,
for every mile I drive.
</P>
<P>
   It's a heady feeling. I'm getting high on fresh air.
</P>
<P>
   Not only am I guilt-free, I begin to feel smug, then
self-righteously resentful at the cretins around me who are
polluting my air.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, I feel good because I am beating the system!
</P>
<P>
   I am laughing in the face of the petro-Pennzoil
cartel/conspiracy. I have slipped off the shackles of their
tyranny.
</P>
<P>
   I think of all the times as a teenager when I was forced to dive
under the couch cushions in search of coins for a gallon of gas.
</P>
<P>
   Now I am speeding past gas stations thinking how retro they are.
As Ray says, ``The internal combustion engine is so 20th century.''
</P>
<P>
   The benefits seem endless. One: For a younger, single man, an EV
would be great for picking up green chicks.
</P>
<P>
   It would give a whole new meaning to the phrase, ``He's a total
zero.''
