<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-DEVILS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN AT `60 PERCENT,' STARS BEAT THE DEVILS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Recordwise, the St. Louis Blues are the
best team in the Western Conference. The numbers similarly point to
the New Jersey Devils as the best team in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   But after the past four days, the Stars showed they might be the
best team in either conference.
</P>
<P>
   Want evidence?
</P>
<P>
   The Stars finished a string of three games in four nights,
playing without their starting goalie in all of them, with a 3-2
victory against the previously mentioned Devils last night at
Continental Airlines Arena. In the other two games, the Stars
defeated the previously mentioned St. Louis Blues and the New York
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole year, everything this team has done and gone
through, it speaks for itself to be in the position we are, to have
done the things that we've done and to be where we are with all the
injuries and turmoil,'' Stars winger Brett Hull said. ``It's some
big wins against some good teams.''
</P>
<P>
   And with players such as Guy Carbonneau, Jere Lehtinen and Blake
Sloan yet to return, they aren't even operating at 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If the Stars are indeed operating at 60 percent, as Stars coach
Ken Hitchcock suggested after watching his injury-riddled bunch
defeat a much-hyped Devils bunch that had just added sniper
Alexander Mogilny, the NHL had better watch out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he says that, then I'm not going to argue with him. It's
like beating a dead horse,'' Stars winger Mike Keane said, coyly.
``We want to try to get healthy again. It's tough to tell how good
we are or how bad we are. We haven't had a full team.''
</P>
<P>
   A Stars bunch firing at 100 percent might be too much to handle.
Just ask New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The game-winning goal came from ... who else? Mike Modano. He
extended his point streak to a personal-best 11 games with his goal
at 5:50 of the third period. It was one of his five shots on the
night. In addition, he played 22-plus minutes, won 58 percent of
his faceoffs and finished a game-high plus-2. ``When he scored, the
whole building went silent,'' Stars goalie Manny Fernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   And while Modano has been good, the Stars around him have been
pretty good themselves. The Jon Sims and Roman Lyashenkos and
Brenden Morrows have come into their own.
</P>
<P>
   OK, Fernandez has, too.
</P>
<P>
   Playing in his fifth consecutive game in relief of usual starter
Ed Belfour Fernandez has ``really'' come into his own. Last night,
he stopped 22 of the 24 shots he faced, including a flurry in front
of his net in the final 10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was good. This kid has got a lot of confidence
right now,'' Hitchcock said. ``We come here, and we beat St. Louis,
and we beat these guys, and we beat the Rangers, in the last three
games. That's a heck of a way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   And with Belfour likely to be in net Saturday in Chicago, the
Stars more than weathered the storm without him. They went 3-1-1,
earning eight of a possible 10 points during the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Last night's game looked as if it was going to be easy. The
Stars were flying in the opening minutes, and a little four-on-four
play courtesy of a couple of penalties did nothing to slow them
down. By the time the four-on-four had expired, the Stars had a 2-0
lead courtesy of goals by winger Jamie Langenbrunner at 2:40 and
defenseman Richard Matvichuk 35 seconds later.
</P>
<P>
   But the Devils answered with two goals of their own. First,
winger Patrik Elias scored a power-play goal at 15:24 of the first
period. Then, center Jason Arnott scored at 5:51 of the second
period.
</P>
<P>
   And it wouldn't be a Stars game without one of their players
being helped off the ice. Matvichuk had a puck deflected into his
forehead 3 minutes, 42 seconds into the third period. Hitchcock
said Matvichuk is all right, but he didn't return to the game. The
Stars scored two minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   Adversity, you see, prompts the Stars to their best
performances. They've been dealing with it all season, and that,
Hitchcock says, might be why they are where they are now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our element, our strength is our attitude right now,''
Hitchcock said. ``Our attitude is very strong. We have a lot of
mental toughness in this group.'' \Ntagtop:Jennifer Floyd, (817)
390-7760 \Ntagbottom:jenfloyd\Nstar-telegram.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
