<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMILARITIES WITH 1980 RUNNERS-UP ARE EERIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; MINNEAPOLIS _ This has happened before. The sloppiness and
inconsistency, the midseason slump, the microscopic NCAA hopes, the
fast finish, the Bay Area sweep, the upset of a No. 1 team _ it's
all happened before.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago this month, under rookie coach Larry Brown, the
UCLA Bruins sneaked into the NCAA Tournament, stunned No. 1 DePaul
and eventually lost to Louisville in the championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Can these Bruins do the same?
</P>
<P>
   They open NCAA Tournament play tonight against Ball State.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of similarities, not so much in the teams but
in the seasons,'' said UCLA assistant Michael Holton, who was the
starting point guard in 1980. ``I remember that in the second half
of league play, we said, `Hey, we've just got to get in the NCAA
Tournament.' Then we got in and we thought, `OK, that's it. Here we
go.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what this team feels. We know the bottom, and just like
in 1980, everybody's aspiring to see what the upside is.''
</P>
<P>
   +++++
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were plagued by inconsistency in 1980, just as they
have been this season. They won at Washington by 15 points one
night, lost by 16 at Washington State two days later. They won at
Arizona by 12, then lost at Arizona State by 12.
</P>
<P>
   They relied heavily on a freshman, guard Rod Foster, just as
these Bruins rely on freshman forward Jason Kapono.
</P>
<P>
   They had a freshman point guard, Holton, who encountered some of
the same problems as Earl Watson, a junior in his first year as
point guard.
</P>
<P>
   They struggled with the complicated offense Brown brought from
his tenure with the NBA's Denver Nuggets, just as these Bruins
struggled with their new attack, the 1-4 high.
</P>
<P>
   Their ballhandling blunders peaked with a 24-turnover game at
Washington State, just as these Bruins committed 24 turnovers in
their 29-point loss at Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much talent on this team,'' Bruins forward Darrell
Allums said in 1980. ``When we rebound, play defense, run and take
care of the ball . . . it's difficult to stop us.''
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar?
</P>
<P>
   Brown made two January adjustments that turned the season. He
simplified the offense by abandoning NBA plays and concentrating on
John Wooden's famed high post. He also benched unproductive
veterans like Allums, Gig Sims and Tyren Naulls in favor of the
freshman guards and sophomore center Mike Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   As the return of JaRon Rush has energized these Bruins, so did
the lineup shuffle 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's moves did not have an immediate effect, but by mid-
February the Bruins were gaining momentum. They won four in a row,
lost at Arizona State, then avenged the earlier loss by beating
Washington State in Pauley Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Brown started his seniors in the home finale against Washington,
then watched the Huskies build a big lead behind guard Lorenzo
Romar (18 points) and hold on for a 72-70 upset. The loss dropped
UCLA to 15-9, its tournament chances fading fast.
</P>
<P>
   Brown blamed himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt he had hurt the team's chances to be in the NCAAs,''
said former assistant Kevin O'Connor, now an executive with the
Utah Jazz. ``He said, `Maybe we shouldn't have done that.' But he
felt he owed it to the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Desperate, the Bruins thrashed Cal and Stanford _ the worst
teams in the league _ and then hoped for the best on Selection
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember thinking, `We're not going to get in,' '' Holton
said. ``We thought we'd be one of the worst UCLA teams ever. We
thought that would be our legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then a manager called me that morning and said we were in. I
felt like we had a new life.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ++++++
</P>
<P>
   Eager and anxious, the Bruins committed 23 turnovers in their
first-round game against Old Dominion, but senior forward Kiki
Vandeweghe's 34 points fueled a 13-point victory.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later they stunned DePaul, holding Mark Aguirre, the
nation's leading scorer, to 19 points (eight under his average).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready to play with anyone,'' Foster said at the time.
``People said we had fallen, and there was that Sports Illustrated
article (`Bruins in Ruins'). But we're a much better team than we
were at the start of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar?
</P>
<P>
   Although these Bruins have not played a tournament game, their
upset of No. 1 Stanford seemingly has filled them with the same
energy and optimism that engulfed the 1980 team after its victory
over DePaul.
</P>
<P>
   Will history repeat?
</P>
<P>
   ``When people get down on you, like they did in 1980 and like
they did this year, you feel the weight of it,'' Holton said.
``Then you reach a point that you can either give up, or pick
yourself up. When the pendulum swings, the result is a lot of
momentum. It happened in 1980, and we're feeling it now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 0056EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
