<SLUG> BC-L.A.-POLICE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES OFFICIALS FEUD OVER INQUIRY INTO POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ADDS sentence in third graf from end clarifying position of U.S.
attorney) (bl)  
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A simmering feud between the Los Angeles police
chief and the county district attorney over the handling of a major
police corruption scandal erupted Wednesday, with the police chief
refusing to cooperate fully with the local prosecutors and then
being humiliated with a rebuke by several law-enforcement
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The chief, Bernard C. Parks, had instructed his department in
recent weeks to provide documents and other information about the
criminal investigation first to the U.S. attorney in Los Angeles,
several people close to the matter said, and only later to
prosecutors in the district attorney's office if the U.S. attorney
approved.
</P>
<P>
   In an increasingly heated exchange of letters, the district
attorney, Gil Garcetti, wrote on Tuesday that while the police
should provide information to the federal officials, that ``doesn't
relieve you of the responsibility to cooperate with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcetti said in a radio interview Wednesday, ``You cannot come
up with a valid reason why he is doing this.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the Los Angeles city attorney, James Hahn, wrote a
letter to Parks insisting that he had a legal obligation to respond
to the district attorney's requests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police chief cannot pick and choose which prosecutors he
deals with,'' Hahn said in an interview, adding that the chief had
never informed him about his resistance or asked for legal advice.
</P>
<P>
   Hahn also said Parks had told him Wednesday that the situation
had been blow out of proportion and misinterpreted. Cmdr. David
Kalish, the department's chief spokesman, did not return calls
Wednesday seeking comment, but he was quoted in The Los Angeles
Times on Wednesday morning saying, ``It doesn't make sense to work
with two prosecutorial agencies simultaneously and have two
parallel investigations. This is the best approach. The cases will
be taken directly to the U.S. attorney, who will make the
appropriate prosecutorial decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The California attorney general, Bill Lockyer, publicly rebuked
the police chief for this stand, saying, ``The current posture of
the Los Angeles Police Department, in refusing to provide
investigatory material to the district attorney is unfortunate,
counterproductive, and without legal authority.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the district attorney's office ``is the best
agency to prosecute those cases arising out of the Rampart
investigations.''
</P>
<P>
   In the scandal, centered on the Rampart station in the
inner-city here, a number of police officers have been implicated
in abuses including stealing drugs, framing innocent people,
beating suspects and shooting at least two unarmed gang members and
then planting guns on them. Hundreds of criminal convictions may be
overturned and the city is preparing for what could be more than
$200 million in civil judgments.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney, Alejandro Mayorcas, refused to comment.
People with knowledge of the investigation said Mayorcas spoke with
Parks Wednesday and made clear that he did not approve of any
refusal to provide information to the district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Parks has vigorously pursued his own investigation of the
wrongdoing and issued a stinging report on the department's
managerial lapses, but he has repeatedly fought with the district
attorney over the speed of the criminal inquiry, and he has
resisted any outside investigation of his department.
</P>
<P>
   Parks' actions also appear to have angered the Police
Commission, the department's civilian oversight body. Despite
corresponding with the district attorney's office for a week on the
problem, the chief never informed the commission of the battle,
even though there was a regularly scheduled commission meeting
Tuesday morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
