<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8425 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN-(SLAN     03-16 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS LOOK TO EXTEND WIN STREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, D.C. _ The Lakers have the Washington Wizards on the
schedule tonight.
</P>
<P>
   But actually, their date is with history.
</P>
<P>
   A victory at MCI Center would be the Lakers' 20th in a row,
matching the second-best single-season winning streak in NBA
history. The Milwaukee Bucks set that mark in 1970-71, a record
surpassed only once, by the 1971-72 Lakers who won 33 consecutive
games.
</P>
<P>
   No NBA team since has won more than 18, a span of 28 years.
</P>
<P>
   Now the current Lakers can move into another strata. Both the
1970-71 Bucks and the 1971-72 Lakers rode their streaks to the
championship.
</P>
<P>
   To this point, the Lakers have avoided using The Streak as
motivation. Each win stands alone. But tonight is different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the team will itself be motivated by that, by the fact
that they can be part of something that's historic in their own
professional lives,'' said coach Phil Jackson. ``I think that's
intriguing for them. Yet we know that we can't take anything for
granted. Washington's playing pretty good basketball right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wizards are 20-45 and still closer to the lottery than the
playoffs. But they've shown some life lately, beating the New York
Knicks and Minnesota Timberwolves last week.
</P>
<P>
   If the Lakers get by the Wizards, they'll go for win No. 21 _
and sole possession of the NBA's second-best streak _ at Detroit on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Potentially undermining all of this a hamstring injury on the
right leg of Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal has had two days of rest and therapy and though he's
unlikely to be 100 percent tonight, he vows to play through the
discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   That the Lakers are even in position to make history the next
two days is remarkable. They ran off 16 straight wins from
mid-December to mid-January, inspiring fantasies of challenging the
33-game record.
</P>
<P>
   But that streak ended with a thud, sending the Lakers into a 3-6
tailspin. Another month-long streak in the same season seemed
unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Logic dictates this streak will end too, eventually. But the
Lakers have come a long way since their late-January hangover and
show no signs of letting down again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've grown in experience, and also we`re playing much better
as a team,'' said Glen Rice, comparing the streaks. ``We have been
able to overcome the lapses we've had during our games.`'
</P>
<P>
   With the NBA's best record (53-11) and a four-game lead over
West rival Portland, the Lakers are trying to stay focused on
retaining their position, not necessarily on sustaining The Streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``The streak doesn't really motivate us,'' Rice said. ``The
thing that motivates us is we want to beat whatever teams are in
our way. If the streak continues, so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who won 18 straight as a player with the Knicks in
1969-70 and again as coach of the Chicago Bulls in 1995-96, views
it differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is special for us,'' he said, ``and we're very proud of
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's an intrigue about playing this string out,''
he said. ``Perhaps after we finish this streak and then we get into
the end of the season, we'll have to push to motivate the players
at some level, but right now, when you have a winning streak, it's
just kind of intriguing to go through it and find a way to continue
on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
