<HEADLINE>
EMERSON QUICKLY MAKES CONTRIBUTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 and 
GREG CHRISTENSEN 
San Gabriel Valley Tribune 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Nelson Emerson had a great scoring chance on
his first shift with the Kings on Wednesday against the Mighty
Ducks and assisted on Bryan Smolinski's goal midway through the
first period.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson is a five-time 20-goal scorer who will work the point on
the Kings second power-play unit. But when Emerson arrived Tuesday
with Kelly Buchberger from Atlanta, one question stood out. Why are
the Kings his seventh organization in a 10-year career?
</P>
<P>
   ``When you play on the second line, you often find yourself the
victim when things don't go right,'' Kings coach Andy Murray said.
``They don't often trade the first-line guys. They make too much
money. Second-line guys make less and move more.''
</P>
<P>
   Emerson, 32, has played with St. Louis, Winnipeg,
Hartford/Carolina, Chicago, Ottawa and Atlanta. Last season, he
played for three clubs and for the second consecutive year, Emerson
was moved at the trade deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't always easy,'' Emerson said. ``It was very difficult
last year, and this time I was very surprised that I was traded.
But I'm coming from a team that worked hard, but was overmatched
most nights, to a team that has a chance to do something in the
playoffs. That's a good feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Silent Ducks: Mighty Ducks president and general manager
Pierre Gauthier said fans must understand why the Ducks haven't
been in the blockbuster trade market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would remind them for every good player acquired one goes
the other way,'' he said. ``We have a good nucleus and we want to
keep adding to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier said the only way teams like Colorado and Detroit can
make big deals is to stockpile and ``in hockey it takes time to
build to that level.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are well into the process of building assets . . . we are
adding all the time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Fiset update: Kings goalie Stephane Fiset (groin) has skated
the last two days and could be ready to back up Jamie Storr on
Friday against St. Louis. Fiset has not played since March 4.
</P>
<P>
   __ Berg out: Aki Berg, who was hit hard and did not return in
Monday's game vs. Vancouver, did not play Wednesday. Berg was
replaced in the lineup by Jarolsav Modry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
