<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GASOLINE-PRICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: COUNTERING HIGH GASOLINE PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, La.)   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, March 16:
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline prices hover around $2 a gallon in parts of the United
States, and threaten to rise to similar levels in many other
regions. Consumers are upset, and there is no easy solution to the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans thought for a time that they had a
deft answer in going after what they called the ``Gore tax,'' the
4.3 cents per gallon that a Democrat-controlled Congress tacked
onto the federal gasoline tax in 1993. But this week Republican
leaders abandoned that frivolous idea. If it were effective,
reducing taxes on gasoline would only encourage Americans to buy
more foreign oil _ at the same time that Saudi Arabia and other oil
producers have tripled their price. But the tax cut would mostly
benefit oil companies, which could raise prices to offset it,
rather than consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Congress does have a partial remedy at hand. Lying in salt domes
in Louisiana and Texas are about 600 million barrels of oil. This
Strategic Petroleum Reserve was created to handle genuine oil
crises, not the run-up in home heating oil prices in New England in
February and in gasoline prices in March. But there is a policy,
called swaps, that would provide some relief without compromising
the use of the reserve for a future crisis. The idea is to invite
oil companies to remove oil today from the reserve, expanding the
supply and easing prices somewhat, in exchange for returning an
even larger amount of oil in the future. Swaps would knock only
about a nickel off the price of gasoline, according to one
estimate.
</P>
<P>
   The simple fact is that Americans will gain substantially lower
prices for gasoline only if oil exporters decide to increase
production by a substantial amount. The exporters will meet later
this month and discuss raising production by about 1 to 2 million
barrels a day. That could cut gasoline prices by up to 7.5 cents a
gallon. Americans can also weaken the impact of high oil prices, no
matter what the future levels, by cutting back consumption. Yet
foreign oil exports will continue to dominate America's energy
picture and will operate largely independent of what Americans do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 0203EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8438 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBITS-NYT &LR;      03-16 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OBITUARIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Hawaii, Ill., Calif., N.Y., N.J)   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jack Mann, 74, Sports Editor and Writer &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jack Mann, an award-winning sportswriter and editor, died March
11 in Columbia, Md. He was 74 and lived in Laurel, Md. The cause
was cancer, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Mann was the sports editor at Newsday from 1960 to 1962, helping
turn what had been a section with a local focus into one that
covered sports events nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   He was a two-time winner of the Eclipse Award for outstanding
writing about horse racing and the Walter Haight Award for turf
writing. He wrote ``The Decline and Fall of the New York Yankees''
(Simon &AMP; Schuster, 1966), which described how one of the great
dynasties in sports declined under the ownership of CBS.
</P>
<P>
   John Austin Mann Jr., who was born in Brooklyn, worked for The
New York Herald Tribune, The Washington Daily News, The Washington
Star, The Baltimore Evening Sun, The Racing Times, The Washington
Times, The Miami Herald, The Detroit Free Press and Sports
Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   Mann is survived by eight children: Karen Stevenson, vice
president and general counsel of Knight-Ridder Inc. in San
Francisco; Alan of Long Island, Steven of Richmond, Va., David of
New York and Donald of Ashland, Ore., from a first marriage;
Katherine of McLean, Va., and Jeffrey of Santa Cruz, Calif.; and a
stepson, Devin Mann of Los Angeles, from a second marriage.
</P>
<P>
   His first marriage, to Edythe Vaughan Stevenson, ended in
divorce in 1966. His second marriage, to Judith Warden Luce, now
Judy Mann, a columnist for The Washington Post, ended in divorce in
1983.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Sullivan, 63; Led Turnpike Unit &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Sullivan, a New Jersey businessman who ran unsuccessfully
for governor and later served as chairman of the New Jersey
Turnpike Authority, died March 13 at a hospital in Morristown, N.J.
He was 63.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a stroke, said a son, Edward Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, who lived in New Vernon, N.J., spent $1 million and
came in third in the Republican primary in 1981, behind Thomas
Kean, who became governor, and former Paterson Mayor Lawrence
Kramer. After the election, Kean appointed Sullivan to head the
turnpike authority. Sullivan was later also appointed finance
chairman of the state's Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Known as Bo, Sullivan was born on Feb. 10, 1937, in Manhattan.
He graduated from Princeton University and earned a law degree from
Seton Hall University.
</P>
<P>
   Before entering politics, Sullivan was president and chief
executive of Bomont Industries, based in West Caldwell, N.J., that
once produced typewriter ribbons but now specializes in laser
printers and industrial fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his son, Edward, who lives in Hoboken, Sullivan is
survived by his wife, Eileen; three other sons, Joseph of Mendham,
N.J.; Michael of Bernardsville, N.J., and James of Mendham, and 10
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Dreier, 83, Broadcast Journalist Who Won 7 Emmys &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Dreier, a broadcaster who was known for his reports
from Europe during World War II and who later worked as a
television journalist in Southern California and Chicago, died
March 12 at his home in Rancho Mirage, Calif. He was 83.
</P>
<P>
   Dreier was born in Honolulu on June 26, 1916. He became a
reporter for United Press and went to Europe soon after his
graduation from Stanford University in 1939. In 1941 he was
expelled by the Nazis and moved to London, where he worked for the
BBC.
</P>
<P>
   From 1948 to 1965 he worked for local radio and television
affiliates of NBC and ABC in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   In 1967 he moved to Los Angeles. He continued reporting in
California for several television stations until 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Renowned for his thunderous delivery, Dreier, who once weighed
more than 400 pounds, won seven Emmy Awards during his career.
</P>
<P>
   More recently he served as chairman of the board of the
Annenberg Center for Health Sciences in Rancho Mirage.
</P>
<P>
   He also served on the board of directors for the Eisenhower
Medical Center there.
</P>
<P>
   No immediate family members survive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
