<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8440 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-NY-PATAKI-NYT &LR;      03-16 0436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-PATAKI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ENLIGHTENED STEPS BY PATAKI 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, March 16:
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki of New York offered constructive proposals
this week on two issues he had previously neglected _ gun control
and ballot reform. The gun proposal probably ends any hope he once
had of receiving the Republican vice presidential nomination, but
these are good moves for New York that will help position Pataki as
a moderate should he seek a third term as governor.
</P>
<P>
   The legislative package on guns is still being worked on. But
its outline includes a ban on assault weapons, background checks
for guns purchased at gun shows and flea markets, raising the age
for purchasing guns from 18 to 21, ballistics fingerprinting of all
new guns to make it easier to trace guns used in crimes, and a
requirement that gun dealers provide a separate trigger lock with
every sale.
</P>
<P>
   The state Senate majority leader, Joseph Bruno, a Republican,
said Wednesday that his chamber was already preparing to act on
trigger locks and the assault weapons ban, and that he was open to
considering Pataki's other proposals _ an encouraging sign for
tangible progress this session.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki stops short of endorsing a strict limit on multiple
handgun purchases, as called for by President Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore. Nonetheless, in bucking the National Rifle
Association to protect public safety, the governor has set a
commendable example for other Republican governors and for
Republican leaders in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   On ballot issues, Pataki clearly heard the public's outrage when
he tried, unsuccessfully, to block Sen. John McCain from competing
statewide in the recent Republican presidential primary. The
aggressive ballot reform plan he unveiled Monday begins to make
amends for that shabby episode, even if it took pressure from Bruno
to finally goad the governor into action.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's bill would automatically put all recognized
candidates on the Republican presidential primary ballot, sparing
them the onerous petition process that poses a special obstacle for
insurgents. The measure would also end the state GOP's galling
practice of listing delegates' names in big type on the ballot,
with the presidential candidates listed below in small print.
Instead, voters would cast ballots directly for candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The plan's key flaw is that it would make the Republican contest
a winner-take-all affair _ an approach that would perpetuate the
overriding importance of backing from the party machine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 0204EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8442 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     03-16 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICE-GUY ZAGS WANT TO PROVE THEY'RE NO FLUKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ Let's face it. They're still a good story.
</P>
<P>
   And as much as they chafe and act suspicious about how the world
tries to turn them into the quaintest, greatest, underdogish little
basketball team in all of Division I, that's our story and we're
sticking to it.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga is back. A No. 10 seed again, but who's counting? They
are ready to roll against seventh-seeded Louisville this evening at
the McKale Center and we're here to say sorry to the Bulldogs from
Spokane.
</P>
<P>
   We know it makes them a little ornery to be treated like the
nice guys whose biggest, best contribution to the NCAA tournament
is to boost its purity quotient.
</P>
<P>
   Is there any reason to think otherwise when TV has put Gonzaga
on during prime time?
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Oklahoma, seeded third in the West, is stuck with a
morning start. Same with Purdue. The Boilermakers are seeded sixth
but their game against Dayton isn't marquee material.
</P>
<P>
   Not so the Zags. They are still the innocents, the darlings with
star appeal _ a notion that did not go unnoticed by their
Louisville opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We read the newspapers. We watch `SportsCenter.' We know
everyone's calling us the underdogs,'' Cardinals forward Tony
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``USA Today came to my hotel doorstep and there wasn't anything
about Louisville in it. It was all about Gonzaga. But we'll show
you on the court what we think about all that.''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the Zags wish their portrayal was a little different _
less Pollyanna and more piranha.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did lose a little toughness'' with the departure of 1999
tournament spark plug Quentin Hall and injured senior guard Mike
Nilson, senior guard Matt Santangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's a lot of fire in that locker room. A lot of people
have something to prove.''
</P>
<P>
   Prove? What could the
six-points-away-from-playing-in-the-1999-Final-Four Zags possibly
have left to prove?
</P>
<P>
   ``That last year wasn't a fluke,'' Santangelo said. ``There are
some people who will take it as it was _ an individual year where a
good basketball team got hot. But if we do it two years in a row,
then we're on our way to accomplishing our goal of establishing
tradition at Gonzaga.''
</P>
<P>
   Santangelo and his teammates valiantly try to retain their
refined edginess. But even they understand they can't quite pull
off the part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure most people look at us and wouldn't find us to be the
most intimidating athletes,'' Gonzaga forward Casey Calvary said.
</P>
<P>
   And thank goodness, because the Zags still serve this important
role of lovable underdogs. They're the Little Engine That Could.
They are the antidote to the machines and the messes out there
littering the college basketball landscape.
</P>
<P>
   After all, here we are in the desert on the eve of the West
subregional. But instead of palm trees and happy-go-lucky
pretourney euphoria, it feels like we're stuck in the Garden of
Good and Evil.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it would be more polite to call it the Garden of Darkness
and Light. The entire college basketball season is reaching this
pinnacle stretch of March Madness in the throes of serious woes _
and the storm clouds aren't quite lifting.
</P>
<P>
   This college hoops season has been punctuated with NCAA probes
into cars, jewelry and prep school tuition. It has been all about
player suspensions and the subsequent name-calling by coaches and
the demand for change in the way ``student-athletes'' should be
compensated through their scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Even as St. John's, the No. 2 seed in the West, was preparing
for its cross-country trip from New York, NCAA investigators were
peppering point guard Erick Barkley and forward Lavor Postell about
more possible NCAA violations.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Johnnies are in the clear, which means they can go
far.
</P>
<P>
   And they arrived in the desert with an obvious public relations
campaign in regards to their sincerity and sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took care of business (with the NCAA questions) and we're
here to get back to academics and playing basketball,'' Postell
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``St. John's is a great institution. My kids are as fine of kids
as anywhere else in the country, be it Duke, North Carolina or
anywhere.'' St. John's coach Mike Jarvis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't done anything different. Trust me. All this
attention bestowed to us, we didn't ask for it and it might not
have happened if things were handled differently. But maybe
something good will come out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the oddest thing, really. The teams with tarnished
reputations and uneasy standing with the NCAA are going out of
their way to create a good-guy image.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Zags are still trying to perfect their persona of
tough guys who won't back down to anyone, anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Mispronounce Gonzaga and they'll shoot a killer look.
</P>
<P>
   Assume that they aren't hungry enough to do what they did last
year, they'll aim to shoot your lights out.
</P>
<P>
   But just as soon as the Zags start to make you believe they're
slightly thuggish in their attitude, out comes a revelation that
returns them to their good-story status.
</P>
<P>
   When their flight from Spokane was delayed four hours, the Zags
arrived at their Tucson hotel Wednesday at 4 a.m. and were found
unpacking their own bags from the bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's standard Gonzaga behavior,'' coach Mark Few gushed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They unload their own bags. They'll sweep the floors. They'll
clean out the locker room. They're the kind of kids you hope as a
parent your kids grow up to be like,'' Few said.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's time for the fellas to try to live down their
boys-next-door reputations one more time.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
