<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8456 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BKC-GONZAGA-SPI &LR;      03-16 1304
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-GONZAGA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZAGS' MIGHTY CASEY BEST WITH SPOTLIGHT SHINING BRIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Before Gonzaga discovered it was heading to Tucson for
its first game in the NCAA tournament, somebody wondered whether
Casey Calvary had a preference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there any place you'd rather not go?'' he was asked.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo, Minneapolis, Cleveland ... they were all plausible
answers. But Calvary came up with the best reply, never hesitating,
proving that even off the court, he is quick on his feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home,'' Calvary said, knowing that when Gonzaga falls, the
curtain will, too.
</P>
<P>
   Spokane is not the destination until April 4, the day after the
national championship game. Until then, Calvary's itinerary calls
for two more days in Tucson followed by a stop in Albuquerque on
the way to the Final Four in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   This afternoon, dry-witted Calvary and his Gonzaga teammates go
from the deadpan to the fire, meeting Louisville in a West Region
first-round game. Just like last year, the Bulldogs are underdogs,
oddsmakers favoring Louisville by two points.
</P>
<P>
   A Cinderella short story? One-and-out from tourney-tested
Gonzaga? Maybe so or maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   The scenario is similar to last year when the Bulldogs came to
KeyArena, also as a No. 10 seed, and knocked off Minnesota. They
then beat second-seeded Stanford and proceeded to knock off Florida
before losing to eventual champion Connecticut. This year No. 2
seed St. John's likely looms in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   That would be an interesting matchup featuring Gonzaga's
goody-two-shoes against a St. John's team with two players, Erick
Barkley and Lavar Postell, being investigated by the NCAA for
possible infractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any ties with agents,'' Calvary said. ``There's
none of that stuff. It's a different program, so clean, so upright.
People know better than to talk to GU people. It's a waste of
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The straight arrows hit the bull's-eye last year. Calvary
climaxed the run by tipping in the game-winner against Florida,
creating a national following for the Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   It also led to heightened media interest, the kind of attention
that Calvary understands and appreciates. But he would prefer the
shadows to the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't take it too seriously,'' said his father, Roger.
``He'd much rather be with his friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Because he plays the game so well, Calvary is best known as a
6-foot-8 junior forward who can drift outside or bang underneath,
bringing intensity to every possession. Powerful in the paint, he's
Casey at the rack. Calvary is also athletic and active. He can
block shots. Scouts notice his range, jumping ability and desire.
</P>
<P>
   ``He plays with integrity and respects the game,'' said Billy
McKinney, Sonics executive vice president of basketball operations.
``You can't go wrong with drafting a player like that. I like him.
He could potentially be a first-round pick.''
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, the cameras, microphones and dot-coms will be
coming at him, seeking whatever is on his mind, searching for newsy
nuggets from his past. This is what they'll find:
</P>
<P>
   An Army brat who zig-Zagged around the country, if you will.
Born in Germany, Calvary spent time in Alabama and California
before his helicopter pilot dad landed at Fort Lewis when Casey was
in the fifth grade.
</P>
<P>
   It was then that Roger Calvary saw his youngest son begin to
dominate on the basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   ``He started guarding the whole other team,'' Roger said. ``I
had to get him to let his teammates cover their men. He said: `No,
dad, they're going to score.'''
</P>
<P>
   So the competitive Calvary showed up early.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when we walked across the street, Casey had to get to the
other side first,'' Roger said.
</P>
<P>
   At Bellarmine Prep in Tacoma, Calvary distinguished himself as a
developing prospect, albeit a skinny one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him: `If you want to be an impact player, you're going
to have to find the weight room,''' Bellarmine coach Bernie Salazar
said. ``I only had to tell him once.''
</P>
<P>
   Calvary looks toned now, the muscles backing up his aggressive
nature. During one high school game against Foss, three Lions
verbally and physically harassed Calvary in the post.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's because he's a junior and people don't want to respect
his game,'' said Calvary's teammate, Damone Harrison. ``But they
will.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a coming attraction. Sir Mix-It-Up exchanged elbows and
shoves with Florida's Major Parker in the tournament last year.
Glares and snarls appeared on Calvary's face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an anger management problem,'' Calvary said in jest
after the game. ``Sometimes I want to turn these games into a
boxing match.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the gloves are always off elsewhere. Calvary enjoys spending
time with his girlfriend, Megan Hoseth, and hanging out with his
roommates, David Michelson and Riley Finnigan, former Bellarmine
classmates attending Eastern Washington University.
</P>
<P>
   Calvary is all of those hyphenated words rolled into one:
easy-going, laid-back, straight-forward. Supportive and sensitive
work, too.
</P>
<P>
   When Dan Monson took over as head coach at Gonzaga, he wondered
if Calvary would still sign a letter of intent. Calvary had been
recruited by outgoing coach Dan Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado State wanted Calvary. So did Arizona and Stanford.
Calvary liked the small school feel and camaraderie at Gonzaga
whether Fitzgerald was there or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``He believed in me before anybody else did,'' said Monson, now
the coach at Minnesota. ``Casey will always be a special player to
me. Before I coached a game, he took a leap of faith in me.''
</P>
<P>
   Which made it extremely difficult for Monson to leave Gonzaga
last October. He preached loyalty to his players, and now he was
defecting in large part because of financial reasons, to secure his
family's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I thought of was Casey,'' Monson said.
</P>
<P>
   How would he react? What would he say? They clicked from the
beginning, two strong-willed competitors who also shared, in
Monson's words, a ``screw-around side.''
</P>
<P>
   Monson walked into Gonzaga's gym, The Kennel, where the Bulldogs
were engaged in a pickup game of shirts-and-skins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really uncomfortable,'' Monson said. ``I knew there
would be some feelings of betrayal. But as soon as the game was
over, Casey walked over and, all sweaty, gave me a great big hug.''
</P>
<P>
   Calvary also told Monson that if Minneapolis ever became lonely
and miserable to give him a call.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's tough back there, I'll talk to you,'' Calvary said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Casey's just Casey,'' Monson said.
</P>
<P>
   That being the case, you can expect Calvary to shine Thursday.
He puts up his biggest numbers against the toughest competition,
most recently reflected by the 28 points he scored against
Pepperdine in the West Coast Conference tournament championship.
After the game, Louisville coach Denny Crum probably will be
talking about how the Cardinals tried to stop him but couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   His parents and older brother, Andy, a senior at Washington
State, will be in their seats at McKale Center. Superstitious
supporters, his mom, Cathy, a history teacher at Mason Middle
School, will wear her lucky horseshoe belt and Andy will wear
basketball shorts that his brother gave him.
</P>
<P>
   In Minneapolis, Monson will be getting home from a recruiting
trip in Hutchinson, Kan., around 9 p.m. local time, right when
Gonzaga and Louisville are in the waning minutes. That's not a
problem: He plans to videotape the game and watch it without
knowing the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   And around the country, they will tune in to see if Calvary's
road trip and the Gonzaga magic continue.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Jim Moore can be reached at 206-448-8013
</P>
<P>
   or jimmoore &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
