<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD BACK TO KEEP ARIZONA'S WOODS OUT OF TOURNAMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ As blows go, this one would knock out any other
team but the Arizona Wildcats. Or so they contended Wednesday after
learning that Loren Woods will not play in the NCAA tournament
because of a back injury.
</P>
<P>
   Woods is expected to make a full recovery, but he needs more
rest to heal a compressed disc. The 7-foot-1 junior center believes
he suffered the injury Jan. 26 at Arizona State and aggravated it
five games later on Feb. 12 at Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got worse when I fell in Pullman,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   A transfer from Wake Forest, Woods was the Pac-10 newcomer of
the year and probably would have been player of the year had he not
missed Arizona's last six games.
</P>
<P>
   He averaged 15.6 points and 7.5 rebounds but was even more of a
factor as a shot-blocker and intimidator who turned away
trespassers in the lane. Woods blocked a school-record 102 shots,
including 14 in one game against Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Woods' absence changes everything and nothing for the Wildcats,
who at least are accustomed to adversity. Because of injuries and
transfers and personal decisions, Arizona, which opens tournament
play Thursday against Jackson State, went most of the season with
seven scholarship players. For the most part, the Wildcats
responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like something has changed for us because it's been
this way for so long,'' said coach Lute Olson.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona overcame the biggest setback _ Richard Jefferson's
broken foot _ to earn a share of the Pac-10 title with Stanford.
The Wildcats defeated Stanford once without Jefferson and did it
again last Thursday without Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson, a sophomore forward, returned March 2 after missing
nearly two months and has played in four games. His body took a
jolt, but his confidence was intact Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can beat a No. 1 seed without Loren, we can beat anybody
in the country,'' Jefferson said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Woods: ``We still have a chance to win the national
championship. But taking me out of the equation hurts a little
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Olson said the Wildcats should not be affected on offense.
Without Woods, power forward Michael Wright has more room to
maneuver inside. Justin Wessel can operate more effectively on the
perimeter. Bill Walton's son, Luke, should continue to flash his
all-around savvy.
</P>
<P>
   With gifted freshman guards Jason Gardner and Gilbert Arenas
sprinting through seams and pulling up for 3s, Arizona has ample
scorers.
</P>
<P>
   But the Wildcats won't have the one-man clean-up crew at the
defensive end. Arizona can't gamble on the wings because Woods
isn't there anymore to help out. With Woods, Arizona limited
opponents to less than 40-percent shooting. Without him, all six
opponents shot better than 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Defiant nonetheless, the West's No. 1 seed carries on. Woods
will remain an example on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still a leader, still a captain,'' he said. ``I can't be
moping. My teammates see that and it will be lost hope for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati was severely weakened by the loss of Kenyon Martin,
the national player of the year who broke his right leg last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to have a Cincinnati situation here,'' Woods
said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had played his last game with Arizona, Woods, a
certain lottery pick if he were to leave a year early, gave a vague
reply.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I'm not thinking about that. It's too big of a
distraction,'' Woods said, knowing there have been enough already.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Jim Moore can be reached at 206-448-8013
</P>
<P>
   or jimmoore &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
