<HEADER>
A8471 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-KINGS-DUCKS-LADN     03-16 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIE HURTS DUCKS MORE THAN KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Another night, another opportunity lost for the Mighty
Ducks in their frustrating attempt to battle back into the Western
Conference playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   Desperately needing two points, the Ducks had to settle for one
in a 2-2 tie with the Kings before a sellout crowd of 17,174 at The
Pond on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The point moved Anaheim ahead of Calgary into sole possession of
ninth place, but the Ducks fell six points back of San Jose and
Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   Firmly entrenched in a playoff spot, the fifth-place Kings moved
two points ahead of Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Wednesday was a microcosm of the Ducks' season:
They outplayed their opponent but blew a two-goal lead and lost
ground in the playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   With only 11 games remaining, Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg said
there's no time to dwell on results, especially with San Jose
coming to town Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great game,'' he said. ``I thought we were good for
65 minutes. We played our hearts out, and that's all I can ask. We
would have liked two points, but now we have to get ready for San
Jose.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks outshot the Kings 39-22 and, to make the result even
more frustrating, they were unable to score on a 4-on-3 power play
in overtime. Two Kings broke their sticks at one point, but Jamie
Storr stopped both Paul Kariya and Fredrik Olausson on great
scoring chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the puck in the slot and were firing away, what are you
going to do?'' Hartsburg asked.
</P>
<P>
   It's getting close to do-or-die time for the Ducks, and that
added intensity showed, especially in Anaheim's physical style of
play. Rookie defenseman Vitaly Vishnevski was especially active,
knocking Ziggy Palffy out of the game in the third period with a
clean check that sent the Kings' star winger to the dressing room
in the third period with a strained right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a playoff game,'' Hartsburg said. ``I don't think
either coach could ask for much more from his team.''
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim led 2-0 in the first period on goals by Steve Rucchin
and Oleg Tverdovsky, on the second and third shots of the game.
</P>
<P>
   But no lead is a safe lead with the Ducks these days.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Smolinski turned the game back around by himself. He
pulled the Kings within 2-1 with his 19th goal of the season at
9:40 of the first period. He tied the score when he ripped a slap
shot from the high slot that appeared to skip just before Hebert
and beat him inside the left post 59 seconds into the second
period.
</P>
<P>
   The first Anaheim power play of the night was headed in reverse
until Tverdovsky took a big hit to keep the puck in at the left
point. The Ducks defenseman slid it over to Olausson and his
harmless-looking wrist shot was deflected past Storr by Rucchin at
4:02.
</P>
<P>
   Rucchin's 16th goal of the season was the 100th of his career.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks' second power-play goal came much easier. The Kings
left Tverdovsky alone in the left circle, and he had virtually all
day to beat Storr for his 13th goal of the season at 8:53, just 19
seconds after Ian Laperriere had elbowed Jeff Nielsen.
</P>
<P>
   But the Ducks' two-goal advantage was short lived. Glen Murray
passed the puck to Smolinski, who drove hard to the net and beat
Hebert just inside the right post.
</P>
<P>
   The goal was just the second in 14 games for Smolinski, whose
only other goal in recent weeks was an empty-netter.
</P>
<P>
   After giving up the two early goals, Storr answered every
Anaheim challenge. In the first period the Kings' goalie stopped
Kariya on a 2-on-1 break, just barely got a toe on the wraparound
try by Matt Cullen and kicked out his left leg pad just in time to
stop Kip Miller's bid from the slot.
</P>
<P>
   In the second period, Kariya made a great move to split the
Kings' defense, but Storr got his glove on the Anaheim winger's
shot.
</P>
<P>
   Hebert was knocked out of the St. Louis game last Saturday and
hadn't practiced since, but he looked especially sharp after
Smolinski's second goal. In less than a minute midway through
second period he stopped both Murray and Nelson Emerson twice. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
