<HEADLINE>
`THE NEW AMERICANS': A SPECIAL 9-PART `ECONOMIST' U.S. SURVEY  
 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   This nine-part package of articles on the changing face of
America _ ``The New Americans'' _ is from the March 11 issue of The
ECONOMIST magazine. They have all moved to the ``k'' commentary
category code.  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use _ free of charge _ by clients of The
Economist. Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special
arrangement. For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OH, SAY, CAN YOU SEE?: IMMIGRATION IS RESHAPING AMERICA &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-US-SURVEY-1-OF-9-ECONOMIST-600&AMP;add-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1st of 9-part special Economist Survey, `The New Americans') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950 census, America was 89 percent white and 10 percent
black. Other races hardly got a passing glance. Now Latinos account
for around 12 percent of the population; within the next five
years, they will overtake blacks to become the largest minority
group. This survey will seek to answer three fundamental questions:
Is the melting pot still working? Is it good for America? And how
will this latest wave of New Americans change their chosen
country? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By John Micklethwait, The Economist &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Three trims, totaling 850 words; total uncut is 2,050) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GIVE ME YOUR TIRED, YOUR CONFUSED: AMERICA'S IMMIGRATION
MUDDLE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-US-SURVEY-2-OF-9-ECONOMIST-425&AMP;add-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (2nd of 9-part special Economist Survey, `The New Americans') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   America's immigration law is rather like a hedgehog: it has a
hard, prickly exterior, but its center is surprisingly soft. The
rules that govern immigrants' entry into America and their legal
status thereafter are, in turn, contradictory, disingenuous,
hypocritical, downright cruel and ridiculously overly generous.
Were they to be efficiently enforced, the result would be total
chaos. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By John Micklethwait, The Economist &QL;
