<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 10:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8564 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN19-CO     03-16 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Why refugees ride the waves
 &HT;    (For release March 19, 2000.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As with the American economy, the rich of the Dominican Republic
are getting richer and the poor are getting poorer, even desperate.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S., of course, operates at a higher level (of richness and
poverty), and being dirt poor in the Dominican Republic is being,
well, dirt poor.
</P>
<P>
   In the Dominican Republic today, it is estimated that 60 percent
of the population lives in poverty. As pointed out in a recent
Miami Herald article, the per-capita income is $1,600 a year. In
the U.S., the amount is $27,000.
</P>
<P>
   President Leonel Fernandez, who cannot seek re-election in May,
has had a partly fruitful reign in that he has introduced modern
life to the country; computers, telephones, education programs.
Along with that, Fernandez has opened his country to foreign
investment, and it has been pouring in.
</P>
<P>
   Santo Domingo is undergoing a building boom, tourism is at its
best ever and the Dominican Republic is seen as the area's
fastest-growing economy.
</P>
<P>
   Why, then, are there boat people? Why are Dominicans risking
their lives _ often losing them _ to get to Puerto Rico and what
they consider to be greater economic opportunities?
</P>
<P>
   The word ``oligarchy'' comes into play. An oligarchy occurs when
a relatively few people hold all the power. An oligarchy was when
the Somoza family ruled Nicaragua from 1937 until 1979. What has
happened in the Dominican Republic is not an oligarchy in the sense
of the same people being in unremitting power. Instead, it is a
nation where the political pendulum has swung far in either
direction, yet despite that diversity of government, everything
seems to stay the same for most of the people.
</P>
<P>
   It reminds me of Ronald Reagan's attempt at a ``trickle-down
economy'' that became more of a ``trickle-up economy,'' the rich
getting richer and the poor, at best, staying in place. That
situation still permeates the American economy. Our levels of
poverty remain constant while at already existing upper echelons,
the profits become greater.
</P>
<P>
   The boat people of the Dominican Republic represent those who
have exhausted every possible chance of living within the existing
economy. Their desperation for a better life is so great that they
gamble with small boats in a body of water notorious for its swift
currents.
</P>
<P>
   Often the results are disastrous. This month, heavy surf ripped
apart a wooden vessel carrying 70 people toward Puerto Rico. At
least 10 died and as many as 30 are missing.
</P>
<P>
   In January, a similar incident happened. It is estimated that
5,000 undocumented Dominicans have reached Puerto Rico in the past
two years and scampered into the countryside. The estimates of
those who have lost their lives in the attempt reach into the
hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   What does that have to say about the Dominican Republic's
ascending stature as an economic success? What it tells me is that
the folks already at the top _ the economic oligarchy _ are having
wonderful days while the others look across the treacherous
75-mile-wide Canal de la Mona for their better days.
</P>
<P>
   The movement of peoples throughout the Caribbean Basin is now
and always has been about economics. The boatloads of Cubans who
take aim at South Florida are coming here to make for a better
life; they really are apolitical.
</P>
<P>
   I am somewhat reminded of a time long ago when I was speaking
with an Arab merchant who was selling goat heads in the Arab
Quarter of Jerusalem. The Israelis had recently taken the city and
I asked the gnarled old merchant what that meant to him.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't mention politics, and not a word about Allah. ``I
don't care who runs the place,'' he told me. ``I just want to make
a living.''
</P>
<P>
   This is what moves people around the Caribbean, principally
toward U.S. territories. They just want to make a living. The
economic oligarchies of the region often make that unobtainable.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1031EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
