<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 10:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8565 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN19-COX     03-16 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: PETA milks its sacred cows
 &HT;    (Eds: Please note the clarification of a previous column at the
end of this column.)
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Good news. Beer is health food.
</P>
<P>
   To thank for this welcome intelligence, we have, oddly, the
organization People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals.
</P>
<P>
   PETA is running ads that mimic the milk mongers' famous ad
featuring milk mustaches on over-hyped celebrities. Where the dairy
industry asks, ``Got milk?,'' the animal rights folks ask, ``Got
beer?''
</P>
<P>
   The ads are to run in college newspapers and are just one more
sign that today's youth are a sorry lot. When I was in college, we
didn't need any prodding to drink beer. What is the world coming
to?
</P>
<P>
   PETA is busily trying to explain that it is not really promoting
campus boozing but means only to discourage the nation's youth from
falling into the wastrel ways of imbibing milk. PETA spokesfolk say
college kids are savvy enough to get the right message without
thinking PETA really-really wants them to start pouring beer over
their Cap'n Crunch.
</P>
<P>
   The better choice for college students, PETA says, is soy milk.
PETA is serious about that.
</P>
<P>
   Dairy industry people insist that a happy cow gives more and
better milk than a peeved one, so farmers, far from annoying their
herds, are doing all they can to jolly up the ladies.
</P>
<P>
   PETA, however, has got it into its head that 1) actual milk is
bad for you _ the fat, you know _ and 2) milking cows is animal
abuse, a sort of bovine sexual harassment in the workplace, I
guess.
</P>
<P>
   This sets up a bit of a problem. Inasmuch as, if we shouldn't
milk cows, then we certainly shouldn't eat them _ eating them is
even more abusive _ just what are we to do with all these cows?
Perhaps, given PETA's sensitivity, take up a collection to send
them to St. Tropez and wish them happy grazing.
</P>
<P>
   While that is being worked out, Mothers Against Drunk Driving
has come utterly unglued. (Did you notice I didn't write
``udderly''? Do I get credit for that?)
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for MADD says her organization is concerned and
appalled, which, when you think about it, MADD usually is.
</P>
<P>
   Neither PETA nor MADD is known for its sense of whimsy, so what
we have here is a clash of titans, of a sort, as two of the
nation's most monumentally earnest organizations collide. It is as
if the Anti-Saloon League and the Ethical Culturalists were
fighting it out on World Wrestling Federation. The action is
amusing, and whichever outfit prevails, not much harm will be done.
</P>
<P>
   The only disappointment is that PETA shied from declaring
beer-drinking what it actually is _ liquid vegetarianism. Maybe
those ads are in the works.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: In a recent column, I cited President Clinton's claim that
13 children a day die from gunshots, some 4,700 annually. ``Youths
and children'' would be more accurate, and Clinton's numbers were a
year or so out of date. Based on data from a 1998 report by the
Center for Health Statistics, the daily average was 11.5, or about
4,200 a year, aged 19 and younger.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
