<P>
   EDWARDS-TRIAL (Baton Rouge, La.) _ Jurors in the Louisiana
gambling license corruption case got a close look at what former
Gov. Edwin W. Edwards apparently did with some of the $400,000 he
allegedly received from then-San Francisco 49ers owner Eddie
DeBartolo in return for assurances that DeBartolo's company would
be awarded a riverboat casino license. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   BRONCO-VERDICT (San Francisco) _ A jury has awarded a San
Francisco insurance executive and his wife more than $26 million
after his Ford Bronco II rolled over and left him a quadriplegic.
Ford Motor Company attorneys said they would ask a judge to reduce
or throw out the award, and may appeal the verdict. By PETER
HARTLAUB.
</P>
<P>
   EMPTY-TRUCKS (Brownsville, Texas) _ A government study says
nearly half the cargo trucks crossing from Mexico into the United
States are empty, contributing to chronic traffic problems and the
slow movement of commerce across the border. But federal officials,
ever wary of the drug trade and illegal immigration, say they must
inspect commercial vehicles _ empty or not. By ALISON GREGOR. (For
release Sunday, March 19.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCE (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WIRELESS-WORLD (San Francisco) _ For the Luddites of the world,
there's good news and bad. First the good stuff: You won't be wired
in the future. Now the bad: Instead of being wired, you'll be
connected seamlessly to a wireless world of networked chips,
software and sensors, plugging you in whether you like it or not.
Resistance, of course, is futile. By ALAN T. SARACEVIC.
</P>
<P>
   TALKING-ATMS (San Francisco) _ Bank of America plans to install
more than 2,500 ``talking'' ATMs in Florida and California as the
start of a nationwide effort to make the machines accessible to the
blind. By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
