<HEADER>
A8598 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-BORDERS-COLUMN17-COX     03-16 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    I'm behind a lens again, but it's temporary
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ I'm too old to be doing this: Climbing up a
metal ladder onto a catwalk above the basketball floor at Johnson
Coliseum on the SFA campus to turn on the remote flashes my former
photographer set up to deliver ``Sports Illustrated'' shots of
games here. I tippy-toe along the catwalk, illogically convinced I
will plunge to my death at any second through the mesh steel, my
only consolation being I'm likely to make the front page if that
happens. Descending safely, I sit on a hardwood floor, propping up
an impossibly heavy camera on my shoulder. This camera is
technologically so far advanced beyond my capabilities as to not be
terribly funny.
</P>
<P>
   The fear of falling through the catwalk reminds me of a recent
encounter at the country club, when several of us were deep in our
cups and talking about a golf trip via a single-engine airplane to
Louisiana. This was not long after Payne Stewart, one of my golf
heroes, died when his Lear jet went down. A friend was criticizing
our headline, which read, ``Golfer Payne Stewart, four others, die
in air crash.'' He took umbrage at relegating the others to ``four
other'' status. I don't disagree, one life being as important as
another and all that. Still, I pointed out, since he was the pilot
on this vaguely planned trip, that if we crashed, in our newspaper
the headline would read: ``Sentinel publisher, three others, die in
plane crash.'' Hey, it's an imperfect business.
</P>
<P>
   My back hurts. I'm sleepy. People in the audience keep coming up
to me and asking what exactly am I doing down there on the floor
taking photos, my hat on backward because otherwise the camera
knocks it off when turned vertically.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is, Dave quit. Dang that Dave. He's in love and gone to
Houston to get married, after shooting for us for five years. Dave
is a fine shooter, even-tempered and fairly normal for a
photographer. My only tense moment with Dave was when I realized he
had been wearing the same pair of jeans with holes at the knees for
five days. I called him in and told him he would be covering
junior-high volleyball in Bobo if he didn't change pants. He said,
``Cool, dude,'' and changed pants.
</P>
<P>
   Dave fell in love and left town, and I'm sure he will do well,
both in marriage and in his career. He has the eye, which is what
counts in photography. The technical stuff is easy. You're born
with the eye.
</P>
<P>
   I speak from experience. I started in this business as a
photographer, 30 years ago, as a part-timer for the Longview Daily
News. I worked for four different papers as a photographer/writer,
got a master's in photojournalism from UT, and then figured out I
didn't have the eye _ at least not good enough to make the big
leagues _ and so I went into management. Now I'm a jack of all
trades, master of none, knowing a tad about photography,
advertising, layout and accounting. And on this Tuesday night, with
Dave gone and all our free-lancers on vacation, I'm spending an
evening first shooting soccer, then basketball. This is great.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be great if I have to do it for the next several weeks.
My job is meetings, management, editing and public relations. I'm
not the day-to-day guy, except for the editorial page, which I
still personally produce each day. We need a shooter, another Dave.
In the meantime, we're relying heavily on a former photographer,
Hardy, and the reporters to take pictures. And me, in a pinch.
</P>
<P>
   I have fallen in love with this camera, which costs more than my
first house out in the woods. It's completely digital, meaning it
records images on a computer card instead of on film. You can take
a photo and then look at it on a tiny screen on the back of the
camera, so once you have an acceptable photo you can leave.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, my brief lesson from Hardy went in one ear and out
the other, and I spent a panicked afternoon before heading to the
sports events reading the owner's manual trying to figure out what
the 9 bejillion buttons on the camera did. I still don't know what
90 percent of the buttons do, but I figured out enough to get a
couple of acceptable shots for the paper. Since then, I've been
sent back out to shoot a front-page photo and plan to take pictures
on election night.
</P>
<P>
   Playing at being a photographer again has been fun, but I liken
it to having a grandbaby, which luckily I don't have just yet.
After a few days, I'm about ready to hand this baby back to someone
who actually knows what he's doing. Or she's doing. We've
interviewed a few prospects and hope to have someone in the job in
a few weeks. Until then, if you see me wandering around with a
camera bag weighing me down and a confused look on my face as I try
to figure out how to work the camera, pay no mind. We'll have
someone qualified here as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Daily Sentinel in
Nacogdoches. E-mail: gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
