<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8600 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GARCIA-COLUMN17-COX     03-16 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    We get letters, sometimes ugly, nasty ones
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ There are a lot of things to like about this
job, but what I like most is the mail the end of a campaign
generates.
</P>
<P>
   My favorites are the ones that end: ``I'll bet you don't have
the guts to print this'' and signed ``Concerned Citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   We get a lot of mail from ol' Concerned and his cousin ``Irate
Taxpayer'' year-round, but they get especially worked up when the
end of a campaign approaches and things aren't developing quite as
they would like. So, they send me mail in the closing days of a
campaign spilling nasty little secrets of candidates they oppose.
</P>
<P>
   The anonymous ones bemuse and amuse me. While we often use
anonymous letters for internal enjoyment, we don't print them and
never have.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder why someone would pour so much work into a tome and
then shun credit for it. Or is it taking responsibility that scares
these champions of democracy and the American way?
</P>
<P>
   Then there are those who do have the gumption to sign the cheap
shots they want to throw right before an election and demand to
know why we don't use them.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the would-be contributors have known since January that
the source of their distress is on the ballot, so I don't feel any
particular obligation to lend my support to their last-minute
spleen venting. Moreover, we have developed a policy over the years
to go dark on campaign letters 48 hours before an election.
</P>
<P>
   I generally don't like making rules, because some idiot is going
to follow them right past the point of absurdity. But this is one
with which I'm more than comfortable because as much as I dislike
rules, I hate ambushes more.
</P>
<P>
   In the last week, I've gotten letters about a couple of
candidates and their private lives, night lives and work habits.
The down-and-dirty ones have been anonymous, and I got of couple of
signed ones that were just downright mean-spirited.
</P>
<P>
   This is such a small town that there wasn't any breaking news in
those letters. I'd heard the gossip before. In fact, collecting
gossip is a hobby of mine, so there isn't much in the way of
lowdown and dirty talk that surprises me.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the rumors involve aethist space aliens who are
conspiring with Jim Bob Moffett to pave heaven and confiscate guns
along the way, we make an effort to check them out. If there is
something to them, you read about it. If not, you don't.
</P>
<P>
   And as far as the anonymous letters go, I follow my momma's
counsel and consider the source.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Garcia is the editorial page editor of the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
agarcia(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
