<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Offutt shown the door, and other election stories
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Perhaps the biggest lesson in Tuesday's
primaries was for State Board of Education District 5 member Bob
Offutt: Don't tug on Superman's cape.
</P>
<P>
   Offutt, the pediatric dentist from San Antonio who leads the
ultra-conservative faction on the board showed up in Iowa and New
Hampshire with former board member Donna Ballard to criticize Bush
on education and endorse Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Dan Montgomery, a retired social studies teacher from
Fredericksburg who'd filed against Offutt, began getting
contributions from Bush friends. Darned if Montgomery didn't get 59
percent _ which at year's end will take Offutt's hands out of
school matters and return them exclusively to kids' mouths. In
other races this week:
</P>
<P>
   Senate District 3 _ Rep. Todd Staples of Palestine won a
surprising 70 percent over Conroe homebuilder Les Tarrance and
also-ran Van Brookshire of Coldspring. Staples won Tarrance's home
base of Montgomery County by a 51-33 ratio.
</P>
<P>
   The seat, where Republican Drew Nixon of Carthage is retiring,
is important because Republicans hold a narrow 16-15 edge in the
Senate. Staples' rural base is considered a plus against Democrat
David Fisher of Silsbee in November.
</P>
<P>
   Senate District 2 _ In the other Senate seat in play in the
partisan balance, Republicans Ron Deuell of Greenville and Richard
Harvey of Tyler will face off April 10 to see who opposes incumbent
Democrat David Cain of Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio House Carnage _ Two incumbent San Antonio members of
the Texas House were defeated, and a third is threatened.
</P>
<P>
   Republican incumbent Bill Siebert was handily vanquished by
Elizabeth Ames Jones, who got 66 percent. Siebert was punished
primarily for brazenly lobbying for clients before San Antonio's
City Council.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic incumbent Juan F. Solis, who got distracted by
becoming involved in Robby Vazquez's effort to win a vacant House
seat, lost 51-49 to Jose Menendez.
</P>
<P>
   And Democratic incumbent Leo Alvarado Jr., who lost his own
district in a special Senate election against Leticia Van de Putte,
was thrown into a runoff. He'll face Trey Martinez Fischer.
</P>
<P>
   Vazquez, running for the House seat vacated by Van de Putte,
lost to Mike Villareal, who was backed by former San Antonio Mayor
Henry Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   Van de Putte, meanwhile, got 54 percent to stand off a strong
primary challenge for the Senate District 26 seat from David
McQuade Leibowitz.
</P>
<P>
   House District 13 incumbent Republican Charles Jones of College
Station was beaten in the GOP primary by Lois Kolkhorst of Brenham.
She got 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Free PAC Fails _ Dallasite Richard Ford's ultra-right Free PAC
backed challengers to three Republican House members; they all won
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Brian McCall of Plano, with 70 percent, easily stood off Kenny
Johnson of Dallas. Kim Brimer in Arlington got 55 percent against
Bill Zedler. And Dennis Bonnen of Angleton got 54 percent to again
beat Dianne Hensley of Alvin, whom he'd beaten four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   7th Congressional District _ In this GOP race to replace
retiring Republican Bill Archer in a lock Republican district,
State Rep. John Culberson, with 38 percent, led into a runoff
against businessman Peter Wareing, with 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
   President Gramm? The rumor: Ray Bowen resigns as president of
Texas A&AMP;M University over the bonfire collapse, and U.S. Sen. Phil
Gramm is named to replace him.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bush appoints Railroad Commissioner and former Secretary of
State Tony Garza to Gramm's seat _ timed so the special election
for the remainder of the term will coincide with the general
election. This'll help Bush with Hispanics not just in Texas, but
also in California and other states.
</P>
<P>
   Only thing wrong is it's wrong, say all concerned. Bowen says he
serves at the A&AMP;M regents' pleasure, but likes his job and has no
plans to step down. Regents' chairman Don Powell of Amarillo says
he knows of no such plan.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm's spokesman Larry Neal just laughed, saying the rumor is
weeks old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sen. Gramm loves being the senator from Texas, and the plan is
to run for re-election in 2002,'' Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
