<SLUG> BC-CHEAP-TRAVEL17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cruise the Web for hot travel bargains
 &HT;    By Ray Marcano
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ There are so many travel-related sites on the
Internet it's easy to get overwhelmed. There are the very popular _
and very good _ sites for just about all of your travel needs. But
there are a host of lesser-known sites that also provide terrific
bargains. Take a look at these three:
</P>
<P>
   Need a hotel? www.washingtonhotels.com is a handy site for good
hotel rates. That's where I found One Washington Circle, my
favorite D.C.-area hotel just a short walk from Georgetown. (It's
an all-suites hotel with separate living room, bedrooms and
kitchens.) The site also has links to hotels in New York, Boston
and Philadelphia and prides itself in offering rates in the
$125-a-night range _ not bad for major cities. The New York hotels,
for example, aren't midtown, but they're just a short subway ride _
or walk _ to the theater district.
</P>
<P>
   Want to take a cruise but think they're too expensive? Try
www.cruise.com, which offers many interesting cruises at $100 a day
or less. Anytime you can find a cruise at that price it's a steal,
when you consider you get food, beverages, entertainment and
lodging. Round-trip airfare should add another couple of hundred
dollars to the total. Still, there are tons of bargains (including
port fees but not airfare). Some recent examples: seven days in
Canada from New York or seven days in the Eastern Caribbean from
Fort Lauderdale for $599.
</P>
<P>
   Try www.familyfunvacations.com if you're interested in ideas for
a family vacation. You have to register but can do so without a
fee. One of the most interesting features: The site offers ideas on
driving tours for the family in all sections of the country. Many
middle-income families will bypass the resort and cruise sections
of the site, but there are a lot of interesting tidbits throughout.
Also offers special discounts and shopping trips.
</P>
<P>
   Anytime you decide to use the Internet, make sure you:
</P>
<P>
   Watch for additional fees. Internet surfing can result in huge
travel savings, but before you book, see if the service charges
additional fees. Among the possible add-ons: taxes, port charges,
airport taxes, surcharges, booking fees and mailing fees. Some
companies charge a higher change fee for airline tickets than the
airlines do. If a Web site doesn't have additional fees posted so
customers can clearly see them, call its 800 number before you
book. If there are additional fees and the company hasn't made it
easy for you to find them, complain _ loudly. Good companies
shouldn't make their customers hunt for information.
</P>
<P>
   Read the small print. Make sure you read the small print when
purchasing over the Internet. Can you change travel dates in the
event of an emergency? Can you get a full or partial refund if you
have to cancel? If you see a deal you like and aren't comfortable
booking online, then call the 800 number on the Web site and talk
to a customer-service representative.
</P>
<P>
   Travel tales. If you visit a spot you think readers would find
interesting, please send a note to the address below. It could end
up in this column.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
