<HEADER>
A8604 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-YANGTZE17-COX     03-16 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-YANGTZE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cherish China's mighty Yangtze River before it's forever altered
by man's hand
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHONGQING, China _ The rickety, wooden gangplank, partially
submerged in mud, stretched 200 feet from the bank of the Yangtze
River to the old riverboat, Ti'an Jin.
</P>
<P>
   Trash, paper wrappers, twisted plastic and sewage floated over
the gangplank boards. The garbage is flushed 1,500 miles in fierce
currents to Shanghai and the South China Sea.
</P>
<P>
   I made a mental note not to touch the lower parts of my boots.
</P>
<P>
   Once on board, I exchanged my ticket for a card that made me an
official passenger on a dilapidated, smoke-spewing steamboat
heading downstream.
</P>
<P>
   The Yangtze is beautiful, and monstrous. It is filthy and
deadly. A quarter of a million people have died on this river this
century _ 3,000 in 1998 _ when floods consumed towns along its
banks.
</P>
<P>
   On this late afternoon, rain came down in a drizzle, but high
water seemed unlikely. I was more concerned that this metal tub
hang together until I left it.
</P>
<P>
   I was sightseeing Chinese-style deep in China's interior on a
near-mythic stream, the third-longest river in the world, flowing
3,400 miles from Tibet to the sea. But soon, the currents will be
stopped.
</P>
<P>
   When the largest dam ever built, the Three Gorges Dam, is
completed in 2009, man will have finally tamed the Yangtze. The
places I would be seeing on this trip soon will be under 500 feet
of mud and water.
</P>
<P>
   More than 150 towns, 4,000 villages, the homes of 1.5 million
people, and 4,000-year-old antiquities will be lost forever.
</P>
<P>
   The time to see the great Yangtze in its wild glory is now,
whether it's by luxury cruise liner or Chinese steamboat. I took
the low road since the luxury ships wouldn't arrive until after
March 15, when cruise season starts.
</P>
<P>
   I was the only non-Chinese person of the 100 people on board. No
one spoke English, but my room number was printed in English on my
card.
</P>
<P>
   A man grabbed my backpack and put it on one end of a bamboo pole
swung over his shoulders. I led the way to my cabin while he spit
great quantities of phlegm on the metal floor of the hallway.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, I was surprised and impressed by my first-class
room ($60 for two people, and I paid for two), which had a
sliding-glass window with a view of the river, a TV and a private
bath. A quick inspection revealed that the TV didn't work, the
window fell off its track when I tried to slide it, and there was
no heat. I could see my breath on this winter day. And the water in
the bathroom looked like what was underneath the boat.
</P>
<P>
   Stained carpet covered the metal floor, which bounced slightly
when I walked on it.
</P>
<P>
   The guy carefully put my backpack down on the narrow bunk and
gave the room its final insult _ he spit on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   No pools, Jacuzzis, bars or floor shows were featured on this
rust bucket. No midnight buffets, in fact no buffets, just a dining
room with rusty metal chairs and floors and a woman who served
plates of noodles.
</P>
<P>
   I ate in my room _ no room service, I brought my own.
</P>
<P>
   But I was here to see the Yangtze, not to see an American-style
cruise ship, and I went to sleep watching the boat's powerful
searchlights roam the riverbanks and listening to the occasional
blast of the ship's horn and announcements made in Chinese, some
lasting an hour or more. I hoped they weren't telling me where the
life jackets were.
</P>
<P>
   The boat was scheduled to stop at Fengdu at 6:30 the next
morning. Because I had such a short time in China, I planned to get
off there and book passage on another boat back to Chongqing.
</P>
<P>
   At 6 a.m. I walked down the dark hallway and found the doors at
both ends locked with bicycle chains. I was trapped like a rat
until someone got up and unlocked them. The ship was moving, so I
waited another hour and tried again.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the doors were open, and I walked to the second-,
third-, fourth- and fifth-class rooms, which had from four to 20
berths in each (some had soft cotton padding, others were rattan).
Men stood on the deck, shaving and brushing their teeth, spitting
toothpaste over the rails.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of my deck was the dining room. No breakfast buffet
here, just small metal plates of steaming noodles and peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   At about 7:30 a.m. we arrived at Fengdu, more popularly known as
Hell Town and Ghost Town. Legend says the King of Hell lives on the
side of this mountain, and numerous temples pay homage, including
the Palace of the King of Hell, Between the Living and the Dead and
Bridge of Helplessness.
</P>
<P>
   But the town was far from hellish. I bought a map from a young
woman, who followed me up the hill and into town. As I walked up
and down the narrow streets, we gathered more women, one who ate
her bowl of noodles as we walked. Soon I had a group of a dozen
women of all ages on my tour. They talked to each other and to me
in Chinese, and occasionally pointed to me and burst out laughing,
at times actually doubled over. It must have been pretty funny, so
I laughed too.
</P>
<P>
   When I got ready to leave, I showed the map lady a sentence
written in Chinese on a small piece of paper: ``Please show me to
the ticket office for the fly boats.''
</P>
<P>
   Big smile, and she marched ahead and motioned for me and my
entourage to follow.
</P>
<P>
   We filed through town, to the ticket office. My note was shown
to the ticket seller, who wrote down the price. I gave her the
money, then she gave me the ticket, which had the time in English.
</P>
<P>
   The map lady marched ahead again, leading our group back down to
the river.
</P>
<P>
   She pulled out a rattan chair in front of a shop next to the
river and motioned for me to sit down. I expected everyone to leave
as soon as I tipped the map lady, but they stayed for an hour until
the boat came, and then waved enthusiastically until I boarded.
</P>
<P>
   Fengdu _ what a cheerful, helpful and heavenly town.
</P>
<P>
   And it will soon be gone.
</P>
<P>
   Fengdu will lie at the bottom of an artificial lake that will be
400 miles long and 574 feet deep.
</P>
<P>
   The map lady and the rest of my group will be relocated to
high-rise apartment buildings being built on a hilltop in the
distance. And the King of Hell and his temples will rest in peace.
</P>
<P>
   Ecologists say the dam will be a disaster. The 1.2 mile-wide
wall will trap 3,000 miles of raw sewage and industrial waste in
the slow-moving lake. The cesspool will kill migratory fish, a
vital source of food in the valley. A series of smaller dams, they
say, would have been more effective in stopping flooding and saving
the valley.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese insist these problems have been considered, and that
the dam will provide 11 percent of China's energy, and will create
a 1,500-mile navigable waterway inland from Shanghai to Chongqing.
Locks next to the dam will allow huge ships to travel from the
coast to Chongqing.
</P>
<P>
   But those cruises will be trips of a different kind. Passengers
will see a placid lake, not a wild river that tumbles though
legendary gorges at the feet of ancient cities.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
