r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN17-COX     03-16 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beware new growth industry: Intrusion on reproductive decisions
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Adventures in big-government conservatism: Texas
courts are giving pingpong-ball treatment to a 17-year-old girl who
wants to have an abortion and who does not want to notify her
parents.
</P>
<P>
   In this, the first appeal of Texas' new parental notification
abortion law for girls 17 and under, we see the dilemmas and
inconsistencies when government presumes to interlope in
reproductive decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The first logical inconsistency is the term ``parental'' in
parental notification. By any definition, certainly in the terms of
abortion foes themselves, the ``parent'' is the pregnant female.
</P>
<P>
   Parental notification? Young lady, you're about to become one.
You are hereby notified. Under the law, a bypass can be granted
only if a local judge decides that the girl is mature enough to
make the abortion decision on her own.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Doe 3's request was denied by the trial. The Texas Supreme
Court considered the case and sent it back.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court added these factors that a trial court must
consider: the young woman's emotional and physical needs; the
possibility of danger; the stability of her home; and whether the
notification could cause lasting harm to the girl's relationship
with her parents.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the sticky business of state intervention. Bring on
the lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Was the girl being abused by her father? Is she suicidal? When
government must ratify personal decisions, we ask it to rule on
distinctions like this.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Bush essentially has three expressed and not
entirely compatible positions on abortion: First, if it were in his
power, he'd abolish it except in cases of rape, incest and medical
necessity; second, he wouldn't change the Republican national
platform, under which a rape victim would have to bear her
attacker's child; third, he doesn't think there's sufficient
popular support to amend the Constitution, so he'd leave it alone.
</P>
<P>
   One can understand why Bush will peddle Option No. 3 as he tries
to get back to the center on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   It would be fascinating to see a constitutional amendment that
not only gave 14th Amendment rights to a fetus but made exceptions,
as Bush would, for a fetus resulting from rape or incest, or whose
mother might not survive childbirth.
</P>
<P>
   That would result in a constitutional amendment just about as
long as the Roe vs. Wade decision, which is longer than the U.S.
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the court cases. A pregnant woman says she was raped.
Raped? Did you press charges? Can you provide physical evidence?
Can you produce the rapist?
</P>
<P>
   Too rarely do we hear conservatives, who are said to mistrust
government, saying government should stay out of matters like this,
matters between a physician and a patient. The hypocrisy is
deafening.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of parental consent/notification laws and the issue of
``partial-birth abortion'' are seen as slam-dunk opportunities for
abortion foes.
</P>
<P>
   But in fact, both issues reflect the excruciating dilemmas that
come with government intrusion into private medical decisions. In
the case of partial-birth abortion, we are to assume that
government can make the call when a doctor fears that a woman might
lose her life or her ability to conceive, or when the fetus simply
is unable to survive outside the womb.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of parental consent/notification, we want government
to determine if a girl has a valid fear of involving her parents,
or if she's sufficiently mature. Define ``mature.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems Jane Doe 3, the real parent in the equation, meets the
definition of mature simply by taking her decision to court. But to
Texas she's just a pingpong ball.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
