<HEADER>
A8607 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-FASHION-PROM17-COX     03-16 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-PROM17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Primping for prom
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It's a unique shopping experience _ fun, exciting
and filled with promise.
</P>
<P>
   Make that promise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every girl wants to look pretty, dolled up and a little extra
special,'' says Bree Gelber, accessories editor for Seventeen
magazine. ``You're looking for that perfect dress, for perfect
shoes. Though it's not true for everyone, most girls want to look
different than they usually do.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the case for Tiffany Collins, a junior at Stebbins High
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm usually in a T-shirt and jeans,'' says the 16-year-old
soccer player. ``For prom, I want something fancy, different,
new.''
</P>
<P>
   Centerville High School senior Rachel Carlson says the prom,
especially your senior prom, is a huge event. Though she and her
friends sometimes borrow one another's dresses, they typically get
a new dress for each big dance.
</P>
<P>
   As a member of Elder-Beerman's Junior Advisory Board, Rachel
regularly gets a chance to try on the season's hottest looks before
they hit the stores. The board's job is to provide feedback to
buyers.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, the group donned sample prom dresses. Rachel
says the big news was the gorgeous colors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a blast!'' she says. ``I love the pastels, and pink and
purple are really hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen's Gelber confirms this season's wide range of colors.
``We've seen a ton of pinks ... from baby pink to fichia, from
light peach to a more vibrant peach. And all shades of purple.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents will be delighted because what's fashionable is also
pretty and feminine.
</P>
<P>
   Miami Valley department stores and specialty shops are filling
up with beautiful hues and delicate fabrics: satins, tulle
overlays, eyelet, with delicate embroidery or simple beading.
</P>
<P>
   Spaghetti straps are popular, as are strapless gowns, often with
matching wraps. Both long and short lengths will be seen on the
dance floor this year, with skirts ranging from very full ballgowns
to body-skimming sheaths.
</P>
<P>
   It's not surprising that separates _ popular for brides and
bridesmaids _ have reached the prom market as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two-piece dresses are really in style this season,'' says
Rachel, who also loved the backless dresses ``that flow at the
bottom.'' Another favorite is the corset top looks.
</P>
<P>
   One of the newer shapes is a handkerchief top with halter back.
Those who seek something different may opt for silky prints with
scarf hemlines or embroidered skirts with tube tops. Vintage looks
are unique and can save dollars as well.
</P>
<P>
   Prices range from less than $100 to $450. You'll pay less for
rentals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They only want to wear the dress once, so renting makes
sense,'' says Tiffany's mom, Donna Collins. ``And that way she can
get a very beautiful gown.''
</P>
<P>
   Prom also provides a wonderful opportunity to show off pretty
accessories.
</P>
<P>
   This season's little handbags are decorated with sequins,
patchwork, beading or fringe. A decorative purse is a perfect
complement to a simple gown.
</P>
<P>
   Other accessories for Prom 2000 include crocheted shawls,
colorful strappy sandals, ribbon necklaces and bracelets. You'll
see lots of dangly earrings. Chunky rings are in demand as well.
</P>
<P>
   Hair accessories include pins and headbands with sparkle, as
well as pretty tiaras. You can also put a fabric flower or even
real flowers in your hair. Accessories also are the big story for
the guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vests with matching bow ties are popular,'' says Edd Wimsatt,
owner of Price Stores. ``Young men really like a vest.''
</P>
<P>
   Other popular looks include button covers instead of bow ties,
worn with a mandarin-style tux shirt, and the Euro-tie _ which
looks like a traditional four-in-hand tie and can be worn with
either a wing-collar or Euro-wing collar shirt.
</P>
<P>
   You'll see piping on the tux coat this season, plus notch, shawl
and peak lapels. A tux from Fubu features a jacket with inside cell
phone and CD pocket. Trendy shoes include black patent with box or
cap toes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys go out and hunt for the hottest GQ looks,'' says
Jason Bayus, a Fairmont High School senior. ``Shopping is a lot
easier for us than for women.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Cathy Ramby of Skeffington's, longer jackets also
are popular.
</P>
<P>
   Students from five Miami Valley schools will model prom fashions
at an upcoming fund-raiser, called ``Style Promenade.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids are trying to do something to help other kids stay
safe for prom this year,'' says Gerda Bray of L'Affair, one of the
event sponsors. Proceeds will benefit the Students Against
Destructive Decisions chapters at each of the participating
schools.
</P>
<P>
   The prom shopping experience can also be a time for bonding _
for friends and families.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been our time together,'' says Donna Collins. ``We've
had fun _ a lot of chuckles. It's especially important when I think
that a year from now, she'll be heading off to school.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
