<SLUG> BC-PROM-SHOP17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Picking the right look for prom
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING TIPS
</P>
<P>
   _ Browse through magazines and tear out pages with gowns,
tuxedos or accessories you like. Bring them along when you shop.
</P>
<P>
   _ Consider shopping first with friends and narrowing your
selection. Then bring a parent back for the final decision.
</P>
<P>
   _ Take along a pair of shoes that are about the same height as
the pair you'll wear to the dance.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't forget the underpinnings you'll need for a specific
dress when you're estimating cost. Some dresses require a strapless
or low-back bra; close-to-the-body dresses may require lingerie
that disappears. Don't wait until the last minute to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep an open mind. Don't rule any style out until you've tried
it on. You may be surprised at what looks great.
</P>
<P>
   _ Leave price tags on dresses if you're unsure about keeping
them. They cannot be returned or exchanged if tags have been
removed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Consider renting a dress. Also think about thrift, consignment
or vintage shops. Or borrow a gown from a friend or sister.
</P>
<P>
   _ Try on lots of accessories; they can make the outfit. When
it's time for makeup, play up your eyes or lips, but not both.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
