<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8609 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-REVIEW-ERINBROCK17-CO     03-16 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-ERINBROCK17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pretty woman takes on polluting bad guys
 &HT;    By Gary Schwan
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Producers were worried about the title,
especially a name so spectacularly ethnic as ``Erin Brockovich.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, they could have called the movie ``Julia Roberts, Julia
Roberts.'' The actress is the film, which is a true story about an
average Jo who mounts a legal battle against a utility company
responsible for poisoning the waters of a California town.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts is rarely off-screen, and it's not exactly painful to
study her milelong legs and canyon-esque cleavage for more than two
hours. She dresses like a call girl and talks like a drill
sergeant. This only underscores the fairy-tale quality of the story
_ a blue-collar Sleeping Beauty awakens from a life of drudgery to
be all that she can be.
</P>
<P>
   Still, too bad the tale is a pastiche of any number of
crusader/underdog movies, from ``Norma Rae'' to ``A Civil Action.''
There is even a whiff of ``Working Girl.'' Brockovich is a nobody
who proves more resourceful than the fancy-pants professionals
around her.
</P>
<P>
   The film is lightened with a good deal of humor. Roberts'
profanity-laced put-downs make you wince but can be funny. And her
portrayal of a frazzled working mother is often touching. Her
domestic trials are the best part of the movie, since the legal
machinations surrounding the pollution case aren't terribly
dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   Brockovich is a twice-divorced mother of three down on her luck.
Although aggressive, even abusive at times, she's the perfect
madonna when it comes to her children.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate for a job, she bullies her way into the office of an
attorney played by an amusing Albert Finney. Looking into a rash of
medical problems in a rural town, she discovers that a utility
company is ducking responsibility for having contaminated the water
years before.
</P>
<P>
   She persuades her reluctant boss (Finney) _ and equally
skeptical townsfolk _ to pursue the case. Although she has no
formal education, she does most of the investigative work,
compiling a mound of evidence at the risk of neglecting her family
and alienating a love interest, a good-hearted biker named George
(Aaron Eckhart).
</P>
<P>
   There are a few courtroom scenes, but no dramatic
confrontations. In large part, ``Erin Brockovich'' is a ``female
empowerment'' movie, the story of a feisty woman who reinvents
herself against the odds.
</P>
<P>
   Save for one bedroom frolic, Steve Soderbergh (``Out of Sight'')
directs the film in a straightforward manner, not forgetting to get
plenty of close-ups on Roberts' intriguing face.
</P>
<P>
   The actress rounds all the bases _ from trademark cuteness, to
comedy, to romantic tenderness and dramatic intensity. It's perhaps
the best performance of her career, and certainly the most complex.
</P>
<P>
   Finney is a comic foil _ a gruff teddy bear who is frequently
exasperated by Roberts' brashness and crudity. Eckhart is engaging
as a tattooed biker who happens to make a great house-daddy. And
Marg Helgenberger is touching as a housewife crushed and bewildered
by her medical problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Erin Brockovich'' works well as a sophisticated soap opera,
and Roberts has never been better. But here's wishing the legal
drama was more complicated and compelling.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
