<HEADER>
A8610 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-ALGERNON17-COX     03-16 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-ALGERNON17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Algernon' ideal - brilliance -
 &HT;    is author's, too
 &HT;    By Chris Hutchins
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Meet Charlie Gordon. He is 37 years old.
He is mentally retarded.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to be smart. He really does.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie is about to have an ``operashun.'' The procedure, he
hopes, will make him smart.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure, in fact, will cause his IQ of 68 to triple.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Charlie will make an entry in his Progress Report:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to think about,'' he'll write. ``Maybe if I
ask (the doctor) he will tell me how I can think now that Im
suppose to get smart. What do smart people think about. Fancy
things I suppose. I wish I knew some fancy things already.''
</P>
<P>
   Now meet Daniel Keyes.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 years ago, Keyes created Charlie in the
award-winning novelette ``Flowers For Algernon,'' a fictional
chronicle of the first human to become ``smarter'' by experimental
surgery. In the story, Charlie befriends a mouse named Algernon,
who has also received the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes fleshed out the character in a novel of the same name in
1966.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you write something, you essentially throw a stone in the
water, and watch the ripples spread,'' the writer said during a
recent chat at Boca Raton's Boca Teeca Inn. ```Flowers' has
affected more people than I can imagine. I know the story will
outlive me.''
</P>
<P>
   Believe him. The novel, now in its 89th printing, has sold more
than 6 million copies worldwide. It is used in schools across the
country. It's generated thousands of letters to the author. And two
movies. And a stage musical. And a theatrical production in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   It also prompted Keyes, who has lived in Boca Raton for the past
eight years, to write a memoir about writing ``Flowers.'' In
``Algernon, Charlie and I: A Writer's Journey,'' Keyes chronicles
his own growth. He writes about his childhood in Brooklyn; about
editing pulp magazines and comic books to make ends meet; about
teaching high school in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes also introduces readers to the real-life inspiration for
Charlie Gordon: a boy he was teaching in a class for slow students.
One day after class, the boy said something that changed the
writer's life.
</P>
<P>
   I want to be smart.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes never forgot that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hit me in the gut,'' he says. ``I suddenly saw _ through
his eyes _ something I hadn't been aware of: A slow learner, a
retarded person, wants to be smart. It never occurred to me before.
As people, we tend to walk by people who are handicapped and don't
get involved with them. Well, teaching these kids, you had to get
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes connected with that boy, and ``Flowers For Algernon'' came
soon after that. Readers have since connected with Charlie. Since
1959, they've connected with his dreams ... and his desperation
when Algernon dies, and his own intelligence begins to revert.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see, I'm Charlie,'' Keyes explains. ``My hopes, my
aspirations, my fears: I just gave them to the character. But I get
letters and e-mail from children and students from all over the
world. They say the same thing: `I'm Charlie.' Somehow, in plumbing
my own depths, I touched some universal thing that all of us
share.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People always ask, `How do you write? What are your
methods?''' Keyes says. ``I wanted to leave behind how I did this
story, and show how my life was involved in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something I had to get out of me,'' he says. ``It was
something I thought would be useful to others.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
