<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8611 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-COUNTRY17-COX     03-16 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-COUNTRY17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MAE
 &HT;    WOODS
 &HT;    BELL
 &HT;    Book Reviewer
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Pipher bridges the gap between generations
 &HT;    BY Mae Woods Bell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. _ ``Another Country'' by Mary Pipher;
Riverhead; 325 pages; $13.95
</P>
<P>
   In this work, subtitled ``Navigating the Emotional Terrain of
our Elders,'' Pipher takes readers inside the minds, hearts and
bodies of older men and women. She does it with insight, humor,
sensitivity and an affinity for relying on common sense rather than
psycho-
</P>
<P>
   babble.
</P>
<P>
   With the dawn of the new millen-
</P>
<P>
   nium, we are entering new territory, with different family
structures, work options, kinds of old age and choices about living
situations and health care. Families are struggling with all the
old problems of aging relatives and the new dilemmas presented by
today's rapidly changing world. Drawing on her 20 years as a
therapist and from interviews with families and older individuals,
Pipher shares the stories of real people as she maps out the
territory that distinguishes the elderly from subsequent
generations. Above all, she offers scenarios _ from
intergenerational church dinners to elementary school field trips
to rest homes _ that bridge the generation gap.
</P>
<P>
   She explores significant issues faced by millions of baby
boomers as their parents and grandparents age. Among the chapters
in this revealing and inspirational look at the often foreign
landscape of old age, are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Time Zones _ An analysis of cultural changes that have
occurred since the early part of the century. These include the
country's shift from a communal to an individualistic society,
changes in values, alterations in sexual roles and attitudes, and a
transformation in the meaning of dependency from a natural to a
shameful condition. Pipher calls intergenerational
misunderstandings ``time-zone problems ... Only by understanding
what things mean to people in other time-zones can we truly
communicate with them.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Great Divide _ A look at how psychology became the great
divide between the generation of our elders and subsequent
generations. It isn't difficult to grasp the technological changes
that earlier generations have experienced; what is hard to
comprehend is the pre-Freudian way in which many elders process
reality.
</P>
<P>
   _ Let a Thousand Old Flowers Bloom _ A reflection on resilience
in the face of adversity. ``The resilient old,'' Pipher says,
``have learned about psychological survival from their long and
complicated lives. They carry on in spite of losses. They tend to
be practical, sensible and well organized. All have interests and
relationships that sustain them ... As much is taken away, that
which remains grows more precious.'' In discussing the needs of the
resilient old, Pipher refers to her ``Five R's'' _ respect,
relationships, results, relaxation and realization.
</P>
<P>
   _ We Grow Souls Together _ A view of the special relationship
that exists between grandparents and grandchildren. She examines
the shift in roles played by parents as their children have
children of their own; the connections between old and young; the
ways in which grandparents pass along wisdom and moral values; and
the ways in which grandparents serve as the connecting tissue
between generations.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Pipher received her bachelor's of arts degree in cultural
anthropology from the University of California at Berkeley, and her
doctorate in clinical psychology from the University of Nebraska,
where she is a visiting assistant professor. She is also a
commentator for Nebraska Public Radio, and contributing editor to
USA Weekend. She is the author of a groundbreaking 1994 best seller
about adolescent girls, ``Reviving Ophelia'' and another
bestseller, ``The Shelter of Each Other'' (1996). She lives in
Lincoln, Neb.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
