<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8612 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-GREENE17-COX     03-16 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-GREENE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On his terms, endearing or not
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ For nearly 30 years, the routine was
unvarying. For a month in the spring and a month in the fall,
Graham Greene would come to Capri, to a small house he bought in
1948.
</P>
<P>
   He would do his daily ration of 350 words, eat at his favorite
restaurants, spend time with a few well-chosen friends _ often his
mistress of this period, the American Catherine Walston, who was
succeeded by Yvonne Cloetta.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Hazzard, the wife of biographer Francis Steegmuller and
a very good novelist in her own right, offers a fragrant, funny,
precise picture of a writer whose considerable worldly success
never tempted him into untoward displays of optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Point me out a happy man,'' Greene once snapped, ``and I will
point you out either egotism, selfishness, evil _ or else an
absolute ignorance.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene, of course, thrived on his internal contradictions; they
were the basis for his art. A renegade Catholic, his first moves
when visiting any town for the first time were to investigate the
local Catholic churches, followed immediately by the local houses
of prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   Married only once, he had several long-term mistresses, each
relationship earning the de facto support of the ladies' compliant
husbands.
</P>
<P>
   His was a character of Dickensian richness. Personally rather
cheap _ he hated the expense of taxis and avoided them whenever he
could, while the price of heating oil received regular arias of
displeasure _ he nevertheless had a habit of financially supporting
writers he respected who were having trouble earning a living wage
from their work.
</P>
<P>
   (Most prominently, Muriel Spark was the recipient of Greene's
largesse for a long time, the monthly checks often accompanied by
some bottles of wine, to take the edge off the charity.)
</P>
<P>
   He had a temper and could fall into contrary moods, when he
sought to provoke a fight. At such times, writes Hazzard, he looked
for all the world, ``like Thomas Mitchell playing Scarlett's
demented father.''
</P>
<P>
   He liked Ralph Richardson and Paul Scofield, abhorred Olivier.
Henry James was a lifelong enthusiasm, until the very end of his
life, when he suddenly found to his chagrin that James had become
unreadable.
</P>
<P>
   He adored practical jokes, as long as he was doing the joking
and someone else was doing the practicing. As is obvious from his
fiction, where Americans are invariably portrayed as rambunctious,
none-too-bright children given to carelessly sprinting through the
sitting rooms of Europe and breaking all the carefully preserved
china, he disliked us but was willing to make exceptions for
certain individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Like every successful writer, he had a strong work ethic and put
in his time at the writing table every day, not just when he felt
like it. He made no particular claims for his later work, and
Hazzard makes some severe criticisms of his books: ``Poignancy was
largely subsumed into world-weariness, resurfacing in spasms of
authenticity ... sheer human sympathy makes an obligatory guest
appearance, like an aging celebrity briefly brought on stage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a book coming out,'' he might say. ``Not a specially
good one.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Evelyn Waugh, he liked things to go wrong, but only on his
terms. He exhibited nearly all human qualities except tenderness,
``that is, there was no self-forgetful surrender _ whether to
affection or to the vulnerable shades of trust or remorse; still
less to any enduring state of happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   Hazzard writes very evocatively, with affection but a clear
sense of Greene's essentially chauvinist views and of his
unharmonious nature. There is also much delicious detail of the
island of Capri itself _ 4 miles long, about 5 1/2 miles of
territory in all.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there is sometimes a bit too much delicious detail, as
the background threatens to overwhelm the character in the
foreground, who was, after all, some kind of great writer.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a small, forgivable fault in a lovely little book
that deserves the attention of anybody who's ever been moved by the
cold anguish of ``The Power and the Glory,'' ``The End of the
Affair'' or ``The Human Factor.''
</P>
<P>
   GREENE ON CAPRI, by Shirley Hazzard. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux;
149 pages; $22.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1122EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 11:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8613 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKSTORES-CULTURE17-     03-16 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKSTORES-CULTURE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bookstores becoming home for more than buying
 &HT;    By Laura Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It must be the coffee.
</P>
<P>
   At Half Price Books in Dayton, the brew is free all day, and
patrons partake as they browse, standing in the aisles, sitting on
stools or cross-legged on the floor for as long as it takes to get
a satisfactory fix of caffeine, words and pictures, be it a few
minutes, an hour, an afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``One guy comes here for five or six hours at a time and
reads,'' said store manager Melanie Adams, who thinks he may have
bought a book once, but she can't really remember. Not that it
matters. ``We don't discourage him at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Daryl Ward, pastor at Dayton's Omega Baptist Church,
often can be found in a comfortable chair at Borders Books &AMP; Music,
or Barnes &AMP; Noble _ he likes to move around a bit, ``because I come
a couple of times a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Ensconsed with his Bible and a silver Starbucks travel mug full
of bookstore blend, Ward works on his sermons, thinks, reads and
watches people.
</P>
<P>
   In the big stores, it's obvious people are doing more than
buying books. They're standing around, reading, talking, sitting,
napping, drinking coffee, eating cookies, meeting friends.
Bookstores have become much more than places to spend money:
They've become places to spend the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love being surrounded by books, but libraries are too
sanitary,'' Ward laughed, ``I like to drink coffee. I like for
something to be going on around me. I can buy books, browse, study,
and they're open late.''
</P>
<P>
   Kettering's renowned Books &AMP; Co. was onto something big when it
opened, in a decidedly tiny nook in the Town &AMP; Country Shopping
Center, with a decided aversion to many stores' ``don't-browse,
buy'' policy. It made itself an inviting destination for window
shoppers with tactile tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like that from the very beginning,'' said Sharon Kelly
Roth, director of public relations for the store. ``Anything we
could do to encourage reading. ... We would never hurry people
out.''
</P>
<P>
   In July 1990, Books &AMP; Co. moved into an expanded space. Part of
the floor plan was reserved for a cafe, to be run by Harriet and
George Argue, owners of Truffles. At the end of 1990, the Argues
opened their second Truffles in the Books &AMP; Co. space, operating as
a separate entity, yet connected to the bookstore so customers
could wander freely from one to the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was strictly in response to customers' requests,'' said
Roth. ``One woman asked if we could just put a pot of coffee on ...
she said, `I like to come all day, and I just get weak!'
</P>
<P>
   Books &AMP; Co. may not have known it then, but it was on the
cutting edge of a trend toward eating and reading, all in the same
place. A day could be spent without leaving the bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   For Borders as well, customers gave them no choice. The chain
started small in 1971, when two brothers opened a used bookstore in
Ann Arbor, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1973 they moved, and started carrying new books,'' said Ann
Binkley, public relations manager. ``They were right in the middle
of the University of Michigan, and you find that with students,
they come in and hang out. They really enjoyed the store.''
</P>
<P>
   As the company started to grow and more locations opened,
Binkley said Borders ``wanted to keep that atmosphere, where people
were comfortable. We want to make the stores very inviting _ we
encourage browsing. That has been our philosophy all along.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until 1991, though, that Borders opened a store with
attached cafe, in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our stores had started to grow, and they were places where
people stayed for a few hours. We wanted to enhance their
experience by adding the cafe, so if they're thirsty or hungry, we
allow them to pick up a book or grab a magazine,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It works, for folks such as David Kang, a 28-year-old medical
student from Cincinnati, who typically spends afternoons at one
bookstore or another, textbooks and highlighters spread out and,
usually, earphones in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Libraries are a sort of sensory deprivation,'' he said one
weekday afternoon at the Borders near the Dayton Mall. ``They're
just too quiet for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Kang has been studying in bookstores ``pretty much since
college,'' at the University of Chicago. ``I can study, drink
coffee, then get up and walk around. I look at a lot of magazines
here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bookstore studying, Kang believes, ``is kind of hip, it's cool.
It's stimulating, believe it or not, and encourages you to study.
At a library, I just kind of float off.''
</P>
<P>
   For Jennifer Saunders, 29, Borders is a near-mandatory daily
stop before she starts work at nearby Lexis Nexis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here two, three times a week,'' she said. ``I'll get a
thing of coffee, maybe a scone,'' before settling in for an hour or
so of reading before her shift, which starts at 1:30 p.m.
``Sometimes, I come just to look around.''
</P>
<P>
   Saunders loves Borders' music section, where she can try things
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Friday nights, sometimes I'll meet friends here and we'll
sit and talk,'' she said. ``I have never been asked if I am going
to buy anything or if I need anything else. The atmosphere is just
good, relaxed. The staff is really friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   At Barnes &AMP; Noble's two area stores _ across from the Dayton
Mall on Miamisburg-Centerville Road and near the Mall at Fairfield
Commons on North Fairfield Road _ students seem to be the norm at
the cafe tables.
</P>
<P>
   Shalini Aggarwal, 26, and her fiance Jon Ryan, 29, are studying
for their medical boards. Both attend Des Moines University, and
were in town visiting Aggarwal's family. But medical school doesn't
believe in vacations, so their afternoon was spent at the
bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come for the coffee,'' said Aggarwal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good break from the isolation of the library,'' said
Ryan. ``Bookstores are becoming more popular places to study.''
</P>
<P>
   He understands why the stores encourage folks like them: ``It
makes loyal customers. We do browse, and we do buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Kendra Steele had trekked through town, from her Harrison Twp.
home to Miami Twp.'s Barnes &AMP; Noble, with her three boys, in search
of a copy of ``Fahrenheit 451'' for 16-year-old Gregory's high
school English class.
</P>
<P>
   She couldn't resist checking out a few titles herself, and soon
the family, including Christopher, 12, and Edward, 13, had taken
over one of B&AMP;N's classic crannies. Gregory started in on
Bradbury's classic while Kendra flipped through several books
before returning all but one to the shelf. She returned to the big,
soft chair and began reading.
</P>
<P>
   ``You sit in these chairs and it is so comfortable,'' she said.
``As soon as I finish my chi (sweet tea and milk), we'll head on
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had one of these big chairs in my room, I might never
leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, a nameless patron dozed in a similar chair, a copy of
``Porting UNIX Software'' face down on the table next to a
near-empty cup of coffee _ proof that there are some things even
caffeine can't combat.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
