<SLUG> BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tolkien and his `Lord' are still ringing up sales
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ J.R.R. Tolkien became famous in the
'60s, mostly because he didn't become famous in the '50s, when he
originally published his ``Lord of the Rings'' trilogy.
</P>
<P>
   The true measure of his accomplishment came in the '70s with a
relentless series of imitations that show no signs of letting up.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, writers such as Terry Brooks, Stephen Donaldson,
David Eddings and Robert Jordan would never have had their careers
without Tolkien's example.
</P>
<P>
   Houghton Mifflin has virtually every scrap of paper the Oxford
don ever scribbled in print, but they just released a volume called
``The Father Christmas Letters,'' an entertaining, nicely
illustrated group of letters that Tolkien wrote to his children as
an annual holiday ritual.
</P>
<P>
   Now that a two-part film adaptation of the ``Rings'' trilogy is
under way in New Zealand, directed by Peter Jackson, look for the
drumbeats to continue as the film's release draws closer.
</P>
<P>
   IN THE TRADE ...
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Nelson, heretofore a religious publisher, has bought
Rutledge Hill, a small publisher with an emphasis on Southern
history and cooking. Rutledge's most successful books have been
titles like ``Aunt Bee's Mayberry Cookbook'' and ``Life's Little
Instruction Book.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson plans to use the Rutledge imprint as a vehicle for
nonreligious books, with about 35 titles issued annually.
</P>
<P>
   FORE! ...
</P>
<P>
   Payne Stewart, who died in a mysterious plane crash last fall,
is the subject of two competing biographies scheduled for midyear
release. One, for Andrews and McMeel, is by veteran Florida
sportswriter Larry Guest; the other, by Stewart's widow, Tracey,
and writer Ken Abraham, is for Broadman &AMP; Holman in Nashville,
Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Another interesting project in the works is a large-scale
biography of Norman Rockwell by Laura Claridge, which Random House
will publish in time for the 2001 opening of a major Rockwell
exhibit at the Guggenheim.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the millions upon millions of non-fans who avoided the
recent Andy Kaufman biopic ``Man on the Moon'' will also have a
chance to avoid yet another book about him. Julie Hecht has been
signed to write a book entitled ``Was This Man a Genius?'' for
Random House.
</P>
<P>
   I haven't read the book, but I can answer the question with some
degree of certainty.
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE UNQUOTE ...
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a story about the Founding Fathers and oral sex, and I
confess to a great interest in both.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Jeffrey Toobin, about ``A Vast Conspiracy,'' his new book on
the Clinton impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
