<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 11:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8615 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-REVIEW-AGNES17-COX     03-16 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-AGNES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Agnes is no Angela: Irish poverty played for laughs
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``Agnes Browne'' is an entertaining
slice of blarney that has arrived in time for St. Patrick's Day.
Agnes is a newly widowed Dubliner, trying to raise her brood of
seven despite a life of unrelenting hardship. The movie is
alternately touching, comic and preposterous, but even when it
loses touch with reality, it is never less than watchable, thanks
to an earthy earth mother title performance by Angelica Huston.
</P>
<P>
   Based on co-screenwriter Brendan O'Carroll's novel ``The
Mammy,'' which has its roots in a popular Irish radio serial,
``Agnes Browne'' will never be mistaken for ``Angela's Ashes.''
Terrible things happen to Agnes and her family, but the movie _
directed by Huston with insufficient grit _ never leaves any doubt
that the Widow Browne will triumph over adversity.
</P>
<P>
   The script has a winking fable quality from its first moments,
when Agnes applies to receive her late husband's pension. She is
refused for lack of a death certificate that she does not have, she
explains, because the bloke died that morning.
</P>
<P>
   So Agnes is forced to borrow from a street-corner loan shark, a
cardboard villain she will anger by paying off the loan early. The
funeral is played for laughs, when the hearse overheats, backfires
and breaks down on the way to the cemetery. At the grave, Agnes
becomes livid when she spies a mysterious attractive woman and
decides she was her husband's mistress, only to realize they are
standing at the wrong burial site.
</P>
<P>
   The best part of the movie is Agnes' interaction with her best
friend, Marion (Marion O'Dwyer in an attention-getting screen
debut), also a produce-market clerk. Agnes listens with wide-eyed
fascination as Marion tells her of her wondrous sexual climaxes _
her so-called ``organisms'' _ which Agnes never experienced in her
entire baby-making career.
</P>
<P>
   If that weren't bad enough, once the women form an enduring bond
of friendship, Marion develops breast cancer. In a touch of
situation comic-tragedy, Marion indulges her dream to learn to
drive, though she does not own a car. During a lesson she and Agnes
erupt in a giggle fit, followed by a sobering reversal.
</P>
<P>
   Realizing one's dreams is a recurring theme, and Agnes harbors a
desire to see hip-swiveling Tom Jones, who is coming to Dublin for
a concert. But she accepts forlornly that feeding her family takes
priority over fulfilling her fantasy. Unfortunately, O'Carroll has
a far more romantic notion involving a cameo by Jones that feels
like one of those guest-starring shots on ``The Lucille Ball
Show.''
</P>
<P>
   In taking her place in the director's chair, Huston follows the
tradition of her father, John. It is an assured, if unexceptional,
job of filmmaking, but perhaps it will lead to more ambitious
projects down the road. It is most distinguished in the performance
she draws from herself, a noble but affecting portrait of a woman
burdened by life, but able to laugh at her plight.
</P>
<P>
   She handles the loan shark, accepts a date from a sensitive
French baker and teaches her kids about survival, all neatly
subdivided into radio show episodes. There are plenty of reasons to
nit-pick this only-in-the-movies view of poverty, or you could step
back, accept its flaws and still enjoy spending time with the
unsinkable ``Agnes Browne.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
