<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Friday, March 17,
2000, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-YANGTZE _ Riding the wild Yangtze, a Chinese adventure.
(Blackerby, Palm Beach Post). 38. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-GULFCOASTLINE _ WALTON COUNTY, Fla. _ The first thing I
notice when I turn off U.S. 98 onto Scenic 30-A, a meandering,
20-mile asphalt ribbon that flirts with south Walton County's Gulf
coastline, is what I don't notice. Unlike Panama City and Destin,
which lie about 30 minutes to the east and west, respectively,
there are no crowded streets filled with towering condos. No tacky
surfside stores hawking airbrushed T-shirts or, um, water pipes.
Not even a set of golden arches to cast its cool shadow across the
shimmering waters of this old-fashioned Florida oasis. The sleepy,
surfside communities along Scenic 30-A shun these brash,
commercialized come-ons. Instead, they allow the twists and turns
of the road to reveal their charms in tantalizing glimpses.
(Laughinghouse, Atlanta Journal-Constitution freelancer; not for
use by NYTNS clients).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 19.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GULFCOAST-TOUR _ WALTON COUNTY, Fla. _ Part of south Walton
County's appeal are the diverse choices it presents visitors. You
can dine on filet mignon served up on fine china, or feast on deep
fried shrimp and hush puppies dished out in red plastic baskets.
There are swanky boutiques you can stalk in strappy heels, funky
folk art galleries for the Birkenstock-clad, and miles of beachside
dunes, lakes and bayous best explored in a pair of disposable
flip-flops. Whether you're a Phipps Plaza patron, a
Poncey-Highlands urban pioneer, or a suburban Jimmy Buffet wannabe,
Scenic 30-A is your scene. (This story details the three different
faces of 30-A, how it's a nice fit for three different types of
tourists.) (Laughinghouse, Atlanta Journal-Constitution freelancer;
not for use by NYTNS clients).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 19.
</P>
<P>
   IMAC-MCDONALDS _ COSTA RICA _ From the outside, it looks like
any other McDonald's, golden arches and all, plucked out of middle
America and plunked down in Central America. But on the inside,
this McDonald's (near San Jose, Costa Rica) has a some slightly
different combination meals. In addition to Big Macs, it has iMac
computers. And if you buy a combo meal and supersize those papas
fritas, you get 30 minutes of Internet access. (Martz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 19.
</P>
<P>
   CHEAP-TRAVEL _ There are so many travel-related sites on the
Internet it's easy to get overwhelmed. There are the very popular _
and very good _ sites for just about all of your travel needs. But
there are a host of lesser-known sites that also provide terrific
bargains. Take a look at three. (Marcano, Dayton Daily News). 15.
WITH: Ray Marcano column mug. MOVED
</P>
