<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   STYLE-PROM _ Young ladies will be wearing less fabric and
showing more skin in strapless gowns, two-piece formals with
hip-hugging waistbands and dresses with high slits or corset-tied
backs. (Hill, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-PROM _ DAYTON, Ohio _ It's a unique shopping experience
_ fun, exciting and filled with promise. Make that promise. Styles
that are hot for this year's prom season. (Moss, Dayton Daily
News). WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   PROM-SHOP _ Shopping tips for picking the right prom dress or
suit. (Moss, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE NEWS AND REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-BLACKJACK _ Movie review: ``Black Jack'' at Cinefest.
(StMurray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 7.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-EMPEROR _ Movie review: ``The Emperor and the Assassin.''
Long foreign film that didn't get an Oscar nod. (Ringel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-ERIN _ Movie review: ``Erin Brockovich'' with Julia
Roberts. It's a Julia you've never seen before (she's got kids and
not always a lot of makeup) in a role that's a cross between
``Norma Rae'' and ``Working Girl.'' Grade: B+. (BLongino, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 19.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-GHOST _ Movie review: ``Ghost Dog.'' Martial arts film.
(StMurray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-MAT _ Movie review: ``Beyond The Mat,'' a controversial
wrestling documentary with some good stuff. Grade: B. ((BLongino,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 14.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-CAPSULES _ Dayton Daily News film capsules, which include
family viewing info. (Dayton Daily News). 50.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-ERINBROCK _ ``Erin Brockovich'' movie review. Two and
one-half stars. Roberts has never been better as a blue-collar
crusader, but the story could have been more compelling. (Schwan,
Palm Beach Post). 21. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-AGNES _ ``Agnes Brown'' movie review. Two and one-half
stars. A sugar-coated look at a put-upon Dublin widow and her seven
children, distinguished by director Huston's earth mother
performance. (Erstein, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS _ Mini reviews of all currently playing
movies. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   MANILOW _ There was a time when the very mention of Barry
Manilow's name would prompt bursts of laughter from musical snobs.
Think Copacabana, Mandy, I Write the Songs and all his other hit
records: A cool set list, it wasn't. But while Manilow's name is
still synonymous with the schlock pop of the '70s, the
singer-songwriter has moved beyond those days. His 30th album,
Manilow Sings Sinatra, released in 1998, earned him critical kudos
and two Grammy nominations. (Passy, Palm Beach Post). 45.
</P>
<P>
   BOYBAND _ ATLANTA _ The making of a boy band. The man behind New
Kids on the Block and New Edition, Maurice Starr, now lives in
Atlanta and is trying to follow his formula, and that of Backstreet
Boys and 'N Sync, to form a new boy band, composed (except for one)
of kids from the Atlanta area. He may not succeed, but 6Piece gives
us a chance to examine how such formulaic bands are assembled.
Their album came out March 7; we attend the filming of their first
video on March 11, which we'll also shoot. (Longino/Eldredge,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 50. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-LATINPOP _ To advance Marc Anthony's performance at the
Tabernacle on Sunday, we take a brief look at the ascendance of
Latin pop. (Harrison, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-MUSIC _ We'll use SXSW as a reason to explore what Austin
music dot-coms are doing in the online world. Local singer Ginger
MacKenzie, for example, has gotten national exposure largely due to
MP3s downloaded from Austin Web sites. How have Austin's music and
tech scenes combined to make more successful musicians? How has the
combo benefitted startup music dot-coms? We'll talk about Austin
companies that are doing streaming audio and live Webcasts from
Austin clubs. (Riemenschneider, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAIN PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet ENTERTAIN page for the current week.
This layout is available now.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAINMENT 0316 _ The current troika of TV network
anchors has reached the age when most people think about
retirement. None has indicated a desire to step down yet. But
sooner or later, change will come for the first time in nearly two
decades. (Holloway, Austin American-Statesman) Art includes a
4-column photo illustration featuring the three anchors in front of
a birthday cake.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   INFO BOX _ An information box highlighting the careers of the
three main anchors.
</P>
<P>
   STAR FILE _ An interview with rock legend David Crosby, who
remains in harmony with today's fans. (Tate, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes a 6-pica color photo of David
Crosby.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO REVIEWS _ In ``The Bone Collector,'' Denzel Washington and
Angelina Jolie ignite a potent sexual chemistry that gives the film
added weight and helps mask the weakest point plots. Also reviews
of ``Outside Providence,'' ``Guinevere'' and ``Drive Me Crazy.''
(Staff, Cox News Service) Art includes a 18-pica color photo from
``The Bone Collector.''
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEWS _ In ``The Road to El Dorado,'' Elton John's second
CD of tunes written specifically for an animated film, the
52-year-old artist sounds like he's cutting these melodies out on
deadline from the same pattern tissue he used before. Also, reviews
of new releases from Gerald Levert and Peter Case. (Staff, Cox News
Service) Art includes a 6-pica color photo of Elton John.
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   RAMSEY-MEDIASAGA _ Friday is the publication date of John and
Patsy Ramsey's book, ``Death of Innocence,'' and of their interview
with Barbara Walters on ``20/20.'' A look at the latest wave in the
never-ending Ramsey media saga. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
