<P>
   MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   MANILOW _ There was a time when the very mention of Barry
Manilow's name would prompt bursts of laughter from musical snobs.
Think Copacabana, Mandy, I Write the Songs and all his other hit
records: A cool set list, it wasn't. But while Manilow's name is
still synonymous with the schlock pop of the '70s, the
singer-songwriter has moved beyond those days. His 30th album,
Manilow Sings Sinatra, released in 1998, earned him critical kudos
and two Grammy nominations. (Passy, Palm Beach Post). 45.
</P>
<P>
   BOYBAND _ ATLANTA _ The making of a boy band. The man behind New
Kids on the Block and New Edition, Maurice Starr, now lives in
Atlanta and is trying to follow his formula, and that of Backstreet
Boys and 'N Sync, to form a new boy band, composed (except for one)
of kids from the Atlanta area. He may not succeed, but 6Piece gives
us a chance to examine how such formulaic bands are assembled.
Their album came out March 7; we attend the filming of their first
video on March 11, which we'll also shoot. (Longino/Eldredge,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 50. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-LATINPOP _ To advance Marc Anthony's performance at the
Tabernacle on Sunday, we take a brief look at the ascendance of
Latin pop. (Harrison, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-MUSIC _ We'll use SXSW as a reason to explore what Austin
music dot-coms are doing in the online world. Local singer Ginger
MacKenzie, for example, has gotten national exposure largely due to
MP3s downloaded from Austin Web sites. How have Austin's music and
tech scenes combined to make more successful musicians? How has the
combo benefitted startup music dot-coms? We'll talk about Austin
companies that are doing streaming audio and live Webcasts from
Austin clubs. (Riemenschneider, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
