<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 11:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8633 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MORMONS-AZR &LR;      03-16 1903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORMONS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LDS CHURCH OFTEN STILL MISUNDERSTOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By MAUREEN JENKINS  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (RETRANSMITTING: EDITORS: INCLUDES KEY
 &UR; POINTS, LIST OF BELIEFS AT END OF TAKE.
 &UR; ALSO MOVING IN THE ``L'' CATEGORY) PHOENIX _ In some ways, the
Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints is a quintessential
American success story.
</P>
<P>
   Fleeing religious and political persecution in the 1840s,
members of this newly established church left Nauvoo, Ill., and
trekked west, setting up colonies and a distinct way of life. A
century and a half later, the little church organized by Joseph
Smith is one of the fastest-growing religions in the Americas &UR; and
across the globe, as well as the richest church per capita in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   So, why is the Mormon Church still so maligned and little
understood within some Christian circles?
</P>
<P>
   This never-quite-resolved question again moved to the forefront
with an ``East Valley Tribune'' story headlined ``Christian fest
snubs Mormons,'' referring to the Jan. 15 Festival of Faith 2000
event at Bank One Ballpark in Phoenix. A gathering billed as the
largest-ever ecumenical assembly of Christians in Arizona history,
it attracted 35,000 people from about 400 Protestant, Catholic and
Orthodox congregations.
</P>
<P>
   The Latter-day Saints, however, were not among these.
</P>
<P>
   Initially included in the festival's planning, the Mormon Church
later found itself excluded, apparently because some conservative
organizers didn't consider Latter-day Saints to be Christians.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an ideal world, there would be total acceptance, total
understanding, total love,'' said the Rev. Paul Eppinger, executive
director of the Arizona Ecumenical Council and a Festival of Faith
lead organizer. ``But unfortunately, we do not live in an ideal
world and therefore, in our desire to make the Christian church
more understanding of each group, there are first steps we must
take, then the second step, the third step, the fourth step.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting Evangelicals, mainline Protestants, Catholics and
Eastern Orthodox Christians to meet with each other was that first
step. Broadening the ecumenical net to include churches such as the
Latter-day Saints clearly would be another.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of this issue lie matters of doctrine and theology
_ and the notion of just WHO is a Christian.
</P>
<P>
   Evangelicals who believe in literal biblical interpretation say
the Mormons aren't. The Latter-day Saints, who believe their faith
is a restoration of the original church founded by Jesus Christ and
his 12 disciples, claim they belong to the true Christian church. &QL; 
ROOTS OF DISAGREEMENT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But just who creates the yardstick that determines which
denominations are Christians? And what standard are these groups
measured against?
</P>
<P>
   Is it a historical faith believed to be derived from the intent
of Jesus' teachings? Or is it the European-spawned brand of
Catholicism and Protestantism, with its various creeds and
traditions influenced by culture?
</P>
<P>
   And does a church's definition of itself determine where it fits
on the religious landscape?
</P>
<P>
   Although the Mormon Church is neither Catholic nor Protestant,
says Phoenix metro area spokesman Wilford Andersen, it's no less
Christian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people understand we can respectfully disagree on
matters of Christian doctrine,'' Andersen said, ``but should never
disagree on Christian conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``There certainly are some (churches) who find it difficult to
work together with us, and I respect that as long as we don't have
ill will toward each other and as long as we don't have
misinformation.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, is the crux of the rift between Mormons and
evangelical Christians.
</P>
<P>
   Richard N. Ostling, co-author of the acclaimed ``Mormon America:
The Power and the Promise'' (HarperSanFrancisco, $26), says the LDS
Church's ``sweeping policy of secrecy'' contributes to the faith
being misunderstood in mainstream American religious culture. Its
weddings are held in temples that require church-issued
``recommends'' to enter, meaning non-Mormons never get inside. Even
the church's governing documents _ the sort that many denominations
publish on their Web sites _ are off-limits to outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you have this situation, it creates rumors,
speculations, misinformation,'' said Ostling, who wrote ``Mormon
America'' with his wife, Joan K. Ostling. ``There is room for a lot
of confusion.``
</P>
<P>
   Not that Mormons and their conservative Christian critics tend
to disagree much on matters of morality and social values. Both
groups stress the importance of family and personal responsibility,
and decry abortion, gambling and same-sex unions.
</P>
<P>
   In California, for example, a coalition of Southern Baptists,
Catholics and Mormons recently joined forces to pass Proposition 22
on Tuesday, which would ban same-sex marriages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the disagreement is doctrinal,'' Ostling said,
``rather than moral, political and cultural. The fundamental issues
between Mormonism and traditional Christianity are the nature of
God, the doctrine of Christ, the Bible's authority, and the
doctrine of humanity and relating to God.''
</P>
<P>
   Attempting to examine the commonalities and differences between
the groups, professors Craig L. Blomberg of Denver Seminary and
Stephen E. Robinson of Brigham Young University wrote the 1997
book, ``How Wide the Divide? A Mormon and an Evangelical in
Conversation'' (InterVarsity Press, $11.99).
</P>
<P>
   Their point-counterpoint text includes a ``joint conclusion'' at
the end of each chapter and doesn't dwell on trying to prove the
other wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen says this civil tolerance and respect _ rather than
active teaching against other religions _ is central to Mormon
faith. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DIFFERENT, YET SIMILAR &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ostling says it's ``almost predictable'' that Mormons and
evangelicals butt heads theologically, as both target the same
group of potential converts.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Cornwall, a sociology professor at the LDS Church's
Brigham Young University in Provo, Utah, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   Many sociologists believe the animosity between the groups
exists because ``we share the same niche,'' Cornwall said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can use that marketplace language, both Evangelicals
and Mormons share the same target: the unchurched,'' she adds. ``We
compete in the marketplace of religion, and evangelicals want to
make sure their targets realize Mormons are different.''
</P>
<P>
   Ostling thinks today's Mormon Church, especially under current
President Gordon B. Hinckley's administration, goes ``back and
forth'' on positioning itself closer to ``mainstream''
Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mormonism probably presents less of its doctrine to persons
before baptism than any other religious group I can think of,'' he
said. ``The key to winning converts and solidifying them in the
faith is the community, and not the isolated individual. Some of
the more complex doctrinal areas are left for later on.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Andersen says the church doesn't dilute its theology
just to make connections with potential members or other
Christians.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past several decades, the church has sought
opportunities to team up with other faiths in humanitarian efforts.
</P>
<P>
   In the Phoenix area, LDS Church members belong to the InterFaith
Action Coalition of Arizona, which is composed of representatives
of 12 different faiths, from Jewish to Buddhist to Christian.
</P>
<P>
   Mormons' involvement in such groups across the nation probably
is a trickle-down effect of Hinckley's public relations-savvy
administration, which is trying to build bridges with other
religions while highlighting positive aspects of Mormon life.
</P>
<P>
   Cornwall says Hinckley's just-released book, ``Standing for
Something: 10 Neglected Virtues That Will Heal Our Hearts and
Homes'' (Times Books, $24.00), is one such effort, capitalizing on
Americans' interest in back-to-basic values without hitting readers
over the head with Mormon theology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mormons want to be both different and the same (as other
Americans),'' Cornwall said. ``Different in the sense we know our
faith is different from other faiths, but the same in that we want
people to see that we can be as successful as anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's establishing this common ground, Andersen says, that
will ultimately break down barriers, both social and doctrinal,
that stand between faith groups. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SOME FACTS ABOUT THE CHURCH OF JESUS CHRIST OF LATTER-DAY SAINTS: &QL; 
 &QL; 
_One of the world's fastest-growing religions, the LDS Church
claims 10.3 million members, with just more than half living
outside the United States. About one-sixth of LDS members live in
Utah. &QL; 
_If the LDS Church were a U.S. corporation, its revenues would
place it No. 243 on the ``Fortune'' 500 list. &QL; 
_The Mormon Church is one of the nation's largest landowners, with
property equal to the size of Delaware. &QL; 
_Unlike most churches, the LDS Church has no professional clergy.
Members take turns speaking at Sunday sacrament meetings, or
worship services. Members also serve in unpaid ``callings,'' or
assignments, that get work done throughout the church. &QL; 
_Some of the church's best-known members include Steve Young, a San
Francisco 49ers quarterback; singers Donny and Marie Osmond and
Gladys Knight; Stephen R. Covey, bestselling author of ``7 Habits
of Highly Effective People''; and Orrin Hatch, a Utah senator and
former presidential candidate. &QL; 
_Until 1978, Black men were not ordained to the lay priesthood _ a
position reversed by official declaration of then-President Spencer
W. Kimball. Today, R&AMP;B singer Knight is probably the Mormon
Church's best-known Black member. &QL; 
_Source: ``Mormon America: The Power and the Promise,''by Richard
N. Ostling and Joan K. Ostling. &QL; 
_About 150,000 Mormons live in the Phoenix area, and about 300,000
live within Arizona. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SOME KEY BELIEFS &QL; 
 &QL; 
_With the revelations delivered by God the father and his son,
Jesus Christ, to church founder Joseph Smith in 1820, a restoration
of the ``truths, powers and priesthood authority of the ancient
church'' was constituted as the Church of Jesus Christ of
Latter-day Saints. Mormons believe they follow Christ's true
gospel, which they say was lost after the deaths of the original 12
disciples. &QL; 
_Divine revelation for the church's direction comes from God to the
president of the church (currently Gordon B. Hinckley). Presidents
are viewed as prophets in the same tradition as Abraham, Moses and
Peter. &QL; 
_In addition to the King James version of the Christian Bible,
Latter-day Saints consider ``The Book of Mormon: Another Testament
of Jesus Christ'' divinely inspired scripture, along with ``The
Doctrine and Covenants'' and ``The Pearl of Great Price,'' other
revelations and writings given since the church's start in 1830. &QL; 
_Mormons don't believe in the traditional concept of ``original
sin'' (that all humans are born sinners because of the Garden of
Eden sin of Adam and Eve), but rather that people are punished for
the sins they commit. &QL; 
_Mormons abstain from using tobacco, alcoholic beverages, tea and
coffee in adherence to ``The Word of Wisdom,'' a health code
revealed to founder Joseph Smith in 1833. &QL; 
_Members are required to tithe, or give a 10th of their income, to
the church to remain members in good standing and gain access to
temples for sacred ordinances. &QL; 
Source: The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1156EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
