<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINOSAURS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DINOSAURS' EVOLUTION CONTINUES EVEN
 TODAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
 (EDITORS: RETRANSMITTING  /  ALSO MOVED IN
 THE ``L'' CATEGORY) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dinosaurs keep evolving. It doesn't matter that they died out en
masse 65 million years ago, that not a single giant lizard remains
alive, even in some remote and steamy Amazonian plateau. None of
that matters: They evolve anyway.
</P>
<P>
   They evolved from cold-blooded sluggards to warm-blooded
amphetamine addicts. They grew feathers. The carnivores bent over
from the anthropomorphized Godzilla posture they used to have to
something a lot more like a gigantic clucking hen.
</P>
<P>
   Such changes shouldn't be surprising. As scholarship advances,
our images of the dinosaurs have had to step forward, too. But it
isn't only paleontology that has caused the changes in our sense of
prehistoric life. It is also politics.
</P>
<P>
   We have a more inclusive sense of culture these days, so the
primarily European and North American bias we have had in the past
about our Mesozoic predecessors has changed to make room for Asia,
Africa and South America.
</P>
<P>
   When I was a boy, fascinated by everything dinosaurian in the
1950s, there were about 20 or so beasts that made up the
``canonical'' list of dinosaurs. They included brontosaurs,
stegosaurs, tyrannosaurs, triceratops and a variety of oddly
ornamented hadrosaurs.
</P>
<P>
   These were the basic animals that populated our vision of a
misty, green tropical prehistory. They are the beasts of ``King
Kong, Lost World'' and dozens of other pop culture permutations of
the terrible lizards.
</P>
<P>
   They also were the fossils found in Wyoming, Utah and New
Jersey. They were ``our'' dinosaurs, and they somehow seemed more
important for that.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there were always more genera of fossil than the popular
ones. And with a recent explosion in dino digs, the number of
official dinosaur genera has increased to something like 350. And
that is just genera: Several of them also include multiple species.
By one count, there are 15 species of triceratops.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in the popular awareness of dinosaur genera _ as
evidenced in many of the recent books on the subject for the
general reader _ is as much a change in our openness to diversity
as it is the number of new fossils found.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, a few ``representative types'' were enough to
define the prehistoric world. But now, those types _ and their
origins _ seem too limited.
</P>
<P>
   And further evidence of this are the many names for dinosaurs
that sound multiculti on the tongue: jubbulpuria (India);
yangchuanosaurus (China); austrosaurus (Australia); majungasaurus
(Africa); riojasaurus (Argentina). There is even an antarctosaurus.
</P>
<P>
   And from the Navajo Reservation in northern Arizona comes the
segisaurus, from Tsegi Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   Just open the new book, ``Walking With Dinosaurs: A Natural
History'' (DK Publishing, $25), and there on a single page you find
leaellynasaura, muttaburrasaurus and koolasuchus, names with a
decidedly third-world flavor on the tongue.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt there is a long way to go before the laplatasaurus of
South America supplants the more familiar North American
apatosaurus (formerly the brontosaurus) in third-graders'
imaginations, but open up any recent book on the subject and you
will find newer, sexier and more politically diverse dinosaurs
showing up.
</P>
<P>
   Prehistory now seems as diverse as today. &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Richard.Nilsen(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or
(602) 444-8823.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1200EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
