<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 12:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8640 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      03-16 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: RETRANSMITTING / ALSO MOVING IN
 &UR; THE ``E'' CATEGORY) &QL; 
Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new books:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``AFTERBURN'' &QL; 
 &UR; By Colin Harrison (FSG, $25) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The thing about thrillers is that so many of them are bad.
Abysmal, even. It's a genre so plagued by hack writers and
bush-league prose that when you find one like this, you want to
call it by another name. But a thriller it is _ the long, patient
kind, with underplayed dialogue and characters who sidestep
stereotype every time it shows up to claim them. The protagonist is
Charlie Ravich, a former Vietnam fighter pilot and POW now in his
late 50s who faces crisis in his private life and in his
multimillion-dollar corporate affairs. Harrison spends much of his
book establishing a thin connection between Charlie and a young
woman named Christina Welles, who has just been released from
prison and who, with her former boyfriend, is suspected of stealing
from a mobster who really, REALLY, wants his money back. There's
sex. There's violence (we don't want to spoil your fun if you have
a taste for it, but for the sake of the squeamish, we'll mention a
little torture scene involving an electric drill and a circular saw
_ and that's not the last of it). If you can take the gore, this
book is enough to give a weak genre a good name. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``CINEMA SOUTHWEST'' &QL; 
 &UR; By John A. Murray (Northland, $21.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The photo on the cover is of John Ford making a scene from ``The
Searchers'' in 1956, but that's just the predictable side of
filmmaking in the American Southwest. Think of the alternatives. In
1965, Max Von Sydow, as Jesus, delivered the Sermon on the Mount on
Utah's Green River Overlook in ``The Greatest Story Ever Told.''
Dennis Hopper and Peter Fonda camped in Anasazi ruins on their way
east in ``Easy Rider.'' Robert Duvall turned his life around on the
Texas prairie in ``Tender Mercies,'' and in ``Bonnie and Clyde,''
Warren Beatty and Faye Dunaway robbed an actual bank in the rural
community of Pilot Point, Texas _ the same bank that the real
Bonnie Parker and Clyde Barrow had robbed about 40 years earlier.
In this book, due out at the end of the month, Murray looks at the
Southwest and its starring role in so many American films. Included
are some great photographs _ our favorite, we confess, is of John
Wayne (in ``She Wore a Yellow Ribbon'') looking grandly out at that
mist-shrouded Big Daddy of film locations, Monument Valley. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``EATING WELL FOR OPTIMUM HEALTH'' &QL; 
 &UR; By Andrew Weil (Knopf, $25) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's a chapter here in which Weil sets out to devise what he
calls ``the worst diet in the world,'' which after a few paragraphs
sounded so suspiciously like our own bill of fare that we began to
wonder whether Weil had us under surveillance. It was humbling, but
more fun to read than, say, the section called ``A Healing Story:
From French Fries to Kale,'' or ``The Macronutrients: An
Overview.'' But we are not hopeless, no siree. We love broccoli. We
love salmon. Unfortunately, we have learned from Weil that not all
salmon are equal, that we need to worry not only about our own
diets but about the diets of the fish we eat, which is one step
further down the food chain than we care to go. Eggs are another
research project. ``Eggs of chickens,'' Weil writes, ``(are) good
sources of omega-3 fatty acids if they come from free-range
chickens or chickens whose diets are supplemented with omega-3-rich
algae.'' Are we up to this task? No, but we know that Weil has made
many converts-to-wellness, so rush to the store: His new book is
out, with the author looking hale and hearty on the cover.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``TIGERS IN THE SNOW''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Peter Matthiessen (North Point, $27) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most of us know that the tiger is beautiful, but we also have
been raised with an unshakable idea of its fierceness, the
fearsome, predatory aggression of Shere Khan in Rudyard Kipling's
``The Jungle Book.'' But Matthiessen points out that the hunter,
Jim Corbett, in his book ``The Man-eaters of Kumaon,'' refers to
the tiger as ``a large-hearted gentleman of bottomless courage.''
That's what this book aims to give you _ a new look at the tiger,
at its history, its endangered habitats, its dwindling numbers, its
extreme vulnerability to poachers, and finally, at the efforts of
researchers and wildlife biologists to study and preserve it. The
book also conveys the quiet majesty of the animal, largely through
the author's eloquent interest and regard for it. With an
introduction and color photographs by Maurice Hornocker, tiger
expert and co-founder of the Siberian Tiger Project. Matthiessen's
fans should also look for ``The Peter Matthiessen Reader''
(Vintage, $14), in which editor McKay Jenkins assembles excerpts
from the author's books of non-fiction, including ``The Snow
Leopard'' and ``Men's Lives.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1201EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 12:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8654 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-IRISH-HEROES-HNS &LR;      03-16 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRISH-HEROES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FOR MARCH, A WEALTH OF READING ON IRELAND 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOBBIE HESS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the publishing world, the month of March is the time to
bring out all books related to Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Among this year's best is Terry Golway's ``For the Cause of
Liberty _ A Thousand Years of Ireland's Heroes'' (Simon and
Schuster, $26, 335 pages).
</P>
<P>
   In 1155, the English first sent troops to Ireland, a land
populated by the Gaels, the descendants of the Celts. ``Detached
not only from the (European) continent but from the neighboring
island to the east (England), the Gaels were different, different
in their practice of Christianity, different in their law and
customs. Religious irregularities such as divorce and the active
leadership of women in religious life were permitted in Gaelic
Christianity, while little heed was paid to the papacy. Ireland had
a vibrant, distinctive literature, filled with heroic tales of
pagan warriors. ... The most famous of these legendary warriors was
Cuchulain, a great champion who was slain in defense of his
homeland.''
</P>
<P>
   So many of Ireland's heroes fought for Ireland's freedom. Some
fought with weapons, some with words. Some were male, some were
female. Some were Catholic, some were Protestant. Some died for
Ireland, some lived to fight on. Some became famous, some were
known only by a few. All fought for what they believed in.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Boru defeated the Vikings in 1014. Red Hugh O'Donnell
fought the English in 1601 and lost. Patrick Sarsfield led the
rebels at the Battle of the Boyne in 1690 and was defeated. In
1729, Jonathan Swift wrote ``A Modest Proposal'' _ a satire dealing
with the plight of the poor after three years of famine. Wolfe Tone
led a failed rebellion in 1798 and killed himself before the
authorities could hang him. In the 1930s, Daniel ``The Liberator''
O'Connell worked in alliance with British liberals and ``he won
reforms that eased the plight of the Irish Catholic masses.''
</P>
<P>
   Jane Francesca Elgee wrote militant poetry under the pen name
Speranza:
</P>
<P>
   Abject tears and prayers submissive _
</P>
<P>
   Have the eyes and cannot see?
</P>
<P>
   Never country gained her freedom
</P>
<P>
   When she sued on bended knee.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Stewart Parnell became the champion of the landless
farmers and Catholics in the mid-1850s. In the 1890s, William
Butler Yeats and Maud Gonne sparked a revival of Irish literature
and culture. In 1902, Yeats and Lady Augusta Gregory wrote
``Cathleen ni Houlihan,'' a play that ``stirred nationalist
passions.''
</P>
<P>
   Those passions led to a new crop of freedom fighters _ Padraig
Pearse, James Larkin, Thomas Clark, James Connolly, Countess
Constance Markievicz, Thomas MacDonagh, Joseph Plunkett, Eamonn
Ceant, Sean MacDiarmadal, Michael Collins, Eamon de Valera, Roger
Casement. For their roles in the Easter Sunday uprising of 1916,
Pearse, Clark, MacDonagh, Plunkett, John MacBride and four others
were executed. In 1922, Collins was shot when he agreed to less
than full independence from Britain.
</P>
<P>
   As Northern Ireland became a battleground in the 1960s, new
leaders would emerge _ John Hume, Gerry Adams, Bernadette Devlin on
the Catholic side; Ian Paisley on the Protestant side.
</P>
<P>
   Golway provides a terrific look at Irish history. This is not
dull history, but a living, breathing look at how a nation evolved
over 1,000 years. And it is fairly impartial, a rarity when dealing
with anything Irish.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, one cannot say the same about William Magan's
``The Story of Ireland _ A History of an Ancient Family and Their
Country'' (Element Books, $19.95 paperback, 413 pages). Magan's
history up to about 1800 is OK. But he is so interested in trying
to prove how valuable his land-owning family has been to Ireland,
he gives short shift to historical events. He barely mentions the
potato famine, and dismisses the Easter uprising with two
sentences. This a book that never should have been published.
</P>
<P>
   For those interested in Irish legends, pick up ``The Raid _ A
Dramatic Retelling of Ireland's Epic Tale'' by Randy Lee Eickhoff
(Forge, $13.95 paperback, 267 pages).
</P>
<P>
   After lovemaking, Ailill, the king of Connacht, and his wife,
Maeve, argue over who is the wealthiest. Maeve insists that each of
their assets must be added up. All is even, until they add on a
magnificent bull owned by Ailill. When she discovers there is an
even better bull in Ulster, she declares war on Ulster and marches
out to retrieve the Brown Bull of Cooley.
</P>
<P>
   Because a curse has been placed on the men of Ulster, the only
person who can stop Maeve and Ailill is the boy warrior Cuchulain.
He is invincible and kills scores at a time. Month after month, he
fights alone, waiting for the curse on Ulster fighters to end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Raid'' is a lusty and violent tale full of the intrigue
and over-the-top characters that every good epic should have.
</P>
<P>
   Another worthy addition to any Irish-lover's bookcase is ``The
Penguin Book of Irish Fiction'' edited by Colm Toibin (Viking, $40,
1073 pages). The first excerpt is from Jonathan Swift's
``Gulliver's Travels.'' Other entries include Anthony Trollope,
Bram Stoker, Oscar Wilde, James Joyce, Samuel Beckett, Neil Jordan,
Patrick McCabe, Roddy Doyle and many more.
</P>
<P>
   I have only skimmed through this weighty tome, but you know it
is one of those books that you'll pick up periodically and find
another author to enjoy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1255EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 12:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8655 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-MUSIC-CAROL-KAYE-LADN     03-16 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CAROL-KAYE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MOST HEARD BASS PLAYER YOU NEVER HEARD OF
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: ART is moving to NYTNS clients.) 
 
 
caption: 
The improvisational interplay of Thumbs Up members Ray Pizzi, left,
Carol Kaye and Mitch Holder is documented on a new live album. Phil
McCarten/Daily News 
 
 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Thumbs Up trio's high level of musicianship becomes evident
the moment you learn the 7 1/2-minute version of the jazz standard
``Green Dolphin Street,'' which opens the band's live album, was
improvised on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the drummerless trio _ Ray Pizzi (sax, flute), Mitch
Holder (guitar) and Carol Kaye (bass) _ have appeared on thousands
of records as session musicians. The three friends came together in
late 1998 to play a series of dates at two local clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The just-issued live album, ``Thumbs Up,'' documents those gigs
with a set of covers and originals touching on straight-ahead jazz,
blues, Latin and r&AMP;b.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were the first gigs we ever played together,'' offers
Pizzi. ``It's all about experience. Carol and Mitch have literally
done it all. They're well-rounded musicians who haven't let work
inhibit creativity. A lot of people who do record dates get so
busy, they forget the joy of making music. We all still have the
joy of playing. That's very important.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's no understatement. This group really has done it all.
Pizzi played and recorded with everyone from Dizzy Gillespie,
Horace Silver and Henry Mancini to John Williams and Frank Zappa. A
former member of the Johnny Carson-era ``Tonight Show'' orchestra,
Holder cut hits with Lionel Richie, Frank Sinatra, Barbra Streisand
and Dionne Warwick, along with scores of TV and film dates. Kaye is
known as the city's No. 1 studio bassist and has worked extensively
with Phil Spector, Brian Wilson, Lee Hazlewood and other top
producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the three of us play together, we know how to groove,''
Kaye said. ``We don't need a drummer to show us where the beat is.
It's a natural thing.''
</P>
<P>
   When Thumbs Up appeared at McCabe's and the Jazz Bakery for
three dates that resulted in the album, word spread, and a chorus
line of percussionists showed up, hoping to land a gig with the
high-profile trio.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact we don't use drums lets people hear a lot more of
what's going on musically,'' Holder said. ``When you have a band,
people tend to hear the melody above all, and the drums and rhythm
instruments become like a blanket. With our trio, you hear so much
more. It allows the listener to become more involved. It's not what
you play, it's what you leave out.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Holder's ongoing session jobs is as part of the ensemble
that scores TV's ``The Simpsons.'' It's one of the last TV shows
that uses actual musicians instead of synthesizers and samples, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   When not working sessions himself, Pizzi appears at 11 a.m.
Sundays at the Lighthouse in Hermosa Beach with the Bobby White
Quintet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice, relaxed date,'' Pizzi said. ``Straight-ahead jazz
standards.''
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Kaye was a mainstream jazz player when she began
guesting on rock 'n' roll dates in the late '50s, beginning with a
Sam Cooke session.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam's music was so good, I didn't mind it,'' she said from her
Canyon Country home. ``It got to be a lot of rock dates after that.
But a lot of that stuff I didn't really like. Still, we all had
kids, and we were making a lot of dough.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaye, who turns 65 on March 24, recalled it was evident that
some of the pop sessions she played had lasting qualities. For
example, there was the Beach Boys' ``Pet Sounds,'' Brian Wilson's
1966 masterpiece, widely considered among the greatest pop albums
ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian was a gas to work for,'' Kaye said. ``Frankly, all the
bass parts I played, he wrote. He wasn't like the other guys I
worked for back then. He wrote down the notes. The others would
sort of tell you what they needed, and you had to make up the
parts. It was obvious he was a genius early on. With him, you got
the idea the records would last forever. You knew the music would
live on.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaye said much of today's pop and rock lacks the ``sound and
feel of real music. Believe it or not, the tunes in the '60s were
not that much better. But we had to dress up the songs with our
playing. We were jazz players cutting rock 'n' roll. And we had to
keep that quiet because some of the young producers were
intimidated by jazz.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other top-flight session musicians of the era, Kaye was
uncredited on most of the albums she worked on. Especially when the
record company wanted the public to believe the band billed on the
record cover was performing its own music.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would take weeks and weeks for some of these groups to get
something good in the studio,'' Kaye said. ``We could cut a hit
album in six hours. The labels didn't want to advertise the fact
that studio players were involved. So, like on the surf records,
we'd cut 'em, and the record company would go out and hire some
cute guys to tour as the band.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with Thumbs Up (which will appear locally in the next few
months), Kaye teaches bass and does the occasional session, such as
one for the current Matthew Sweet disc.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great fun,'' she said. ``We were trying to capture the
Phil Spector sound, and we actually got pretty close. There were
really nice vibes.''
</P>
<P>
   With the recent addition of a session musicians category to the
Rock and Roll Hall of Fame induction ceremonies, Kaye is optimistic
that architects of pop such as herself will begin getting the
recognition they've long deserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not bragging, but I think it's important for kids to know
there were hard-working people who cut that music who weren't into
drugs,'' she said. ``I'd like young people to realize that being in
the music business can be a great profession even if you're not a
big star. You can make a very good living all your life through
music.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if you don't play, you can teach.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
