<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8664 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-16 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MARTHA STEWART CAN PAINT THE RED PLANET GREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Houston, we have a problem, but I know just the
person who can solve it. Ask Martha.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you heard that NASA scientists have discovered a scary
threat to the astronauts who will eventually embark on the space
agency's two-year mission to Mars.
</P>
<P>
   Because there is no way to pack a spacecraft with enough
prepared food to last two years, the crew will have to grow,
process and cook much of its food. The threat:
</P>
<P>
   Processing and cooking the kinds of raw plant products the crew
will grow _ rice, soya, grains _ release something called
``volatile organic compounds,'' or VOCs.
</P>
<P>
   In a regular kitchen or even a Winnebago, VOCs are
inconsequential. You just open a window or turn on the exhaust fan.
But spaceships have no exhaust system; VOCs will build up and cause
major irritation of eyes, mucous membranes and (yikes) genitalia.
</P>
<P>
   If it took only a few months to get to Mars, everybody could
bite the bullet. Russian and American astronauts already proved
this last year when the Mir space station deteriorated into a
semi-slum.
</P>
<P>
   But two years is way too long for working scientists _ or
anybody, for that matter _ to endure perpetually inflamed eyes,
noses, mouths and private parts.
</P>
<P>
   What to do?
</P>
<P>
   As I said, ask Martha Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, why not sign her up as a crew member and take her
along?
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to living conditions, Martha knows everything
about how to make them better, and more beautiful. Or if she
doesn't know, she'll dig away and soon find a solution. She is the
queen of habitat problem-solving.
</P>
<P>
   The best minds at NASA may be stumped about VOC build-up and
alternatives to growing and cooking food onboard a spaceship. But,
as anyone knows who has read Martha Stewart's magazine, browsed her
Web site, watched her TV show or listened to her daily ``Ask
Martha'' radio program, NOTHING stumps her.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the task is fashioning little bags of candy confetti out
of tulle or winterizing a lawn mower and properly storing it in the
garage, Martha knows the best way.
</P>
<P>
   Why would her problem-solving prowess stop at Earth's
atmosphere?
</P>
<P>
   Just picture Martha up there in Star Trek country, pacing the
spaceship, hands on hips. She surveys every piece of hardware,
every design element, every curve and plane. No matter where she
stops, no matter what she looks under or behind, she smiles gently
and announces, ``We can do better than this!''
</P>
<P>
   Really, this is a win-win prospect for everyone. NASA will get
its VOC glitch solved (long before the spacecraft blasts off for
Mars) and the addition of Martha to the crew should alleviate most
of the mission's other potential problems.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, according to the London Independent, the Mars
flight is expected to be ``one of the most unpleasant that anyone
could experience. Psychologists have already likened it to being
stuck in the Antarctic winter, with no option of going outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Games like chess will be verboten because they might foster
hostile, uncooperative vibes.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, as for sex, there is still no evidence that it is
feasible in space, even if the crew members wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   Not feasible? Where there's a will, Martha Stewart finds a way.
And the sex would be beautiful, gracious AND functional.
</P>
<P>
   She would also dream up fabulous games and activities that build
team spirit. And, if NASA gives her a decent decorating allowance,
crew members wouldn't think they're in Antarctica, but in a condo
complex in Key West.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of us will win, too. For two full years, no matter how
easy or simple Martha tells us a project will be, we won't have to
feel guilty, stupid or slothful for not doing it.
</P>
<P>
   After all, she will be in a spaceship headed for Mars. Even
Martha Stewart can't make us believe that is a world within our
reach.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
