<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN COULD USE A THATCHER-LIKE THRASHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Japanese stock market took a dive early this week when the
Japanese government announced that the country's economy had once
more fallen into recession.
</P>
<P>
   For investors, this was a case of deja vu all over again. Since
1992 the Japanese economy has regularly threatened to break out of
its slump only to sink back into the mire.
</P>
<P>
   Here's our advice to investors: The time to get excited about
Japan is when you see a Japanese politician come to power who
reminds you of Margaret Thatcher.
</P>
<P>
   No, it doesn't have to be a woman. Nor would she have to start a
war in a remote part of the world. We are talking about Margaret
Thatcher, the free-market radical, the Margaret Thatcher who said
quite bluntly that the old system wasn't working and that it needed
to be junked, not just fine-tuned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a feeling in Japan that the system that
worked so well is quite dysfunctional and needs a thorough
shaking,'' said Daniel Yergin, chairman of Cambridge Energy
Research Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Yergin is a good person to ask about parallels between Japan and
Mrs. Thatcher's Great Britain. In 1998 Yergin and a colleague wrote
``The Commanding Heights,'' a book about the triumph of market
economies around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The best chapter in the book is the story of Thatcher and her
intellectual mentor, Keith Joseph. The Britain they confronted in
the 1970s was an economic disaster area. Unemployment was high. So
was inflation. And there was a widespread feeling that the country
was on a permanent path of decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine _ people accepting decline?'' Thatcher told
Yergin.
</P>
<P>
   Thatcher concluded the problem was too much government
involvement in the economy. Joseph put it simply when he said, ``We
are over-governed, over-spent, over-taxed, over-borrowed, and
over-manned.'' The two also decided that the classic Keynesian
remedy, government deficit spending, wasn't going to fix things.
</P>
<P>
   What was needed was nothing less than an overhaul of the
country's political and economic culture. Over a period of years
Thatcher tangled with labor unions and privatized many of Britain's
leading industries. She made plenty of enemies and mistakes along
the way.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the end, most people in Britain, even her political
rivals, conceded that the country badly needed the cage-rattling
that Thatcher administered.
</P>
<P>
   Like Britain in the 1970s, Japan in the year 2000 is confronting
the prospect of permanent decline.
</P>
<P>
   The country's economy has barely grown since 1992. Once a
technological leader, Japan these days is playing catch-up in many
industries. Consumers refuse to spend money. The stock market has
rallied, but without much conviction.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's budget deficit has ballooned because the government
keeps spending money on massive public works projects that don't
seem to do much good.
</P>
<P>
   To many economists, the Japanese government is still part of the
problem, rather than the solution. ``Japan still has a
command-and-control economy,'' said Mark Zandi, chief economist at
RFA Dismal Sciences, a Pennsylvania forecasting firm. ``When it
comes to deregulation, they are at least a decade behind the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Japan has made changes, particularly in the financial sector,
but Japan-watchers say the moves amount to baby steps when giant
steps are required. Maureen Allyn, chief economist at Scudder
Kemper Investments, complains that some of the government's
spending programs have propped up politically connected failing
companies. ``There is still too much of an attitude that says: `We
will protect you from change,' '' said Allyn.
</P>
<P>
   In most countries, a decade of rotten economic performance would
have spelled trouble for the ruling political party. In this
country, the rascals would have been tossed out long ago.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, however, the Liberal Democratic Party has managed to
cling to power. ``There doesn't seem to be enough sense of crisis
yet,'' said Nariman Behravesh, chief international economist at
Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI.
</P>
<P>
   Yergin is among those who see some glimmers of hope. He points
out that there are signs of life in some of Japan's leading-edge
companies. Young people are demanding change. Small stocks have
outperformed big ones because they are more attuned to the world's
new economy. ``Below the surface you have a lot of innovation going
on,'' said Yergin.
</P>
<P>
   He may be right. But we are not convinced yet. In fact, we are
keeping our money on the sidelines until we see that Japanese Mrs.
Thatcher make her appearance. We want to hear a Japanese leader
declare as Thatcher once did: ``I am the rebel head of the
establishment government.''
</P>
<P>
   When that day comes, we'll issue our ``buy'' recommendation for
the Japanese stock market.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1320EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8675 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-2TAK     03-16 1159
</HEADER>
