<HEADER>
A8676 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-PRICELINE-GROCERIES-B     03-16 1268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRICELINE-GROCERIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRICELINE BRANCHES OUT INTO GROCERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Priceline.com, the Web company known for its name-your-own-price
airline tickets and offbeat ads featuring ``Star Trek's'' William
Shatner, is about to extend its grocery business through an
alliance with the Stop &AMP; Shop Supermarket Co.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Sunday, Priceline WebHouse Club, a private affiliate of
Priceline.com Inc., plans to offer consumers similar
name-your-own-price deals on everything from TV dinners to tuna
fish and tortilla chips.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, the way consumers would place bids on a Web
site, then pick up their groceries in a brick-and-mortar Stop &AMP;
Shop, might seem complex and confusing.
</P>
<P>
   But that hasn't slowed down New Yorkers. Since first offering
its grocery service in the metropolitan New York market in
November, close to 300,000 consumers have applied for WebHouse
membership cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``In tough, tough New York, 4 percent of the population signed
up in less than two months,'' said Harry E. Wells, an analyst with
Adams Harkness &AMP; Hill in Boston. ``I didn't think you could get 4
percent of New Yorkers to sign up for free $2 bills.''
</P>
<P>
   Webhouse isn't stopping with groceries. In May, it plans to
apply the name-your-own-price philosophy to gasoline. And down the
road, who knows? Maybe prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   WebHouse of Stamford, Conn., is not to be confused with online
grocers such as HomeRuns.com, Streamline.com, or ShopLink.com,
where customers order groceries online and then get home delivery.
In theory, a customer of one of these services never needs to visit
a brick-and-mortar supermarket again. These outfits use the
Internet to offer convenience.
</P>
<P>
   WebHouse has a different strategy. Instead of convenience, it
uses the Internet to offer discounts and value, said Jay S. Walker,
founder of both Webhouse and Priceline.com.
</P>
<P>
   At a special place on Priceline.com's Web site, consumers make
offers on groceries, much as they might bid on airline tickets from
the company. If their grocery prices are accepted, consumers next
go to a Stop &AMP; Shop, pick the items off store shelves, and take
their shopping carts through a checkout line.
</P>
<P>
   In return for their extra time and effort, WebHouse customers
are rewarded with average savings of about $13 on a $35 order,
Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our customer is anyone who wants to save $10 to $20 a week on
groceries,'' said Walker, adding that a value-conscious consumer
who is fond of using coupons or shopping at a BJ's Wholesale Club
should like WebHouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great deal for our customers,'' said Debbie
Principi, Stop &AMP; Shop's technology support project manager.
</P>
<P>
   Stop &AMP; Shop, a 202-store chain based in Quincy, Mass., is one of
several supermarket chains to team up with WebHouse in the New York
market. A ``positive'' initial response from customers persuaded
Stop &AMP; Shop to offer the WebHouse service to customers in
Connecticut, Western Massachusetts, and Greater Boston, she said.
WebHouse is also available in Baltimore, Detroit, Philadelphia, and
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how WebHouse is supposed to work in this market: At the
Priceline.com Web site or a Stop &AMP; Shop store, consumers can sign
up for a WebHouse membership card that's linked to a Visa or
Mastercard credit card or debit card. Consumers get a free 90-day
trial period. After that, there can be a $3 monthly fee for using
the service.
</P>
<P>
   Once they have been issued a WebHouse card, consumers are ready
to shop online in the grocery section of Priceline.com's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose a customer wants to buy a box of raisin bran. On one
page of the Web site Wednesday, three brands were displayed _
Kellogg's, Post, and Total.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, a box of this cereal would sell for about $2.99,
WebHouse claims. Consumers are then offered four possible price
choices. They can bid to pay $2.66, $2.48, $2.33, or $2.18 for the
cereal. Or they can offer a different price.
</P>
<P>
   The lower the bid, the less likely it will be accepted. But if a
consumer opts to pay $2.66 for a $2.99 box of cereal, there is an
85 percent chance the offer will be accepted, WebHouse said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Internet is functioning smoothly, consumers should learn
within 60 seconds whether their offer has been accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Now here's something consumers need to know: The very instant a
shopper's offer on a product is accepted, the price is
automatically billed to his credit or debit card.
</P>
<P>
   There's something else consumers need to know. If their price
offer is accepted, WebHouse dictates which of the three brands of
raisin bran they have to buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be brand flexible,'' Walker says.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose a local consumer goes to the Priceline Web site with a
grocery list of 20 items, and 15 price offers are accepted. The
consumer then gets a printout of accepted items for his or her next
trip to a Stop &AMP; Shop.
</P>
<P>
   At the store, consumers pick up the items on their lists.
However, if they decide to buy additional products, they must keep
them separate from WebHouse items in their shopping carts.
</P>
<P>
   At the cash register, consumers swipe their WebHouse cards
through a scanner much as they would an ATM card. Items not on
their WebHouse list have to be paid for separately.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent hoarding, there are limits on the quantity of items a
consumer can buy at one time.
</P>
<P>
   WebHouse claims to list on its Web site about 800 brands of
packaged goods found at supermarkets. There's also a limited
selection of perishable items, meat, and fish.
</P>
<P>
   Because WebHouse reimburses supermarkets for the difference
between the price paid by consumers and the item's shelf price,
Webhouse is a good deal for participating supermarket chains.
</P>
<P>
   With discounts, WebHouse can lure more customers into the
supermarkets, and supermarkets can better compete with a BJ's and
other discount warehouse clubs, analyst Wells said. WebHouse is a
``win-win'' for both supermarkets and consumers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, WebHouse members can pick up groceries at several
supermarket chains. It's possible that WebHouse will soon have
agreements with additional supermarket chains in the Greater Boston
market.
</P>
<P>
   How does WebHouse make money on its grocery business? In a
couple of ways. One is by taking a slice of the $5 billion a year
that consumer-products companies spend on coupon redemptions and
free samples.
</P>
<P>
   For confidentiality reasons, WebHouse won't reveal which
consumer-product companies are its clients. But suppose a cereal
company is looking to grow its market share. One way it can do that
is by paying WebHouse a fee to ensure that its raisin bran finds
its way into the shopping carts of WebHouse customers.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that fee from the consumer-products company goes toward
reimbursing the supermarkets at which WebHouse customers pick up
their discounted groceries. And part of that fee goes into
WebHouse's pocket.
</P>
<P>
   WebHouse also runs promotions on its Web site. For giving a
magazine a free trial or for signing up for a Discover card,
WebHouse members can qualify for ``tokens'' that can be redeemed
for even bigger discounts on grocery items.
</P>
<P>
   For this form of advertising, the magazine publisher and the
credit card company would pay WebHouse a fee.
</P>
<P>
   Walker stressed WebHouse and Priceline are not auctions. An
auction, he said, is a competition between two or more bidders.
</P>
<P>
   ``At WebHouse, you're making an offer on price,'' he said. ``But
you're not competing against someone else. With this system,
everyone can win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
