<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8677 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-COMPUTERS-XCOMMUNITY-     03-16 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-XCOMMUNITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUTURISTIC X-COMMUNITY TAKES ITS PLACE IN THE PRESENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SIMSON L. GARFINKLE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five years ago, my wife and I wrote a novel about an Internet
start-up that created a multimedia groupware system for UNIX-based
computers. The company was called Deus Ex Machina Software. The
product, called ExCommunicate, was designed to let people in
different offices work together on large projects. They could
simultaneously edit different parts of the same document, insert
spreadsheets and multimedia presentations, create task lists, leave
messages for each other, and even teleconference.
</P>
<P>
   You can imagine my surprise when X-Collaboration Software Corp.,
a Boston Internet startup, began advertising its software on public
radio last fall. Intrigued, I contacted the firm and learned that
the company's new X-Community service, announced on Monday, was
astonishingly close to the ExCommunicate software that my wife and
I had envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   The X-Community system is designed to let many people work on
the same project at the same time. You can create a 500-page report
and let different people edit different sections at the same time.
You can work on the document from anywhere in the world that has an
Internet connection _ your documents are stored on the X-Community
server.
</P>
<P>
   Information on the X-Community system is divided into different
``Workspaces,'' each of which contains multiple ``Whiteboards.'' On
each Whiteboard you can store as many ``Note cards'' as you wish. A
Note card can be a Microsoft Word document, a PowerPoint
presentation, a spreadsheet, images, sound clips, or just about
anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other collaborative work systems that I've seen,
X-Community understands Word's file format, allowing the system to
take a document with headings and subheadings and display the
document's outline on a Web page. People on your team even can
check out paragraphs for editing while the rest of the document
remains available on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   A particularly innovative feature of X-Community is that you can
copy the structure of a Workspace without copying the data that it
contains. Kevin Lo, X-Collaboration's founder, calls this
``knowledge management.'' For example, he says, a consulting firm
could develop a 68-step procedure for doing an audit of an Internet
business. That audit could include questionnaires, spreadsheets,
and even photographs that had to be taken on-site. The consulting
firm then could clone the structure of the audit Whiteboard and end
up with a blank template for conducting more audits in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Much of what X-Community does falls under the category of
document management. Although law firms and consulting companies
have used document management systems for years, the vast majority
of these systems are based on local area computer networks. Even
the fictional software that I created back in 1995 ran on a LAN.
</P>
<P>
   X-Collaborate, on the other hand, is Web based. The service is
delivered through a combination of software running on the
X-Community Web site and a browser plug-in that runs on your
Windows PC. It's this plug-in that takes care of the
behind-the-scenes magic of automatically downloading the files to
your local computer when you need them, then saving the files back
to X-Community when you are done. Naturally, you can control who
within your organization has what kind of access to which files
stored on the server.
</P>
<P>
   Designed for hectic work environments, X-Community lets you
track multiple versions of documents, access backup files, and
annotate documents with comments. You can assign tasks to
particular individuals and monitor when they are completed. And you
can take a snapshot of the project as it exists on a particular day
and archive it for future reference.
</P>
<P>
   There are advantages and disadvantages to a Web-based document
management system. The big advantage is that it frees X-Community's
corporate customers from the hassles of running their own software,
keeping that software up to date, and backing up the user's data.
Even taking into account the cost of the X-Community, Web-based
services can be dramatically cheaper for most businesses than
running the same services for themselves in-house.
</P>
<P>
   The disadvantage arises from the corresponding lack of control
that comes when you hand over control of your company's documents
to an outside provider. If the Internet is down, then a company
that depends upon X-Community will find itself unable to work. And
storing your documents off-site increases the chances that they
might leak into a competitor's hands.
</P>
<P>
   The folks at X-Collaboration Software seem to understand these
sorts of data custodian issues. Unlike many Internet startups its
size, the company has an individual in charge of enforcing both the
company's security and privacy policies. The system uses high-grade
encryption for sending documents over the Internet, as well as for
storing them on the company's servers. And X-Collaboration has
taken measures so that only a few people inside the company have
access to customer data.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there are problems with X-Collaboration. For starters, even
though it is Web-based, it really only works for people who use
Windows-based PCs. If you have a Mac or a Linux computer you can
browse a Workspace or Whiteboard, but you can't actually edit the
documents themselves. A second problem is that right now,
X-Community's search feature only looks at the titles and search
tags of a document.
</P>
<P>
   Pricing for X-Community is very reasonable: a 10-user license
that includes 100 megabytes of storage is $100 per month. There is
also a free version of the service that allows individuals to store
up to 25 megabytes of information on X-Community's servers, as well
as access Workspaces belonging to other customers.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, I like X-Community. It's not as cool as my fictional
ExCommunicate program, but on the other hand, it's real and
available today. You can find out more at www.x-community.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Simson Garfinkel can be reached at http://chat.simson.net/)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
