<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8681 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HOME-KITCHENS-2TAKES-     03-16 1395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-KITCHENS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 WRIGHT, GROPIUS DESIGNED EFFICIENT KITCHENS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The kitchen in the house that Walter Gropius designed for
himself and his family in Lincoln, Mass. in 1937 was a statement of
the Bauhaus style, transported to and translated for New England,
after the great architect fled Nazi Germany and arrived to teach at
Harvard. Ultramodern though the house was, there was still a maid's
room attached to the kitchen, and a pantry that was the maid's
staging area, blocked off from the dining room by a sliding gray
plastic shower curtain.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen in the house that Frank Lloyd Wright designed for
Isadore and Lucille Zimmerman in Manchester, N.H. in 1950 made no
accommodation for servants. During the war, maids had morphed into
Rosie the Riveter, and after, there was no going back to mopping up
other people's messes. The Zimmermans were privacy-oriented people
anyway, who didn't want hired help even for parties. But what their
kitchen did boast was a huge _ for its day _ freezer chest, where
they stashed party food they cooked ahead of time.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen of today is a place where bigger is better, where
it's desirable to have a granite island the size of a small
country, maybe a walk-in fireplace with a spit for roasting
venison, possibly an art collection and SurroundSound, an antique
table and collection of deliberately mismatched chairs, and
gadgetry that spends your time rather than saving it: machines for
making bread, ice cream, cappuccino. A Biedermeier sofa in your
kitchen might get you a write-up in a shelter magazine. The kitchen
of 2000 has become a place to linger.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchens in the Gropius and Zimmerman houses were designed
to get out of. They were small and corridor-shaped, to save steps.
Time-saving appliances were the watchword in both, efficiency the
goal. Both Gropius and Wright would have enjoyed the recent Rhode
Island School of Design project ``The Universal Kitchen,'' which
set out to create a kitchen that's a kit of parts that can be
assembled to accommodate people of all ages and abilities, and
minimize movement. In the average American kitchen, RISD designers
found, it takes more than 400 steps to turn out a simple spaghetti
dinner. They developed a floor plan that requires fewer than 100.
Gropius and Wright would have loved that.
</P>
<P>
   There were also striking differences in the kitchen designs of
these two 20th-century titans _ more in style than in philosophy,
though. Gropius's palette was black, white, and silver; Wright's,
terra cotta and natural wood tones. So the Gropius and Zimmerman
kitchens look quite different: the former, sleek and lab-like; the
latter, earthy. But both architects wanted to blend indoors and
out, with as much natural light as possible in the kitchen and
accommodation for dining outside whenever the New England climate
permitted.
</P>
<P>
   And both were on a strict budget. The architects may have been
grand personas, but these particular houses were hardly grandiose:
The Zimmermans' is 1,700 square feet; the Gropius house, 2,300.
Gropius's daughter, Ati Gropius Johansen, still refers to the home
her father built on a $20,000 budget as ``an econobox.'' The
Zimmermans' house, which was supposed to cost $35,000, ended up at
close to $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Neither was a starter home; both were built for couples in
middle age who knew what they wanted. It's testament to the
practicality of these houses _ and their meticulously thought-out
kitchens _ that the Gropiuses and Zimmermans lived in their
respective residences for more than 30 years, literally until their
death.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for architecture lovers, both houses are now in the
care of public institutions that offer regular tours: The
Zimmermans bequeathed their house to the Currier Gallery of Art in
Manchester; Gropius's widow, Ise, donated the family house to the
Society for the Preservation of New England Antiquities. The
Zimmerman house has been open since 1990; the Gropius house, since
1985. But only recently has the Gropius kitchen become part of the
tour, making a comparison possible.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ``sugar cube on the hill'' is the derogatory nickname
neighbors gave the house Gropius built for himself, Ise, and Ati.
The Gropius house rises assertively from its regal, isolated knoll
in Lincoln, a plot granted by philanthropist Helen Storrow. She
gave several architects the use of adjacent parcels of land,
including Marcel Breuer, another key Bauhaus figure, who designed
some of the furniture in the Gropius house. From Gropius's living
room windows, you can see Breuer's house down the hill.
</P>
<P>
   Gropius, says SPNEA director of interpretation and public
programs Peter Gittleman, ``wanted to come to grips with nature by
making the architecture a contrast with it,'' the opposite of
Wright's idea of blending houses into their surroundings. Gropius
used rectilinearity and a stark, monochromatic palette to set off
natural forms.
</P>
<P>
   The way the Gropiuses ate and entertained helped determine the
design of their kitchen and its relation to the rest of the house.
Gittleman says that Ati Gropius Johansen contends that her mother
invented nouvelle cuisine _ minimal portions of minimalist food.
``A typical dinner would be a good piece of fish, five beans, and a
couple of tomatoes,'' says Gittleman. ``Ati told me her mother
would have objected to The New York Times having a whole section
devoted to food. Excess food seemed Victorian to the Gropiuses. If
you were a guest, you might have a small second helping, but that
was it.''
</P>
<P>
   There weren't many dinner guests at any one time. The white
laminate dining table, set with black and white dishes, Japanese
ceramic soup spoons, and never a tablecloth, sat four to six
people, under a recessed pinpoint fixture that created a pool of
light on the table. The novel lighting created an exquisite play of
shadows and tended to unite the diners in conversation. ``The talk
was about serious subjects,'' says Gittleman, ``not about food.''
The chairs are tubular steel, covered in plain white cloth. The
sideboard seems to grow out of a curving glass brick wall that
filtered light from the foyer into the dining space. Made of black
Caffelite, a laminate the Gropiuses discovered in a New York oyster
bar, the sideboard is sleek and asymmetrical. From here, the
Gropiuses would serve the main course after the starter had been
cleared by the maid.
</P>
<P>
   The maid took the dirty dishes to the sink in the pantry, where
the dishwasher was installed. She could have put them in the
dishwasher _ but didn't. ``She never used it,'' says Gittleman.
``She thought it might explode.'' She also never used the garbage
disposal, another newfangled, suspect gadget that she felt might
blow up in her face. The positioning of the disposal will strike
modern viewers as weird. It's at the far end of the kitchen,
nowhere near the dishwasher or the sink where dirty dishes were
washed. ``That's because the disposal was for food preparation,''
says Gittleman. ``With such small portions, there weren't supposed
to be any leftovers to dispose of.''
</P>
<P>
   Both dishwasher and disposal were gifts from General Electric.
In return, GE was allowed to use the Gropius house in ads that
promoted the idea of modern people using modern machines, a
principle tenet of the Bauhaus but not one that had caught on
universally in America, as the reaction of the Gropius's American
maid attests. The Gropiuses developed brand loyalty: Both their
white range and refrigerator are also GE.
</P>
<P>
   Every labor-saving device then invented was represented in the
Gropius kitchen, including an early blender and electric mixer.
SPNEA has outfitted the kitchen, mostly with the original pots,
pans, and measuring spoons, to present it just as it was in the
late 1960s, when the architect last lived there. Accessibility was
key to the way he wanted the kitchen to function: Covering part of
one kitchen window, where you can't miss it, is a white pegboard on
which hang ladles, graters, strainers, and other utensils, so the
cook didn't have to fish through drawers for them.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1327EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8685 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HOME-KITCHENS-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     03-16 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-KITCHENS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... for them.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cook changed during the war. When the maid left, Ise Gropius
took over. ``This was meant as a one-person kitchen,'' Gittleman
says, ``and when Gropius was in here with her, he had to sit on a
stool to keep out of the way. Two people can't function at the same
time in here.''
</P>
<P>
   Both kitchen and pantry are studies in black and white. While
Gropius's contractors persuaded him to use cork floors in other
parts of the house, because cork hid dirt and was easy on the feet,
the architect insisted on black linoleum for the kitchen and pantry
floors _ even though the material showed every footprint.
Countertops, too, are black, while the cabinets are stock
laboratory models in white enamel, with striated Art Deco handles
jazzing them up. To assess the radicalness of this design, consider
that it was only in the 1930s that the continuous wall of kitchen
cabinets, as opposed to individual pieces of furniture, came into
general use.
</P>
<P>
   There's something of the science lab inside those cabinets, too:
glass petri dishes in several sizes, the small ones used as
ashtrays, the larger ones as salad dishes. ``Gropius loved
ordinary, modern, mass-produced things that were well designed,''
says Gittleman. It may come as a surprise, therefore, to see
bone-handled fish knives, shell-patterned sterling, and gold-rimmed
wine goblets in the same cabinets. ``They were family heirlooms
that he couldn't bear to leave behind in Germany,'' Gittleman
explains. ``But he never actually would have used them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Frank Lloyd Wright didn't call it a ``kitchen.'' It was a
``workspace.'' You didn't mess much with the dictates of the
autocratic architect, so ``workspace'' it was to Isadore and
Lucille Zimmerman, who moved into their Wright-designed New
Hampshire house in 1952, two years after they'd commissioned it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their dream,'' says Zimmerman House site administrator Hetty
Startup, ``was a house that was easy to take care of, where they
could stay until they died.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``workspace'' also served as laundry and utility room,
uniting all the house's backstage functions in one place, all right
around the corner from the hearth that Wright considered the heart
of the home.
</P>
<P>
   A Wright ``workspace'' of a half-century ago was a place to get
the job done as fast as possible. Lucille Zimmerman made her Jell-O
mold and tuna casserole and that was that. The Zimmermans consumed
said casserole not in the kitchen, where there wasn't room for a
table, but in the ``dining loggia,'' as Wright called it, around
the corner. The dining table Wright designed comes apart and has
various configurations, including a hexagonal one: Wright sent
Lucille Zimmerman patterns for coordinating hexagonal table linens
to sew. Cooking and cleaning up were made more efficient by the
corridor shape of the kitchen: 26 feet long but just 8 feet wide,
with no great distances to travel from one appliance to another.
</P>
<P>
   Practicality was the goal, especially in the modestly priced and
scaled ``Usonian'' houses like the Zimmermans', which Wright
started designing during the Depression. In these houses, kitchens
were often placed on the inside, away from exterior walls; natural
light came from clerestory windows and skylights. Wright also wrote
that it was desirable to ``make the kitchen tall so cooking odors
can rise.''
</P>
<P>
   The Zimmermans _ he was a doctor, she was his nurse _ were
living in a 13-room Colonial Revival house they disliked when,
after researching in their local public library, they got up the
nerve to write to Wright. To their surprise, he wrote back. The
commission was underway. (They kept Wright happy with regular
shipments of the New Hampshire maple syrup he liked.) The
Zimmermans were the very definition of deference _ perfect Wright
clients, in other words. ``In listing below some utilitarian items
for your consideration,'' Isadore Zimmerman wrote to the architect,
``we are keenly sensitive that (itals)nothing should be allowed to
interfere in any way with your architectural creation.''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Among their requests: stainless steel appliances to avoid the
glare of white; an extra sink for handwashing. (They compromised on
the white issue.) Eventually, they'd also get an electric mixer,
dishwasher, pressure cooker, electric griddle, waffle maker, and
toaster, all plugged into strips of electrical outlets along the
counters. Right above is a long shelf for pot lids: Wright believed
in having frequently used utensils in full view, to avoid
scrambling through cabinets. About the only decorative element in
the room is a collection of the Arts &AMP; Crafts pottery Wright
favored.
</P>
<P>
   The Formica counters simulate red linen, echoing the Cherokee
red of the floor and deflecting the fluorescent lighting under the
shelves. The Currier has kept the spirit of the Zimmermans' era by
stocking the shelves with containers of Sanka and Royal Pudding,
and a copy of ``The Joy of Cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   That red floor is practical, economical, and aesthetically
pleasing: easy-to-clean poured concrete in big squares that extend
from the kitchen right through the glass doors beyond, connecting
indoors and out.
</P>
<P>
   No doors separate the kitchen from the rest of the house;
indeed, wraparound wooden shelves unify the spaces. The cook was
not supposed to be cut off. ``Wright,'' says Startup, ``thought of
the woman of the house as an executive. The workspace would be
L-shaped. It was the fulcrum from which the American housewife
would manage her operations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
