<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8688 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-16 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER WINS ONE FOR THE SPAMMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A law to ban Internet spam just took a shotgun blast to the gut,
and even as I behold the grisly spectacle, I have to admire the
artistry of the lad working the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   Washington state officials thought they had found a way to
control the flow of unsolicited e-mail advertisements into their
citizens' computers. In 1998, the state outlawed the sending of
e-mail ads with deceptive headers, designed to trick recipients
into reading them. The law also barred a common spammers' trick:
concealing the source of their unwanted messages. Spammers use fake
return addresses to prevent complaints to their real Internet
providers. Most providers respond to such complaints by canceling
spammers' accounts.
</P>
<P>
   An Oregon spammer named Jason Heckel fell afoul of this law when
he sent get-rich-quick messages to citizens of Washington state.
The attorney general's office sued in King County Superior Court;
Heckel fought back.
</P>
<P>
   His attorney, Dale Crandall, argued that the Washington law
violated the US Constitution. No, not the First Amendment. That
argument might not have flown. Commercial speech has fewer First
Amendment protections, remember? That's why the government was
allowed to ban TV ads for cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Crandall sought his client's salvation in a less glamorous
portion of the Constitution known as the commerce clause. This
clause gives Congress the power to regulate interstate commerce.
Implicitly, it limits the rights of any state to regulate a
business located in some other state. And that's where Crandall
made his stand. By trying to regulate spam produced in Oregon, the
state of Washington was violating the commerce clause.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington attorney general's office argued that the clause
doesn't prevent all efforts to sue out-of-state firms, such as
mail-order scam artists who defraud citizens from a distance. Ah,
but the Internet is different, Crandall replied.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Bill Gates of Redmond, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Poor helpless Bill is getting carpet-bombed with spam messages,
sent from around the world. But sent where? Not to Bill Gates of
Redmond, Wash., but to billg(at)microsoft.com. And where is this
billg? Everywhere he wants to be _ checking his e-mail from 35,000
feet above the Atlantic, or between bouts of antitrust settlement
negotiations in Chicago. And sometimes even at his desk _ but only
sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that the spammer uses e-mail addresses harvested from
the Net in various sleazy but legal ways. He has no idea where his
victim resides or whether spam is legal in that state. It'd be
extremely difficult _ in many cases impossible _ to identify the
recipient's home address. So there's no practical way for a spammer
to comply with the law.
</P>
<P>
   Defraud somebody via snail mail, and you're using a physical
address. Attack by phone, and the area code reveals the relevant
legal jurisdiction. But when you spam, you hurl your messages into
the unknown _ and this very ignorance, says Crandall, is a valid
defense against a state antispamming law.
</P>
<P>
   It's a deliciously clever argument, and it worked _ at least
this time. An appeal is probable. Crandall admits that his argument
wouldn't go very far against a federal antispam law. He'd haul out
the good old First Amendment to fight such legislation, seasoned
with a sprinkling of the equal protection clause. Crandall says any
special requirements placed upon spam, such as an advertising
warning in the message header, should also be applied to radio and
TV ads. For instance, at the start of each commercial, an announcer
might be ordered to solemnly intone, ``This . . . is a
commercial!''
</P>
<P>
   This time, Crandall ignores his earlier insight _ the Internet
is different. Radio and TV ads are obvious. But spam ads can be
made to look like something else at first glance. So it's
reasonable to require that spam be identified as spam.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's no question that Crandall has artfully
demonstrated the problem with trying to regulate spam on a
state-by-state basis. Even sleaze merchants have rights, including
the right not to have to fret over 50 different state laws
governing spam.
</P>
<P>
   Even John Mozena, cofounder of the Coalition Against Unsolicited
Commercial E-mail, admits there's a certain logic in the court's
ruling. ``We've been saying for some time that there are potential
problems with state legislation,'' says Mozena, ``which is why we
support federal legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Me too, John. Now more than ever.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Hiawatha Bray is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached by
e-mail at bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
