<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HER APARTMENT DOOR WON'T CLEAR THE RUG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I moved into a new apartment on the second floor. My door is
tight and protected, but it is so long that when I open it inward,
it messes up a nice runner I put down inside. I removed the
weatherstripping from the bottom edge, but two screws remain, and
scrape on the runner, and I cannot pull them out with a power
driver. How can I make that door clear the runner?
</P>
<P>
   STEPHANIE BOLLER, West Newton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. First of all, try pulling out the screws with a hand diver;
you might be able to get more torque by hand. Squirt some WD-40
aorund the screw to see if you can loosen it that way. Another
method is to use a screw extractor, sold in hardware stores.
</P>
<P>
   Short of that, you may have to cut ther door And since this is
an apartment, you may have to get the landlord to do it, or have it
done, because it may require cutting the bottom of the door.
</P>
<P>
   But this might work without cutting the door: Install
rising-butt hinges, which raise the door slightly as you open it.
Buy them in the Constantine catalog (800-223-8087).
</P>
<P>
   If that doesn't work, have a small amount cut off the bottom of
the door so it will clear the runner; then install a movable
threshold, one that pops up when the door opens, and pops down,
snugly, when it closes. These are also sold in hardware and home
supply stores.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My condo is in a rebuilt factory. I had the bedroom
soundproofed, but in so doing the contractor reduced the size of
the room by 6 inches on all walls. That is a big loss of space,
which I can tolerate in the bedroom, but now I want to soundproof
my living room. How can I do it without taking so much space away?
</P>
<P>
   MIKE TWOMEY, Newburyport, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The contractor soundproofed the room correctly by adding an
extra wall, except it did, indeed, use up a lot of space. Building
an extra wall was to separate the new wall from the old, thus
stopping the passage of sound, which is vibration that travels
through the solid parts (studs, for example) of the wall.
</P>
<P>
   You can do virtually the same thing without using up more than 2
inches or so of floor space on each wall. First, remove the wall
finish (plaster, plasterboard, drywall, or paneling), exposing the
studs. Fill the space with unbacked fiberglass insulation.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the important part. Buy resilient acoustical channels,
which are strips of steel shaped like a square-edged ``S.'' Screw
one flange of the channel on the studs, horizontally, spaced 16
inches apart. Then screw on sound-absorbing board, and finally
plasterboard as the finish. This separates the new wall by less
than an inch from the studs, but it is enough to be effective.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A reader from Charlotte, N.C., e-mailed this tip:
</P>
<P>
   ``In your column in the Charlotte Observer, a reader posed the
question about cleaning the fiberglass/vinyl floor of a shower
stall. I have tried each of your suggestions (Spic and Span,
Softscrub, Gel-gloss) and none have worked for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I found a product that worked extremely well on our shower
stall floor. It's called Zap. I purchased it from the Solutions
catalog. It's made by Sirius Products Inc. in Woodland Hills, Calif
(800-987-6564). I love it when I find a product that really works,
and like to pass on the information to other consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a second application for our floor, but now it's back
to the original white. Hope you can use this tip.''
</P>
<P>
   The handyman can use all the tips he can get, and has put this
one in his file for future use. There are so many products out
there to do so many things that it gets very confusing, but adding
one more product won't hurt. Thanks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My 100-year-old house has shingles stained a dark brown. I
would like a lighter color. Should I paint or restain?
</P>
<P>
   NANCY MUELLER, Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Your best chance for lightening that dark brown stain is to
put another semitransparent stain on it, but don't change the color
too much. Make it a cocoa or maybe toast color. If the new stain
beads up and does not penetrate the wood, you cannot use it because
the old stain is still making the finish waterproof.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the old stain could bleed through paint or solid stain, so
I would avoid those two finishes. If you want to use a solid stain,
I suggest painting the old stain with an oil-based exterior primer
first.
</P>
<P>
   Before using any of these stains or paints on the house, try
them in a small area of the wall to see how they work, or don't
work. It always pays to experiment first.
</P>
<P>
   If the old stain is less than five years old, wait another year
or two for it to wear off and weather before trying the
semitransparent stain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail him
at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
