NYT-03-16-00 1331EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8690 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-16 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANDS THAT SHAPE THE MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Using your hands makes you smart. Isn't that amazing?
</P>
<P>
   At Waldorf schools, boys and girls learn to knit in first and
second grades and to crochet in third. Then they go on to
cross-stitch and embroider, to work with clay and wood, to garden,
to make felt for clothing, and to sew. Playing a musical
instrument, painting, and accurately drawing objects from nature
are also fundamental to a Waldorf education.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolf Steiner, founder of the Waldorf schools, believed that
the use of the hands was essential to the development of the
intellect, and as a result Waldorf first graders learn to knit
before they learn to write or use numbers. It doesn't surprise
Waldorf teachers, who have observed children's progress for many
years, that recent neurological research has confirmed Steiner's
belief that mobility and dexterity in the fine motor muscles,
especially in the hand, stimulate cellular development in the brain
and strengthen the physical foundation of thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Because Waldorf kids are strongly discouraged from watching TV
or using computers in the early grades, my granddaughter, who is 8,
turns to these manual activities in her leisure time with great
pride and enthusiasm. At Christmas, Jessie handmade all her
presents. We're now knitting squares for a baby quilt _ 10 down, 12
to go.
</P>
<P>
   I marvel at Jessie's absorption in the task. Her right needle
must enter a tightly wound loop of yarn on the left needle and pull
the yarn held on her left hand through it. To purl, the process is
slightly different, but equally demanding. ``Only a steady,
controlled hand can accomplish such a feat, so the power of
concentration is awakened _ indeed, there is no other activity
performed by 7- or 8-year-olds that can evoke such a degree of
attentiveness as knitting,'' says Eugene Schwartz in an essay
titled ``Handwork and Intellectual Development.''
</P>
<P>
   I can't help but agree. Jessie is completely wrapped up in her
work, counting stitches, maintaining the proper tension, following
the line of yarn as closely as she will later, we hope, follow a
line of thought. In knitting, there's no room for error,
carelessness, or inattention. The task must be carried out
precisely, demanding both self-discipline and self-control. There
is something wonderful about work that requires exactitude without
any human nagging, about responsibility that derives from the task
itself. Imagine _ a dropped stitch is its own punishment.
</P>
<P>
   After Jessie binds off the last row of a square, we admire its
perfection. Each block seems an impressive accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   Jessie thinks so too. She likes the idea that she is doing
something adult. She's proud to produce a finished product equal to
anything her grandmother can make. The quilt is aesthetically
pleasing, too, a combination of coral and turquoise to be bound by
a yarn that combines various shades of both colors. The material is
soft and pliable under Jessie's fingers; there is a sensual
pleasure to this work (or is it play?) that is rhythmic and
calming. In the overstimulating environment our children inhabit,
knitting is a pathway to self-soothing, to centeredness, to a more
peaceful engagement with a stress-filled world. Looking back, I see
that I couldn't have gotten through several college courses without
it.
</P>
<P>
   Steiner believed that education should not be the means for
filling children with theoretical knowledge, but ``that it should
become a way of life, involving the whole human being.'' My friend
Mary, who teaches handcrafts at the Cape Ann Waldorf school, sees
herself in a similar way, not as a teacher of specific skills, but
as someone entrusted with the nourishment of her students' souls.
She's not training artists, she's helping children balance their
heads and hearts and hands. ``Children need a feeling life and to
develop mastery over their will,'' she says. ``When children
recognize their ability to do things in the world, they learn that
they can accomplish something with their thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   My mother, with no such ambitions, taught me to knit. To keep me
busy when I was sick and home from school, she showed me how to
turn a ball of yarn into a semblance of a scarf. Knowing how to
knit convinced me I could crochet, quilt, embroider, and sew, all
of which have brought great pleasure into my life. One thing led to
another. Could knitting have also taught me that my words and my
political ideals could be safely put into practice in the world as
well?
</P>
<P>
   Which handcrafts do you know?
</P>
<P>
   Make sure you pass them on.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
