<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUEBEC-IRISH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TOUCH OF THE AULD SOD, IN QUEBEC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANNON, Quebec _ A Celtic cross, carved of granite and
inscribed in Gaelic, rises outside St. Joseph's Chapel. Embedded in
the floor of Shannon's Hotel de Ville, or municipal hall, is a
stone shamrock.
</P>
<P>
   In a swirl of flouncy skirts, schoolgirls rehearse the intricate
spins and steps of traditional Irish dances, their breathless
chatter flicking from English to French and back again. They've
been practicing all year, and their performance, as always, will be
the centerpiece of the town's exuberant St. Patrick's Day
festivities.
</P>
<P>
   Against all odds, this little community on the banks of Riviere
Jacques Cartier, deep in the separatist heartland of French Quebec,
has maintained a resolutely Irish identity over the course of 180
years _ a fact that only Shannonites seem to find unremarkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, We've simply remained what we've always been,'' said Eddy
Conway, 84, a retired farmer and logger. ``Good friends to the
French, sure, but Irish to the core.''
</P>
<P>
   Conway's voice is burred by the brogue carried to the new world
by his great-great-grandparents. It was in 1826 that they quit
Kilkenny to cross the North Atlantic and carve a homestead on the
wild banks of the Riviere Jacques Cartier, which Irish locals still
insist on calling the ``Jackarty.''
</P>
<P>
   The Irish exodus of the 19th century is associated mostly with
the great cities of the eastern United States, whose character was
irrevocably changed by these Gaelic newcomers fleeing cruel poverty
and English rule.
</P>
<P>
   But huge numbers of Irish also poured into the St. Lawrence
River ports of Quebec City and Montreal. Many then flocked to tiny
farm towns in the Quebec countryside. In the bustling crossroads
that would become Shannon, for example, an 1851 census showed that
every county of Ireland was represented by the hardworking new
inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passage to Quebec was cheaper than to Boston or New York, and
the French of Canada were Roman Catholics, like ourselves,'' said
Conway, puffing on his briar pipe. ``So the Irish by the tens of
thousands came to Quebec.''
</P>
<P>
   In Montreal, the Irish quite literally changed the urban
tapestry: The city's flag bears the Irish harp along with the
English rose, French fleur-de-lys, and Scottish thistle _ tribute
to the three peoples that most shaped the city. And for sheer size
and spirit, the St. Patrick's Day march through Montreal, a
tradition since 1824, is rivaled only by the parades of Boston and
New York.
</P>
<P>
   But Montreal is a notorious rock of anglophone culture in the
only Canadian province dominated by French. Elsewhere in Quebec,
the Irish were mostly absorbed into the French mainstream _ keeping
their surnames, but surrendering the English language and, to large
extent, Gaelic identities to become ``green French.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Assimilation is a fact,'' said Quebec demographer Jan Warnke.
``Quebec has all these O'Farrells and McCarthys who don't speak a
word of English.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so in Shannon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow, this has remained a true Irish enclave in the most
French region in North America,'' said Dan Griffin, who, upon
retiring from a civil service job in 1995 returned home to Shannon
to pursue his fascination with the history of les Irlandais du
Quebec _ the Quebec Irish.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an Irish feeling here that remains remarkably strong
and alive,'' said Griffin. ``They came here from counties
Kilkenney, Wexford and Carlow, and the first came in the 1820s,
before the great famine, which is unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Roughly a third of the community's 1,850 people are of more or
less pure Irish descent, claiming English as their first language
(although the majority also speak French, often fluently). The rest
of the population is either French-Quebecer _ mainly commuters from
Quebec City _ or spillovers from the sprawling military base at
neighboring Valcartier.
</P>
<P>
   That base, which expropriated more than 8,000 acres of land in a
bitterly-contested expansion during the Cold War, has been curse
and blessing for Shannon. Many dairy farmers _ Eddy Conway among
them _ were booted from their land in 1965 to make way for new
artillery ranges, barracks and drill grounds.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the base provided a sort of linguistic shelter
from the storm that swept over the province as the Quebec
separatist movement gathered force in the 1970s, with the
secessionist Parti Quebecois _ which still governs a province that
calls itself a nation _ enacting tough ``French primacy'' laws that
spelled doom for many smaller English-speaking towns.
</P>
<P>
   But the military, as a federal institution, offered schooling in
English (or French) from kindergarten through high school.
Moreover, it offered jobs and other opportunities, and enriched the
tax base of tiny Shannon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Canadian army invaded our land, and caused considerable
suffering,'' said Griffin. ``Paradoxically, the military occupation
also was a factor in the survival of anglophone Irish culture in
Shannon.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Shannon is remarkably free of the antipathy that
marks relations between English- and French-speakers elsewhere in
Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   ``Irish and French have always been good neighbors,'' mused
Conway, who served as mayor for 14 years and remains Shannon's
unofficial archivist, using a makeshift basement photo studio to
reproduce and preserve hundreds of old black-and-white photos of
townspeople, some dating to the 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Partly it's our shared religious faith,' he said. ``And,
historically, we shared a mistrust of the English.''
</P>
<P>
   French-Quebecers certainly seem to hold a special fondness for
the Irish in their midst. Of the three Quebecers to serve as
Canada's prime minister over the last few decades, only Brian
Mulroney _ a p'tit gars de Shannon, or ``little guy from Shannon,''
where his father was born _ remains beloved in his home province,
while Pierre Trudeau and incumbent Jean Chretien, both of
impeccable French heritage, are widely scorned as sellouts to
English Canada. Mulroney made headlines when he joined
then-President Ronald Reagen in singing ``When Irish Eyes are
Smiling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Irish love Brian, of course _ he's our pure tweed lad,''
Conway said. ``And the French respect as good Quebec stock who
happens to be Irish.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Shannon can maintain its Irish identity in the new
century is uncertain. This is a very small town, after all, and its
sons and daughters are increasingly drawn down the highways leading
to Montreal, Toronto, and beyond. Or else they marry French
Quebecers and raise their children in the language that dominates
surrounding villages and towns.
</P>
<P>
   ``For certain, we're more keenly aware of being Irish than we
were in times past,'' said Conway. ``And it's a hard truth that you
appreciate most what you are about to lose. So we'll wave our
Republic flags and raise our Guinness, but there's bit of sadness
and a lot of wondering what the future holds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
