<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMES MIRROR CEO'S LEGACY WON'T SOON BE FORGOTTEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To recall one man's sendoff to his critics in the media, we
won't have Mark Willes to kick around anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The Times Mirror CEO (and former publisher of the Los Angeles
Times) put a bull's-eye on his back in 1997 when the American
Journalism Review picked up on his professed interest in using a
``bazooka'' to ``blow . . . up'' the wall between advertising and
news operations. From then until this week's stunning Times
Mirror-Tribune Co. merger that put him out of a job, Willes
couldn't stay out of the headlines or away from controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to his colleagues _ men like Tribune Co. CEO John
Madigan, New York Times Co. chairman Arthur Sulzberger Jr., and
Washington Post Co. CEO Donald Graham (who was recently tickled in
the New Yorker for being too moderate) _ Willes was a rolling
cannon on the deck, the George Steinbrenner of media bosses. Like
Steinbrenner, he was an easy target, inspired a fierce debate about
the corrupting influence of money on his business, and will be
remembered for his outlandishness.
</P>
<P>
   In a business where bottom line pressure is steadily but quietly
grinding away at journalistic values, Willes's intemperate tongue
was his worst enemy. He boasted of plans to increase the Times's
circulation by a nonsensical 500,000 copies and stumbled with
ham-handed suggestions that the paper create a separate Latino
section and mutterings about quotas for quotes from minorities and
women.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say Willes's actions didn't speak on their own.
The former General Mills executive oversaw thousands of layoffs and
shuttered the highly regarded New York Newsday, helping earn the
``Captain Crunch'' and ``Cereal Killer'' nicknames that forever
dogged him. He created a blueprint for matching up business-side
executives with editorial sections. And he seemed willing to meet
every marketing problem with an editorial solution _ a new feature
section to snag women readers, a Latino desk to attract the growing
Hispanic population.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it all came back to haunt him. Late last year, when
word surfaced that the Times had shared ad revenues with the
Staples Center sports arena, the paper was rocked to its core.
Former publisher Otis Chandler emerged from the shadows to attack
the ``ill-advised steps that have been taken by the current
management.'' In a massive post-mortem, Times media writer David
Shaw blamed the fiasco on ``deadened sensibilities and diminished
standards.'' Willes was clearly the target.
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, Willes professed to be stunned by his critics.
In a 1998 speech to the American Society of Newspaper Editors, he
cited a bunch of high-profile detractors _ from former New York
Times executive editor Max Frankel to former Washington Post
executive editor Ben Bradlee _ and claimed their ``rush to
judgment'' left him ``flummoxed.''
</P>
<P>
   But he kept publicly propounding his vision and slowly seemed to
win converts. After the ASNE speech, one observer noted that ``he
doesn't have horns. That's what people learned here.''
</P>
<P>
   A proponent of ``civic journalism'' _ under Willes, the Times
launched a sweeping ``Reading by 9'' child literacy project _ he
earned the praise of Jan Schaffer, executive director of the Pew
Center for Civic Journalism. ``He talks the talk; he speaks like a
journalist,'' she once said.
</P>
<P>
   His basic mantra was always the same. Newspapers need emergency
triage. ``Yes, we are pushing the envelope,'' Willes told ASNE.
``And yes, we risk being remembered as the crash dummies of
American journalism.'' Asked why he was remaking the Times so
feverishly, Willes told The Boston Globe, ``We're just too slow.
You have to try a lot of things to find out what works.''
</P>
<P>
   There is evidence to suggest that Willes was not so out of step
with his colleagues. In a survey run in Editor &AMP; Publisher late
last year, 63 percent of editors and 85 percent of publishers
somewhat or strongly agreed with his call for increased cooperation
between business and news sides. So many papers have established
cross-departmental teams of editorial and business staffers to
brainstorm about the news product that former Dallas Morning News
president Jeremy Halbreich once declared that the ``news coming out
of Los Angeles . . . did not take us by surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   What Willes did do, with his penchant for loud and bold
pronouncements, was put the Times under a microscope. When the
Staples Center scandal unfolded _ forcing his inexperienced
publisher protege Kathryn Downing to offer up mea culpas _ it was
widely viewed as the chickens coming home to roost.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after the Staples episode, merger talks began in
earnest. News reports indicate that after the idea was first
broached with Willes last spring, this year's negotiations that led
to the deal circumvented him. The company's board may have soured
on Willes. Yet after the Staples story broke, The Wall Street
Journal ran a piece stating that ethical embarrassment
notwithstanding, Willes had kept the board happy by tripling the
stock price in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he exits, Willes was the classic product of his times,
an era when news values must compete with the desire for sated
shareholders. His legacy reflects that.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of cleaning up the balance sheet, ``everything in the
company has been working well,'' says newspaper analyst John
Morton. ``The only place where his tenure has not been marked with
great success is the Los Angeles Times itself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He streamlined the company, fattened it up, and made it ready
to sell,'' echoes Brill's Content chairman Steve Brill. But ``he
sure diminished the stature of the paper.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
