<HEADER>
A8699 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-WIRELESS-WORLD-HNS &LR;      03-16 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIRELESS-WORLD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BAD NEWS FOR TECHNOPHOBES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALAN T. SARACEVIC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For the Luddites of the world, there is good
news and bad.
</P>
<P>
   First the good stuff: You will not be wired in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Now the bad: Instead of being wired, you will be connected
seamlessly to a wireless world of networked chips, software and
sensors, plugging you in wherever you go.
</P>
<P>
   Resistance is futile. At least that is what a group of
technology specialists gathering in San Francisco said this week.
They say the world is fast approaching the point where networked,
interactive computers will outnumber people.
</P>
<P>
   ``At every level and in every conceivable environment, computing
will be fully integrated into our daily lives and public
infrastructure,'' said David Tennenhouse, vice president and
director of research at the Intel Corp., the Santa Clara-based
manufacturer of computer chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computation will become so ubiquitous that we would no longer
be conscious of its every application, instead drawing on it as
frequently and reflexively as when we reach for a light switch,''
said Tennenhouse, delivering the keynote address Wednesday at
Intel's Computing Continuum Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Assembled to hear Tennenhouse's forecast were more than 500
industry professionals, academics and government officials. Their
goal is to steer the future of computer research.
</P>
<P>
   And that does not mean desktop computing. Instead, embedded
microprocessors and their accompanying software will become
omnipresent, replacing the simple human-sitting-at-computer
relationship we have just now grown accustomed to.
</P>
<P>
   Tennenhouse projected the chip industry will produce 8 billion
microcomputers this year, more than 95 percent of which will be
embedded into buildings, machinery, cars and clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, said Tennenhouse, researchers remain focused on
networking desktop, business-related computers. They should shift
that focus to embedded chips for computing to reach its full
potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``The research community has no choice but to follow the numbers
of microcomputers shipped and invest a larger fraction of its
intellectual capital in this space,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``By doing this, we'll be moving from an environment in which
our sources of information are largely human-mediated to an
environment in which computers tap directly into a tremendous
volume of information concerning the world around us.''
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate how these new embedded computing devices will
work, a number of researchers were on hand to demonstrate new
applications for technology. Some of the examples displayed were:
</P>
<P>
   _ A computerized shoe, called ``expressive footwear,'' that uses
16 internal sensors to feed data on pressure and movement to a
central transceiver. Developed by academics at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, the supershoe is being tested by dance
experts at Cornell University among other places, although its
real-world applications are murky. To date, the shoe has been used
to generate music from the dancers' movements.
</P>
<P>
   _ A ``power-harvesting shoe,'' also developed by MIT
researchers, which charges a battery using the energy generated by
footsteps.
</P>
<P>
   _ A ``wireless digital input pen'' developed by Intel. It works
like a regular pen, putting ink on paper, but also records the
writer's words internally on an embedded chip. The user can then
download the words to a computer or use a wireless network to fax
the written message straight from the pen, via cell phone.
According to Wilfred Pinfeld, a microprocessing researcher at
Intel, the pen could be used to augment voice recognition software,
allowing the user to touch up words the computer's voice receiver
missed.
</P>
<P>
   _ A ``mobile augmented reality system,'' or MARS, being
developed by Columbia University in New York. Tobias Hoellerer, a
doctoral student at Columbia, came marching into a
question-and-answer session at the conference fully equipped with a
backpack, global positioning satellite antenna and a head-mounted
display screen. MARS is intended to be a situational information
machine, feeding users a stream of information on what they are
experiencing. The students working on MARS hope to get the whole
system down to the size of a Walkman, with the visual display
coming across a standard pair of eyeglasses.
</P>
<P>
   While Luddites and techies alike may recoil at this level of
computer interaction, Tennenhouse and his colleagues feel the
evolution of embedded, networked computers will actually reduce our
fear of computers, making the entire experience of technology
human-oriented, rather than machine-oriented.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to find that interactive computing will become
oppressive,'' said Tennenhouse, referring to the pervasive brand of
command-based computing popular today. ``We need to rework the
boundary between the physical world and the virtual world.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, we'll move from huan-centered computing to
human-supervised computing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Computer Continuum Conference is part of Intel's
``Technology for Education'' program. In 1997, Intel distributed
$90 million worth of computer equipment to 26 leading universities
to enable creative research on the use of computer technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
