<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-COVERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFLATING THE DIRIGIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL BEGGY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It all comes down to marketing. Book editors around the country
this week received a mailing from ReganBooks, the publicity-savvy
division of HarperCollins Publishers in New York, which would
indicate that a book really can be judged by its cover.
</P>
<P>
   The uncorrected proofs of ``Making Love to the Hindenburg,'' due
out June 1 by first-time author Gordon Churchwell, have been
circulating for weeks. Now, the publisher has made the unusual move
of dispatching a new cover for the memoir about Churchwell's wife's
first pregnancy _ with the far more neutral title of ``Expecting.''
</P>
<P>
   The new title ``just better characterizes what's in the book,''
maintains Maggie McMahon, HarperCollins spokeswoman. ``It says what
the book's about.'' She insists the publisher hadn't received any
complaints about the title and cover design, which was also
changed. One can only imagine a very pregnant and very offended
copy editor objecting to being likened to an ill-fated blimp. While
the title was toned down, the artwork and subtitle were torqued up
a bit. The art morphed from a life-like photograph (two models _
not the author and his wife) to an exaggerated, cartoonish
depiction of a pregnant woman. Plus, the subtitle of ``observations
from a father-to-be'' made way for more provocative verbiage: ``One
man's uncensored memoir of pregnancy.''
</P>
<P>
   Churchwell, who lives in New York, couldn't be reached for
comment, but McMahon said he had to have OK'd the change. ``Book
titles are changed all the time,'' she noted. Making them, one
might say, a lot like diapers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1342EST &QL; 
