<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TALKING-ATMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BANK PLANS TO ADD `TALKING' ATMS FOR THE BLIND 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Bank of America plans to install more than
2,500 ``talking'' automated teller machines in Florida and
California as the start of a nationwide effort to make the machines
accessible to the blind.
</P>
<P>
   The first 15 machines will be installed in major markets in
California by May 15. It will be three years before every ATM in
the two states is equipped for the blind.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of America, which operates the largest network of ATMs
with more than 14,000 machines, eventually plans to extend the
pilot program to the other 20 states where it offers retail banking
service.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a real breakthrough announcement because this is such
a big bank. I think the rest of the industry will realize this is
not some far-out radical idea,'' said Lainey Feingold, a lawyer
representing the California Council for the Blind.
</P>
<P>
   The talking ATMs will relay instructions to blind customers and
others with poor vision through a headset. The headsets will be
provided by the bank, although some people may want to use their
own.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America is not the first bank to agree to install ATMs
for the blind. Threatened by a lawsuit, Wells Fargo &AMP; Co. became
the first U.S. bank to make that agreement in June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Feingold said Citibank started installing some talking machines
in the fall and the Royal Bank of Canada started the process in
1997. The city of San Francisco set up a talking ATM operated by
the San Francisco Federal Credit Union in October.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Wells Fargo, Feingold said Bank of America's action was
not prompted by threat of legal action.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of an industry move,'' company spokeswoman Ann
DeFabio said. ``We're trying to meet customers' needs while
complying with requirements of making our services accessible.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the bank, 95 percent of existing ATMs will need
only to be upgraded to accommodate the technology. About 5 percent,
all older machines, will have to be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   DeFabio said the bank has been looking into making ATMs
accessible to the blind for the past few years and the headset
technology was necessary for privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want someone to be able to hear it, but you don't want
someone next to you to be able to hear it,'' she said, referring to
such information and account balances.
</P>
<P>
   While many ATMs are equipped with Braille signs and number pads,
they are next to useless because they do not explain what is
happening on the screen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
