<SLUG> BC-BOOK-FAMILY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDWED'S CINEMATIC, AMUSING `HOST FAMILY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
HOST FAMILY 
By Mameve Medwed 
Warner Books, 309 pp., $23.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For more than 20 years Daisy and Henry Lewis have been a host
family for international students attending Harvard. At a reception
featuring ``white wine and foods-from-many-nations,'' they're
praised as ``the rock of stability, the very model of a model
family,'' and honored with an award for their ``Generous
Hospitality and Caring Friendship.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lewises are clearly heading for a swift fall. Sure enough,
minutes after the award ceremony, Henry breaks the news to Daisy in
a seedy sushi bar. ``Our marriage. I think it's run its course,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Daisy, though she feels ``kicked in the gut,'' responds by
asking, ``Like a horse put out to pasture? A car that flunked its
one-hundred-thousand mile checkup and needs to be traded in?''
</P>
<P>
   Anxious and insecure, Daisy has a compulsive need to make jokes.
It's one of her charms as a character, but it's a bit of a
liability, too: There were times when I found myself wishing that
Daisy weren't quite so adorably neurotic. Meg Ryan could play her
in the film adaptation. Mameve Medwed's shamelessly charming second
novel has ``movie'' written all over it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Host Family'' is more ambitious than Medwed's first, ``Mail.''
It's funnier, too _ and, for better or worse, slicker. Medwed tells
the story in the present tense in the third person, but from
Daisy's viewpoint. With her flights of free association (``Like a
perverse variation of Proust's madeleine, the throw-up has released
a stream of memories . . .''), Daisy can be a little tiresome.
Seeing certain events through the eyes of one or two of the other
characters might have made for a more satisfying novel.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say ``Host Family'' isn't engaging. It's fun to
read, perhaps especially if you know Cambridge. Like ``Mail,'' it's
set in and around Harvard Square on the fringes of the university
community. Medwed knows the landscape: She's lived and worked in
Cambridge for years, and she has a certain milieu down cold. The
plot of ``Host Family'' progresses at the Rialto Bar, in Holyoke
Center, in Pennypacker Hall, in the Holden Green married students'
housing complex, at the Border Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   Daisy and Henry are recognizable types, Harvard graduates who
stayed on in Cambridge close to what a neighbor of mine used to
call, without a shred of irony, ``the center of the universe.'' The
Lewises live in a big Victorian house near Porter Square. They've
reared a trophy son, Sammy, a Harvard freshman. Daisy organized
food banks for years and now works as an ombudsman for a
supermarket chain. Henry is an expert on computer viruses.
</P>
<P>
   Daisy is described as a woman who has made a career of settling
for less. That's certainly true when it comes to her husband. Henry
calls himself ``Henri,'' sports a beret, and peppers his
conversation with French phrases. He's fascinated with all things
French, especially a red-haired exchange student named Giselle.
</P>
<P>
   Once dumped, Daisy doesn't waste any time. Within hours of
Henry's bombshell, Daisy has met Truman Wolff, an earnest
parasitologist whose work on the host-parasite relationship
provides an extended metaphor for ``Host Family.'' Soon Truman has
Daisy appreciating the beauty of bloodsuckers and the symmetry of
symbiosis. As it happens, Truman's wife has left him for a French
pastry chef, so he and Daisy bond over their mutual hatred of the
French.
</P>
<P>
   The French connection is one of a number of coincidences,
contrivances, misconceptions, and misunderstandings that keep
``Host Family'' perking along. Daisy's son and Truman's daughter
fall in and out of love. The Lewises' very first exchange student,
an irrepressible Indonesian, returns to Cambridge a changed man.
Daisy's glamorous, much-married best friend becomes involved in an
unlikely romance. Everyone is afflicted with lice, which leads to
nit-picking, literal and figurative. It's probably not giving away
too much to reveal that the novel's penultimate scene is a happy,
communal Thanksgiving feast that seems made for a major motion
picture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
