<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8706 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-MACDONALD-2TAK     03-16 1456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-MACDONALD-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 THE MAN WHO OPENED THE WINDOWS AND SCREAMED 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Intensity is the quality that immediately springs to mind when
one is around Michael Patrick MacDonald. There is, first of all,
the intensity of MacDonald himself. A husky Irish-American with
piercing blue eyes, the 34-year-old author-activist seems
perpetually distracted and permanently coiled, like a combat vet
reliving his last firefight.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tell me that whatever made me a survivor, they should
bottle it,'' says MacDonald, scowling. ``But that kind of talk just
pisses me off. I don't want anyone to bottle it. It was not fun to
live through. Making kids more resilient is not what being a kid
should be about.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, too, the intensity of MacDonald's book. ``All Souls: A
Family Story from Southie'' was published in September by Beacon
Press and excerpted in The Boston Globe. In its seventh printing,
the book is a bittersweet coming-of-age saga set in South Boston
during the 1970s and 1980s, chronicling a series of family
tragedies, including the deaths of four of MacDonald's siblings,
that occurred within a proud community besieged by social change
and bedeviled by violence and denial.
</P>
<P>
   Two of MacDonald's older brothers committed suicide. Another
brother, a promising boxer, was killed at age 24 during a bungled
armed robbery. A 19-year-old sister was abusing drugs when she flew
off a rooftop in Southie, leaving her severely brain-damaged. The
youngest of Helen MacDonald's seven living children (all raised
without a father around) graduates from college this year, despite
his arrest _ at age 13 _ in the shooting death of a friend. Those
who did not lose their lives bear other scars, the book attests,
some inflicted by neighborhood predators like ex-Southie crime boss
Whitey Bulger.
</P>
<P>
   Michael MacDonald, born ninth in the family pecking order,
eventually went into community activism, working on initiatives
like the Boston gun buyback program and cofounding the South Boston
Vigil Group and Southie Survivors. In 1998, he was featured in a
documentary film titled ``Strong At the Broken Places: Turning
Trauma Into Recovery,'' produced by Oscar-winning filmmakers
Margaret Lazarus and Renner Wunderlich. Last summer, MacDonald also
toured Northern Ireland as part of a peacekeeping mission. Over the
past few years, he has spoken in hundreds of venues on behalf of
organizations like Facing History and Ourselves. Like Holocaust
survivors, MacDonald has borne witness to the past in order to help
others confront it and move forward with their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael didn't come by this book in six months,'' says Sandy
King, an antiviolence crusader in Southie who's worked closely with
MacDonald. ``He's been writing it in his head his whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, MacDonald sweated over the book _ his first _ for
nearly two years. The results so far, including more than 40,000
copies in print, have surpassed even his sunniest expectations.
Reviewers are already comparing the memoir to such classics as
Claude Brown's ``Manchild in the Promised Land'' and Betty Smith's
``A Tree Grows in Brooklyn.'' Amazon.com lists 54 customer reviews,
all raves. Mail has poured in from around the country, from people
and places with no ostensible connection to Southie. The
activist-turned-storyteller is an author-with-a-capital-A now.
</P>
<P>
   Beacon Press editor Deanne Urmy says it's no surprise that ``All
Souls'' has struck such a universal chord.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael had a great personal story to tell, but that's not why
I bought the book,'' says Urmy, who rates it among the highlights
of her 20 years in publishing. ``The social-justice issues were
just burning for him. He was making connections I had literally
heard no one else make.``
</P>
<P>
   It is, finally, this intensity of reaction to MacDonald's book
that is most extraordinary. At one extreme are the Southie
residents _ by most accounts, no more than a handful _ who have
taken offense at what MacDonald wrote about them and their Old
Colony neighbors. Several scheduled readings were disrupted or
canceled last fall due to safety concerns. Urmy was visited by
three Southie families that ``wanted to vent,'' as she puts it,
although no explicit demands were made. MacDonald won't talk about
it on the record but says that while the situation has calmed down,
he still takes threats of violence seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen too much in my lifetime not to,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   At the other extreme are scores of readers, many high-school
aged or younger, who have given MacDonald the sort of feedback no
amount of hype can buy. Again and again, they write about not being
able to put the book down, about laughing and weeping on the same
page, about the courage it took for MacDonald to portray tragedy
without sentimentality.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the great achievements'' of the book, wrote one reader
from New York, ``is to let us know just how short of facts we are.
You explode stereotypes and replace them with real people.''
</P>
<P>
   A Georgia woman who lived through school desegregation in
Atlanta said the book made her want to volunteer in urban schools
again. A Dorchester native praised its unsparing look at the
culture of violence. ``I have spent a lifetime running from it, you
faced it down and made a difference,'' the woman wrote.
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald has heard from clergymen, cops, filmmakers, social
workers, therapists, single moms, and African-Americans who watched
Southie desegregate from the opposite side of the school bus
windows. One reader, a lawyer, urged MacDonald to file a
class-action suit against the FBI, modeled on smokers' suits
against Big Tobacco, for allowing Bulger to terrorize Southie
residents with impugnity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crime and violence you mention also helped me to realize
that I wasn't the only `white' Irish-American wondering why the
press and everyone else thought that the problems of inner-city
youth were reserved only for people of color,'' wrote another
reader, echoing a major theme of MacDonald's. ``Your book had a
profound and heartwarming impact on me. It helped me to reaffirm my
identity and to continue my struggle to help inner-city children
succeed . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald lugs around dozens of these letters in a battered
manila envelope. In some ways, they are the only home he has. Last
fall, again for safety reasons, he moved out of his apartment in
Southie. Since then, he's either been on the road or staying with
friends in the Boston area. He figures he has done about a hundred
readings since ``All Souls'' came out, appearing all over the
country in pubs and bookstores as well as in classrooms and college
campuses.
</P>
<P>
   What has happened over the past five months ``has been
overwhelming _ and not all good,'' says MacDonald, during an
interview in Dorchester last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier responding to the negative comments,'' he avers,
``than to go someplace like Downtown Crossing, where people
recognize me and want to tell me their life stories. It's great
they react that way, I mean, but it's almost too much to bear. An
80-year-old woman in Denver told me she was not the same person
after reading my book. Eighty years old. That was it for me. I was
in tears.''
</P>
<P>
   Jen McAuliffe, a 20-year-old Southie resident and cofounder of
Southie Survivors, says the reaction she's seen locally has been
overwhelmingly positive. ``People are kind of in awe about it,''
says McAuliffe. ``It's about our Southie but with different
examples.''
</P>
<P>
   King says MacDonald can be generous almost to a fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael drives me nuts sometimes,'' she says. ``We'd be on our
way to some appointment, and people would stop him in the street
and tell him some ungodly story for two hours. Because he feels a
lot of pain, especially for the young people in this community, he
has a hard time walking away.''
</P>
<P>
   While gratified by the reaction in Southie, MacDonald says that
part of what writing the book did was allow him to let go of
Southie in a way.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I left before _ '' in the late 1980s _ ``I hated the
place,'' he says. ``Now I don't. I only felt unsafe there because
of a few people. And not the gangsters, either. They have bigger
concerns than me, believe me.''
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald did change some names in the book, he admits, though
not names published in news accounts of Southie's woes. He decided
the name issue case by case. Still, he says, ``It's hard to change
any name when you're into this truth-and-reconciliation thing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1348EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8707 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-MACDONALD-2ND &LR;      03-16 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-MACDONALD-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... reconciliation thing.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``My grandfather once told me, `Forget you lived in the projects
and get on with your life,' '' he says. ``But I also came to
realize that my mother's personality was partly a rebellion against
that sort of hush-hush Irish attitude. It wasn't `mind your own
business' for her, it was `open the windows and scream.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Helen MacDonald, now 66, moved to Colorado 10 years ago, where
she lives with her daughter Kathleen, son Joseph, and Kathy's
12-year-old daughter. While in many ways the central character in
``All Souls,'' she has not read the book all the way through,
according to MacDonald.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother was standoffish at first, but she accepted it,'' he
says. ``She knows what's in the book, but she hasn't read it all.
And she still doesn't like to talk about the sex parts. On the
other hand, she wants to fly back East and take on anybody who says
a bad word about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some traumas will never heal, MacDonald suggests. His brother
John, 42, lives in Costa Rica. Years ago the two of them had a
bitter falling out over John's role in the shooting for which
13-year-old Stephen MacDonald was tried and convicted (the
conviction was later overturned). Though the brothers patched
things up, says MacDonald, they have not spoken for a couple of
years. John is also estranged from other family members, according
to MacDonald.
</P>
<P>
   Of all his siblings, says MacDonald, his sister Kathy, 38, is
the most tragic figure. Severely incapacitated since she plunged
from a rooftop in 1981, she spends most days in the recesses of her
own diminished memory, scrawling antibusing slogans from the 1970s
on scraps of paper as if stuck in some cruel Santayana-esque time
warp.
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald also says he's unbothered by criticism that his book
was somehow not judgmental enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people think my mother was a saint for the way she raised
her children, others think she's a horrible person,'' he avers.
``What I want is for readers to decide for themselves. I want them
to feel the power of denial. Mostly I wanted to get away from my
activist's voice and into my storyteller's voice, because that's
what I see myself as now. I would have been miserable writing a
book that asks, `Why, oh why did my brother Frankie get involved in
cocaine?' That's a different book. Not this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the present keeps weirdly harking back to the past
for MacDonald, who is thinking about moving to New York in the near
future and embarking on a second book: possibly another memoir,
almost certainly a continuation of his interest in young people,
social trauma, and the healing process.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say the least, it's been an interesting few months since
the book came out,'' he says with a laugh. ``Judge Garrity died.
Dapper O'Neil retired. Bodies got dug up out by the Southeast
Expressway. And that's just around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Stories like the Columbine High School or Flint, Mich.,
shootings come along, MacDonald continues, and the same finger
pointing follows that helped keep Southie down for decades. How
does a first-grader get a gun? outsiders ask. What kind of music
are those teenagers listening to? politicians want to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we should all be asking,'' says MacDonald, ``is, `where
was I when this happened?' When you see all the hand-wringing over
teenage culture, over listening to Marilyn Manson records, it's
clear that most people don't have a clue.''
</P>
<P>
   His blue eyes flash with intensity. ``Kids know the world is run
on lies,'' MacDonald hisses. ``That's the real problem. They're
going to act out because of it. I'm not into anger or resentment or
blame. I'm into telling the truth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
