<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DO YOU REALLY NEED TO USE PREMIUM GASOLINE? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For many of you, the recent news stories about gasoline brought
back ugly memories of the long lines of cars in the 1970s, when
drivers waited in those lines to pay exhorbitant amounts of money
for gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   And now, the stories warn, we are in the midst of another
explosion in gasoline prices. Some say prices may hit $1.85 or even
$2 per gallon by this summer, the peak travel season. Even now,
we're paying $1.65 and higher for premium gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Many of you buy premium gasoline because that is what your car
requires and, hey, it hasn't been that expensive anyway. Others
burn premium, even though their cars can handle regular, because
they think it improves their car's performance or gives better gas
mileage or helps keep the engine clean, or is better for the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   But now many are asking themselves if they should keep pumping
the high test into their cars, or if they should save money and use
a lower grade of fuel.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fair question _ oddly, AAA estimates that only 5 percent
of the cars sold in the United States require premium gasoline, yet
20 percent of the gasoline sold is premium _ and it's a question
that's all about octane.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people think octane somehow is directly related to
power obtained from the fuel you burn; that 92 octane, say, somehow
gives your car more power than 87. Octane, however, is not a
measure of power.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, octane measures how resistant a grade of fuel is to
combustion. And it might surprise you to know that the lower the
octane level, the more combustible the fuel. But doesn't combustion
equal power? Not by itself.
</P>
<P>
   And here's where octane comes in. Some engine basics: An engine
generates power when fuel and air are mixed in the cylinder,
compressed by the piston, and detonated by the spark plug.
</P>
<P>
   Compress the mixture tighter _ high-compression engines _ and
you get a more even, explosive burn. These are the engines that
require high-octane (harder to detonate) gasoline. Why?
</P>
<P>
   Because in the process of compression, it is possible for the
mixture to detonate by heat or friction before the spark plug
fires. This sends a screaming fireball upward in the cylinder. But
before that fireball consumes all the mixture, the spark plug
fires, and another screaming fireball goes in the other direction.
The piston, riding the engine's inertia, pushes up through the
downward explosion before beginning its descent.
</P>
<P>
   This is the phenomenon that causes loud pings and knocks. It can
burn a hole in a piston, wreak havoc with your engine. It is a very
bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   Lower-compression engines are set to fire their spark plugs
earlier in the compression process, so lower-octane fuel (easier to
detonate) is no problem for them.
</P>
<P>
   So, faced with rocketing gasoline costs, what do you do?
</P>
<P>
   John Paul, a spokesman for AAA in New England, has simple
advice: Read your owner's manual and follow it.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline comes in three grades, for the most part: regular, 87;
midgrade, 89; and premium, 92 or 93.
</P>
<P>
   Burn what the manual tells you to burn.
</P>
<P>
   If you put lower-grade fuel in a high-compression engine, you
are endangering the engine. And in summer, when ambient
temperatures are higher, the octane requirements of all engines are
a bit higher, so it is even more critical then.
</P>
<P>
   And not only will you endanger your engine, you will also
probably get worse performance and worse gasoline mileage.
</P>
<P>
   But what if you drive a car that can run on 87 or 89, but are
using 92 or 93 for better performance, to help keep your engine
clean, or because it is better for the environment?
</P>
<P>
   You might as well take that extra money and give it to the next
squeegee man who puts his face in your windshield and wipes it with
a dirty rag with one hand while he holds out the other.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission says that, as a rule, high octane
does not out-perform regular octane in helping to remove engine
deposits or keep your engine cleaner. All grades of gasoline must
contain engine-cleaning additives, so the additive you get at $1.85
per gallon is likely the same you'll get at $1.50.
</P>
<P>
   And if your concerns are environmental, consider that it takes
far more energy to produce high-octane gasoline at the refinery
than it does to produce regular.
</P>
<P>
   So here's the octane rule to live by: If your car does not knock
or ping on 87 or 89, that's what you should run. You're wasting
money running higher-octane gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   If your owner's manual says you need premium gasoline, use
premium gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   That settled, Paul, of AAA, has a couple of other tips for you:
</P>
<P>
   Make sure your tires are inflated properly. Millions of gallons
of gasoline are wasted every year in engines powering vehicles on
improperly inflated tires.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, hey,'' Paul says in a blast from the '70s, ``you could
always car pool. Two people in a car doubles the gas mileage.''
</P>
<P>
   About gasoline mileage figures
</P>
<P>
   I read in my newspaper's Ombudsman's report last Monday that a
reader was concerned I do not list EPA estimates for gasoline
mileage in my car review columns.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody asked me, but it reminded me of a great line from a Dan
Jenkins book, ``Baja Oklahoma,'' in which a woman wanders into a
bar and finds her husband seated in a chair with a young woman on
his lap. ``Who you gonna believe _ me or your own eyes?'' the
culprit responds.
</P>
<P>
   I don't use EPA estimates because I don't need to. They are
estimates, they are broad, they do not factor in real-life uses for
vehicles other than highway or city (and how many of us drive
exclusively in either situation?).
</P>
<P>
   Here's what I do: drive cars, which have been broken in before I
get them, between 800 and 1,000 miles each week. I haul kids to
soccer, garbage to the recycling center, myself in and out of
Boston on the interstate. I put them through snow, mud, water, on
country roads, fine highways.
</P>
<P>
   And when I am done, I figure what each vehicle got for gas
mileage and I include that figure in each of my reviews.
</P>
<P>
   No estimate. Just what my own eyes tell me.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Ford's e-mail address is
</P>
<P>
   ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
