<P>
   RENO-FUNDRAISING (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno,
responding to accusations she deliberately avoided appointing an
independent counsel to investigate possible White House campaign
fundraising violations, says she probably won't make public the
recommendations of her top advisers on case. One of those advisors,
Charles LaBella, who headed the Justice Department's campaign
fundraising task force, reportedly accused his superiors in a memo
of performing legal ``contortions'' to avoid an independent
investigation. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Here we go again: what do women
want, anyway? The gender gap that first appeared in the 1980
presidential election is still with us. A new USATODAY-CNN Gallup
poll shows that if the election were held today 15 percent more
women than men would vote for Vice President Gore, while 12 percent
more men than women would vote for Texas Gov. George W. Bush. How
can the candidates appeal to one sex without losing the other? Do
women and men think so differently after all? By MARIANNE MEANS .
</P>
