   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Bill Bradley and John McCain
offered voters a brief blast of fresh air. Unfortunately, their
campaigns are already being forgotten as we focus on the exploits
and insults of Al Gore and George W. Bush. By the November
election, the Bradley-McCain interlude may be as much an event of
the past as Barry Goldwater's quest for the presidency in 1964 or
Gene McCarthy's campaign in 1968. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
