   DNA-TESTING _ ATLANTA _ Georgia will become a national leader in
DNA testing now that legislation to create a state DNA database has
all but cleared the General Assembly. The program will be phased in
gradually, depending on funding. Supporters say it will reduce the
number of innocent people convicted of crimes and serve as a
powerful deterrent. Story looks at how the samples would be taken
and stored and prospects for the phase-in to all felons. we take a
look at how the GBI would put the data base to use. Exactly how
would samples we taken? Cost per sample? Storage costs? Other
state's experiences with DNA databases? Georgia apparently would
become one of the five leading states in the country in DNA
testing. Could the new database have an impact on Georgia's death
penalty situation (particularly after Illinois governor's
moratorium on executions)? Also will talk further with ACLU about
its reservations. (Mantius/Harvey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
WITH PHOTOS.
