<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8720 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ST-PATRICKS-DAY-CHICA     03-16 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ST-PATRICKS-DAY-CHICAGO-STYLE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 PULEEEEEASE, DON'T SWIM in the GREEN-TINTED RIVER!  
 &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.  By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   As I type these words on a late afternoon, I can see the Chicago
River just outside my office window in the gloam of a Monday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   To the east, the river is a sturdy shade of steel gray-blue _
but under the Michigan Avenue Bridge, that fine color gives way to
an artificial green.
</P>
<P>
   It's quite putrid. We're talking about a green usually found
only in Jo Anne Worley's closet, circa ``Laugh-In.'' Think lime
meets chartreuse and they both spill their drinks. If your daughter
came home from college with her hair this shade, you'd cut off her
tuition support.
</P>
<P>
   The city dyes the river every year as part of our ever-expanding
St. Patrick's Day festivities, which include thousands of beer
promotions at local taverns (``Win your own genuine Irish pub!'');
dozens of ``St. Patrick's Day Sales'' at all kinds of stores;
several skyscrapers (including the Hancock Building and Sears
Tower) bathing their crowns in green lights; two huge parades;
dozens of concerts, dances and parties.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yeah, and some people go to church.
</P>
<P>
   For the year 2000 we're actually getting a St. Patrick's Day
week. March 17 doesn't arrive until Friday, but Mayor Daley won't
allow weekday parades in the city unless it's a legal holiday _ so
we had the Chicago march last Saturday, followed the next day by
the South Side Irish Parade.
</P>
<P>
   This gives us plenty of time to nurse our hangovers and rest our
``Danny Boy'' vocal chords so we can return strong and rowdy for
the 17th. (Or to continue hibernating while growling about all the
overserved boobs who turn this March Madness into ``Amateur
Night.'')
</P>
<P>
   Not that there's typically any serious trouble related to
Chicago's version of Mardi Gras. In fact, considering the volume of
alcohol consumed and the sheer numbers of revelers at the various
parades and inside the bars, it's a miracle that St. Patrick's Day
isn't marred by rampant hooliganism. You're more likely to see two
big red-haired lugnuts singing and hugging than swinging and
slugging each other.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one disturbing trend that surfaces every year at
this time, and it's reason enough to keep me out of the pubs for
the most part. Something so insanely goofy that I cringe just
thinking about it.
</P>
<P>
   I'm talking about American guys doing Irish accents.
</P>
<P>
   We don't imitate Pope John Paul II on Casimir Pulaski Day and
unless we're John Rocker-heads we sure don't lampoon Martin Luther
King's dialect on the day named in his honor; we don't do Italian
or Mexican accents on the designated dates on which we honor those
great cultures.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish voice, though _ too many Chicago-area men can't resist
doing it. Even worse, some of them lapse into it while in the
presence of Irish natives.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen it happen, more than once. A guy who was born in
Little Company of Mary Hospital, attended St. Thomas More grade
school and went to Brother Rice or Mt. Carmel followed by a stint
at DePaul _ in other words, he's never lived anywhere but here _
will be talking in his normal ``Chi-caw-guh'' voice when he's
introduced to someone from Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   Six beers later, the Chicago guy is sounding like Brendan Behan
on a bender, calling the waitress ``lass'' and ordering ``another
four pints for me and the lads,'' even though everybody at the
table is drinking Bud Light. It's ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone thinks the Irish accent is easy to do, but it's not.
For proof of that, consider that many trained and famous American
thespians have butchered the voice, from Tom Cruise in ``Far and
Away'' to Richard Gere in ``The Jackal'' to Julia Roberts in
``Michael Collins'' to Brad Pitt in ``The Devil's Own'' to Danny
Noonan's girlfriend in ``Caddyshack.''(I still can't figure out why
she was an Irish girl.) They're all so cartoonishly overwrought
that you half-expect to hear them say, ``Always after me Lucky
Charms!'' and be done with it.
</P>
<P>
   If any of the aforementioned is ever given a lifetime
achievement award, don't expect to see their Irish schtick in the
highlight montage, unless someone is trying to get some easy
laughs.
</P>
<P>
   So if most pros can't wrap their voices around the Irish accent,
what chance to the amateurs have? Let it go, boys.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, it's almost always a male tendency. As we've noted here
before, women rarely do impersonations or accents in public because
they know how nutty it makes them sound, whereas men insist on
doing their ethnic voices and their celebrity impersonations
because they're, well, stupid men.
</P>
<P>
   Have all the fun you want with this extended faux-holiday, but
unless you're trying to be a buffoon, don't sport the ``Kiss Me,
I'm Irish'' button all day, don't say ``Top 'o the mornin' to ya!''
to anyone, don't order the green-tinted beer, don't wear the gag
Leprechaun-print tie to work _ and leave the Irish accent in the
shower.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard O'Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) is of Irish and German
descent, but he has long since retired his bad impersonations of
Darby O'Gill and Sgt. Schultz. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (In addition, Roeper is a columnist for the Chicago Sun-Times
and the author, most recently, of ``Urban Legends: The Truth Behind
All Those Deliciously Entertaining Myths That Are Absolutely,
Positively, 100% Not True!'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
