<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8732 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV19-C     03-16 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: THE CLOCKS TICK FOR MICROSOFT
 &HT;    Moving in (k) commentary and (f) financial categories for
release
 &HT;    Sunday, March 19.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two clocks tick away for Microsoft, the world's
most valued corporation.
</P>
<P>
   One clock hangs on an opulent oak-paneled wall in Chicago's
Lawyers Club. The club serves as a neutral meeting ground in the
ongoing battle between the software giant and government
trust-busters.
</P>
<P>
   The other clock hangs in the modest chambers of U.S. District
Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson on the second floor of the federal
courthouse in Washington. There, Jackson is busily drafting a
ruling that almost surely will find Microsoft guilty of flouting
the nation's antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's clock is a legal time bomb, set to go off within the
next few weeks. It can be defused only if the talks in Chicago,
prodded along by a senior federal judge, yield a negotiated
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Periodic rumors that a deal is in works cause Microsoft's stock
to bounce upward, a fair sign of how Wall Street would react should
the company succeed in lifting the antitrust monkey off its back.
</P>
<P>
   But a ruling from Jackson would force Microsoft to fend off a
raft of private civil suits, which could carry triple damages. The
plaintiffs would hold the high ground, armed with the presumption
that the wealthy defendant had broken the law.
</P>
<P>
   Later on, Jackson would still have to decide how to penalize
Microsoft for its bad behavior. Since most judges would prefer to
duck the chore of regulating a business _ the telephone company
breakup was an exception _ Jackson is most likely to opt for a
so-called structural solution.
</P>
<P>
   That would mean splitting Microsoft into two or more parts. One
perhaps would sell the Windows operating system, while another
marketed Microsoft programs that run on Windows, such as Word.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be just plain nuts,'' said T.J. Rodgers, the
founder of Cypress Semiconductor, a $6 billion Silicon Valley firm.
``That would mean,'' Rogers noted, ``trying to divide millions of
lines of computer code that have been written to work seamlessly
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers has never met Bill Gates, Microsoft's founder and the
world's richest entrepreneur. But he's happy to sell him, at 85
cents a pop, the tiny computer chips that act as the brains of each
intelligent Microsoft mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gates has stepped down as Microsoft's chief executive
officer, he takes an active interest in seeking to settle the case.
Gates talks often with the mediator, Richard Posner, the chief
judge of the U.S. 7th Circuit Court of Appeals, and he has gone to
Chicago at least twice for face-to-face exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time, shortly before the case was filed in 1998,
that the Justice Department would have gladly gone away if only
Gates would have agreed to publish his prices, drop his exclusive
contracts and let rival Netscape attach its browser to the
installed Windows package.
</P>
<P>
   But two years later, the price of any deal that the government
would buy has risen steeply. Microsoft would probably be better off
striking a bargain _ even a harsh one _ to skirt further protracted
litigation. But at this point it's by no means certain that it can
keep Jackson's clock from ticking off its fate.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
