<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8759 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TECH-FUTURE-$ADV19-CO     03-16 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-FUTURE-$ADV19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AMERICA MAY BE HEADING FOR A GREAT TECH DIVIDE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (k) commentary categories for
release Sunday, March 19.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Americans, always eager for a better life, picked
up and moved in two great waves in the last century. First,
millions left the farm for the city. Then, after World War II,
masses abandoned cities for the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as a new century begins, another great migration may be
under way: millions are heading for the nation's high-tech hotbeds.
These booming cities, such as San Jose, Seattle, Atlanta, Los
Angeles, Austin and others, are attracting both foreign immigrants
and young domestic migrants who want to go where new technologies
are generating jobs.
</P>
<P>
   These cities tend to be clustered in a handful of states,
including California, Texas, New York, Massachusetts, Washington
and Georgia. In those states, the populations are becoming more
ethnically diverse and entrepreneurial. The younger residents of
these fast-paced tech centers are having children, starting
businesses and leading the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the rest of the country, the population is getting
older. With more than 70 million baby boomers inching closer to
retirement, most states will see a surge in senior citizens
starting in 2011, when the youngest boomers hit 65. As more boomers
die off, the population of many states will decline.
</P>
<P>
   These demographic trends mean that the United States may be
starting to split into two nations. One country, Tech America, will
have 10 to 15 states, each characterized by its youth,
multi-cultural diversity and entrepreneurial zeal. The other
country, Traditional America, will be older, whiter and less
prosperous.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, the impact of that divergence is hard to predict.
Perhaps the residents of Traditional America will be satisfied
living in the shadow of Tech America. Maybe they will appreciate
the wealth being generated in the go-go states, wealth that will
fund Social Security and Medicare and hold down tax rates.
</P>
<P>
   But younger workers in Tech America may resent seeing so much of
their income going to the gray heads living elsewhere. Even today,
the Social Security tax is the single largest tax for most workers.
In the future, young tech workers may want to see more of their tax
dollars going toward education and road building. They may want
more open immigration laws and bigger free trade zones than
Traditional America would like.
</P>
<P>
   Political arguments over how to use scarce government resources
``used to be split between Democratic cities and Republican
suburbs,'' said William Frey, a demographer and senior fellow at
the Milken Institute, a research group here. In the 21st century,
``the divisions will be between the 'melting pot' and the
'heartland' states,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Frey was among those presenting data at the Milken Institute
2000 Global Conference here this month, which focused on economic
and demographic changes around the world.
</P>
<P>
   A theme that emerged was that while new technologies can lead to
higher standards of living for everyone, the relative gap between
tech-haves and tech-nots is widening, whether on a global level or
at home.
</P>
<P>
   Countries with high levels of education, sophisticated
telecommunications systems and abundant computers tend to be far
richer than those without such advantages. For example, North
America is one of the wealthiest places on Earth, and it's also the
most wired. In 1999, about 57 percent of Americans and Canadians
had access to the Internet, either at home, in school or at work.
Meanwhile, in Africa, the world's poorest continent, only about 1
percent of the population had Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, economists at the conference were cheery about
the financial prospects for tech-laden North Americans. But on the
African continent, ``optimism is hard to find,'' a Milken Institute
study concluded.
</P>
<P>
   While the digital divide is widening between nations, gaps also
exist within countries. Heavily wired cities such as Atlanta, San
Francisco, Austin, San Jose, Seattle, Washington D.C., Boston and
Dallas have booming economies and surging populations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology and immigration tend to complement each other,''
Frey said. When tech companies start growing quickly, they draw
both young domestic migrants seeking high-paying jobs and
low-skilled foreign workers. Most immigrants are not educated
enough to take tech jobs, but they flock to tech centers anyway, he
said, because boom towns ``need more people to do service work,
like nannies and gardeners.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every tech center draws foreigners, he noted. Cities such as
Ann Arbor, Mich., and Raleigh, N.C., have tech-led economies, but
lack large numbers of immigrants. But those cities draw other young
people, such as college students, who can fill service jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, though, cities with fast-growing technology
companies are attracting both young Americans and foreign workers.
For example, between 1990 and 1998, metro Atlanta drew 440,668 new
residents, as well as 68,515 immigrants, according to Milken
Institute data.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in parts of the Midwest and New England, populations
have been stagnant or even declining. In North Dakota between 1990
and 1998, the population fell slightly as young people moved away.
The percentage of the state's population over age 65 rose to 14.4,
compared with Georgia's 9.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   States with rapidly aging populations include Iowa, Kansas,
Maine, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, South Dakota and West Virginia.
Those states have few tech hot spots within their borders. But the
states with relatively young populations, such as Utah, Texas,
Georgia, New Mexico and California, have booming technology
centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The places attracting both immigrants and domestic migrants
are doing so because of their dynamic economies,'' Frey said.
``What that translates into is younger people with greater needs
for education and consumer markets.'' In other words, residents of
these states will need more schools for their families, more roads
for their shopping centers and more global connections.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Tech America will coalesce to create a powerful voting
bloc remains to be seen. But last week, a bipartisan group of 18
members of Congress gave a hint of what may be coming. The
lawmakers representing high-tech districts in California, Texas,
Virginia, Washington state and Georgia joined forces to push for a
sharp increase in visas for highly skilled foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
   While traditional labor groups oppose immigration to fill U.S.
jobs, the high-tech House members are sponsoring legislation to
boost to 200,000 the number of visas granted each year to
well-educated foreigners such as engineers and computer
programmers. That would be up from 107,500 currently allowed for
2001. Among the supporters were bedrock conservatives as well as
liberals, united in the belief that their tech-heavy states will
benefit from more immigration.
</P>
<P>
   As Rep. Lloyd Doggett, a Democrat from Austin, said, tech
companies need to attract ``the best and brightest, not only from
all over the country, but from all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Traditional Americans may eventually feel run over by
hard-charging Tech Americans could shape the political battles of
the early 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
