<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8778 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-DRJOY-COLUMN-ADV24-NY     03-16 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRJOY-COLUMN-ADV24-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV24 
 A GOOD STEPPARENT IS A FRIEND AND HOST, NOT A WARDEN OR JUDGE  
 FOR USE FRIDAY, MARCH 24, OR ANYTIME THEREAFTER
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by DRJOY-COLUMN clients. Nonsubscribers can
use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call (888)-269-8796. 
 By DR. JOY BROWNE 
 c.2000 Dr. Joy Browne. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. JOY: Please give me some guidance. I can't call your
radio show because my husband listens to you every day. I'm afraid
he would recognize my voice and circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   In your view, what role should a stepparent play in disciplining
a child? My husband and I have been married for four years _ the
second marriage for each of us. I have a daughter who was 9 when we
married and is now almost 13. My husband had been married for 17
years and had no children. I am 45, he is 49.
</P>
<P>
   My husband and I have totally different styles of parenting. He
thinks I am too lax, and I think he is often too petty. What is
happening is that I am starting to get very angry and resentful
when he criticizes my daughter _ she is a good girl, great student,
cute, etc. She is beginning to hate him because she thinks he runs
our home like a military state. I feel that way, too. He seems to
be putting her life under a microscope and is critical of me when I
don't ``call'' my child on what I deem ``unimportant'' issues.
</P>
<P>
   I am a teacher and pride myself on doing an excellent job with
my child prior to getting remarried. My daughter now tries to avoid
my husband and she spends a lot of time in her room. When we were
dating my husband gave me the impression that he really liked my
child and wanted to have a happy family unit. Now I feel as if he
really doesn't like children at all _ even my daughter _ and I'm
stuck in the middle. Is there a way to restore family harmony? _ M.
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: If your husband listens to my radio show, he knows that
I think the role of a stepparent is to be a good friend and good
host _ not a disciplinarian, warden or judge.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that your husband doesn't try and discipline your
daughter _ which is good. But he seems critical of her, which makes
you chagrined. I understand why you might feel upset by this.
However, he should be allowed to have an opinion as long as he
doesn't try to discipline her.
</P>
<P>
   You may recall from your own childhood that _ especially during
adolescence _ parents don't always agree on a child's behavior. And
adolescents avoiding their parents _ either biological or step _ is
not unusual.
</P>
<P>
   The situation sounds like much more of a marital _ rather than a
parenting _ issue. Maybe the two of you could find a marriage
counselor and sort out what's going on here. It's unclear whether
your husband feels competitive with your daughter for your time and
attention, or whether he is being completely critical of her. It's
important for both of you to know.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of his behavior before you were married, he probably
did like your daughter. Living with somebody on a day-to-day basis
is completely different from seeing them occasionally when everyone
is on their best behavior. Don't give up on this one but do seek
some marriage counseling.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR. DR. JOY: My husband and I have a dispute that comes up
every few months. When we ground our children, my husband also
believes that they should not participate in organized team
sporting events. I believe that since the children have committed
to be a part of a team they shouldn't be forced to let the team
down.
</P>
<P>
   I do concur that they should not participate in team snacks,
team parties, etc. However, I want my children to show up, fulfill
their commitment to the team, and then come straight home. What do
you think? We agreed in advance to abide by your response. _ C. and
M.
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: I would suggest that the person who grounds the child _
for whatever reason _ determines the perimeters. For example, if
you ground the child, they are allowed to go to sporting events. If
your husband grounds them, they cannot attend.
</P>
<P>
   We have this notion as parents that we must be monolithic and
agree across the board on all matters. That is not realistic. Our
job as parents does not require us to be in constant agreement, but
we must agree not to undermine each other's decisions.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if your husband grounds them and says they can't
go to a sporting event, you can't go and plead their cause. You
have to accept his ruling in this particular case. Conversely, if
you ground your children, but allow them to attend team sporting
events, he is not allowed to undermine your position.
</P>
<P>
   If you think about it, your parents, like mine, didn't always
agree on exactly what the punishment should be. As long as you
don't undermine each other, your kids will survive your differences
in parenting.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Questions may be sent to Dr. Joy Browne, c/o The New York Times
Syndication Sales Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168, or
to drjoy &LR; nytsyn.com. Questions of general interest will be answered
in this weekly column. Dr. Joy regrets that unpublished letters
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
