</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Washington) _ What is Democrats' strategy on
getting China trade bill through? By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-ELECT (Taipei) _ Exuberant elections are a sign of
Taiwan's recent transition from dictatorship to democracy, but an
unsparing and hilarious satire of the politicians that is airing
weekday nights on cable television here may be the ultimate proof.
By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-BOMB (London) _ In latest sign of republican efforts to
disrupt peace effort, three men are arrested after the discovery of
500 pounds of homemade explosives in a car near Belfast, the
Northern Ireland police said. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   IRS-CONSERVATIVES (Washington) _ A bipartisan congressional
study found no evidence that conservative groups were audited by
the IRS for their anti-Clinton views, but it did determine that the
Clinton administration tried in two instances to obtain
confidential taxpayer information. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   COLO-RAMSEY-MURDER (Denver) _ After 3 years of virtual
seclusion, the parents of a 6-year-old girl who was killed in
Boulder have emerged to make the case that they were not involved
in her death. Coincidentally, they have a book coming out.
Meanwhile, an investigator in Colorado Springs who worked for them
is promoting the idea that an intruder was guilty. By Michael
Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   SC-FLAG-MARCH (Atlanta) _ Mayor Joe Riley of Charleston, S.C.,
worried about the effect the dispute over the Confederate flag is
having all over South Carolina, plans a major march to Columbia,
the state capital, to demand the flag be brought down. By David
Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   VT-CIVIL-UNIONS () _ A final vote is expected in the Vermont
House on a bill that would give gays the benefits of marriage
through civil unions. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-LABOR (Undated) _ Al Gore won the Democratic nomination
with a lot of help from organized labor. But now faces the problem
of how to show his gratitude while trying to convince voters he is
not in labor's pocket. The China trade deal presents a special
problem. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN (Cambridge, Mass.) _ Patrick Buchanan journey's to
Harvard's Kennedy school to don the mantle of reformer and
jumpstart his spoiler's campaign for the presidency. By Francis X.
Clines.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes on the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GENE-ALTERED-FOOD (Sioux City, Iowa ) _ Despite the rancorous
debate over the safety of gene-altered crops, American farmers seem
to be preparing to plant such crops again this year because they
are easier and cheaper to produce, and because there is still a big
market for them in the United States. More important, the nation's
largest agricultural companies have formed a line of defense
against the opposition by promising farmers to buy genetically
altered crops. And major seed companies have fanned out across the
country this winter, in an effort to assure farmers that the big
grain companies will buy what they grow. A special report by David
Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   BMW-ROVER (Frankfurt, Germany) _ BMW, after six years and nearly
$10 billion in losses, is selling most of its Rover Cars unit, the
last major auto manufacturer in Britain, to a British venture
capital group. Looking at what comes next for BMW, which has been
seen as a ripe takeover target. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   BMW-ROVER-OUTLOOK (London) _ Looking at the plans the British
venture group, Alchemy Partners, has for Rover. The firm, headed by
Jon Moulton, will rename the company the MG Car Co. Can anyone make
Rover, with inefficient plants and stubborn unions, work? Also
looking at the political fallout. By Alan Cowell and Andrew Ross
Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ The economic column. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-GROCERY (Undated) _ Four firms have canceled plans to
invest $120 million in online grocer Peapod Inc. , citing the
resignation of Peapod's chief executive, Bill Malloy. Shares of
Peapod fall as much as 50 percent. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-RATES (Frankfurt, Germany) _ The European Central Bank
raises interest rates by a quarter point, the third rate increase
in less than five months, in a sign that policy makers are growing
concerned about a pickup in inflation in the 11 euro nations and
the decline in value of the single currency. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   NISSAN-APPOINT (Tokyo) _ Carlos Ghosn of Nissan will add the
title of president, the first time that a foreigner has assumed
such a role at a company considered an icon of Japan Inc. (Mazda,
which lacks the same cachet, has had foreign presidents.) By
Stephanie Strom.
</P>
