<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8814 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-STPATS-GREENBEER-COX     03-16 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STPATS-GREENBEER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's all Irish to me when it comes to beer
 &HT;    By Amy Kincheloe
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Erin Go Braugh _ Ireland Forever!
</P>
<P>
   St. Patrick's Day is here _ let the celebration begin. But what
is everybody celebrating on this day?
</P>
<P>
   According to Suzanne Barrett with the ``Ireland for Visitors''
guide at www.about.com, St. Patrick's Day in Ireland is a day to
honor Saint Patrick, the country's patron saint who purportedly
drove all the snakes out of Ireland, not the loud and rowdy
beerfest that it has come to be in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Irish version is primarily a religious and bank holiday,
celebrated by relaxing at home with family and friends after
Mass,'' Barrett said.
</P>
<P>
   But in America, St. Patrick's Day is often celebrated with
parades, festivals and, of course, drink.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes that drink is green beer _ a light, domestic beer
tinted green with food coloring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think green beer is strictly an American invention,''
laughed Kendall Garrison, consultant to the brewing industry and
instructor of a beer-tasting course at McLennan Community College.
``St. Patrick's Day is just a fun holiday _ the country is green,
so what could be more fun? On March 17, everyone's Irish.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``everyone's Irish'' attitude is what turns people out in
droves all over America to celebrate with a mug of tinted beer. The
idea of green beer seems to be in keeping with the tradition of
``wearin' o' the green,'' which, especially on St. Patrick's Day,
is considered to be both lucky and an act of paying respect to
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   And even though green brew will be served in several area bars
and taverns, there are a couple of places that can be counted on to
not serve the beer with a Dennis Rodman dye job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did it last year, but not this year,'' said Robert Donnell,
general manager of Cricket's Grill &AMP; Draft House in Waco. ``It's a
huge hassle, and food coloring stains the fingers. But we will have
deep green margaritas.''
</P>
<P>
   Scruffy Murphy's Irish Pub in Waco, which has traditionally put
on one of the biggest St. Patrick's Day celebrations in town and
expects well over 1,000 people throughout the day this year, won't
be serving green beer, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an American tradition, not an Irish one,'' said Don
Stevenson, manager at Scruffy Murphy's. ``We still have people ask
for it, but we don't do it. One of our owners is Irish, and he
hates the idea of green beer.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of green beer is somewhat of a joke to many Irish
people because it's not even close to the preferred beers of
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Garrison said there are three different well-known examples of
Irish beers offered in the United States: Murphy's Irish Stout, a
dark beer with a creamy head; Harp Lager, a light, golden
lager-style beer; and Guinness Stout, a dry Irish stout with a
roasted-coffee flavor.
</P>
<P>
   ``All Irish beers are available here in the U.S.,'' Garrison
said. ``Everybody drinks them in Ireland. It's customary to have
one after work with friends or during a lunch break with friends.''
</P>
<P>
   And Garrison said most of Ireland drinks Guinness.
</P>
<P>
   ``They treat Guinness as a national treasure,'' Garrison said.
``Ireland and Guinness go hand-in-hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, these dark, robust beers are not everyone's cup of
tea, but since a few bars and restaurants in town have them on tap,
there must be some public interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guinness is pretty popular (at Scruffy Murphy's),'' Stevenson
said. ``Sometimes (people drink it) just for the novelty, but some
people actually do enjoy the taste.''
</P>
<P>
   Garrison added, ``There are people who really do enjoy those
styles of beer and drink them at times other than St. Patrick's
Day. The guy who drinks green beer is not the guy who drinks
Guinness.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the idea of green beer or any other beer from Ireland
doesn't suit your spirit this St. Patrick's Day, there are always
other options.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have bottled beer, so I don't have any kegs to dye green,''
said Gina Johnson, owner of The Grape in Waco, which opened in
June. ``So, I'll probably dye some bottles of white wine green. I
know traditionally it's green beer, but what the heck, we'll have
green wine. It'll be fun. This is our first St. Patrick's Day, so
we'll see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   As Garrison reminds everyone, to each his own on St. Patrick's
Day, because this is the one day that everyone's Irish.
</P>
<P>
   ``(On St. Patrick's Day) I've got to have a Guinness and a shot
of Bushmills Irish whisky, and that's what turns me into an
Irishman,'' Garrison said. ``You enjoy this holiday with your
friends. I'm not sure if St. Patrick actually drove the snakes from
Ireland, or if it's just an excuse for a beer-drinking holiday.''
</P>
<P>
   Amy Kincheloe can be reached at akincheloe(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1528EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 15:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8816 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-EMPTY-TRUCKS-$ADV19-H     03-16 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMPTY-TRUCKS-$ADV19-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     EMPTY RIGS HELP TURN TRADE ROUTES INTO SLOW HAULS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, March 19)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALISON GREGOR  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROWNSVILLE, Texas _ A government study found that nearly half
of the tractor-trailer rigs crossing from Mexico into the United
States are empty, contributing to chronic traffic problems and
slowing the burgeoning flow of commerce across the border.
</P>
<P>
   But federal officials, wary of the drug trade and illegal
immigration, as well as vehicle safety, say they must inspect
commercial vehicles _ empty or not.
</P>
<P>
   In the report released last week, the General Accounting Office
said 1.7 million of the 3.6 million trucks that crossed the border
in 1998 were empty but still had to be cleared by U.S. Customs and
the Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lines of trucks _ many of which are empty _ waiting to enter
the United States can run up to several miles during peak periods
in the early to late afternoon'' at some border crossings, Benjamin
Nelson, the GAO director of international relations and trade, said
in the report. The GAO is the investigative branch of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The traffic also contributes to the air pollution, road wear and
public safety problems that plague border crossings, he said.
</P>
<P>
   James Giermanski, a Texas A&AMP;M International University professor
in Laredo, said there always will be an imbalance of trade
necessitating empty hauls. But the percentage of empty trailers
cited in the report _ 47 percent _ is high, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Reba, who oversees eight ports on the border for the U.S.
Customs Service, said agents have found drugs concealed in trucks.
``So even if it's empty we have to inspect it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, truck safety remains an issue despite efforts to improve
the flow of commerce under the 6-year-old North American Free Trade
Agreement that was signed by Canada, Mexico and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transportation department has to make sure the trucks are
safe, because we don't want to have an accident on the streets,''
Reba said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the GAO report, trucks handled 75 percent of the
$173 billion in trade between the United States and Mexico in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. policy restricts Mexican truckers to commercial zones no
further than 20 miles north of U.S border cities. Mexico, in turn,
has refused to allow U.S. trucks to travel to the interior of
Mexico. These policies have helped create a flourishing
``drayage,'' or short-haul, trucking industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some public and private officials have suggested that this
policy contributes to the high volume of empty trucks at the
border,'' the author of the GAO report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is because much of the cross-border traffic is handled by
Mexican local firms that shuttle containers between warehouses
within the commercial zones on both sides of the border.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the limited distance the truckers can go, officials
point to another reason why there are so many cargoless trucks
headed into the United States: American companies generally pay
more for shipping, giving drivers incentive to drop loads in Mexico
and return to the United States for more.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is economics, and a lot of it is they can't find a
shipment to take back'' into the United States, Reba said. ``For
the most part, the reason this (drayage) industry has developed is
trucks can't go to the interior of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   NAFTA was supposed to open the U.S. interior to Mexican truckers
four years ago. But U.S. authorities have raised questions about
the safety of Mexican trucks and their drivers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the U.S. Department of Transportation reported that 44
percent of Mexican trucks inspected at the border were put out of
service until they could comply with safety regulations. The
out-of-service rate for U.S. trucks was 26 percent, and the rate
for Canadian trucks was 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In January, a Mexico-bound pasadero, or short-haul trucker, was
blamed for an accident that caused a chemical spill in Brownsville
that killed millions of fish. After the driver fled into Mexico, it
was discovered that he was uninsured and the brakes on his rig did
not work.
</P>
<P>
   The International Brotherhood of Teamsters has lobbied heavily
to prevent Mexican truckers from making further inroads into the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico has not yet made the changes necessary in their
transportation infrastructure to ensure that their drivers are
trained and safe drivers or that their vehicles are maintained and
inspected,'' said Bret Caldwell, a spokesman for the Teamsters.
</P>
<P>
   Also, studies have found there are not enough inspection
stations and employees to prevent unsafe Mexican trucks from
entering the United States. The only alternative right now is to
keep Mexican truckers out of the U.S. interior, Caldwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell said that if the United States is opened up to Mexican
tractor-trailer rigs, ``we believe there would be a greater loss of
life on highways, and it would be highest in South Texas, where you
have the highest amount of truck traffic going across the border.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Mexican truckers generally have a good safety
record in the border areas, according to some officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been very fortunate,'' Brownsville City Commissioner
John Wood said. ``I don't think we should just let everything and
anything go through, but we do need to promote commerce as much as
we can in a good, safe manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Giermanski said he doesn't believe a legitimate reason exists to
keep the interior closed, thereby allowing the drayage industry to
flourish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ridiculous use of this form of motor carriage here is
really inefficient,'' he said. ``All it does is add costs to the
cargo. We don't do anything at the border except make it more
expensive. We don't add any value.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Giermanski contends that comparing the condition of Mexican
drayage trucks to U.S. and Canadian long-haul trucks is specious.
</P>
<P>
   Another U.S. Department of Transportation report, this one
released in November 1999, inspected a small sampling of Mexican
long-haul trucks that were found traveling illegally in this
country.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 66 trucks found traveling in states other than the four
border states _ Arizona, California, New Mexico and Texas _ 15
percent of the vehicles and 17 percent of the drivers were put out
of service.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were almost twice as safe as U.S. trucks,'' Giermanski
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said U.S. and Canadian drayage trucks and truckers have
out-of-service rates similar to those of Mexico, and attempts to
keep Mexican trucks out of the United States are politically
motivated to protect the jobs of U.S. truckers.
</P>
<P>
   But Caldwell said the out-of-service rates for Mexican trucks
were so low in the study because ``local authorities did not
believe they had the right to put Mexican trucks out of service.''
</P>
<P>
   The Motor Carrier Safety Act of 1999 is an attempt to change
that, he said. It raises the U.S. safety standards for trucks and
severely penalizes Mexican trucks found traveling in the U.S.
interior.
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell did say there is a certain amount of protectionism
involved in the Teamsters position on cross-border trucking.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Mexican workers are in government-controlled unions and
don't have the same union regulations in place to protect them as
U.S. workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mexican drivers are making $7 a day hauling $70,000 or
$80,000 worth of goods on our highways,'' he said. ``These Mexican
trucking companies are taking advantage of their workers at the
same time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1531EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8823 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CYBERCRIME-$ADV19-COX     03-16 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERCRIME-$ADV19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLICE VS. PRIVACY: A TUG OF WAR OVER INTERNET CRIME CURBS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, March 19.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the annals of cybercrime, the FBI's all-time
poster boy is a Russian-born math whiz named Vladimir Levin.
</P>
<P>
   Working from his kitchen table in St. Petersburg on a vintage
laptop computer, Levin (once known online as Vova) managed to
transfer more than $10 million from Citibank accounts in six other
countries. He now resides in a federal prison in Florida, serving a
three-year term.
</P>
<P>
   Levin committed his spectacular online heist in 1994, when the
Internet was still in its infancy. It still stands as the largest
recorded electronic crime in history, but that's because nobody
knows how much goes unrecorded and unpunished.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to develop the capacity to actively investigate and
work with our colleagues around the world to bring these people to
justice, and to do whatever we can to prevent cybercrime in the
first place,'' Attorney General Janet Reno told a House
appropriations subcommittee March 8.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Reno released a 28,000-word report on the problem
titled ``The Electronic Frontier: The Challenge of Unlawful Conduct
Involving the Use of the Internet.'' (It can be found on the Web at
www.usdoj.gov/criminal/cybercrime, along with a 21,000-word
appendix.)
</P>
<P>
   Reno's report noted that in most cases, existing laws cover
online crimes. But the Internet does pose fresh challenges, it
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These challenges,'' it said, ``include the inability to trace
criminals who hide their identities on line, difficulty in finding
criminals who might be located in other jurisdictions and the need
for trained personnel at all levels of law enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   The report received scant attention in the press. Behind the
scenes, however, it has ignited a spirited debate.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy pits members of the law enforcement and national
security worlds against champions of privacy and civil liberties.
Both sides criticize Reno, but for different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   One side argues that the attorney general should be pressing
Congress for more resources to combat cyber-criminals, who, they
say, pose a grave threat the continued rapid growth of the
so-called New Economy. The other side views the report as a direct
threat to online privacy by weakening constitutional guarantees of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony on Capitol Hill, much of it in closed session, shows
that what most vexes cops and counter-spies is what the report
describes as ``the lack of identification mechanisms on global
networks.''
</P>
<P>
   In essence, this means that architecture of the Internet allows
everyone, including would-be criminals, to remain anonymous or even
to take on masked identities by adopting false personas or by
providing inaccurate biographical information and misleading
digital names.
</P>
<P>
   Given the current state of technology, ``it can be difficult to
accurately identify an individual (especially sophisticated users
who take affirmative steps to hide their identity) on the
Internet,'' the report says.
</P>
<P>
   It calls this a ``thorny issue.'' But even the mere suggestion
that online privacy can get in the way of effective law enforcement
has civil libertarians up in arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the laws are going to be updated, they need to be updated
to guarantee more privacy rights to Americans, rather than less,''
said Barry Steinhardt, associate director of the American Civil
Liberties Union (ACLU).
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Nojeim, a legislative counsel with the group's national
office, said: ``Anonymity on the Internet is not a 'thorny issue;'
it is a constitutional right. Law enforcement and national security
agencies want to outlaw the digital equivalent of pen names.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before Reno released the massive report, the ACLU had
voiced its unhappiness in a 1,200-word open letter to the attorney
general. (The Justice Department had given several key public
interest lobbying groups, including the ACLU, an advance peek at
the contents.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The report contains virtually no statistics on the extent of
computer-related crime, or whether such activity poses a truly
significant threat to our nation,'' the ACLU letter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead, the report merely mentions several anecdotes on how a
few
</P>
<P>
   individuals have used the computers to commit crimes. Such
statistics should be disclosed before any statutory changes are
even considered.''
</P>
<P>
   But many independent Internet security experts believe the
threat, if anything, has been understated by top government
officials, including Reno and President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corporate image and reputation are at serious risk in the wake
of increased cyber-vandalism attacks against corporate America,''
argues Dan Woolley, president and chief operating officer of Global
Integrity Corp., an online data protection firm based in Reston,
Va.
</P>
<P>
   To better thwart online criminals, the report cites ``the need
for real-time tracing of Internet communications across traditional
jurisdictional boundaries, both domestically and internationally.''
</P>
<P>
   This seems to place the Justice Department behind the idea of a
national tracing authority, which civil libertarians doubt can
function within a constitutional framework.
</P>
<P>
   By and large, security experts see this as an idea whose time as
come.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's useful because you want to be able to streamline the
process, you want to be able to trace these transactions in a
matter of hours and days, and not weeks or months,'' Mark Rasch, a
former federal prosecutor who works for Global Integrity, recently
told National Public Radio.
</P>
<P>
   Added Rasch: ``What is electronic mail? What is voice over
Internet? Is it mail? Is it phone? We don't know. And so you just
present that as an issue and say, 'We need to develop a new legal
paradigm for the new technologies.'''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
