<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8828 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-FILM-ERIN-SPI &LR;      03-16 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ERIN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS `ERIN,' JULIA ROBERTS IS PRETTY TOUGH WOMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STUDIO HEAD: Okay, the door is closed, the phone is turned off
and I'm ready for your pitch.
</P>
<P>
   AGENT: You're just gonna love this one! It's the true story of a
sleazy lawyer or paralegal or something who gains self-respect by
single-handedly taking on a multi-billion dollar corporation that's
been polluting the ground water with toxic chemicals and callously
poisoning the people of a small town and ...
</P>
<P>
   SH: Hold it right there! I saw this movie last year. It was that
Travolta thing in New England ... ``A Civil something or other.''
</P>
<P>
   A: But this one takes place in California.
</P>
<P>
   SH: I don't care where it takes place. It's exactly the same
story.
</P>
<P>
   A: But ``A Civil Action'' grossed over a hundred mil.
</P>
<P>
   SH: Hmmmmm.
</P>
<P>
   A: And get this ... Julia Roberts is interested in playing the
...
</P>
<P>
   SH: The lawyer is a woman?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not exactly a lawyer. She's a kind of office worker in a
small legal firm _ no education at all _ who takes on this
impossible fight when none of the real lawyers can be bothered. Her
name's Erin Brockovich.
</P>
<P>
   SH: No education, huh? That's good _ people hate lawyers.
Unless, of course, they're John Travolta.
</P>
<P>
   A: She says exactly that in the movie _ ``I hate lawyers.'' The
lawyers all look like idiots.
</P>
<P>
   SH: A woman of the people.
</P>
<P>
   A: Exactly. And a trashy-sexy woman of the people. She dresses
the way Julia did in ``Pretty Woman.'' We'll have her model the
entire Frederick's of Hollywood catalog before the movie's done.
</P>
<P>
   SH: Hmmmm. Interesting. Still, I dunno. A sexy Julia is good but
not necessarily great box-office. Not the kind that'll guarantee a
return on Julia's $20 million up-front salary.
</P>
<P>
   A: But wait! Not only is she sexy, she's an earth mother. She's
got three kids _ including a baby _ that she drags through the
movie like she's Norma Rae.
</P>
<P>
   SH (moving to the edge of his seat): Trashy but a devoted
mother. Now I'm interested. Tell me about the rest of the package.
</P>
<P>
   A: And we got Albert Finney as her crusty boss. He's
conservative, she's gutter-mouthed. Think of the potential for
conflict. And I ask you: Is there anything cuter than Julia being
gutter-mouthed?
</P>
<P>
   SH: Albert ... who?
</P>
<P>
   A: British actor. Almost won the Oscar in 1963 for ``Tom
Jones.''
</P>
<P>
   SH: I wasn't even born in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   A: Forget Albert Finney. He'll bring in the boomers. We got
Aaron Eckhart as Erin's biker next-door neighbor and sometime lover
_ the handsome guy from ``In the Company of Men.'' And get this.
The biker takes care of her kids while Erin's on her crusade _ a
biker Mr. Mom. I mean, eat your heart out, Chris Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   SH: I'm liking this idea more and more. Still, that name. Erin
Brockowhatever. It's a mouthful. Can't we change it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Nah, I'm afraid we're stuck with it. It's the woman's real
name _ and we're claiming this is a true story.
</P>
<P>
   SH: So what? Look at ``The Hurricane.'' None of that stuff
really happened and they still called it a true story.
</P>
<P>
   A: But they kept the guy's name. We can change everything else,
but we have to keep the name. That's the unwritten rule of true
stories. Anyway, Julia likes the name.
</P>
<P>
   SH: I see your point.
</P>
<P>
   A: Julia even wants to use it as the title. Can't you see it?
Julia Roberts is ``Erin Brockovich.'' Gives you goose bumps,
doesn't it? Oozes integrity.
</P>
<P>
   SH: Who's the director?
</P>
<P>
   A: Steven Soderbergh is interested.
</P>
<P>
   SH (suddenly cautious): Soderbergh! ``The Limey'' ... ``Out of
Sight'' ... I dunno. Great reviews, terrible box-office.
</P>
<P>
   A: But Soderbergh's got edge. And Julia wants edge. She's tired
of being regarded as a cream puff.
</P>
<P>
   SH: Edge is good, but it only plays to college kids and critics,
not real people. I wouldn't want another ``Mary Reilly'' on my
hands.
</P>
<P>
   A: Forget ``Mary Reilly.'' Think of ``Notting Hill'' and
``Runaway Bride.'' The woman who wrote the script also co-wrote
``Pocahontas'' and ``Ever After,'' for crying out loud, so how edgy
can it be?
</P>
<P>
   SH (still cautious): Yeah, but ... people being poisoned. We're
talking kids with cancer here, right? I dunno. Is it uplifting?
Does it have a depressing ending?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not at all! This woman helps 600 and some-odd small-town
people go the distance. It's ``Rocky'' times 600. It's ``Mary
Poppins'' not ``Mary Reilly.''
</P>
<P>
   SH (still hesitant but weakening): But does Julia smile a lot?
Audiences just hate it when Julia frowns. Think of ``Dying Young.''
Think of ``Michael Collins.''
</P>
<P>
   A: I have to be honest with you. She does frown once or twice.
Okay, three times. But otherwise, she smiles all through the movie
_ that radiant billion-dollar smile just beams down on us like a
light from heaven.
</P>
<P>
   SH: Hmmmmm. Let me see if I have this straight. Julia's
gutter-mouthed cute-as-a-bug and she's a great mother and she
dresses like a hooker and she makes the lawyers look like fools and
she lights up the world with her smile.
</P>
<P>
   A: That's about it.
</P>
<P>
   SH: Then I think we got ourselves a movie.
</P>
<P>
   Erin Brockovich. Directed by Steven Soderbergh. Written by
Susannah Grant. Cast: Julia Roberts, Albert Finney, Aaron Eckhart.
Universal/Columbia. 126 minutes. Rated R for language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1545EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
