<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8830 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MANILOW-COX     03-16 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANILOW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Theater, CDs, huge TV ratings bolster crooner's career
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a time when the very mention of Barry Manilow's name
would prompt bursts of laughter from musical snobs. Think
Copacabana, Mandy, I Write the Songs and all his other hit records:
A cool set list, it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   But while Manilow's name is still synonymous with the schlock
pop of the '70s, the singer-songwriter has moved beyond those days.
His 30th album, Manilow Sings Sinatra, released in 1998, earned him
critical kudos and two Grammy nominations. A two-hour special for
A&AMP;E, Manilow: Live By Request, was the most-watched show in the
cable network's history. And he's got two Broadway shows in the
works.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be that Barry Manilow is finally ready to be taken
seriously?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the 53-year-old Manilow says that the career he has
today is what he always intended for himself: That pop-star phase
was just an aberration. ``It's a fulfillment of musical dreams of
mine,'' he explains by phone of his current artistic success,
speaking in advance of his performance at the MARS Music
Amphitheatre on Friday night. ``My roots really have not been in
pop music. I found myself making pop albums and it was a big
surprise to me that they were successful. My roots were always in
Broadway, jazz, cabaret and that kind of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, before Manilow, a New York native, found his way to the
top of the charts, he was working as a jingle writer and producer
for a still unknown Bette Midler. ``It was much more challenging
music for a musician than what was on the pop radio of the '60s,
except for The Beatles and Stones.... The bubble-gum stuff never
interested me at all,'' he explains. But by the '70s, Manilow was
singled out by record producers as a potential pop poster-child. On
the surface, he seemed an unlikely star _ he didn't have the
golden-boy looks or the reckless rocker's attitude. Instead, he
gave the impression of a musical geek who spent too much of his
time fiddling at the keyboard. Which, in fact, he was.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Manilow's musical explorations meant he knew how to write a
tune, always a valuable commodity. Even his first big hit, Mandy, a
song he didn't compose, benefited from his clever craftsmanship: In
its original version, it was an uptempo rocker; Manilow found the
tender ballad buried within. ``I seemed to have invented the power
ballad,'' he says with nostalgic fondness.
</P>
<P>
   But not all the memories of those days are kind. Manilow took
many a swipe from the critical community _ and while he admits some
of the remarks were perhaps deserved since he ``was learning on the
job,'' others were not. ``I would get up in the morning and I would
wince,'' he recalls of his reaction to the negative press. ``I
would go into self-pity, then I would get angry, then I would get
really furious and then I would go on stage.'' His fans, in other
words, became his salvation _ along with the honors he earned,
including Grammy, Emmy and Tony awards.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, Manilow says, ``the way you get through is by
just believing in what you do.'' He points to the example of the
much-maligned Copacabana, a song he considers among his best.
``It's a beautifully crafted song ... with a catchy melody you
can't get out of your head,'' he asserts.
</P>
<P>
   In that vein, Manilow is revisiting the song in the form of a
Broadway show, simply titled Barry Manilow's Copacabana: The
Musical, a collaboration with original lyricist Barry Sussman. It
already has played to sold-out houses during an 18-month London
run. Now, he is planning on touring it in this country starting in
June.
</P>
<P>
   And that's not Manilow's only Broadway project. Working with
Sussman again, he's also developed a more serious show, Harmony,
about the Comedian Harmonists, a famous German singing group
disbanded by the Nazis because some of its members were Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   While other pop artists have ventured into theatrical waters
with disastrous results _ remember Paul Simon's The Capeman? _
Manilow is confident about his chances. ``Paul came into it
thinking he could do it because he's such a brilliant songwriter,
but there's a craft to writing Broadway musicals that you must
have,'' Manilow says.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, however, Manilow is putting his Broadway
aspirations aside so he can concentrate on his career as a concert
artist (and, yes, he still sings his old hits).
charlespassy(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
