<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8831 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIE-CAPSULES17-COX     03-16 2396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-CAPSULES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE MOVIE GUIDE
 &HT;    Short reviews of selected films
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RATINGS
</P>
<P>
   A_Excellent
</P>
<P>
   B_Good
</P>
<P>
   C_Fair
</P>
<P>
   D_Poor
</P>
<P>
   F_Abysmal
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  _Not reviewed
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN BEAUTY
</P>
<P>
   (R) A
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Spacey is nominated for an Oscar for his mesmerizing
performance in this brilliant dark comedy. The witty, insightful
film is a biting exploration of how adhering to societal
conventions can lead to false and unfulfilling lives. However, its
ironic humor may be too dark for mainstream tastes. While we know
where it's heading from the outset, American Beauty delivers enough
off-the-wall plot twists to get there in unexpectedly tense
fashion. (10/1) Strong sexuality, profanity, violence, drug
content; 17 and older.
</P>
<P>
   ANY GIVEN SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   (R) B-
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Stone captures the raw excitement of professional
football, casting the players and coaches as modern-day gladiators
whose chivalric age is coming to an end. Unfortunately, the drama
runs more than 2 1/2 hours, and Stone's hyperkinetic mix of images
and film speeds seems overly stylized. The film hits its notes hard
and often, but it gets more involving as it goes, building to one
of the most thrilling climaxes in sports-movie history. (12/22)
Strong profanity, some nudity/sexuality; 17 and older.
</P>
<P>
   THE BEACH
</P>
<P>
   (R) C
</P>
<P>
   Leonardo DiCaprio plays a morally flawed U.S. traveler searching
for a fabled island paradise in this dark and bloody tale, based on
Alex Garland's novel. Though ambitious, Danny Boyle's stylish but
downbeat film is way overdone _ particularly when DiCaprio's
unsympathetic character descends into loopy, Apocalypse Now
-inspired fantasy. Heavy narration and an overly self-conscious
stylistic approach keep viewers at arm's length. (2/11) Violence,
strong sexuality, profanity, drug content; 17 and older.
</P>
<P>
   BOILER ROOM
</P>
<P>
   (R) C+
</P>
<P>
   In Ben Younger's timely, bracing drama _ set amid the current
stock-market explosion _ disenfranchised young men working for a
backroom brokerage firm sell their souls to become instant
millionaires. The taut, testosterone-intensive film starts off
strongly, absorbing you with the hyper-aggressive action, but it
plummets like overhyped stock in the second half, simmering to a
tepid remake of Oliver Stone's Wall Street. (2/18) Strong
profanity, some drug content; 16 and older.
</P>
<P>
   THE CIDER HOUSE RULES
</P>
<P>
   (PG-13) B-
</P>
<P>
   John Irving wrote the screenplay for the most successful
adaptation of one of his works since The World According to Garp.
But the sweet, touching drama is only a surface reading of the epic
coming-of-age tale about an orphan who is searching to find his
place and purpose in the world. The condensed version retains the
central story but lacks a strong narrative structure. The plot
doesn't take hold until the second half of the film. (12/24) Adult
content, sexuality, nudity, substance abuse, some violence; 13 and
older.
</P>
<P>
   DROWNING MONA
</P>
<P>
   (PG-13) B
</P>
<P>
   Who killed Mona Dearly (Bette Midler), the most reviled resident
of Verplanck, N.Y.? As the outrageous caper unfolds, with its
motley crew offering boatloads of alibis and one-liners, you can't
help but laugh at the amusingly pathetic events. William Fichtner,
Marcus Thomas and Jamie Lee Curtis manage to keep straight faces
and elevate the laugh quotient in the bargain. (3/3) Profanity,
sexuality, violence; 13 and older.
</P>
<P>
   THE END OF THE AFFAIR
</P>
<P>
   (R) B+
</P>
<P>
   Neil Jordan's powerful adaptation of Graham Greene's classic
novel is an old-fashioned romantic drama about love, betrayal and
sacrifice during World War II. Emblazoned by Julianne Moore, Ralph
Fiennes and Stephen Rea's emotionally rich performances, the story
has a strong dramatic center that doesn't reveal itself until
midway through the film. Though melodramatic, the simple tale
becomes more compelling as it progresses. (1/21) Strong sexuality;
17 and older.
</P>
<P>
   THE GREEN MILE
</P>
<P>
   (R) B+
</P>
<P>
   The Green Mile is a thoughtful prison drama with a supernatural
bent. Based on Stephen King's serialized novel, the touching tale
of miracles on death row is humorous and heart-wrenching. Director
Frank Darabont trims the back stories from King's text, but his
lean adaptation still runs long at more than three hours. Tom Hanks
gives an endearing performance, and Michael Clarke Duncan is a
revelation as the tragic central character. (12/10) Violence,
profanity, some sex-related material; 16 and older.
</P>
<P>
   HANGING UP
</P>
<P>
   (PG-13) C
</P>
<P>
   This rubber-stamp dramedy about three sisters (played by Meg
Ryan, Lisa Kudrow and Diane Keaton, who also directed) teems with
equal measures of solemnity and slapstick. Practically all that
distinguishes this from a prime-time soap is the constant use of
cellular phones and grumpy Walter Matthau's zingers. (2/18)
Profanity, mature themes; 13 and older.
</P>
<P>
   THE HURRICANE
</P>
<P>
   (R) B
</P>
<P>
   Denzel Washington gives a ferocious performance as Rubin
``Hurricane'' Carter, a boxing title contender who in 1966 was
wrongly convicted of triple homicide. Director Norman Jewison
presents a stirring account of Carter's 20-year fight for justice,
focusing on his friendship with a youth who mounted a campaign for
his release. However, the film takes many liberties with Carter's
story. The script's obviousness strikes a much bigger blow. (1/14)
Profanity, some violence; 16 and older.
</P>
<P>
   MISSION TO MARS
</P>
<P>
   (PG) D
</P>
<P>
   Brian De Palma's befuddling sci-fi drama involving the first
manned mission to Mars boasts some cool special effects and several
action-packed set pieces, but the clunky thriller lacks clear
vision, thereby making virtually no sense. De Palma wastes too much
time on the characters without really developing any of them.
Nothing ties together and the dramatic moments don't pay off.
(3/10) Sci-fi violence, profanity; 10 and older.
</P>
<P>
   MY DOG SKIP
</P>
<P>
   (PG) C+
</P>
<P>
   Willie Morris' best-selling memoir about his childhood canine
gets a sugary coating from director Jay Russell, whose well-meaning
adaptation slathers on warm photography and a patriotic score. A
nostalgic, innocuous slice of 1940s Mississippi, made digestible by
young star Frankie Muniz and kernels of conflict. (3/3) Mild
profanity, fleeting violence; 8 and older.
</P>
<P>
   THE NEXT BEST THING
</P>
<P>
   (PG-13) D
</P>
<P>
   This dreary romantic drama with strained comedic overtones,
about a woman and her gay male best friend who attempt to raise a
child together, is a gender-bending twist on Kramer vs. Kramer. The
downbeat story lacks a linear flow and lurches into overwrought
melodrama. Its only laughs come when Rupert Everett resorts to
mincing stereotypes. Madonna, in her first film role since 1996's
Evita, fails to exude any warmth. (3/3) Adult content, sexual
content, partial nudity, profanity; 13 and older.
</P>
<P>
   THE NINTH GATE
</P>
<P>
   Roman Polanksi returns to form _ at least until an
out-of-control finale _ with this symbolic horror-mystery starring
Johnny Depp as a book detective and Frank Langella as the collector
who hires him. The task at hand, pinpointing the original version
of an ancient book purportedly penned by Lucifer, leads to as much
fiery nonsense as it does intrigue. (3/11) Adult language,
sexuality, nudity, violence; 18 and older.
</P>
<P>
   PITCH BLACK
</P>
<P>
   (R) B-
</P>
<P>
   Pitch Black is nothing sci-fi fans haven't seen before in such
films as Alien and Starship Troopers. Yet the derivative thriller
is well done, given its limited budget and lack of big stars. Shot
in Australia with a largely Aussie cast, the scrappy sci-fi horror
film recalls George Miller's similarly earthy classic, The Road
Warrior. Vin Diesel's menacing, charismatic turn as the hardened
antihero marks him as a potentially major talent. (2/18) Sci-fi
violence and gore, profanity; 16 and older.
</P>
<P>
   PRINCESS MONONOKE
</P>
<P>
   (PG-13) B+
</P>
<P>
   Hiyao Miyazaki's beautifully animated epic is a sophisticated
environmental fable about the struggle between man and nature,
adapted to the English language by Neil Gaiman and featuring the
voices of Claire Danes, Billy Crudup and Minnie Driver. Some of the
folkloric elements of the top-grossing Japanese film are lost on
American viewers, but the appeal of Miyazaki's characters and the
sheer beauty of his images are universal. (11/19) Images of
violence and gore; 13 and older.
</P>
<P>
   REINDEER GAMES
</P>
<P>
   (R) C-
</P>
<P>
   Originally slated for release on Christmas, when its holiday
setting would have made a lot more sense, this preposterous
thriller stars Ben Affleck as a clueless ex-convict forced to
mastermind a casino robbery. The ridiculous story is as hard to
swallow as 2-month-old eggnog. It's all just buildup for the
explosive and extremely bloody heist sequence, in which the robbers
shoot it out wearing Santa Claus costumes. (2/25) Strong violence,
profanity, sexuality; 17 and older.
</P>
<P>
   SCREAM 3
</P>
<P>
   (R) C
</P>
<P>
   The third and final chapter of the teen-horror trilogy is as
redundant as those tired old slasher movies whose conventions the
first film so cleverly skewered. Minus creator Kevin Williamson,
Scream 3 is forced and overly self-referential, relying on too many
in jokes. There are a few good laughs, mostly drawn from pop
culture references, but it's not scary. We know every beat of the
formulaic story from having seen the previous films. (2/4) Strong
horror violence, profanity; 16 and older.
</P>
<P>
   SLEEPY HOLLOW
</P>
<P>
   (R) B
</P>
<P>
   Not so much sleepy as bloody, Tim Burton's reworking of the
Washington Irving folktale boasts enigmatic Johnny Depp as Ichabod
Crane (here a constable), on the bloody trail of a headless
horseman (Christopher Walken) with a penchant for severing noggins.
The director's remarkable calling cards _ atmospheric sets,
haunting imagery, a compelling story _ are well in place; the
nonstop gore seems out of place. (11/19) Profanity, violence and
gore, sexuality; 17 and older.
</P>
<P>
   SNOW DAY
</P>
<P>
   (PG) D-
</P>
<P>
   This feeble, absent-minded comedy, aimed at children's wildest
fantasies, focuses on two stories: a lovelorn teen's infatuation
with a popular classmate and the local school kids' unsupervised
battles with a psychotic snowplow operator (Chris Elliott).
Uniformly mean-spirited and unrealistic, the film's grandest
achievement may be its ability to evoke sympathy for Chevy Chase,
as a meteorologist. (2/11) Fleeting violence; 10 and older. _
</P>
<P>
   STUART LITTLE
</P>
<P>
   (PG) C-
</P>
<P>
   E.B. White's beloved tale about a mouse (voiced by Michael J.
Fox) adopted as a normal child, reaches the silver screen and falls
in line with the recent slew of animal-talking flicks. It's a genre
whose time has passed, and director Rob Minkoff _ despite clever
bits involving alley cats _ can't bring it back without a diet of
rehashed morals. (12/17) Profanity, mild violence; 10 and older.
</P>
<P>
   SUPERSTAR
</P>
<P>
   (PG-13) F
</P>
<P>
   This dreadfully incoherent comedy spotlights Molly Shannon's
Saturday Night Live alter-ego Mary Katherine Gallagher, whose
pining for a genuine kiss knows no boundaries _ or laughs, for that
matter. The usually dependable Will Ferrell and insufferable Elaine
Hendrix compound the disaster, and its 80-odd minutes seem to last
an eternity. (10/8) Adult language; 13 and older.
</P>
<P>
   3 STRIKES
</P>
<P>
   (R) D
</P>
<P>
   Rap producer D.J. Pooh's directorial debut samples the majority
of its ideas from other movies _ most notably Friday , which Pooh
co-wrote with Ice Cube. Pooh trots out the same tired cliches and
stereotypical characters that have been seen in a host of lowbrow
urban comedies. It attempts to draw laughs from crude sex gags and
juvenile flatulence jokes, delivered amid a constant stream of
strong profanity, but it fails to score single chuckle. (3/2)
Pervasive profanity, strong sexual content, drug use, brief
violence; 17 and older.
</P>
<P>
   THE TIGGER MOVIE
</P>
<P>
   (G) B+
</P>
<P>
   The first Winnie the Pooh theatrical release in 17 years is a
funny, heartwarming musical comedy about the importance of friends
and family. Rendered in the classic style of Disney's 1960s Pooh
featurettes, with hand-drawn cels and beautiful watercolor
backgrounds, the charming adventure is pure old-fashioned
entertainment. The songs aren't that memorable, but the gentle
humor will draw laughter from young and old alike. (2/11) Nothing
objectionable; all ages.
</P>
<P>
   TOY STORY 2
</P>
<P>
   (G) A
</P>
<P>
   The wildly imaginative sequel to the 1995 computer-animated
blockbuster improves on the original with more realistic animation
and a surprisingly deep and poignant storyline. The delightful
comedy-adventure is more emotionally involving than the first film,
centering on what happens when children outgrow their toys. It's
also more consistently funny, with tons of great gags that will
have viewers of all ages roaring with laughter. (11/24) No
objectionable material; suitable for all ages.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT PLANET ARE YOU FROM?
</P>
<P>
   (R) C
</P>
<P>
   Garry Shandling's first film venture puts a disappointing spin
on the Men Are From Mars, Women Are From Venus battle of the sexes.
Like much of Shandling's stand-up shtick, the sci-fi comedy deals
with his alien character's inability to score with or understand
women. The premise gives him license to play a cluelessly crude and
sexist jerk, as well as to make a million penis jokes. There are
some good chuckles but no solid laughs. (3/3) Sexuality and
profanity; 16 and older.
</P>
<P>
   THE WHOLE NINE YARDS
</P>
<P>
   (R) B-
</P>
<P>
   Playing notorious contract killers, Bruce Willis and Kevin
Pollack embody their deadpan bits to perfection, but Matthew Perry,
as a frenzied dentist, overplays the physical gags. Its premise and
dialogue, expectedly wacky and improbable at turns, remain
gleefully true to the hit-man comedy genre. (2/18) Strong
profanity, sexuality, brief nudity, violence; 17 and older.
</P>
<P>
   WONDER BOYS
</P>
<P>
   (R) B-
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Hanson's first film since L.A. Confidential is a midlife
coming-of-age story that combines elements of character drama and
screwball comedy, about a dissolute novelist (Michael Douglas)
trying to write the follow-up to his masterpiece. The offbeat,
original comedy treats its eccentric characters with warm
affection, but at times the film is as unfocused as Douglas'
dope-smoking character and too whimsical for its own good.
Profanity, drug content; 16 and older.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
