<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8832 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TECH-MUSIC-COX     03-16 1481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-MUSIC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Musicians wander to the Web
 &HT;    By Chris Riemenschneider
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Sure, big things are accomplished. Thousands of
CDs are sold with the click of a mouse. Huge mailing lists,
essential to a new band's fan base, are built off of e-mails. There
are even record deals offered on MP3 downloads alone.
</P>
<P>
   It's the little things, though, that demonstrate just how much
opposites can attract and Austin's music scene can take advantage
of the burgeoning high-tech world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet saved my hide,'' said one musician, Josh
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The bass player of a little band called the Bellfuries was
recently playing a little bar, Ego's, when a little miracle of
modern-day dot-comdom happened.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the band's set, a phone call came from a
thousand miles away in Chattanooga, Tenn., by someone listening to
the show via a-- Austin Web site called Clubcastlive.com. The
company broadcasts MP3 audio streams from 20 different music venues
in town, allowing musicians to be heard by fans from all over the
world _ including, in Williams' case, from home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my dad,'' Williams said. ``He told the bartender to
tell me that if I didn't wish my mom a happy birthday, I'd be in
serious trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Williams' ``Happy Birthday'' serenade from her son, his
bandmates and the patrons of Ego's indicates how music and
technology are intertwining in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   That developing relationship is especially evident this week
with the 14th annual South by Southwest Music Conference, which has
been inundated with music-related Web companies from Austin and
around the country. Local bands who used to seek record deals at
the conference are now being courted by Internet sites offering
money and exposure. Meanwhile, everyone at the festival is trying
to come to grips with the Internet's impact on the music industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Music is one of the first products that can be made, marketed
and sold completely by computers and on the Internet,'' said SXSW
managing director Roland Swenson. ``I think our conference and
Austin in general are at the forefront of all this.''
</P>
<P>
   Acceptance of the high-tech world is a giant step on the part of
the local music scene, which still blames the computer folks for
driving up rents, cramming the highways and bulldozing its favorite
live music venue, Liberty Lunch (torn down to make way for Computer
Science Corp.'s new downtown headquarters).
</P>
<P>
   But the techies' presence has proven beneficial to the music
community, too. It's getting easier for musicians to find someone
who can build them a Web site, or who know-- someone who knows
someone whose Web company is paying for music content, or who
know-- the advances in recording technology that are taking over
the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Any band that doesn't have these three developments on their
radar screen is far behind the times, say the musicians who have
made the most forays into the high-tech world.
</P>
<P>
   Musicians plug in
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet has been invaluable to me,'' said Austin
singer-songwriter Ginger Mackenzie. The Lilith Fair alumn-- sold
more than 10,000 copies of her album, ``Kismet,'' online and was
voted best artist of 1999 on San Diego-based MP3.com, one of the
biggest in the flurry of dot-com companies offering free downloads
of music by both new and established artists.
</P>
<P>
   With those kinds of achievements, it's no surprise Mackenzie is
being sought by many of the biggest record companies with
representatives at SXSW.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've told record company people the things we've been able to
accomplish, and they're all like, `What?!' Mackenzie said. ``Now I
see a lot more Austin bands on MP3 and a lot of the other Web
sites. I think the musicians in this town are becoming pretty savvy
when it comes to the Internet, so I wouldn't be surprised if there
are more acts from here that carve a path for themselves on the
Web.''
</P>
<P>
   One Austin band that has done so, Household Names, was far from
a household name in Austin when its catchy pop-rock single ``Bright
Spot'' became the No. 1 most-downloaded single on Soundclick.com.
That success then earned them a nice-sized mention in a Rolling
Stone magazine article.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing about it is it's so grass-roots,'' said
Household Names singer Jason Garcia, whose band has yet to play
more than a handful of local club gigs.
</P>
<P>
   Now that CDs are quite inexpensive to make and manufacture
(often around $1,000 if done on a small scale), many acts can
record a disc soon after forming and send it out to Internet
companies for promotion, as Household Names did with
Soundclick.com.
</P>
<P>
   Musicians aren't just using computer technology to promote their
music. They're also using it to make music, too, even music of high
quality and classic sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a breeze,'' said Austin's Zen-country legend
Jimmie Dale Gilmore about the recording of his new, critically
acclaimed album, ``One Endless Night.'' Though fueled by
traditional country and folk instruments heard on records 50 years
ago (guitars, mandolins, dobros, etc.), the disc's clear, crisp
sound quality can be credited to the fact that Gilmore and
Nashville producer Buddy Miller recorded it entirely on a Macintosh
in Miller's home studio, the singer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no tape involved whatsoever, which was one
advantage,'' Gilmore said. ``Also, it just negates the need for the
big, fancy, expensive recording studio. We did the entire album at
Buddy's house, and it was comfortable and felt a lot more organic
than all the other albums I've made.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies plug away
</P>
<P>
   Web companies are hoping a lot more can be accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, high-tech giants such as Austin Ventures and IBM have
aligned themselves with various online music companies. Other,
smaller companies _ such as Clubcastlive.com _ have based their
content solely on music.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no better city for us to have started in,'' said
Clubcastlive marketing director Steven Phenix whose company
(started last summer) wants to create an international network
where fans such as Josh Williams' parents can hear bands performing
in a number of cities.
</P>
<P>
   As proof, Clubcastlive signed on as the official online
broadcaster of SXSW and began running ads in cities that have local
bands performing at SXSW.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is that fans in Seattle or Chicago or wherever can
hear their hometown heroes play what is often one of the biggest
gigs of their careers,'' Phoenix said. He said Clubcastlive should
be broadcasting from three other cities soon after SXSW.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not every city has 50-plus live music venues or the
plethora of music talent for Clubcastlive and other Web companies
to tap.
</P>
<P>
   This, said Audiogalaxy.com music content editor Eric Zappa, is
the main advantage his company has over its competitors in other
cities. Audiogalaxy offers music downloads and promotional
opportunities for bands, similar to Web sites such as MP3,
Listen.com and Liquid Audio.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of those companies are in the Silicon Valley and places
that don't have any kind of music scene whatsoever,'' Zappa said.
``We don't consider ourselves to be an Austin music site, but you
look on our site and you'll see Toni Price, Chris Wall, The
Damnations and many others ... There's so much great music here, it
keeps us inspired to do what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Mackenzie: ``Music is one of the things that makes this
city so great to live in. I hope the computers start to respect
that more.''
</P>
<P>
   Many musicians and music-loving techies believe respect is on
its way.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the best-case scenario, mentioned by some musicians, is
that the high-tech world may finally give the local music scene the
business foundation it has always lacked. Though rich in talent
since the dawn of 2/4 time, Austin has never been able to compete
with the big-three music hubs _ Los Angeles, New York and Nashville
_ because it never had the business sense or infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has always been an imbalance between the amount of
talent here and the level of the music business,'' Zappa said. ``I
think it's possible for the Austin tech companies to fill that gap,
and I think it's even happening now.''
</P>
<P>
   Web companies nationwide are threatening to replace age-old
record labels based mostly in the nation's three music hubs.
Considering the high-tech resources here, it's possible Austin may
even have a leg up on Los Angeles, New York and Nashville. In that
case, Austin musicians might have a lot more to sing about than one
mother's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Said Phenix: ``We have something cool to show the world, our
music scene. What better way to show it off nowadays than on the
Internet?''
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Chris Riemenschneider at
criemenschneider(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
