<HEADLINE>
`MIRACLE' AIDS DRUGS FAIL TO LIVE UP TO HOPE OR HYPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Four years ago, a new class of anti-AIDS drugs brought
hope that the deadly disease could become a chronic, manageable
condition such as diabetes. A few even spoke of a cure.
</P>
<P>
   Today, a grim realization is dawning that for many people, the
``miracle'' drugs are only buying time.
</P>
<P>
   Precious little time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have patients who we saw rise from the dead thanks to
some of these drugs,'' said Dr. Thomas Hooton, medical director of
the University of Washington's AIDS clinic at Harborview Medical
Center. ``We don't see that any more.''
</P>
<P>
   The drugs he's talking about are known as protease inhibitors _
anti-HIV medications with such mystical-sounding names as
nelfinavir, indinavir or saquinavir. In 1995, after the protease
inhibitors first became available, many extremely ill people made
astounding recoveries.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS mortality rates plummeted. At a 1996 international AIDS
conference, a few researchers even went so far as to suggest
science had found a ``cure'' for AIDS _ a drug therapy that could
suppress HIV to undetectable levels and perhaps prevent disease.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, with 14 different anti-HIV drugs on the
market, the optimism has faded. Some are predicting AIDS death
rates will increase again. And confusion reigns as experts debate
which therapeutic approach works best.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question that the drugs, used together with other
anti-HIV medications in a ``drug cocktail'' often known as HAART
(highly active anti-retroviral therapy), saved lives and improved
quality of life, particularly in the United States and other
developed countries where the $10,000 annual cost is affordable.
</P>
<P>
   But many are not doing so well any more, Hooton said, and new
studies now indicate that only half of those on HAART appear to
fully benefit from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``For whatever reason, the virus outwits the drugs,'' Hooton
said. HIV is constantly undergoing genetic mutations, he said, a
random process that occasionally allows it to stumble onto a new
way around medicine's latest therapeutic assault against it.
</P>
<P>
   The complicated new anti-HIV drug regimens have been difficult
for people to adhere to, Hooton said, and inadequate adherence can
create drug-resistant HIV. If the virus is allowed to replicate in
the presence of inadequate medication, drug resistant forms of the
virus can emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Also, newly recognized complications associated with the HIV
therapies _ such as an increased risk of heart disease,
osteoporosis and diabetes _ have further diminished initial
enthusiasm for these new drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Some doctors continue to be strong advocates of aggressive drug
therapy, believing that when the medications fail, new combinations
of drugs will take their place. Others now tell their infected
patients to wait until they get sick before going on anti-HIV
therapy _ a complete about-face from the previous policy of
starting therapy immediately upon learning of the infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we can do is buy time,'' said Dr. Robert Killian, a
Seattle physician who treats people with HIV infection. ``I've
backed off on pushing these drugs until completely necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the strange and sometimes disfiguring problem of
body-fat maldistribution, in which people on anti-HIV drugs lose
nearly all their subcutaneous fat only to see it collect in big
lumps on the neck or stomach.
</P>
<P>
   This fat distribution problem is thought to be related to the
dramatic increase in cholesterol and blood lipids seen in some
HIV-infected people.
</P>
<P>
   While none of the experts is certain if these problems are
caused by the drugs or are simply long-term complications of HIV
infection, everyone's quite certain now that the promise of the
protease inhibitors was oversold.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hope and hype has not been realized,'' Dr. Jeff Schouten,
an HIV-positive physician active in local and federal AIDS policy
matters who works with the Seattle Treatment Education Project, a
nationally recognized organization that provides AIDS/HIV
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gave people a false sense of complacency,'' Schouten said.
``There's a perception out there that doesn't match the reality.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a dangerous misperception.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are becoming unsafe again in their sexual behavior
because they think the infection can be controlled by these
drugs,'' Schouten said. The word needs to get out there, he said,
that people are still dying from this disease and the drugs so far
have only provided a temporary respite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prevention remains critically important,'' agreed Dr. Ann
Collier, chief of the UW's AIDS Clinical Trials Unit. ``Treatment
hasn't yet made this a chronic, manageable disease for most
people.''
</P>
<P>
   The history of the battle against AIDS, she said, has been like
a roller coaster with a repeated series of high-flying expectations
followed by scary plunges. We're on one of those plunges right now,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   But both Collier and Schouten said there are new experimental
therapies that may hold promise when people ``burn out'' on the
HAART therapies.
</P>
<P>
   Most anti-HIV therapies work by interfering with the virus'
ability to reproduce itself.
</P>
<P>
   HIV is different from most other viruses that infect us. It's a
slow-acting virus that attacks the immune system cells, called
T-cells, that are supposed to protect us from such invaders. And
it's a ``retrovirus,'' which means it incorporates its genetic
material into the infected T-cell's DNA to make our cells crank out
new HIV particles.
</P>
<P>
   AZT was the first anti-HIV drug _ a member of a class of drugs
known as nucleoside analogues. These drugs mimic genetic material
and are used to infiltrate HIV's genetic command center to disable
it and prevent it from incorporating its DNA into our cells.
</P>
<P>
   When AZT began to fail, doctors turned to a second class of
drugs, ``non-nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitors,'' which
worked by halting HIV's genetic invasion by blocking an enzyme
needed to convert HIV's genes into usable DNA.
</P>
<P>
   The third class of drugs, the protease inhibitors, attack HIV at
a completely different point, after the virus has already inserted
its DNA into the infected cell. These drugs interfere with an
enzyme to block the production of new viral particles.
</P>
<P>
   The protease inhibitors were so effective that some experts
initially speculated long-term use of these drugs could eventually
clear the virus out of the body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody believes any more that you're going to
get viral clearance,'' said Brian Coppedge, a treatment information
specialist who works with Schouten at STEP.
</P>
<P>
   New anti-HIV drugs in the clinical-trial pipeline aim to attack
HIV on some new fronts. These drugs are available only to those few
patients accepted into clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   The experimental drugs are still ``inhibitors,'' but they
inhibit the virus in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   Entry inhibitors work to prevent the virus from entering the
human cell in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Another category of experimental anti-HIV drugs are called
integration inhibitors. These drugs aim to stop the integration of
the viral genes into the T-cell's DNA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so much further along than we were five years ago,''
said Hooton, referring to drugs now on the market. ``We do have
something to offer HIV patients therapeutically.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's no magic bullet yet, Hooton said, and about 40,000
people still become infected in the United States every year. The
problem of HIV and AIDS worldwide, especially in the developing
world, is even more urgent and terrifying, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Schouten said he's become more hopeful about the new drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``But none of this has yet made having HIV like having a chronic
disease,'' he said. ``People are still dying.''
</P>
</TEXT>
