r a BC-AIDS-WOOD-SPI &LR;      03-16 1391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-WOOD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRONT-LINE AIDS EXPERT FACES UNCERTAIN FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Dr. Robert Wood has been King County's public health
point man on AIDS since the beginning of the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   He's also an HIV-infected man facing an increasingly uncertain
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm scared, yes,'' said Wood, director of the HIV/AIDS control
program for Public Health _ Seattle &AMP; King County.
</P>
<P>
   Like others with the infection, he has benefited from new drugs
that many believed would allow people with HIV to completely
suppress the virus and indefinitely prevent the onset of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Few experts believe that any more.
</P>
<P>
   Wood is watching his viral load _ an estimate of the amount of
the deadly virus in his blood _ increase again.
</P>
<P>
   Because he began taking the drugs early in his battle against
the disease, he fears that what's happening to him may soon be
commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``These aren't good signs,'' he said, reverting to his
matter-of-fact doctor's voice, as if rendering a diagnosis on some
random case report. ``The death rates are going to go up.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the public Dr. Wood, 57, a health professional who makes
his case in the analytical and objective manner expected of him.
</P>
<P>
   But in private these days, Wood weeps about friends who have
died and sometimes also for himself and his partner, Dave Cervenka,
47. Both learned they were infected in the mid-1980s. They've fared
pretty well over the years, thanks to the arsenal of anti-HIV
medications that allowed them to keep the virus at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, a new generation of drugs called protease
inhibitors brought many AIDS patients back from near death.
Mortality rates plunged, and many resumed lives and careers they
thought were lost.
</P>
<P>
   But now the threat has returned, and Wood is in the unique
position of dealing with it on two fronts, public and private.
</P>
<P>
   He's been on the front lines of the battle against AIDS since he
diagnosed the county's second official AIDS patient in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   He's been there through the community warfare over condom
distribution in schools, and in 1989, he worked with activists to
start one of the nation's first hypodermic-needle exchanges aimed
at curbing AIDS among injection drug users.
</P>
<P>
   As a public health physician who made no secret that he was gay,
Wood was in a key position to take on the potentially explosive
combination of homophobia and fear of this new and unknown disease.
He was soft-spoken, but forthright and professional. He gained the
trust of the community at large, and of the gay community in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   But he also has been willing to take on AIDS activists when he
believes a public health goal should transcend politics. Wood
enraged people in the early 1990s _ and still does today _ by his
support for confidential reporting of the names of HIV-infected
patients to track the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   At the heat of the battle, several public health department
buildings were spray-painted with graffiti lambasting Wood for his
stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came under a lot of attack for that,'' said Dennis
Braddock, chairman of the state Board of Health. The state adopted
a compromise policy, reporting names at the local level and
tracking by a coded number at the state level.
</P>
<P>
   Wood's unswerving devotion to science and public health has made
him a lightning rod in AIDS politics, Braddock said. But it also
allowed him to serve as an effective liaison between disparate
groups _ activists and government, gays and the medical
establishment _ in the highly charged world of AIDS policy.
</P>
<P>
   Wood's reputation extends beyond the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew of him before I even got here,'' said Dr. Alonzo
Plough, director of the health department since coming from Boston
in 1995. ``His work on AIDS prevention is known nationally. ... As
a scientific resource, his knowledge is tremendous.''
</P>
<P>
   But sitting in the front room of his Seattle home, the private
Wood talks with his partner about the couple's 15 years of struggle
against HIV.
</P>
<P>
   Both were among those who ``burned out'' on AZT, the first
anti-HIV drug. In 1987, they were enrolled in one of the first
studies of AZT. When the drug became ineffective, they turned to
other drug combinations, with mixed results.
</P>
<P>
   The news about the powerful therapeutic effect of the protease
inhibitors came just in time for Cervenka. He had been diagnosed
with AIDS in 1994, and went on disability a year later, quitting
his job in medical and research supply at the University of
Washington. Wood, though infected since the early 1980s, has never
been diagnosed with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had already prepared to die,'' Cervenka said. ``I kept
asking myself why I should take these drugs if all they're going to
do is prolong the limbo I've been in.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wood encouraged his partner to try the new drugs. Cervenka's
turnaround was as remarkable as it was for many of those taking the
protease inhibitors _ drugs with mystical sounding names such as
nelfinavir, indinavir or saquinavir.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just unbelievable,'' Cervenka said. ``In a matter of
weeks, my T-cell count (a blood cell count indicating immune system
health) doubled.''
</P>
<P>
   Cervenka is still doing well on the new drugs. But Wood's HIV
count has been increasing, indicating the effectiveness of his
current drug regimen is diminishing. And, as is true for many
others with the infection, there's no other new option out there
for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you become resistant to one protease inhibitor, you're
probably resistant to all of them,'' Wood said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone burns out the protease inhibitors ...,'' Wood's
voice trailed off as he glanced at Cervenka. ``I'm just a realist,
I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Cervenka looked back at Wood for a long time. Then he turned and
said, ``I still feel optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Cervenka already gave up once. He's not about to accept his
partner's resignation _ just as Wood refused to accept Cervenka's
desire to simply die years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been lucky so far to be riding this crest, just staying
ahead of death,'' he said. ``I do have hope, even if it's more
uncertain now.''
</P>
<P>
   When Wood started taking his new course of protease inhibitors _
having run the course on an early regimen _ he got very sick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prior to all this, I had tolerated the drugs pretty well,''
Wood said. ``This combination made me sick.''
</P>
<P>
   That disturbing turn of events pushed his partner over the edge.
</P>
<P>
   Cervenka had come to depend on Wood's well-being for his own
sense of security. He was the one who had been diagnosed with AIDS.
He was the one taking 35 pills a day. Wood was supposed to be the
strong factor in this equation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just went ballistic,'' Cervenka recalled. His anxiety about
Wood, compounded by an ongoing struggle with bipolar disorder,
became so pronounced he required hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
   Wood still suffers from drug complications and has lost nearly
all his body fat, apparently a side effect of the protease
inhibitors. But the two have come to terms with their situation in
different ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob's a scientist and says things objectively, while I still
tend to get all emotional,'' Cervenka said. ``But I'm getting more
objective about it and, at times, he can be very emotional.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the stresses of his job and his illness, Wood said he has
learned to rely on Cervenka's support at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times I just come home and cry on Dave's shoulder,''
Wood said.
</P>
<P>
   But Wood and Cervenka say they are somehow more at peace these
days despite the clouds on the horizon. They and their cats enjoy
quiet evenings and, when weather permits, take in a view of Lake
Washington from their deck.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the old television show ``Star Trek'' is weekly de
rigueur for the couple.
</P>
<P>
   They have different temperaments that clearly work in
complementary fashion. Wood, reared in upstate New York, has an
Eastern intellectual way about him and sometimes can't kick out of
work mode when he comes home.
</P>
<P>
   Cervenka, who grew up in nearby Sumner, Wash., is more of a
homebody and likes to spend his time in the garden. Circumstances
have forced both to live for today, something he would advise
everyone to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've learned to live in the here and now and not think too
much about the future,'' Cervenka said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1607EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8838 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-AIDS-VACCINE-SPI &LR;      03-16 1871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-VACCINE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE TO BE CENTER FOR HIGH-STAKES FEDERAL AIDS EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Scientists appear closer to checkmating the AIDS virus
with a vaccine, and Seattle is at the center of the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Within the next several weeks, Seattle will be named global
headquarters for all the AIDS vaccine work being done under the
National Institutes of Health. The HIV Vaccine Trials Network will
be run by Dr. Larry Corey, head of the infectious disease program
at the Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center.
</P>
<P>
   As new anti-AIDS drugs lose their power against the quickly
mutating virus, an effective vaccine could be the last, best hope
to contain the epidemic. An estimated 40 million people worldwide
are infected with HIV, with an additional 16,000 people, most in
developing countries, infected per day.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle effort will coordinate a massive, expedited effort
to get new vaccines into widespread clinical trials as quickly as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   The search for an AIDS vaccine has turned into a high-stakes
chess match with scientists trying to trick the virus at its own
game _ manipulating the body's immune system. As researchers devise
ever more clever and sophisticated molecular strategies to combat
it, the virus has continued to outwit efforts to erase it.
</P>
<P>
   But after years of frustrating effort, the science of
vaccination _ still rooted in 18th-century principles _ appears
ready to move forward by biological quantum leaps.
</P>
<P>
   Those leaps will come in the form of new genetic technologies,
which are now emerging in laboratories around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure most of these technologies will be in place within
five years,'' said Phil Greenberg, a professor of medicine and
immunology at the University of Washington and a virologist at the
Hutchinson Center. ``Certainly, we will be testing in clinical
models (patient trials) within the next five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Corey and his colleagues hope the federal effort will mark a new
era in vaccine development.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to put under one umbrella a group of scientists to
try to speed development of a vaccine and coordinate (the
development) in a way that's not been done before,'' said Corey,
who has a joint appointment at the University of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, scientists assumed that the secret to an AIDS
vaccine was simply finding the right piece of the virus to use as
the ``antigen'' to elicit an immune response. This is old-school,
mainline vaccine warfare. Antigens are proteins, usually foreign to
the body, that cause the immune system to generate antibodies. In
an immune response, the antibodies lock onto the antigenic protein,
``neutralizing'' it and allowing the body to rid itself of foreign
invaders.
</P>
<P>
   This is the body's front-line defense against disease, the
mechanism by which we combat most viral and bacterial pathogens.
Traditional vaccines that harness this mechanism have brought many
devastating diseases under control, from polio to smallpox.
</P>
<P>
   But it hasn't worked with HIV.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, there have been more than 40 AIDS vaccine
regimens tried in more than 3,000 subjects. The results have been
disappointing _ weak, short-lived immune responses that failed to
neutralize the virus.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for these failures lies in the nature of the virus
itself.
</P>
<P>
   HIV does not trigger the body's immune system, Corey said. ``The
virus is very clever. It's developed ways of masking itself from
the immune response. It's been a formidable obstacle.''
</P>
<P>
   The biology of HIV is different from other viruses, particularly
those that cause acute infections, Greenberg said. ``Its special
characteristics make it a lot more difficult than many of the
viruses we have vaccines for.''
</P>
<P>
   HIV causes a chronic, persistent infection that has a latent
phase. The virus lurks in the immune system, hiding out undetected
by the body, while it prepares for the eventual assault on immune
system cells that leads to AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The virus is a notorious shape shifter, mutating quickly into
different strains that make it more difficult for any one antibody
to ``neutralize'' all the different versions.
</P>
<P>
   But there is something even more difficult about trying to
control HIV through vaccines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The really critical obstacle with HIV is that vaccines in
general have been effective as means of preventing disease, not
preventing infection,'' Greenberg said. ``The problem is that
probably won't be an acceptable outcome for an HIV vaccine because
of the nature of the infection.''
</P>
<P>
   Once in the door, the virus can exploit even the tiniest
foothold in the immune system, eventually overtaking it and killing
the patient. Some AIDS researchers now believe that any vaccine
will have to prevent infection, not just prevent the development of
the disease after infection.
</P>
<P>
   But others disagree, arguing that a vaccine that slows the onset
of disease, or reduces its severity, is a legitimate goal. While
such a vaccine may not contain the epidemic, it would allow people
to live longer with HIV, and reduce human suffering with the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the issues being debated at the moment is whether the
vaccines we're dealing with now, especially the combination vaccine
regimens, are good enough to move into clinical trials,'' said
Corey, who is optimistic that the current generation of vaccines
may prove effective. ``The question is how do you assess what's
good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   This question has essentially divided the vaccine research
community into two camps. One believes in waging the search for a
vaccine in the laboratory, the other in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Killer cells:
</P>
<P>
   Corey's optimism is rooted in a new understanding of how to
manipulate the immune system at a molecular level to generate
larger immune responses.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have long been intrigued by a special group of
patients _ the so-called ``non-progressors'' _ who are infected
with the virus but who don't go on to develop AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   What distinguishes this group is that they typically have high
levels of ``cytotoxic T lymphocytes'' (T-cells), which are
specialized killing cells that attack foreign invaders.
</P>
<P>
   The immune system has two arms _ one that generates antibodies,
and another that generates T-cells. Scientists now believe that the
secret to an effective HIV vaccine lies in stimulating both arms of
the immune system.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, there are at least a half-dozen vaccine strategies
under development that hope to do just that. Some of these include
using other non-pathogenic viruses as ``vectors'' to shuttle HIV
genes into the body, essentially turning the body's own cells into
antigen-producing factories. There is some evidence that such ``DNA
vaccines'' can produce a more vigorous, sustained immune response,
including the production of killer T-cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``The live vector-based approach is very, very exciting right
now,'' said Dr. Norman Letvin of Harvard Medical School and a
leading AIDS vaccine researcher.
</P>
<P>
   A new paradigm:
</P>
<P>
   Targeted Genetics Corp., a Seattle-based biotech firm, is
banking on such a vaccine. The company, which has developed
proprietary techniques for gene therapy, is looking at ways of
harnessing those techniques to transfer HIV genes to cells.
</P>
<P>
   Targeted's approach is based on ``adeno-associated virus'', a
common virus that doesn't itself cause disease. By using
recombinant DNA techniques to insert HIV genes into the AAV genome,
then ``infecting'' cells with the recombined virus, the cells begin
producing viral antigens, turning on the immune system.
</P>
<P>
   Studies have shown that the response is both strong and
long-lasting, said Pervin Anklesaria, director of research at
Targeted Genetics.
</P>
<P>
   Targeted recently signed a $6 million, three-year deal with the
International AIDS Vaccine Initiative, a non-profit funded in large
part by the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation, to fund development
of an AAV-based HIV vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   The Targeted Genetics deal represents a new strategy in vaccine
research in another way as well.
</P>
<P>
   Most vaccine development in past decades has been done by
commercial companies. However, the HIV problem has been so
formidable, the risk so high and the cost so great that the private
sector has all but abandoned the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It killed a few companies along the way,'' Corey said.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers realized several years ago that the discovery of an
AIDS vaccine was unlikely to happen without collaboration between
the public and private sectors.
</P>
<P>
   That is now starting to happen. Last year, the Gates Foundation
awarded $25 million to the International AIDS Vaccine Initiative.
In addition, part of the foundation's $750 million fund to improve
childhood vaccination in developing countries has been dedicated to
AIDS vaccine research.
</P>
<P>
   Provocative work:
</P>
<P>
   Despite the renewed resources for clinical trials, and promising
new technologies to exploit, there are still some basic scientific
questions that need to be answered.
</P>
<P>
   For example, scientists are still struggling to figure out which
HIV genes will best elicit immune responses.
</P>
<P>
   But they do have clues.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, for example, a group of scientists in Montana
discovered that when the virus first infects a cell, it undergoes a
slight change in surface configuration. This change fleetingly
exposes a new receptor on the surface of the virus. Researchers
have been able to capture this transitory configuration in a
so-called ``fusion product.''
</P>
<P>
   If they then immunize mice against this ``fusion product,'' they
get a stronger immune response. And the response appears to be
capable of neutralizing many different strains of the virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very provocative work,'' said Greenberg, whose lab is now
collaborating with the Montana group.
</P>
<P>
   And there are more intriguing clues as well. Researchers have
recently identified a molecule called CTLA-4 that is part of the
checks and balances of the immune system, Greenberg said. It
functions by dampening the immune response, preventing the body
from overreacting and producing too many T-cells. In a clever
twist, scientists discovered they could use this to their
advantage. By using an antibody against CTLA-4 molecules, they
could block them from working, thus enabling the body to naturally
produce more T-cells. Researchers are looking at ways of combining
such an antibody with an HIV vaccine to boost the immune response.
</P>
<P>
   And there are still other immune system molecules that could be
used in conjunction with a vaccine to increase effectiveness,
Greenberg said. Immunex Corp. in Seattle, for example, has cloned a
molecule known to stimulate dendritic cell growth. Dendritic cells
are the specialized cells in the immune system that ``present''
antigens to T-cells, essentially programming them to attack that
type of antigen.
</P>
<P>
   That type of creative tinkering in the immune system is what is
most likely to pay off in an effective vaccine, Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technologies are limitless,'' he said. ``And fortunately,
our imaginations are also limitless so there will be much better
ways to vaccinate in the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
