<SLUG> BC-FILM-GHOSTDOG-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFBEAT `GHOST DOG' TURNS DARK WITH GRATUITOUS BLOODSHED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've got to give indie filmmaker Jim Jarmusch credit for
reinventing and mixing genres in his eccentric films.
</P>
<P>
   His vision is so embraced by cult film audiences in the United
States and Europe that he's become the Jerry Lewis of independent
cinema to the French.
</P>
<P>
   He blended the grittiness of John Cassavetes' cinema verite
movies with screwball comedy for ``Down By Law'' (which starred
Oscar-winner Roberto Benigni), ``Night On Earth'' and ``Stranger
Than Paradise'' and a Hong Kong theme meshed with the ghost of
Elvis in ``Mystery Train.''
</P>
<P>
   He's even traipsed into documentary territory with his last
movie, ``Year of the Horse,'' while his 1995 film, ``Dead Man,''
though it was inert and tedious, paid homage to revisionist
westerns such as ``McCabe and Mrs. Miller.''
</P>
<P>
   With ``Ghost Dog: The Way of the Samurai,'' he's stirred Zen
austerity with an Italian ``spaghetti western'' sensibility. As
directed by Sergio Leone, '60s films such as ``The Good, the Bad
and the Ugly,'' ``A Fistful of Dollars'' and ``For A Few Dollars
More'' featured a ``man with no name,'' a loner antihero played by
Clint Eastwood as an extension of such stolid and stoic western
matinee idols as John Wayne and Gary Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Ghost Dog: The Way of the Samurai,'' Forest Whitaker,
playing a mysterious ronin-like hit man named Ghost Dog, embraces
the lessons of ``Hagakure, The Book of the Samurai,'' while
communing with the gangster-mentality of the mob.
</P>
<P>
   The film is a cross-cultural walking movie reference and, for
its first half, the fusion of styles works. Ghost Dog lives atop an
old apartment building in New Jersey and he shares his still and
ordered life with a cage of pigeons. Ghost Dog daily honors his
allegience to Louie (John Tormey), a mob man who once saved his
life, by performing hits on mob marks. But one night, something
goes wrong on what should have been a routine job and Ghost Dog
finds the Vargo crime family wants to eliminate him.
</P>
<P>
   Jarmusch gets an absorbing and fascinating performance from
Whitaker who, despite his large bulk, moves as effortlessly as a
cat through the rundown cityscape, and terrific character bits from
Cliff Gorman and Howard Silva as two aging mobsters. He also
incorporates disciplines and lessons from the ``Hagakure'' into the
film and, for once, the inserts cleverly mesh with the action.
</P>
<P>
   But halfway through the film, the tone shifts to a violent new
plateau that is both shocking and unsettling when a woman cop is
shot point blank and a child witnesses a faceoff in the middle of a
city block. While it may be Jarmusch's intent to document the
changing rules beneath the strange, structured code of ethics in
the worlds of both the urban samurai and the mob, he seems instead
to introduce gratuitous bloodshed that is out of sync with the
engaging, offbeat tempo and dark, comedic moral fable that has come
before.
</P>
<P>
   Ghost Dog: The Way of the Samurai. Directed and written by Jim
Jarmusch. Cast: Forest Whitaker, John Tormey, Cliff Gorman, Isaach
de Bankole, Henry Silva, Victor Argo. Artisan Entertainment. 116
minutes. Rated R for violence, language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1611EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
