<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8851 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-AIDS-CAMERON-SPI &LR;      03-16 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-CAMERON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DRUGS KEEP HIM, AND HIS HOPES, ALIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Timm Cameron is waiting for a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be his first.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron, 38, has AIDS. He's been on every possible combination
of currently available drugs, but they aren't working for him any
more.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't the first time for that, either.
</P>
<P>
   Each time his medication options have run out, a new drug has
come along just in time to push back his disease one more time.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron found out he was HIV-positive just before his 30th
birthday in 1992. At the time, he was a junior at Seattle
University and had gone in for some surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an accident (in surgery) with a scalpel,'' he said.
``They asked to test my blood.''
</P>
<P>
   He was positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's indescribable to get the news,'' he said. ``In that
instant, everything changes.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, ``that meant death.''
</P>
<P>
   AZT had been approved, but it was the only drug available.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one was taking AZT alone and getting better,'' he said.
``The prognosis was you watched your T-cells, watched them fall,
and then you died.''
</P>
<P>
   His T-cells, an immune system cell that fights invading viruses,
continued to fall. At the time of his diagnosis, they were at 600.
(Normal is about 1,000.) A month later, they had slipped to 400. He
started AZT.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wake up every day wondering what's next,'' he said. ``You
do a mental check. If you're breathing a little different, you
think it's pneumonia. If there's a spot on your skin, you think
it's cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he managed to get his degree in psychology and work for
a year in social services, the disease was sapping all his energy.
</P>
<P>
   He ``retired'' one year after graduating from college.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1992 and 1996, a series of AZT-like drugs came out, but
none reversed his disease. His T-cell count fell to zero.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1996, the first protease inhibitors became widely
available.
</P>
<P>
   That gave Cameron a new shot. He started dual therapy with a
combination of AZT and a protease inhibitor. His energy levels
began to improve. His T-cells rebounded to 130.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always felt blessed by this,'' he said. ``Every time I've
run out of options, something new has come out just about the time
we were done.''
</P>
<P>
   Others shared his sense of relief and euphoria.
</P>
<P>
   Within six months of the arrival of the new protease inhibitors,
the perspective of patients and care providers changed, he said.
``There was finally some kind of hope. People were getting
better.''
</P>
<P>
   By this time, Cameron was feeling well enough to volunteer as a
counselor at the Northwest AIDS Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he is employed there as the client support services
coordinator. One of his jobs is helping patients adhere to their
medication regimens.
</P>
<P>
   Adherence is critical to success of the drugs, he said. Studies
have shown that 95 percent of patients who take their drugs 95
percent of the time achieve long-term viral suppression. When
patients take the drugs 70 percent of the time, only half of them
will get viral suppression.
</P>
<P>
   But the drugs don't work indefinitely, even for patients who
stick perfectly to their schedules. And the confidence that
combination therapies were going to be a permanent fix for AIDS
patients has begun to wane.
</P>
<P>
   The last combination Cameron tried, for example, worked for only
four or five months. ``Then my viral load started creeping back
up,'' he said. His T-cells now hover around 12.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron has been off medication since November. He's out of
options. His viral load continues to climb, and his fatigue is
mounting as well. He's had to cut back on his work hours.
</P>
<P>
   But he remains hopeful. There is a new protease inhibitor that
is nearing approval, and he hopes to be able to start it soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those of us who have been around awhile, you never know
what's around the bend,'' he said. ``I don't get as anxious as I
used to about my numbers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
