<SLUG> BC-FILM-BEAUTIFULPEOPLE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BEAUTIFUL,' FAST AND FUNNY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This film comes at you like the assault that begins the movie:
fast, furious, comic and unexpected. The first half-hour tumbles
out in near-chaos; we don't see much beauty, but we do meet a lot
of people, and the movie expects us to be patient even though it's
in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Stick with it, though, because the rewards are ample. This
London-set melange of British, Welsh, Serbian and Croatian
characters starts off in conflict _ some stemming from nationalist
fervor, some from family arguments. It sometimes feels like it
needs a score card, but it gels when a young, heroin-addled
hooligan (Danny Nussbaum) finds out in the most unexpected way that
there is pain in other parts of the world. Wouldn't dream of
spoiling it for you.
</P>
<P>
   As the movie hurtles along, it encounters birth, marriage, death
and isolation. Its nearest American equivalent is ``Magnolia.''
Like that movie, it has a motley crew of characters and an
insistent soundtrack, but it plays out in much funnier ways, with
its emotions at a lower pitch (it's also barely half as long as
``Magnolia''). Writer-director Jasmin Dizdar keeps the pace
frenetic; he may let things get a little confusing in the
beginning, and his end message may not be any deeper than that we
all need to learn to get along, but he never fails to make the
journey entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Beautiful People''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Length: 100 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
