<SLUG> BC-FILM-ERINBROCKOVICH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE SMART COOKIE: JULIA ROBERTS TAKES ON WEIGHTIER ROLE, AND
DOESN'T CRUMBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fact-based ``Erin Brockovich'' seems like it has
``backlash'' written all over it, so it makes sense to put a
poster-child for backlash like Julia Roberts in the lead role.
Here's an actress who charmed audiences with early supporting roles
(''Mystic Pizza,'' ``Steel Magnolias'') before appearing in a huge
hit (''Pretty Woman'') that has nearly as many detractors as it has
fans. Once Roberts hit it big, her critics became harsher _ kind to
her when she starred in fluff like ``My Best Friend's Wedding,''
not so kind when she attempted more serious projects.
</P>
<P>
   Director Steven Soderbergh may have found the solution to
Roberts' drama problems with ``Brockovich,'' a movie that uses a
wicked sense of humor to examine serious themes. It's the kind of
David-vs.-Goliath story told in ``The Insider'' and ``A Civil
Action,'' but it drops the self-importance of those movies and
replaces it with a refreshingly feisty attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Soderbergh, who may be the best director that Roberts has ever
worked with (well, she worked with Steven Spielberg and Robert
Altman, but let's not bring up ``Hook'' and ``Ready to Wear''),
puts her to good use immediately. The movie's opening shot is a
loving closeup of Roberts, big hair, big eyes, big teeth filling
the screen as if it were a magazine cover. It's only when
Soderbergh pulls back that we see that she's not in control here;
as Erin Brockovich, she's at a job interview, practically begging
to be hired.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't have much luck. A single mother with three young
children, Erin has a penchant for the type of tight-fitting,
revealing clothing that high-school guidance counselors say is a
no-no for a job-hunter. She also has an abrasive, sarcastic streak.
During her search, Erin has a nasty car wreck that puts her in a
neck brace; when she decides that her lawyer (Albert Finney) isn't
doing enough to get her a settlement, she bullies her way into a
position at his firm.
</P>
<P>
   It's there that she discovers some medical records that make her
curious enough to investigate their source, and then finds that the
illnesses are tied to contaminated water near the Death Valley
community of Hinkley, Calif. The source of the tainted water:
utility giant Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric, which apparently has been
telling residents that the water is just fine.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, what ensues is by the numbers _ Erin rallies
Hinkley's residents with a class-action suit, finds some
townspeople who are reluctant to stir things up, tangles with her
boss, encounters shady characters and argues with smug attorneys
who dismiss her because of her looks and fashion sense.
</P>
<P>
   But Soderbergh and screenwriter Susannah Grant dress up the
formula story with a lot of wit and spirit. Soderbergh is a smart
director, and he knows how to play to Roberts' strengths and
conceal her limitations. Under his guidance, she makes Erin, a
snappish character with a chip on her shoulder, appealing because
she summons up the kind of ``root for me'' pluck that goes all the
way back to the days of silent-movie actresses. Soderbergh also
uses ideas he worked out in less mainstream fare such as last
year's excellent ``The Limey'' and 1998's ``Out of Sight,'' playing
with editing and music in a way that's more immediately accessible
than it was in those less star-driven movies.
</P>
<P>
   This is Roberts' show, but Finney isn't about to be blown off
the screen by anybody, and it's amusing to watch his bluster. The
gifted Aaron Eckhart is all but wasted (and looks more than a
little ridiculous) in the role of a kindly biker who hooks up with
Erin but begins to whine about how she's never around. ``Cradle
Will Rock's'' Cherry Jones continues to impress in the role of a
woman affected by the water contamination.
</P>
<P>
   Recent fact-based movies such as ``The Hurricane'' and ``The
Insider'' were assailed for their truth-twisting, but Soderbergh
and his producers say that they've tried to stick as closely to the
facts as possible here. That doesn't mean that backlash won't
happen, especially since they acknowledge some fictionalization.
Soderbergh's biggest triumph, though, is that he delivered a film
that received enthusiastic applause from a packed preview audience.
That's evidence of a hit _ and as one of our most gifted filmmakers
who's not exactly a household name, he deserves all the success
that comes his way.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Erin Brockovich''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Steven Soderbergh
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Julia Roberts, Albert Finney
</P>
<P>
   Length: 131 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ profanity and adult situations
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
