<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV19-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MCCAIN, BRADLEY INTERLUDE IS ONE TO REMEMBER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, March 19)   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Let history record that in the first spring of the
new millennium, a fresh breeze billowed across the American
political landscape, providing hope of reform.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as February faded into March and the first jonquils and
forsythia of the emerging season festooned the banks of the
Potomac, the two men responsible for that breeze _ John McCain and
Bill Bradley _ were eliminated from competition for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the interlude was a short one that already is
being forgotten as America focuses on the exploits and insults of
Al Gore and George W. Bush. By November, when we elect our next
president, the interlude may be as much an event of the past as
Barry Goldwater's quest for the presidency in 1964 or Eugene
McCarthy's campaign in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   But the words and deeds of McCain and Bradley should not be
forgotten. They reignited the flames of idealism in the stagnant
souls of many Americans who are weary of Clinton's sexual escapades
and wary of what Gore and Bush have to offer. For a brief time they
could dream the dreams that fired insurgents of the past to fight
for an America less manipulated by the rich and entrenched.
</P>
<P>
   The one who made the most lasting imprint on the presidential
campaign was John McCain, the feisty Arizona senator who has the
rare distinction of having emerged from imprisonment in Vietnam as
a valiant soldier of a war that produced few public heroes.
</P>
<P>
   McCain sought to revitalize the republic and the Republican
Party by urging reform of campaign fund-raising practices that have
become a continuing scandal in both parties, and by suggesting that
government deal more sternly with the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   He had the audacity to challenge Bush _ the candidate who had
been anointed as the party's standard-bearer by members of
Congress, governors and party professionals even before the
campaign began. In doing so, McCain charged down the campaign trail
like a latter-day Harry Truman, indulging in straight talk rather
than convoluted campaign rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   The second reformer, Bradley, a former basketball star and
senator from New Jersey, had less impact on the electorate. A
lanky, diffident one-time Rhodes scholar, the Democratic
presidential hopeful was less successful than McCain at
communicating with the people and energizing them.
</P>
<P>
   Like McCain, he urged reform of the system of campaign
fund-raising and preached the need to invest the nation with ``new
politics,'' although it was difficult to discern from his speeches
exactly what he meant by that. His most memorable accomplishment,
and one that Bush constantly emulates, was questioning Gore's
veracity.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a full-page advertisement that appeared in the
Washington Post commended Bradley for ``a valiant effort in a truly
just cause to make America a better place for all of us.'' The ad
was signed by seven couples, including basketball great Michael
Jordan and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Since Bradley and McCain abandoned their campaigns after the
March 7 ``Super Tuesday'' contests, politicians and pundits have
been trying to figure out whether the campaigns will have any
long-range impact.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bush began immediately to cultivate the supporters of
the vanquished. Both have made pitches for campaign fund-raising
reform, with Gore's proposal appearing to be closer to the more
sweeping changes sought by McCain. Bush, who has raised an
estimated $70 million, would ban some money from labor unions and
corporations but not from wealthy individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have watched many insurgent campaigns flourish and
fade.
</P>
<P>
   In 1952, when Truman's administration was tarnished by scandals
involving White House regulars, the military stalemate in Korea and
assertions by Republicans that the U.S. government was brimming
with communists and communist sympathizers, Adlai Stevenson won the
favor of liberals with his eloquence and idealism.
</P>
<P>
   But Stevenson's campaign for the presidency in that year and
again in 1956 was doomed to failure because a personable and
popular military hero of World War II, Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower,
invaded the Republican Party and won its presidential nomination
over the solid opposition of the party's isolationist right wing.
</P>
<P>
   Goldwater, the colorful senator from Arizona, scored heavily in
1964 with the Republican right wing, which had grown weary of the
party nominating moderates for president. But his nomination split
the GOP and he was defeated badly by Lyndon Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, Sen. Eugene McCarthy of Minnesota won the plaudits and
support of millions of Americans when he challenged Johnson's
Vietnam policy. Johnson, winning only a narrow victory over
McCarthy in the New Hampshire Democratic primary, withdrew from the
race.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Kennedy entered it, echoing McCarthy's anti-Vietnam
rhetoric. Had he not been assassinated, Kennedy might have gone on
to win the party's presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson is this: America admires reformers but does not
always elect them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
