<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY WHAT RIGHT ARE YOU GETTING YOURSELF A GUN?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every week, mobster Tony Soprano drives onto the screens of
millions of American cable TV viewers, accompanied by rollicking,
raunchy background music that contains the refrain:
</P>
<P>
   ``Woke up this morning, got myself a gun, got myself a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   The song obviously is perfectly attuned to the character of the
boss Soprano because of how he earns his living and the things he
is sometimes obliged to do to keep on living.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Soprano and the real-life characters upon whom he is based
are not concerned in the least about the new national debate about
gun regulation triggered by the cheap shots taken recently by
National Rifle Association President Charlton Heston and NRA
Executive Vice President Wayne LaPierre at President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In a new television commercial, Heston suggests strongly that
Clinton lied about the NRA's efforts to block reasonable gun
control laws. Heston maintained that the president stymied the
legislation by refusing to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Clinton, when what you say is wrong, it's a mistake. When
you know it's wrong, it's a lie. Remember?'' said Heston.
</P>
<P>
   It was painfully obvious that Heston was attempting to obscure
the substance of the issue by resurrecting the image of Clinton as
prevaricator-fornicator during the tawdry Monica Lewinsky business.
</P>
<P>
   LaPierre then sent shivers down the spines of some of even the
most fervent gun rights advocates when he accused the president of
needing ``a certain level of violence in this country ... a certain
level of killing to further his political agenda and his vice
president, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite those ad hominem attacks, Clinton appears more
determined than ever to push for what he calls ``common-sense gun
control,'' which would require:
</P>
<P>
   _ Background checks on sales at gun shows that could take up to
72 hours. The NRA wants such checks limited to no more than 24
hours.
</P>
<P>
   _ Trigger locks on new guns.
</P>
<P>
   _ A ban on the import of large-capacity ammunition magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Soprano, of course, would not be the least concerned about
incremental gun regulation that might evolve into gun confiscation.
Being an outlaw, he is comforted by the bumper stickers that
proclaim: ``When guns are outlawed, only outlaws will have guns.''
</P>
<P>
   That other bumper sticker about guns not killing people,
however, would strike him as absurd and an insult to his
intelligence. He knows that guns do kill people. People just point
them. More precisely, guns make killing people a lot easier,
whether accidentally or on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   But the gun worshipers keep reiterating that ridiculous refrain
like a mesmerizing mantra. The other mantra they keep chanting is
that the right of every American to wake up in the morning and get
a gun is enshrined in the Second Amendment to the U.S.
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's just not so, McGee.
</P>
<P>
   Either Heston and his crowd don't know that, which would mean by
his reasoning that they are mistaken, or they do know it and they
are lying to the American public.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the Second Amendment does say that ``the right of the
people to keep and bear Arms, shall not be infringed.'' But that
comes after it says: ``A well-regulated Militia, being necessary to
the security of a free state ...''
</P>
<P>
   That first part is what the Hestons and LaPierres of this nation
like to gloss over. But the Supreme Court has said in no uncertain
terms that the first part is the crucial part.
</P>
<P>
   The court spoke emphatically and with impeccable logic in 1939
with its ruling in the case of United States vs. Miller. In that
case, the Supreme Court overturned the dismissal by a lower court
of charges against an Arkansas bootlegger for carrying a sawed-off
shotgun across state lines.
</P>
<P>
   The court said that the Second Amendment confers no individual
right to possess a firearm that does not have ``some reasonable
relationship to the preservation or efficiency of a well-regulated
militia.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously a sawed-off shotgun flunked that test. But the
important part of that ruling was the interpretation of the Second
Amendment that tied it to the militia condition.
</P>
<P>
   That interpretation has stood for more than 60 years and has
filtered down through more than 100 appellate and lower court
rulings.
</P>
<P>
   But last year a federal district judge dismissed an indictment
against a Texas physician who brandished a gun in front of his
estranged wife and her daughter while he was under a restraining
order.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, it sounds ludicrous, but that judge concluded that the
doctor had a Second Amendment right to wake up in the morning, get
himself a gun and violate the terms of the restraining order.
</P>
<P>
   That ruling in the case of U.S. vs. Emerson stands about as much
chance of surviving the scrutiny of the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals as a Tony Soprano has of winning the Nobel Peace Prize.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the very fact that a federal judge could be so
mistaken _ influenced, perhaps, by NRA propaganda _ shows the
pernicious influence that the gun lobby is having on public opinion
and public policy by continuing to propagate the big lie that the
Second Amendment gives all of us the constitutional right to wake
up in the morning and get ourselves a gun.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can reach him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
