<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BLACKJACK17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Prognosis is gory for `Black Jack'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Black Jack'' is the given name of a mysterious, possibly
unaccredited doctor for hire, with a scarred face and two-tone
hair. A master surgeon, for those who can afford his sky-high fees,
he swoops into action, scalpel in hand, muttering things like ``I
think the problem stems from the pituitary system.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sci-fi anime feature that equally likes action scenes and
gory surgeries, Black Jack investigates the crash-and-burn symptoms
of superathletes who broke world records two years earlier at the
1996 Olympics. He encounters a brainy, duplicitous female doctor
who knows more than she initially lets on, uncovers a medical
conspiracy and a lethal drug, and runs into activists working for a
group called Medical Soldiers for Justice.
</P>
<P>
   It's all very hard-boiled, except for when the movie focuses on
Black Jack's sidekick, an unbelievably annoying little girl named
Pinoko. A talky medical noir, this film isn't as visually
interesting as other animes. And it's the sort that lets one of its
dying characters deliver a long-winded explanation and personal
self-defense as her blood seeps into the sand.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the flick is based on the manga by Osamu Tezuka.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black Jack''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   An anime feature directed by Osamu Dezaki. Unrated, but designed
for mature audiences.1 hour, 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: All hard-boiled action and gore.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constiution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
