A8884 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-IMAC-MCDONALDS19-COX     03-16 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMAC-MCDONALDS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Macs electronic and edible big hit in Costa Rican cafe
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 19.
 &HT;    By Ron Martz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEREDIA, Costa Rica _ From the outside, it looks like any other
McDonald's, golden arches and all, plucked out of Middle America
and plunked down in Central America.
</P>
<P>
   But on the inside, this McDonald's has some slightly different
combination meals. In addition to Big Macs, it has iMac computers.
And if you buy a combo meal and supersize those papas fritas, you
get 30 minutes of Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Known as MiMac Cafe (``My Mac'' in Spanish), this McDonald's has
become increasingly popular with students from the National
University of Costa Rica just up the street in this suburb of the
capital, San Jose. But young businessmen also find it convenient to
stop in for a quick bite and some quick bytes, checking e-mail,
reading the latest news, or trolling for job opportunities. Parents
with young children also come here to see what the Internet is all
about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually I go to an Internet cafe in San Jose, but this is
closer and I can come here to check my e-mail or when I need to do
some research while I get something to eat,'' said Antonio Nunez,
22, a second-year medical student.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 computers were installed five months ago when other
Americanized fast-food restaurants began popping up in the area,
said Grettel Gonzalez, hostess at the MiMac Cafe. Within a block
are a Burger King, a Kentucky Fried Chicken, a Papa John's Pizza
and a cyber-cafe that has drinks but no food.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was necessary for us to do something different to stay
competitive,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   Getting online here is as simple as ordering one of McDonald's
standard combination meals, including a McBurger Supreme or a
Cuarto de Libra (a quarter-pounder) and saying: ``Papas fritas
super.'' One of the online assistants provides a special code that
allows Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Many Costa Ricans are Internet-savvy, Gonzalez said, but
McDonald's is sponsoring introductory courses at the university to
help students learn how to use it as a research tool.
</P>
<P>
   The MiMac Cafe's one big shortcoming, according to its regulars,
is that it has no printers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm doing research and I want to print out something, I
have to go to the cyber-cafe in San Jose,'' Nunez said.
</P>
<P>
   But probably with a supersized order of papas fritas to go.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Martz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
