r l BC-STYLE-PROM19-COX     03-16 0232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-PROM19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Prom gowns take a shine to color in sweet, sexy, sophisticated
looks
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 19.
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The slogan for prom dresses this year: Less is more.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Young ladies will be wearing less fabric and showing more skin
in strapless gowns, two-piece formals with hip-hugging waistbands
and dresses with high slits or corset-tied backs.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Even some of the classic styles have less satin and tulle. For
example, ballerina skirts are not as puffy, especially when paired
with bustiers or spaghetti strap tops.
</P>
<P>
   But designers didn't skimp on color or fabric.
</P>
<P>
   The hot hues this year are lilac, silver, sky blue, pink,
periwinkle and burnished gold. White, black and silver metallics
are still cool. Look for matte crepe, satin, organza and, for those
who want to be really daring, a shiny, hologram vinyl.
</P>
<P>
   Dresses are accentuated with such details as embroided flowers
and trim, ethnic prints and rhinestones. Jewelry is understated,
perhaps because the gowns speak for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   For more suggestions about what to wear to the prom, check out
these Web sites:
</P>
<P>
   www.prom-dresses.com
</P>
<P>
   www.pzaz.com
</P>
<P>
   www.cybernetplaza.com/promAlma E. Hill writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
