<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8887 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     03-16 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK DETAILS INSIDER'S VIEW OF HIS ROLE, OTHERS IN S&AMP;L DISASTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA McUSIC 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Move over, Tom Wolfe. A California banker has a tale that rivals
parts of your last great novel.
</P>
<P>
   And, unlike Wolfe's fiction-based-on-fact, this book is more
fact-that-reads-like-fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Its subjects _ from Donald Trump to Charles Keating to Peter
Ueberroth _ are as colorful and flamboyant and blindly ambitious as
any character Wolfe could contrive. Its story line is as serpentine
and unpredictable as a well-devised fictional plot.
</P>
<P>
   And the author is a true insider: Robert Smith, chairman of the
board and chief executive of Security Pacific, once the
fifth-largest bank in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The book is ``Dead Bank Walking: One Gutsy Bank's Struggle for
Survival and the Merger That Changed Banking Forever'' (Oakhill
Press, Winchester, Va., 426 pages, $27.95).
</P>
<P>
   This is banking in the go-go 1980s and the crash-and-burn
megamerger '90s. Smith chronicles this roller-coaster ride with
good writing, big-picture analysis and candor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Smith attributes the good writing to his co-author, Mike
Crowley.
</P>
<P>
   For an example of how character, plot and good writing come
together, consider the first chapter, in which Smith meets with a
major Security Pacific borrower: Charles Keating. The real-estate
developer is looking for a savings and loan to buy, and Smith
innocently puts the idea of Lincoln Savings and Loan into Keating's
head.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln later went down in flames, marking the most costly S&AMP;L
failure in history. Only later does Smith realize his error in
judgment, not only for Lincoln and the savings and loan industry,
but for his own bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transgressions of Keating served as the lightning rod for
Congress to enact new legislative changes that were a catalyst for
Security Pacific's downward spiral,'' Smith writes. ``Although
Security Pacific had barely begun its meteoric rise to fifth
largest bank in the United States, in many respects its path to
destruction was carved the moment Keating walked into my office. If
only I'd smelled the cheese of deceit in Keating and sent him
packing at that first meeting, our story and the stories of many
other banks might have turned out differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Keating was just one of the famous and infamous developers of
the '80s who marched into Smith's office seeking partners in a
deal. For Ueberroth, who was orchestrating a deal to buy Hawaiian
Airlines, Security Pacific financed $80 million and lost virtually
all of it.
</P>
<P>
   So as reckless as Keating must have looked to responsible
bankers, even responsible bankers were taking risks far beyond what
they had done before.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whether Smith enabled a criminal, the exploits of
Keating and others caused Congress to react and substantially
change the way all banks and S&AMP;Ls work, particularly when valuing
real estate loans and participations. Security Pacific was heavy in
that area, and the Financial Institutions Reform, Recovery and
Enforcement Act of 1989 sent the S&AMP;L into a tailspin.
</P>
<P>
   Smith devotes the rest of the book to how his bank spent the
early '90s shrinking, then in 1993 merged with Bank of America, the
biggest merger to that time. Although Smith often slips more into
``banker talk'' during this final section, with attention to
``REO'' and ``basis points'' and other financial jargon, the story
maintains a fast pace.
</P>
<P>
   This book will truly entertain anyone who was in the industry at
the time, but as an insider's account of the second-most tumultuous
period in U.S. banking history, it also has wide general interest.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``WetFeet.com's Industry Insider Guide: The Inside Scoop on the
Job You Want''
</P>
<P>
   By WetFeet.com
</P>
<P>
   Jossey-Bass, $26
</P>
<P>
   This is different from any job-hunting guide I've ever seen, and
not just for being based on finding jobs through the Internet. It
also helps readers research an industry through an overview,
profile of a current worker, What's Great/What's to Hate section
and other information to prepare job candidates better. This is a
frank and insightful look at 60 industries.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Work With Me! Resolving Everyday Conflict in Your
Organization''
</P>
<P>
   By Gini Graham Scott
</P>
<P>
   Davies Black, $27.95
</P>
<P>
   Gini Graham Scott has written many books dealing with conflict
resolution and other business topics. Here, she covers overcoming
common communication problems, dealing with difficult people,
applying different conflict and negotiation styles, and conquering
emotional barriers to resolve conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Dictionary of Financial Terms
</P>
<P>
   By Virginia B. Morris and Kenneth M. Morris
</P>
<P>
   McGraw Hill, $14.95
</P>
<P>
   From acquisition to zero-coupon bond, this dictionary offers
definitions that are easy to read and graphically enhanced. The
Morrises are well-known in the financial and business publishing
world, having written ``The Wall Street Journal Guide to
Understanding and Investing'' and other popular books. This
dictionary has the added bonus of a Web address for updates to
existing words and new terms, and it lets readers offer terms for
consideration for future editions.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
