<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8903 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GORE-WOMEN-$ADV19-COX     03-16 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-WOMEN-$ADV19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DAUGHTER KARENNA BRINGS SPARK OF YOUTH TO AL GORE'S CAMPAIGN
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington, (p) politics and (l) lifestyle
categories for release Sunday, March 19.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Tipper Gore formally registered her husband's
presidential candidacy in New Hampshire last fall, she autographed
a poster marking the state's first-in-the-nation primary. ``The fun
starts here. New Hampshire rocks!'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But the driving beat of the vice president's campaign has come
mostly from another brainy, beautiful blonde in the family _ Al and
Tipper's eldest daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff.
</P>
<P>
   She may be a political neophyte who was repelled by public life
as a youth, but 26-year-old Karenna now calls herself ``an extra
set of eyes and ears'' for her father's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   She is much more than that, however. She is, in the estimation
of The New York Times Magazine, ``the Golden Child'' of American
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Karenna's mix of earnest and cool has made her a favorite
stand-in for her father or mother at campaign events. Though eight
months pregnant, she even subbed for a hoarse Tipper to introduce
Gore when he announced his candidacy for the Democratic nomination
in Tennessee last summer. Eighteen days later, with perfect timing,
she gave birth to her son Wyatt on the Fourth of July.
</P>
<P>
   Karenna's cover girl looks and poise have made her invaluable to
fund-raisers for ``GoreNet,'' the Web-based get-out-the-youth-vote
effort she heads for her father.
</P>
<P>
   Karenna is becoming a role model for career women trying to
balance the demands of jobs and home, though her life is hardly
typical: she is a third-year student at Columbia Law School who
lives on the exclusive Upper East Side of New York City with
8-month-old Wyatt and her physician husband, Andrew, the scion of
banking and publishing empires in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   And, with her mother, Karenna is half of the inner circle the
vice president turns to for unfiltered, unvarnished advice on how
he is doing in his quest for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   It was Karenna and Tipper who told Al late last summer to move
his campaign headquarters to Tennessee and to get back to the
informal open meetings with voters that had been the basis of his
congressional campaigns. Otherwise, ``you lose,'' they said.
</P>
<P>
   Karenna has, in fact, taken on a campaign role normally reserved
for spouses, fathers, brothers and, occasionally, sons. Gore
campaign aides often compare the relationship to that of Jack and
Bobby Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in a better place when she's around,'' Bob Squier, Gore's
longtime media adviser, told reporters before his death in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``A child who can go out and speak credibly about a parent
running for president, you don't see that very often,'' said Ryan
Karben, a New Yorker who worked with Karenna as a summer associate
at a Manhattan law firm.
</P>
<P>
   Her performance has been such that she is now the subject of
speculation about whether she will follow her father into the
family business.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, when asked if she would consider running for
Congress in 2002, she said, ``I wouldn't rule it out.'' In 2002,
her son will be 3, the same age she was when her father first ran
for Congress. He was elected on her birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea what options she'll consider or discard in the
future, but I'm very proud of her,'' Gore said of Karenna in a
recent interview. ``She really has perfect pitch, or very nearly
perfect pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Karenna has three siblings: Kristin, 21, and Sarah, 20, both
college students, and Albert, 16, a sophomore in high school. All
three occasionally make campaign trips with their father, but dad
talks to Karenna nearly after night after campaigning to get her
take on his performance.
</P>
<P>
   The reason Gore says his daughter has only ``nearly perfect''
political pitch may be that she recruited her friend, feminist
writer Naomi Wolf, to the campaign last year. It was nearly a
disastrous move.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf's high-priced advice to Gore _ be the ``alpha'' male, wear
earth tones _ subjected the vice president to public ridicule and,
for some, confirmed their suspicions that Gore was artificial, the
product of polls and focus groups, willing to take on any persona
to win.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it is this view of Gore as a humorless policy-driven
android that brought Karenna into the campaign. She wanted American
voters, especially other Gen-Xers, to know that her dad was
``really cool.''
</P>
<P>
   She told interviewers that his private nickname was ``Inspector
Gadget'' because of his love of technology, that he is a big fan of
Bob Dylan and the Grateful Dead, and that one of his favorite TV
programs is ``The Simpsons.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent bus swing through Tennessee, she kept up a now
familiar drumbeat of the reasons people should vote for Gore:
``He's a visionary. He's a principled fighter. And he's a policy
pioneer. If you need a fourth, he's a really great dad.''
</P>
<P>
   Tipper had tried to give her husband the same kind of political
face-lift, but her efforts _ she described in one magazine
interview how Al slept in the nude _ largely fell flat.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, even though she played drums for an all-girl rock band
called ``The Wildcats'' in high school, Tipper just did not rock in
the minds of the hip and the cool.
</P>
<P>
   She had created the impression of a prudish, interfering
housewife with her crusade against lewd and violent rock lyrics in
the 1980s, a crusade that began after she heard a 14-year-old
Karenna listening to a song about ``Darling Nikki,'' whom Prince
sang that he had met ``in a hotel lobby masturbating with a
magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She was ahead of her time,'' Karenna said of Tipper recently.
But during Karenna's adolescence, it was hard to be cool when mom
was routinely portrayed as a modern-day Carrie Nation, trying to
rid the world of raunchy rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very embarrassed at the time,'' she told The New York
Times last November. She recalled how the rapper Ice T had written
a song about Tipper that was ``upsetting'' to her. ``I wanted to be
cool, like a lot of 14-year-olds, and that definitely didn't
help,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Karenna's ``hippie'' phase began at the elite National Cathedral
School in Washington. It continued at Harvard, where she had a
reputation as a campus Deadhead, though her friends ranged from the
nerdy to the preppy.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she immediately connects with her audiences with the
observation that they all had ``lived through grunge.''
</P>
<P>
   After college, Karenna worked for a while at Slate, Microsoft's
online magazine. But her life changed dramatically in 1996 when she
was introduced to ``Drew,'' as her husband Andrew is known to
friends. Five months later, they were engaged.
</P>
<P>
   They were married at the Washington National Cathedral in the
summer of 1997, and at the conclusion of the ceremony, the bride's
late grandfather, Albert Gore Sr., still waiting to see a Gore in
the White House, stood and yelled, ``Joy to America!''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
