   NIRELAND-BOMB (London) _ In the latest sign of republican
attempts to disrupt peace efforts, three men are arrested after the
discovery of 500 pounds of homemade explosives in a car near
Belfast, the Northern Ireland police said. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-FILES (Washington) _ Nearly four years after the
Whitewater independent counsel began investigating how the White
House acquired some 900 confidential FBI files, many of them of
prominent Republicans, the current counsel, Robert W. Ray,
officially reported Thursday that there was no criminal wrongdoing
involved. The report is the first of several to be issued over the
next several months by Ray as he closes down the independent
counsel's office. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   VT-CIVIL-UNIONS (Montpelier, Vt.) _ The Vermont House has moved
within a key vote of backing a bill that would grant homosexuals
the benefits of marriage through civil unions. (Summary from wires)
By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Investors bought stocks furiously on
Thursday, sending the Dow Jones Industrial Average to its biggest
one-day gain since October 1987. At least for one day, the rally
put to rest fears that the Federal Reserve is pressing too hard to
slow the U.S. economy. As trading began Thursday, buyers flocked to
the old economy companies that make up the bulk of the stock market
and that have suffered for much of this year. Stocks of financial
companies such as American Express performed especially well, as
did shares of companies like airlines, whose profits are likely to
be strong if the economy stays healthy. But by mid-afternoon, the
buying had spread to new economy technology and Internet companies,
which have already posted strong gains this year. By the end of the
day, all segments of the market were sharply higher, with the Dow
Jones Industrial Average up 488 points, or 5 percent, to 10360, and
the Nasdaq composite index up 2.94 percent. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   BMW-ROVER (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Six years and nearly $6 billion
after buying Rover, BMW A.G. of Germany essentially gave away the
British automaker's money-losing car business Thursday to a
little-known group of British investors. BMW also was nearing a
deal to sell the remainder of Rover, its Land Rover line of sport
utility vehicles, to the Ford Motor Co. The giveaway of the car
business was stunning enough. But BMW's Land Rover deal with Ford,
which executives close to the talks said could be announced as
early as Friday, raised speculation that BMW might soon put itself
up for sale after years of fiercely maintaining independence, and
that Ford was a possible buyer. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``s'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HKN-DEVILS-SALE (New York) _ In a long-expected move, N.J.
Devils owner John McMullen announces he will sell his hockey team
to the YankeeNets, the parent company of the Yankees and Nets,
following the end of the 1999-2000 NHL season. The move opens the
way for the YankeeNets to move ahead with their plan to build a new
arena in Newark that would house both teams. By Richard Sandomir.
</P>
