<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8905 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOK-NOTES16-COX     03-16 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ha Jin's latest honor: PEN/Faulkner finalist
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Atlanta writer Ha Jin is on a roll. After winning the National
Book Award in November for his novel ``Waiting,'' the Emory
University professor has been selected as a finalist for the
prestigious 2000 PEN/Faulkner Award for fiction.
</P>
<P>
   The PEN/Faulkner Award is the largest annual juried prize for
fiction in the United States. The winner receives $15,000, and the
four other nominees each receive $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Nominated along with Jin are Frederick Busch for ``The Night
Inspector,'' Ken Kalfus for ``Pu-239 and Other Russian Fantasies,''
Elizabeth Strout for ``Amy and Isabelle'' and Lily Tuck for ``Siam
or the Woman Who Shot a Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Ha Jin's novel traces Lin Kong's 18-year struggle to free
himself from an arranged marriage and marry the woman he loves in a
society designed to regulate his every move. It is also a
penetrating portrait of contemporary China.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Night Inspector,'' Busch follows maimed Civil War
veteran William Bartholomew as he battles to reconstruct a life for
himself in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pu-239 and Other Russian Fantasies'' is Kalfus' second
collection of short stories, all of which explore individual lives
during a century of Russian history. The title story follows a
doomed nuclear power plant worker as he sells a most unusual
package on the black market, a canister of weapons-grade plutonium
(Pu-239).
</P>
<P>
   In her first novel, ``Amy and Isabelle,'' Strout explores the
secrets of sexuality that jeopardize a mother-daughter relationship
when a teenage girl crosses the line with her math teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Tuck's third novel, ``Siam or the Woman Who Shot a Man,''
follows the fortunes of Claire, a 25-year-old bride from Boston, as
she adjusts to her new life in Thailand during early stages of the
U.S. bombing of North Vietnam in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   The winner will be announced in April. All five authors will be
honored May 13 at the 20th PEN/Faulkner Award ceremony at the
Folger Shakespeare Library in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Music and marinades: Ricky Martin is the latest celebrity to
step into the kitchen. The Latin sensation is shopping around a
cookbook with recipes from Casa Salsa, the restaurant he owns in
Miami. With bids expected in the high six figures, the publishing
action is likely to be as hot as the recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Other celebrity cookbooks already on the market include Patti
LaBelle's ``LaBelle Cuisine: Recipes to Sing About'' (Broadway,
$25), Sara McLachlan's ``Plenty: A Collection of Sarah McLachlan's
Favourite Recipes'' (Madrigal, $24.95), and Trudie (Mrs. Sting)
Styler's ``The Lake House Cookbook'' (Potter, $35).
</P>
<P>
   The recipes range from LaBelle's ``Over-the-Rainbow Macaroni and
Cheese'' and McLachlan's ``Writer's Block Oatmeal-Raisin Cookies''
to Styler's ``Rolled Lamb with Chile Sauce and Mole.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Short-term memories: Teen pop diva Britney Spears' memoir is
due out in May from Three Rivers Press. Yes, a memoir. Written with
the help of her mother, Lynne, the book is touted as an
inspirational tome. Coincidentally, it's also scheduled to hit
stores at the same time as her new CD.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
