<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8908 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MUSIC-LATINPOP17-COX     03-16 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-LATINPOP17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hot sounds take pop charts by storm
 &HT;    By Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hot, it's sexy and it's bursting with Latin flavor.
</P>
<P>
   No, we're not talking about that skimpy Versace dress Jennifer
Lopez wore at the Grammy Awards. We're talking about the U.S. pop
charts.
</P>
<P>
   They may not get the respect of the tradition-laden Cuban sound
of the Buena Vista Social Club, or the much admired jazz of Texas
percussionist Poncho Sanchez, but Ricky Martin, Enrique Iglesias
and Marc Anthony are loved by U.S. pop fans with a gusto that
eluded such earlier crossovers as Puerto Rican pop phenoms Menudo
or the Spanish duo Los del Rio. (Their ``Macarena'' was a smash hit
in 1996, but it has since become as big a pop culture punch line as
Milli Vanilli.)
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Latin sabor dominate the Grammy ceremony on Feb. 23
_ with performances by Martin, Anthony and the Buena Vista Social
Club and a trunkful of awards for guitarist Carlos Santana _ but
the National Academy of Recording Arts &AMP; Sciences unveiled some
rather startling news that night. Pop songstress Christina Aguilera
and actor Jimmy Smits made the announcement that on Sept. 15, for
the first time ever, there will be a Latin Grammy Awards in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   This is no attempt to ghettoize, but an acknowledgment of the
fact that Latin music is dominating the pop charts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing this because it's time, and not because of the
popularity of Ricky Martin or anyone else,'' says Adam Sandler,
vice president of communications for NARAS. He was in Mexico City
recently, reassuring the musical communities in Latin America that
the move will benefit the entire spectrum of acts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The community down here has been very concerned that the
awards would be about the most popular artists,'' he said. ``But we
can recognize an album that much of the general public has never
heard. That's one of our goals, to give exposure to artists that
otherwise might not be heard by the general public.''
</P>
<P>
   Next on the radar screen: Colombian siren Shakira and hunky
Mexican singer Luis Miguel, both of whom have conquered Latin
audiences and are being pitched as the next Ricky.
</P>
<P>
   What a difference a generation makes.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that an exotic touch guaranteed only that an
artist wouldn't be taken seriously by mainstream radio. Hits from
Hispanic artists peppered the pop charts through the years, but
many were fads (remember the lambada, the ``forbidden dance''?).
</P>
<P>
   A hop in the way-back machine traces other inroads. In the 1940s
and '50s, Carmen Miranda parlayed her film success into a musical
career, recording her samba-drenched music and appearing on ``The
Jimmy Durante Show.'' Meanwhile, bandleaders such as Xavier Cugat
(the one-time Mr. Charo, with whom Miranda recorded), Desi Arnaz
and Mongo Santamaria added a touch of tropical jazz to popular
music. It would continue sporadically into the early '60s, with
hits from Stan Getz and Astrud Gilberto's version of Antonio Carlos
Jobim's ``The Girl From Ipanema'' to Eydie Gorme's airy ``Blame It
on the Bossa Nova.''
</P>
<P>
   On the rockier end of the spectrum, a teenage Ritchie Valens
took ``La Bamba'' onto the charts in 1959 _ but a month later, the
man who might well have been the first enduring Latino rock star
died in a plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   Spanish rock quintet Los Bravos had a 1966 hit with ``Black Is
Black,'' but then it was Santana's turn to give the San Francisco
scene a taste and climb into the Top 10 with ``Evil Ways'' and
``Black Magic Woman'' in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   The disco era, with its rhythmic focus, brought back a little
Latin touch to popular music, though artists such as Santa
Esmeralda, the Salsoul Orchestra and Kid Creole and the Coconuts
were a bigger presence in club land than chart land.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, that suave, smooth Spaniard Julio Iglesias landed two
duets in the Top 40, one with Willie Nelson and the other with
Diana Ross. His albums would continue to sell large numbers, but
haven't scaled the U.S. pop charts since.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Gloria. Cuban-born vocalist Gloria Estefan's Miami
Sound Machine was a hit-making operation that landed seven songs in
the Top 10 between late 1985 and the summer of 1988. Estefan's solo
career, commencing with 1989's chart-topper ``Don't Wanna Lose
You,'' boasts its own string of hits.
</P>
<P>
   Like Valens before her, the Tejano singer Selena didn't live to
see her career take off on this side of the border _ though she was
a star in Mexico. Shot by the president of her fan club in 1995 at
age 23, she might have taken her blend of ranchera, country, pop
and polka to the top of the American charts.
</P>
<P>
   Today's stars _ particularly Martin and Anthony _ appeal to both
Latin and American audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the shows, Marc Anthony sings salsa, too,'' says Sammy
Zamarron, program director of local Latin radio stations WLBA-AM,
WAOS-AM and WXEM-AM. ``He caters to both markets and gets the best
of both worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   The Latin American market has been good to these performers, and
they're not about to forsake it for U.S. sales. The increase in the
Hispanic population _ locally and nationally _ makes that a good
strategy. The U.S. Census Bureau recently forecast that Hispanics
will replace African-Americans as the nation's largest ethnic
minority group within five years; they already outnumber blacks in
21 states.
</P>
<P>
   CNN.com reported in February that American retailers spent more
than $291 million in 1999 for albums and videos by Latin artists _
an 11 percent increase from the year before and also the fifth
straight year that sales of Latin artists have risen.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are seeing that there is a growing market,
that Hispanics do spend money,'' says Zamarron. Then he laughs.
``And they have a good beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Marc Anthony
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Sunday. $30-$38. Sold out. The Tabernacle, 152 Luckie St.
N.W. 404-659-9022.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Harrison writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
