<SLUG> BC-BRONCO-VERDICT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JURY AWARDS $26 MILLION FOR MAN HURT IN ROLLOVER CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PETER HARTLAUB  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A jury has awarded a San Francisco insurance
executive and his wife more than $26 million after his Ford Bronco
II rolled over and left him a quadriplegic.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the Ford Motor Company said they would ask a judge
to reduce or throw out the award, and may appeal the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   If the verdict stands, lawyers for Richard and Dana Raimondi say
it may be one of the largest against the automaker in Bronco
rollover cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a horrible, horrible injury and no amount of money can
make up for that,'' said Paul D. Nelson, one of the Raimondis'
attorneys. ``I think the jury did its best to be fair and the
Raimondis are happy to have the process finished.''
</P>
<P>
   The Alameda County Superior Court jury awarded Richard Raimondi,
57, almost $39 million in compensatory damages. Dana Raimondi, who
was not in the car, was awarded $13 million.
</P>
<P>
   But the jury, which heard the case in Hayward, Calif., also
found that Richard Raimondi was 50 percent responsible for his own
injuries. It was unclear whether the ruling will effect Dana
Raimondi's award.
</P>
<P>
   The jury did not award punitive damages in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Platt, a lawyer representing Ford, maintained that driver
error caused the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think there's any evidence that the vehicle caused
the rollover,'' Platt said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was filed after a 1996 accident on Interstate 880 in
Fremont. Raimondi, who had just bought the 1988 Bronco II, swerved
to avoid an object in the road.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting the concrete center divider and another car, the
Bronco rolled over three times, lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get in that kind of situation, virtually any vehicle
will roll over,'' Platt said.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence showed that the Bronco II is the most dangerous
sports utility vehicle, certainly in modern times,'' Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Raimondi uses a ventilator to help him breathe. Nelson said his
medical expenses prior to trial exceeded $2.6 million and are
expected to total more than $14 million over his lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   The jury of six men and six women reached a decision Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ford built more than 700,000 Bronco IIs from 1973 to 1990. The
model was replaced by the Explorer. Lawyers for the plaintiff claim
the narrow wheelbase and high center of gravity make the vehicle
susceptible to rollovers.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has settled more than 650 rollover claims involving the
Bronco II, Nelson said. He said about a dozen have gone to trial,
where Platt said most plaintiffs have lost.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a Missouri jury awarded $295 million to the families
of a couple and their son who were killed in a rollover of a 1978
Bronco.
</P>
</TEXT>
