<HEADER>
A8915 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-GORE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      03-16 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`INVENTING AL GORE': TOTING THE MERIT BADGES   OF A BOY SCOUT
CANDIDATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In outline at least the Al Gore who emerges from Bill Turque's
thoughtful new biography will be familiar to anyone who has
followed print and television coverage of his vice presidency and
the opening rounds of the 2000 campaign: a cautious politician who
frequently seems programmed, despite labored efforts to retool his
image with a ``game-show host wardrobe'' and a high-decibel
congeniality; an often awkward man whose Boy Scout persona belies a
slashing braggadocio and a Clintonesque taste for double-talk and
self-promotion.
</P>
<P>
   What Turque, a Washington correspondent for Newsweek, has done
in ``Inventing Al Gore'' is to amplify this portrait of the vice
president with lots of details and a carefully considered appraisal
of his career. There isn't much that's actually new in this book,
save the claim of two former friends that Gore was an
``enthusiastic recreational user'' of marijuana through the early
1970s, which was already cited in Newsweek's recent excerpt from
this book.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part Turque simply focuses on contradictions and
flip-flops in Gore's record and reviews his continuing efforts ``to
convince the world, and perhaps himself, that he was his own man,''
that he has emerged, at long last, from the shadows of his father,
Sen. Albert Gore of Tennessee, and more recently, Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Groomed since childhood to be a politician on the national
stage, Gore early on developed a careful, reflexive style. That
operating style, Turque observes, has ``remained largely intact for
nearly 25 years,'' from his days in the House of Representatives
and the Senate through his current tenure as vice president: ``a
relentless work ethic; tactical caution; passionate advocacy of
worthy but low-risk issues; and a willingness to revise, or simply
muddy up, politically inconvenient positions.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's zigzagging on issues is a recurrent theme in Turque's
biography, a book that, despite its judicious tone, draws an often
damning picture of the vice president as a hypocrite, driven by a
curious mixture of duty, loyalty and cold political calculus. This
is a man, Turque writes, who believed the Vietnam War was wrong but
enlisted in 1969 to protect his father's political career and
guarantee his own viability within the system. This is a man who
believed that Bill Clinton's behavior in the Monica Lewinsky affair
was indefensible but who nonetheless took up the role of
cheerleader, hailing his boss as one of our greatest presidents in
history.
</P>
<P>
   In his first race for Congress in 1976, Turque writes, Gore ran
``a campaign carefully trimmed of the dissident liberalism'' that
had ended his father's career, reinventing himself ``as a
conservative on several hot-button issues.'' He opposed additional
gun registration laws and declared shortly before primary day that
he did not ``believe a woman's freedom to live her own life, in all
cases, outweighs the fetus' right to life.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoing Bill Bradley's suggestion that the vice president has
not always come clean about the evolution of his views, Turque
writes that Gore's ``turnabout on abortion remains the most
dramatic shift of position in his career.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore declared during this year's New Hampshire primary
that he had ``always supported a woman's right to choose,'' Turque
points out that he had once been ``a reliable `pro-life' vote in
the House'' with ``an 84 percent rating from the National Right to
Life Committee'': he supported a version of the Hyde Amendment,
which barred federal assistance in ending pregnancies that resulted
from rape or incest; and in 1980 he voted to prohibit women
employed by the federal government from choosing health insurance
that covered abortion under any circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   An element of hypocrisy has informed Gore's stands on other
issues as well, says Turque. He observes that Gore continued ``to
take contributions from cigarette manufacturers and grew tobacco''
on his Tennessee farm for seven years after his beloved sister,
Nancy, died of lung cancer, though he would later memorialize her
at the 1996 Democratic convention as a victim of the cigarette
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Turque also contends that for all Gore's passionate evangelism
about the environment he has demonstrated ``a pattern of passivity
and timidity on environmental policy'' as vice president,
relegating the beliefs he laid out in his book ``Earth in the
Balance'' ``to a separate intellectual account, above and apart
from his political life.''
</P>
<P>
   On the matter of Gore's involvement in 1996 campaign finance
scandals, Turque rehashes other reporters' findings but comes up
with little new evidence, writing simply that the vice president's
``usually circumspect instincts had been flattened by the money
hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's eagerness to become the Democrats' ``solicitor in
chief,'' he suggests, stemmed in part from memories of watching his
father go down to defeat after being badly outspent in his last
Senate campaign, in part from being ``a creature of Washington''
with an inner circle ``dominated by lawyers and lobbyists immersed
in the city's money-and-influence culture.''
</P>
<P>
   So what sort of president would Al Gore make? On this question
Turque, like his subject, is cautiously fuzzy. He writes that two
themes would probably surface in a possible Gore administration:
``faith in the blessings of science and technology'' and a
commitment to civil rights. He points out that as vice president
Gore was often quicker than Bill Clinton ``to favor military force
as an option,'' and that under his stewardship, the ``Reinventing
Government'' initiative made some significant reforms but also
appeased interest groups and deferred tough questions.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly his style would differ significantly from Clinton's.
Turque observes that where Clinton ``was famously malleable,
constantly assimilating opposing views, appeasing political
enemies, and shifting positions,'' Gore tends to be more combative.
On the one hand, this means ``he brings a quality of directness''
to negotiations; on the other, it means he tends to ``lecture and
browbeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Turque quotes one former State Department official as saying:
``I think Gore believes you can shame other people into doing
things. With Gore, it's more `I know better.' Clinton, for all his
115,000 faults, saying `I know better' is not one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `INVENTING AL GORE' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Biography &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Bill Turque &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 448 pages. Houghton Mifflin. $25.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
