<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8916 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FINBAR-FILM-REVIEW-NY     03-16 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINBAR-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE DISAPPEARANCE OF FINBAR': A TEENAGER   VANISHES, AND THAT'S
JUST THE START 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among the prerequisites for enjoyment of ``The Disappearance of
Finbar'' is a taste for the shaggy dog story.
</P>
<P>
   In telling the tale of the consequences of a feckless Irish
teen-ager's disappearance, this English-Irish-Swedish
co-production, directed and co-written by Sue Clayton, wanders from
the slums of Dublin to the tidiness of Stockholm to the pale glory
of the Arctic Circle.
</P>
<P>
   It travels a long way. Much of the trip is intriguing. Some of
it is funny. Some of it splendidly scenic. But neat resolution is
not to be found at the end of the road.
</P>
<P>
   Acted by an appealing cast, enlivened with well-chosen and
varied music and filmed with bleak beauty by the cinematographer
Eduardo Serra, ``The Disappearance of Finbar,'' which opens Friday
in New York, is propelled by the puzzle it poses at its outset:
what has become of Finbar Flynn (played by Jonathan Rhys Meyers),
the hopeless young loser last seen by his worried friends late one
night as he bounced a soccer ball along the narrow edge of an
overpass above a busy highway? Is he dead or alive?
</P>
<P>
   Although the mystery of Finbar's fate and the geography of his
pursuit by his best friend, Danny Quinn (Luke Griffin), exercise a
beguiling magnetism, neither of the principal characters proves
sufficiently complex to evoke a profound emotional response.
</P>
<P>
   But Fanny Risberg as Abbi, the abandoned beauty living with her
musical-loving grandmother, Johanna (Sif Ruud), in Lappland, is
drawn and realized with a depth that makes her pain and longing
palpable.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Clayton's film, written with Dermot Bolger and
adapted from Carl Lombard's novel ``The Disappearance of Rory
Brophy,'' makes the most of its riddle, spices its travels with
deft humor that includes a running joke about the origins of the
tango and introduces some striking characters, from musicians in an
Irish cowboy band to an addled Irish grandpa with his own tale of a
disappearance to a Chinese couple in a Stockholm apartment and to
the hoary, menacing denizens of a bar in the frozen north.
</P>
<P>
   As for Finbar himself, he is at the pinnacle of his young life
when first encountered. A promising soccer player, he is off to try
out for a team in Zurich with the cheers of his neighbors in his
desolate, littered public housing development ringing in his ears.
</P>
<P>
   He is back soon enough, unable to take the pressure. ``You'll
never get out of this hole,'' his angry father tells him.
</P>
<P>
   Even Finbar knows the prospects are unlikely. Embittered by his
vision of his future and indifferent to his education, he has taxed
the patience of his schoolteacher to the point where she calls him
a ``self-opinionated intellectual pygmy.'' And he has pronounced
himself bored with the sexual favors of Katie (Lorraine
Pilkington), the girl Danny adores.
</P>
<P>
   For three years after the night of Finbar's disappearance, there
is no word of him. Danny is traumatized and angry at the suffering
Finbar has caused. The community is anguished. Roche, the police
detective assigned to the case, remains patient, although Finbar's
mother is devastated and Danny's mother worries that her son might
also vanish.
</P>
<P>
   Finbar Flynn has become part of lore and one night, after a
ballad about him makes its way to video, Danny receives a mocking
call from his old friend, who says he is in Stockholm.
</P>
<P>
   By the next day, Danny, too, has vanished from his home, bound
for a confrontation with his old friend. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE DISAPPEARANCE OF FINBAR' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Sue Clayton; written by Dermot Bolger and Clayton
and adapted from Carl Lombard's novel ``The Disappearance of Rory
Brophy''; director of photography, Eduardo Serra; edited by J.
Patrick Duffner; music by Davy Spillane; produced by Bertil Ohlsson
and Martin Bruce-Clayton; released by Film 4 International. Running
time: 103 minutes.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Luke Griffin (Danny Quinn), Jonathan Rhys Meyers (Finbar
Flynn), Fanny Risberg (Abbi), Sif Ruud (Johanna), Lorraine
Pilkington (Katie), Sean Lawlor (Michael Flynn), Jake Williams
(Young Finbar) and Robert Hickey (Young Danny). &QL;
</P>
