<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8918 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-EVERYDAY-ETHICS-COLUM     03-16 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERYDAY-ETHICS-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ADV19-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV19 
 EVERYDAY ETHICS
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Refiling to replace dropped words in 2nd and 3rd paragraphs
of first answer.)
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by EVERYDAY ETHICS clients. Nonsubscribers can
use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, see end of text. 
 By RANDY COHEN 
 c.2000 Randy Cohen 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Idle Worshiper
</P>
<P>
   Q. My elderly father-in-law, who is handicapped, has always been
active in his synagogue. The new rabbi, in an effort to more
strictly interpret religious law regarding vehicular travel on the
Sabbath, has closed the handicapped parking area so worshipers will
not drive. This prevents many disabled congregants from attending
activities. How do you balance access for the handicapped with
religious edicts?
</P>
<P>
   _ Linda Watts Broun, Washington
</P>
<P>
   A. For the strictly Orthodox, it is better not to go to the
synagogue at all than to drive on the Sabbath, and so your
father-in-law seems stuck in an intractable situation. He may,
however, have more options than you realize.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes there are extenuating circumstances,'' says Rabbi
Samuel Intrator of the Carlebach Shul, an Orthodox congregation in
New York. ``He should discuss it with his rabbi and see if a
dispensation could be found, respectful to the community and his
special needs. For instance, perhaps a non-Jew might drive him to
the synagogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Your father-in-law's rabbi is obviously not trying to
discriminate against the disabled. No one is compelled to obey
Jewish law, and attendance at synagogue is voluntary. Your
father-in-law chooses compliance, and attendance. In that sense he
is not a victim of injustice.
</P>
<P>
   However, while the intent of the parking policy is not
discriminatory, its effect is. And even when membership and
obedience are voluntary, no group is exempt from ethical scrutiny.
Some Boy Scouts object to their organization's exclusion of
homosexual Scoutmasters. Members of many religions criticize their
faith's refusal to ordain women; i.e., to treat all congregants
equally. A precept's being based on religious belief does not give
it special ethical status.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, it is possible to embrace a body of beliefs but
reject a particular edict. Such conflicts can lead people to reform
an organization, secular or sacred. Religious practice is not
immutable; all faiths have altered over the centuries. Rabbi David
Lincoln of the Park Avenue Synagogue, a Conservative congregation,
offers this advice: ``Conservative Judaism is the answer _ a
traditional service and plenty of parking.''
</P>
<P>
   However, your father-in-law does not seem inclined to leave his
congregation. And you do not seem to have a principled objection
based on rights for the disabled as much as a desire simply to get
him to shul. I'd look for ways to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Recently I had a phone message from a reference-checking firm
about a colleague in another department. He is a first-class
producer, and my company will suffer a real loss if he leaves. On
the other hand, I have nothing but respect for him and would like
to be of service. Should I return the call and give this person the
high reference he deserves? Or should I place my employer's
interests first and not return the call.
</P>
<P>
   _ Anonymous, Cleveland, Ohio
</P>
<P>
   A. You should give your co-worker the praise he deserves: this
is simply a matter of honesty. With luck, he won't leave your
company. He may not be offered the job. And even if it's offered,
he may decline it, particularly if his current boss gives him
enough of a raise to keep him where he is.
</P>
<P>
   But in any case, that's not your call. Your colleague is not an
indentured servant; he's entitled to change jobs. And I suspect
you'd feel dreadful if you thwarted him.
</P>
<P>
   One last guideline - when evaluating ways of keeping your
co-worker in place, a tactic is probably unethical if it involves
epoxy or similar industrial adhesives.
</P>
<P>
   Do you have ethical questions that you need answered? Send them
to ethicist &LR; nytimes.com, or Everyday Ethics, New York Times
Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St., 14th floor, New York, N.Y. 10168.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on EVERYDAY
ETHICS and other features. &QL;
</P>
