<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8919 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER17-COX     03-16 1356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Proof of the pudding?
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore, in Maryland addressing an organization that lobbies for
investment in low-income neighborhoods and for improved credit for
such residents, criticized George W. Bush's tax cut plan Thursday
as ``economic snake oil'' that would imperil prosperity, take money
from social services and perhaps put the government back deep in
debt. Gore noted that Congress refused a day earlier to act on a
budget plan similar to Bush's proposal for across-the-board tax
cuts. ``Now, if it is so risky that even the group that Newt
Gingrich ushered into the Congress will not vote for it, you know
it is risky indeed,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   1996 FUND-RAISING BACK TO HAUNT
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department, with a new prosecutor, Robert Conrad,
running the campaign finance task force, is moving to bring
money-laundering charges against some of the remaining defendants
in the 1996 fund-raising scandal, the Wall Street Journal reported
Thursday. The effort could complicate the campaigns of Al Gore and
Hillary Clinton. Money-laundering charges could be lodged against
Thai-born businesswoman Pauline Kanchanalak and her sister-in-law,
Duangnet ``Georgie'' Kronenberg, who were indicted in 1998 on
charges of funneling more than $600,000 to the Democratic Party
from foreign sources.
</P>
<P>
   ARMS LENGTH AFTER HAND-TO-HAND FIGHTING
</P>
<P>
   There won't be a quick shake-and-make-up between John McCain and
George W. Bush. McCain's advisers have taken offense at a New York
Times interview in which Bush refused to reach out to McCain. The
interview was viewed by the McCain staff as a sign that Bush has no
intention of making concessions to his former GOP rival. They said
it also makes an endorsement of Bush less likely, although McCain
would eventually be willing to help Bush if he shows respect for
McCain and his campaign-finance cause, advisers said.
</P>
<P>
   DIFFERENT AREAS, DIFFERENT THEMES
</P>
<P>
   Abandoning talk of gun control, Al Gore touted himself as a
friend of unions, families and working class Americans at a
suburban Pittsburgh high school _ and criticized George W. Bush.
But earlier in Philadelphia, on the other side of the Pennsylvania,
he talked about his proposals for gun control _ a theme not
discussed later in the more conservative western part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   SO MUCH FOR DIVERSITY
</P>
<P>
   The Education Department has acknowledged that a former
third-grade teacher from Iowa invited to an Education Department
seminar on promoting diversity described George W. Bush and Florida
Gov. Jeb Bush as racists. Jane Elliot, who also is an author, was
at the department March 8 to deliver a presentation on how children
become prejudiced. Elliot also advised employees attending the
seminar not to vote for Republicans. ``The comments were
spontaneous and unanticipated,'' said department spokeswoman Erica
Lipping. Elliott received about $7,500 for participating in the
department's speaker's series on diversity.
</P>
<P>
   JESSE SHOULDN'T HOLD HIS BREATH
</P>
<P>
   Neither Al Gore nor George W. Bush should expect Jesse Ventura's
endorsement without paying a price, the Minnesota governor said. To
win him over, a candidate would ``have to sever from being a
Republican or Democrat,'' Ventura said on MSNBC. The former
wrestler predicted that John McCain would be elected president if
he ran as an independent.
</P>
<P>
   IT DOESN'T TAKE VERY LONG SOMETIMES
</P>
<P>
   John McCain's campaign communications director says his
candidate made ``three major mistakes'' at the end. Dan Schnur,
speaking at Harvard, said the first mistake was to compare George
W. Bush to President Clinton in ads in South Carolina. The second
mistake was the phone calls to Catholic voters in Michigan, which
``allowed Bush to turn questions about (Bob Jones University) from
himself to our own campaign tactics. ... Even worse, we lied about
it, too. ... It really hurt our credibility.'' The last major
mistake was McCain's criticism of Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell.
``For 10 months, we ran as near a perfect campaign as we could have
. . . but in seven days we melted down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   BOB JONES BACK TO BASICS
</P>
<P>
   Bob Jones University President Bob Jones III has reposted
statements against Catholics and Mormons on the fundamentalist
school's Web site. Jones said he wanted to show nothing had changed
about his views on Catholicism after it was reported earlier this
week that the message in the ``President's Corner'' no longer
referred to Catholicism and Mormonism as cults. The message was
cited repeatedly after George W. Bush was criticized for speaking
on campus Feb. 2.
</P>
<P>
   FIRING BACK AT THE NRA
</P>
<P>
   A day after wrapping up the Republican presidential nomination,
George W. Bush distanced himself from the National Rifle
Association, saying it went too far in its recent attacks on
President Clinton. Seeking a middle ground on gun control, Bush
disagreed with the NRA's recent assertion that Clinton accepts gun
violence because he wants to use it as a political issue. ``I
thought they were wrong in saying the president condones killing,''
Bush told Knight Ridder Newspapers in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   LINCOLN NEVER SLEPT THERE, DID HE?
</P>
<P>
   Trying to allay a growing controversy, campaign officials for
George W. Bush released a list of all of his overnight guests at
the Texas Governor's Mansion. Bush's list showed the mansion has
been opened to relatives, longtime friends and Republican
officials, not fund-raisers. But the watchdog Center for Public
Integrity released a separate study saying that 60 of the 131
guests had contributed or raised more than $2.2 million for Bush's
presidential campaign. Douglas Hattaway, a spokesman for Al Gore,
said Bush has ``a lot of explaining to do about his behavior in his
presidential campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW KENNEDY CHALLENGER POPS UP
</P>
<P>
   Republican Jack E. Robinson III, 39, a former Eastern Airlines
executive now running a cellular phone company, will run this fall
for the seat that Sen. Ted Kennedy (D-Mass.) has held for 37 years,
said Plymouth County District Attorney Michael Sullivan, who is
bowing out after a six-month exploratory campaign. The Boston
Herald reported that an announcement by Robinson is imminent.
</P>
<P>
   `TERM LIMITS' GREAT WHEN YOU'RE NOT IN OFFICE
</P>
<P>
   A conservative radio show host, Richard Clear, 51, is
challenging Rep. George Nethercutt (R-Wash.) for the Republican
nomination, mainly because of the congressman's about-face on term
limits. Nethercutt is seeking a fourth two-year term despite a
pledge in 1994 to serve only six years. Nethercutt became a hero of
the term-limits movement when he ousted 15-term Democratic
incumbent and then-House Speaker Tom Foley in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   KEEP THOSE WALKING SHOES HANDY
</P>
<P>
   No one can recall the last time a first lady marched in one of
New York's parades, but this first lady is turning up with the
regularity of a baton-twirler. Two weeks ago, Hillary Clinton
marched in an early St. Patrick's Day parade in Queens. Today she
is scheduled to walk up Fifth Avenue in the main St. Patrick's Day
extravaganza. She also plans to take part in the Million Mom March,
an anti-gun event on Mother's Day, as well as the Gay Pride parade
in June.
</P>
<P>
   PARTY CORES: THEY'RE DEPENDABLE _ AND THEY VOTE
</P>
<P>
   The voters who turned out to help George W. Bush clinch the GOP
presidential nomination were mostly Protestant or evangelicals,
white, Republican and over age 50. For Al Gore, they were more
likely to be women, black, Catholic and also middle-aged. They are
the most dependable voters, those who go the polls under any
circumstance to back their candidates even, as was the case
Tuesday, when the race was pretty much already decided.
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news services
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
