<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8921 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-RENO-FUNDRAISING-HNS &LR;      03-16 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-FUNDRAISING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RENO SAYS SHE IS RELUCTANT TO RELEASE FUNDRAISING MEMO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno, responding to
accusations she is covering up White House campaign fund-raising
violations, said Thursday that she probably won't make public the
recommendations of her top advisers on the case.
</P>
<P>
   One of those advisers, Charles LaBella, who headed the Justice
Department's campaign fundraising task force, reportedly accused
his superiors in a 1998 memo of going through legal ``contortions''
to avoid coming to the conclusion that Reno should seek an
independent investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at her weekly news conference, Reno said releasing the
LaBella memo would ``hamper'' future attorney generals by making
department lawyers wary of giving fully ``candid'' advice because
of fears their opinions would be made public.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some wonderful lawyers in this department who I want
to make sure will continue to give their best advice without the
thought that it will be spread all over, everywhere,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., chair of the House Government Reform
Committee, has subpoenaed the LaBella memo and another memo written
by FBI Director Louis Freeh, which called for an independent
counsel to investigate White House fund-raising activities during
the 1996 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter that accompanied his subpoena, Burton accused the
attorney general of ``crippling'' his investigation into the
matter.``You tried to keep the committee from learning how you had
mishandled the investigation,'' he wrote. Reno promised to ``work
with Congress in every way possible,'' but declined to say if she
would allow Burton to see the memos.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are reviewing the subpoena carefully now,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Los Angeles Times quoted the LaBella memo as
saying Justice Department officials used ``gamesmanship'' and legal
``contortions'' to avoid an independent inquiry into White House
fund-raising matters.
</P>
<P>
   In the memo, LaBella reportedly recommends that Reno appoint an
independent counsel, saying the probe needed to look at ``the
entire landscape'' of campaign finance practices, ``conjured up by
sophisticated political operatives to circumvent'' election finance
laws during President Clinton's re-election campaign.The newspaper
said the LaBella memo accused top Justice Department officials of
using ``intellectually dishonest'' double standards by endorsing
independent counsels to investigate Cabinet-level officials _ while
opposing the appointment of counsels to investigate Clinton, Vice
President Al Gore, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and former
White House aide Harold Ickes. Ickes is a top adviser to Mrs.
Clinton's Senate campaign in New York. Although not commenting on
specific charges in the memo, Reno downplayed LaBella's strong
language and his questioning of the motives of her top aides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want (Justice Department) lawyers to be able to debate, to
discuss, to be able to use, if they so choose, language that they
think might make their argument more effective,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, a federal jury convicted Maria Hsia, a
longtime political Gore fundraiser, on five felony counts for her
role in arranging more than $100,000 in illegal donations to the
Democratic Party and its candidates in 1996. Of that amount,
$55,000 was contributed to the Democratic National Committee in
connection with the vice president's much-criticized visit to a
Buddhist temple in the Los Angeles area. The event, at the Hsi Lai
Temple in Hacienda Heights, has shadowed Gore throughout the
current political season, with a variety of his opponents using it
to remind voters of the Clinton-Gore campaign's fund-raising
embarrassments. The verdict made Hsia, an immigration counselor
from Los Angeles, the major catch thus far in the Justice
Department's investigation of campaign finance abuses. &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
