A8926 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-NIRELAND-BOMB-415&AMP;ADD     03-16 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-BOMB-415&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPLOSIVES LINKED TO PARAMILITARY GROUPS SEIZED NEAR BELFAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The Ulster police arrested three men and seized 500
pounds of explosives that were being transported to Belfast on
Wednesday night after being tipped off to bomb plots organized by
paramilitary groups opposed to the Northern Ireland peace
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The seizure took place when two cars under surveillance were
stopped by Royal Ulster Constabulary officers on a highway eight
miles outside Belfast. The men were held for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking as police officers put plastic bags of bomb-making
materials on display at a West Belfast police station Thursday,
Chief Inspector Ken Henning declined to identify the group the
arrested men were thought to belong to but said, ``We believe the
people responsible are connected to dissident republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   In Northern Ireland, republicans are those, largely from the
Catholic minority, who wish to see the British province linked more
closely with Ireland. The dominant republican paramilitary force,
the Irish Republican Army, is observing a ceasefire, but splinter
republican groups at odds with this stance have pledged to bring
down the peace accord signed in April 1998. One of them, called the
Real IRA, blew up the center of the town of Omagh in August 1998,
killing 29 people in the worst single case of violence in the past
three decades of sectarian conflict, which have caused more than
3,600 deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The intercepted bomb plot was seen as an effort to disrupt
faltering negotiations at a moment when representatives of the
IRA's political wing, Sinn Fein, and all the other principals in
the effort to end the bloodshed in Northern Ireland are meeting in
Washington on the fringes of the St. Patrick's Day celebrations at
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Progress halted when the power-sharing home rule government that
is the centerpiece of the peace settlement was suspended by London
on Feb. 11 after the IRA failed to make moves to start disarming.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting vacuum has left Ulster in an increasingly volatile
state, with so-called punishment beatings by both Protestant and
Catholic paramilitary groups and threats of violence by renegade
guerrilla groups on the rise. The police on both sides of the
border between Ireland and Northern Ireland have had success in
recent months confiscating chemicals and timing devices used in
bombs, but several plots have eluded the security forces.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Last month a hotel in Irvinestown in County Fermanagh was badly
damaged in a fire-bomb attack, a bomb partly exploded close to
sleeping quarters in the British army base at Ballykelly in County
Derry and a primed rocket launcher was found on the perimeter of
another base in Dungannon in County Tyrone. None of the attacks
caused injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the seizures Wednesday night, the head of the Royal
Ulster Constabulary, Sir Ronnie Flanagan, went ahead Thursday with
an announcement that 500 British soldiers are being withdrawn from
the province because of improving security. The reduction of
British forces in Northern Ireland has been cited by Ireland, which
with Britain is a co-sponsor of the peace talks, as an important
confidence-building measure in the effort to resume progress in the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The battalion going home is from Belfast, where there has been
no military patrolling since 1998. When they return to England next
month, troop strength in Northern Ireland will dip below 14,000,
down from 30,000 at the height of ``the troubles'' in the 1970s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1724EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8928 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-GHOSTDOG-TEX     03-16 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GHOSTDOG-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS `DOG' IS A KILLER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With so few original ideas out there, some directors are
deciding that the best film route is one that crosses paths with
many genres. The Wachowski brothers did it with ``The Matrix,''
blending science fiction, martial arts and action inspired by Hong
Kong films; David O. Russell did it with ``Three Kings,'' merging
``The Treasure of Sierra Madre,'' ``Gunga Din'' and ``MASH'' and
tossing them into a Persian Gulf War story.
</P>
<P>
   Now Jim Jarmusch is doing it with ``Ghost Dog: The Way of the
Samurai,'' in which Jarmusch appears to be after the all-time
cinematic cross-pollination. ``Ghost Dog'' lifts from Japanese
literature, ``Sopranos''-style gangster dramas, spaghetti westerns,
hip-hop and urban dramas, French films, classic cartoons and The
Simpsons' 'toon-within-a-'toon, ``Itchy &AMP; Scratchy.'' Jarmusch
sprinkles it with his typically quirky characters and laid-back
rhythms; it's not for everyone _ which with an oddball like
Jarmusch is like saying that naked motorcycle riding isn't for
everyone _ but it's unusually entertaining for those who are game.
</P>
<P>
   Forest Whitaker, heavy-lidded and tight-lipped, plays Ghost Dog,
a samurai-inspired contract killer who prefers solitude, living on
a rooftop with his coop of carrier pigeons. When Ghost Dog was
younger, a mobster (John Tormey) saved his life, so Ghost Dog
pledges eternal loyalty to him; that becomes trouble when the
mobster asks the hit man to execute a ``made man,'' considered an
untouchable mob figure. Ghost Dog does the deal, and brings down
the wrath of many odd _ and none-too-bright _ mob types.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, ``Ghost Dog'' is a standard revenge story, but
Jarmusch doesn't treat it like one. He loads the movie with quotes
from ``Hagakure: The Book of the Samurai'' and gives Ghost Dog some
benevolent friends in a French-speaking ice-cream man (Isaach de
Bankole) and a young girl (Camille Winbush) who's trying to
understand the killer's ways.
</P>
<P>
   Jarmusch puts the emphasis on humor and mood, with a big help
from The RZA's atmospheric hip-hop soundtrack. Pacing has never
been Jarmusch's strength, but ``Ghost Dog'' moves quickly, although
it does pile on a few too many climaxes. But Jarmusch's ability to
toss all these ingredients into his cultural stew without making
mush is admirable; some folks won't like the taste, but it goes
down easy if you're in the right mood.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Ghost Dog: The Way of the Samurai''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Jim Jarmusch
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Forest Whitaker, John Tormey
</P>
<P>
   Length: 114 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ violence and profanity
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1726EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8929 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-FINALDESTINATION     03-16 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-FINALDESTINATION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THIS A FINAL ANSWER IN TEEN-GORE GENRE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK, you gotta admit that even for adamant horror fans,
``Scream'' and its imitative ilk of pretty-teens-in-peril pictures
are getting kind of tired. With ``I Know What You Did Last Summer''
and ``Urban Legend'' sequels waiting in the shadows along with
Keenen Ivory Wayans' parody of the subgenre, ``Scary Movie,'' due
in theaters soon, there aren't a whole lot of original spins left
on gutting teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, have any of the cast members from Fox and The WB's teen
shows not starred in one of these things yet?
</P>
<P>
   Not that that slowed down the producers of ``Final
Destination,'' who, to their credit, manage to wring out a few
drops of originality for their addition to the teen body-count
equation.
</P>
<P>
   You have writer/director James Wong and writer/producer Glen
Morgan to thank for that. If those names sound familiar, it's
because you recognize them from some of the best episodes of Fox's
``The X-Files,'' along with ``Millennium, Space: Above and Beyond''
and NBC's new ``The Others.''
</P>
<P>
   Wong and Morgan actually scare up quite a few surprises, even if
the territory is all too familiar. The story is worthy of the
original ``Twilight Zone'' series with Devon Sawa (''Idle Hands'')
as Alex, a nervous high schooler preparing for an overseas field
trip. When he dreams of the plane exploding during takeoff, his
subsequent hysterics get him and several of his friends ousted from
the flight. But when the jet actually does go up in a fireball,
everyone suspects that he may have had a hand in the accident.
</P>
<P>
   The real trouble is that Alex and his pals were supposed to have
died on the flight, and when the survivors start dropping dead,
most under unusual circumstances, it appears as if Death is out to
complete its design, unless Alex can unravel its pattern.
</P>
<P>
   The characters are stock: Ali Larter (''Varsity Blues'') is
Alex's loner love interest; Kerr Smith (''Dawson's Creek'') is the
angry jock who resents his savior; Chad E. Donella (''Disturbing
Behavior,'' ``The X-Files'') is Alex's lecherous best friend, and
Tony Todd (''Candyman'') is the spooky undertaker.
</P>
<P>
   But the film's most creative attributes are the ways it
dispatches its stars; some go in a bizarre Mousetrap series of
actions that come off like a supernatural salute to Rube Goldberg,
while others go in ways so shocking and quick, it left preview
audiences gasping.
</P>
<P>
   It's better than you think, but not as good as you hope.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Final Destination''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Devon Sawa, Ali Larter, Kerr Smith
</P>
<P>
   Director: James Wong
</P>
<P>
   Length: 93 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ graphic violence, profanity and adult subject matter
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp reviews films for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1726EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8930 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-ART-N     03-16 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUES: TWO WEEKS WHEN EAST MEETS WEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``None of us expected the Asian fair to be the huge
success it's been since Day 1,'' said Khalil Rizk, director of the
Chinese Porcelain Co. in Manhattan. He was one of the instigators
of New York's International Asian Art Fair, which opens on Thursday
night and runs through March 29 at the Seventh Regiment Armory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came up with the idea in 1994 because we were concerned
that Asian art was losing its appeal in America,'' Rizk said.
``Everything we sold went abroad. We were all asking ourselves how
we could renew interest in Asian art and attract young new
collectors.''
</P>
<P>
   He met with Brian and Anna Houghton, the English couple who
organize many art fairs in New York. ``The idea was to schedule a
fair at the same time as the Asian auctions,'' Houghton said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Ellsworth, the acknowledged dean of New York's Asian art
dealers, said, ``Three dealers made it possible.'' He was too
modest to say that he was one of the three, but once he signed on,
the Houghtons knew they could produce a fair.
</P>
<P>
   This year the fair has 61 dealers from eight countries,
including China. Houghton said there will be more Japanese
antiques, early Chinese bronzes and antique textiles than in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's significant about the Asian art market is that it is
dominated by dealers, not auction houses,'' Rizk explained. ``At
the fair you see very little that has been at auction before.
That's why the museum interest is huge. Last year on opening night
80 curators were lined up with their trustees. When do you see
that? Whether you are a curator, a dealer or a collector, if you
are a serious participant in the Asian art market, you cannot
afford to miss the fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Rizk will exhibit a dramatic Chinese figure from the Northern Qi
period (A.D. 550 to 577). The unglazed pottery official is 55
inches tall and has a fierce expression on his face. He is a tomb
guardian, standing at attention, hands clasped over his chest.
</P>
<P>
   Ellsworth will show an eighth-century A.D. Tang dynasty silver
box made as a gift to the imperial Chinese household. He also has a
group of fourth-century B.C. bronze deer from China. Forming a
complete set of finial mounts for the canopy of a horse-drawn
carriage, they have huge ears that seem to be flopping as they
gallop.
</P>
<P>
   A London dealer, Linda Wrigglesworth, a new participant, is
showing an embroidered yellow satin emperor's dragon robe from the
18th century. Uragami Sokyu-Do of Tokyo is exhibiting 18th- and
19th-century Choson dynasty blue-and-white ware from Korea. M.D.
Flacks, one of the few dealers showing furniture, has a sublimely
simple late-17th-century huanghuali altar table from China. These
are only a few of the participants in Asian Art Week, a misnomer as
it is actually two weeks of auctions, parties, openings, shows and
fairs that attracts collectors from Asia and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   It starts Saturday with a loan exhibition, ``Treasures From
Ancient Beijing,'' at Christie's in Rockefeller Center. On Monday
Doyle's Asian art auction includes 20 paintings from the collection
of Anna C. Chennault. She is the widow of General Claire L.
Chennault, commander of the Flying Tigers, American volunteers who
flew audacious air raids against the Japanese in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Among the many shows at private galleries is one opening Monday
at J.J. Lally &AMP; Co. Oriental Art, 41 E. 57th St., Manhattan. This
show of ancient Chinese ceramics and tomb sculptures has neolithic
pots from 6000 B.C. that look amazingly modern. ``You must realize
this is before the appearance of figural materials,'' said Jim
Lally, the gallery owner, referring to a melon-shaped vessel
resting on three short pointed feet. ``It is one of the earliest
Chinese ceramics in America.''
</P>
<P>
   The oxidized red vessel has smooth sides and two lug handles
pierced with holes. ``It's very rare because it is so
sophisticated,'' he said. ``It is curious a potter would go to such
lengths for a storage vessel. Was it made for a specific function
or for status? We don't know. It's clearly more artful than is
necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   He has a neolithic pottery beaker that looks like a beer stein,
circa 4500 B.C. to 2500 B.C. It is white because it is made of
Kaolin clay. ``If it were fired at a higher temperature, it would
be porcelain,'' Lally said, pointing out the eggshell-thin sides.
``We don't know if it was meant to be used. It may have stood on an
altar to be appreciated by the gods.''
</P>
<P>
   Lally's show is timely. On Tuesday ``Dawn of the Yellow Earth''
opens at the China Institute in America in Manhattan. This
exhibition will include 63 ancient Chinese ceramics from 5000 B.C.
to 300 B.C.
</P>
<P>
   Lally also has several Chinese dancing female figures made about
200 B.C. The unpainted dancers were put in tombs to honor the
occupants. ``Each shows a frozen movement in a ritual dance,'' he
said. ``After death you would enter a mirror world with the same
laws of status and hierarchy you left behind. That's why you needed
an entire retinue.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuseppe Eskenazi, the London dealer, is showing at
PaceWildenstein, 32 East 57th Street, Manhattan, beginning on
Monday. Like Ellsworth he has ancient bronze fittings. One gilt
bronze pair includes birds and monkeys and dragons inlaid with
malachite and other stones.
</P>
<P>
   Another pair, lavishly inlaid with gold and silver, were made to
hold a crossbow on a chariot. Nicholas Grindley, another London
dealer is showing classical Chinese furniture at the Kate Ganz
Gallery, 25 E. 73rd St., Manhattan, from Wednesday to March 30. He
is selling a pair of spindle-back huanghuali chairs from the Kangsi
period (1662-1722) that are as modern in design as anything on
today's market.
</P>
<P>
   The Asian art auctions at Christie's and Sotheby's take place
all next week. The Asian decorative arts sale at Christie' East
opens on Monday. Sotheby's first sale, of Netsuke from the
collection of Raymond and Frances Bushell, is on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's sale of Indian and Southeast Asian art on Thursday is
particularly strong. Lot 46 is a Nepalese bronze group from the
13th century. It represents the Hindu god Shiva and his consort
Parvati, who is languidly leaning on him. The crowned Shiva has his
foot on back of a lion; Parvati holds a lotus flower. ``This is a
museum-quality bronze,'' said Carlton C. Rochell Jr., the
specialist in charge of the sale. ``There is almost an ethereal
quality to these heavenly beings, who are supposed to be divinely
beautiful.'' The estimate is $150,000 to $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   Lot 118, a monumental Gandharan gray schist torso of Buddha from
the third or fourth century A.D., is literally larger than life.
The figure clearly shows the influence of Hellenistic sculpture. It
is wearing a pleated robe draped across his body. The estimate is
$60,000 to $90,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Southeast Asian sculpture is very undervalued,'' Rochell said.
If the piece were from Greece, it would go for 10 times more. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
