<SLUG> BC-IVOR-OSCAR-NIGHT-PARTIES-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APRES-OSCAR: THE BEST OF THE OSCAR-NIGHT PARTIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Academy Awards
host Billy Crystal. 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    For the more than 3,000 members of the media covering the 72nd
annual Academy Awards on March 26, it isn't until the televised
show ends that the real work will begin.
 &HT;    The chronically long-running ceremonies will probably wind down
around 10 p.m. _ 1 a.m. on the East Coast _ and winners and losers
alike will pour out of Los Angeles' Shrine Auditorium and into the
Academy's invitations-only Governors Ball.
 &HT;    But then, after only fleeting appearances at the official
post-awards party, the rich, the famous and the
famous-for-the-moment will hustle off to the places where the real
action is _ the post-post-Oscar parties, where seeing and being
seen with the in crowd is, as they say in the local parlance, where
it's at.
 &HT;    And for valiant journalists who, like your reporter, have
covered Oscar for more than 20 years, that means trying to be in
six places at once.
 &HT;    In the good old days, the only party that counted was the
Governors Ball, which this year has moved from under canvas on a
parking lot to the Shrine's Exposition Hall, only steps away from
the Oscar venue.
 &HT;    Some 1,650 guests are expected to show up at this year's ball,
where they'll feast on offerings from superstar chef Wolfgang Puck
that include marinated lobster salad, roasted potatoes with caviar,
smoked salmon, roasted chicken breast and black truffles, washed
down with assorted wines and rounded off by Puck's gold-dusted
chocolate Oscar, only one of five desserts available.
 &HT;    But despite the preparations, the food and thousands of dollars
in decorations, the truth is that many of the big names wouldn't be
caught dead spending the entire evening at the Governors Ball. As
quickly as they can get their limos out of the parking lot, they'll
be off to the more prestigious party of their choice.
 &HT;    This year's two hottest parties are the exclusive bashes tossed
by Dreamworks, which hopes for a festive night built on ``American
Beauty'' and its eight nominations, and Miramax, which pits ``Cider
House Rules'' against ``American Beauty'' for the Best Picture
statuette, only one of the film's seven nominations.
 &HT;    The Dreamworks shindig will be at Spago's restaurant, while the
Weinsteins of Miramax will hold court at the Beverly Hills Hotel.
The success of these events will, of course, depend on the success
of their movies.
 &HT;    And, no, observers should not read anything into the fact that,
while Miramax's owner Walt Disney also has seven nominations for
``The Insider,'' the parent studio is not planning a private
celebratory affair on Oscar night.
 &HT;    This whole business of dueling parties began back in the 1980s,
when agent Irving ``Swifty'' Lazar took over Spago's and invited
his celebrity pals to a black-tie dinner sans traffic jams. Golden
statuettes lined the bar as guests hobnobbed with the winners, and
Swifty's became the place to be on Oscar night.
 &HT;    When Lazar died in 1993, so did his party. But others quickly
stepped into the breach, and the parties proliferated.
 &HT;    Not that everybody goes. Director Chuck Workman is a veteran of
the Hollywood party circuit, and won a 1987 Best Documentary Oscar
for ``Precious Images,'' but he won't be making the party rounds
after this year's ceremony.
 &HT;    His new film, ``A House on a Hill,'' opens later this year, but
Workman may be best know for his brilliant assemblages of movie
clips that highlight the Oscar show every year. Last year, for
example, he had top stars picking their favorite movie moments.
This year he'll salute Warren Beatty, recipient of this year's
Irving Thalberg Award, with a movie retrospective.
 &HT;    ``Most of the people who work on the Oscar telecast have
finished a 16-hour day and are Oscared out,'' Workman says. ``So
it's the Governors Ball and then home for me. But many of the
younger stars like to make the scene, and they have the stamina to
show up at two or three post-Oscar parties.''
 &HT;    And for those celebrities who have that energy _ and who don't
have a 5 a.m. makeup call on Monday _ this year offers more parties
than ever, once the final Oscar credits have rolled. There are at
least six post-awards bashes, with several providing fine cuisine,
drinks and giant television sets for those who didn't get invited
to the actual show.
 &HT;    In some cases John Q. Public can even buy tickets and rub elbows
with show-business royalty, although the tariff is pretty steep _
as much as $1,500 per person.
 &HT;    That top ticket applies at a West Hollywood restaurant where, in
collaboration with In Style magazine, Elton John will host his
eighth Oscar-night party as a benefit for his AIDS Foundation. Last
year's party raised a beefy $360,000 for the cause.
 &HT;    Guests can stick around after dinner for dancing and
entertainment, and hope to bump into Oscar nominees such as Toni
Collette, Jude Law, Kevin Spacey, Michael Clarke Duncan, Chloe
Sevigny, Hilary Swank and Annette Bening _ assuming that her fourth
baby hasn't chosen that night to enter the world.
 &HT;    Sharon Stone, Charlize Theron, Oscar host Billy Crystal and
Elizabeth Hurley are also due to put in appearances at the party,
which will offer guests chances to win a Lexus or luxury watches.
Those who can't be there can go online for live coverage at
EltonJohn.com, and even bid on some of the singer's personal
belongings being auctioned to benefit the charity.
 &HT;    If you've got a spare $1,500 and want to make the scene, call
(310) 276-5802.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, across town at the Beverly Hills Hotel, music agent
Norby Walters offers a less expensive affair _ priced at a mere
$750. His ninth annual Night of 100 Stars gala benefits Martin
Scorsese's Film Preservation Foundation.
 &HT;    Once the ceremonies end, Walters promises, a host of celebrities
will make their way thither, including Rip Torn, Cliff Robertson,
Rod Steiger, Tony Curtis and Lynn Redgrave. If you'd like to
mingle, call (310) 289-8660.
 &HT;    For the less well-heeled, there's a shindig sponsored by
Hollywood's Entertainment Museum at 7021 Hollywood Blvd. Called a
``Salute to the Academy Awards with a Taste of Hollywood,'' it will
benefit a counseling center for troubled youth.
 &HT;    The fun of this one is that guests can book a table for four on
the ``Cheers'' set or, for $1,500 for a table of eight, in the Star
Trek Alien Warship Room. The museum hopes to attract some 600
guests, including some celebrities, though as of yet they aren't
dropping any names.
 &HT;    Then there's the Hollywood Stock Exchange's second annual
Academy Awards party at the House of Blues on Sunset Boulevard. To
start with, they'll be cordoning off an entire block on Sunset,
before the party moves into the House of Blues later on, with
entertainment provided by Earth Wind and Fire.
 &HT;    At least 2,000 people are expected to gather, including
celebrities galore. Last year, Nicolas Cage, Patricia Arquette,
Gov. Jesse Ventura, Dan Aykroyd, Donna Dixon, Courteney Cox
Arquette and Drew Barrymore showed up.
 &HT;    ``Stars have obligations to go to their respective studio
parties _ and then they come to our one,'' says spokeswoman
Jennifer Meillios.
 &HT;    It's not open to the public, except via online participation at
www.hsx/O2k.com.
 &HT;    And finally, if you know a member of the Writer's Guild, perhaps
you can wangle an invitation to the guild's first-ever Oscar dinner
in Beverly Hills.
 &HT;    ``It's an eclectic evening from tuxes to jeans,'' a Guild
spokesperson notes, ``where you can cheer with your peers.''
 &HT;    Except, of course, for those who've been nominated. They'll be
spending the early evening somewhere else entirely.
 c.2000 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site
at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood
Stars and other features. &QL; 
