<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BABYMOTHER': MOMMY THE DRUDGE BY DAY, DANCEHALL DIVA BY NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Babymother,'' like most pop movie musicals that know where
their bread is buttered, gets serious only long enough to sketch in
a story before it loses its head and surrenders giddily to song,
dance and merriment. Since its idiom is the percolating postreggae
style known as Jamaican dancehall, the movie's good mood isn't
simply upbeat, it's voluptuously ecstatic.
</P>
<P>
   When the spunky heroine, Anita (Anjela Lauren Smith), a
free-spirited dancehall diva, and her sassy two-member ``rude
girl'' crew (Caroline Chikezie and Jocelyn Esien) show off musical
chops in songs that are a cotton-candy-textured hybrid of rap,
reggae and pop, they are queens in a dress-up world of
phantasmagoric nightclub royalty.
</P>
<P>
   The witty, flamboyantly gaudy costumes, jewelry and makeup worn
by the male as well as female performers turn them into pagan
deities, strutting human birds of paradise spreading their wings
while undulating to the music's intensely erotic pulse.
</P>
<P>
   Money appears to be no obstacle in the creation of these
fantastic get-ups. The only limit to the costumed extravagance
seems to be imagination.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, set in the Harlesden section of London, paints that
largely Jamaican neighborhood as a funkier West Indian-flavored
descendant of the title city in Jacques Demy's ``Young Girls of
Rochefort.''
</P>
<P>
   The housing may be drab, but the streets explode with a
pageantry that makes every day a kind of impromptu Mardi Gras
festival. The happily-ever-after romantic ditziness in Demy's movie
musicals, however, is very different from the here-and-now
sensuality of ``Babymother,'' where an easygoing sexual energy
pours out of every frame.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's Anita is a beautiful, haughty ``babymother'' raising two
young children, Anton (Anton Rice) and Saffron (Saffron Lashley),
in an apartment she shares with her educated, strait-laced older
sister Rose (Suzette Llewellyn) and their scolding mother, Edith
(Corinne Skinner Carter). Byron (Wil Johnson), the dashing young
singer who sired Anita's children, shows up from time to time, but
he and Anita usually end up fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Although Byron loves Anita and their children, he has been too
busy pursuing his career (and other women) to spend much time with
them. Impulsively he decides to be a live-in father, but his dream
of a conventional close-knit family is shattered by Anita's refusal
to give up her dream of pop success. (She even goes so far as to
trade sexual favors for studio time.)
</P>
<P>
   The film's climactic scene is a musical battle of the sexes
waged when Anita and her crew crash a nightclub talent show and
compete head to head with Byron.
</P>
<P>
   Had ``Babymother'' evoked even a semblance of social realism, it
might have amounted to something more than a candy-colored,
beat-driven show-business fantasy. But the movie, written and
directed by Julian Henriques, would much rather wallow in music
than develop the strands of a story in which Anita defies her
mother, weathers a family tragedy, adjusts to an astounding
revelation about her parentage and deals with shady music-business
types and jealous rivals.
</P>
<P>
   While the real world occasionally intrudes on ``Babymother,'' it
never stays long enough to dampen the movie's infectious party
spirits. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Babymother' is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying parent
or adult guardian). It has sexual situations. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `BABYMOTHER'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Julian Henriques; edited by Jason
Canovas; music by John Lunn; choreographer, L'Antoinette ``Osun
Ide'' Stines; production designer, Choi Ho Man; produced by
Parminder Vir; released by Independent Pictures/Fine Line Features.
Running time: 80 minutes.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Anjela Lauren Smith (Anita), Wil Johnson (Byron), Caroline
Chikezie (Sharon), Jocelyn Esien (Yvette), Don Warrington (Luther),
Suzette Llewellyn (Rose), Corrine Skinner Carter (Mistress Edith),
Anton Rice (Anton), Saffron Lashley (Saffron) and Tameka Empson
(Dionne). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
