<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, March 17, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Much colder weather will return to the Northeast as brisk winds
from the northeast follow low pressure racing off the coast. Rain
will end as wet snow in much of New England. Only a small
accumulation is expected near the shore, but several inches should
fall inland. Even in southwest New England, rain may end as snow
showers. Skies will clear rapidly over western and northern
sections during the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Polar air will surge southward into the Middle Atlantic region
and through the Ohio Valley. The clockwise circulation around high
pressure in Ontario will keep clouds and flurries over parts of the
central Appalachians. The leading edge of chilly air will stretch
from North Carolina to the central Gulf states. Showers will
accompany the front along the Southeast coast. Florida will stay
sultry with fewer thundershowers.
</P>
<P>
   A small, but potent disturbance moving east across Texas will
produce rain and thunderstorms in eastern sections, and the wet
weather will spread into Louisiana, Oklahoma and southern Arkansas.
It will be dull and cool in the remainder of the southern Plains.
Milder air with increasing clouds will dominate the western Plains
as a cold front sweeps east from the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Gusty winds and patches of snow showers are expected in Wyoming
and Colorado as cooler, moist air pushes in from the Pacific. A
ridge of high pressure building into Oregon will draw warmer, dry
air from the deserts into California. The Northwest coast will
become damp as rain returns ahead of a warm front.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Patchwork Snowstorm
</P>
<P>
   When wintry weather comes to Colorado, a few miles makes a
staggering difference in the depth of new fallen snow. Thursday
morning, over 2 feet of snow had accumulated near Estes Park, while
10 miles away in Boulder, the blanket of white was just 8 inches
deep. Colorado storms are shaped by the cooling of moist air that
ascends the steep slopes. The temperature of moist air falls 3
degrees for each 1,000 feet it rises. As the air cools, more water
vapor condenses into flakes, resulting in a patchwork of snow
depths that responds to the undulating terrain.
</P>
</TEXT>
