<HEADER>
A8944 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-NASCARNOTES17-COX     03-16 1697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCARNOTES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    News and notes from NASCAR
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell &AMP; Rick Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Making headlines
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING BACK
</P>
<P>
   Fans, NASCAR thrilled with Atlanta race: Bruton Smith, chairman
of Speedway Motorsports, Inc. (which owns Atlanta Motor Speedway)
said he has been told by many people that last weekend's Cracker
Barrel 500 was the ``greatest race'' they had ever seen. It's hard
to argue. With Dale Earnhardt nipping Bobby Labonte by .010 seconds
-- less than two feet, this likely will be remembered as the most
memorable spring race. It required a finish-line photo to determine
the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte shows champion's attitude: Labonte had numerous chances
during the final 12 laps to bump Earnhardt into the wall, as The
Intimidator did to Terry Labonte at Bristol last year; but the
little brother didn't. He saved his tires and nearly pulled off a
pass on the final lap. The most touching scene of the weekend
happened after Labonte spoke to ABC-TV immediately after the race:
He broke down and cried in the arms of a team member.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   Enough already: There should be no more comments from Dale
Jarrett, the defending Winston Cup champion. With the thrilling
finish at the Cracker Barrel 500, Jarrett can quit being NASCAR's
public relations expert on the subject of ``boring racing'' and
focus again on his efforts at repeating as champion. Jarrett spent
last weekend chewing out reporters for calling the first three
boring races, ``boring,'' and it appeared to distract the Ford No.
88 team's preparation for the race.
</P>
<P>
   Time to make changes in the pits: Actions speak louder than
words: Pit road is an accident waiting to happen, as evidenced by
several more injuries to crew member in Atlanta. NASCAR is
``looking into'' the situation, but does somebody have to die
before changes are made?
</P>
<P>
   Elliott having a great run: The worst-kept secret in Winston Cup
was revealed last weekend when Bill Elliott joined Dodge for the
2001 season. But the spotlight stays on the No. 94 team; Elliott
stands fourth in the Winston Cup points standings.
</P>
<P>
   Hear that sigh of relief? There are changes in provisionals
</P>
<P>
   Darlington Raceway is not the favorite track for many Winston
Cup drivers because of its tough surface and narrow lanes. But it
will be a darling place this weekend for veterans Johnny Benson and
Ken Schrader and rookies Dale Earnhardt Jr. and Matt Kenseth.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's provisional process changes this weekend. The TranSouth
400 is the fifth race of the Winston Cup season, which means
provisionals will be judged on owner's points compiled during the
2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   For the previous four races, the provisionals were based on the
final standings of owner's points from the 1999 season. So pressure
was on the rookies and many veterans with new race teams. These
teams had to make races on first-round qualifying times.
</P>
<P>
   With owner's points now stacked up after the first four races,
Benson, Schrader and Earnhardt Jr. can be more aggressive during
qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   They have provisionals in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   STORY OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   The return of excitement: Sunday's Cracker Barrel 500 at Atlanta
Motor Speedway was one of the most thrilling races of the young
NASCAR season with Dale Earnhardt and his No. 3 Goodwrench
Chevrolet holding off a determined effort by Bobby Labonte and his
No. 18 Pontiac for the win. It required a finish-line photo to
determine the winner.
</P>
<P>
   LEADERS OF THE PACK
</P>
<P>
   A quick look at some of the sport's top owners
</P>
<P>
   1. Robert Yates. He has resurrected the career of Ricky Rudd and
in February won his third Daytona 500 title as a car owner _ 1992
with Davey Allison, 1996 and 2000 with Dale Jarrett. He pulled off
a major coup by hiring the Rainbow Warriors from the No. 24 team
last year and he has two drivers who are contenders for the Winston
Cup title.
</P>
<P>
   2. Joe Gibbs. The ``coach'' has learned that, to be successful
in racing, you need to have good people in place in your
organization and allow them to do their job. Crew chiefs Jimmy
Makar and Greg Zipadelli fit perfectly into Gibbs' philosophy. His
drivers _ Bobby Labonte and Tony Stewart _ are positioned to win
and challenge for the title. Gibbs also spends time with his sons,
J.D. and Coy, who have racing aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   3. Richard Childress. He might be the most powerful owner on the
circuit. Childress started complaining about the ``disadvantaged''
Chevrolets at Daytona and did not let up until NASCAR announced
modifications last week. During the last five years, Childress had
taken a backseat to Hendrick Motorsports as the top Chevy team on
the circuit, but not in 2000. Childress' most difficult job this
year could be keeping the peace between his two drivers _ Dale
Earnhardt and Mike Skinner.
</P>
<P>
   4. Jack Roush. You have to give credit to the long-time Ford
owner, who demonstrates a workmanlike attitude every week. The
addition of Jeff Burton four years ago was a good move by Roush;
the No. 99 team has become one of Winston Cup's elite teams. He
also has brought talented rookie Matt Kenseth into the fold. Chad
Little continues to struggle, despite a good run in Atlanta last
week. The success of Mark Martin and Burton makes Roush an easy
pick.
</P>
<P>
   5. Felix Sabates. Some people might question this selection, but
the criteria cover more than just winning races. Sabates is the
ultimate owner in terms of staying out of the way of his teams and
providing unlimited funds. Sabates also makes the list for his
colorful personality, sadly missing in most of the garage area.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE RISE
</P>
<P>
   Some strong performances from those who are making a move toward
the front of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Car owner Tim Beverly. The Tyler Jet Motorsports team has been
the Cinderella story of 2000. Beverly deserves credit for giving
veteran driver Johnny Benson a chance to redeem himself after
Benson spent more than six figures to buy his way out of the
remainder of his contract with Jack Roush.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dale Earnhardt. The Intimidator has built the ``Garage Mahal''
to house his two entries in Winston Cup. Dale Earnhardt Jr. and
Steve Park are two of the sport's future stars. With deep pockets
and talented personnel in place, DEI probably will be one of the
top five racing teams in Winston Cup by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   FREE-FALLIN'
</P>
<P>
   Some weak performances from those who appear headed toward the
back of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Brett Bodine. He is one of the last remaining single team
owner-drivers and it is taking its toll. Bodine has failed to
qualify for two of the first four races and already is behind in
the provisional game for coveted starting spots.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A.J. Foyt. The Conseco team was struggling with driver Mike
Bliss, so Foyt replaced him Wednesday with Dick Trickle.
``SuperTex'' always has been a fierce competitor and decided to
withdraw as a team owner in the Indy Racing League at the end of
1999 to focus on a Winston Cup team. He gambled by hiring the
rookie Bliss. The team also has been hurt by not having
provisionals. After missing the race in Atlanta, Foyt vowed he
would make changes on the No. 14 team. ``It was a necessary step to
make,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR QandA with KEN SCHRADER
</P>
<P>
   Veteran driver Ken Schrader, 44, is driving a new car this
season _ the No. 36 Pontiac owned by Tom Beard, Nelson Bowers and
Read Morton. Although he finished 23rd in the Cracker Barrel 500 at
Atlanta, Schrader is 10th in Winston Cup points. Here he talks with
Cox News Service's Rick Minter, who filed this report.
</P>
<P>
   Q:How is your relationship with your new owners?
</P>
<P>
   A:I almost went to work for them four years ago when they
started this deal. I didn't know them, but Rick Hendrick (whom
Schrader once drove for) spoke very highly of them, and that was
all I needed to know. I've really enjoyed it so far. We have
different seats on Sunday, but I hear they have a lot of fun on
race days.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Are you pleased with how your season has gone?
</P>
<P>
   A:Overall I am, other than our qualifying. We've struggled
there, which I didn't really anticipate. But we had a decent run at
Daytona (9th), ran 13th at Rockingham and a 16th at Vegas, but we
would have been a lot better without the rain. We're off to a
fairly solid start.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What are your thoughts on the debate over the aerodynamics of
the three makes of cars?
</P>
<P>
   A:When you sit down in that car you just see the dashboard and
you can't tell what make it is. NASCAR has got a pretty good way of
handling that and they keep it pretty competitive. Everybody can
say what they want but at the end of the race there are always
Fords, Pontiacs and Chevys up there.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Would it help the show if the cars were slowed some?
</P>
<P>
   A:Any time cars go faster, the track becomes more one-groove.
We've got better bodies and better engines, but most of our speed
gains in the last couple of years have come from Goodyear. Goodyear
can build us a little slower tire.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Is age a big factor for race drivers?
</P>
<P>
   A:Not as long as you stay in shape and want to do it. Bobby
Allison was having one of his best years when he was 50 and then
got hurt. Harry Gant won four races at 51 and Dale Earnhardt, we
don't know for sure how old he is, but he still looks pretty stout.
</P>
<P>
   Q:How many short track races do you plan to run in addition to
the Winston Cup schedule?
</P>
<P>
   A:Probably about 40 _ mostly one-night deals with the dirt car.
I go to the Midwest to run the dirt car. I like that kind of dirt
because you can run sideways. I don't like clay (which is on most
dirt tracks in the Southeast). Clay's like running asphalt and I do
that every weekend.
</P>
<P>
   IT TAKES TWO
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen of the 20 top-5 finishes in 2000 _ 90 percent _ have
been by multi-car teams. Here's how they stack up:
</P>
<P>
   5 _ Roush Racing
</P>
<P>
   5 _ Joe Gibbs Racing
</P>
<P>
   2 _ Richard Childress Racing
</P>
<P>
   2 _ Robert Yates Racing
</P>
<P>
   1 _ Penske Racing
</P>
<P>
   1 _ Dale Earnhardt Inc.
</P>
<P>
   1 _ Bill Davis Racing
</P>
<P>
   1 _ Andy Petree Racing
</P>
<P>
   0 _ Hendrick Motorsports
</P>
<P>
   0 _ Petty Enterprises
</P>
<P>
   0 _ Team Sabco
</P>
<P>
   0 _ Travis Carter Enterprises
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
