<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8945 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-PITS-DANGER17-COX     03-16 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-PITS-DANGER17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Injuries in the pits prompt review of NASCAR rules
 &HT;    By Rick Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The excitement and danger inherent in Winston Cup racing doesn't
end when it comes time for pit stops, 20-second races within the
race that often determine winners and losers.
</P>
<P>
   During pit stops, 301 pit-crew members _ seven per team _ will
run onto pit road at some point and service their cars. All the
while, drivers are trying to work their way through the maze of
mechanics to get to their pit stalls and back onto the track.
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies the problem. In the young 2000 racing season, there
already have been several serious accidents in the pits, including
cars hitting drivers and fires created by spilled gasoline. That's
why drivers and crew members agree that working on pit road is the
most hazardous job in racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Driving feels safer because you're strapped in a steel roll
cage,'' said Andy Thurman, who changes tires for Bill Elliott. ``On
pit road, you feel like you're just out there in the open.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Thurman takes the chance because being on a crew gets him
into the Winston Cup garage. There, he hopes to meet people who can
help him graduate from working with wheels to steering them.
</P>
<P>
   And, then there's the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty incredible rush trying to knock down a real good
pit stop and beat the 42 other teams out there,'' Thurman said.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, NASCAR has taken steps to keep crew members
safe. A review of pit road safety is under way in the wake of
mishaps involving crew member in three of the four races this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on a mission to look at a lot of details, one of which
is pit road,'' said Mike Helton, NASCAR's chief operating officer.
``That's part of the sport, but we want it to be a safe part of the
sport.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, drivers raced on pit road just as they did on the
track. But that changed in 1990, after Mike Rich, a crew member for
Elliott, was struck and killed in a race at Atlanta Motor Speedway.
Now, pit road speeds are limited to 35 to 55 mph, depending on the
size of the track and the arrangement of the pits.
</P>
<P>
   But the potential for injury remains. ``You still have 43 cars
that have 700 horsepower and weigh 3,400 pounds each and a whole
bunch of them coming down pit road at the same time,'' rookie
driver Matt Kenseth said. ``It's amazing more accidents don't
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth said drivers have to be patient and not take chances
with other people's lives, particularly during the heat of battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody has you blocked in the pits, it's hard not to just
stand on the gas, spin the back end around and try to get out of
there,'' Kenseth said. ``You just have to be smart and not run
anybody over.''
</P>
<P>
   Driver Kenny Wallace isn't bashful about what he thinks needs to
be done. He said teams should be ordered to pick up tires once they
are taken off the cars. During the Daytona 500, Mike Lingerfelt, a
crew member on Tony Stewart's car, was trying to move a wayward
tire out of Stewart's path and was struck by Stewart. The impact
broke Lingerfelt's leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``All NASCAR has to do is say, `Gentlemen, pick up your tires,
and if you don't there's a penalty,''' Wallace said. ``Why they
don't mandate that is beyond me.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace and several other drivers said making pit stalls bigger
would give crews more room to work. But he said he doesn't expect
that to happen soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I know the racing community like I know it, the first thing
they'll think about is how much money it will cost, and they'd
rather have people run over than put in bigger boxes,'' Wallace
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Clark, president of Atlanta Motor Speedway, said Wallace,
``doesn't have any idea what he's even talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We do everything NASCAR tells us to do, and we go beyond that
and make suggestions on how to do things better,'' Clark said.
``We've spent $93.5 million on capital improvements at this track
and a few more dollars to make the pits safer wouldn't be a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Other drivers said NASCAR is doing its best to keep crew members
safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think NASCAR has done a great job, and they'll continue to
work in that area,'' Elliott said. Of modern era drivers, Elliott's
crew has suffered the most injuries on pit road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have few regrets about my career, but the things that
happened on pit road have been the hardest thing I've ever had to
deal with,'' Elliott said.
</P>
<P>
   Helton said the sanctioning body constantly evaluates video of
races and tries to improve conditions for all racing participants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to anticipate as much as we can in our procedures and
policies, but we can't anticipate every freak happening that can
happen in that environment,'' Helton said. ``Every time something
happens, we go to work and see how we can do it better. We just
haven't found a better policy or procedure that keeps everything
else intact.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nelson, who manages the Winston Cup division, said the
encouraging result is the response by race teams to the early
season pit road incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The competitors went to work on their pit crew practices,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   INJURIES ON PIT ROAD
</P>
<P>
   Here are some serious mishaps on NASCAR's pit road:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1960 _ Two crew members, Paul McDuffie and Charles Sweatmund
of Atlanta, and NASCAR official Joe Taylor of Paterson, N.J., are
killed when Bobby Johns' car spins out of control at Darlington.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1975 _ Randy Owens, Richard Petty's brother-in-law, dies when
an air tank explodes at Talladega.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1979 _ Dennis Wade, a jack man for Dave Watson, is struck and
killed by Watson at Atlanta Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1987 _ Four of Bill Elliott's crew members are injured when
Michael Waltrip's car is struck by another car and knocked into
Elliott's pit area.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1990 _ Michael Rich, a crew member for Bill Elliott, dies
after being struck when Ricky Rudd's car slid out of control.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  2000 _ During the Bud Shootout at Daytona, Mark Martin strikes
his jack man, Mike Ehret, causing minor bruises. A distraught
Martin drops out of the race; During the Daytona 500, Mike
Lingerfelt, a crew member for Tony Stewart, suffers a broken leg
when he tries to move a tire out of Stewart's way and is struck by
Stewart. At Rockingham, Joe Karasinski, gas man for Wally
Dallenbach, is burned by a fire in the pits; At Atlanta, a jack man
for Ken Schrader was struck by Kyle Petty's Pontiac and a fire
erupted in Ted Musgrave's pit area when a spark ignited spilled
gas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
