<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8947 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOYBAND17-COX     03-16 2281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOYBAND17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE MAKING OF AN ATLANTA BOY BAND
 &HT;    Step 1: Find 6 CUTE guys!
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino and Richard Eldredge
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Last August, six teenage boys from rather ordinary
homes in Atlanta's ring of suburbs sat down at a conference table
in Alpharetta, Ga., and opened up a white three-ring binder that
contained a 60-page business plan. It spelled out how they were
going to become rich and famous in two years as the Next Great Boy
band in America. Pared down to its essence, says one, the idea was
to:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Learn to sing in harmony.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Learn to dance in synch.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Perform at places like Six Flags and the Mall of Georgia, and
make every little girl who happens to pause and watch you believe
she's special, and that you're singing to her. Just her. (It helps
to sign autographs and hand out roses.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make an album, and shoot a video _ which is what brought the
group to the heart of Atlanta last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It's March 11 and the members of 6Piece are standing in the
rain, emoting into the camera and lip-synching their way into the
American pop consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   The scene is somewhat surreal. The six young teenagers, dressed
in leather Avirex athletic jackets purchased at a local mall, stand
at bewildered attention while a makeup artist dabs their baby
faces.
</P>
<P>
   One is a little worried, and asks, ``Do I look like I have 10
pounds of lipstick on?''
</P>
<P>
   A boom box begins blasting a thump-beat love song that sounds
like a cross between All-4-0ne's ``I Swear'' and Cher's electronic
vocal noodling on her recent hit ``Believe'' _ ``My first, my last,
I'm gonna love you forever.'' On cue, the guys launch into a kind
of sexy dip/bounce that seems oddly out of place in front of the
old facade of the Roxy Theatre. Bizarrely, the whole thing is
nearly drowned out by the pounding horns of the Tucker High School
marching band high-stepping its way through the Dazz Band's ``Let
It Whip,'' part of a St. Patrick's Day Parade which,
coincidentally, is weaving its way through Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin, Alex, Brandon, Bobby, Micah and John aren't household
names yet _ but they're working on it. These six kids from
Alpharetta, Lilburn, Ga., Cumming, Ga., and Loganville, Ga., who
just a year ago were roaming the malls or pondering their scores on
the SAT, have become Atlanta's answer to the Backstreet Boys and 'N
Sync. Or at least their creator Maurice Starr _ who is also
manager/producer/songwriter _ hopes so.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, the 46-year-old Svengali who essentially invented the
formula of packaging squeaky clean white kids as hip-hop performers
in 1986, when he assembled New Kids on the Block, is back in the
game. After watching his own proteges turn acts such as Backstreet
Boys into multimillion-dollar hit machines, he emerged from his
Alpharetta recording studio (where he has been quietly producing
gospel acts for five years) and went looking for another set of
boys with potential to shape into stars.
</P>
<P>
   To the chagrin of anyone who believes the music comes first, his
strategy seems to have little to do with artistic creative
expression. Starr is a master chef with a recipe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like baking a cake,'' he says, watching his six young
students point and wink and move their hands like a maitre de
inviting someone to sit down to dinner. ``New Kids on the Block
were a cake. Everything starts from a vision, an embryo. Everybody
can fry chicken, but the man who started KFC had his own style.
This is my recipe for cooking up a boy band.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr began assembling his ingredients last spring when he
passed out flyers at area high schools to recruit teens who would
be willing to essentially turn their lives over to him for two
years. He personally screened about 200 calls, narrowing his search
by asking three questions: ``How tall are you? How much do you
weigh? And are you good looking?''
</P>
<P>
   Next, Starr held auditions at his home studio, where he watched
the teenagers mimic song lyrics and dance steps. Following the
boyband recipe _ which calls for a diversity of boy types _ he knew
what he needed. First on board was 19-year-old Kevin Swan, a
parttime model with ladykiller looks who Starr decided would be the
group's ``heartbreaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin describes his style this way: ``I wear 10 rings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At first my friends and my parents were real skeptical,'' the
teen says politely, his responses peppered with ``Yes ma'ams.''
``They never expected to hear us on the radio or see our CD in
stores. Now they are as mind-boggled and excited as I am _ `My
son's gonna be a superstar!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Then Starr found his wisecracking rebel (John), his good buddy
(Bobby), the baby-faced innocent (Micah), the swarthy crooner with
creative facial hair (Alex) and the all-important sixth member
(Brandon), who still seems to be searching for his role in the
group. But Brandon's presence was essential to Starr in order to
make 6 Piece different from the glut of boy bands saturating the
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody else looks the same because they've got five guys,''
he says matter-of-factly. ``We're gonna look different on TV
because we've got six.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the group was assembled, Starr began holding rehersals
seven days a week, six hours a day. Contracts were signed, with the
boys retaining an entertainment lawyer to carve out their end of
the deal. According to Kevin, Starr gets 20 percent as manager. The
guys split 10 percent between the six of them. The rest goes to
Starr's independent label, Starrworks, and for promotion and
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   But there was another expectation, perhaps more important than
any conventional music business game plan. The guys of 6 Piece had
to develop a fan base _ before their music was ever on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   How? By aiming straight for the hearts of little girls.
</P>
<P>
   Like a pop version of Amway or Mary Kay Cosmetics, Starr's idea
enlists young girls to chat up 6 Piece to their friends. There are
hundreds of them here today, as VIP extras on the video shoot,
shivering in the damp rain. They are waiting to catch the eye of
their favorite 6 Piecer. Wearing tight short skirts, low-waisted
bell bottoms, black platform shoes and more halter tops than a
``Baywatch'' episode, they hang around the stairway leading to the
dressing area at the Celebrity Rock Cafe, swapping 6 Piece stories
like salesmen at a convention.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen-year-old Niki Sexton of Lawrenceville, Ga., and Rachel
Cook, 13, of Kennesaw, Ga., explain how it works.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on the Promote Team,'' Cook says.
</P>
<P>
   The Promote Team?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah. Each guy picked 10 girls to be part of the Promote
Team,'' Sexton explains. ``They give us stuff to hand out. Like
when Bobby from the band gave me these black cards (forms to
pre-order the group's album) and told me to run down the mall, and
I went into stores and yelled `Come see these hot, fine guys!' ``
</P>
<P>
   Over the months, Starr has trotted out 6 Piece on small stages
all over the Atlanta area. As girls stop to watch, the young
performers use the careful training Starr has given them to work
the crowd. After the show, rather than ducking into a dressing room
or being whisked off in a limo, Kevin, Micah, Bobby, Brandon, John
and Alex hang around and talk with their fans. They exchange e-mail
addresses and collect names for a mailing list to notify the girls
where they will appear next. A slickly designed Web site
(www.6pieceonline.com) also contains direct e-mail links to each
boy in the group. Kevin says each time he sits down at his
computer, he has ``at least 100'' messages from this interactive
fan base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about it,'' Starr says over a bacon cheeseburger at
Johnny Rockets, on break from the video shoot. ``You do this all
across the country. You get 100,000 of them, and each buys 10
records, what's that? Platinum.''
</P>
<P>
   The entire scene here could be a documentary on the lure _ or
perhaps more accurately, the illusion _ of fame. Plop any one of
these guys down at Publix or the Gap, and it's unlikley anyone
would know who they are. But behind the velvet rope sealing them
off from fans, these young stars in the making seem special.
</P>
<P>
   Older teen girls pump their hips to loud rap lyrics _ ``move it
move it move it'' _ waiting for the members of 6 Piece to lean over
a balcony railing. Alex playfully takes off his shirt, setting off
high-pitched screams. The others wander down into the crowd and
invite girls to join them behind the velvet rope. Outside in the
rain, a girl in a black tube-top dashes for cover while trying to
protect the autographs _ she got all six! _ scrawled on her upper
body in magic marker. Everyone is caught up. Soon even casual
onlookers know Kevin from Micah from Bobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting,'' Niki says. ``The lifestyle, the screams,
people knowing your name. Like when I went to the CD release party,
I had on this VIP pass and I felt like `Oh my gosh, I feel so
important!'''
</P>
<P>
   Nicki's mom, 41-year-old Debbie Sexton, believes it's all
innocent fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are nice people. We show up at everything,'' she says.
``Right now, the guys are having as much fun as the girls. ... I
can remember when the Beatles came, it was your dream to just say
`I met them'. This is like, `I was there. I know them.'''
</P>
<P>
   Starr's strategy comes with perks and bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``These girls can't control themselves because we make them feel
like VIPs,'' he says. ``We give them the game plan, fill them up
with energy and send them on their way. It's not unlike that
motivational speaker, what's his name ...Tony Robbins. The ones who
do the best (i.e. high record sales in their neighborhoods) get
limo rides, dinner with their favorite guy, a concert in their
living room.''
</P>
<P>
   In the months leading up to this video shoot, some of the fans
have even become friends with the guys, hanging out with them at
Steak &AMP; Shake, riding the water slides at Whitewater, attending
youth nights at Cowboy's. But the girls, their parents and Starr
insist the relationships stay strictly platonic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a date,'' Rachel says. ``It's like a hangout.''
</P>
<P>
   Paula Youngblood of Stone Mountain, whose daughter Kimberly, 20,
appears as a fan in the video, said she had her doubts when Starr
approached her daughter at a local teen club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work at a law firm, and I checked him out, believe me,'' she
says. ``Anytime a 40-something year old man is looking at my
daughter, he's going to be checked out by me. I made him take me to
lunch at Picadilly, and we discussed things.''
</P>
<P>
   With Starr as songwriter on all 10 tracks, 6 Piece's first
album, ``Phase I,'' arrived in stores last week. The single, ``My
First, My Last,'' was picked up in Atlanta by new Top 40 station,
95.5 The Beat. The video is being rushed into post-production, then
will be distributed to music channels such as the Box, an
all-request cable channel that has become a tryout forum for new
acts before they make it to MTV. That's when the Promote Team will
be put into action to start calling the 1-900 phone number over and
over again to ask that it be played.
</P>
<P>
   What will it take for 6 Piece to succeed? They seem set to be
the Next Big Thing for teenage girls, at least for awhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they'll make it. It's a totally different type of
sound,'' says Mike Abrams, program director of 95.5 The Beat, who
thinks Starr's latest creation sound-- ``more R&AMP;B'' than Backstreet
Boys. ``They have a great stage show. They are hungry and
ambitious. Maurice Starr is still a big name in this industry, and
that will open doors.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with Starr's track record and clout _ beyond vocal coaches
and choreographers, Kevin says the business plan mentions an
appearance on ``Oprah Winfrey'' in the near future and someday, a
show at Philips Arena, downtown _ it seems a daunting challenge in
a pop music market teeming with cloned boy bands. In addition to
the two big moneymakers, Backstreet Boys and 'N Sync, there's
Boyzone, 98 Degrees, LFO, C-Note, 5IVE and Youngstown. There's even
a parody of the genre, a fictitious group called 2+gether, now
making the rounds on MTV's ``Total Request Live.'' And ABC is
creating a reality-based show (``Making the Band'') about the birth
of a boy band, which will air Friday nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's always room for another boy band,'' says Ellen
Jurcsak, editor of 16 Magazine. ``Exposure is a big part of it,
getting them out there where girls can see them and listen to their
music and get to know them a little bit. With that comes the desire
to know everything about them, to meet them, collect posters,
pinups. A lot of it has to do with luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Starr would have to concede that birthing a boy band can be
problematic, especially if the group makes it big. His own
creations, New Edition and New Kids on the Block, went on to seek
solo careers after a fairly short shelf life. Two of today's
hottest boy groups, Backstreet Boys and 'N Sync, have both sued
their creator _ Orlando mogul Lou Pearlman _ for bigger shares of
the pot and jumped ship to a different set of handlers.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin believes he made the right decision to put art college on
hold for awhile to give 6 Piece a shot. He says he is getting used
to ``being a character onstage,'' and that working a crowd in live
performance ``is an adrenaline rush, like a feeling I've never had
before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans are looking for a person who can touch them and make them
excited,'' he says. ``They want to see six good-looking guys
onstage who are pretending to sing just to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino and Richard Eldredge write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
