<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8948 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-RAMSEY-MEDIASAGA17-CO     03-16 1338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMSEY-MEDIASAGA17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Media blitz by Ramseys starts today
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If only Lt. Columbo were here. He'd walk away from John and
Patsy Ramsey, then turn unexpectedly, all rumpled and raspy, and
say, ``Uh, just one more question.''
</P>
<P>
   And we'd know who murdered JonBenet Ramsey.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we are a nation of armchair Columbos, always asking,
but with the truth as elusive as ever. The maw of television opens
wide again, the Internet hyperventilates with invective, the
whodunit rattles our national cage.
</P>
<P>
   ``This story has moved beyond something that is merely
newsworthy to become a communal event, an experience,'' says
Matthew R. Kerbel, author of ``If it Bleeds, It Leads,'' a new book
that offers a scorching analysis of television news.
</P>
<P>
   Today marks a peak, if not in actual news, then in the communal
event that is our fascination with the Ramsey case. John and Patsy
Ramsey's book, ``The Death of Innocence'' (Thomas Nelson, Inc.,
$24.99) goes on sale today with a first printing run of 300,000
copies (several bookstores around the country jumped the gun,
claiming to be unaware of the publisher's embargo). At 10 tonight,
ABC airs a Barbara Walters interview with the Ramseys on ``20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   The publicity drumbeat continues next week with a live Internet
chat with the Ramseys at 10 p.m. Monday on the website ABC.com; a
five-part interview with Katie Couric on NBC's ``Today'' show; and
then a March 27 appearance on ``Larry King Live.'' The true
newsworthiness of any of these interviews is debatable; the Ramseys
say exactly what they said on CNN on Jan. 1, 1997, and on a British
documentary that ran on A&AMP;E in 1998: That they are innocent, that
they did not kill their 6-year-old daughter on Dec. 26, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``The audience loves it, and I'm curious to a point, but there's
got to be something new,'' CNN's King said in January. ``I don't
think there's been any real development in the last 12 shows we've
done.''
</P>
<P>
   The book publication and media blitz are new, but that's not
necessarily the same as being news.
</P>
<P>
   The very notion of ``news'' in the Ramsey case has been
slippery, as the level of journalism has been a shocking mix of
laziness and aggressiveness resulting in a blur of misinformation
and misleading leaks that surpasses even Clinton-Lewinsky, along
with the usual speculation, blind alleys and ax-grinding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm amazed that the whole world doesn't think we're guilty,
given what they've been told,'' John Ramsey tells Walters in
tonight's interview. And indeed, many do think he and/or his wife
Patsy are guilty, and see their book and the well-orchestrated TV
appearances as a cynical manipulation. But many others see the
Ramseys as innocents, unjustly persecuted by a Boulder police force
that rushed to judgment, and by a ravenous media in which
distinctions between tabloid and mainstream no longer hold.
</P>
<P>
   The book itself, ``The Death of Innocence'' (the 10th book about
the case) is 396 grueling pages, in which the Ramseys describe
their last three years and three months in detail; outline the case
that an intruder killed JonBenet; and wreak extended vengeance on
the Boulder police and the national media. Although the supermarket
tabloid The Globe gets it the worst (Geraldo Rivera is second),
they also poke at CNN, citing their devastation when they heard
former talk-show host Mary Tillotson say JonBenet looked like ``a
hooker'' when she dressed for child beauty pageants. They refer to
MSNBC (the cable venture of NBC and Microsoft) as ``the video
tabloid brought to us by Bill Gates and GE.''
</P>
<P>
   But frequently in ``The Death of Innocence,'' the media is just
an undifferentiated mob, a perpetual stalking machine both in
Colorado and in Atlanta, where the Ramseys now live in a house on
West Paces Ferry Road.
</P>
<P>
   They turned down nearly all interview requests; ``we did not
feel obligated to fill their time slots with macabre
entertainment,'' they write.
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, there is no other way to publicize their book
but to present themselves as ``macabre entertainment'' in the media
they despise. Thomas Nelson, a Nashville Christian publishing
house, set up the carefully calibrated appearances on the Ramseys'
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted these interviews to air when the book is in
bookstores,'' says Jeff Zucker, executive producer of ``Today.''
``If we hadn't agreed, they wouldn't have taped it.'' So Couric
interviewed the Ramseys in late February, as did Walters, and their
news organizations agreed in advance not to air the interviews
until the book's release.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not unique,'' says Zucker. ``We've seen this on other
books of major interest; Colin Powell's book comes to mind.''
</P>
<P>
   If this extended dance is indeed about news, it's just as much
about promotion. But as Matthew Kerbel notes, ``The public creates
the demand; the media feeds the demand.''
</P>
<P>
   On ``20/20'' tonight, Walters is tough but not vicious,
definitely not in her super-sympathetic mode. She tells the couple
that to many people, the videos of JonBenet in beauty pageants look
``perverted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That didn't come from JonBenet; that came from the viewer,''
Patsy responds.
</P>
<P>
   Walters also reviews the evidence that an intruder killed
JonBenet (as does the current Newsweek, as does the book), but the
show is aimed more at the casual follower of the case rather than
the hard-core obsessives.
</P>
<P>
   For those, the Internet is the medium of choice. The Ramsey case
is unmeasurably huge in cyberspace. One popular webpage lists 118
links to the case, but each link leads to countless more. Susan
Bennett, a homemaker in North Carolina whose Internet site led to
her becoming friends with the Ramseys, being questioned by the
police and being threatened by Internet crazies, has a timeline of
the case that runs more than 3,000 printed pages.
</P>
<P>
   She also runs one of the many Internet forums, where thousands
of people speculate endlessly (and sometimes mindlessly) on the
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hobby for some,'' says Bennett. ``Some are there
because they really care about JonBenet, some are there because
their lives are lacking something.'' She agrees with the notion
that many, but not all, Ramsey case fanatics are armchair
detectives, sifting through the clues in an effort to solve the
case.
</P>
<P>
   While Bennett's site is independent but pro-Ramsey, other sites
argue so strongly for the guilt of one or both parents that a Net
acronym was coined, based on a ``Star Trek'' alien race: BORG, or
Bent On Ramsey Guilt. Even the sleaziest media outposts have at
least some standards _ fear of libel, if nothing else _ but the
Ramsey obsessives on the Net, many of whom post using anonymous
names, are completely unfettered. They attack the Ramseys, the
police, the district attorney, and one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Patsy and I have lived through might go down in history
as the first cyberspace lynching,'' John writes in ``Innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have here is the blurring of the line between reality
and fiction,'' says Kerbel. ``A real murder happened. People then
latched onto the mystery of it, the celebrity, and became
captivated by it, as if it was a whodunit novel.'' This one,
though, had more clues than any self-respecting ``Columbo'' would
ever allow: the bizarre ransom note, the stun gun, the DNA, the
garotte, the duct tape, the shoeprint, the snow outside the house
(or lack of it).
</P>
<P>
   ``So we beat on, boats against the current, borne back
ceaselessly into the past.'' F. Scott Fitzgerald closed his novel
``The Great Gatsby'' with that line 75 years ago. Now it describes
us all: the media talking heads, the cyber-sleuths, and even the
Ramseys themselves. The nature of modern news, with every day a new
cycle, makes it seem as if we're moving forward. But we really just
keep going back, and going back, trying to figure it out.
</P>
<P>
   TV INTERVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   10 tonight on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1744EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
