<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8950 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-MAPLE-SYRUP-ART-2TAKE     03-16 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAPLE-SYRUP-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN VERMONT, TURNING SAP INTO AMBROSIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITINGHAM, Vt. _ Early spring quickens in this state's southern
mountain hamlets with the first rising curls of wood smoke from
roadside sugar houses and the sweet fragrance of newly boiled amber
maple syrup served pure and plain in thin paper cups.
</P>
<P>
   For an aficionado like Leon Corse there is no comparison between
name-brand pancake varietals, which he scorns as Karo corn syrup
with a little flavoring _ ``Just read the label'' _ and the various
grades of golden maple syrup that for six generations his farm
family has made by tapping sugar-maple trees in the chill air of
the Green Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   When the weather is kind, and the transparent sap is dripping
from his farm's nearly 10,000 tree taps, Corse and his family are
fond of calling their 400 acres in Whitingham ``the Land of Milk
and Maple Syrup.'' But unlike a winery, a sugar house gets just one
chance a year to prove the mettle of its maple with fresh tastings
for amateur connoisseurs: for only about 45 days in the spring,
when the nights are cold and the days are warm enough to coax the
sap to flow.
</P>
<P>
   Just in the last two weeks Corse and dozens of other farmers in
this informal pancake zone have started the annual ritual of
sugaring, a craft handed down through generations. This is the time
when farmers stock giant King evaporators with cords of dry wood to
boil the sap collected in hundreds of buckets that hang from the
local sugar maples like silver charms.
</P>
<P>
   And it is a fleeting opportunity for tourists to experience the
small-town spell of a pancake breakfast flapped by the local Lions
or an afternoon luncheon or ham supper prepared a la maple by
groups like the Ladies Benevolent Society of Whitingham or the E-Z
Riders Snowmobile Club.
</P>
<P>
   Vermont is, after all, the top producer of maple syrup in the
United States, with 370,000 gallons last year, or more than a third
of all the maple syrup in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Quebec and Ontario are actually the largest producers, but that
doesn't deter the city of St. Albans in northern Vermont from
dubbing itself ``the Maple Sugar Capital of the World'' and
celebrating that boast with an annual festival and parade that
features sugar house demonstrations, maple syrup contests, snacks
of maple sugar on snow, and a supper featuring the selection of
maple sugar royalty.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time St. Albans is crowning its king and queen of
maple, the prime sugaring season is over. So now is the time to
head for farms in Pennsylvania, Vermont, New Hampshire and New York
for the chance to taste maple syrup fresh from a throbbing
evaporator while discussing recipe tips for maple-baked ham
directly with the farmer.
</P>
<P>
   The hamlet of Whitingham, about 220 miles north of New York
City, is celebrating its own annual Maple Sugar Festival next
weekend, so tourists _ or flatlanders, as visitors are sometimes
called here _ can taste fresh syrup samples. The doors will be open
at 8 of the 18 sugar houses in the area, which are scattered along
two-lane roads or nestled in a gulch reachable by horse-drawn
sleigh if the snow has not melted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it liquid gold,'' said Edmund McLaughlin, a retired
health-care executive who has become the town's chief maple sugar
booster. ``It's part of the fabric of the lifestyle here.''
</P>
<P>
   With a population of 1,182, Whitingham, including the village of
Jacksonville, revolves around a bend in the road on Route 100 that
is the town center. There's a sprawling white municipal center
building, a general store, a firehouse and a library that's open
three days a week. Whitingham is so small that there is no public
telephone in the town center and none to be found within six miles.
</P>
<P>
   It is most fabled for a native son who left: Brigham Young was
born here and eventually led thousands of Mormons across the Rocky
Mountains to found Salt Lake City in 1847. On an isolated hilltop
in Whitingham stands a white granite monument with a curious
inscription, which may have figured in its mysterious disappearance
and reappearance last year after a tour group of Mormons paid a
visit to the town: ``Brigham Young. Born on this spot 1801. A man
of much courage and superb equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   Many transplanted flatlanders have come for a visit to the Green
Mountains and never left, seduced by rural charms. Patience
Merriman moved to Whitingham five years ago from Philadelphia to
work for the local newspaper, The Deerfield Valley News, and as a
freelance writer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an education,'' she said. ``The first couple of
years I just wandered around in a kind of daze, not really
believing I would never wear high heels or panytyhose again, or
that I would end up sitting on a folding chair in the basement of
the Town Hall covering a zoning board meeting during which there
was a break for ice cream and maple syrup.''
</P>
<P>
   Northeast of Whitingham in Halifax _ along a dirt road that
thaws and freezes daily in the early spring _ the former Long
Islanders Bill and Patti Pusey operate a working farm and a
bed-and-breakfast that they have built up over the last 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   In March the 100-year-old sugar maples shadowing the Shearer
Hill Farm are hung with metal sap buckets, which are collected by
Pusey and an assortment of relatives and visiting friends who come
from all over the Eastern Seaboard to, in effect, work for maple
syrup. On one weekend a Rhode Island trial lawyer, Bob Iuliano,
tried to forget the stresses of the courtroom by doing volunteer
duty in the sugar shack, where the evaporator was working till well
past 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We love it,'' said Pusey, who offers guests freshly made maple
syrup drizzled on her home-baked apple betty. ``It's just such a
magical time of the year: to take 40 gallons of sap and turn it
into a gallon of syrup. We like the late hours. We like the sugar
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very highly concentrated time of year. And every time
you use the maple syrup, you revisit the experience. You can't help
but reflect on gathering the sap, emptying the buckets from the
tree, being knee deep in mud.''
</P>
<P>
   In Vermont, various legends circulate about the origins of maple
syrup. But all the tales contain a few basic elements.
</P>
<P>
   In early spring an Indian leaves a bowl sitting below the base
of tree. Drips of sap collect in the bowl, but the liquid looks
like water. Maple syrup is discovered when the Indian boils the
``water,'' and it reduces to an amber treat.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the history of the United States, maple syrup has
been valued not only for its taste but also for its potential
political power. Thomas Jefferson argued that maple sugar (which is
produced by further boiling the syrup) offered a means of
self-sufficiency for early settlers. Abolitionists theorized that
the increased production of maple sugar could cripple the slave
trade by reducing demand for imported cane and beet sugars, which
were grown with slave labor.
</P>
<P>
   Today the power of maple sugar lies in its sweetness and the
nostalgic memories that it evokes. There are, after all, only a few
weekends when a traveler can spot the smoke rising from a sugar
house like the one at Whetstone Valley Farm on Cooke Road in
Brattleboro and taste Fancy Grade A, warm, golden and steaming from
the boiler.
</P>
<P>
   Whitingham, Vt., is 220 miles north of New York City. Here is a
sampling of attractions, along with travel information:
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   SHEARER HILL FARM BED-AND-BREAKFAST, P.O. Box 1453, Shearer Hill
Road, Halifax, (800) 437-3104. A restored farmhouse overlooks a
meadow and a sugar house supplied with sap from sugar maples
bordering a dirt road. Rooms also available in a nearby carriage
house. Children welcome. Daily rates: $90 for a double room, $70
for a single.
</P>
<P>
   WHITINGHAM FARM BED-AND-BREAKFAST, 742 Abbie Morse Road,
Whitingham, (800) 310-2010. A Greek Revival house built in 1860.
Offers sleigh rides drawn by Blitz and Blaze, a matched pair of
Morgan-Percherons. During Whiting-ham's Maple Sugar Festival (March
24-25 this year), the owner, Newt Brosius, transports guests by
sleigh to a local sugar house. Daily rates: $120 to $140, based on
double occupancy. Sugar Houses
</P>
<P>
   SPRAGUE &AMP; SON SUGAR HOUSE, Route 100, Jacksonville, (802)
368-2776.
</P>
<P>
   WHETSTONE VALLEY FARM, 120 Cooke Road, West Brattleboro, (802)
257-0597.
</P>
<P>
   CORSE FARM, Corse Road, Whitingham, (802) 368-7192.
</P>
<P>
   COOMBS VERMONT GOURMET, 2016 Maple Hill Lane, Whitingham, (888)
266-6271.
</P>
<P>
   Attractions
</P>
<P>
   NORTH RIVER WINERY, Route 112 (River Road), Jacksonville, (802)
368-7557. Vermont's first winery offers an eclectic selection of
wines made with pears, green apples, raspberry, rhubarb and
blueberry. Housed in a farmstead, the winery offers a Vermont
Harvest vintage made from apples, cinnamon and 10 percent Vermont
maple syrup.
</P>
<P>
   WHITINGHAM MAPLE SUGAR FESTIVAL, Whitingham-Jacksonville, (802)
368-2387 or www.whitinghammaplefest.com, March 24-25. The second
annual festival celebrates maple sugaring with sledding, a bonfire
and tours of sugar houses that can be reached by buses or even
snowshoes. Local residents are organizing three meals featuring
maple syrup, starting with a Lions Club breakfast on March 25 at
the Municipal Center in Jacksonville and including a ham supper
later that day at the same site with sugar-on-snow desserts.
</P>
<P>
   VERMONT MAPLE SUGAR FESTIVAL, St. Albans, (802) 524-5800 or
www.vtnet.com/maplefest, April 28-30. Pancake breakfasts, maple
exhibits, food demonstrations, a parade, a carnival, crafts and
antiques.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   LE PETIT CHEF, Route 100, West Wilmington, (802) 464-8437.
Casual French and some not-so-French meals in an old farmhouse with
a lounge that is home to original work by a cartoonist, Skip
Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   MAPLE LEAF MALT AND BREWING COMPANY, 3 North Main Street,
Wilmington, (802) 464-9900. Microbrewery, restaurant and taproom
housed in a historic building. Brewing operations are visible from
the the dining area.
</P>
<P>
   Getting There From New York City
</P>
<P>
   BY CAR: Take the Major Deegan Expressway to the Thomas E. Dewey
Thruway north to the Cross County Parkway east; continue as it
becomes the Hutchinson River Parkway north and then the Merritt
Parkway to I-91 north. Continue to Exit 2 in Vermont (Route 9 West)
and travel 17 miles west to Route 100 south. The trip from
Manhattan takes about four hours.
</P>
<P>
   BY TRAIN: The station nearest Whitingham is Brattleboro, Vt. An
Amtrak train leaves Penn Station in Manhattan daily at 11:30 a.m.
and arrives in Brattleboro at 5 p.m.; round-trip fare, $54 ($27 for
children ages 2 to 15). Amtrak information: (800) 872-7245. Taxis
are available for transportation to rental car agencies.
</P>
</TEXT>
