<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINTER-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WINTER SLEEPERS': AGAINST A GORGEOUS LANDSCAPE, YOUNG ADULTS
LACKING IN VISION 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To the gleaming tinkle of ``Tubular Bells''-like music, the
camera in Tom Tykwer's film ``Winter Sleepers'' swoops like a
reckless downhill skier across the peaks and along the icy roads
surrounding a picturesque skiing village in the German mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The gorgeously photographed film by the German director of ``Run
Lola Run'' distills the beauty and peril of this wintry environment
with a laserlike concentration that virtually blows a cloud of snow
in your face. In an early scene, as a car skids off a mountain road
and plunges into a snowbank, the sickening crunch of the vehicle
hurtling into a drift is so perfectly coordinated with a shot of
snow slamming into the windshield that for that split second you
might as well be behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winter Sleepers'' has many such breathtaking moments in which
sounds and images synergize with an explosive precision. In one
extraordinary scene in a hospital, the beep of a machine monitoring
a patient's vital signs slowly bleeds into an exquisitely sad piece
of music that extends the machine's pulse and captures the despair
of the nurse watching over the patient.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the film, a skier racing down a slope leaps over a
ledge and into free fall to the strains of Arvo Part's ``Elegy for
Benjamin Britten,'' a piece that seems suspended in midair as its
descending melodic circles suggest a slow-motion dive into an
eternal void.
</P>
<P>
   These thrillingly virtuosic cinematic feats add tremendous
resonance to the stories of five intersecting characters. Laura
(Marie-Lou Sellem), a nurse and would-be actress who is appearing
in a local production of ``A Streetcar Named Desire,'' shares a
house with Rebecca (Floriane Daniel), a beautiful, indolent
translator who is having an affair with Marco (Heino Ferch), a
handsome, hotheaded ski instructor.
</P>
<P>
   As we follow a relationship that is one long, bickering power
struggle interrupted by passionate interludes, Rebecca and Marco
emerge as spoiled, aimless young adults out of touch with any deep
set of values.
</P>
<P>
   One afternoon while Marco and Rebecca are making love, Rene
(Ulrich Matthes), a gaunt young movie projectionist from the
village, goes out for a walk and happens upon Marco's brand-new
sports car, which is parked in front of Rebecca's house with the
keys in the ignition.
</P>
<P>
   Impulsively, he decides to take it for a spin. Minutes later the
car skids off the highway to avoid a collision with a vehicle
driven by Theo (Josef Bierbichler), a middle-aged farmer taking his
sick horse to the vet in an attached trailer.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't until after the accident, when she is discovered
unconscious and gravely injured, that Theo realizes his young
daughter had stowed away in the trailer. Meanwhile, Rene, fighting
his way out of the snow, walks away from the accident, leaving the
stolen car buried and invisible from the roadside. Later, when Theo
insists that another vehicle was involved, no one believes him.
</P>
<P>
   The circle of connection among the characters is completed when
Laura becomes one of the nurses watching over Theo's comatose
daughter at the village's clinic. She and Rene, who suffers from
chronic short-term memory loss as a result of an old head injury,
also become romantically involved. Rene, to try to refresh his
memory of the previous day's events, habitually takes snapshots
wherever he goes.
</P>
<P>
   If the characters in ``Winter Sleepers,'' adapted from a novel
by Francoise Pyszora, don't begin to harmonize with the beauty and
terror of the landscape, they're not supposed to. For ``Winter
Sleepers'' is really about the malaise of young Germans (except for
Theo, all the characters are in their late 20s or 30s) who appear
spiritually and morally unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   The short-term memory loss of Rene (who at odd moments resembles
Anthony Perkins in ``Psycho'') is a rather forced metaphor for his
generation's lack of larger vision. The movie leaves deliberately
unclear exactly what Rene remembers and what he forgets.
</P>
<P>
   Although Marco and Rebecca seem to have everything life could
offer, they emerge as spoiled brats who idly flirt with others.
Among the four, Marco offers the sourest observations about life in
general. He questions the value of human longevity and suggests
that the most anyone can expect in life is ``three good years.''
</P>
<P>
   If ``Winter Sleepers'' is very different in tone and style from
``Run Lola Run,'' the beat-driven, jet propelled, MTV-style race
against time that put Tykwer on the map as a hot international
filmmaker, it deals with many of the same themes.
</P>
<P>
   Both movies ruminate (``Winter Sleepers'' in its angst-ridden
way, ``Lola'' in its frenzied live-action cartoon style) on how
human destiny has everything to do with timing and the instant and
endless chains of causality that ripple from a single chance
encounter. Or, as the song ``What a Difference a Day Makes,''
featured prominently in ``Lola,'' reminds us, what seems like
chance can create ``the sun and the flowers where there used to be
rain.'' Of course, it also works the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   Together, ``Lola'' and ``Winter Sleepers'' confirm Tykwer as a
somewhat cold but dazzling cinematic magician whose movies can
conjure whole worlds with just the snap of a shutter, then make
them vanish just as quickly. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `WINTER SLEEPERS' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Tom Tykwer; written (in German, with English
subtitles) by Tykwer and Francoise Pyszora; director of
photography, Frank Griebe; edited by Katja Dringenberg; music by
Tykwer, Johnny Klimek and Reinhold Heil; production designer,
Alexander Manasse; produced by Stefan Arndt and X-Filme Creative
Pool GmbH; released by Winstar Cinema. Running time: 124 minutes.
This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Ulrich Matthes (Rene), Marie-Lou Sellem (Laura), Floriane
Daniel (Rebecca), Heino Ferch (Marco) and Josef Bierbichler (Theo).
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1747EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
