<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8954 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BUFFALO-THEATER-REVIE     03-16 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUFFALO-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AMERICAN BUFFALO': AN ODDLY BREEZY REVIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Things and stuff like _ well, you know _ things and
stuff are what make the world go round in ``American Buffalo,''
David Mamet's career-making conversion of sooty, carbon speech into
diamond-hard theater. ``You want to tell me what this thing is?''
begins a typical exchange. Or: ``Forget the thing.'' Or: ``The
thing, it ran two years.'' The listeners in the play, by the way,
know exactly what the speakers mean. So do we.
</P>
<P>
   In this 1975 tale of a crime that never happens, which opened
Thursday night in a brisk, oddly breezy revival starring William H.
Macy, the words that carry the most weight are those nonspecific
nouns that have long been the refuge of verbally challenged English
speakers: things and stuff, for sure, not to mention the assortment
of cruder, four-letter equivalents that made theatergoers prick up
and even cover their ears 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Yet out of the collision of monosyllables that spring from the
mouths of the play's three hapless crooks, a painstaking pattern
emerges, centered on, as it happens, a two-syllable word: business.
That noun hisses like a riled cobra through the current production
of ``American Buffalo,'' directed by Neal Pepe as the third
offering in the Mamet season from the Atlantic Theater Company and
already a hot ticket.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter-century after it was first performed, instantly
thrusting Mamet into the front line of a new generation of
dramatists, ``American Buffalo'' scarcely seems like a fossil. The
contemplation and pursuit of things and stuff (words that are
conveniently both abstract and material) is, after all, what
continues to keep this country moving. The marginal urban losers of
``American Buffalo,'' self-defined entrepreneurs, are enduring
American archetypes, dark soulmates to the day traders of today.
</P>
<P>
   With the novelty of the play's brusque, blue dialogue long worn
off, it's the careful, bravura manipulation of language to thematic
ends that seems most apparent now. The status of ``American
Buffalo'' as one of the most eloquently inarticulate plays ever
written remains secure. And this latest interpretation, previously
produced to cries of acclaim at the Donmar Warehouse in London,
cannot be faulted as a primer in Mamet semantics.
</P>
<P>
   The three-member cast, which also features Philip Baker Hall and
Mark Webber, has a disarmingly fluid command of Mametspeak; no one
lets on, as is often embarrassingly the case in less accomplished
productions, that what the actors are saying is in fact as
artificial as Elizabethan blank verse. There's a temperate quality,
too, in Pepe's direction that lets the wit and the linguistic
structure of the play shine more cleanly than ever.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, when did you ever hear a production of
``American Buffalo'' described as temperate? For all its wordiness,
this play, famously performed in New York in productions starring
Robert Duvall (1977) and Al Pacino (1981), has traditionally come
across as a fist in the face. This incarnation tickles and
occasionally offers a stinging slap, but it certainly doesn't knock
you out.
</P>
<P>
   The principal reason can be found in what is at once the show's
greatest asset and its greatest handicap. That's Macy as Teach,
whose long-winded philosophizing and paranoid rants justify his
nickname. In a play about bumblers, Teach is a virtuoso of
ineptitude, a nonstop, self-justifying spielmeister whose
cockiness, like that of sexual braggarts, is in inverse proportion
to his performance.
</P>
<P>
   Teach is a comic figure but also a scary one. That, in any case,
was how he registered as portrayed by Duvall and Pacino, who
respectively brought a cold fury and a maniacal fire to their
performances. They were very different interpretations, but each in
its way was a juggernaut, giving the plot its overcharged,
self-destructive engine.
</P>
<P>
   Macy comes to Teach with a formidable pedigree in Mamet
portrayals, ranging from Bobby the addict (played here by Webber)
in the original ``Buffalo'' at the Goodman Theater in Chicago to
the harassed and harassing professor of ``Oleanna.'' That he knows
how to talk the talk, with enough confidence to shade it in
unexpected ways, is not in question.
</P>
<P>
   But as anyone knows who has seen Macy's sterling work in films
like ``Fargo'' and the current ``Magnolia,'' his particular
strength is in conveying a brittle anxiety. No matter what heinous
deeds his characters perpetrate, they exude the sense of someone
who expects to be caught out any minute. His performances may be
pitched just short of the snapping point, but he usually seems more
on the verge of collapse and confession than explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Applying this sweaty self-consciousness to Teach isn't
inappropriate. It certainly makes you see the character from a
fresh angle, and it's fun watching the variations on the dance of
aggression and retreat that provides the central rhythm of Macy's
performance.
</P>
<P>
   But you can't imagine this skinny fellow, who with his
slicked-back hair and hopelessly unsuave mustache looks like a
dropout from a school for gigolos, selling anyone on any idea,
especially not the sturdy, seasoned junk store owner played by
Hall. This Teach backs down as quickly as an undersized schoolyard
bully, and when he finally erupts into violence, your inclination
is less to shrink back than to drape your arm over his shoulders
and mutter, ``There, there.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the dynamic of this ``Buffalo'' feels more like a lope
than a stampede. Hall's Don, who presides over Kevin Rigdon's
spectacularly cluttered secondhand store setting, is tough but also
benignly paternal. And the young Webber, who gives a beautifully
natural-feeling interpretation, seems to radiate an almost
untarnished innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, the three performances give off a strangely sweet,
likable quality, but there's not much urgency to them. The evening
as a whole has a puzzling feeling of distance, when what I remember
from earlier versions of the play is how it grabbed you by the
lapels.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage of this distance is that it does let you savor the
music of Mamet's ingeniously shaped sentences, with their cadenced
twists and repetitions. It's a pleasure, for instance, to hear
Hall's Don talking on the phone, saying, ``Lookit, Sir, if I could
get ahold of some of the stuff you were interested in, would you be
interested in some of it?'' Or Macy's Teach, after making an
awkward apology, defensively asking, ``What do you want me to do?
Dress up and lick him all over?''
</P>
<P>
   It all makes a pleasant, faintly academic night at the theater.
Pleasant? Academic? It seems hard to believe that the play under
discussion is ``American Buffalo.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `AMERICAN BUFFALO'
</P>
<P>
   By David Mamet; directed by Neil Pepe; set by Kevin Rigdon;
costumes by Laura Bauer; lighting by Howard Werner; fight director,
Rick Sordelet; production stage manager, Darcy Stephens; production
manager, Richard Burgess; general manager, Bardo S. Ramirez.
Presented by the Atlantic Theater Company, Pepe, artistic director;
Hilary Hinckle, managing director.
</P>
<P>
   With: Philip Baker Hall (Don), Mark Webber (Bobby) and William
H. Macy (Teach).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
