<HEADER>
A8959 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SPRAWL17-COX     03-16 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRAWL17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MORE SPRAWL UNAVOIDABLE, ACADEMICS SAY
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ More suburban sprawl in Texas and the Southeast
appears unavoidable, a group of Harvard University urban planners
warned Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``No growth is not an option,'' Nicolas Retsinas, director of
the Joint Center for Housing Studies at Harvard's graduate schools
of design and government, said at a Capitol Hill luncheon. Not only
will the number of Americans double within the next century, he
said, but immigration will add to population pressures.
</P>
<P>
   The growth will not be spread evenly across the country.
California will lead the way, but Texas, Georgia and Florida will
be among the other rapidly growing states, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And because the number of households is growing even faster than
the population, housing needs will escalate.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing a trend that began at the end of World War II, most
of this housing growth will be horizontal rather than vertical,
Retsinas said. Already, the growth in non-metro areas is about as
rapid as in cities and their suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   At the luncheon, Retsinas and other academics spoke to a handful
of lawmakers attending a ``Congressional Initiative for Livable
Communities.'' The initiative's goal is to develop a federal
response to the problems of sprawl that have plagued expanding
metropolitan areas such as Atlanta and Austin: two-hour commutes,
disappearing farmland, and strip-mall architecture described as
``suburban acne.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprawl is a product of prosperity, the planners said. A record
67 percent of households now own homes, and buyers want bigger
houses. The median size for a new home in 1998 was 2,200 square
feet, compared to 1,500 square feet in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Also, more families can afford two or more cars, the planners
said. That makes living in the exurbs more feasible _ and
exacerbates sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   But sprawl is not restricted to the prosperous. In some rapidly
growing areas, high-density rental apartment complexes are being
built on what was recently pasture.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs as well as people are moving outward, he said, as the
concept of cities as employment centers is changing. Increasingly,
people are working as well as living in medium- to low-density
counties.
</P>
<P>
   To control sprawl, cities must be made more liveable, said Rep.
Robert Weygand, D-R.I., a landscape architect. To that end, federal
programs to improve urban schools, fight urban crime, stimulate
urban job growth and improve urban housing could all be considered
part of an anti-sprawl policy.
</P>
<P>
   The planners said Congress should also encourage regional
governmental planning for growth. In the West and South, the
populations are not only going to grow faster but also will be
composed more of Hispanics and Asians, Retsinas said, and the needs
of these areas will differ from those in the slower-growing
Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
