<HEADER>
A8963 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MAT-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      03-16 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAT-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BEYOND THE MAT': IDOLS TO LOOK DOWN ON, SOMETIMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine the level of a mind that watches wrestling?''
huffs the supercilious Max von Sydow in Woody Allen's ``Hannah and
Her Sisters.'' The director Barry W. Blaustein includes that clip
in ``Beyond the Mat,'' his documentary tracking his own obsession
with professional wrestling, a devotion that began at age 8. His
apparently is just the sort of mind that watches wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   The sport is ``theater at its most basic,'' says Blaustein, who
also narrates and appears in the film. Theater at its most base is
probably closer to the point. Blaustein doesn't dwell on the
history of wrestling since his fascination began, when it was a de
facto pro sports league with wrestlers heaving insults, challenges
and eventually chairs at each other.
</P>
<P>
   He moves through that quickly to get to Vince McMahon, the
hustler-savant behind the World Wrestling Federation, who made pro
wrestling even more shameless, a concept you no doubt thought
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   McMahon, who has the doughy, slightly gone-to-seed good looks of
a 1950s movie star after a few too many helpings of his favorite,
chicken pesto pasta, at the WWF. Cafe, has a keen description of
what the federation does. ``What we're really about: we make
movies,'' he says with the self-satisfied smirk he constantly wears
_ movies for the kind of people who find the nuanced character
development of the later ``Kickboxer'' movies to get in the way of
the action.
</P>
<P>
   McMahon is the Willie Wonka of pro wrestling, and his factory
includes in-house costume design and composers flailing away on the
whammy bar of an electric guitar to crank out the volume-crunching
martial rock that would make Wagner wince. (The one thing the
wrestlers all have in common is a toneless, gravelly voice, the
result of forearms and flying drop kicks to the throat.)
</P>
<P>
   After spending a bit of time with McMahon, who is later seen
stepping into the ring as a villain (``Who wouldn't want to beat up
the boss?'' Blaustein says of McMahon's canniness), the director
travels the back roads of pro wrestling to a wrestling school run
by a bearded dumpling who, when not advising his guys to read food
labels for fat content, is training them to join the ranks of the
few, the loud, the WWF.
</P>
<P>
   Blaustein tracks down a childhood idol, the 50-ish Terry Funk,
who hauls his athletic body out of bed and into the ring for
Extreme Championship Wrestling, an organization that Blaustein
calls ``wrestling's Ellis Island'' but is more like the sport's
Island of Broken Toys.
</P>
<P>
   Blaustein is interested in families. He offers a portrait of
Mankind (Mick Foley), the pudgy behemoth who once wrestled in a
mask that looked like something Hannibal Lecter would wear on a
formal night out and is now concerned about the effect of his work
on his loving wife and children.
</P>
<P>
   Then he tracks down Jake Roberts, a part-time father whose days
of blood and glory are behind him. Roberts is reunited with his
20-something daughter, who is wary of her abandoning dad. ``He has
had a lot of encounters with demons,'' a promoter says of Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   This perverse set of family portraits is the way Blaustein wants
to present these wrestlers: as men who are coping, or not, with
real life and the ring. Funk is seen praying at his daughter's
wedding and, a few scenes later, with blood streaming from his
scarred brow at a match. The movie is at its most chilling when
Funk, with a bloody nose after purposely losing his last match,
bids farewell to the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beyond the Mat'' wants to blend thrills and pathos, getting at
the many sides of what is, as Blaustein describes it, a carny act.
The problem is that he doesn't articulate any of his own thoughts
beyond a few slight asides.
</P>
<P>
   The film is out to display the range of human drama, but his
idea of an insight to end with is that wrestlers ``are just like
you and me, except they're really different.'' If that's the best
he can up with after three years on the road, then he has no
confidence in himself or his subject. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Beyond the Mat' is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It includes on-the-mat violence and
on-camera confessions that some might find disturbing. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `BEYOND THE MAT' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Barry W. Blaustein; director of
photography, Michael Grady; edited by Jeff Werner; music by Nathan
Barr; produced by Brian Grazer, Ron Howard, Michael Rosenberg,
Barry Bloom and Blaustein; released by Lions Gate Films. Running
time: 102 minutes.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Barry W. Blaustein, Vince McMahon, Mick Foley, Terry Funk
and Jake Roberts. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1753EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8965 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-BEYONDTHEMAT-TEX     03-16 0360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BEYONDTHEMAT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SURPRISE MOVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Certain movies deserve two ratings: One for hardcore fans of the
movie's subject, another for people who just couldn't care less.
Consider the rating for this preaching-to-the-converted wrestling
documentary to be an average.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, pro wrestling is hot right now and has thousands,
probably millions, of fans. One of them is former ``Saturday Night
Live'' writer-producer Barry W. Blaustein, who became obsessed
enough with the sports-entertainment phenomenon to write and direct
his own movie about it. Blaustein finagled impressive access to the
wrestling world, and snagged extended time with legend Terry Funk,
current star Mick ``Mankind'' Foley and troubled celebrity Jake
``The Snake'' Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   What does Blaustein do with this access? Provide the
unsurprising revelation that although pro wrestling is completely
staged, the pain that results from the choreographed violence is
real _ and that wrestlers' families often wish they'd find
something else to do for a living. What we don't learn is why these
guys subject themselves to this violence for a living. Often, the
answer is just that they can't think of anything else to do. We
also don't learn why wrestling has become so huge that ``WWF
Smackdown!'' virtually rescued UPN from oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beyond the Mat'' provides the kind of information that can
often be gleaned from Web sites or fanzines, but it does have
plenty of wrestling action thrown in for the faithful. It lapses
into bad taste, though, when it dwells on Mankind's terrified young
daughter as she watches her daddy take a vicious beating in the
ring. It's possible that Blaustein meant this as a cautionary move,
but his lack of irony and his continued enjoyment of the sport
indicate otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Beyond the Mat''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Length: 91 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: Not rated
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-Telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
