   BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Move over, Tom Wolfe. A California banker has a tale
to tell that can rival parts of your last great novel. And, unlike
the fiction-based-on-fact style of Wolfe, this book is more
fact-that-reads-like-fiction. Its people _ from Donald Trump to
Charles Keating to Peter Ueberroth _ are as colorful and flamboyant
and blindly ambitious as any character Wolfe could contrive. It's
story line is as serpentine and unpredictable as a well-devised
plot. And the book is written by a true insider, Robert Smith,
chairman of the board and chief executive of Security Pacific, once
the fifth-largest bank in the United States. The book is called
``Dead Bank Walking: One Gutsy Bank's Struggle for Survival and the
Merger That Changed Banking Forever.'' By TERESA MCUSIC. Story has
moved in ``f'' financial category. &QL; 
