<HEADER>
A8971 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MEXICO-WINE-$ADV19-CO     03-16 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-WINE-$ADV19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MOVE OVER TEQUILA? MEXICO DEVELOPING A NEW ``WINE COUNTRY'' ON
ITS PACIFIC COAST
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    EDs: For locator map purposes, Guadalupe Valley is about 50
miles southeast of San Diego, across the U.S.-Mexico border.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., March 19 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUADALUPE VALLEY, Mexico _ As Victor Torres swished the amber
liquid between his teeth, an expression of joy spread over his
face.
</P>
<P>
   A French-trained winemaker, Torres knew he had a sweet nectar of
exquisite caliber in the making.
</P>
<P>
   Are we talking France here? Maybe Napa Valley?
</P>
<P>
   Neither. Torres is among a new breed of winemakers in the
Guadalupe Valley, a pocket of surprisingly fertile land on the
Pacific Ocean side of Mexico's Baja California. The valley is only
about 50 miles southeast of the border city of San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Blessed by a cooling coastal fog that takes the hot edge off the
region's near-desert terrain, the valley is starting to produce
award-winning wines that are gaining a toehold at upscale
restaurants and among wine lovers on both sides of the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be the Napa Valley of Mexico,'' said Torres, the
winemaker for Chateau Camou, one of about a half-dozen wineries
that have started to produce premiere wines in the valley over the
last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Just down the road from Chateau Camou, winemaker Hans Backhoff,
who grew up in this area, also praises the soil, sun and chilly
nights that create a nourishing micro-climate for grapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the influence of the sea. That's what makes this valley
so special,'' Backhoff said, as he poured a sample of Merlot aging
in a French oak barrel at his winery, Monte Xanic (pronounced,
``Mon-TAY Sha-NEEK'').
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans consume less than half a bottle of wine per person per
year, a figure that's a fraction of what consumers drink in
countries that have a love affair with the grape. Argentineans, for
example, consume around 50 liters per person annually.
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans still produce far more of the ever-popular tequila and
beer. But wine consumption is indeed increasing, buoyed by a taste
for fine wine among Mexican professionals and Baja's homegrown
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Guadalupe Valley is about 10 miles east of the Baja beach
town of Ensenada, which is touting Mexico's new ``wine country'' as
a great place to visit while eating lobster enchiladas and swimming
and surfing. Hotels are stocking fliers on the Guadalupe Valley
now, and offering tours for tasting and to attend a number of
annual festivals. Cruise ships that dock in Ensenada are also
encouraging visitors. The valley's wines are featured now in fine
restaurants in Acapulco, Cancun, Mexico City and a growing number
of American cities.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the oldest winery in this hemisphere started in
Mexico, where in the 1520s Mexico's Spanish conquistadors ordered
1,000 vines planted for every 100 Indians forced to work for them.
</P>
<P>
   Then Spain, fearing competition from its colony, subsequently
banned vineyards from Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Wine grapes were eventually born again in Mexico, but for
centuries vintners have produced mostly grapes for brandy or for
wine that was mediocre.
</P>
<P>
   Now vintners in Baja California, where most of Mexico's wine
grapes are grown, are getting serious about quality rather than
quantity.
</P>
<P>
   That's the mission of the Guadalupe Valley vintners, including
the oldest of the bunch, Bodegas de Santo Tomas, which was
established in 1888.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 Santo Tomas winemakers teamed up with American friends
in Northern California, a region that was also once considered an
upstart in a world of wines dominated by Europeans. The joint
venture, which first produced 5,000 cases that were released in
1998, was the brainchild of Santo Tomas and Wente Bros., a
century-old winery in the Livermore Valley east of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Christened Duetto, the wine is a blend of 50 percent Mexican and
50 percent California grapes. It is bottled in Mexico, and thus
escapes tariffs on U.S. wine imports that are hovering at about 8
percent now. A high-quality red wine mix of Cabernet Sauvignon,
Cabernet Franc and Merlot, Duetto's first vintage sold out in a
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico has the quality of the grapes. They have everything to
produce a good wine. That's for sure,'' said Marc Bourreli, Wente's
director of Latin American exports.
</P>
<P>
   This year, for the first time, 1,000 cases of Duetto will be
released in the U.S. market for retail sale and stocking at
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Torres and Backhoff's wines are also heading north.
</P>
<P>
   Backhoff, a British-trained food scientist, said he made wine as
a hobby in Baja California before getting together a group of
investors in 1987 and opening up Monte Xanic. Housed in a classic
stone building, the winery has a tasting room featuring white and
red wines that are now on wine lists in restaurants in New York,
Colorado, Arizona, California and Florida. Backhoff's wines have
picked up awards at a number of California festivals in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   The Henry Wine Group is distributing Monte Xanic now to
retailers and the Napa Valley-based Chalone Wine Group is offering
bottles of the wine to its shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Backhoff said he and his partners thought of the name of their
winery after spring rains prompted beautiful desert flowers to
bloom throughout the valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want a French name,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So they chose Xanic, which in an Indian language means ``the
first flower that blooms after the rain,'' Backhoff said. ``It's
Mexican. But it doesn't sound like tequila or tacos.''
</P>
<P>
   The vineyard is 175 acres, he added, and some of the vines are
40 years old. Part of the vineyard was previously owned by a family
of Russian descent, which took up grape growing like other Russian
immigrants to Baja California at the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Xanic's wines range from US$15 to US$100. Only about 3 percent
of the product is exported, but Backhoff expects exports to climb
to 6 percent this year. Tariffs are low on Mexican wine imports to
the United States and if Mexican vintners export their wines, they
get a substantial tax break at home.
</P>
<P>
   Chateau Camou's wines are being carried by the United States'
Wine Warehouse and can be found in Chicago, Washington and this
year, the company hopes, Texas. Prices range from US$6 to more than
US$100 for wines that have won awards in French competitions in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The winery, which was founded in 1985, is constructing a new
mission-style building and its tasting room is also open for
tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Torres said he is particularly proud of his white wines _
Chardonnay and Chenin Blanc _ which many experts believe Mexican
soil simply cannot produce.
</P>
<P>
   One of Torres' white wine blends, Flor de Guadalupe, recently
beat California whites in a competition north of the border, Torres
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that was one of our lower-end wines,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Torres is equally proud of the French techniques he uses, such
as gently agitating the wine periodically with a stick while it
ferments in French oak barrels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why change something that's worked for more than 200 years?''
Torres said. ``We're trying to combine tradition with modern
techniques.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
