<HEADER>
A8975 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ART-NOTES-NYT &LR;      03-16 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Mass., D.C.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once Radical, Now Recherche
</P>
<P>
   A group of contemporary artworks from what Sotheby's describes
only as a private European collection are to be auctioned May 17 in
New York at Sotheby's as part of a wider evening sale of
contemporary art. The works, dating from 1965 to 1971, range from
Minimalist sculpture and painting to Conceptual photography and
neon installations. The entire collection is expected to sell for
about $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most prized works is Bruce Nauman's ``Light Trap for
Henry Moore, No. 1'' (1967), a black-and-white photograph made by
twirling a flashlight in a darkened room and recording the glowing
spirals. It is expected to sell for $250,000 to $350,000. The
artist's catalog raisonne says it is from the collection of Angelo
Baldassarre, who is thought to be the seller of the collection.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Europeans buying art in the mid-1960s and early '70s,
the collector evidently had a taste for radical American art.
``Unlike so many Americans of that period, who were thrust into the
Vietnam War and looking for peace through art by buying Color Field
paintings or Pop Art, Europeans were championing more radical
artists,'' said Tobias Meyer, director of contemporary art for
Sotheby's worldwide. ``Their thinking was all about the future.
They were trying to forget the past.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes this collection particularly desirable, Meyer added,
is that the works were bought right after they were made and few
were ever exhibited.
</P>
<P>
   The collection includes sculptures and installation pieces by
Donald Judd, Carl Andre, Richard Serra and Dan Flavin as well as
Nauman. There are also paintings by Robert Ryman and Brice Marden
and photographs by John Baldessari.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rain Forest,'' a 1971 painting by Marden, is expected to sell
for $1.5 million to $2 million. It is a three-panel abstract work
with lush gray-green tones reminiscent of a tropical landscape. A
classic floor piece by Andre with alternating metal plates has an
estimate of $300,000 to $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   For the National Gallery
</P>
<P>
   Once a year at the National Gallery of Art in Washington, a
group that calls itself the Collectors Committee asks curators to
present works of art they feel the Gallery should have to enrich
its holdings. Led by Barney A. Ebsworth, a St. Louis collector who
is a trustee, and Doris Fisher, the San Francisco collector who is
a co-founder of the Gap clothing stores with her husband, Donald,
the group votes on what works the institution needs most.
</P>
<P>
   This year's choices were described by Earl A. Powell III, the
gallery's director, as mainstream modern.
</P>
<P>
   By far the most important is an Andy Warhol self-portrait from
1986. A large-scale silk-screen _ it measures 80 inches square _
the painting depicts the artist with his signature fright wig in
four head shots in a palette of pink and yellow. The committee
bought it from the Gagosian Gallery in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had very good early Warhols but no late ones,'' Powell
said. ``This is a particularly spectacular image.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee also gave the gallery several other works,
including a drawing by the Abstract Expressionist painter Ad
Reinhardt, a portfolio of 15 photographs published in 1974 by Garry
Winogrand and a 1966 photograph by David Lyon.
</P>
<P>
   Big Gift in Boston
</P>
<P>
   As the Institute of Contemporary Art in Boston ambitiously tries
to raise $50 million _ $30 million of it for a new building on the
waterfront at Fan Pier, the first new major cultural institution to
go up in Boston in nearly 100 years _ it has received a lead gift
of $5 million from the Barbara Lee Family Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, where taste is famously conservative, Lee's gift is
among the largest ever given to an arts institution. ``For
contemporary art, it's off the charts,'' said Jill Medvedow, the
institute's director. Lee, a trustee for 10 years, is honorary
chairman of the campaign for the new building.
</P>
<P>
   Medvedow said the museum was beginning an international search
for an architect. If things proceed on schedule, the
60,000-square-foot museum should open in about four years.
</P>
<P>
   A New Sotheby's Team
</P>
<P>
   With the widening federal antitrust investigation that led to
the resignations of Sotheby's chairman, A. Alfred Taubman, and its
president and chief executive, Diana D. Brooks, the new president
and chief executive, William F. Ruprecht, is beginning to put his
team in place.
</P>
<P>
   This week the auction house announced that Warren P. Weitman,
who has been at Sotheby's since 1978 in several positions,
including head of business development and vice chairman for North
and South America, had been named chairman for North and South
America.
</P>
<P>
   Weitman replaces Richard Oldenburg, a former director of the
Museum of Modern Art in New York, who became chairman in 1995.
Oldenburg will be affiliated with Sotheby's as honorary chairman.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves one important management slot open: managing
director for Sotheby's North and South America, the job Ruprecht
held before his promotion last month. Asked when that job would be
filled, Matthew Weigman, a spokesman for Sotheby's, said, ``We
expect a management structure to be announced soon.''
</P>
<P>
   An Equitable Change
</P>
<P>
   In September, Equitable Cos. changed its name to AXA Financial
Inc. to underscore the broader range of services it has offered
clients since the Paris-based company AXA bought a controlling
interest in Equitable in 1991. So it makes sense that the Equitable
Gallery in Manhattan at 787 Seventh Ave., at 52nd Street, should
change its name, too. It will now be known as the AXA Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea to change the gallery's name evolved over time,''
said Pari Stave, its director. ``It's to show that the company as a
whole is aligned with a global brand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1758EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
