<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 UPDATE &HT;    UPDATES
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Friday, March 17,
2000.
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eds. Adds: SCFLAG, BAXTER-CONVERTS
</P>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUDOLPH _ Update on Eric Rudolph search pegged to FBI Director
Louis Freeh's appearance Thursday before Congressional
appropriations subcommittee. (Manuel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SCFLAG - CHARLESTON _ Mayor Joe Riley of Charleston, S.C.,
worried about the effect the dispute over the Confederate flag is
having all over South Carolina, plans a major march to Columbia,
the state capital, to demand the flag be brought down. (Burritt,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   STPATS-SAVANNAH _ Advancing St. Patrick's Day activities in
Savannah, which hosts the nation's second largest celebration.
Weather threatens the party, but organizers still expect it to be
the largest ever. Efforts continue to cut down on the debauchery,
such as smaller beers and the purchase of only one at a time.
(Chapman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   STPATS-IRISHBEER _ Story about Irish beers and green beers, tied
to St. Patrick's Day. With lists of toasts, Irish beers, etc. (Waco
Tribune Herald). 24. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DNA-TESTING _ ATLANTA _ Georgia will become a national leader in
DNA testing now that legislation to create a state DNA database has
all but cleared the General Assembly. The program will be phased in
gradually, depending on funding. Supporters say it will reduce the
number of innocent people convicted of crimes and serve as a
powerful deterrent. Story looks at how the samples would be taken
and stored and prospects for the phase-in to all felons. we take a
look at how the GBI would put the data base to use. Exactly how
would samples we taken? Cost per sample? Storage costs? Other
state's experiences with DNA databases? Georgia apparently would
become one of the five leading states in the country in DNA
testing. Could the new database have an impact on Georgia's death
penalty situation (particularly after Illinois governor's
moratorium on executions)? Also will talk further with ACLU about
its reservations. (Mantius/Harvey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-GLITCHES _ ATLANTA _ The U.S. Bureau of the Census's 2000
count has had a few glitches, causing some to wonder how accurate
the count will be if the agency has problems just getting the forms
mailed. (Cook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   FLOYD-LESSONS _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ September's flooding
disrupted school for thousands of students and uprooted hundreds
more. What do attendance figures, class grades and test scores
indicate about how the youth of Pitt County have handled this
trauma? How many kids shifted schools (temporary and permanent)?
Have the teachers taken it easy on flood victim students?
(Jakubowski, Greenville Daily Reflector). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Third of six installments looking at Eastern North
Carolina's recovery from Hurricane Floyd on the six-month
anniversary of the storm.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-CONVERTS _What a year for conversions. Already, the Pope
has apologized for such excesses as the Inquisition, Bob Jones
University has allowed interracial dating, and Vice President Al
Gore is running on campaign finance reform. (Baxter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   AIRPORT-SECURITY _ WASHINGTON _ Passenger screening is the
weakest link in airport security systems, the House aviation
subcommittee was told Thursday. Witnesses said the main reason is
high turnover in the low-paying jobs. (Turay, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   SPRAWL _ WASHINGTON _ Harvard Univerity's Department of Urban
Planning and Design and its Joint Center for Housing Studies
release a report on the federal government's role and
responsibility in controlling urban sprawl. Also Thursday, the
National Association of Realtors hold a news conference to discuss
the role of consumers and real estate agents in community growth
management. (Dart, Cox News Service). 22.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TRIP _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton leaves Saturday
for a weeklong swing through the Indian subcontinent, where he'll
try to shore up badly strained U.S.-India ties and prevent an
Indian-Pakistani security crises from escalating into catastrophe.
Clinton, who will also promote grassroots development in the
impoverished country of Bangladesh, will be the first president to
visit the region since Jimmy Carter's trip in 1978. (Deans, Cox
News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   INDIAHOTEL-CLINTON _ NEW DELHI, India _ The staff of the Maurya
Sheraton hotel in New Delhi has been working around the clock to
prepare for President Clinton''s visit, the first by a U.S.
president since Jimmy Carter. (Basu, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CARE-BELL _ CARE President Peter Bell returns from a trip to
Chile where he spent time with an old friend, the country's new
president. (Melvin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
