</P>
<P>
   (5th of 9-part special Economist Survey, `The New Americans') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is the hyphenated American (e.g., Mexican-American) giving way
to the ampersand one (Mexican &AMP; American)? A recent poll by the
Washington Post of 2,500 Latinos showed that nine out of ten who
have newly arrived in America think it is important to change to
fit in. But nine out of ten also think it is important to retain
part of their ethnic culture. With third-generation Latinos, this
proportion rises to 98 percent...By John Micklethwait, The
Economist &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Four trims, totaling 1,050 words; total uncut is 2,100) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A RAW DEAL: AMERICA'S SCHOOLS COULD SERVE IMMIGRANTS BETTER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SURVEY-6-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (6th of 9-part special Economist Survey, `The New Americans') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's learner is tomorrow's leader.'' The motto of Public
School 220 in Queens, N.Y., would do nicely for most New Americans.
Many of the notes pinned on the school's bulletin boards _ sample:
``Snowflakes are different, and so are we'' _ hint at the
challenges of trying to teach students who between them speak 26
foreign languages at home. Bilingual education is only part of the
problem, but it is indicative of the raw deal immigrants are
getting from America's education system...By John Micklethwait, The
Economist &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (775 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS SLOWLY AWAKENS TO THE NEXT AMERICA &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
