<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8986 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOMA-EXHIBIT-2TAKES-A     03-16 1313
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOMA-EXHIBIT-2TAKES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MAKING CHOICES': FOUR DECADES AT MOMA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to New York Times photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Here we go again. ``Making Choices,'' the second
segment of ``MOMA 2000,'' the self-reflective (navel-gazing?)
trilogy of exhibition cycles with which the Museum of Modern Art is
greeting the millennium, has begun its staged landing. Its subtitle
indicates what is in store in this second round: ``24 Exhibitions
of Modern Art From 1920 to 1960.'' Eleven can be seen now, three
more open on March 30 and the remaining 10 on April 30.
</P>
<P>
   The trilogy began last fall with ``Modern Starts: People, Places
and Things,'' which considered mostly European art from 1880 to
1920 and was organized by a team of curators led by John
Elderfield, chief curator at large at the museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making Choices,'' which looks at the next four decades, has
been overseen by Peter Galassi, chief curator of the museum's
photography department, working with Robert Storr and Anne Umland,
respectively senior curator and associate curator in the department
of painting and sculpture. Surrealism, the Bauhaus and the
International Style, the rise of photography, advertising and the
movies, Abstract Expressionism and the first stirrings of Pop Art
and Minimalism, as well as the founding of the Modern itself _ all
fall within the exhibition's purview; most are examined or touched
on in this opening gambit of shows, or will be in those to come.
</P>
<P>
   After the 24 shows close (also in stages) beginning in late
August, a curatorial team headed by Kirk Varnedoe, chief curator of
the department of painting and sculpture, will present the final
installment, ``Open Ends,'' which will bring art up to the present.
</P>
<P>
   This project is much more than a historical survey of the 120
years spanned by the Modern's collection divided into three neat
slices. It is an enormous and free-form stock-taking during which
the Modern's curators have been given carte blanche to sort through
the collection and mix things up, mingling media in a way that is
still out of character for the Modern, and to bring in works from
other periods when germane.
</P>
<P>
   Their mission, not impossible at all, is to experiment with the
Modern's vaunted collection in ways that move beyond the museum's
highly influential, largely linear, style-by-style and
medium-by-medium presentation of that collection. The pressures to
do this come from all directions: the end of the century whose art
history the Modern so prominently defined; the far more porous,
nonlinear definition of modernism lately proposed by postmodern
theorists and art historians, and the pending expansion of the
museum's building, which will give the institution more space in
which to tell a fuller story.
</P>
<P>
   Elderfield gave ``Modern Starts'' a unifying concept, dividing
the art according to the traditional artistic subjects of people,
places and things. Yet beneath the thematic umbrella, his team's
20-odd shows often lurched between extremes of homogeneity,
monotony and discord. One saw things that seemed unprecedented for
the Modern: a gallery, painted dark green, full of late 19th- and
early 20th-century figurative, mostly bronze sculptures, another
gallery devoted exclusively to paintings made in Paris during World
War I. The shows seemed to smash the Modern's traditional narrative
to smithereens, but they still managed to keep most of modernism's
big names front and center.
</P>
<P>
   The curators of ``Making Choices'' have avoided any overriding
concept and instead have strung together a series of medium-size
theme shows punctuated by small ones devoted to single artists,
organized by themselves and other curators. One could say that what
was rent asunder by ``Modern Starts'' is here being judiciously
reassembled and reconfigured. Iconoclasm has given way to inspired
tinkering and readjustment. Nothing feels too long, too homogenous
or too discordant. Everything looks plausible as a Museum of Modern
Art show, and an exceptional one at that: temperate, beautifully
installed, thought through.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a complex game is quietly afoot. While pulverization has
been avoided, there has been a concerted effort to level the
playing field, to take modernism out of the hands of the anointed
few and show it to be an effort of hundreds of people working alone
or together in a range of styles and media.
</P>
<P>
   ``Choices'' is the operative word. Especially level, is the book
that accompanies but does not catalog the exhibition. It is a
compendium that reproduces 306 works in all media from the Modern's
holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Each was made in one of four years that the curators have deemed
historically and aesthetically significant: 1929, 1939, 1948 or
1955. The point of these ``core samples'' is to ignore not only the
Modern's version of modern art history but any version, to simply
show that in art as in life everything is happening at once, all
the time. ``History is flux,'' states the brief introduction, ``a
vast matrix almost inconceivably extensive and almost inconceivably
dense.''
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to convey and to organize some of that flux for
the viewer, the shows unfold with carefully calibrated shifts in
subject, size, visual rhythm and also curatorial strategy.
</P>
<P>
   In ``War,'' organized by Storr, subject matter reigns, and the
century's major conflicts are often wrenchingly evoked. But its
weight is relieved by what comes next: the ivory-tower purity of a
small exhibition of Giorgio Morandi's landscape and still-life
etchings organized by Starr Figura, assistant curator of prints and
illustrated books.
</P>
<P>
   Other small shows focus on the efforts of artists who rarely get
top billing: the quiet polymathic work _ paintings, relief, poetry,
sculpture _ of Jean Arp (organized by Umland); the consistently
sultry innovative photographs of Man Ray (organized by Virginia
Heckert, a curatorial fellow in the photography department); and
the late 1950s and '60s designs of the architect Louis I. Kahn, who
looked past the glass curtain wall to the monolithic forms of
ancient architecture for inspiration. (In this show, organized by
Peter Reed of the architecture and design department, don't miss
the big, pulsating drawing of a grid whereby Kahn re-envisioned the
traffic patterns of downtown Philadelphia.) A quibble: taken as a
group, these artists are a tad on the quiet side. It might have
been nice to isolate a straining-at-the-leash type like Otto Dix,
who does appear in several shows.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout these exhibitions media are regularly and often
imaginatively mixed; every gallery features two and usually more.
The Surrealist half of Storr's ``Dream of Utopia/Utopia of the
Dream'' (in the lead for worst-title prize) includes paintings,
drawings, sculptures and photographs by artists ranging from Ernst
and Magritte to Horst P. Horst to the recently resurrected sculptor
Maria Martins. There is also a vitrine of Surrealist publications
illustrated by many of the same artists _ something probably never
done at the Modern.
</P>
<P>
   When things do turn homogenous, they still feel fresh, as with
the large group of tubular-steel furniture in ``Modern Living 1,''
which demonstrates how many designers and architects responded to a
new material. This show, organized by Matilda McQuaid and
Christopher Mount, associate curator and assistant curator of
architecture and design respectively, concludes with an unannounced
one-artist cluster: a series of textiles and textile designs by
Anni Albers. It's great to see, especially after the intriguing
sight of a single Albers drawing among works by Klee, Kandinsky and
Sophie Taeuber-Arp in the Bauhaus part of ``The Dream of
Utopia/Utopia of the Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There are few overexposed masterpieces (although it will be
interesting to see if every part of the ``MOMA 2000'' trilogy must
include Meret Oppenheim's fur-lined teacup; so far it is two for
two.) There are surprising works by known, lesser-known and unknown
artists in nearly every gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Regard the labels. Often, a work that appears to be by one
artist is actually by someone unexpected. For example, in
``Graphic/Photographic,'' a 1921 graphic design that looks right at
home next to one of Kurt Schwitters' designs for his magazine,
Merz, turns out to be by the Surrealist Pavel Tchelitchew, who
would later paint ``Hide and Seek,'' one of the Modern's two most
popular paintings. Their juxtaposition is typical of this dense,
smallish show, organized by Galassi and Mount. They examine the
overlap of photography and graphic design between the wars through
the efforts of a large and diverse cast of sensibilities, from
August Sander to Florence Henri, and the Stenberg brothers to
Herbert Bayer.
</P>
<P>
   The two most ambitious shows, each accompanied by its own thick
catalog, are Storr's ``Modern Art Despite Modernism'' and Galassi's
``Walker Evans &AMP; Co.'' Storr's effort concentrates entirely on
figurative art, reminding us that the Modern has always collected
art that might be called nonmodern or antimodern, along with the
so-called modern kind. Depending on how one you enters Storr's
show, it opens with three Balthus paintings, or a marvelously dark
Matissean still-life-with-window that is actually by Andre Derain.
Later one encounters the ever-popular ``Hide and Seek'' and Andrew
Wyeth's ``Christina's World.'' Drawings and prints are plentiful,
which stresses the artists' different formal approaches over their
shared subject matter. In one of the best drawings a 20-year-old
Jean Dubuffet brings off a neo-Classical portrait to rival those,
nearby, of Braque and Picasso.
</P>
<P>
   At times Storr seems to incline toward the Modern of old: a wall
of German Expressionists here, a wall of weird American realists
(Ivan Albright, Paul Cadmus) there. But the Germans are in a
gallery that includes an enchanting self-portrait by a little-known
Mexican artist named Jose Pancetti, works by Frida Kahlo and Diego
Rivera, and the paintings of Walter Sickert, Gwen John and Stanley
Spencer, British English artists rarely seen in these parts. And
the wall of Americans includes Honore Sharrer's jewel-like
``Workers People and Paintings,'' which shows a dark little main
street lined with people of different races and cultures, all
examining well-known, brightly- colored paintings, among them ` one
of the Modern's Picassos, ``Girl Before a Mirror.'' Man cannot live
by bread alone, it seems to say.
</P>
<P>
   Another surprise is ``Young Man in the Sun,'' an exquisite
drawing on pale green paper made in 1935 by Carl Pickhardt. It
jibes perfectly with a work in the next gallery, Alex Katz's
drawing of a young sunbather, ``Boy With a Hat,'' from 1974. One of
Storr's ideas, filled out in the catalog and unfortunately
truncated in the show, is that the Modern's buried strain of
figuration sets the stage for the recent return of representation.
He has squeezed in some contemporary work, including a fabulous new
portrait by Jim Nutt, two late-40's portraits by Lucian Freud and,
less impressively, work by Komar and Melamid and Troy Brauntuch.
But it is not enough. It is too bad that there was no room for
David Salle's ``Muscular Paper,'' from 1985, detailed on the
catalog's title page, which the Modern acquired in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walker Evans &AMP; Co.'' is in many ways the standout of the
opening 11, in part because Galassi has the room to follow his
thesis into the present. On the face of things his show looks like
an attempt to validate Evans as the Jackson Pollock or Pablo
Picasso of American photography. And indeed, this show presents
Evans as a highly influential artist who helped establish the
uninflected documentation of America _ its people, architecture,
well-worn interiors, towns, storefronts, signage and advertising _
as a worthy artistic subject.
</P>
<P>
   But Galassi does this with an unusual inclusiveness, mixing
Evans' work with that of 100 other photographers and artists.
Crediting Evans' forebears and his contemporaries, Galassi suggests
that no artist acts alone. He then widens his scope, showing how
Evans is a precedent not only for such great photographers as
Robert Frank, Lee Friedlander and Diane Arbus, but also for Pop Art
and photo appropriation, as well as for the sculpture of Robert
Gober and the architecture of Robert Venturi.
</P>
<P>
   Thus this show tracks an amazing complex map of influence. It
shows not a single line or a straight one, but a series of
branches, crossing and recrossing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Modern Art Despite Modernism'' and ``Walker Evans &AMP; Co.'' say
emphatically and in considerable detail what seems to be the
underlying message of all the other shows, that it is almost all
here in this museum if we just figure out how to use it. One hopes
that the next 13 shows will reveal the tangled path of art with
such clarity.
</P>
<P>
   As the ``MOMA 2000'' trilogy proceeds, it is emerging as a
series of curatorial points and counterpoints, a meditation on the
curator's art. It is also a kind of exquisite corpse. Its different
parts are being created autonomously and asthey unfold, each fits
with the others in ways that are giving the Modern and its audience
plenty to think about.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
