<HEADLINE>
`FARSCAPE': AN OFF-KILTER OUTER-SPACE SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lh) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I'm just looking for a way home,'' says the earthling
astronaut John Crichton during the opening credits of ``Farscape.''
At the rate he's going, he'll never make it. But that would be just
fine with the fans of this off-kilter outer-space series, which
begins its second season Friday night on the Sci-Fi Channel.
Invigorated by the show's weekly jolt of imagination overload, they
hope that Crichton (played by Ben Browder) keeps drifting through
the void with a mismatched bunch of intergalactic fugitives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farscape,'' created by Rockne S. O'Bannon and packaged by the
fantasymeisters at the Jim Henson Company and Hallmark
Entertainment, has more familiar elements than a periodic table.
You'll find echoes of ``The Odyssey'' and ``Les Miserables,'' of
``The Wizard of Oz'' and ``Gilligan's Island,'' and compounds
distilled from ``Star Wars,'' ``Star Trek'' and maybe even
Starbucks. Still, there's something special about this mixture: a
grin-inducing strain of inspiration that seems to say, simply,
``Sit there, and I'll tell you a story.''
</P>
<P>
   That story can get a bit complicated. Here's some of what has
happened so far:
</P>
<P>
   Crichton is being hounded through space by Crais (Lani John
Tupu), a renegade from a powerful bunch of warriors called the
Peacekeepers. Crais' brother was killed in an accidental collision
with Crichton's off-course module; Crais craves revenge.
</P>
<P>
   Now Crichton is trying to escape aboard Moya, a living leviathan
spaceship who can get kind of moody, especially when she's worried
about the safety and whereabouts of her son, Talyn, who was born at
the end of last season. Although Moya can more than think for
herself, she is piloted by Pilot (a Muppet with a voice supplied by
Tupu), who is organically attached to Moya and couldn't leave his
post if he wanted to, which he wouldn't anyway. Would you?
</P>
<P>
   The fate of Crichton, who looks like your typical sandy-haired
action hero, is bound to those of his fellow travelers. The
strongest and smartest of the bunch (Crichton included) is Aeryn
Sun (Claudia Black), a runaway Peacekeeper, who looks like your
typical unbelievably fit raven-haired commando in skintight togs.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Ka D'Argo (Anthony Simcoe), a hulking Luxan, a sort
of huge bear with an owl's face and a seminarian's hunger for moral
truth; Pa'u Zotoh Zhaan (Virginia Hey), a blue bald-headed Delvian
priestess; Chiana (Gigi Edgley), a quick-witted
tattletale-gray-skinned sylph who wears very little and talks like
a valley girl (although one cannot imagine just which valley); and
the beach-ball-size Rygel XVI (voice by Jonathan Hardy), who can't
get used to losing a king's perks, even though he was overthrown
250 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night's episode picks up where the first season ended,
with the refugees fleeing not only Crais but the unspeakably evil
Scorpius (Wayne Pygram), a cadaverous fellow whose head is secured
inside headgear that looks as if he stole it from a World War I
flying ace. The sight of Scorpius having some sort of glowing
crystal inside his head replaced through the side of his helmet is,
to say the least, memorable. (The series manages to proffer a
couple of such dandy visual effects each week.)
</P>
<P>
   Crais promises to leave Crichton and company alone if Crais can
make off with Talyn, the baby ship. Asked what he wants, Crais
replies, ``Simply to escape, to travel deeper into the uncharted
territories, to re-examine my path.''
</P>
<P>
   Crichton replies: ``You want to have a midlife crisis, fine.
Just ditch the firm, head off to Maui, shack up with the
supermodel. But you do not get to keep the Porsche. You don't get
the keys to Moya's baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Crais can't seem to make sense of the references. But making
literal sense isn't what this show is about. It's about friendship
and doing your best and knowing right from wrong. Or something. You
try to figure it out. Like Crichton, you may not always know where
you're going, but you'll surely remember the journey.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `FARSCAPE'
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. ET Fridays on the Sci-Fi Channel
</P>
<P>
   David Kemper, Brian Henson, Rod Perth and Robert Halmi Jr.,
executive producers; Naren Shankar and Richard Manning,
co-executive producers; Ian Watson, Andrew Prowse, Tony Tilse,
Rowan Woods and Catherine Millar, directors; Rockne S. O'Bannon,
executive consultant; Justin Monjo, creative consultant; Gabrielle
Stanton and Harry Werksman, executive story editors; Lily Taylor,
story editor; Russell Bacon, director of photography.
</P>
<P>
   With: Ben Browder (Cmdr. John Crichton), Claudia Black (Officer
Aeryn Sun), Anthony Simcoe (Ka D' Argo), Virginia Hey (Pa'u Zotoh
Zhaan), Gigi Edgley (Chiana), Tim Mieville and Jonathan Hardy
(Rygel XVI), Sean Masterson and Lani John Tupu (Pilot), Tupu (Capt.
Bialar Crais) and Wayne Pygram (Scorpius).
</P>
</TEXT>
