<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GENDER POLITICS IS HERE TO STAY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Here we go again: What do women want, anyway? Not
exactly what men do, that's for sure.
</P>
<P>
   This has nothing to do with Freud, that ignoramus. We're talking
politics here, folks, not hanky-panky.
</P>
<P>
   The gender gap that first appeared in the 1980 presidential
election when Ronald Reagan swept the country is still with us.
Reagan's macho manner and his campaign appeal to Southern white
males split the sexes, winning over a majority of men but turning
off a majority of women.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Democratic presidential candidates have consistently
done better at the polls with women than have Republican
candidates. President Clinton enjoyed an 11-point advantage among
women in 1996, the largest ever in a presidential election and the
single most important factor to his re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes a new USA Today-CNN-Gallup poll that shows if the
election were held today, 15 percent more women than men would vote
for Vice President Al Gore, while 12 percent more men than women
would vote for Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The funny part is that a year ago, polls showed the reverse,
with 12 percent more women backing Bush than Gore. In those golden
days, however, Bush was beating the socks off Gore everywhere in
every way. It couldn't last, and didn't. The two contenders are,
overall, in a statistical dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   Republican strategists talk a great deal about wooing female
voters but they don't know how to go about it. They take a
patronizing view toward our political intelligence. If the GOP just
softens its campaign language to sound more family-friendly, they
figure, moms by the carload will come to their senses and desert
the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   It is a cynical strategy, since no accompanying change in policy
is contemplated. The basic GOP platform is stuck in cement: less
government oversight of business practices and massive tax cuts for
the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   Many women do not think concentrating more wealth at the top of
society can improve their own lives, particularly if it means
cutbacks in popular federal domestic programs and services. They
want to hear what the candidates will do for THEM, not for distant
vested interests.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's original theme of ``compassionate conservatism''
specifically had women in mind. But it was too mild and mushy to
stand up under the brutal barrage of insults he exchanged with
Arizona Sen. John McCain, his main primary rival. That message has
been lost for the moment, although Bush will try to return to it.
</P>
<P>
   Words are not enough. Policies matter, and so do personalities.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have done well with female voters because they have
emphasized education, health care reform, the environment, gun
control and Social Security protection.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, men see politics through the prism of economic
prospects and their workday jobs. Women hold outside jobs too but
are also more directly involved in family responsibilities _
raising children, caring for elderly relatives, worrying about
health care, fearing random violence and fending off all the
self-appointed moralists who lecture them on how to conduct their
private lives.
</P>
<P>
   Gore understands this. He won the New Hampshire Democratic
primary because women gave him a 53 percent to 47 percent margin
over Bill Bradley, while the male vote split evenly.
</P>
<P>
   Bush can go after more male votes or he can try to reach out to
moderate women. He will get conservative women, as he will get
conservative males. But he needs a broader appeal. And his personal
history and his record make the latter tough for him.
</P>
<P>
   There is the gun control problem. As governor, Bush signed bills
allowing Texans to carry concealed _ concealed! _ handguns on the
streets and laws barring local jurisdictions from suing gun
manufacturers to recoup the public health costs of treating gunshot
wounds. He never supported a gun control measure, although now he
suggests he might go for some long-demanded minor ones on the
federal level.
</P>
<P>
   There is the abortion problem. A stand that honors a fetus over
a pregnant woman's life sends a message suggesting the second-class
status of women. Bush initially favored dropping the party's rigid
refusal to make an exception for the health of the mother in its
demand to criminalize abortion. But by the time the religious right
worked him over, he was back at the uncompromising position.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the Social Security-health care issue. Bush's
proposed tax cuts are so enormous that even the Republican
congressional majority could not swallow them this week. The
problem is that he put his tax cuts ahead of concern for Social
Security, and his priorities are in the wrong place.
</P>
<P>
   But so much for the policies. How about the personalities? Aha,
that's another subject, yet to be determined. Women will be
watching.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
