<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISLAND-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TREASURE ISLAND': A CHAOTIC COMEDY ON WORLD WAR II 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the film ``Saving Private Ryan'' and the book ``The
Greatest Generation,'' World War II has made a spectacular public
relations comeback in the last three years as the United States has
finally recovered from the lingering post-Vietnam blues.
</P>
<P>
   Triumphantly reclaimed, the war, in most people's minds, once
again represents what it did in the 1950s: the apogee of American
heroism and rectitude.
</P>
<P>
   But even the noblest endeavor has its dark underside. And
``Treasure Island,'' an intermittently witty parody of a 1940s
movie with an angry political agenda, heaves and strains to put
self-congratulation and flag-waving about the past in some
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   This independent black-and-white film, which takes its name not
from Robert Louis Stevenson but from a San Francisco naval base, is
a surreal, increasingly chaotic comic riff on ``The Man Who Never
Was,'' Ewen Montague's account (made into a 1956 film starring
Clifton Webb) of a scheme concocted by British intelligence to
mislead Germany about the invasion of Sicily.
</P>
<P>
   The deception involved arranging for the corpse of a British
naval officer carrying bogus secret documents to be washed up on
the coast of Spain.
</P>
<P>
   In the parody, dreamed up by Scott King, who wrote and filmed
``Treasure Island'' with a 1936-vintage camera, a body outfitted
with false papers and letters describing an imaginary personal
history is kept in an office where Samuel (Nick Offerman), a
mathematician specializing in code, collaborates with Frank (Lance
Baker), a linguist. They plan to deposit the body with its false
documents in the Pacific for the Japanese to discover.
</P>
<P>
   Both Samuel and Frank lead guarded, secretive lives. The burly,
macho Samuel camouflages his latent homosexuality by regularly
bringing strange men home to have three-way sex with him and his
wife, Penny (Daisy Hall).
</P>
<P>
   Frank juggles two wives and a fiancee. One wife, Yo-Ji (Suzy
Nakamura), is a Japanese woman hiding out in Chinatown to avoid
being sent to an internment camp. The other, Anna (Rachel Singer),
is a skinny bundle of nerves severely afflicted with psoriasis. His
fiancee is the blunt, sexually aggressive Stella (Stephanie
Ittleson).
</P>
<P>
   Overstuffed with characters whose identities are inadequately
explained, the movie jumps around awkwardly from person to person
to create a kinky '40s mosaic of frightened, repressed American
patriots. As Samuel and Frank devise an easily crackable code for
the papers to accompany the body, their talk about ``Japs'' is
casually and viciously racist (the way it really was during the
war, when it was convenient and probably necessary to demonize the
enemy).
</P>
<P>
   The film makes an elaborate and glaringly out-of-place sidetrack
to the rape trial of a man played by an actor in blackface, a
reminder that similar attitudes applied to blacks in those days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Treasure Island,'' which opens Friday in New York, takes a
macabre science-fiction turn when the body comes to life. (At
least, it does in the minds of the two men creating its false
identity.) To Samuel, the creature that stirs to life is his
suppressed shadow self, a mocking, proudly effeminate 97-pound
weakling ogling him with a lascivious leer.
</P>
<P>
   Scene by scene, ``Treasure Island'' loses its narrative
continuity as it turns into an increasingly strident,
finger-pointing essay. At the last minute, it throws in a
corrective vision of V-J Day, suggesting that many of the innocent
kisses shared by strangers in famous vintage photographs gave way
to rapes and other acts of random violence.
</P>
<P>
   For all the ideas it tosses around _ and many of them are useful
and painful correctives to our rose-colored fantasies _ ``Treasure
Island'' is too crude a movie to muster much rhetorical clout. But
in deconstructing a myth, it does find one ingenious parallel: its
man who never was a paradigm becomes a paradigm for an era that
never was. Or at least it wasn't the way we would like to remember
it. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `TREASURE ISLAND' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Scott King; director of photography,
King; edited by Dody Dorn; music by Chris Anderson; production
designer, Nathan Marsak; produced by Adrienne Gruben; released by
King Pictures. Running time: 86 minutes. This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Lance Baker (Frank), Nick Offerman (Samuel), Jonah
Blechman (The Body), Pat Healy (Clark), Suzy Nakamura (Yo-Ji),
Rachel Singer (Anna), Stephanie Ittleson (Stella) and Daisy Hall
(Penny). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1825EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
