<HEADER>
A8994 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT     03-16 0350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPOTLIGHT ON A NEW ALBUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DO MAKE SAY THINK: ``Goodbye Enemy Airship the Landlord Is
Dead'' (Constellation)
</P>
<P>
   One of the original intents of rock 'n' roll, and later punk and
now indie rock _ that whole series of basement rebellions since the
1950s _ has been to show up the professionals. But at a certain
point, naivete isn't enough. Charming technical limitations become
insurmountable walls, and applying amateurish rock technique to
more complicated music seems contrary to the point, or not worth
the effort.
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon of post-rock, the contemplative art music of the
indie scene, addressed that problem in the '90s, and now we're
already in post-rock's second generation, seeing new bands building
on the work of forerunners like Tortoise and Slint.
</P>
<P>
   The instrumental sextet Do Make Say Think, from Toronto, is one:
it plays long, heavily plotted songs that are spacey, gooey with
echo, densely layered and often beautiful. The gift of post-rock's
first wave may not be its jazz-influenced chords and rhythms as
much as a knowledge of studio hardware: the inspired low-budget
production on this album, the band's second, keeps all the music's
elements in flux, commanding your attention to zoom in on tiny
details.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goodbye Enemy Airship'' is dotted with musical naivete: one of
its two drummers has trouble keeping a groove and some relatively
simple guitar and saxophone parts are played a little gracelessly.
But the indie-rock amateurism isn't grating; it's just part of the
band's honesty and dedication.
</P>
<P>
   Tracks abruptly change tempos and moods, from one drone to
another. Bubbling, crackling noises from analogue synthesizers
briefly hijack a song. A drum pattern comes in and saturates the
recording; then the microphones seem to roll backward from the
drums and bring them into focus.
</P>
<P>
   It's a headphones album and, as with dub reggae, there's so much
tension-and-release and spatial effects in the music that it almost
becomes a visual experience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1828EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8995 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      03-16 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Being Charlie Kaufman
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Hundreds of the most famous faces in movies mingled
over drinks in the lobby at the Academy Awards Nominees Luncheon or
posed for pictures on the red-carpet arrival line, a bright chatter
of successful Hollywood celebrating itself. But Charlie Kaufman sat
alone at one of the otherwise empty tables in the Beverly Hilton's
grand ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really hate this kind of thing,'' Kaufman said. He wore the
distinctive black badge that identified him as an actual nominee,
in his case for writing the script for Spike Jonze's ``Being John
Malkovich,'' arguably the most dementedly original script in a year
celebrated for its original screenwriting. He looked utterly
uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman said his life hadn't really changed much since the movie
was released. ``I'm doing my work,'' he said. ``I'm a writer, so I
work by myself. I get up, I try to write and I panic when I
can't.''
</P>
<P>
   The stars began to trickle past. Tom Cruise. Warren Beatty and
an extremely pregnant Annette Bening. Julianne Moore. Jonze came by
to say hello. Catherine Keener, nominated for best supporting
actress for the film, gave him a hug. ``Being John Malkovich'' was
written five years ago, Kaufman said, and took all that time to
make it to the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has all been surprising, I guess,'' he said. ``I never
really expected John Malkovich to even read the thing, much less
agree to be in it. It went through all of that and then it got
made. It's all very exciting and gratifying.''
</P>
<P>
   When the time came, Kaufman jumped up and joined the throng of
nominees posing for the ``class photo'' _ everyone who is up for an
Oscar this year at the March 26 ceremonies in the Shrine
Auditorium. But he didn't seem happy about it. He said the other
moviemakers and the film's distributor hadn't pushed him too hard
to give interviews and have his picture taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of a little bit shy,'' he said. ``And they know this,
so they're gentle.''
</P>
<P>
   Just the Facts
</P>
<P>
   Susannah Grant said she watched from the sidelines late last
year as controversies erupted over the accuracy of various portions
of ``The Insider,'' Michael Mann's thriller about big tobacco and
big media, and ``The Hurricane,'' Norman Jewison's drama about
efforts to undo the murder conviction of the boxer Rubin Carter.
</P>
<P>
   But Grant said she remained confident that such complaints would
not bedevil ``Erin Brockovich,'' the based-on-a-true-story drama
she wrote that stars Julia Roberts as a legal secretary who
uncovers a California public utility's toxic dumping ground. She
said she and the director, Steven Soderbergh, worked hard to tell
the story as accurately as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Steven came on to the project, he just said he wanted it
to be true, period,'' Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   There are composites in the film, and some characters' names
have been changed, she said, but the sequence of events and the
actions of the pivotal characters are as close to accurate as the
filmmakers could render them.
</P>
<P>
   It promises to be a busy few weeks for Grant, who came to
Hollywood nine years ago to study at the American Film Institute.
After ``Erin Brockovich'' is released this weekend, Grant will be
looking forward to the April 14 release of ``28 Days,'' a comic
drama she wrote that stars Sandra Bullock as a woman going through
drug and alcohol rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a lot of serious, inaccessible movies about
rehab,'' Grant said. ``So I really wanted to make one that had some
laughter in it, too. Because people don't stop laughing just
because they go into rehab. Some of the best moments in rehab come
from people laughing about the things they did before they were
sober.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Grant plans to buckle down and finish the script she is
preparing for her debut as a director. She won't discuss the plot,
though. ``It doesn't help if you tell the story too many times,''
she said. But she does acknowledge that there is a major, central
role for an older actress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Originally, I was going to work on another story,'' she said.
``But then I said to myself, `If I don't write these kind of
scripts with roles for older women, then who's going to do it?'''
</P>
<P>
   He's No. 1
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Pollak thoughtfully tugged on his cigar at the Grand
Havana Room, a private club for cigar lovers in Beverly Hills that
comes complete with private humidors bearing brass nameplates
(Arnold Schwarzenegger, Robert De Niro, John Travolta, Sylvester
Stallone and Pollak among them). He was talking about playing the
president of the United States, as he has done in his most recent
film, ``Deterrence,'' his debut in a leading role.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the writer and director, Rod Lurie, called and told me he
had a story that he wanted me to be in, I stopped him halfway
through and said, `Wait a minute, you want me to play the
president?''' said Pollak, a former stand-up comic. ``He said,
yeah, he saw this character as a kind of everyman president who's
almost accidentally thrust into the role.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollak said he had taken the part in the low-budget, independent
film both because he was attracted to the story and because it was
the lead. He certainly didn't do it for the money, he said: ``We
all basically worked for coffee and doughnuts.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was glad it had taken so long for him to get a
leading role because by the time it came he felt confident and
ready to tackle it. ``I must say, though, it was very nice to show
up every day and to be, as they say, No. 1 on the call sheet,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar's House
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mondshein and Leslie Holleran probably have the only
house in Larchmont, N.Y., whose occupants, between them, have a
claim on 13 Academy Award nominations.
</P>
<P>
   Mondshein, a film editor, is nominated for his work on ``The
Sixth Sense,'' which has five other nominations. Holleran, his
wife, was a co-producer on ``The Cider House Rules,'' which is up
for seven Oscars. In four categories, Mondshein said, the couple's
films are competing head to head.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit of a competition,'' he said. ``A friendly
and supportive kind of competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it was Mondshein who introduced his wife to Lasse
Halstrom, the director of ``Cider House'' and a Westchester County
neighbor, and now Holleran has forged a regular working
relationship with the filmmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel a little bit like ground zero these days,'' Holleran
said. ``We talk about it quite a bit. I knew the minute I heard the
news when they announced the nominations. I told Andy, `It will
never be better than it is this morning.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1830EST &QL; 
