<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8996 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-CYBER-INDIA-CLINTON-R     03-16 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBER-INDIA-CLINTON-RESEND-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANGALORE OR HYDERABAD: TWO HIGH-TECH CITIES VIE FOR CLINTON
VISIT  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for Clinton's March 20 visit to India)   (RESENDING from March 14 for timely heads-up)  
  
 (This insightful 775-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By PETER POPHAM  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DELHI _ Which is it to be, Mr. Clinton?
</P>
<P>
   The American president comes to India on March 20, the first
such visit for 22 years, and the subcontinent's two most
strenuously forward-looking cities, Bangalore and Hyderabad, are
competing furiously for his attention.
</P>
<P>
   Both are in the south of India, and are both vying to become the
most important centers of India's booming software industry but he
will only visit one of them. Which will it be?
</P>
<P>
   Bangalore is the obvious choice. The original home of India's IT
industry, the one home-grown industry since independence which has
truly shown signs of growing into a world beater.
</P>
<P>
   Bangalore is also the home of India's richest man, Wipro chief
executive Azim Premji, who is now hot on the heels of Microsoft's
Bill Gates for the title of richest man in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Indians dub Bangalore ``the garden city.'' It also has a balmy
climate and the glimmerings of a modern lifestyle for its
burgeoning middle class, notably a number of pubs where hard-driven
software engineers go to unwind.
</P>
<P>
   Amid these pleasant surroundings, the city's software companies
have increased their exports from 50 million rupees in 1991-2 to 32
billion in 1998-9, making it without question the IT capital of
India.
</P>
<P>
   Hyderabad, by contrast, is an upstart, with less than one-tenth
the value of Bangalore's software exports.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the competition for Clinton's attention has been fierce, and
there have recently been some indications that Hyderabad may clinch
it. If it does, two men can share the credit: Bill Gates and
Chandrababu Naidu.
</P>
<P>
   Bangalore's problem is that the IT companies have made their
homes there despite rather than because of Karnataka state's
politicians and policies.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its natural endowments, Bangalore, like most Indian
cities, is strikingly ill-governed. The power supply is inadequate
and erratic, with wild fluctuations in voltage; the air, which
should be perfumed by the millions of flowers, instead is poisoned
by the fumes of the thousands of rickshaws which run in place of
proper taxis.
</P>
<P>
   The last chief minister, J.H. Patel, didn't help much: he freely
confessed to the prime minister's task force on information
technology that he didn't understand the difference between
software and hardware.
</P>
<P>
   In Hyderabad, by contrast, the state's chief minister,
Chandrababu Naidu, is working overtime to ensure it becomes India's
first truly modern city, where high technology firms will function
with ease.
</P>
<P>
   By convincing Bill Gates, among other important foreigners, that
he really means it, and can pull it off, Naidu has gone a long way
to achieving his goal. Clinton's visit, if it transpires, will be
another milestone along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, Microsoft opened a research and development center
on the top floor of Cyber Towers, Naidu's answer to Bangalore's
Electronics City. It was Microsoft's first research-and-development
facility outside corporate headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Cyber Towers looks set to succeed more smoothly than Bangalore's
equivalent. And the city displays a lucid appreciation of what IT
companies expect and need: totally dependable services, including
electricity, drinkable tap water, banks with ATMs, even speedy,
localized customs clearance.
</P>
<P>
   If it resembles a little node of extraterritoriality, almost a
colony, Naidu, recently voted man of the millennium by one national
newspaper, isn't bothered. The important thing is to give the lead.
</P>
<P>
   The speed with which he is transforming Hyderabad into a sort of
Indian Osaka or Shanghai is stunning.
</P>
<P>
   But although Naidu's achievement in Hyderabad displays much more
political muscularity than is the Indian norm, both he and his
recently elected opposite number in Bangalore, S.M. Krishna,
confront similar basic problems.
</P>
<P>
   Their substantially middle-class cities both sit amid vast
poverty-stricken hinterlands. The chief ministers babble of bytes
and hobnob with men worth billions. But millions of the people who
voted them into power have barely enough to eat, plough their
fields with the aid of bullocks, have no electricity and few
amenities of any sort.
</P>
<P>
   Many commit female infanticide or secretly sell girl babies to
escape the dowry trap.
</P>
<P>
   Literacy rates are low in both states. The north of Andhra
Pradesh, the state of which Hyderabad is capital, is racked by a
long-running insurgency by left extremists.
</P>
<P>
   India's permanent nightmare is of absolute polarization: of what
locally they call ``the creamy layer'' getting as rich as
middle-class consumers in the West _ richer, if you throw maids and
chauffeurs into the calculation _ while the outcasts, the bonded
laborers and poor farmers sink into permanent misery, or migrate to
the cities and scavenge what they can from the city's rubbish. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 775-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
