<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8998 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-IRS-AUDITS17-COX     03-16 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRS-AUDITS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE'S OFFICE DEFENDS IRS CONTACTS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional investigators said Thursday that two
aides to Vice President Al Gore had made questionable inquiries
about records at the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   The aides asked about the employment status of a labor union
associate, said Lindy Paull, staff director for the Joint Tax
Committee, as she released a three-year study of IRS practices.
</P>
<P>
   The report dismissed allegations of political bias by the IRS in
auditing nonprofit groups. However, it criticized the vice
president's staff for contacting the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Quinn, communications director for the vice president,
defended the inquiries as proper.
</P>
<P>
   She said the staff members involved were Kumiki Gibson, who
served as the vice president's counsel, and Joe Eyer, an assistant
to the deputy chief of staff. Both have since left the White House.
</P>
<P>
   IRS officials declined to provide the information the aides
sought.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn said the two officials apparently asked the IRS in 1997
``how certain workers would be classified,'' either as contract
workers or full-time employees, by an unidentified labor union.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn said that Gibson, as a member of the White House counsel's
office, had the authority to ask such questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's within the guidelines for her to make inquiries in a
matter like this one, which was a policy, legislative or
administrative matter,'' Quinn said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore spokeswoman said that her staff had been unable to
determine why the IRS had been contacted. She said that a check of
the vice president's schedule found no meetings with union groups
around the time of the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas,
who ordered the study three years ago, said Thursday that he was
``disturbed by the revelations in the report that administration''
had made the contacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that in the interests of full disclosure, all the
information and records relating to these contacts to the IRS by
the Office of the Vice President be made available to the public
and to the media immediately,'' Archer said.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Department officials welcomed the general conclusions
of the report on the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   Of the instances of the Gore staff contacts and one other
instance involving a Treasury official, a spokesman said, ``The
report makes clear that neither contact influenced the conduct or
the outcome of any matter.''
</P>
<P>
   IRS Commissioner Charles O. Rossotti said, ``I think we can
conclusively lay to rest concerns that the resources of the IRS
have been diverted for political purposes. We will remain vigilant
to ensure that this admirable record is sustained into the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson, who is now at the Washington law firm of Williams &AMP;
Connolly, did not return a reporter's call.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
