<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9001 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOYD-LESSONS17-COX     03-16 1488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-LESSONS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    N.C. students struggling in aftermath of historic flooding after
Floyd
 &HT;    By Glenda Jakubowski
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHEL, N.C. _ The poster affixed to the concrete-block wall of
music teacher Kathy Ulloa's classroom may not state a fact, but it
does tell a truth of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``A song makes the sun shine,'' the poster reads, with a
cheerful yellow cartoon sun shown triumphing over a stormy day.
</P>
<P>
   If it were a fact, all of Pitt County would have been singing
away the rains brought by Hurricane Floyd, which flooded the Tar
River and its feeder creeks to historic levels.
</P>
<P>
   Less than six months after the floodwaters have receded, it was
the truth of the poster's message that lit student's faces and
filled this Bethel Elementary classroom with song.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the floodwaters inspired the song.
</P>
<P>
   The 70-member chorus of sixth-, seventh- and eighth-graders
wrote the song for a contest sponsored by Weyerhaeuser. The theme
of the contest is flood recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Among the student lyricists is Kristen Abeyounis, who knows
something about recovering from floods. Her stepfather is a farmer
who lost 80 percent of his crops to the flood.
</P>
<P>
   After the hurricane, Kristen and her family waded through
waist-deep floodwaters, boarded a helicopter and flew to a shelter
in Tarboro, 15 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I looked down, all I could see was water, the tops of
trees and water,'' said Kristen, 14.
</P>
<P>
   The high school shelter was so crowded that Kristen and her
family had to sleep outside on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Floodwaters displaced students like Kristen throughout Pitt
County and eastern North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Pactolus Elementary in eastern Pitt County lost 167 students,
with 100 of them still attending school elsewhere. Wellcome Middle
School lost 125 students. Only 25 to 30 of those have returned to
the school. Belvoir lost 120 students. Kristen's school lost five
children.
</P>
<P>
   Other schools saw their populations grow. C.M. Eppes Middle
School, in Greenville, took in 70 new students who moved to
state-funded trailers for homeless flood victims. South Greenville
Elementary, also within city limits, found room for 40 additional
students. Grifton Elementary lost 16 of its own students and gained
16 from other schools.
</P>
<P>
   No teachers were reassigned from schools that lost a large
number of students, according to Gibb Chauncey, director of student
information for county schools. But teachers were added to schools
that gained significant numbers of students. Teacher assignments
for next year will be determined based on the student populations
at each school going into that school year.
</P>
<P>
   County schools were out of the business of education for 13 days
because of flooding.
</P>
<P>
   And it wasn't business as usual when classroom doors reopened.
</P>
<P>
   Students came to school without shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Students came to school without backpacks or books.
</P>
<P>
   Students came to school without homes.
</P>
<P>
   Kristen was lucky in that respect. The floodwaters came right up
to the steps leading to her house, but no further.
</P>
<P>
   Other children didn't fare so well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could go to work at Belk now, because I can look at any
child and tell what size they wear,'' said Belvoir Elementary
counselor Valerie Galberth. ``Teachers would line up their classes
for clothing and shoe fittings.''
</P>
<P>
   Even six months later, a number of children are not back in
their homes, and flood-related problems for some students can't be
fixed with a new pair of shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Arlene Ferren, director of student services with Pitt schools,
meets with counselors periodically. The counselors have seen an
increase in students' and teachers' stress since the flood, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing a lot of fighting and aggression ... to the point
that some schools have 'no-fight Fridays,' as incentives,'' Ferren
said.
</P>
<P>
   A ``no-fight Friday,'' according to the security officer at
North Pitt High School, occurs when students go an entire week
without a fight. If the next Monday through Thursday remains
fight-free, the students can leave class five minutes early that
Friday. The time off accumulates with each fight-free week, so that
students could shave five minutes off each day of the week, in
theory.
</P>
<P>
   Ferren said that children who formerly did very well are now
having trouble coping. Kids are breaking down and crying during and
after tests, and counselors are seeing significant signs of
depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depression among high school students is at an all-time
high,'' Ferren said.
</P>
<P>
   Several principals and teachers are worried about the flood's
effect on end-of-grade tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't help but to be affected, because the students have
gone through a difficult time,'' said Bethel principal Roscoe
Locke, echoing the worries of many.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers at Bethel Elementary spoke about one student who could
represent many.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a good student, but he has suffered,'' said English
teacher Jennifer Berry, who teaches Kristen as well.
</P>
<P>
   Kristen's social studies teacher also knows this child, who lost
his house in the flood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I noticed behavior problems when he was most stressed out in
his private life,'' MaryAnne Pennington said. ``He became moody,
rude and obnoxious. He stopped turning in his work, and his grades
were slipping.''
</P>
<P>
   When the results of the child's behavior were reflected on his
report card, he came to Pennington and poured out his troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have told someone what I was feeling sooner,'' he
told the teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Pennington worries now about how many students were identified
as behavior problems or moody, when they were actually reacting to
their lives being turned upside-down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has gradually turned back into the kid he was at the
beginning of the year,'' Pennington said. ``He's gotten through the
worst of it. He's back on the right road.''
</P>
<P>
   When music teacher Ulloa learned about the songwriting
competition, she saw an opportunity not just to win a contest, but
to help her students work through post-flood feelings.
</P>
<P>
   The children brainstormed, writing all their thoughts about the
flood on the blackboard, Ulloa said. Then they created rhyming
patterns, lyrics and a melody.
</P>
<P>
   The results were so good that a contest entry wasn't enough.
Ulloa decided to record a CD, which will be mass-produced and
available for sale to the public by the end of April. Proceeds will
benefit the school.
</P>
<P>
   Ulloa brought in Wesley Pritchard from Mill West Studios in
Fayetteville to record and mix the students' voices. Pritchard sat
in front of a mixing board with headphones over his ears and
adjusted slide controls while Ulloa arranged students on metal
risers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want baritones over here,'' Ulloa said, pointing to her
left. ``Sopranos in the middle, altos over here.''
</P>
<P>
   Seventy pairs of eyes locked in on Ulloa as she conducted the
students through the song with the particular sign language of a
chorus teacher, touching the tips of her fingers together, cupping
her cheekbones, exaggerating facial features.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y'all sound great,'' she said, after the first run-through.
</P>
<P>
   Pritchard shifted his headphones and asked the students for one
more chorus, and then another.
</P>
<P>
   The room was heating up. The kids looked a bit wilted. But when
they were asked to sing another chorus, when Pritchard asked for
just the sopranos, or just the baritones, or just one phrase, and
that phrase again and again, the kids gave it to him. These
children know about perseverance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take a breather,'' Ulloa finally told the students, who
collapsed in relieved chatter as they passed around cups of water.
Someone opened a window, searching for a breeze. Kristen Abeyounis
politely told her story as a tiny bead of sweat trickled from her
hairline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was never going to get better,'' Kristen said.
``But you look around now and see everything is coming together,
and it is better.''
</P>
<P>
   The break was over. Ulloa called the students to order, arranged
them on the risers, and waited for Pritchard to nod the signal to
begin.
</P>
<P>
   On a sunny day that sparkled with springtime, with pear trees
and daffodils blooming and floodwaters long since receded, students
closed the music room's windows against traffic noise, stood up
straight, opened their mouths, and sang.
</P>
<P>
   Excerpt from ``We'll Arise''
</P>
<P>
   by the Bethel Elementary School chorus, taught by Kathy Ulloa
</P>
<P>
   Mother Nature is powerful to see
</P>
<P>
   She often moves unexpectedly
</P>
<P>
   In a moment least expected, the rivers began to rise
</P>
<P>
   The floods rushed in, covered the land, much to our surprise
(but)
</P>
<P>
   We'll arise, we'll restore, We will rebuild again
</P>
<P>
   Much was lost at such great cost
</P>
<P>
   Together we will stand
</P>
<P>
   Helping one another, cleaning up our coast
</P>
<P>
   Sharing everything we have with people who need it the most.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
