<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1840EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9006 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BAXTER-CONVERTS17-COX     03-16 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-CONVERTS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore trying to get handle on finance reform
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ What a year for conversions. Already, the Pope has
apologized for such excesses as the Inquisition, Bob Jones
University has allowed interracial dating, and Vice President Al
Gore is running on campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush's campaign has made sure via e-mail that the
political media has Jay Leno's latest laugh lines about Gore's
announcement that he's making campaign finance reform a
``cornerstone'' of his campaign. ``And he also said anybody could
have their name engraved on the cornerstone for a simple donation
of $10,000,'' cracked the late-night comic.
</P>
<P>
   It did take some nerve for Gore to spotlight this issue only a
few days after the sentencing of Maria Hsia in a case that hinged
largely on the money she raised at Gore's infamous Buddhist temple
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have learned from my mistakes,'' Gore said. If he were
consciously trying to get a rise out of his Republican detractors,
the vice president could not have chosen more irritating words. ``I
have a passion for campaign reform that is fueled in part because
of the pain of those mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   This is an issue, however, on which it is possible for even the
lowest sinner to get religion. Remember that the patron saint of
campaign finance reform, Sen. John McCain, was tainted in the
Keating Five scandal, a transgression candidate McCain admitted
with the light-heartedness of the lately baptized.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who became a ``reformer with results'' immediately after
McCain beat him in New Hampshire, has advanced his own campaign
finance plan, but he was having nothing to do with a proposal by
Gore to have the national parties eliminate soft-money advertising
in the upcoming campaign.
</P>
<P>
   If it was brazen, Gore's embrace of campaign finance reform was
a predictable turn in a campaign in which Gore has benefited from
the problems McCain has caused Bush, without winning much affection
from McCain's independent-leaning voters.
</P>
<P>
   It would have seemed unlikely last year that Gore might have
reason to worry about peaking too soon at the close of the primary
season. That stretches the situation a little _ while Gore has
gained much ground on Bush, most polls still have him behind.
</P>
<P>
   But the abrupt embrace of McCain's issue was a signal that
Gore's campaign, despite beginning the general election campaign in
better shape than expected, perceives the need to retool quickly
for the next race. With the memory of the GOP divisions still
fresh, Gore lumped Bush together with Pat Robertson and Jerry
Falwell in an answer to a question about abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans in the meantime have been focusing on the effort
to tie Gore and the Clinton administration to the rising gas
prices. This introduces what could be the most unpredictable issue
in the upcoming campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A sharp spike in New England fuel oil prices before the New
Hampshire primary, seemed to have had relatively little impact on
how people voted.
</P>
<P>
   But a big jump in gas prices and the resulting ripple effect on
the national economy could have a much more dramatic impact in the
general election. In the economy, as in the polls, Gore might be
cause for worry in peaking too soon.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
