<SLUG> BC-NISSAN-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENAULT EXECUTIVE WILL BECOME PRESIDENT OF NISSAN MOTOR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Carlos Ghosn, the Renault SA executive dispatched to
Japan a year ago to help restore Nissan Motor Co.'s profitability,
will become its president, officials of the struggling Japanese
automaker and its French partner said Thursday. The promotion
represents the first time a foreigner has assumed such a
prestigious role in a major Japanese corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Another senior Renault executive on assignment at Nissan,
Thierry Moulonguet, will become Nissan's chief financial officer as
part of a broader management shakeup, the companies said.
</P>
<P>
   Renault took a 35 percent stake in Nissan last year, and Ghosn,
nicknamed ``Le Cost Killer'' in the French press for his aggressive
record in reducing overhead, became Nissan's chief operating
officer, giving him day-to-day control. The announcements Thursday,
which will become effective at the Nissan shareholders meeting in
June, strengthens Renault's grip on Nissan.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Ghosn, no foreigner has held a top executive position at
a pillar of corporate Japan. While foreigners have served as
president of Mazda Motor Corp., an affiliate of Ford Motor Co.,
Mazda is much smaller than Nissan.
</P>
<P>
   In a Western sense, the titles mean little as both Ghosn and
Moulonguet have effectively been playing those roles within Nissan
already. ``We don't consider this to be such a major event but more
of a natural process,'' said Yoshikazu Hanawa, who relinquished the
president title to Ghosn but remains chief executive and chairman.
</P>
<P>
   But in Japan, where titles confer status and designate authority
and perhaps no title is more coveted than that of the company
``shatcho,'' or president, the announcement's symbolism was
resonant. At a news conference, Hanawa acknowledged the
significance of the title.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we say `shatcho,' there's this insinuated message making
it something like a CEO, so that the shatcho decides on
everything,'' Hanawa said.
</P>
<P>
   He insisted that the decision to transfer the title was his own
and said he had been thinking about it ever since Ghosn arrived at
Nissan. ``In a practical sense, his responsibility was equal to
that of a president,'' Hanawa said.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Ghosn said he was honored to have the title but
spent more time stressing his commitment to returning Nissan to
profitability and competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   He refused to comment on a report in the evening edition of the
Nihon Keizai Shimbun, Japan's leading business newspaper, that
Nissan's operating profit for the fiscal year ending March 31 would
be a third of the company's earlier forecast.
</P>
<P>
   The management appointments announced Thursday also illustrated
the limits of imposing change on Japanese organizations. There had
been some expectation that Hanawa would announce his retirement,
not merely relinquish a title. By staying, he created a bottleneck
at the top of the company.
</P>
<P>
   That was evident from the reassignment of Kanemitsu Anraku, who
is currently chief financial officer. He will become the company's
vice chairman, a new position, and take charge of external and
government relations.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear what Hanawa's role in the company will be, since
his role after Renault's investment was largely the one Anraku will
now be playing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
