<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NKOREA-DIPLOMACY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECLUSIVE NORTH KOREA REACHING OUT TOWARD OTHER NATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ In the space of a few short weeks, North Korea has gone
from one of the world's most politically reclusive states to one of
the most diplomatically active.
</P>
<P>
   With little fanfare, but with a speed that has surprised many
observers of the Communist country, the government in Pyongyang has
established diplomatic relations with Italy and has resumed
diplomatic discussions with Japan and Australia for the first time
in years.
</P>
<P>
   It has also recently sent out discreet feelers to at least two
other major Western nations, Canada and Britain. And according to
diplomats in the Philippines, it has approached their country about
joining the Association of Southeast Asian Nations Regional Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Political experts attribute much of this unusually intense
diplomatic activity to a feeling among the North Korean leadership
that they have consolidated their authority and that their
government, which until recently regarded any foreign contact as a
threat, will survive. They also believe recent economic progress
shows that the country's overall direction is promising.
</P>
<P>
   These diplomatic moves are also taking place against the
backdrop of talks between the United States and North Korea that
diplomats say will be crucial to easing the country's isolation and
lowering tensions on the politically divided Korean peninsula, one
of the Cold War's final flash points.
</P>
<P>
   In New York this week, North Korea's deputy foreign minister,
Kim Gye Gwan, and an American delegation led by Charles Kartman
have been discussing final arrangements for high-level talks
between the two countries tentatively scheduled for April in
Washington. No high-ranking North Korean official has visited
Washington since the Korean War ended in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the Clinton administration lifted some trade,
banking and other sanctions that had been imposed on North Korea
for decades. Now Pyongyang wants Washington to take it off a list
of nations that Washington says support terrorism. Among other
things, the United States reportedly wants North Korea to agree
that it will not resume tests of ballistic missiles like the one it
fired over Japan in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has also sought to encourage Pyongyang to respond
more favorably to the so-called Sunshine Policy of the South Korean
leader, Kim Dae Jung. North Korea has recently accepted limited
forms of investment and tourism from South Korea, but has spurned
offers for direct talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. has been encouraging them to engage with the outside
world,'' said Park Young Ho, a senior research fellow at the Korean
Institute for National Unification, in Seoul. ``And this is
happening at a time when North Korea seems to have realized that it
needs to have more relations with other countries in order to
improve its own situation further.''
</P>
<P>
   Other experts have taken a much more skeptical view of
Pyongyang's opening, saying it is a short-term ploy meant to
minimize the use of North Korea's weapons programs and often
belligerent posturing as campaign themes in important national
legislative elections in South Korea in April, and in the U.S.
presidential election in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be a diplomatic flurry for the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea. But, like they say, they've been down so long it
looks like up now,'' said Nicholas Eberstadt, a North Korea expert
at the American Enterprise Institute in Washington. ``All of the
new diplomacy is with countries that are willing to give
assistance, and it is meant to cover them in case the Washington
scenario doesn't work out.''
</P>
<P>
   But other recent signs of diplomatic activity by North Korea
have involved the country's historic ideological patrons. This
month President Kim Jong Il, paid an unusual visit to the Chinese
Embassy in Pyongyang, at the invitation of the Chinese ambassador,
Wan Yongxiang.
</P>
<P>
   In its only explanation of the visit, the official North Korean
media said Kim ``expressed thanks for the invitation and conversed
with the leading officials of the embassy.'' The visit immediately
set off speculation among North Korea experts that Kim was
preparing to visit China. If so, it would be his first overseas
trip since assuming power after the death of his father, Kim Il
Sung, in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea has also recently signed a new friendship treaty
with Russia.
</P>
<P>
   This ongoing diplomatic activity comes at a time when Kim
believes he is in a strong position politically, despite a sharp
and prolonged economic decline brought on by the disappearance of
its Cold War allies from the Soviet bloc, and by unusually harsh
weather and crop failures that led to famine.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the economy is believed to have grown slightly, for
the first time in a decade. And in a change from his normal diet of
visits to military installations, the 58-year-old North Korean
leader began emphasizing visits to factories and food production
centers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, many experts say Kim appears determined to bring about a
rebound from economic collapse. He has apparently decided that one
of the keys to doing this is through a controlled opening to the
rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   If this is so, there is still considerable divergence among
experts over the economic direction to expect from Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
   Under its Sunshine Policy, South Korea is investing heavily,
both in economic and diplomatic terms, in encouraging its neighbor
to emulate the gradual evolution toward capitalism undertaken by
Communist nations like China and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, President Kim of South Korea said
Pyongyang had three options before it: war, which would end
disastrously for it; the status quo, which he said has already
proven a dead end, and evolutionary change.
</P>
<P>
   ``This third option, which I believe is the only viable option,
is to follow the example of China and Vietnam,'' Kim said. ``They
have maintained their political systems, while gradually opening up
economically. This is what we, and all of our friends and allies,
want from North Korea, and we are prepared to help them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1856EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0273 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9020 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TAIWAN-ELECT-NYT &LR;      03-16 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TAIWAN, A POLITICAL SPOOF IS PROOF OF POLITICAL FREEDOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (Taiwan Journal) 
(bl) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ ``I have heard the rumors of various rates
being paid to buy votes, and I solemnly declare that this is not an
activity of my party,'' says the man on the screen, who bears an
uncanny resemblance to President Lee Teng-hui.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my party buys votes, it pays a uniform rate,'' says the
character, working himself into an arm-waving frenzy. ``We offer
the fairest deal! No bargaining!''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not right, I didn't mean that!'' he adds a moment
later, capping a deft caricature of the real Lee's penchant for
blurting out things that require, as they say, some later
clarification.
</P>
<P>
   Exuberant elections are evidence of Taiwan's transition from
dictatorship to democracy, but an unsparing and hilarious satire of
the politicians on the air weekday nights on cable television here
may be the ultimate proof.
</P>
<P>
   Performed live and homing in on the day's news, the show also
provides welcome comic relief from the campaign for Saturday's
presidential election, which is understandably driven by weighty
issues of war and peace that have engaged the Taiwanese people in
endlessly earnest conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that everybody is too up-tight in this election,'' the
show's originator, Bobby Hou, said the other night as his Lee
Teng-hui makeup was being applied. ``Everybody should relax!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to test where the breaking point of this new democracy
is,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   In their quest to skewer all the new candidates equally, Hou and
his ensemble say, they have an easy time harvesting satirical
material from the campaign's cant and mudslinging.
</P>
<P>
   The show is called ``An Appointment With the Chairman,'' the
chairman being Lee, who in actuality may derive more power from his
chairmanship of the long-governing Nationalist Party, or
Kuomintang, than from his elected office. While Lee is not himself
a candidate, the specter of his personality and policies pervades
the presidential race and, as portrayed by Hou, it also provides
the show with a comic center.
</P>
<P>
   A veteran comic actor of 35, Hou has mastered the impulsive,
messianic speech, the sometimes rustic mannerisms and the memorable
expressions on the face of Taiwan's president.
</P>
<P>
   Filling out the ensemble are equally piercing impersonators of
the three main candidates, who together with Hou perform sketches
that are only slightly battier than reality.
</P>
<P>
   The three candidate-characters are Vice President Lien Chan, who
in real life is Lee's chosen successor and is never allowed to
forget it; Chen Shui-bian of the Democratic Progressive Party, a
crusading idealist who has been accused of expedient flip-flops
including a retreat from his longtime advocacy of formal
independence for Taiwan; and James Soong, a former Lee protege and
Nationalist star who bolted to run an independent campaign as a
white knight reformer.
</P>
<P>
   Each show is hastily written by a team that draws on the latest
scandals and gaffes. The actors give the script one quick read
together, just before air time, and then they suddenly morph into
their roles.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday night's show, the Chen Shui-bian character does his
best to dispel the fears dogging the candidate that he will provoke
a war with China, which has threatened to use force to block
Taiwan's independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee that if elected I will not declare Taiwan's
independence,'' the character says, ``At least until my son has
finished his military service.''
</P>
<P>
   A sketch earlier this week captured Lee's tendency to patronize
his candidate, Lien, as well as the rumor-mongering that all sides
have used as a campaign tactic.
</P>
<P>
   Dismissing stories that the seemingly strait-laced and very
married Lien had visited a massage parlor, the Lee character said,
``The Lien Chan I know never went to a massage parlor. When he
wants to find a woman he doesn't need to go to a massage parlor!''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not right, I didn't mean that!'' he continued.
``Anyway, it was a legitimate massage parlor.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lien character, like his real-life counterpart wearing a cap
and golf jacket to counter his image as a rich and aloof man who
was handed all his high positions, sits pathetically grinning and
then says, ``I work very hard all day long _ in an air conditioned
office.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I didn't mean that!'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   Lampooning leaders this way would land an actor in jail in
mainland China, and until quite recently it was considered over the
top in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Only two years ago, Hou said, he tried a similar political
satire at another network. It was canceled after one episode, he
said, because of objections from the supposedly liberal Democratic
Progressive Party, which partly controlled the network.
</P>
<P>
   He shopped the idea at several other channels until Gala TV, a
local network, agreed and three months ago the nightly skewering
began.
</P>
<P>
   The 45-minute show has a modest but growing number of loyal
viewers, though its ratings remain well below those of the real
nightly news. In a tacit acknowledgment of its popularity, all
three major candidates are showing commercials during the breaks _
and risking the juxtaposition of comic portrayals and the
embarrassingly similar images in their ads.
</P>
<P>
   In another mix with the real world, each night after the initial
scripted skit, Hou and his comrades take live calls from viewers. A
surprising number try to speak sincerely, only to find themselves
teased. When a woman called to say she preferred James Soong for
president, Hou as President Lee answered, ``I guarantee that you'll
get a big tax bill at the end of this month,'' a reference to the
Nationalist Party's alleged habit of abusing government powers and
its legal hounding of the renegade Soong.
</P>
<P>
   Hou said that in previous incarnations he had played Mao
Tse-tung, the founder of Communist China, and Jiang Zemin, China's
current president and Communist Party leader, but Taiwanese were
not much interested. But if China ever does reclaim Taiwan, will he
lampoon Jiang?
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course!'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   Hou said he hopes to continue with the show after the election,
and it appears that Lee may keep on providing raw material, since
he has expressed his intention to stay on as Nationalist Party
chairman until his term runs out more than a year from now.
</P>
<P>
   That was grist for a sketch this week in which the Lee character
said: ``Ignore those rumors that I'm going to step down as party
chairman. I'm telling you, I'm going to stay forever!''
</P>
<P>
   He paused a second, then continued: ``That's not right. I didn't
mean that!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1858EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
