<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-TAIWAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA'S SCARE TACTICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Taiwan's presidential balloting Saturday, the second democratic
election in the 5,000-year history of the Chinese nation, features
three closely matched contenders and one overbearing kibitzer.
</P>
<P>
   The communist regime on the mainland, displaying a stubborn
refusal to honor the democratic principle of the voters' free
choice, has sought to scare the citizens on Taiwan away from one
candidate. Chen Shui-ban of the Democratic Progressive Party has
drawn the wrath of the Reds because they do not believe his
statement that, if elected, he will not push for the formal
declaration of independence commended in the platform of his party.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Beijing tried to interfere in a presidential
election on Taiwan, in 1996, the voters pondered the mainland's
denunciations of incumbent Lee Teng-hui and reacted by giving him
an overwhelming victory. The arrogance of Beijing's meddling
reflects not merely the communists' incomprehension of democratic
elections but also the degree to which the Chinese have become
intoxicated by their own propaganda. After all, if they believe
Taiwan has never ceased being an errant province of communist
China, then no effort they make to intimidate voters on the island
could qualify as interference in the internal affairs of another
country.
</P>
<P>
   So deeply ingrained is this credo that even the moderate Prime
Minister Zhu Rongji tried at a press conference Wednesday to
frighten Taiwan's voters. ``The people of Taiwan are standing at a
very critical historical juncture,'' Zhu shouted, shaking a finger
in the air. ``So let me give advice to all the people of Taiwan: Do
not act just on impulse. Otherwise you will regret it very much and
it will be too late to repent.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome of Saturday's election, President Clinton
and his successor will have to walk a fine line on the issue of
Taiwan. Washington must be firm enough to deter Beijing from any
rash military action but supple enough to encourage polical
dialogue and the continued development of lucrative commercial
relations between Taiwan and the mainland. China may be unified
when the mainland emulates the democracy of Taiwan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
