<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-KING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-VENTUROUS READING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Join the American Association of Fuddy-Duddies if you are one of
those who can't imagine why anyone would want to suffer the
eyestrain to read Stephen King's new e-book. At 16,000 words,
roughly 64 typewritten pages, the story can be printed out or read
on a computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   Posted this week, King's novella, ``Riding the Bullet,'' has
been so popular that Web sites carrying it collapsed, unable to
handle all the point-and-click demands.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was fascinating. Scribner _ an imprint of Simon &AMP;
Schuster _ and King's press, Philtrum, co-published the work,
posting it on line and charging readers $2.50 for access. This
slashed the traditional year-long publishing cycle, getting readers
to new writing quickly. In addition, special software enables
booksellers with Web sites to get in on the act, becoming e-book
sellers.
</P>
<P>
   This time around the money-making potential is tough to measure,
because some sites, including Amazon.com, are offering the story
for free _ if the server isn't already overwhelmed with requests.
</P>
<P>
   Like most technological change, there are possibilities to cheer
and possibilities to fear.
</P>
<P>
   E-publishing could lead to a renaissance in short fiction. Web
sites could offer a 21st century version of the hospitality that
magazines such as the Saturday Evening Post in its heyday provided
for the likes of F. Scott Fitzgerald and William Faulkner.
</P>
<P>
   With deliberate care and thought, the Internet could grow into
much more than an outlet for fabulously famous writers. Web-readers
could also be exposed to novice voices as well as up-and-comers.
And those less inclined to read books may be more attracted to
reading material that's on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But fuddy-duddies of the world should unite to defend the art of
books. As sheer physical objects _ with no portals for plug-ins or
add-ons _ books are a delight. The paintings and photographs on
book covers, the design, the typography, even the smell are all
part of reading's vivid impact on the imagination. It would be a
tragedy to lose this physical pleasure in some technological tidal
wave of good intentions.
</P>
<P>
   Let the bookstores and libraries grow to accommodate both good
old books and new e-books.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1901EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
