<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PRESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA BARS INTERVIEWS WITH CHECHEN REBEL LEADERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Russia-Journalists)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Renewing fears that press freedoms are increasingly in
peril, the Kremlin made it illegal this week for Russian media to
quote rebel leaders in their reports on Moscow's war against
separatist guerrillas in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The government justified the move as part of its ``fight against
terrorism.'' Journalists and free-speech advocates, however, called
it the latest step in an intensifying government crackdown on news
media.
</P>
<P>
   With Russian troops bogged down in Chechnya and presidential
elections less than two weeks away, the Kremlin has become
increasingly intolerant of dissenting voices. Some critics are
saying that under Acting President Vladimir V. Putin, who is widely
expected to win the March 26 vote, freedom of the press and other
hard-won civil liberties may be in peril.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putin and his team are doing everything possible to make sure
that the press isn't free,'' said Oleg Panfilov of the Russian
Journalists' Union. ``They have been waging a campaign to control
the media and this is the latest step in that process.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, however, press minister Mikhail Lesin
said, ``The mass media have no right to give terrorists and people
suspected of terrorism an opportunity to advertise themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement broadened an edict issued the day before that
barred Russian media from quoting Chechnya's president, Aslan
Maskhadov, rebel spokesman Movladi Udugov, and guerrilla commander
Shamil Basayev. Journalists who violate the ban, Lesin said, would
be given two warnings, and the ministry would then begin court
proceedings to close them down.
</P>
<P>
   Panfilov and others said the chief target of the gag order might
be US-funded Radio Liberty, which has infuriated the Kremlin with
witheringly critical coverage of the war.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Radio Liberty's Moscow bureau received a letter from
the ministry demanding that it turn over everything it had
broadcast in the past month. Radio Liberty has aired interviews
with rebel leaders and focused much of its war reporting on high
Russian troop losses and the plight of civilians.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Radio Liberty reporter Andrei Babitsky was detained
in Chechnya by Russian forces. He was released Feb. 29 after a
bizarre six-week ordeal. Russian officials claimed they had turned
Babitsky over to the Chechen rebels in exchange for Russian
prisoners of war, but Babitsky said he was in the hands of Russia's
security services the entire time.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have said Babitsky is under investigation for siding
with the guerrillas and is not allowed to leave Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Savik Shuster, Radio Liberty's Moscow bureau chief, said the
station would continue to give both the Russian military and
Chechen rebels a chance to tell their sides of the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not be intimidated. We work in the public interest,
and it is not for the government to decide what we should and
should not report,'' Shuster said. ``When the government starts
telling journalists what to do it means we are living in a very
unhealthy situation. It means that the government is doing
something it should not be doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia has come under intense international criticism for
alleged human-rights violations and large numbers of civilian
casualties in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   While state-run media here have been largely supportive of
Russia's conduct in the war, some privately owned newspapers, radio
and television stations have been more critical.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Clinton administration official, in Moscow for talks,
said he had raised the issue of press freedoms with the Russians.
The official, who spoke on condition he not be identified, said it
was too early to tell whether or not a crackdown on the media was
coming under Putin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The history of freedom of the press in Russia is not that
long. This is a country that has a different attitude about the
balance of order and freedom then we have, and they're struggling
with it,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Filipov of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1914EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9033 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NJ-SPRAWL-ART-2NDTAKE     03-16 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-SPRAWL-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 HOPEWELL, N.J.: Jersey sites.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Eileen McGinnis, the governor's chief policy adviser, lives in
Hopewell and defends the project, even as she has her own personal
misgivings about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I separate my personal feelings from my professional
feelings,'' McGinnis said. ``On a personal level I drive by it
every day and I do wish the project wasn't there. But on a
professional level I know that the State Plan is not about no
growth, it's about smart growth.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The State Plan, adopted in 1992 as guidelines for directing
growth to areas with transportation access and to already built-up
areas, is often invoked by preservationists for its goal that the
state should use its power to push some new development towards the
state's hollowed-out cities. But the plan's guidelines are
advisory, not mandatory and subject to economic and political
pressures.
</P>
<P>
   The Merrill Lynch site is designated for growth under the State
Plan as an area with public space such as retail and housing.
Critics point out, however, that there is no public component in
the 3.5 million square foot first phase.
</P>
<P>
   The site is designated as a growth area under the State Plan,
because it is adjacent to an interstate highway.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But Jeff Tittle, executive director of the New Jersey Sierra
Club, maintains that by helping Merrill Lynch build on a pristine
rural site, it was working against its own aim of buying land for a
public greenway trail from the Delaware River to Princeton through
Hopewell, since all land in the area will now be made much more
expensive by the immense new development.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Building deep in the country makes perfect sense from the
company's perspective, said Hamill, even though the state might
have wished that the project had gone go to a city like Trenton,
which has acres of unused industrial space, and which lies only a
few miles from Hopewell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cities in general, and Trenton is no exception, are much
less certain than the suburbs as planning environments,'' Hamill
said. ``Things don't happen as quickly in the cities, buildings
inspections aren't on time and policy plans are much more vague, so
anyone going there has this uncertainty in the approval process.''
</P>
<P>
   When Merrill Lynch told the state that it would build in
Hopewell or leave New Jersey, state officials gingerly raised the
idea of building in Trenton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merrill Lynch officials said very clearly that they would not
look at Trenton,'' said Tom Dalessio, an assistant in the
governor's policy office. ``They wanted a suburban style campus, so
it was either here or Pennsylvania.''
</P>
<P>
   In Hopewell, Merrill Lynch found 450 acres of open farmland that
had been owned, with development in mind, by Bristol Myers Squibb,
the pharmaceutical concern, since 1955.
</P>
<P>
   It also found a five-member all-Republican town board with
strong land-owner sympathies that welcomed the prospect of millions
of dollars in new taxes for sewers and schools. It did not hurt
that the company also bought 440 additional acres across the road
from William E. Schluter, an influential state senator who sits on
the Economic Growth, Agriculture and Tourism committee.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch has final approval to build 1.3 million square
feet of office space on the land, and has preliminary approval to
build 2.2 million more at the site. The adjacent 440 acres is zoned
for 2 million square feet of commercial development, for a total of
5.5 million square feet potential _ and probable _ construction on
both sides of the road. One World Trade Center tower contains 4
million square feet.
</P>
<P>
   Local reaction followed the now familiar arc from surprise to
anger to despair. An anti-growth coalition swept the Republicans on
the town board and replaced them with a 4-to-1 Democratic majority
that succeeded in stopping Merrill Lynch's preferred sewer option _
it has others _ but could not block the development.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Now Ferry, an office worker, has to wonder if she and her
husband Dennis, a chemist, should think of moving again, to stay
ahead of the wave. When they moved from their starter home in
Trenton to a house in Hamilton in 1978, they had fields behind.
When they left for Hopewell in 1985, she said, the fields in
Hamilton were covered with houses, and a drive that once took ten
minutes took half an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do we go next?'' Ferry wondered. `There's really no
place you can go to hide.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
