<HEADER>
A9035 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-FILM-DESTINATION-SPI &LR;      03-16 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DESTINATION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUN MOSTLY MISSING FROM `DESTINATION' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SEAN AXMAKER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was only a matter of time before someone twisted the
spiritual sight of ``I see dead people'' into a teenage body count
spectacle with a metaphysical hook.
</P>
<P>
   Devon Sawa is high school student Alex Browning, a kid who
awakens from a frightful dream with the powers of foresight.
</P>
<P>
   He's on a plane waiting for takeoff when he ``sees'' the flight
explode, but his panicked plea falls on deaf ears as he and a
handful of passengers caught in his fracas are removed from the
flight. When the plane explodes, he's the FBI's top suspect, but
the deaths don't stop there. Seven would-be passengers have cheated
death, and death has a rain check.
</P>
<P>
   Director James Wong and his co-writer Glen Morgan are
``X-Files'' alumni who helped that show perfect its formula of
eerie images of other-worldy suggestion leavened with a hint of
humor. But they start the film off so grim and humorless that the
first half almost sinks into silliness.
</P>
<P>
   The first death, involving toilet bowl cleaner, is farfetched
and mean-spirited. The second is a black joke played for pure shock
effect.
</P>
<P>
   The third ``killing'' is a meticulously constructed sequence
that turns a series of random events into doomed inevitability and
presents it as devilish spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   There's no wisecracking killer, no mysterious supernatural
presence. These kids are up against a confluence of fate, chance
and an absurd skew on the laws of probability. Their only defense
is Alex's visions.
</P>
<P>
   Once the picture settles on its preferred method of execution,
Wong starts to have some fun. Tony Todd (``Candyman'' to horror
movie aficionados) plays an unsettling mortician who whispers
``death has a design.'' The scene is half tongue-in-cheek and Todd
is the only actor in the film who manages to straddle the line
between seriousness and spoof.
</P>
<P>
   When Alex and his glum art-chick girlfriend (Ali Larter)
immediately take his cockeyed philosophy as a literal explanation,
the film falls back into its seesaw tonal shifts, one minute stone
serious, the next playfully goofing.
</P>
<P>
   When it gets the tone right, as it does increasingly toward the
end, ``Final Destination'' is clever and often deviously
entertaining, but ultimately it's all about Wong's imaginative
spectacles from the amusement park of the grim reaper. If the rest
of the film was directed with as much deftness and wit, he might
have another ``Scream'' on his hands. Instead, he'll have to settle
for an appreciative giggle.
</P>
<P>
   Final Destination. Directed by James Wong. Screenplay by Wong,
Glen Morgan and Jeffrey Reddick. Cast: Devon Sawa, Ali Larter,
Seann W. Scott, Kerr Smith, Chad E. Donella. New Line Cinema. 93
minutes. Rated R for violence and language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1917EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0283 </DOCNO>
