<HEADER>
A9038 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-L.A.-OPERA-NYT &LR;      03-16 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-L.A.-OPERA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RIGOLETTO' GOES HOLLYWOOD: LA DONNA E MOBILE, BABY 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By DAVID MERMELSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In a city where movies dominate culture, the Los
Angeles Opera has never attained a high profile. Yet rather than
meekly accepting second-class status, the company is forging links
with Hollywood, enticing directors and designers to apply their
skills in its service.
</P>
<P>
   Until now the results of this strategy have been decidedly
underwhelming, with the film director Herbert Ross making the only
substantial contribution to the cross-pollination when he
supervised a conventional staging of ``La Boheme'' in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But on March 1 the Los Angeles Opera unveiled a new production
of Verdi's ``Rigoletto,'' relocating the action from 16th-century
Mantua to present-day Hollywood. The production, which runs through
Tuesday at the Dorothy Chandler Pavilion (home of the opera company
and, frequently, the Academy Awards), is directed by Bruce
Beresford, whose films include ``Breaker Morant,'' ``Driving Miss
Daisy'' and ``Double Jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
   Changing an opera's time and place is nothing new, of course.
But the Los Angeles Opera's attempt at contemporaneity, an
unapologetic embrace of the movie world, is a bold move.
</P>
<P>
   There is no mistaking the company's intent. In advertisements
for the production, the opera's name is superimposed on a Beverly
Hills street sign. And the program features a contrived plot
synopsis instead of a standard explication of the story.
</P>
<P>
   In Beresford's production the Duke of Mantua, that amoral
playboy whose third-act aria ``La donna e mobile'' rings in
everyone's head, is now Duke Mantua, ``head of a thriving
production company,'' in the words of the program. Rigoletto, the
deformed, smart-mouthed court jester whose cheek begets deadly
consequences, has been turned into a Hollywood agent. The assassin
Sparafucile has morphed into a stuntman.
</P>
<P>
   What has not been changed, purists will be relieved to know, is
Verdi's music and the libretto. Even the supertitles above the
Chandler stage remain true to Francesco Maria Piave's original
text, though opera company officials and Beresford did consider
altering them to match the action.
</P>
<P>
   Beresford, who directed his first opera in 1986, defends the
integrity of his staging. ``I don't think anything's lost,'' he
said. `` `Rigoletto' has been done since 1851, and there have been
so many God-awful conventional productions.'' With sets by John
Stoddart and costumes by Johann Stegmeir, Beresford's production
looks anything but conventional. Stoddart has made the Duke's
sumptuous palace a sparely furnished, ultramodern Hollywood Hills
mansion and has turned the dilapidated inn near which the opera
concludes into a seedy Venice Beach bar. Stegmeir has outfitted the
cast in trendy fashion statements, with the principals wearing
slightly modified Giorgio Armani designs. Hipsters are certain to
recognize the eyeglasses replacing masks in the first act's second
scene; they come courtesy of L.A. Eyeworks, an expensive optical
boutique that counts movie stars among its clients.
</P>
<P>
   On opening night a mix of reactions greeted the production. The
audience, weighted with Hollywood people, seemed delighted by
novelties like a fake swimming pool and dancers boogieing to
Verdi's faux Renaissance strains. The use of a prop cell phone to
convey the exclamation ``Gran nuovo!'' (``Great news!'') also
brought smiles, though the ringing of a real one mid-performance
caused frowns among more traditional operagoers. As the final
curtain fell, scattered boos mingled with loud cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Critical response was also mixed. Writing in Daily Variety, Alan
Rich called the production ``one of the company's few genuine
Verdian triumphs.'' But Mark Swed, chief music critic of The Los
Angeles Times, found the updating imperfect and the production
design ``annoyingly tacky,'' and he was troubled by Beresford's
turning Sparafucile into a ``black thug.''
</P>
<P>
   But the reviews have apparently had little impact on ticket
sales. The eight-performance run is selling very well, the company
said.
</P>
<P>
   More important, the production appears to have registered, at
least to some degree, on Hollywood's radar. The opening-night cast
party (at which the vegetarian buffet was flanked by klieg lights,
director's chairs and outsize film reels) included such actors as
Faye Dunaway and Kyle MacLachlan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love anything that makes something more accessible,'' said
-MacLachlan, repeating a common refrain. Dunaway said, ``It worked
for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   An arguably more discerning encomium came from the veteran
soprano and teacher Phyllis Curtin, in from the East Coast to give
a master class. ``I enjoyed it tremendously and thought it in no
way betrayed the music,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps fearful that the attention focused on this production
might cause some to question the the opera company's professional
seriousness, Peter Hemmings, its general director, is playing down
the Hollywood angle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This production wasn't intended to be a vote-catching thing,''
he said. ``It's an opportunity to shed a new light on a standard
work, and I think we've seized the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Hemmings, however, has in the past made no secret of his desire
to involve the film world in his company's efforts, not only for
the potentially intriguing artistic results but also with the hope
that Hollywood might bring money to the collaboration, since the
Los Angeles Opera, like most nonprofit arts organizations, depends
on the support of patrons, and new productions almost always demand
underwriting.
</P>
<P>
   Next season the company will have a new artistic director,
Placido Domingo, and he is already talking about courting film
people. ``We have to be very much connected with the world of
Hollywood,'' he said recently.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to reviving Ross' ``Boheme,'' Domingo has engaged
the film director John Schlesinger (``Midnight Cowboy,'' ``The Next
Best Thing'') to direct Benjamin Britten's ``Peter Grimes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan on involving the studios, too,'' Domingo said. ``In a
city so connected to the movies, it will be a nice marriage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
