<HEADER>
A9040 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS &LR;      03-16 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRASHING BAD WEEK FOR CORDOVA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRADENTON, Fla. _ Life in limbo was not supposed to be this
hellish.
</P>
<P>
   Marty Cordova Thursday morning was angry, vexed, and perplexed,
but he also was still a member of the Red Sox, the team that
doesn't want him. ``I don't know what's going on,'' Cordova had
said of his descent into baseball limbo.
</P>
<P>
   And then, a few hours later, Cordova was laid out on the grass
behind third base, players and coaches first signaling for a
stretcher after a three-way chase for the popup among Cordova,
shortstop Nomar Garciaparra, and third baseman John Valentin in the
fourth inning of the game with the Pirates. Cordova and Garciaparra
had collided.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin, Garciaparra and Cordova all were on the ground as the
collective breaths of the Red Sox were held. Valentin got up first,
then Garciaparra, but Cordova remained on the grass.
</P>
<P>
   In time, Cordova was able to get to his feet. The Red Sox and
Pittsburgh trainers accompanied Cordova to nearby Manatee Memorial
Hospital, where X-rays of his ribs proved negative. Cordova was
released from the hospital just in time to catch the Red Sox buses
heading back to Boston's headquarters in Fort Myers.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Garciaparra) got me in the side of the ribs,'' said Cordova
before stepping on the bus, ``but I'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was running for the ball, you know?'' said Garciaparra. ``I
saw (Cordova) and I looked at him and I saw his hat fly off but I
thought I maybe had a chance for the ball. I knew I'd hit him
pretty good. I looked down and it wasn't pretty. I was scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra's right knee _ the knee he'd strained earlier in
camp _ had hit Cordova ``and I got something square with me knee,''
said the shortstop, still distraught an hour after the play. ``When
I looked down, I looked at him. I wanted to see his face right
away. His head was down and I was kind of worried about that . . .
I got him right in the ribs.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, who said he was unhurt, said ``You don't like to
see anybody get hurt like that. You don't like to see one of your
teammates go down like that. You don't want anybody to get hurt.
You're scared.''
</P>
<P>
   As Valentin reconstructed the play, ``The wind was blowing
pretty hard, and I really thought the popup was just a little in
back of me. But it kept going and it hung up there and I really
didn't have a shot at it. Nomar and Marty were going after it . . .
it was like no-man's land there, and both were being aggressive for
the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   So, a truly weird scenario had played out Thursday because
Cordova, officially sent into limbo by general manager Dan Duquette
Tuesday, appeared in Bradenton, put on a Red Sox uniform, and was
promptly put in the starting lineup by manager Jimy Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``C'mon on the trip,''' Williams said he told Cordova Thursday
morning in Fort Myers, as Cordova tried to regain his bearings
after the Red Sox had failed to put him on their major league
roster. ``C'mon on the trip and I'll play you in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Cordova suited up, hacked his swings in BP and took his position
in left field against the Pirates, even though the Red Sox
Wednesday had chosen not to assign him to their major league
roster. Under the contract Cordova had signed with Boston in
January, the Red Sox had until March 15 to assign him to their
major league roster or Cordova would be free to make a deal
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Which his agent energetically had been trying to do since
Wednesday morning. And a Yankees scout was busily writing notes
during Boston's game Thursday at McKechnie Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they weren't ready to make a deal yet,'' Cordova
said before the game of his decision to once again put on a Red Sox
uniform, ``so I decided my best choice was to remain here.''
</P>
<P>
   And play the game.
</P>
<P>
   Alas.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth inning, with the gusts blowing straight out,
Pittsburgh already leading, 13-6, behind six home runs, John Vander
Wal lifted a high pop behind third base. Popups and fly balls
already had been adventuresome in the swirling wind, especially to
Red Sox center fielder Michael Coleman, but this time Cordova,
Valentin and Garciaparra had a bead on the ball, until . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``If something comes up, I've got to do the best for me,''
Cordova had said. ``They pretty much said they're going to go
day-by-day with me, so now I've got to look out for myself. I
understand that I'm still a Boston Red Sox, but also I'm a person,
too, and I've got to do what's best for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Cordova had been asked if he might try extra
hard to make an impression on the Red Sox. His words in the morning
belied his extra effort in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's little point in trying to make an impression now, or
putting on a power display, said Cordova. ``Anybody who knows me
knows I'm going to hit 15 or 20 home runs a year, and that I'm
going to drive in runs _ I've always been good in driving in runs.
I always like to get up there with runners in scoring position and
I always hit well then.''
</P>
<P>
   Cordova was only winding up.
</P>
<P>
   ``They knew what they were getting when they talked to me in the
offseason,'' he went on. ``It wasn't as if I come out here and I
hit 15 home runs, they're getting Mark McGwire. That's not the way
it is. They know the type of player I am. They know I can play
several positions in the outfield, They know I can steal bases. I
can DH. They know I can play defense in the outfield. They know the
role.''
</P>
<P>
   And now Cordova delivered.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I went out (Thursday) and hit four home runs, I don't think
tomorrow they'd say, `Ohmygosh, we've got Mark McGwire.''' No, said
the outfielder, it'd make no difference if he went 0 for 4 or
4-for-4, ``they already know what they've got.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is a hustling, aggressive outfielder who gave his all for
a team that didn't want him a day earlier. And found himself in a
Bradenton hospital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
