<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9041 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-NIKKO-FIRS-ART-NYT &LR;      03-16 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIKKO-FIRS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RARE FIRS STAND TALL AGAINST EXTINCTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT17 and NYT18 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By ANNE RAVER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Nikko firs rose 70 feet over our heads, their
soft needles and elegant branching more suggestive of a mountain on
the coast of Japan than the rivers of traffic around their home at
the New York Botanical Garden in the Bronx. But this rare stand of
30 trees, which includes a few American and Mediterranean firs, is
in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were planted in the '20s, when precipitation and
temperature were very different,'' said Dr. Kim Tripp, the
botanical garden's vice president for horticulture. ``And we didn't
have as much pollution.''
</P>
<P>
   The trees are suffering the effects of summers of high heat and
drought, and winters with temperatures rising and falling like a
roller coaster. These shallow-rooted firs can't reach deep into the
earth for moisture during a drought. And when temperatures rise
suddenly in winter, the trees begin photosynthesizing and losing
water from their thousands of flat needles. Their roots try to draw
moisture from the soil, but the ground is frozen, so the trees dry
out. Add to that the pollutants of city life, and, well, these firs
are on shaky ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing this skyline of firs in New York City is just
amazing,'' said Tripp, who earned her doctorate at North Carolina
State University in Raleigh. ``But if something happened tomorrow,
we could never replace them.''
</P>
<P>
   She was referring to something like the ill wind that felled
10,000 trees in Versailles, France, last year. Even if new firs
were planted, she said, they wouldn't thrive under today's
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp, who is partial to conifers, cone-bearing trees, led the
way through the 40-acre collection, noting how it fans out ``like a
skirt around the conservatory,'' ad contains specimens rare even
in Japan. Many of the trees were artfully planted over the rocky
hills 100 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they have a certain persistence and stateliness,''
Tripp said, standing by a towering Himalayan pine with long soft
needles. Conifers are ancient plants, which evolved to withstand
the wind, intense light and poor soil of high elevations. Plants
with needles conserve more moisture than those with broad leaves,
which turn their stomata toward the sun. (Stomata are microscopic
holes that allow the exchange of carbon dioxide, oxygen and
moisture.)
</P>
<P>
   Conifers also conserve energy by not replacing their canopy
every year. ``They're a mutual fund kind of tree, rather than a
Nasdaq kind of tree,'' Tripp said.
</P>
<P>
   We walked toward a grove of five tanyosho pines, their
red-orange multistem trunks and spreading branches kindled with the
fiery light of the setting sun. Then we stood among them, almost
mesmerized by their gracious spacing, 20 feet from one another. It
was like music.
</P>
<P>
   ``These trees are the most extraordinary in the country,'' Tripp
said. ``Even in Japan, a grove of this distinction would be highly
revered.''
</P>
<P>
   A single Pinus bungeana, or lacebark pine, stands at the grove's
edge, its mottled green, gray and white bark a stark contrast to
the red pines.
</P>
<P>
   ``As it gets older, it will turn completely white,'' Tripp said.
``It glows like a ghost in the moonlight.'' This tree, planted in
1909, is now threatened in the wild, so it, too, is a living
treasure.
</P>
<P>
   As winter tumbles into spring, the conifer collection will
provide a dramatic backdrop for early bloomers like the kobus
magnolia, which nestles in a protected depression in the hill just
south of the conservatory. Its great open shape shows the benefits
of years of judicious pruning, and its branches spread 35 feet
across. Right now, they are loaded with big fuzzy gray buds, which
have swelled in warm days. Let's hope that a sudden freeze doesn't
turn their velvety petals to brown rags.
</P>
<P>
   If you hurry, you may see the sprawling granddaddy of a witch
hazel, Hamamelis mollis, still blooming. Its dangling yellow
ribbons look like bursts of light against the firs' dark curtain of
green needles.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp trudged energetically up the hill across from the
conservatory to show off the fine old cherry trees, which are still
dark silhouettes of black trunks and bare limbs, surrounded by
somber black pines.
</P>
<P>
   ``They bloom before the leaves come out,'' Tripp said. ``So you
have all this floral extravagance next to the reserve of the pines.
I just want to run up and kiss them.'' The design, laid out 100
years ago, with just that achingly exquisite moment in mind, is
still working.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp fell in love with botanical gardens as a student at North
Carolina State, where her mentor, J.C. Raulston built an arboretum
on a shoestring and the labor and passion of his horticulture
students.
</P>
<P>
   They wrote a book together, ``The Year in Trees: Superb Wood
Plants for Four-Season Gardens'' (Timber Press, 1995), and Tripp is
continuing the Raulston tradition of propagating rare plants and
getting them into the trade.
</P>
<P>
   She hopes to propagate specimen trees, like the great Korean
white pine, which rises 30 feet, with branches twisting this way
and that like a dancer on a windswept hill.
</P>
<P>
   If you have ever wondered why pines twist and turn the way they
do, it has to do with the growing tips turning toward light. If
something blocks that light, like a building or growing plant, the
branch turns in another direction.
</P>
<P>
   And if you can't tell the difference between a fir and a spruce,
just try to roll a fir needle between your fingers. You can't.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's flat,'' Tripp said. ``Just remember `firs' and `flat.'''
A spruce needle, on the other hand, rolls easily between the
fingers. And its cones hang down, while a fir tree's cones stand
up. Though the firs here, alas, have no cones, which is an ominous
sign of their distress.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp is a born teacher _ she came to the Bronx from Smith
College, in Northampton, Mass., where she taught plant science and
public garden administration, and directed the college botanic
garden _ so if you bump into a beaming woman worshiping the
tanyosho pines at sunset, she will no doubt show you something.
Like how the fine needles of these red pines look like filigree
lace full of tiny cones when you stand beneath them and look
straight up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite a tough landscape tree,'' she said. ``And if you
plant one, you can experience some of that beauty in your own
garden.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't let these big specimens discourage you from trying them in
your own little backyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a small garden and would like a paperback maple,
then you should have it, as long as you have enough light,'' Tripp
said. ``If it's no longer appropriate 15 years from now, you can
donate or sell it to a nursery.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the garden, we could see the firs rising over the tops of
all the other trees, and I wondered how long they would survive the
ravages of a hotter, drier climate and the polluted city. So go see
them now, before they are just a memory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
