u w BC-CLINTON-LAW-LICENSE-6     03-16 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LAW-LICENSE-610&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEEKS EXTENSION IN ARKANSAS ETHICS COMPLAINT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton asked a special lawyers committee
in Arkansas Thursday to grant him an extension until after he
leaves office to respond to an ethics complaint that could cost him
his law license in his home state.
</P>
<P>
   The deadline for Clinton to respond to the complaint was
Thursday. Under state rules, Clinton was required to seek an
extension or respond to the complaint from a federal judge and a
conservative legal group asking that the bar group consider some
kind of punishment for what they asserted was his dishonesty under
oath about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyer, David Kendall, said in a brief statement that
he had asked the Arkansas Supreme Court Committee on Professional
Conduct to extend the deadline until Feb. 19 of next year, 30 days
after the president leaves office. Kendall said the filing was made
under seal and he would have no further public comment.
</P>
<P>
   The law provides for a possible extension of up to 90 days,
making the president's request for a delay of nearly a year highly
unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew J. Glavin, the president of the Southeastern Legal
Foundation, which filed one of the original complaints, said he
would challenge the request for such a long delay, both with the
lawyers committee and, if necessary, at the state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Howard Brill of the University of Arkansas Law School
at Fayetteville, the leading authority on how lawyers are
disciplined in Arkansas, said several factors could persuade the
committee to grant the extension.
</P>
<P>
   He said lawyers have their licenses suspended or revoked mainly
to protect the public from unscrupulous lawyers with active
practices in Arkansas. Clinton has not practiced law in Arkansas
for many years.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Brill said, the case against Clinton is based entirely
on the record of his testimony and public statements, which means
there is no issue of a need to move quickly to prevent witnesses
from having their memories fade or because evidence might become
harder to obtain.
</P>
<P>
   The case involves Clinton's statements under oath on Jan. 17,
1998, when he gave a deposition in the sexual misconduct lawsuit
brought by Paula Jones. In the presence of Judge Susan Weber
Wright, who was presiding over the civil lawsuit, Clinton said he
had never engaged in a sexual relationship with Lewinsky, a
one-time White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton has continued to insist his answer was legally
accurate, Wright strongly disagreed and ruled that he was in civil
contempt of court. She said the president had subverted the rule of
law and violated Jones' right to information in her civil rights
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Wright referred the matter to the Arkansas bar committee last
April but the case remained dormant until Glavin's group filed a
second complaint and asked the state Supreme Court to order the
committee to move on the complaints.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the Arkansas Supreme Court ordered the committee to
move on the complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Brill said the January ruling in which the court ordered the
committee to get on with it may make it difficult for its members
to grant the long extension that Kendall is seeking.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, a Yale Law School graduate, is still licensed to
practice law in Arkansas and still holds Arkansas Bar
identification number 78019 although he has spent most of his adult
life in politics. Whatever penalty might be imposed might be mostly
an embarrassment rather than a hindrance to his employment after he
leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Kendall's statement that the president is seeking
an extension to file a response shows that he will not easily
surrender his license as some have speculated.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In an interview, Glavin said, ``This request is outrageous and
unreasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavin said Clinton was asking that the public interest be set
aside for his convenience.
</P>
<P>
   The arguments about the delay are similar to those in which
Clinton sought to have the Jones lawsuit delayed until after he
left office only to have the U.S. Supreme Court rule that he could
not do so.
</P>
<P>
   In its unanimous ruling, the court said the Jones lawsuit would
probably not take up too much of his time. As the lawsuit led to
the discovery of Clinton's relationship with Lewinsky and
ultimately to the impeachment battle, that ruling has since been
widely criticized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
