<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9045 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ONLINE-GROCERY-NYT &LR;      03-16 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-GROCERY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLED ONLINE GROCERY PIONEER CONSIDERING PUTTING ITSELF ON
MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Minn., Mass.)  (rk) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After nine money-losing years in the online grocery business it
pioneered, Peapod Inc. Thursday appeared ready to pack it in.
</P>
<P>
   The company announced that its 46-year-old chief executive and
president, Bill Malloy, who had been hired from AT&AMP;T's wireless
division less than six months ago, would be leaving for unspecified
health reasons. Then a group of investors who had promised to put
$120 million into the company said they would not be doing so,
given the departure of Malloy.
</P>
<P>
   And the company said it had asked its investment bank,
Wasserstein Perella &AMP; Co., to explore ``strategic alternatives,''
including a sale.
</P>
<P>
   It was a dramatic shift for Peapod, whose co-founder and chief
technology officer, Thomas Parkinson, is shown in a photograph on
the company's Web site dressed in a green peapod costume. The
company, which is based in Skokie, Ill., and had $51.6 million in
sales during the first half of last year, would not elaborate on
its statement, and a spokeswoman refused to say what Malloy's
illness or symptoms were.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Peapod, which began trading at $16 apiece when the
company went public in June 1997, fell more than 50 percent
Thursday to close at $3.72. The company said its chairman, Andrew
Parkinson, who founded the company with his brother, would step
into the role of chief executive. In addition, two board members,
Drayton McLane and Mark Van Steklenburg, will assist him, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which invested in bright green Volkswagen Beetles
that it christened ``Pod Bugs'' to help market itself, has just $3
million in cash, it disclosed Thursday, and may seek alternative
financing to replace the $120 million that was pulled out. Apollo
Management was one of the companies that had promised Peapod an
investment, but changed its mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you lose a significant player like Bill was, there
certainly would be some nervous investors,'' said George S.
Dahlman, an analyst for US Bancorp Piper Jaffray in Minneapolis,
who called Malloy ``a sparkplug'' who fit in well at Peapod. ``This
group was about to buy half the company.''
</P>
<P>
   The company was a pioneer in what has proved to be a tricky
business. Consumers, while they say they want convenience, have
been slow to embrace the concept of buying groceries on the
Internet. Peapod and its competitors, which include Webvan,
Netgrocer and Streamline, have encountered obstacles in figuring
out how to get those groceries delivered without having them melt
or run into other unappealing developments. Solutions have ranged
from relying on Federal Express to installing refrigerators in
customers' garages.
</P>
<P>
   A few large grocery chains intend to start their own online
services, mainly as a means of prying market share away from other
bricks-and-mortar rivals, and that is expected to put further
pressure on smaller players. Recently, Peapod had reorganized
itself and switched from relying on supermarkets to fill their
customers' orders to relying on their own warehouses, said David
Cooperstein, an online retail analyst for Forrester Research in
Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Evie Black Dykema, another analyst for Forrester, said she did
not think Peapod's experience would mean the continued decline of
the online grocery business. ``As more consumers start using the
service, it will drive density, which lowers the incremental costs
to each consumer,'' she said. And once demand reaches critical
mass, online retailers will raise prices for brand-name products,
improving their own margins, and start emphasizing private-label
competitors, she added.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, many companies are working on solutions to the
problem of how to deliver groceries to customers who are away from
home all day, without anyone else around to accept the packages.
``There are a number of options emerging, like satellite-controlled
garage doors that will open for particular retailers, and
unattended delivery boxes on front lawns,'' Dykema said. ``If all
Americans had doormen, we wouldn't have this issue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
