<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9048 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BKC-PITINO-COX     03-16 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PITINO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pitino really needs a string of victories
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're an interesting pair, Lenny Wilkens and Rick Pitino, the
former on track for perhaps his worst record in 27 years as an NBA
coach, the latter, trying to gird a young team for an uphill run at
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In his seventh year as coach of the Hawks, Wilkens has been
unable to win with the assortment of players Pete Babcock gave him
in a rebuilding year.
</P>
<P>
   In his third year as coach of the Celtics, Pitino is trying to
win with the latest crop of young talent he brought in as president
of the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkins' team is 24-39, 12 defeats shy of his worst two seasons
ever and has dropped nine of 11 in a town where interest has always
been a sometime thing. The Hawks are in lottery land and every
beating brings them a small step closer to a higher draft choice.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino's bunch has won four of its last five and at 28-36 sits 2
1/2 games behind No. 8 Orlando. But the Celtics tonight take the
first step on a 19-day path that has them playing nine of 11 games
away from Fleet Center. At 6-25 on the road, a victory tonight is
mandatory if the Celtics are going to show they mean business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to do it on the road and we're a
tremendous home team,'' Pitino noted after the Celtics creamed
Golden State, 121-104, Tuesday in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be our key to decide whether we go to the
playoffs,'' forward Paul Pierce added. ``Starting Friday is the big
test for us and we haven't been doing it on the road all year long,
but somehow we have to pull it out. It's gut-check time for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics have not been to the playoffs since 1995 when they
were eliminated by Orlando in the first round. In his third season,
Pitino is only 83-113 in Boston, 14 games under .500 in five years
as an NBA coach after winning 74 percent of his college games at
Boston U., Providence and Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Once, this was Pitino's time of year - ``the greatest month in
all of basketball.'' He took Providence to the NCAA semifinal in
1987, took Kentucky to the national semifinal game before losing in
overtime to Michigan in 1993, won the championship with Kentucky in
1996, lost the championship game to Arizona (with Jason Terry) in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   But recruiting in college was easier for Pitino than drafting,
trading and free agent signings. With the Celtics it's been one
step forward, two back. Yes, Antoine Walker and Paul Pierce are
gems. But he could not recruit Tim Duncan and missed him when the
Spurs scored a lottery upset and pulled No. 1 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   And look at the missteps: drafting Chauncey Billups with the
third pick overall in 1997; trading his other 1997 first-rounder
Ron Mercer (No. 6 overall) last August for Eric Williams
(previously a Pitino discard) and Danny Fortson. How about $30-plus
million for Vitaly Potapenko, $8 million to Walter McCarty, $24
million for Chris Mills before dumping him in New York?
</P>
<P>
   A lot of games, not much fun for Pitino, whose relationship with
owner Paul Gaston has deteriorated as his relationship with Celtics
fans cooled, long before he lectured the city about it's
``negativity.''
</P>
<P>
   But at a time when Atlanta is hearing the unfounded and
unwarranted rumor of Tubby Smith, Pitino is dealing with silly talk
in Beantown. Understand the Celtics still owe him $29 million over
the next seven years (three as coach, four as president), so you
know he's not going away. Know that the balance of his contract is
due in full with a few days if he's fired and you know the Celtics
aren't even thinking about running him out.
</P>
<P>
   Here's where Pitino enjoys another edge on Wilkens who has $10.4
million on his contract. That translates to a little less
protection.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
