<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WOMENS-BRACKET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UConn, Vols gear up for tourney
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pat Summitt of Tennessee and Connecticut's Geno Auriemma tried
to make the case this week that their respective routes to the
Final Four may not be as easy as they're perceived.
</P>
<P>
   The two programs that have won four of the last five national
championships are once again at the top of the heap as the NCAA
Tournament begins today.
</P>
<P>
   But neither team made the Final Four last year. UConn hasn't
been there since 1996, and Tennessee's bid for four straight NCAA
crowns came up short in the Elite 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why these are the three greatest weeks in sports,''
Auriemma said. ``You better bring your 'A' game with you just in
case the other team brings theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies (30-1), No. 1 all season, shouldn't have to worry
about that tonight against Hampton in the East Regional.
Second-ranked Tennessee (28-3), the top seed in the Mideast, gets
underway Saturday against Furman.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a lot of competition, anything can happen,'' said
Summitt, whose team wouldn't have to go out of state to reach the
Final Four. ``Right now, our goal is just to be in Memphis (site of
the Mideast Regional).''
</P>
<P>
   UConn and Tennessee split two regular season games that
generated solid television ratings. And because the Final Four
regional pairings aren't determined until after the 64-team bracket
is drawn up, there's plenty of anticipation that they could meet
for the national championship in Philadelphia on April 2.
</P>
<P>
   So where does that leave everyone else? A Philadelphia Inquirer
columnist recently described Georgia and Louisiana Tech, the other
top seeds and in the national elite for more than 20 years, as
``lesser giants.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Georgia's a great example,'' said coach Tara VanDerveer of
Stanford, whose team could face the Lady Bulldogs in the second
round. ``Sometimes it seems like they're totally in the shadows.
They were in the Final Four last year, not UConn or Tennessee. If
there's anyone who could feel put out, it would be Andy
(Landers).''
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia coach says he doesn't care. Nor was he surprised
when Tennessee bumped the Lady Dogs out of the No. 2 ranking in the
writers' poll after edged UConn 72-71 in February, only two weeks
after Georgia crushed the Lady Vols by 27 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It falls into that group of things you have no control over,''
Landers said. ``Sometimes you guys (the media) feed that monster.''
</P>
<P>
   And that two-headed monster that emerged when UConn toppled
Tennessee in the 1995 NCAA finals has been slow to embrace other
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to the rest of us to get it done on the court,''
VanDerveer said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
