r s BC-GLF-MASTERS-COX     03-16 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Masters eligibilty losing its luster, players say
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Something's definitely missing from this year's Masters, and the
PGA Tour players aren't happy about it.
</P>
<P>
   Augusta National no longer invites all PGA Tour tournament
winners from the previous Masters. Instead, it takes the top 50
from the controversial and often-confusing Official World Rankings
and the top 40 from the previous PGA Tour money list.
</P>
<P>
   That's why you won't see 1999 tournament winners Brad Faxon,
Olin Browne, Rich Beem, J.L. Lewis, Tom Pernice Jr. and Brian
Henninger at Augusta National on April 6-9.
</P>
<P>
   With the conclusion of the Doral-Ryder Open on March 5, the
Masters field was set, although another invitation could come from
The Players Championship if that winner is not in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Players say the change, in its first year, has taken some of the
luster from one of golf's most prestigious events. Golf's March
Madness is gone, and with it, the dramatics. Davis Love III won the
weekend before the Masters in New Orleans in 1995 in his final
attempt to make the field; he finished second behind Ben Crenshaw
at Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Paul Stankowski won the BellSouth Classic in Atlanta;
on the next day, he drove down Magnolia Lane, walked on the course
and scooped sand from an Augusta National bunker as a souvenir.
</P>
<P>
   ``You talk to any player who's won his first tournament,'' Billy
Andrade said, ``and the first thing they say is, 'I'm going to
Augusta.' It was great for the Masters, and, in essence, it helped
build the aura of the Masters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think,'' Love said, ``this is was one time when (the Masters
committee) followed along when they probably shouldn't have. I was
shocked when they did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Faxon recalls getting caught up in Love's 1995 run to Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   ``The saddest thing to me is, the drama of the remaining few
weeks is really gone,'' Faxon said, ``and I think it's something
that gave the Masters positive press. I'm sure that when Davis won
at New Orleans to get in the Masters, that was one of the top
stories of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   The players say that winning does not seem to matter as much as
it used to. The world rankings are such that nobody really knows
where they stand. Two weeks ago at Doral, No. 48 Paul Azinger
actually helped his Masters case by not playing. Had he made the
cut and finished in the middle of the pack, he might have dropped
out of the top 50.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the top 50 is a pretty good indication of who's played
well over the last two years,'' Nick Price said, ``but I still
think the tournament winners (from the PGA Tour) should get in. I
think they're just worried about getting too big of a field there
(at Augusta), and I'm not quite sure why.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think it's right,'' John Daly said. ``You win on
our tour, you deserve to play in the Masters. It was always cool to
see who was going to win New Orleans, who was going to get in the
Masters. Now Atlanta's there, but now it doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the eligibility changes hit Atlanta hard. The BellSouth
Classic at Sugarloaf, which swapped its pre-Masters weekend date
with New Orleans, spent only last year as the final qualification
chance for the Masters. The BellSouth was played the week before
the Masters in 1996 because of the Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great subplot,'' said Peachtree City's Franklin
Langham, who would not have made the Masters had he held his
back-nine lead at Doral two weeks ago. ``I don't understand why
they did it. You're really not talking about that many guys. I know
this -- they could have kept that money in New Orleans when Davis
won. He just wanted to play Augusta.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrade said he told Masters chairman Hootie Johnson last year
that he loved the course changes but hated the eligibility switch.
``I think that on our tour, which is the hardest tour in the world
to play, you should be rewarded by winning a tournament,'' Andrade
said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrade said Johnson told him the Masters Committee would look
into the possibility of revisiting the old qualification.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, they're inviting (amateur) Aaron Baddeley from
Australia for winning one tournament (the Australian Open),''
Andrade said. ``I don't know what kind of a field they had there,
but I know that when Phil Mickelson won the Tucson Open (in 1991 as
an amateur), he didn't get any special treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seems to be they're not taking care of our players. I
think all the changes made favor the international players.''
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to understand a field that excludes winners of
PGA Tour events while accepting the U.S. Mid-Amateur and U.S.
Public Links champions and the loser of the U.S. Amateur.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I bitter? No,'' said Faxon, who has five top-25 finishes at
Augusta in eight apperances. ``Am I disappointed? Yeah. The Masters
is my favorite tournament, and I'd love to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
