<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-GORDON-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON AND LOOMIS FEEL THE PRESSURE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK ZIER   The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The pressure to win is on Jeff Gordon this year, which means the
pressure is also on Robbie Loomis and everybody else who has
anything to do with Gordon's No. 24 Chevy.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since former crew chief Ray Evernham left late last season
to take over the Dodge program, Gordon has been in free fall. That
has added credence to Gordon's detractors, who have always
maintained it was the car _ not the driver _ that won all those
races and three Winston Cup championships before Gordon reached his
28th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Evernham has always defended Gordon, saying he is one of the
best, if not the best, drivers in NASCAR, but Gordon has done
little to prove him right since he and Evernham split.
</P>
<P>
   It can be argued that Gordon has not fallen off, but his
equipment has. He has had a host of mechanical problems since
Evernham left. The reliability once built into Gordon's cars seems
to have left along with Evernham.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday at Atlanta Motor Speedway, the Chevys were given a
rule concession by NASCAR which allowed them to extend the front
air dam two inches out from under the bumper. The Chevys seemed to
have better downforce and dominated the race. Gordon came in ninth
_ his best finish of the year _ and might have been able to
challenge Dale Earnhardt for the win had he not lost a lap when he
was forced to pit because of a blistered tire.
</P>
<P>
   When the race was over, Gordon said he thought he was as fast as
anybody at the end, which was a much needed boost for him and
perhaps even a bigger boost for Loomis, who has taken over as
Gordon's crew chief.
</P>
<P>
   In somewhat of a surprise move, Loomis, who had been running
Richard Petty's two-car operation, left to jump into the fire at
Hendrick Motorsports, where Evernham and Gordon had teamed to
dominate NASCAR in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who did not start driving in Winston Cup until 1993,
accumulated 49 victories in just seven years, tied for 10th
all-time with Rusty Wallace and won those three Winston
championships. Only two drivers in history, Petty and Earnhardt,
have won more than three championships in their career.
</P>
<P>
   When Evernham left, Loomis was brought in to continue the roll,
but it was a daunting task. Loomis understands that, having taken
over at Petty Enterprises just before Petty, the winningest and
best-known driver in NASCAR, decided to retire.
</P>
<P>
   As with Gordon now, there was immense pressure on Loomis to help
Petty Enterprises return to the domination of Petty's golden years,
and Loomis got the team headed in the right direction, although the
operation is still not where it wants to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure to win is always there,'' Loomis said. ``I don't
worry about what the expectations are.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that's surprised me is how similar Richard and Jeff
are in the way they treat people,'' Loomis said, referring to Petty
and Gordon. ``They both treat people right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Another thing that surprised me is how much he knows about the
race car,'' Loomis said of Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a good feel for how the car handles. He doesn't come in
and say we need to change the springs. He'll come in and say we
need to change the spring on the right front,'' Loomis said.
</P>
<P>
   If Gordon's slump has done nothing else, it has destroyed the
image many have of him as a spoiled brat.
</P>
<P>
   For those who have been able to observe him, Gordon has handled
his situation with class. He does not blame anybody, and he has
backed Loomis and team manager Brian Whitesell, who has gone back
to focusing on improving the cars after a brief stint as crew
chief, to the hilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a chance to help build a team again, and I enjoy
that,'' Loomis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like working with people. I learned how to do that working
with Petty,'' Loomis said. ``This team's used to being on top.
We'll get back up there.''
</P>
<P>
   (Patrick Zier writes for The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla. The Ledger
is part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
