<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-BUYING-ONLINE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROWLING CYBERSPACE'S USED-CAR LOTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: 2nd take consists of optional sidebar) 
(bl) 
 By ANDREW H. FIXMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking for a low-mileage Trans Am driven only to church on
Sundays (by a little old lady, naturally)? Or do you have your own
cream puff to sell, like that '72 Gremlin up on blocks in the
backyard?
</P>
<P>
   You can find such unlikely machines on the Internet, of course,
but increasingly you'll also find hundreds of thousands of more
promising vehicles. And if you shop on the World Wide Web, you can
kick the tires while kicking back in your pajamas _ and without a
cigar-chomping salesman barking, ``So, how much can you afford to
pay?''
</P>
<P>
   Just as entrepreneurs are remaking the new-car landscape by
trying to reduce, or replace, the middlemen between manufacturers
and consumers, others are trying to find a magic formula for
used-car sales over the Internet. Their incentive is substantial:
the used-vehicle market amounts to $370 billion a year, according
to J.D. Power &AMP; Associates, the market research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Power says that 26 percent of used-car shoppers went to the
Internet last year before buying, up from 14 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Sites that offer free used-car classified listings include top
Internet new-car retailers like Autobytel.com, AutoWeb.com and
Cars.com. Here are some other sites that offer forums for buying or
selling used cars: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AUTOTRADER.COM _ This site says it is the largest used-car
marketplace in cyberspace with 1.5 million listings. Its size can
be attributed, in part, to the participation of thousands of
bricks-and-mortar dealers and large auction houses where dealers
buy used vehicles at wholesale.
</P>
<P>
   The site allows a shopper to restrict a search by make, model
and region. For instance, one can look for a '95 Honda Accord
within 25 miles of New Brunswick, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers list their cars without charge; the site makes money by
selling enhancements like bold-face type, hyperlinks to dealerships
or ads alongside the listings.
</P>
<P>
   EBAY.COM _ This site, the Internet's premier on-line auctioneer,
recently struck an agreement with AutoTrader.com and now has
listings for most makes and models of used cars across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The cars being auctioned are coming from both dealerships and
private listings. Although it is free to buy or bid on a car, the
seller pays eBay $25 to list the car online, and another $25 after
the car is sold.
</P>
<P>
   YAHOO.COM _ As it continues to expand into new fields of
e-commerce, Yahoo now offers automobiles through its online
auction.
</P>
<P>
   Interested bidders can search for a car by make or model, but it
is difficult to restrict a search by region. A recent hunt for a
1996 Ford Mustang convertible found no available cars in the New
York City area. As with eBay, a user can search for every Mustang
convertible being auctioned and decide if the car is worth the cost
of having it shipped. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IMOTORS.COM _ This site, which calls itself the Web's only
direct used-car seller, says it will track down any car a shopper
wants, recondition it and deliver it to the customer. The site
allows a shopper to order a car up to five years old, even
specifying mileage, trim and options. But the lower the mileage,
the higher the price, and hard-to-find trim may add to the
customer's wait _ iMotors says the average wait is about three
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Imotors.com searches for the car through auctions and private
listings _ but not through dealers _ then reconditions it to retail
condition. The customer drives off with a seven-day, 700-mile
money-back guarantee and a three-month, 3,000-mile warranty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a true retailer, trying to build a new supply channel
for consumers,'' said Eli Halliwell, co-founder and chief strategy
officer. The company, which started in San Francisco, recently
expanded to the East. It now has reconditioning centers near
Cincinnati, Atlanta and Sacramento, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   BESTOFFER.COM _ This site, which currently operates only in
Northern California, holds the hands of buyers and sellers as they
move through a transaction in an auction-style marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers can list their cars without charge; both buyer and
seller pay fees after they reach a deal. To reassure potential
buyers, BestOffer sends mechanics out to make an 80-point
inspection of the vehicle and prepare a report on it. The Web site
makes arrangements with independent dealerships where sellers can
leave their cars and interested bidders can come to examine them or
take test drives. This frees sellers from having strangers come to
their homes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRICE AUTO OUTLET _ Vehicles returned to Bank of America at the
end of their leases go to giant lots in Linden, N.J.; Bethpage,
N.Y.; and Anaheim, Calif. The ever-changing inventory of these
late-model vehicles is posted at PriceAutoOutlet.com and is updated
daily.
</P>
<P>
   Prices tend to be below Kelley Blue Book values. If you find a
car on the Price site that interests you, but you live more than 50
miles away, the company will give you $50 to come over and take a
look.
</P>
<P>
   Mechanics check each vehicle. Cars come with a 72-hour
money-back guarantee and a six-month, 6,000-mile warranty.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS IN 2nd TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANOTHER SITE FOR PRICE INFORMATION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ANDREW H. FIXMER &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Playing catch-up after being left behind in the rush to the
Internet, the National Automobile Dealers Association has put its
used-car prices online.
</P>
<P>
   For 67 years, NADA, the nation's leading organization of car
dealers, has provided information on market values of cars, trucks
and motorcycles to insurance companies, lenders and government
agencies. Over the years, it added prices for other conveyances,
including motor homes, yachts and airplanes. Many consumers have
used NADA's pocket-sized yellow books to determine the current
value of a used car they are buying or selling; prices are based on
annual surveys of dealers, auctions and classified ads. Like the
book, the Web site (www.nadaguides.com) gives prices in three
categories _ low, average and high _ based on the car's condition.
</P>
<P>
   By taking so long to move online, NADA let its chief competitor
on price data, Kelley Blue Book, become entrenched. Since its
Internet debut in 1995, Kelley has expanded its site (www.kbb.com)
to offer new-car prices, buying tips and other data. It routinely
ranks among the most-used auto sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to put something out unless it was complete and
accurate,'' said Lenny Simms, general manager of NADA appraisal
guides. ``Should we have gone on the Internet five years ago? Sure,
but I think the wait was worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years there has been explosive growth in the number of
Web sites vying to play a role in the car-buying process, often by
providing leads on interested customers to dealerships in exchange
for commissions, flat fees or a percentage of sales.
</P>
<P>
   Many sites provide research tools and new-car price data. Kelley
has long offered such information, as has Edmunds.com, a
clearinghouse for consumer information that last week announced
ties with several leading Internet auto retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely have a lot of catching up to do,'' Simms said.
</P>
<P>
   NADA's site has been operating for only about a month, and it
still has some bugs. For instance, during a search for the market
price of a '94 Jaguar XJS convertible, the site asked if the car
had a sunroof.
</P>
<P>
   The NADA and Kelley Blue Book sites, which are both free,
provide similar prices. In a random sampling, Kelley's retail
prices for four common cars were within $200 of NADA's average
prices.
</P>
<P>
   While Kelley's online data bank includes only cars made within
the last 20 years, NADA provides values for 50 years, making it
more useful for old-car enthusiasts. Kelley also provides new-car
prices, which NADA intends to add this month.
</P>
<P>
   Each company asserts that its pricing guide is the industry
standard, and both expect more competition. ``When you're No. 1,
everyone wants a piece of the action,'' said Stephen Henson,
director of marketing and business development for Kelley Blue
Book. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
