   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Investors bought stocks furiously, sending
the Dow Jones industrial average up nearly 500 points in its
biggest one-day point gain since October 1987. Broader indexes also
rose sharply as investors _ at least for the day _ put aside fears
that the Federal Reserve will aggressively raise interest rates and
slow the economy. By Alex Berenson. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m.
ET in ``f'' news file.) 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   With 2-column graphic.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   NO-INSURANCE-DOCS (Undated) _ A growing number of doctors have
severed their ties to HMOs and insurance companies. In return for
cash payments, the doctors often offer a lavish level of service _
uncrowded waiting rooms, uninterrupted office visits and an office
staff that knows the patients. Nearly a decade after President
Clinton's failed effort to remake health care in America, the
health care market is remaking itself. For those with insurance or
the money to pay for health care, there is evolving a two-tiered
system. One tier is made up of doctors who have cut their prices at
the insistence of health insurers and who make up for the reduced
prices by increasing their volume. The other tier is made up of
those who offer time and attention _ but at a cost. By Lawrence K.
Altman. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
1,900 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT21,22.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-DIPLOMACY (Tokyo) _ In the space of a short few weeks,
North Korea has gone from one of the world's most politically
reclusive states, to one of the most diplomatically active. With
little fanfare, but with a speed that has surprised many observers
of the Communist country, the government in Pyongyang has
established diplomatic relations with Italy and has resumed
diplomatic discussions with Japan and Australia for the first time
in years. It has also recently sent out discreet feelers to at
least two other major Western nations, Canada and Britain. And
according to diplomats in the Philippines, it has approached their
country about joining the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
Regional Forum. By Howard French. (The story has moved in ``i''
news file.) 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-FILES (Washington) _ Nearly four years after the office
of independent counsel began investigating how the White House
acquired some 900 confidential FBI files, many of them of prominent
Republicans, the current head of the office, Robert Ray, officially
reports that there was no criminal wrongdoing involved. The report
is the first of several to be issued over the next several months
by Ray as he closes down the independent counsel's office that has
been investigating a wide range of issues involving President and
Mrs. Clinton. By Neil A. Lewis. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET
in ``w'' news file.) 1,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT20.
</P>
