<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9058 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     03-16 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTEWORTHY MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The New York Times of
new or noteworthy movies currently playing in theaters. Running
times and ratings of films are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   `ALL ABOUT MY MOTHER,' starring Cecilia Roth, Marisa Paredes,
Antonia San Juan and Penelope Cruz. Directed by Pedro Almodovar (R,
101 minutes; in Spanish with English subtitles). A whole new order
of Almodovar extravaganza. The antic fizz and theatrical
exaggeration of his earlier work have blossomed into a newly
sophisticated style, one that is far more wise and deeply felt.
Lovingly dedicated to actresses who have played actresses, this
film weaves its own soap opera around ``A Streetcar Named Desire''
and tells of splendidly resilient women; Almodovar has aptly
described his material as ``screwball drama.'' Rich and
entertaining, this story celebrates the power of artifice and
impersonation to transcend ordinary truth. The irrepressible San
Juan, a Spanish nightclub performer, plays a transsexual named
Agrado and is the film's biggest treat (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `AMERICAN BEAUTY,' starring Kevin Spacey, Annette Bening, Chris
Cooper, Wes Bentley and Thora Birch. Written by Alan Ball. Directed
by Sam Mendes (R, 116 minutes). With heavenly finesse Spacey plays
a buttoned-down 42-year-old suburbanite who flips his lid for a
teen-age cheerleader. And he never gets it back on. The midlife
crisis motif is familiar, but the stage director Sam Mendes brings
terrific visual flair and dry humor to this barbecuing of the
bourgeoisie. All the actors display coolly expert timing,
especially Bening as the antihero's grasping wife. Although the
story spreads itself thin among many characters, the film coalesces
for a devastating finale (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `BOILER ROOM,' starring Giovanni Ribisi, Vin Diesel and Ben
Affleck. Written and directed by Ben Younger (R, 110 minutes).
Ribisi portrays a young stockbroker in training at a fly-by-night
company called J.T. Marlin. Like Oliver Stone's ``Wall Street,''
``Boiler Room'' tells the story of an ambitious young man's rise,
fall and redemption. And like Charlie Sheen's Bud Fox, Ribisi's
Seth carries some heavy Oedipal baggage _ a troubled relationship
with his demanding, disapproving father _ onto the trading floor.
But at its best, which is awfully good, ``Boiler Room'' avoids the
thumping moralism that has made Stone the least misunderstood
director in Hollywood. It's less about selling your soul than about
feeling your oats (A.O. Scott).
</P>
<P>
   `THE CIDER HOUSE RULES,' starring Tobey Maguire, Charlize Theron
and Delroy Lindo. Directed by Lasse Hallstrom (PG-13, 125 minutes).
Radically downsized in scope, and its examination of the issue of
abortion greatly softened, John Irving's sixth novel (with a
Dickensian screenplay by the author) has been turned into a lovely
World War II-era fable about a young man venturing out into the
world. Maguire is Homer Wells, a doleful innocent raised in an
orphanage by Dr. Wilbur Larch (Michael Caine), who performs
abortions. Fleeing the institution with a golden young couple
(Theron and Paul Rudd), he becomes an apple picker. Sentimental but
smart, the movie has the sweetness and narrative drive of a 1940s
``David Copperfield'' (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `GHOST DOG: THE WAY OF THE SAMURAI,' starring Forest Whitaker.
Directed by Jim Jarmusch (R, 116 minutes). In his new film Jarmusch
does for the samurai epic and the gangster movie what he did for
the western in ``Dead Man,'' his dreamy, elegiac deconstruction of
cowboys-and-Indians mythology. Here he has composed a ruminative,
bittersweet visual essay on brutality, honor and tribalism, which
may frustrate audiences expecting more visceral thrills. ``Ghost
Dog'' is worth seeing for Whitaker's witty, moving performance as a
modern-day samurai caught up in a Mafia vendetta, for Jarmusch's
offbeat sense of cinematic style, and for hip-hop artist the RZA's
brilliant musical effects (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   `THE HURRICANE,' starring Denzel Washington. Directed by Norman
Jewison (R, 120 minutes). The life story of Hurricane Carter, a
middleweight contender who spent nearly 20 years in prison for a
triple murder he didn't commit, is a big, schmaltzy ballad of a
movie redeemed by Washington's moving, bone-deep portrayal of the
boxer from Paterson, N.J. But the movie plays fast and loose with
the facts, giving far too much credit to the members of a Canadian
commune who took up Carter's cause and all but eliminating his
heroic co-defendant, John Artis, from the story. And the minor
characters are either saints or monsters. Yet the story of a man
heroically fighting his demons and winning his freedom is still
inspiring (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `MISSION TO MARS,' starring Gary Sinise, Tim Robbins, Don
Cheadle and Connie Nielsen. Directed by Brian De Palma (PG, 113
minutes). This film's visual design is spectacular, and the scenes
on the Martian surface look so real that the picture could have
been made on location. But the movie is undermined by De Palma's
uncharacteristic wet-eyed awe. All this addled sincerity comes from
trying to create wonderment for adults, growing out of a morose
astronaut's rediscovery of his humanity on Mars. Sinise plays the
depressed astronaut, and his thoughtful patience makes him appear
to be a little sluggish, though not as sluggish as the movie:
narratively it seems to be taking place in zero gravity, where each
minute seems to last an additional 30 seconds. In space no one can
hear you snore (Elvis Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   `THE NEXT BEST THING,' starring Rupert Everett and Madonna.
Directed by John Schlesinger (PG-13, 107 minutes). A contemporary
screwball comedy about a Los Angeles yoga teacher (Madonna) and her
gay best friend (Everett) who have a baby together, ``The Next Best
Thing'' intermittently fizzes in its early scenes. But once it gets
serious, the movie turns into a stumbling, poor man's ``Kramer vs.
Kramer.'' Madonna is a curt, cool cookie whose painfully flat
performance is all but devoid of feeling. Everett has a few bright
comic moments as a man who discovers the joys of fatherhood
(Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `THE NINTH GATE,' starring Johnny Depp and Frank Langella.
Directed by Roman Polanski (R, 133 minutes). For those with an
interest in seeing a dinner-theater version of ``Eyes Wide Shut,''
then look no further. This film, with its wizened decadence and its
tired stabs at comedy, is calling your name. Langella is Boris
Balkan, a wealthy and therefore evil collector of Devil-inspired
antiquities, who hires Dean Corso (Depp), a weedy rogue book
dealer, to locate a volume called ``The Nine Gates.'' Will Balkan
get Satan's powers in his clutches through mastery of the book?
Polanski is out to cross ``Rosemary's Baby'' with his saucy spoof
``The Fearless Vampire Killers,'' but this movie is about as scary
as a sock-puppet re-enactment of ``The Blair Witch Project,'' and
not nearly as funny (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   `NOT ONE LESS,' starring Wei Minzhi and Zhang Huike. Directed by
Zhang Yimou (not rated, 106 minutes). Zhang Yimou's new drama
enlarges the possibilities of filmmaking even as it grounds itself
in one of cinema's oldest, most basic principles: the camera's
ability to document reality. At the center of the film is Wei (Wei
Minzhi), a 13-year-old primary school graduate who has been pressed
into service as a substitute teacher in the Shuiquan Primary
School. When one of her students is sent to the city to work off
his parents' debts, Wei, who has been promised a bonus if she can
keep her class intact (this is the source of the film's title),
sets out to bring him home. And the movie, which has so far been a
slow, touching study of village life, becomes something else: a
work of lyrical realism that has some of the shattering, redemptive
power of Vittorio De Sica's ``Bicycle Thief'' (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   `REINDEER GAMES,' starring Ben Affleck, Gary Sinise and Charlize
Theron. Directed by John Frankenheimer (R, 99 minutes). This is a
wheel-within-a-wheel thriller that's a lot of fun until, near the
end, it becomes a Xerox copy of a blueprint of a hit. Affleck, who
suggests one of the Kennedys playing Clark Kent _ he wants to keep
his light under a bushel, but he's not quite up to it _ plays Rudy,
an ex-con who gets dragged into a casino heist planned for the
Christmas season. Theron is the girl who lures him into the job.
The seamy kicks of one double cross after another keep the movie in
motion, and Frankenheimer's ruthless precision keeps it on track
(Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   `TOPSY-TURVY,' starring Allan Corduner and Jim Broadbent.
Directed by Mike Leigh (R, 161 minutes). Leigh's grandly
entertaining ``Topsy-Turvy'' is one of those films that create a
mix of erudition, pageantry and delectable acting opportunities,
much as ``Shakespeare in Love'' did. Instead of a love-struck young
playwright, it presents the curiously matched personalities of the
librettist William Schwenk Gilbert and the composer Arthur Sullivan
in the midst of a robust, knowing, frequently hilarious look at the
musical theater over which they held sway (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `WHAT PLANET ARE YOU FROM?,' starring Garry Shandling, Greg
Kinnear and Annette Bening. Directed by Mike Nichols (R, 115
minutes). There's a lot of Shandling in this movie, which isn't
surprising since he is one of its writers. He plays Harold, an
alien whose mission is to find a woman to bear him a child he can
take back to his home planet. Eventually the flakiness of
earthlings infects Harold as he spends more time among them; he
can't trust himself anymore. It's ``The Man Who Fell to Earth''
played for laughs. Unfortunately, ``Planet'' is just as cold
conceptually. Nichols drapes his dry imperiousness over the script,
which results in a romantic comedy without a romance. This movie
wants to be sweet and dark at the same time, but it is as distant
as a planet's satellite (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   `THE WHOLE NINE YARDS,' starring Matthew Perry and Bruce Willis.
Directed by Jonathan Lynn (R, 100 minutes). Oz (Perry) is a
nice-guy dentist beaten down by his bored wife. When the confident
Jimmy (Willis) breezes into the house next door, Oz's anxieties are
ratcheted up several points on the Richter scale. It turns out that
Jimmy is a former Chicago organized-crime figure who ratted out his
associates. The movie has an intricate plot, with hit men, love
interests, large sums of money and allegiances constantly in
motion. But it is missing the verve of someone who can take a
simple idea to the extreme; it must have been directed by a
sleepwalker. Despite Perry's plucky slapstick and the treacherous
gunplay that accounts for the second half of the movie, ``Yards''
is underwhelming, amusing only in fits and starts (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   `WONDER BOYS,' starring Michael Douglas, Frances McDormand and
Tobey Maguire. Directed by Curtis Hanson (R, 112 minutes). This
film boasts a first-rate cast, a credible literary source and a
director whose last film, ``L.A. Confidential,'' showed a
prodigious ability to capture the headlong rhythms of a complex
plot and the particularities of a motley assortment of characters.
But even with so much going for it, this adaptation of Michael
Chabon's novel about a pot-smoking middle-aged novelist burdened by
romantic and creative problems is flat and unconvincing. There's no
shortage of screwball material: a dead dog, an errant tuba and a
very tall drag queen, for starters. But Hanson, perhaps aiming for
wry understatement, has smothered whatever antic rhythm the story
might have had. Despite a brilliant supporting turn by Robert
Downey Jr. as a gay book editor, ``Wonder Boys'' is like a George
Cukor movie with a bad head cold: slow, muffled and vague (Scott).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 1937EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
