<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9062 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      03-16 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RELATIONSHIP BEHIND `LIMEY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Viewers inclined to skip or doze through DVD filmmaker
commentaries are advised to drop in on the exchange between Steven
Soderbergh and Lem Dobbs regarding ``The Limey,'' to be released on
Tuesday on disc and videocassette by Artisan.
</P>
<P>
   Soderbergh directed the film, and Dobbs wrote it. He also wrote
Soderbergh's ``Kafka'' (1991). The director describes a ``playfully
contentious relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   On the disc the playing is a little rough. Here's an opportunity
many screenwriters would kill for: going public with a director who
didn't exactly do it the way you intended.
</P>
<P>
   DOBBS: That scene was the glue.
</P>
<P>
   SODERBERGH: It ground the film to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   DOBBS: Your direction, then.
</P>
<P>
   SODERBERGH: No, I don't think so. It just didn't fit.
</P>
<P>
   Both of them stay in stride. Later, during a telephone
interview, Soderbergh said, ``Because of the way Lem and I relate
to each other, I knew if we got into a room and did a commentary it
wouldn't be the standard back-slapping situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Limey'' is one of those good little films that attract a
growing audience, though not a large one, and gain a reputation far
beyond their box-office receipts, which in this case amounted to
about $3 million. Years earlier Dobbs had the most stripped-down of
concepts.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy comes to L.A. to avenge a murder,'' Soderbergh said.
Later the two of them developed a film about an English ex-convict
named Wilson (Terence Stamp) who goes to California to investigate
the death of his daughter, Jenny. When she died, supposedly in a
car accident, Jenny was the mistress of a record mogul named
Valentine (Peter Fonda) who had his start and early successes in
the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   From there, director and writer diverged. Soderbergh sought to
keep the focus solely on Wilson, a tough, haunted character of
about 60 who is obsessed with the loss of his child. As portrayed
by Stamp, wiry and 60-ish himself, Wilson wipes out a roomful of
thugs one moment and settles into wistful memories of Jenny the
next. For the director, that was character enough for this film.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs, though, had written several side stories about Valentine
and other characters. Soderbergh said they distracted from the
concentration on Wilson and cut them. On the disc Dobbs chides him
about not being interested in inner lives and relationships, and he
worries that people will think the film sketchy and underwritten.
</P>
<P>
   The director holds his ground. ``I err on the side of less, but
that just reflects my taste about what I want to see in a movie,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Points made, the two move on. Not to contradict himself, Dobbs
praises Soderbergh for making a movie about an individual and not
resorting to the ensemble approach common today.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Soderbergh, whose ``Erin Brockovich'' opens
Friday, reiterated his sympathy for Dobbs. ``He is correct in
saying that he was criticized for writing a shallow piece, because
I did cut out a lot of that other stuff,'' he said. ``I do get his
point, but there's not a lot I can do about it.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Jakob the Liar &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In another ``upbeat'' Holocaust movie, a Polish restaurateur
(Robin Williams) decides he'll cheer up his fellow concentration
camp inmates by pretending he has a radio and is hearing news of
imminent liberation. That gives Williams a chance to do his Winston
Churchill imitation, but it also opens the floodgates for a rush of
strained good spirits that rob the tale of credibility.
</P>
<P>
   In this Holocaust story, an Anne Frank look-alike (Hannah Taylor
Gordon) may just live happily ever after. And, Janet Maslin wrote
in The New York Times, ``the film anticipates all laughter and
emotion in ways that make it its own worst enemy.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. Columbia Tri-Star. $105.77; DVD, $27.95. 114 minutes.
Closed captioned. PG-13. Release date: March 21. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Endurance &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A bombastic score of East African folk music doesn't help an
excruciatingly dull film about the Ethiopian long-distance runner
Haile Gebrselassie. Much happy trotting through the fields and
scenes from races is augmented with a fictionalized re-creation of
his youth, which counts for little because little is subtitled.
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly the film meant well, but interest flags in a film
that resembles a 1950s National Geographic spread, and ``its
mixture of biographical hype and social studies quickly curdles''
(Stephen Holden). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. . $104.16. 83 minutes. G. Closed captioned. Release date:
March 21. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   B. Monkey &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Washing the clown-wig-red dye out of her hair, B. (for Beatrice)
Monkey (Asia Argento) signals to her live-in partners in crime
(Rupert Everett and Jonathan Rhys Meyers) that she's ready for
other things in life. Soon she has traded in her wayward ways for
crazed domesticity with a schoolteacher (Jared Harris), who lives
on a junky little houseboat.
</P>
<P>
   But old habits interfere when a former pal reappears, bringing
more trouble to a character who has been ``either written or
directed to be a little too aware of her charming quirkiness''
(Anita Gates). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. Miramax. $104.16; DVD, $29.99. 90 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: March 21. &QL; 
