<SLUG> BC-STPATS-SAVANNAH17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rain or shine: It's still a great day for Irish in Savannah
 &HT;    By Dan Chapman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAVANNAH, Ga. _ The ruddy-faced rector was a picture of serenity
as the skies threatened to douse Thursday's military parade, and
hopes for a festive, record-setting St. Patrick's Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Father William O. O'Neill watched the white clouds scudding low
across the sky. His thoughts, though, drifted higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the help of God,'' said O'Neill, rector of the Cathedral
of St. John the Baptist, ``we'll survive. We're Irish. We hope for
the best of everything. If it doesn't happen, we'll go on in the
rain.''
</P>
<P>
   Fatalism has long served the Irish well. A healthy dose was also
evident Thursday afternoon among Savannah boosters and others who
expect today's St. Patrick's Day parade _ the nation's second
largest _ to shine, regardless of the weather.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers predict up to 600,000 people will fill the city's
cobblestoned streets to watch the 176th parade honoring the Irish,
their culture and American kin.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the projected three-hour parade, for many, is simply a
prelude to three days of hard revelry along River Street. An
auspicious set of circumstances _ a three-day weekend, the midst of
Spring Break, the new millennium _ could well mean more people than
ever before drink up Savannah's pleasures.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, a record 450,000 people lined Bull, Bay,
Broughton and other streets cheering the bands and beribboned
floats. St. Paddy's Day fell on Wednesday last year; maybe 300,000
chilly spectators turned out.
</P>
<P>
   City leaders make very clear the distinction between the parade
and the Festival on the River, which will roll merrily along
through Sunday. There's not much drinking o' green beer at the
former; there's too much at the latter, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Tired of young drunks and bare breasts, Savannah clamped down on
the beer-fueled bacchanal last year. Cops manned gates to control
the crowds. Wristbands were required of all drinkers to limit
underage shenanigans.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by a mellower festival _ and eager to make the weekend
more palatable to families _ city fathers redoubled their
anti-Dionysian efforts this year.
</P>
<P>
   Wristbands now cost $5, a buck more. Seven beer trucks will
dispense the frothy elixir; last year, there were a dozen.
Customers may buy only one beer at a time, and those mugs won't
hold more than 16 ounces, down from 32. And, in perhaps the most
conservative move of all, river festival organizers hired old-fogey
favorites Three Dog Night and The Rascals to perform.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have heard that it's not as wild and crazy as it used
to be,'' said Gordon Varnedoe, director of the Savannah Waterfront
Association. ``So we expect many, many people to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
