<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, March 19,
2000. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE Stories &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-AUDREY-HEPBURN (Hollywood) _ For an actress who epitomized
American cool, Audrey Hepburn is inspiring a lot of nervous sweat.
In life, her fragile beauty and elegantly pared-down fashion sense
made her one of the most distinctive, most admired stars on the
Hollywood screen. And that is precisely the problem. ``People are
very protective of Audrey Hepburn,'' said Susan Lyne, executive
vice president for movies and mini-series at ABC, which will
broadcast ``The Audrey Hepburn Story'' this month. ``They worry
that someone will come along and try to besmirch her reputation.
It's not like doing the Marilyn Monroe story where people are
salaciously interested in every misstep she took.'' The drama,
starring Jennifer Love Hewitt, will be shown on Monday, March 27.
By Bernard Weinraub. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-HEWITT-HEPBURN (Undated) _ While Jennifer Love Hewitt, who
will star as Audrey Hepburn on March 27 in ``The Audrey Hepburn
Story,'' has considerable charm and her talent have been
corroborated by an astonishing number of teen-zine cover stories,
the portrayal by a popular young actress of a show business
original like a Hepburn, and Hepburn, can only result in lobsided
comparisons. It seems to me that the outcome of viewing something
like this will be to increase our longing for the genuine article
at the expense of our regard for the woman playing her. By Jeff
MacGregor. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIRGIL-THOMSON-MUSIC (New York) _ To a devoted core of admirers,
including this critic, ``The Mother of Us All'' by Virgil Thomson,
which comes to the New York City Opera this Sunday afternoon in a
new production by Christopher Alden first unveiled at the
Glimmerglass Opera in 1998, is the most original and arguably the
greatest of American operas. In a 1984 article in The New Yorker,
Andrew Porter, an infuential critic and opera scholar not known for
a casual use of superlatives, stated that every time he heard ``The
Mother of Us All'' he was ``tempted to consider it the best of all
American operas'' and, on calm reflection, would ``hardly modify
that beyond `one of the three best.''' By Anthony Tommasini.
(Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   REGGIO-FILMS (New York) _ Godfrey Reggio is an alien who wants
to destroy the future from within. At least, that is what he says.
And the funny thing is that the reclusive 59-year-old filmmaker
makes a beguiling sort of sense as he arranges his far-reaching
abstractions about humanity's high-tech dilemmas into pleasant
conversation, much as films like ``Koyaanisqatsi'' and
``Powaqqatsi'' string together pearls of staggering imagery into
artful condemnations of Western civilization. By Ty Burr. (Moved).
WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BLACKS-OSCAR (subslug) (Undated) _ It's been nearly 40 years
since the first time an African-American man won the best-actor
Oscar. And in the long, parched stretch of desert since the night
Sidney Poitier got the statuette for his 1963 starring role in
``Lilies of the Field,'' no other black male has received an Oscar
for best actor. Lately, if you were a black man looking for an
Oscar nomination, you had to go to prison. Both of this year's
nominees, Denzel Washington in the best-actor category for ``The
Hurricane'' and Michael Clarke Duncan in the best-supporting group
for ``The Green Mile,'' spend time as convicts in their films. By
Elvis Mitchell. (Moved).  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CRUDUP-FILMS (Undated) _ So far, most of the articles about
Billy Crudup, 31, _ and there have been a bunch since his 1995
Broadway debut as the heart-piercing tutor in ``Arcadia'' _ have
noted the pronunciation of his name. CREW-dup. CRUDE-up. KROO-dup.
And they have predicted that any time now, any time at all, the
name would become as familiar as DiCaprio or Damon or Affleck: that
the bitter college ladykiller he played in ``Inventing the
Abbotts'' (1997) or the star-crossed runner he played in ``Without
Limits'' (1998) or the pining cowboy he played in ``The Hi-Lo
Country'' (1998) would make him a star. Well, here they come again.
This time, the movie is ``Waking the Dead,'' based on Scott
Spencer's novel about an up-and-coming politician haunted by
intertwined memories of lost love and abandoned ideals. By Sylviane
Gold. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MAJIDI-FILMS (New York) _ On a sunny Friday afternoon last fall,
the director Majid Majidi, in town for the New York Film Festival
from his native Tehran, was in demand. Negotiations for the
American distribution of his latest film, ``The Color of
Paradise,'' which opens March 31, were under way. Earlier in the
week reporters had been talking with him about Iranian films, about
why they are so often about children and what it is like making
films under censorship. By Friday, Majidi was in Cliffside, N.J.,
at the home of a friend, Jamsheed Akrami, a professor of film and
television at William Paterson University in Wayne, who was
interviewing him for a documentary. The festival circuit is nothing
new to this soft-spoken, sad-eyed 40-year-old director. His last
film, ``Children of Heaven,'' was the first Iranian film ever
nominated for an Academy Award. By Nancy Ramsey. (Moved).  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TIBET-FILMS (Undated) _ Considering the Hollywood versions of
Tibet and Buddhist monks, Jamyang Norbu, a Tibetan immigrant and
writer living in Tennessee, considers ``The Cup,'' which opened in
late January, to be a fresh breeze. In it young monks break the
rules, sneaking out at night and snickering over Victoria's Secret
catalogues and snapping wisecracks during kitchen duty. ``It has a
sense of fun and a sense of reality,'' Norbu said. The director of
``The Cup,'' Khyentse Norbu, a high-ranking Buddhist lama from
Bhutan (who is no relation to Jamyang Norbu), knows the foibles of
young monks well, having taught in monasteries in Bhutan and India
for years. ``The romantic idea should stop now,'' Khyentse Norbu
said. ``In the West, people have higher expectations and see
Tibetans as holy and high _ people who don't eat and sleep. Sooner
or later, they're going to be disappointed. I'm trying to demystify
Tibetans.'' By Barbara Stewart. (Moved).  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JUGGLER-DANCER (Undated) _ The music hall and the circus are not
the places devotees of dance hang out looking for revelations,
which as a rule probably saves them disappointment, but every so
often a revelation comes along. A case in point: the Ukrainian
juggler Viktor Kee, 29, currently in San Francisco through next
Sunday with Cirque du Soleil's extravaganza, ``Dralion.'' His act
involves seven solid plastic balls, hand-molded by the artist
himself, which he not only sends flying in arcs that amaze the eye
but somehow also catches _ no hands _ on a shoulder, on a knee, on
the back of his neck. By Matthew Gurewitsch. (Moved).  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ELTON-JOHN-AIDA (New York) _ No one was selling peanuts, and
instead of metal bars there were velvet ropes, but Elton John, the
evening's prize peacock, was being ogled as surely as if he were in
a zoo. It was Dec. 9, 1999, the opening-night performance of
Disney's ``Aida'' in Chicago _ a little more than three months
before the Broadway opening this Thursday at the Palace Theater.
The gawkers lined up, and watched, as if John was on the television
screen in their own homes. That is a by-product of celebrity, of
course. It's just that some of those gawkers also happened to be in
the cast or on the staff of ``Aida'' and they wanted a look, too.
Because, beside his one visit to a New York rehearsal last
September, they hadn't seen him either. By Alex Witchel. (Moved).
WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WAGNER-MUSIC (Undated) _ Recordings of Wagner's tetralogy, ``Der
Ring des Nibelungen,'' are no longer the cultural milestones they
were at midcentury. The first studio recording _ Decca's _ took
shape in stages from 1958 to 1966, with the as yet unknighted Georg
Solti leading the Vienna Philharmonic and a cast headed by Birgit
Nilsson, Hans Hotter and Wolfgang Windgassen. More than three
decades on, remastered and reissued on at least two occasions, it
remains the best-selling ``Ring'' in the catalog. By Matthew
Gurewitsch. (Moved). WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN-PIE-MUSIC (Undated) _ ``American Pie'' is one of the
great monuments of musical cheese, a song everyone scorns but few
can resist. Since its overwhelming success in 1972, the song's
eight minutes of tangled allusions to the icons of the turbulent
1960s, offered by Don McLean in a collegiate folkie's warble, have
come to represent the nadir of songwriterly self-seriousness. By
Ann Powers. (Moved).  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MUSCLE-WOMEN-ART (New York) _ The New Museum of Contemporary Art
unveils its ``Picturing the Modern Amazon'' on March 30. From
drawings of the ``Female Sampson'' (Angela d'Atalie, 1873) to
artfully staged photographs of ebony-skinned musclewomen by Andres
Serrano (with paintings, sculptures and comic book covers in
between), the exhibition, which runs through July 2, will
unabashedly proclaim a new participant in the 30-year-old
discussion of body art: the hypermuscular woman. By Michael Rush.
(Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THOM-MAYNE-ARCH (Undated) _ Like other architects of his
generation, Thom Mayne has resisted the idea of beauty. He has
evidently considered it a seductive idea that, like Circe,
threatens to take away a big guy's strength. So I am happy to
report that the strength of the new Diamond Ranch High School,
designed by Mayne and his firm Morphosis for the city of Pomona,
California, lies precisely in the beauty it brings to an already
spectacular hilltop site east of Los Angeles. By Herbert Muschamp.
(Moved).  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SUBURBIA-PHOTOGS (Undated) _ Considered a groundbreaking
exemplar of documentary photography upon its publication in 1972,
``Suburbia'' later went out of print, dropping off the radar in
much the same way its creator, Bill Owens, did. By the end of that
decade _ after showing at institutions like the Museum of Modern
Art and the Smithsonian, winning major awards and producing two
more books _ he decided he could no longer raise a family on a
photographer's wages and quit the art world. Now ``Suburbia'' is
available in a new edition, with a foreword by the journalist and
social historian David Halberstam, published late last year by
Fotofolio. And Owens, today better known as an authority on brewing
beer, is suddenly in vogue again, showing in major galleries from
New York to Paris and, through April 2, in a retrospective at the
San Jose Museum of Art in San Jose, Calif. By Jeffrey Kastner.
(Moved).  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
