<SLUG> BC-NASDAQ-NORRIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ'S SIGN IS GREAT, BUT DOES ITS MARKET MEASURE UP? 
</HEADLINE>
  (Norris Column) 
(lh) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The signs of Times Square have long been amazing.
Remember the cigarette billboard that blew perfect smoke rings? In
retrospect, the tobacco companies might have been better off today
if they had found another use for their money, but there is no
doubt that the sign impressed a lot of tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Today the most awe-inspiring sign is the $37 million Nasdaq
extravaganza on the corner of Broadway and 43rd Street. It
certainly gets Nasdaq noticed. So do all those television
commercials on football and basketball games.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, you have to wonder whether Nasdaq is spending its money
wisely. This is a time of upheaval in the securities markets, when
technological change has made it possible for new competitors to
arise _ and at least conceivable that the dominant markets now will
be eclipsed if they move too slowly to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the signs are that Nasdaq has been too busy
promoting itself as the home of all those high-tech wonder
companies to bother spending enough money on its services. The move
toward decimal prices for stocks is going to be delayed, perhaps
for many months, because Nasdaq computer systems are inadequate.
And Arthur Levitt, the chairman of the Securities and Exchange
Commission, said Thursday that Nasdaq's SelectNet system, which
matches orders electronically, ``continues to be plagued with
shortcomings, delays during heavy trading volume, and even
outages.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank G. Zarb, the man brought in to run Nasdaq after the
scandal of a few years ago, doesn't like the new criticism.
``You're really being unfair,'' he told me Thursday. He argued that
Nasdaq spent a lot on better systems but that volume rose faster
than anyone expected, making it dangerous to convert to decimals
until system capacity improved. ``We're just asking for a saner
schedule,'' he said. As for SelectNet, he says the problems have
been fixed.
</P>
<P>
   In any industry facing rapid change, the dominant company often
wishes things would slow down. Nasdaq, for the first time in its
history, faces real competition from growing electronic markets for
trading volumes in Nasdaq-listed stocks. If it can't get its
systems in order, it may discover that marketing is no substitute
for capacity.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, the big headlines regarding Nasdaq relate to
its volatility, not to its systems. The Nasdaq composite index hit
a record last Friday, having tripled in less than 18 months. By
11:11 a.m. Thursday it was down 11.8 percent from that peak. Then
it made up nearly half the loss in five hours. Up or down, Nasdaq
is where the action is, and the gamblers _ er, traders _ are
flocking to it.
</P>
<P>
   But change is coming. The electronic networks, which hitherto
operated as Nasdaq members rather than competitors, are talking of
becoming full-fledged exchanges. Archipelago's new link with the
Pacific Stock Exchange, announced this week, could make it a
formidable competitor _ particularly if the SEC manages to assure
that competition between markets benefits investors rather than the
brokers who are often tempted to compete with, rather than for,
their customers.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq is now trying to sell stock in itself. First comes a
private offering, which it is now pitching to a variety of
investors. If all goes well, a public offering will follow.
</P>
<P>
   In the offering memorandum for the deal, Nasdaq warns
prospective investors, in bold type, that ``System limitations and
failures could harm Nasdaq's business.''
</P>
<P>
   It got that right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
