want, anyway? The gender gap that first appeared in the 1980
presidential election is still with us. A new USATODAY-CNN Gallup
poll shows that if the election were held today 15 percent more
women than men would vote for Vice President Gore, while 12 percent
more men than women would vote for Texas Gov. George W. Bush. How
can the candidates appeal to one sex without losing the other? Do
women and men think so differently after all? By MARIANNE MEANS.
(Already filed.)
