<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IRELAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. PATRICK'S DAY MOOD CLOUDED BY EVENTS IN ULSTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and w coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN AND KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was meant to be what the Irish call a
``hooley,'' a grand party, a St. Patrick's Day that President
Clinton and Irish leaders could celebrate not only as Ireland's
national day, but as the first one in decades when Northern Ireland
was at peace and under local rule.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Patrick's Day events of this week, however, have instead
taken on the quality of another peculiarly Hibernian gathering: an
Irish wake. The peace process, while hardly dead, is in dire need
of resuscitation, and leaders on both sides of the Atlantic did not
seem optimistic that a cure would be found soon.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing a 20-year tradition, Clinton, members of Congress,
and Irish leaders sat Thursday for a traditional St. Patrick's Day
lunch _ this one, a day early to accommodate the legislative
schedule. There was prime rib, potatoes, green beans, and even dark
Guinness beer, unusual for a midday event on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The key players were there: Ulster Unionist leader David
Trimble, Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern, and Sinn Fein president
Gerry Adams. Cardinal Law delivered the invocation, and Clinton
made a speech.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of what Clinton hoped to have _ a St. Patrick's
address congratulating all parties for their success in forging a
long-fought and hard-won peace _ all the president could do was
deliver what witnesses described as a wistful thanks for the
progress that had been made, and a plea that the warring parties
not allow things to regress.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ``spoke from the heart,'' thanking the members of
Congress for their bipartisanship on Ireland amid an otherwise
bitterly partisan seven-plus years, said Representative Martin
Meehan, Democrat of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The president was ``a little melancholy,'' however, expressing
his great frustration and even anger, Meehan recounted.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble sat on one side of the room; his foe, Adams, was perched
on the other. When the luncheon ended about 80 minutes later, the
men departed the Capitol through separate doors.
</P>
<P>
   Ahern and Adams set off for separate meetings with key members
of Congress. Clinton, who Thursday night received the Millennium
Peace Award from the American Ireland Fund for his work on Northern
Ireland, is expected to meet with leaders in the peace process
Friday _ also separately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm growing impatient,'' Peter Mandelson, the British state
secretary for Northern Ireland, told reporters in Washington
Thursday. ``The coming weeks will demand more courage and more
compromise. Everyone will have to take risks. Everyone will be
asked to stretch. Nobody will get exactly what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   At this stage, those close to the process say, the best hope is
that both sides will hold tightly to the progress that has been
made and not slip back to the bloody ``Troubles'' between Catholics
and Protestants that have ravaged Northern Ireland for the last 30
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not expect any major breakthroughs'' during the Irish
leaders' visit to Washington, said Michael Hammer, a spokesman for
the National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   The British government last month suspended the fledgling
power-sharing government in Northern Ireland just 72 days after it
had handed power back to local politicians for the first time since
1974. Mandelson, who is leading the British delegation to
Washington, said he suspended the assembly to avert a threatened
walkout by the Ulster Unionists, who represent most Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, however, whose party is close to the IRA, said a unionist
disarmament deadline was unilateral and fell outside the terms of
the 1998 Good Friday Agreement. The accord, a compromise that
created political institutions intended to transform Northern
Ireland into a peaceful, democratic society, provides that all
paramilitary groups should be disarmed by May 2000. Adams accused
the British government of caving in to a unionist veto.
</P>
<P>
   In a Catch-22 for which no one has found an exit, the IRA says
it will not discuss disarming until the power-sharing government is
restored, while unionists say they will not sit in government with
Sinn Fein until the IRA begins disarming.
</P>
<P>
   ``If David Trimble advances the mantra, `no guns, no
government,' you can be sure the IRA response will be `no
government, no guns,' '' said Representative Richard Neal, Democrat
of Springfield, who confers frequently with Clinton on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Exploiting the political vacuum, dissident Irish republican and
British loyalist paramilitary groups have stepped up their
activities in the past month. The republicans are trying to set off
bombs, hoping it would lead to a collapse of the peace process,
while loyalists are busy trying to settle some lethal internecine
scores and continue to kill ordinary Catholics occasionally in what
seems an attempt to goad the Irish Republican Army into breaking
its cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   Britain did make a conciliatory gesture Thursday, as Mandelson
announced that more troops were being pulled out of Northern
Ireland. The pullout means that for the first time since 1969,
there will be no British batallion resident in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, elsewhere the security profile is higher,''
Mandelson said. ``But that is because elsewhere the level of threat
is higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams downplayed the move as ``cynical,'' though welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always glad to see British troops going home,'' he said in
an interview. ``But I have to say that I'm quite cynical about the
timing of the announcement. A little media announcement on St.
Patrick's Day in Washington isn't what's required here.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandelson, meanwhile, criticized the IRA for failing to give up
its weapons, calling it ``a stumbling block'' to peace.
</P>
<P>
   Turning in weapons ``remains an essential part of the peace
process,'' he said. ``I know that people have fears, fears that
they will be asked to move first, or make bigger sacrifices than
the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   But those who ``retreat into those fears . . . will pay a heavy
price for their insularity,'' Mandelson said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Milligan reported from Washington; Cullen reported from London.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
