<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9082 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-OLYMPICS-CORPORATIONS     03-16 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPICS-CORPORATIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPICS CONTINUE TO LURE CORPORATE SPONSORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the end, the Olympics simply proved too attractive as a
marketing platform for major corporations to resist.
</P>
<P>
   A year after scandals wracked the International Olympic
Committee and the Salt Lake Organizing Committee, IOC officials
said Thursday that their most loyal sponsor, Eastman Kodak, has
extended its relationship with the games through 2008. They added a
few more current sponsors will renew their agreements in the next
several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really back to business as usual,'' said Robert Madrigal,
professor at the Warsaw Sports Marketing Center at the University
of Oregon. ``The Olympics are just way too valuable for companies,
and the core idea of what the Olympics are about and what the
companies are buying has not been damaged.''
</P>
<P>
   After the disclosure last year of a $1.2 million campaign to
give gifts to the Salt Lake Organizing Committee during the effort
to locate the 2002 Winter Games in Utah, 10 IOC members resigned or
were expelled. Earlier this week, a former member of the US Olympic
Committee pleaded guilty to federal tax violations in connection
with the organization of both the Salt Lake games and the 2004
Summer Games in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the major corporate sponsors headed for cover during the
scandals, refusing to comment. Others would say only that they were
monitoring the events. Only David D'Alessandro, president and chief
operating officer of John Hancock Financial Services Inc. went
public with his chagrin, eventually threatening to pull the
company's sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   But, for the corporations, the Olympic rings never lost their
luster.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the problems were focused on the athletes _ a drug scandal,
or something that directly affected the competition _ that might
have made a difference,'' Madrigal said. ``But this was about
things financial, the business of the Olympics, not the games
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, D'Alessandro directed Hancock employees to restore
the rings to Hancock's stationary. Last month, after obtaining a
morals clause in Hancock's agreement with the IOC, allowing the
company to withdraw if more troubles occur, the company renewed its
sponsorship through 2004 for $55 million.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak has sponsored every Olympics since the first of the
corporate-backed games in 1896. Company officials said Thursday the
Olympics provide a unique medium to show off Kodak's new products
to the world. Kodak will build and operate a huge photo lab at the
summer games to support the thousands of journalists who attend,
and make available its new digital technology to supply
accreditation badges to 200,000 officials, athletes, sponsors,
volunteers and workers who will attend the games in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Sports sponsorship specialists pegged the value of the agreement
at about $110 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the sixth TOP (The Olympic Partners) sponsorship that
we have announced, and our target is 10,'' said Michael Payne, the
IOC's marketing director, referring to the highest level of Olympic
sponsorship. ``We are confident we will meet or exceed that before
the games in Sydney.''
</P>
<P>
   Sources said negotiations are nearly complete with some of the
five current TOP sponsors, whose agreements expire this year:
McDonalds, UPS, Panasonic, Samsung and Xerox. A UPS spokeswoman
said Thursday, however, that negotiations with the IOC had not
begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've essentially reached agreement with several of them, in
negotiations,'' Payne said. ``As soon as we get the lawyers to
behave, we'll be executing those agreements and making the
announcments.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies which had already renewed are Coca-Cola Inc. and
SEMA Group, through 2008; and Sports Illustrated/Time Inc., Visa
International Corp. and Hancock.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak and IOC officials refused to comment Thursday on whether
their agreement includes a morals clause similar to Hancock's. But
observers said they believed several companies negotiating with the
IOC have followed Hancock's lead, and insisted on some way of
voiding their agreements if the image of the games is damaged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
