<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9083 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-LEBANON-TERRORIST-2TA     03-16 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-TERRORIST-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGING JAPANESE TERRORIST TRIES TO AVOID DEPORTATION FROM LEBANON 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ He calls himself Ahmed now, having taken a
Muslim first name two weeks ago when he converted to Islam in a
Lebanese prison, trying again to shake off the shackles of his
past.
</P>
<P>
   But not even a change of name and faith _ nor even the
widespread popular following he has developed in Lebanon, a country
with a majority Muslim population _ seems likely to bring lasting
relief to the 52-year-old man formerly known as Kozo Okamoto.
</P>
<P>
   On May 30, 1972, Okamoto was one of three Japanese Red Army
members who pulled machine guns and grenades from bags coming off
an Air France flight from Rome at Israel's international airport
near Lod. In the ensuing carnage, 26 people were killed, including
16 Puerto Rican Roman Catholics on a pilgrimage to the Holy Land,
and 74 were injured. Two of the Japanese attackers were also
killed.
</P>
<P>
   Okamoto survived and was sentenced to life in prison by an
Israeli court. He served 13 years before being released in a
prisoner exchange with Palestinians in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   The Lod massacre was one of the deadliest of its time. But as in
many other events that have strained relations between Israel and
its Arab neighbors, the prism of politics has transformed what
happened that day into legend among impassioned Arabs. For many in
Lebanon and elsewhere in the Arab world, Okamoto became a hero, so
much so that he is now at the center of a diplomatic tug of war.
Japan wants to extradite him to face trial for terrorism and acts
against the state at home, and Lebanon bowed to popular feeling
this month and rejected the Japanese request.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Okamoto, and for four other Japanese Red Army
members who along with him have just completed three-year jail
sentences in Lebanon for living here on forged passports, the
Beirut government's finding that Japan's extradition bid ``lacked
enough evidence'' and fell outside Lebanon's statute of limitations
did not end the matter. While a parliamentary committee headed by
Interior Minister Michel Murr considers the prisoners' requests for
political asylum, Lebanon is scouring the world for any country _
Cuba has been mentioned, as have North Korea and Libya _ that might
accept them.
</P>
<P>
   It is a humiliating postscript for a group that once bestrode
the world of international terrorism. From the early 1970s until
the late 1980s, when its flame finally flickered out, the Red Army,
formed in 1971 by a group of Marxist students, made common cause
with Ilich Ramirez Sanchez, known as Carlos the Jackal, the
terrorist now imprisoned in France who is said to have been a
planner of the Lod airport attack. It also worked with other groups
that struck fear with aircraft hijackings, assassinations, embassy
takeovers and bombings, like the Popular Front for the Liberation
of Palestine-General Command, the Italian Red Brigades and the
Baader-Meinhof gang in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's eagerness to put the five on trial _ evident in the
dozens of Japanese reporters and television crews covering the case
here, more than doubling the resident Japanese population _
reflects years of frustration.
</P>
<P>
   According to Japanese officials, only five of the 40 to 50
Japanese who formed the core of the Red Army ever ended up in
Japanese jails, and only a handful of the group's activists died in
the dozens of terrorist attacks it mounted in Japan and around the
world. Apart from the five held in Lebanon, there are at least
seven others on Japan's wanted list, including the woman who is
believed to have been the Red Army's leader, Fusako Shigenobu, 54.
She is thought to have gone into hiding somewhere in the former
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lebanon's prosecutor general, Adnan Addoum, who
recommended that the government refuse Japan's extradition request
and deport the five Japanese to a third country, Okamoto is now
``only half a man,'' weakened to the point of debility by years of
harsh treatment and torture in Israeli prisons.
</P>
<P>
   His poor condition is cited as the reason he is sitting out a
hunger strike begun last week by three of his comrades, who are now
in a hospital. The fifth prisoner, Masao Adachi, a 60-year-old
former film director who is also sitting out the hunger strike, is
said to be needed to help feed and care for Okamoto.
</P>
<P>
   In their determination to avoid a forced return to Japan, the
five have shown some ingenuity. As his prison term for using a
false passport neared its end, Okamoto, shown in recent photographs
to be salt-and-pepper gray now, with a goatee, did what he could to
whip up support, sending letters to supporters in which he declared
himself, in effect, an honorary Arab.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the Lod operation,'' he said, ``I have earned the right
to be considered a citizen of all Arab countries.'' The attack, he
said in another pronouncement, was ``to support and defend the
cause of the oppressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, on March 2, five days before their prison terms were
officially to have ended, three of the five converted to Islam, and
summoned one of Lebanon's most eminent Sunni Muslim clerics, Sheik
Ahmed Al Kurdi, to sanction the conversion in prison. In addition
to Okamoto, they were Kazuo Tohira, 47, who now calls himself
Bassem, and Mariko Yamamoto, the only woman in the group, 59, who
took the name Maryam. A few days later, they petitioned the
Lebanese government for permission to join the pilgrimage to Mecca
in Saudi Arabia, a huge annual migration, now under way, that is
considered the greatest fulfillment for any Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth member of the group used the same tactic, but with a
different twist. Adachi, the former filmmaker, converted to the
Greek Orthodox branch of Christianity and persuaded prison
authorities to allow him to marry a 35-year-old Lebanese Christian
woman who works as an acupuncturist, Ummaya Abboud. She was living
with him in 1997 in Lebanon's Bekaa region, along the Syrian border
east of Beirut, when he and the other four Japanese were picked up
in a Lebanese police sweep in February 1997. Only one member of the
group, Haruo Wako, 51, refused to convert, telling prison officials
he would not stoop to a ``transparent ploy.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Red Army professed Marxist beliefs, all five of the
Japanese previously listed their faith with prison authorities as
Buddhist.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, the Lebanese authorities are holding the five in
prison under 15-day renewable detention orders, but a decision to
let them remain in Lebanon or to deport them is thought to be
imminent.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Libya received Okamoto as a hero when he arrived there after his
release by Israel in 1985, printing front-page photographs in its
newspapers of him being hoisted atop the shoulders of Palestinian
militants in Tripoli. But it has cooled to its onetime protege,
apparently because Col. Moammar Gadhafi, the Libyan leader, is
eager to end Libya's diplomatic isolation and attract new
investment in Libya's oil and gas fields. Libya was apparently glad
to see the back of Okamoto when he went to Lebanon sometime in the
late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The situation confronts Lebanese leaders with a vexatious
choice. After a devastating civil war that lasted 15 years _
killing at least 130,000 by its end in 1990 and turning the Bekaa
into a terrorist haventhat benefited from the total lawlessness of
wartime _ Lebanon is only now struggling to its feet again. It is
desperate to establish itself as a responsible member of the
international community, and eager for foreign investment,
especially from Japan, one of the largest investors here before the
war.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does it want to put at risk a $120 million low-interest loan
pledged by Japan, whose prime minister, Keizo Obuchi, sent a
personal emissary here in December to argue for the Red Army
group's extradition.
</P>
<P>
   Unedifying as the group's history may seem to the countries that
were its victims, its popularity in Lebanon _ or Okamoto's, at
least _ is undeniable. For the last week, a group of Beirut
University students have maintained a round-the-clock vigil outside
the Interior Ministry in the heart of the Lebanese capital,
demanding political asylum for Okamoto. Cars passing the spot in
the heavy Beirut traffic frequently honk their horns in support.
Some 20,000 people are said to have signed a petition in support of
asylum for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kozo didn't go to Lod airport just for the fun of killing, he
went there for the cause of all Arabs,'' Huda Hafez, a 23-year-old
English literature major at Lebanese University, told a reporter.
``Why do you Westerners always think only of the innocents who died
in Israel, and not of the thousands of innocent Arabs that the
Israelis have killed?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 2000EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
