<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAKE UP   AND MOVE IN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By   JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If you thought that this week's spate of off-Broadway
closings might do something to ease the theater crunch, think
again.
</P>
<P>
   The producers of both ``Wit,'' at the Union Square Theater, and
``Hedwig and the Angry Inch,'' at the Jane Street Theater,
announced they would close on April 9. But just as quickly, both
theaters had new bookings.
</P>
<P>
   At the Jane Street, as expected, ``Wake Up and Smell the
Coffee,'' a new work by Eric Bogosian, will begin previews on April
24 with a May 4 opening. His wife, Jo Bonney, will direct; Fred
Zollo and Nick Paleologos will produce. The piece, Bogosian's first
solo show since 1994, includes an array of characters and concepts
including airlines, Jesus and overpriced java. (More on this
later.)
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday, the producer Roy Gabay said that the next tenant
at the Union Square would be ``The Laramie Project,'' a dramatic
meditation on the 1998 killing of Matthew Shepard, a gay college
student, directed by Moises Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   The piece, written by Kaufman's ensemble, opened to strong
reviews at the Denver Theater Center on Feb. 26 and is scheduled to
run there until April 1. Immediately thereafter, the show will
transfer to the Union Square, with performances likely to begin the
last week of April. Opening night will be in mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   The question here was not if but when. The piece opened at the
Denver Theater Center on Feb. 26 and is scheduled to run there
until April 1.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to move the piece came after several days of back
and forth deliberation between Kaufman and Gabay.
</P>
<P>
   Arguments for the immediate move revolve around the play's early
momentum, including glowing reviews in Denver and advance features
in the New York press. On the other hand producers worry about the
timing of a possible opening, reasoning that the work's serious
subject matter might not play in the summer months or that a
crowded Broadway Tony season could limit its impact. in.''
</P>
<P>
   FEAR OF FLYING
</P>
<P>
   Eric Bogosian doesn't want you to think he's gotten soft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not mellow,'' he said, ``I like being fierce, and what
makes me laugh is what I'm going to put onstage.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, he admits that there's something slightly different
about ``Wake Up and Smell the Coffee,'' most notably the structure,
which he calls ``more stream-of-consciousness.'' He has also added
several leit-motifs, including air travel, a phenomenon he sees as
summing up the American experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wait in line to hurry up,'' he said. ``And then's there's
the fear of crashing at any moment.''
</P>
<P>
   TRUE NEW?
</P>
<P>
   It's Broadway's newest hit, to be sure. But is ``True West'' a
new play?
</P>
<P>
   That's a question that may well end up before the Tony
administration committee in coming weeks. While the answer may seem
self-evident, producers of the play, a 1980 black comedy by Sam
Shepard, are mulling whether to ask Tony voters formally to
consider their production as eligible for the award for best new
play.
</P>
<P>
   How? Well, Tony rules stipulate that, regardless of age,
productions can be considered ``new'' provided that they have never
appeared on Broadway. ``True West,'' which opened to raves on March
9, never has, although a 1982 production ran for well over a year
Off Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   OK, then: Why? Well, although producers are mum on the matter,
the reasoning would seem to be that the prospective Tony
competition in the new-play category would be less formidable than
that in the revival category, where the acclaimed British import
``The Real Thing'' is considered an early favorite.
</P>
<P>
   As such, the ``True West'' move would just be the latest chapter
in a long and sometimes ludicrous history of Tony jockeying. It is
also a topic Shepard is familiar with. In 1996 his 1979 play,
``Buried Child,'' successfully lobbied the Tony committee to be
considered a new play on the grounds that it had been substantially
rewritten. It won the decision but lost the award.
</P>
<P>
   As for the immediate future of ``True West,'' its two stars are
booked through mid-June, and discussions have begun about a
possible extension.
</P>
<P>
   THE FARMER'S STRIFE
</P>
<P>
   First came ``Iceman.'' Now comes ``Moon.'' Next up is
``Desire.''
</P>
<P>
   Devotees of Eugene O'Neill will understand the shorthand. Last
year saw the return of O'Neill's ``Iceman Cometh.'' A revival of
his ``Moon for the Misbegotten'' opens on Sunday, and in October
the Roundabout Theater Company will produce ``Desire Under the
Elms,'' a tale of Oedipal angst involving a farmer and his son,
each enamored of the father's young wife, Abbie.
</P>
<P>
   The director of ``Desire'' will be David Leveaux, who made his
name at age 26 with a 1984 Broadway production of ``Moon'' and
burnished it with a production of another O'Neill drama, ``Anna
Christie,'' in 1993. No casting yet, but Leveaux said he intended
to pursue Mary Louise Parker, who played Abbie in a reading last
fall.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he intended to explore the themes of sex and
language in ``Desire.'' ``I think it works to strip it back to the
basics,'' Leveaux said. ``Once you get back to those literal
relationships, you get what flies in the theater.''
</P>
<P>
   JUST IN TIME, TOO
</P>
<P>
   Another major revival has been sighted: ``Bells are Ringing,''
is aiming for a March 2001 Broadway opening. The director is
something of a surprise: Tina Landau, the force behind experimental
works like ``Floyd Collins'' and ``Space.'' Landau has directed
``Bells'' twice before, at Yale University's annual Dramat and at
the Kennedy Center in Washington in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a constant karmic companion in my life,'' she said,
with a laugh. ``I intend to watch the old tapes and steal from
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1956 musical, by Jule Styne, Betty Comden and Adolph Green,
follows the romance of an answering-service operator, originally
played by Judy Holliday, who falls for one of her clients. The
producers this time around are Mitchell Maxwell, Mark Balsam,
Victoria Maxwell and Robert Barandes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 2004EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0321 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9087 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-RAYTHEON-CONTRACT-BOS     03-16 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-CONTRACT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON SEEKS UK MISSILE CONTRACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raytheon Co.'s priority target: the Royal Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   The British military is reviewing bids for a new air-to-air
missile program, and the Massachusetts defense contractor is
lobbying fiercely to snare a contract worth about $1.6 billion. Its
competitor is a mostly European consortium that also wants to arm
the UK's new Eurofighter warplane.
</P>
<P>
   An official decision by Britain's Labor government is expected
as soon as next week, and a win would help Raytheon reverse its
recent slump, showing it can still land the lucrative overseas
contracts that historically have generated much of its profits.
</P>
<P>
   Losing the contract wouldn't break Raytheon, which had revenue
of around $20 billion last year. But the company and its chief
executive, Daniel Burnham, could use some good news after a string
of earnings disappointments and technical setbacks in some of its
programs combined to depress Raytheon's share price. The company's
class B shares closed at $19.50, up 25 cents, but still are less
than one-third of their July high of $74.9375.
</P>
<P>
   The slump has tested the leadership of Burnham, who has
reorganized the company and taken criticism from employees after
ordering thousands of job cuts since he took over in 1998. A win
for Raytheon would also lighten the mood in the Pentagon, whose
shifting procurement policies, some say, are partly to blame for
the woes of the defense industry.
</P>
<P>
   But the British Ministry of Defense could still opt for a
competing missile system known as ``Meteor'' under development by a
group that includes British Aerospace and France's Aerospatiale
Matra.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins the British contract would probably receive
billions of dollars worth of future missile orders from other
European countries as well. Combined with potential US purchases,
the total market for the new missile could be as many as 15,000
over 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   If the European group wins the British contract, it would also
gain a foothold in the global missile market, which Raytheon has
dominated since it acquired Hughes Electronics in 1997. Since the
end of the Cold War, European governments have been under
increasing pressure to support local industries and bolster
economic cooperation across the continent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The British decision will tell us a lot about the future
course of European economic integration, and what the market will
be for American defense contractors looking forward,'' said Loren
Thompson, director of national security programs at the Lexington
Institute in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   NATO countries are still the biggest weapons buyers, he said.
``If (US) companies can't make an impact there, there's not much
left in the rest of the world,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   The marketing war is proceeding on both technical and political
fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Under its proposal, Raytheon would upgrade an existing missile
design in stages through 2008, adding first an advanced rocket
motor and later, perhaps, some type of ``ramjet'' engine that would
require less fuel. ``It's clear we've got the more flexible
offering,'' said Peter McKee, director of Raytheon Systems Ltd.,
the company's British subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the Meteor team proposes to begin work on a ramjet
immediately, which it says would lead to the creation of a more
powerful and agile missile.
</P>
<P>
   Some think a Raytheon win unlikely, since the company used up
many political chits in London and Washington last year to win a
$1.3 billion UK radar contract. But Raytheon's current missile bid
is being promoted by President Clinton and Defense Secretary
William Cohen, who recently told his British counterpart that it
would be ``neither feasible nor prudent'' for the United States to
cooperate on Meteor's development.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's statement came as a snub to Boeing Co., which is part of
the Meteor team.
</P>
<P>
   But Meteor's members have official backing from Germany and
Spain, which will be looking to arm Eurofighters of their own soon.
The European consortium isn't afraid to tweak Raytheon as an
outsider, calling the company ``a threat from Arizona'' in a trade
press advertisement last fall, a reference to the Tucson factories
where Raytheon produces many of its missiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the nastiest competition I've seen in years,'' said
Larry Dickerson, defense analyst at Forecast International in
Newtown, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   For the Europeans, the outcome could suggest whether defense
forces there will continue to use mainly American equipment, he
said. ``It's gone from being a battle about the technical
requirements to a question of whether Europe is going to remain
unified and all the emotions that come with that,'' Dickerson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Air Force is set to take its first Eurofighter
deliveries in 2002 and the first contract proposal requests for
air-to-air missiles to arm the planes came several years ago. At
the time, British officials were spooked by a Russian missile
design based around an engine known as a ramjet, which burns oxygen
from the atmosphere in addition to the fuel supply it carries.
</P>
<P>
   In theory the design offers greater range and speed than an
existing Raytheon armament known as the Advanced Medium Range
Air-to-Air Missile, or AMRAAM, a mainstay of the US and NATO air
fleets today. Raytheon's bid for the $1.6 billion contract calls
for supplying an updated version of the AMRAAM.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how close the Russian ramjet is to deployment isn't
clear. Raytheon says it has been told by American and British
intelligence officials that the Russians aren't proceeding with the
expensive design; analysts estimate it would cost several hundred
million dollars at least for France's Aerospatiale to develop such
an engine of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon says it could design its missile around the French
motor by 2008 if needed. In the meantime, Raytheon proposes to
build for the British an interim missile whose range would be
midway between the Meteor ramjet's reach of around 70 miles and
AMRAAM's current 20-mile range. The interim design would make use
of a ``pulse'' rocket motor that could be switched off and on
again, producing a more agile weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon's McKee called the proposal an example of ``smart
procurement'' because it would allow the British to put off a
decision whether to pay to develop the ramjet missile, perhaps
until a superior technology emerges. ``In 10 years' time there's
likely to be a better way of doing it in any event,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   British Aerospace spokesman Charles Miller counters that work on
the ramjet should begin as soon as possible, and that the creation
of a competitor to Raytheon would mean cheaper and better weapons
in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raytheon has put forward a very strong proposal, but one of
our arguments has been that Raytheon wouldn't have put forward such
a strong bid if there hadn't been competition already,'' Miller
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
