<SLUG> BC-MARKET-DOW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW ADDS 500 POINTS IN BIGGEST ONE-DAY GAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average shot up almost 500 points
Thursday, its biggest one-day point gain ever, as investors rushed
to buy consumer, drug, and financial stocks they had shunned for
the past two months.
</P>
<P>
   The gain brought the two-day rise in the Dow to a remarkable 819
points, or more than 8 percent. It was the average's most
spectacular rally since rebounding from the stock-market crash of
1987.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow closed at 10,630.6, up 499.19 points, after an exuberant
day on Wall Street, where computer screens flashed stock prices in
a blanket of green _ for rising stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's powerful move also pulled up technology stocks, which
had flirted with a correction in three frenzied trading days this
week. The Nasdaq Composite stock index, which is dominated by
high-flying technology firms, rose 134.77 points, or nearly 3
percent, and closed at 4717.39.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dow was the star. The 30-stock index, which has come to
symbolize the old-fashioned economy, suddenly looked appealing to
investors seeking bargains in companies with profits as an
alternative to overpriced, money-losing technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was high time we had a snapback in these tremendously
depressed `old economy' stocks,'' said William Lawrence, senior
vice president of Beacon Fiduciary Advisors in Boston. ``They had
been beaten down to levels that were below where they should've
been.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither a government report that wholesale prices had their
biggest monthly rise in nine years, nor prospects of an interest
rate hike next Tuesday by the Federal Reserve, could dampen
enthusiasm for stocks. Producer prices surged 1 percent in
February, driven by spiraling oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies that make up the Dow index, such as Citigroup,
Merck &AMP; Co., Home Depot Inc., and Minnesota Mining &AMP; Manufacturing
Co., posted gains of between $4 and $6 per share.
</P>
<P>
   Rising stocks outnumbered declining stocks by a 7-to-2 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street veteran Harry Laubscher said the money going into
the Dow was ``coming out of'' technology stocks. Some analysts
speculated that Nasdaq stocks may be past their heyday and face
extreme volatility and _ in certain stocks _ sharp declines as
investors see through promises and start demanding profits.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the only two stocks in the Dow index that declined were
Hewlett-Packard and Microsoft Corp. IBM Corp. squeezed out a small
gain.
</P>
<P>
   Laubscher, an analyst at the brokerage firm of Tucker Anthony
Inc. in New York, noted the Dow has now recovered half of the
losses suffered as it slid from a Jan. 14 high of 11,723 to a low
of 9796 last week. ``A two-thirds recovery would be a bull
market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's second-largest one-day rise occurred Sept. 8, 1998,
when the stock market rose 380 points in the midst of a
full-fledged bull market.
</P>
<P>
   Market observers said what might be happening this week is a
phenomenon known as a a bear-market rally: Investors are buying on
the dips, though it is less clear whether they are optimistic about
the market's future overall or just betting on individual stocks.
In particular, institutional investors such as mutual funds and
pension managers, which are required to be fully invested in the
stock market, see a slump in the Dow as an opportunity to make
long-term investments.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said some of the market's extreme volatility was due to
Friday's simultaneous expiration of options and futures in stocks
and stocks indexes, an event known on Wall Street as a ``triple
witching.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq Composite index ended its three-day losing streak as
investors dived back into technology stocks that had been hammered
earlier in the week. Some of the buying may be have been caused by
continued speculation by day traders and aggressive individual
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Veritas Software Corp., after being crushed earlier this week,
rose more than $18.3125 a share, to $151.75. The world's largest
chip maker, Intel Corp., gained $4.875 a share, closing at
$125.0625. Biotechnology stocks, which rebounded Wednesday, rose
again Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Rallies in both the Nasdaq and the Dow on the same day has
become unusual in a year in which the two indexes frequently move
in opposite directions. On Wednesday, the Dow's huge gain was
countered by a 124-point fall in the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   ``For once the Dow has actually pulled the Nasdaq along with
it,'' said Ned Riley, chief investment strategist for State Street
Global Advisors, division of State Street Corp. ``That's more
balanced.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
