<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW RISES ALMOST 500 POINTS AS INVESTORS GO ON BUYING SPREE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Investors bought stocks furiously on Thursday,
sending the Dow Jones industrial average up nearly 500 points in
its biggest one-day point gain since October 1987. Broader indexes
also rose sharply as investors _ at least for the day _ put aside
fears that the Federal Reserve will aggressively raise interest
rates and slow the economy to a crawl.
</P>
<P>
   When trading began, buyers flocked to the old economy companies
that make up the bulk of the stock market but that have languished
much of this year. Stocks of financial companies such as J.P.
Morgan performed especially well, as did shares of airlines and
other companies whose profits will probably be strong if the U.S.
economy stays healthy.
</P>
<P>
   But by mid-afternoon, the buying had spread to technology and
Internet companies, new economy stocks that had already posted
strong gains this year. By the end of the day, all segments of the
market were sharply higher, with the Dow Jones industrials rising
499 points, or nearly 5 percent, to 10,631.
</P>
<P>
   The technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index ended three days of
sharp losses with a gain of nearly 3 percent. Apparently afraid
that they would miss out on gains, investors scurried to join the
rally, setting a record for trading on the New York Stock Exchange,
with 1.5 billion shares changing hands.
</P>
<P>
   By any standard, the gains were outsized. Venerable old economy
companies like American Express and General Motors saw their stocks
dance like new technology butterflies, with American Express
gaining $10.25, to $143.125, and GM $4.9375, to $83.75.
</P>
<P>
   The performance of the broader Standard and Poor's 500 index was
equally giddy. The S&AMP;P 500, which represents about 70 percent of
the value of all U.S. stocks, rose 66 points, or 4.8 percent, to
1458. While the point gain was the biggest for the Dow in over a
decade, at 4.9 percent it was the biggest in percentage terms only
since September 1998. Combined with Wednesday's 3.3 percent
increase, Thursday's gain amounted to the best two-day performance
for the index since its rally after the crash of October 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``A calm is settling in over the market on interest rates,''
said James Weiss, deputy chief investment officer of State Street
Research, which manages $55 billion. ``The market at the moment
seems to be comfortable that the Fed is going to raise interest
rates a couple of times but not more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve has raised short-term interest rates four
times since June in an effort to slow the booming economy, and Fed
Chairman Alan Greenspan has said he is worried about the potential
for inflation to accelerate. Along with higher oil prices, the
higher interest rates appear to have slowed the economy slightly,
said Jeffrey Applegate, chief investment strategist for Lehman
Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Applegate, a longtime bull, said a moderate economic slowdown is
good news for stocks, because it means that over the next few
months, the Federal Reserve will not have to raise rates as much as
investors previously expected. So investors can begin to look well
past the expected quarter-point increase by the Fed policy makers
next week to another period of steady interest rates and strong
corporate profits. That combination almost always makes for higher
stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``If, in fact, the Fed can go on hold, because there's not a
reason to do a lot of tightening, that's good for the markets,''
Applegate said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Greenspan has expressed concern that the meteoric rise in
technology stocks is encouraging spending by consumers who feel
increasingly wealthy on paper. Their spending could in turn fuel
inflation. To lessen that risk, Greenspan has said he would like
stock prices to grow more slowly, a warning heeded by technology
investors in the previous three days but disregarded on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street traders, who were even more swamped than usual on
Thursday, said buy orders seemed to come from all directions. While
investors' appetite for stock mutual funds has abated from its
record highs in February, when it averaged $10 billion per week, it
remains strong, according AMG Data Services of Arcata, Calif. AMG,
which tracks investment in mutual funds, said $5 billion went into
stock funds in the week ended Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The day began rather quietly. A few minutes after the opening
bell on the New York Stock Exchange, the Dow was up fewer than 100
points. The Nasdaq composite, which has been extremely volatile
lately and was down more than 9 percent the previous three days,
opened up, but fell sharply toward midday. Shortly after 11 a.m.,
it was down more than 100 points.
</P>
<P>
   As the day progressed, the Dow rocketed higher, and by
mid-afternoon, it had pulled the Nasdaq into positive territory.
From there, old economy and new economy stocks sprinted, closing
the day near their highs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
