<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9093 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-16 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE PRODIGAL SENATOR RETURNS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John McCain arrives home from his vacation in Bora-Bora this
weekend. On Monday he returns to the Senate, and everybody is dying
to see how he is greeted. The Republican leaders are eager to
demonstrate they are uniters, not dividers, good-natured guys who
don't at all mind having been constantly referred to as the Forces
of Darkness by one of their own members.
</P>
<P>
   The senator is said to be hoping for something low-key. ``He
never was much for senatorial courtesy anyway,'' noted an aide.
</P>
<P>
   People, you should jump into this discussion. True, McCain
failed in his mission to reform the campaign finance laws, so
voters still don't have quite as much pull in Washington as, say,
the pharmaceutical industry. Still, choose one of the following:
</P>
<P>
   John McCain should return to the Senate . . .
</P>
<P>
   A) Wrapped in a rug, like Cleopatra, which when unrolled will
deposit him at Trent Lott's feet.
</P>
<P>
   B) For a great welcome-home fiesta, during which Republican
senators will take turns swinging at a giant pinata filled with
soft money and shaped like McCain's head.
</P>
<P>
   C) Under armed guard.
</P>
<P>
   The wounds of the primary campaign have, um, not exactly healed.
The McCain campaign reports that many, many emissaries have been
attempting to achieve rapprochement on behalf of the Bush camp,
possibly with an eye to delivering the senator the way Big Pussy
Bompensiero delivered the guy who tried to rub out Tony Soprano's
favored underling.
</P>
<P>
   There had been some signs during the primaries that Bush is a
sore loser _ after New Hampshire, according to the McCain camp, he
tried to concede through an aide. But lately it's been looking as
if the Texas governor is not all that charming as a winner either.
He told The New York Times that he regrets nothing, has changed his
mind about nothing, and plans to do nothing in response to all
those weeks of listening to McCain talk about reform. He did,
however, genially give his former opponent credit for having
``forced me to play to my strength better.''
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing so dispiriting, really, as presidential
candidates who absolutely insist on sticking to stereotype. But
here we have George W., back from his first two months of
hand-to-hand combat on a national stage, and you ask him what he's
learned, and he stares at the ground and moves some dirt with his
foot and mutters, ``Nuttin'.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy never did take to schooling.
</P>
<P>
   But on the other hand, gosh, did Al Gore ever learn stuff. He
took notes! Which he has already, of course, transcribed on his
Thinkpad 600 and filed in color-coordinated folders. (All
references to Bush tax proposals can be found under R for
``risky.'') Gore hardly ever gives a speech now without reverently
quoting John McCain. Some people are wondering whether the
vacationing senator has heard he's become the vice president's new
role model.
</P>
<P>
   ``That'd be hard to miss even in Bora-Bora,'' said a McCain
aide.
</P>
<P>
   The post-primary campaign is getting a little too intense for
this stage of the game, especially after Bush made those soothing
comments about the public's right to hibernate from politics for a
while. Cynics said he was actually only trying to avoid Gore's
challenge to engage in immediate wall-to-wall debates. But it's
hard to believe that a would-be Reaganite like Bush would joke
about something as important as naps.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, a lot of ordinary citizens have taken Bush at his
word and gone home to put their heads down. On Tuesday in Al Gore's
hometown, the local paper's headline was ``STATE PRIMARY LARGELY
INSIGNIFICANT.'' There were some complaints that this was not a
very good way to drum up voter turnout.
</P>
<P>
   The schoolchildren, however, dutifully showed up to watch the
vice president vote for himself. Afterward Gore invited them to ask
questions, and before you knew it he was telling the little kids
about his role in reinventing government, the Telecommunications
Reform Act, bridging the Digital Divide and shoring up Social
Security. They ran out of questions in a remarkably short time.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president needs coaching on his Talks to Youth. Perhaps
McCain could give him some tips he picked up at the MTV awards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
