<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BARNHOUSE-BONNIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST UPSET BID OF TOURNAMENT FALLS JUST SHORT AT THE FINISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Sometimes, the wrong team wins.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky, a No. 5 seed, was supposed to win and did. St.
Bonaventure, the No. 12 seed, was supposed to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like we should be playing Saturday,'' said Bonnies
senior guard David Messiah Capers. ``The crowd wanted us to win
that game.''
</P>
<P>
   So did most of America.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth-seeded Wildcats needed two overtimes plus every bit of
their talent and blue-blood reputation to advance in the NCAA
Tournament. Kentucky (23-9) will play in the second round for the
ninth consecutive year because of Thursday's 85-80 first-round
victory over St. Bonaventure (22-10), an NCAA entrant for the first
time since 1978.
</P>
<P>
   St. Bonaventure _ the patron saint of near upsets. In the first
game played in this year's NCAA Tournament, with CBS sending the
game to most of the country, the Bonnies nearly produced the first
surprise story.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it would be a great game because it was a 5-12 game
and everybody was looking for an upset,'' said Kentucky sophomore
forward Tayshaun Prince, who helped make it great. His 3-pointer at
7.1 seconds sent the game into overtime. Prince finished with a
career-high 28 and at one point scored 15 of his team's 20 points.
</P>
<P>
   Prince was Kentucky's hero. Messiah Capers was ... what? The
anti-hero? The near-hero? Heroes are supposed to play for winners.
</P>
<P>
   This game went two overtimes because of a why-did-he-do-that
foul on Kentucky's Marvin Stone. With four-tenths of a second
remaining, Messiah Capers went to the line, the Bonnies trailing
76-73.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a good free-throw shooter, I'm not Shaquille O'Neal,'' he
said. ``I just got off to a bad start this season.'' The stat sheet
has Messiah Capers as a 55.6 percent foul shooter. In six of his
past eight games, he did not have an attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the situation everybody dreams about,'' St. Bonaventure
senior guard Tim Winn said. ``I was standing there thinking, `I've
had this dream and I was at the line.' But I was glad it was him
instead of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Messiah Capers swished the first. Kentucky, timeout. He swished
the second. Kentucky, timeout. He swished the third. ``Those
timeouts seemed kinda long,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's as many free throws as Messiah Capers had made in his
past eight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't thinking about the past, I was looking at right
then,'' he said. ``Percentages go out the window. There was no
doubt in my mind, it was just all confidence. I didn't want to wind
up on ESPN because I missed the game-tying free throw.''
</P>
<P>
   The teams traded 23-5 runs and shooting droughts. Kentucky's
came in the first half. The Wildcats led 44-31 with 15:55
remaining. Then, the Bonnies self-ignited, hitting four of five
3-pointers to produce a 23-5 game-changing spurt. For the last 18
minutes, the biggest lead for either team was five.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky's biggest basket in the second overtime came with 11.6
seconds remaining. Freshman Keith Bogans gathered a loose ball and
laid it in for an 83-80 lead. Winn's last-chance 3-pointer kicked
in, then out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to play our hearts out,'' said Prince, who could tread
water in a test tube.
</P>
<P>
   St. Bonaventure had a handful of mighta-been, shoulda-been
moments. After taking a 52-48 lead, Caswell Cyrus was called for a
technical for hanging on the rim. Kentucky made one of two free
throws. Moments later, up 54-49, the Bonnies frittered away three
good-for-nothing possessions.
</P>
<P>
   With 1:23 remaining, senior guard Winn failed to convert a
three-point play opportunity. Then, with the chance to win the game
in regulation, he couldn't convert a contested layup. In the first
overtime, J.R. Bremer made the first two, but missed the third
after being fouled on a 3-point try.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great way to start of the NCAA Tournament,'' St.
Bonaventure coach Jim Baron said. ``We did everything we possibly
could.''
</P>
<P>
   Except win.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
