<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARE-BELL17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chile's president comes full circle
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One Sunday evening in September 1973, Ford Foundation
official Peter Bell and his wife, Karen, sat down to dinner at a
restaurant in Santiago, Chile, with their friends Ricardo and Luisa
Lagos.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone sensed that a political coup was coming. They could
feel it. Bell and Lagos, an educator and university official,
talked about it. Salvador Allende, a socialist elected in 1970 with
a third of the vote, had overplayed his hand and abandoned the
center.
</P>
<P>
   But none of the people at that dinner, Bell said, thought the
coup would come as soon or be as virulent as turned out to be the
case.
</P>
<P>
   And there was something else they didn't foresee, Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us would have believed in our wildest dreams that 27
years later, Ricardo would be democratically elected as the
president of Chile,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But it happened. Last weekend, Bell, now the president of CARE,
the Atlanta-based relief and development organization, traveled
with his wife to Chile as Lagos' special guests to celebrate his
inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   Just a day and a half after that Sunday dinner _ early on
Tuesday morning, Sept. 11, 1973 _ a junta led by Gen. Augusto
Pinochet ousted Allende's government. Allende was killed.
</P>
<P>
   During Pinochet's 17 years in power more than 3,000 people were
killed or ``disappeared'' in a campaign against the country's
leftists. Fear was in the air. Bell, who lived in Chile from
1970-74, found himself on a list of suspicious people. He returned
home one day to find his wife cradling their infant son and saying
that a neighbor _ a person the Bells suspected of being a
right-wing vigilante _ had dropped by to say that Bell should be
executed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, things have come full circle. Pinochet has returned to
Chile, free from international prosecution but discredited and,
said Bell, irrelevant to Chilean politics. And Lagos, a socialist,
was sworn in Saturday as president.
</P>
<P>
   Bell said he thinks Lagos has what it takes to govern well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew him as a very competent manager who is also politically
adept,'' Bell said. Furthermore, Bell said, Lagos is determined to
hold the country together and avoid the polarization of past eras.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have every reason to believe that he will be a very
successful president of all Chileans,'' Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
