<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-TEXAS-INDIANA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWITCH TO ZONE LIFTS TEXAS OVER INDIANA STATE
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Texas was more than halfway through a tense,
basket-trading first half with Indiana State on Thursday in its
NCAA Tournament opener when coach Rick Barnes decided to shuffle
the deck.
</P>
<P>
   He went with the big lineup of Chris Mihm, Chris Owens and Gabe
Muoneke and shifted the Longhorns from their trademark man-for-man
defense into a 2-3 zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we did that, our whole body language changed,'' Barnes
said. ``I thought we were a little jumpy to start the game. We went
to the zone and later a triangle-and-two and got a great effort by
the players. The zone slowed (Indiana State) down and helped us
save a little energy and work a little harder on the offensive end.
It kept us alert because we were playing defenses we don't normally
use. I think it surprised them a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes' strategy had the desired effect.
</P>
<P>
   Texas trailed 22-19 when he made his move. Seven minutes later,
the fifth-seeded Longhorns held a 39-26 halftime lead and were on
their way to a 77-61 first-round victory over the Sycamores to move
into Saturday's second-round battle in the West Region against No.
4 seed Louisiana State.
</P>
<P>
   ``A well-strategized game,'' Muoneke said. ``You do anything you
can to adjust and try to win. The 2-3 zone was good to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas' front line contributed 48 points, divided equally, and
guard Darren Kelly responded from outside with a trio of 3-point
shots that sparked the late first-half spurt on his way to a
team-high 17 points. Point guard Ivan Wagner passed out a
career-tying 10 assists and contributed seven points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fantastic to get this win,'' said Mihm, who was limited
to 28 minutes because of foul problems, but still pulled down eight
rebounds. ``To have this team play well like we did and advance is
really special. We played all-around solid basketball at every
position.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas held ISU's leading scorer, Nate Green, to only five points
on eight shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their zone was very tough,'' Green said. ``We had a hard time
getting into it all game. They did a great job on defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sycamores did provide a few hairy minutes in the second half
after Texas stretched its lead to 54-37 at 14:42 when Owens laid in
a follow shot. But Mihm drew his third foul on a pushoff and went
to the bench at 11:20 after ISU crept to within 12. The Sycamores
cut the lead to 56-49 following what amounted to a five-point turn
when Muoneke incurred a technical foul for taunting after a jam.
Mihm re-entered, but drew his fourth whistle on an offensive move
and sat down again after only 13 seconds back on the court.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Menser (22 points) nailed a 3-pointer at 10:35 and ISU
was within five (56-51). But at that point, the Longhorns slammed
the door. The Sycamores left the lane with Mihm on the bench and
discovered they couldn't cover Owens one-on-one. He hit two dunks
and a layup over the next four minutes, Muoneke hit a pull-up,
10-foot jumper and then Kelly scored five consecutive points. When
Mihm came back in at 3:38, Texas was up 69-61 and the big sweat was
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided to post up a lot deeper and move the ball around to
get better looks,'' Owens explained. ``That's why we were able to
score inside in the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows our offense runs through Chris Mihm,'' Kelly
said. ``But Coach always tells me to create, look for my shots and
some for my teammates and that's what I did with Mihm on the
bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes was pleased with the Longhorns' performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played very well against a team I was very impressed
with,'' he said. ``Indiana State would finish in the top six in the
Big 12. That's as good an offense as we've played against all year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest game in the tournament is always the first one.
Once that's over, the players settle in and get more comfortable
with the situation. Today was a good win. But we've got to forget
about it and get ready to play another tough game.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
