<HEADER>
A9102 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-WOLF-BIGAPPLE17-COX     03-16 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOLF-BIGAPPLE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wolf sinking teeth into Big Apple
 &HT;    By Renee DeGross
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Chuck Wolf is looking at opportunity in the Big Apple
through a wide-angle lens.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Atlanta-based Wolf Camera has gained a foothold in New
York, its founder says it will be only a matter of time before his
company becomes a household name there in film processing, camera
equipment and video services.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf Camera entered New York through its purchase of Westside
Camera in Manhattan in 1998. This month the company agreed to buy
four Alkit Pro Camera stores in Manhattan, and it plans to open two
more locations by May 1.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview this week at his headquarters in Alpharetta, the
57-year-old Wolf said New York offers endless potential for his
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``People line up outside of that (Westside) store,'' Wolf said.
``That's why we're excited about New York.''
</P>
<P>
   The Westside store is the chain's No. 2 in sales volume. In
2,400 square feet, Westside pulls in $5 million annually, behind
the gargantuan Midtown Atlanta store. Wolf did not release sales
figures for the Atlanta site.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the photofinishing industry has evolved and can be
lucrative because of consumer interest in digital cameras and
imaging.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a capital-intensive proposition to keep up with the
latest digital technology. Wolf said his company invests up to
$200,000 per digital imaging machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very competitive business that requires substantial
capital per outlet,'' said analyst Pete Enderlin with Ryan Beck &AMP;
Co. in New York. ``But that's an advantage for Wolf because the
company can develop economies of scale with its 800 or so stores.''
</P>
<P>
   Photofinishing worldwide, including digital imaging, is an
estimated $59.2 billion industry, according to the Photo Marketing
Association International of Jackson, Mich. About a third of the
business comes from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take years before we get the percent of market in New
York that we have in Dallas, Atlanta, Houston and Chicago,'' Wolf
said. But, he added, because New York is so big, ``even if you have
a small share, it's great.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf admits that the 1998 purchase of 450 CPI/Fox Photo stores
took time to digest. The company had to close 140 locations that
didn't fit the Wolf Camera concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't do the Fox thing, we'd be making more money,''
Wolf said. ``It has been a big challenge and has taken two years to
change the employees to the Wolf culture.'' That culture, Wolf says
is service, service and more service.
</P>
<P>
   While Wolf Camera declined to provide financial data on its
business, it ranked No. 11 among the largest privately owned
companies in the 20-county metro Atlanta area, based on 1998
revenue of between $250 million to $499 million, according to a
survey by Arthur Andersen LLP. It was also one of the state's
fastest-growing businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf Camera began operations in 1974 with seven stores in metro
Atlanta and three in Charlotte. Now the company operates in 34
states.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf isn't divulging much about what's next for the business as
he nears 60. ``I still have a passion for the business,'' he said.
``But I am thinking of certain options.'' His son, Alex, is vice
president of real estate.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from New York and other markets, Wolf sees more potential
on the Internet. His two Web sites _ www.wolfcamera.com and
www.wolfxpress.com _ are places where customers can buy camera
equipment and download photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it's the photofinishing business, not the big-ticket digital
cameras or camcorders, that pump up business in the end, Wolf said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't make money on cameras.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
