<HEADER>
A9107 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DOW17-COX     03-16 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Market keeps shifting between `old' and `new' economy stocks
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The good news for investors about this week's activity
on Wall Street is that money is staying in the market and not
spilling out into cash, bonds, gold and other alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   It's flowing back and forth between ``old economy'' and ``new
economy'' stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indeed, (this week's) powerful rally in the long-lagging Dow
Jones industrial average and S&AMP;P 500 apparently attracted funds
that had been sidelined because of worries over the earlier
divergence,'' said Standard &AMP; Poor's analyst Arnold Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   At Prudential Securities, technical analyst Ralph Acampora
attributed this week's volatile trading to technology stocks that
had become overbought and blue-chip stocks that were oversold.
</P>
<P>
   ``These gyrations are due primarily to the depressed nature of
the old-line companies and the stretched nature of the new economy
stocks,'' said Acampora.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts believe that tech stocks will continue to dominate
the market as long as the Federal Reserve sticks to its policy of
fighting inflation with higher interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Rising rates, aimed at slowing the economy's torrid growth, hurt
primarily the profit outlook of companies that need bank and other
loans to operate and expand.
</P>
<P>
   Internet, dot-com and other computer-related companies
apparently are less dependent on loans, using cash flow and equity
markets to fund expansions and operations.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say that even the high-tech stocks will eventually
be hurt by rising rates if their low-tech customers and clients
can't buy their products and services.
</P>
<P>
   This is why Wall Street is intensely interested in what the Fed
does, watching for any snippet of evidence that inflation is not a
problem, or that the economy might be slowing.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts also believe the market itself may be playing into
the Fed's hands with every selloff, such as this week's Nasdaq
plunge.
</P>
<P>
   A slower market means less of a wealth effect and less consumer
spending, in this view. The Fed has made it clear that it is
concerned about the consumer's role as an engine of economic growth
and has been accused by critics of trying to engineer a stock
selloff.
</P>
<P>
   But as big as it was, some analysts believe the Nasdaq's selloff
only put a dent in the historic valuations of many technology
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is worrisome now is not the fact the market has a
divergence, but the size of it,'' said Legacy South strategist
Phillip Larkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``The S&AMP;P 500 is trading at 24 times earnings but the Nasdaq is
at 300 times earnings. It's not that the Nasdaq has taken center
stage, but that so many stocks are trading on the long-term hope
that technology leads to earnings. And the odds are that most
Internet companies won't be profitable even in the long term,''
said Larkins.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the investors' money is staying in the stock
market, enough is moving into Treasury bonds to push bond prices
higher and yields lower. This is still another boost to stocks,
since falling yields make bonds less attractive than stock returns.
</P>
<P>
   However the stock market indexes end the year, analysts say the
one certainty is that investors can look forward to a highly
volatile market.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
