<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSCAR CONTENDERS WASHINGTON, JOLIE AT WORK IN `THE BONE COLLECTOR'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Rob Lowman's weekly video column.) 
By ROB LOWMAN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a thriller, ``The Bone Collector'' is a bit above average _
creepy enough, but a bit short on logic and believability.
</P>
<P>
   But it does boast two of this year's Oscar nominees in starring
roles _ Denzel Washington, who is up in the best actor category for
his role of wrongly convicted boxer Rubin Carter in ``Hurricane,''
and Angelina Jolie, who received the best supporting actress nod
for her role as the mentally disturbed teen, Lisa, in ``Girl,
Interrupted.'' Both already picked up Golden Globe Awards earlier
in the year, and Jolie won a Screen Actors Guild statuette on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Collector'' is another serial-killer story, the twist being
that Washington's character _ forensic detective Lincoln Rhyme _ is
a quadriplegic. Rhyme had been injured while investigating a crime.
He remains on the force, however _ albeit bedridden and surrounded
by an array of high-tech gadgetry _ and continues to help solve
crimes. Jolie plays Amelia Donaghy, a smart beat cop who Rhyme
recognizes has potential to be more.
</P>
<P>
   Jolie and Washington make a compelling combination, with both
playing variations of roles that they are known for. Even in action
roles, Washington comes across as cerebral, and _ except for
flashbacks to when his character wasn't paralyzed _ that's what you
see in this film. But Washington, a former best supporting actor
Oscar winner, can do a lot with a little. And while his Rhyme
character is fairly predictably drawn, Washington imbues him with
strength and dignity without overreaching, making him far more real
than any of the events in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   The characters Jolie plays, on the other hand, always seem
dangerous _ either to themselves, others or both. Donaghy is no
exception, carrying around a lot of past baggage. It's not the
character but Jolie's edginess, an animal-on-the-prowl quality,
that keeps you watching. Jolie, the daughter of Academy
Award-winning actor Jon Voight, has already picked up a couple of
Emmys. Oscar won't be far behind.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, who is nominated along with another former winner in
the best supporting actor category, Kevin Spacey, is a favorite to
win the Oscar. But win or lose, go back and check out some of
Washington's previous work, particularly in his films with Spike
Lee _ ``Mo Better Blues (1990), ``Malcolm X'' (1992) and ``He Got
Game'' (1998) Others include ``Cry Freedom'' (1987), in which he
played South African activist Steven Biko; ``Glory,'' for which he
won his Oscar; Carl Franklin's `Devil in a Blue Dress'' (1995),
which is based on the Walter Mosley novel; and ``Courage Under
Fire'' (1996).
</P>
<P>
   Jolie has a much shorter resume, but check out last year's
``Pushing Tin'' and ``Gia,'' the HBO movie where she played
outrageous supermodel Gia Carangi, who died of AIDS. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MAKING SENSE
</P>
<P>
   Get ready for the force _ the force that will be brewing with
the VHS release of ``Star Wars: Episode 1 _ The Phantom Menace,''
on April 4. That's right, despite all the digital elements in the
film, George Lucas' prequel to his three hit films will not be
released on DVD. Go figure. But last year's surprise hit and this
year's Oscar nominee for best picture ``The Sixth Sense'' will come
out on DVD March 28. &QL; 
_____
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bone Collector'' (Universal) is priced for rental on VHS
($107.37) and is $29.98 on DVD. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 2044EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0339 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9111 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOVIES-SXSW17-COX     03-16 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SXSW17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Less star power, but more screen punch than fests past
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ On Monday night at the South by Southwest party
on the roof of Waterloo Brewing Company, Louis Black confided to me
that this is the best SXSW Film Festival in its seven-year run.
</P>
<P>
   Well, sure. What else is the fest's senior director going to say
_ it's the worst? The most OK?
</P>
<P>
   This is only my third SXSW, but I'll vouch anyway for Black's
assessment. Star power might be at a premium _ despite Janeane
Garofalo and Jerry Stiller's appearance at the Paramount for
Sunday's premiere of ``The Independent'' _ but the lineup of 200
films has aroused more curiosity in this viewer than any other SXSW
festival.
</P>
<P>
   As of this writing, I've seen about eight festival films, few of
them stinkers. By the Saturday closing, that figure should hit 15.
(Black, on the other hand, said he's seen few if any of the movies
playing at his festival. No time. He's been zigzagging theaters,
introducing shows to the lucky ones who get to stay for them.)
</P>
<P>
   John Pierson, president of Grainy Pictures, host of the
Independent Film Channel's ``Split Screen'' and gleeful movie
gadfly, did not hesitate Wednesday to call this year's schedule ``a
good batch of films.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding muscle to the nine-day movie slate is an unusually strong
backwash of titles from the Sundance Film Festival. Most of these
circuit-cruisers have landed in the top ranks of SXSW offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big Kahuna,'' a Kevin Spacey drama, has drawn droves (it
shows again Saturday). Repeating its Sundance buzz, Marc Singer's
documentary about New York's homeless mole people, ``Dark Days,''
became an instant festival classic, winning the senior programmers'
pick at Tuesday's awards ceremony. The word on Paul Stekler's
Sundance award-winner ``George Wallace: Settin' the Woods on Fire''
has been roundly euphoric. ``Just, Melvin'' and ``The Ballad of
Ramblin' Jack'' are must-see docs.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there have been a few stars pulling people in. On
panels and introducing their films were directors D.A. Pennebaker,
Monte Hellman, Marc Singer, the Hughes brothers, Gregory Nava, John
Carpenter and ``Exorcist'' screenwriter William Peter Blatty.
</P>
<P>
   Attending Austin luminaries have included director/writers
Stekler, Richard Linklater, Robert Rodriguez, Tim McCanlies, Larry
Wright, L.M. Kit Carson and Guillermo Del Toro.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday at the Alamo, Linklater gave a droll, heartfelt
introduction to Hellman's 1971 classic ``Two-Lane Blacktop'' _
still my favorite screening yet. ``This is a great night in my
cinematic life,'' gushed Linklater, who helped acquire the new
print from Universal.
</P>
<P>
   He called it the ``purest road movie ever'' and singled out
James Taylor's performance with the brilliant observation that he's
``like a refugee from a Robert Bresson movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Hellman praised us right back. ``From what I've seen so far, I
love Austin,'' said the director. ``It's a great city. You're lucky
to live here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Two-Lane Blacktop'' showed many signs of age, all of them
exquisite. Its laid-back humor and underlying angst, not to mention
killer performances by Taylor, Dennis Wilson and the inimitable
Warren Oates, braced in ways movies rarely do anymore.
</P>
<P>
   My first SXSW movie this year was a bust. I groaned watching the
cheesy Abbie Hoffman biopic ``Steal This Movie!,'' which premiered
last Friday night at the Paramount. Vincent D'Onofrio was game but
unconvincing as the puckish political agitator, while comedian
Garofalo made tortured essays into dramatic acting. The film's
title, I think, is wishful thinking. I doubt they could give away
this movie.
</P>
<P>
   I like to crow about my outsized appreciation for esoteric
art-filmmaker Peter Greenaway, whose ``The Cook, the Thief, His
Wife and Her Lover'' is a personal favorite. I'm also a big fan of
``The Draughtsman's Contract,'' ``The Belly of an Architect,''
``Drowning by Numbers,'' ``A Zed and Two Noughts'' _ you get the
idea. These films strike a prepossessing balance between
Greenaway's painterly exuberance and challenging thematic
obsessions.
</P>
<P>
   But somewhere around ``Prospero's Books'' and ``The Pillow
Book'' Greenaway's films have lurched from mesmerizing to
impenetrable. So with ``8 1/2 Women,'' which got its U.S. premiere
Saturday at the Paramount. A beautiful bore, this oblique homage to
Greenaway's kindred spirit, Fellini, traffics in the filmmaker's
familiar compulsions: sex, the flesh, death, beauty, class
distinctions and the tyranny of mathematical order.
</P>
<P>
   Throngs came out to the Paramount on Monday night for the Hughes
brothers' documentary ``American Pimp,'' a SXSW main attraction.
The film's taken flak since its premiere at Sundance in 1999, so I
had low expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pimp'' proved a gritty, revelatory pleasure. The intimate tour
of urban underworlds grooved to the beat of funk and hip-hop,
shining a dim light into filthy pockets of America that exhilarated
as they repelled.
</P>
<P>
   As of this morning, there are 39 screenings left at SXSW. You
can find me tonight at the John Cusack comedy ``High Fidelity'' and
the professional wrestling documentary ``Beyond the Mat.'' On
Saturday I'll be heading to Hellman's offbeat western ``Ride in the
Whirlwind,'' ``Noriega: God's Favorite'' and ``The Big Kahuna.''
</P>
<P>
   Best one yet. Black says so. So do I.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
