u e BC-BLATTY-QA17-COX     03-16 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLATTY-QA17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Exorcist' scares even its writer
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Screenwriter William Peter Blatty showed up at
the Paramount Theatre for Wednesday night's world premiere
screening of the new, expanded version of ``The Exorcist.'' So did
a bat.
</P>
<P>
   Blatty, wearing a spiffy sweater, came first. He introduced an
immaculate new print of the evergreen 1973 thriller, which he
considers ``a supernatural detective story'' _ a surprise to
legions of damaged filmgoers who have always considered the film a
lethal horror movie capable of obliterating many a good night's
slumber.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the bat, which fluttered about with possessed abandon
in front of the screen just as Satan was pulling up the moving van
to take residency inside little Regan MacNeil, indelibly played by
chubby-cheeked Linda Blair. The bat furnished a redundant spooky
touch to the evening, eliciting nervous titters from the large
crowd. Batty, meet Blatty.
</P>
<P>
   Blatty, who also produced the film and wrote the novel on which
it's based, said 11 minutes were restored to ``The Exorcist,''
footage that director William Friedkin was pressured to pare for
length. This version, shown as part of the South by Southwest Film
Festival, features unseen sequences, including some crowd-pleasing
jolts (beware Blair's contortionist crab walk down the stairs),
silly semi-subliminal images and a happier ending.
</P>
<P>
   Made for $12 million, ``The Exorcist'' has made $400 million
worldwide. It was the highest-grossing horror movie in U.S. history
until ``The Sixth Sense'' surpassed it.
</P>
<P>
   Upon its release, the Catholic Church condemned the film.
Critics reviled it as trashy and misogynistic. Some filmgoers
passed out from fear.
</P>
<P>
   Blatty asked the Paramount crowd, ``How many of you have never
seen `The Exorcist' on the big screen?''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of hands shot up.
</P>
<P>
   Blatty grinned. ``Good luck,'' he said. The house lights dimmed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why do you think ``The Exorcist'' has stood the test of time
as potently as it has?
</P>
<P>
   A: The truthful answer is that it's been a mystery to me. We can
say all the obvious things: beautifully acted, beautifully
directed, all of that. But I think it has to do with the desire for
religious belief. I really think that's at the heart of it. It's
kind of a spiritual ``Rocky.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's amazing is how seriously the film is taken. It hasn't
grown a camp quotient that could degrade its terror. Audiences
still take it on its own terms, and it's perceived as it was 27
years ago. ...
</P>
<P>
   A: It is. It has the same power and effect it had on its
original audiences. I know when I'm forced to watch it I'm very
clinical. And then at the end, at some point during the exorcism, I
look down at my hands and they're tightly gripping the arms of the
chair. So something has gotten to me. It has a tremendous power
that's kind of mysterious. Billy Graham said there's a force in
this movie, right in the film itself. He meant a source of evil of
some kind. But at least he perceived that there is a power in it
that's extremely mysterious.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Clearly you like this version much better.
</P>
<P>
   A: Oh, yeah. I liked it the first time I saw it 26 years ago. I
know one executive told Friedkin that the end of the movie had to
be when Father Dyer (the Rev. William O'Malley) stares down the
empty steps. We had (the new scenes) in the picture originally.
This version has been my idea for years. I wanted it always.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The upbeat ending is especially noticeable. What does it add
to the film?
</P>
<P>
   A: It lets you know everything's OK and that it's not a downer.
Too many people are not watching closely enough. They think the
demon took Father Karras (Jason Miller) out the window. If you
watch closely, you know that isn't true. But if you're all sad and
gloomy at the end, you think maybe the demon did. This tells you
everything's OK.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was the pea soup your idea?
</P>
<P>
   A: (Laughs.) The vomit was in the book and the script.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was it described as the green gruel we see flying at faces?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, because bile would be greenish, yellow-green. Mixing in
the oatmeal was someone else's idea. (Laughs.)
</P>
<P>
   Q: Didn't Pauline Kael call itmisogynistic?
</P>
<P>
   A: You know what she called it? In her review she said, ``This
film is the biggest recruiting poster for the Catholic Church since
`Going My Way.''' She just hated it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about those critics who did call it viciously
misogynistic?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's just ludicrous overanalysis.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've always been a little perplexed by the connection of the
opening scenes in the Iraqi desert to the rest of the film. The new
version seems to take pains to bridge a connection.
</P>
<P>
   A: We added one more bridge in there, that subliminal image of
(the demon statue) on the bedroom door. But we always had that
large superimposure of it during the exorcism.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's it mean? Did Father Merrin (Max von Sydow)
inadvertently bring the devil back with him?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. It's nothing. Nobody brought anything back. The demon, I
think, came back to Merrin for another round.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
