u w BC-IRS-CONSERVATIVES-NYT     03-16 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRS-CONSERVATIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-GORE AIDES ARE FAULTED IN IRS CASE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two aides to Vice President Al Gore improperly
called the Internal Revenue Service on the same day in early 1997
seeking information on a tax case of interest to a union whose
president was scheduled to meet with Gore the following day,
congressional investigators said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators, staff members of the bipartisan Joint
Committee on Taxation, said in a report made public Thursday that
the two aides ``appear to have attempted to obtain taxpayer return
information to which they were not entitled.'' Federal law bars
almost any release of information by the IRS about specific
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Lindy L. Paull, the committee's chief of staff, said many
details of the episode were fuzzy and that she was constrained by
taxpayer confidentiality from identifying the union. But Paull said
at a news conference that the calls, which were rebuffed by the
IRS, raised questions about whether the vice president's office had
created at least the ``appearance of influence'' on behalf of a
group with ties to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas seized on the report, describing
the calls as part of a pattern, including the vice president's fund
raising at a Buddhist temple and his fund-raising calls from the
White House, that cast doubt on Gore's fitness to hold the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Gore, Laura Quinn, said the vice president's
staff had followed all White House procedures for contacting the
tax service and had done nothing improper in making what amounted
to a routine status check on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn said that the information in the committee's report was
wrong in many respects, that Gore's schedule showed no meetings
with union officials in January 1997 and that the two staff members
had both left the White House and could not remember the phone
calls.
</P>
<P>
   She said that based on the information provided by the
committee, she did not know what union might have been involved.
Gore's office said it was also checking to see whether the vice
president had met with any union leaders in February 1997, but that
it did not yet have an answer.
</P>
<P>
   The report by the Joint Committee on Taxation focused on
accusations that the IRS had investigated, audited or generally
treated unfairly tax-exempt conservative groups that were at odds
politically with the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   It concluded that there was ``no credible evidence'' that the
groups had been targeted by the tax service. But in the course of
its investigation, the committee said it came across two instances
where the administration had made what it termed ``nonroutine
contacts'' with the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   The first involved an inquiry by a Treasury Department official
in 1995 to the IRS about an examination of a tax-exempt
organization. The committee concluded that the contact had not
influenced the outcome of the case.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the attention Thursday was focused on the calls
between Gore's office and the IRS, which congressional aides said
took place on Jan. 28, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Paull said a junior staff member in Gore's office had called the
Treasury and then the IRS in search of the information about the
tax case involving the union.
</P>
<P>
   After the staff member was rebuffed, Paull said, a more senior
staff member called the IRS that same day, and was told that the
tax agency could not provide any information about specific cases
and could only discuss the issue in general terms.
</P>
<P>
   Paull said the issue had to do with whether a group of people
working for a union should be classified as employees or
independent contractors for tax purposes. The report did not
identify the IRS official who spoke to Gore's aides or the
official's title.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional aides who were briefed on the report said
documents kept by the IRS quoted the Gore aides as saying they
needed the information because Gore was to meet with the union's
president the following day.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's office said the staff members referred to by Paull were
Kumiki Gibson, who in early 1997 was Gore's counsel, and Joe Eyer,
who was an assistant to Gore's deputy chief of staff. Gibson did
not return a phone call. Eyer declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Committee investigators incorrectly described Eyer as Gibson's
superior, and said Eyer had called the IRS after Gibson had no luck
getting the information she was seeking.
</P>
<P>
   White House policy requires any contacts with the IRS to be
cleared with the White House counsel's office. Quinn said that as
Gore's counsel, Gibson satisfied that requirement, and that Eyer
had told the vice president's office that his practice was to clear
such calls with the counsel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 2057EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
