<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9127 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CLINTON-FILES-ART-(TR     03-16 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FILES-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDEPENDENT COUNSEL SEES NO CRIMINAL WRONGDOING OVER FBI FILES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo _ NYT20 _ is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nearly four years after the office of independent
counsel began investigating how the White House acquired some 900
confidential FBI files, many of them of prominent Republicans, the
current head of the office, Robert Ray, officially reported on
Thursday that no criminal wrongdoing was involved.
</P>
<P>
   The report is the first of several to be issued over the next
several months by Ray as he closes down the independent counsel's
office that has been investigating a wide range of issues involving
President and Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released at the same time he filed the report at
the federal courthouse here, Ray said:
</P>
<P>
   ``In the FBI files matter, the Independent Counsel determined
there was no substantial and credible evidence that any senior
White House official, or First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, was
involved in seeking confidential Federal Bureau of Investigation
background reports of former White House staff from the prior
administrations of President Bush and President Reagan.''
</P>
<P>
   The report itself was filed under seal and was not released
publicly, under procedures established under the independent
counsel law that give those named in the report a chance to
respond. Lawyers familiar with its contents said that it concluded
that the files were inadvertently collected at the White House
through a series of errors committed by mid-level officials in the
White House security office.
</P>
<P>
   The report also definitively clears Bernard Nussbaum, a former
White House counsel, of any wrongdoing in connection with a
peripheral matter involving the White House files.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of the FBI files led to wide criticism of the
Clinton White House for its apparent carelessness in handling
sensitive personnel files. More troublesome was a broad range of
speculation that the files were collected purposely in order to
collect political intelligence on prominent Republicans. Some of
the files requested and received by the Clinton White House were
those of Brent Scowcroft, President George Bush's national security
adviser; Kenneth Duberstein, President Ronald Reagan's chief of
staff, and Marlin Fitzwater, press secretary to both Reagan and
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation included fingerprint analyses of the files
themselves to see if any senior Clinton officials or the first lady
had handled them. Those tests produced no evidence that the files
were read by senior officials or Mrs. Clinton, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   The report concluded that the files were improperly collected
because a mid-level investigator, Anthony Marceca, requisitioned
them from the FBI using an outdated list compiled by the Secret
Service of who had passes to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Some senior Clinton associates on Thursday said they were
pleased about the findings and sought to portray them as evidence
that justified their complaints that enormous time and money has
been wasted in the investigation which started with the Clinton's
investment in the Whitewater real estate venture and expanded to
many other areas. The investigation, which has lasted more than
five years, is estimated to have cost more than $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   The only public statement the White House offered on Thursday
was given by Jim Kennedy, a spokesman, who said that the Ray
statement, ``confirms what Mr. Starr said two years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ray's office is planning to file other reports in the coming
months. The next report due about July will deal with how White
House officials fired seven longtime employees of the White House
travel office and planned to replace them with longtime associates
of the Clintons. That report may be more problematic for the
Clintons as it will likely explore Mrs. Clinton's role in the
dismissals. She has insisted to investigators she was only slightly
aware of what was happening while others have testified that she
was at the center of it.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement on Thursday, Ray struck a different tone than
his predecessor, Kenneth W. Starr who had deeply strained relations
with the White House. Ray made a point of thanking the White House
for its cooperation in the investigation of the FBI files.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Under the independent counsel law, the reports are filed with a
special three-judge panel that administers the law. Although the
law expired in June, its provisions still govern Ray's operation.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge panel is supposed to allow persons named in the
report to see it to allow them to rebut or respond to it. After
that, a process that could take as long as three months, the
reports may then be released publicly.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   More than a third of the 100-page report that was filed today is
devoted to the Nussbaum investigation which had come to symbolize
for many in the Clinton White House, the quickness with which
Attorney General Janet Reno had once sought to turn minor
allegations into full-blown independent counsel investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Reno had asked the independent counsel's office, then under the
direction of Starr, to investigate whether Nussbaum had testified
untruthfully before Congress. A House committee investigating the
acquisition of the files wanted to determine who had hired Craig
Livingstone, who was in charge of the office when the files were
collected.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony before the committee, Nussbaum denied that he had
ever told an FBI agent that Livingstone was hired because either he
or his mother were friends with Mrs. Clinton. The agent, Dennis
Sculimbrene, had produced handwritten notes of his interview saying
that Nussbaum attributed Livingstone's hiring to an association
with Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials were angered that Reno sought an
independent counsel to investigate Nussbaum as many argued that the
case was always flimsy as it involved two different accounts of a
meeting, Nussbaum's and Sculimbrene's. In the end, the report is
unequivocal in its conclusions that there is no case against
Nussbaum, lawyers familiar with it said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ray said in his statement that, ``The independent counsel found
no substantial evidence that Nussbaum lied to the House Committee
on Government Reform and Oversight about his discussions with Mrs.
Clinton regarding the hiring of former Office of Personnel Security
Director Craig Livingstone or about his knowledge regarding the
circumstances of Mr. Livingstone's appointment.'' Ray added that
there was no evidence that Mrs. Clinton was involved in the
Livingstone hiring in any way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
