<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9128 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-R-RUSSIA-PRESS-ART-2T     03-16 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-RUSSIA-PRESS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RUSSIA'S REGIONAL PRESS, MORE FREEDOM OR NEW POLITICAL
ALLEGIANCE? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add art note)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT41 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARTYOM, Russia _ The most autocratic governor on Russia's
Pacific Rim received a particularly warm birthday greeting in
February: heads of the regional press gathered to give him a cake
in the shape of his fief and offered up a specially composed ditty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Volodya, what a friend, your opposition is at the end,''
the editors congratulated Yevgeny Nazdratenko, the governor of the
Primorye, or Maritime, region.
</P>
<P>
   These days, that kind of press praise for the men who rule
Russia's regions is hardly unique. From Pskov on Russia's western
border to here, on its eastern frontier, Russia's regional
newspapers are increasingly under the thumb of local authorities.
</P>
<P>
   This has not escaped the attention of Acting President Vladimir
Putin, a passionate advocate of building a strong federal state in
a Russia whose vast and distant lands have slipped from the
near-ironclad authority that Moscow enjoyed in Soviet times.
</P>
<P>
   One of Putin's first decrees as acting president authorizes
federal subsidies to 2,500 local newspapers, including 19
provincial newspapers here in Primorye. More than $6 million in
subsidies are planned for this year.
</P>
<P>
   The president's men insist he is striking a blow for press
freedom. But critics say the unspoken agenda is to shift the
allegiance of the regional press from the regional overlords to
Putin, the overwhelming favorite to win the March 26 presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
   In Artyom, a downtrodden town with sporadic heat and no hot
water, a top editor of Vybor, a local weekly, is not troubled by
the moral debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're backing Putin,'' said Lyubov Vozian, the deputy editor
of the cash-poor paper, cheerfully. ``We want the money.''
</P>
<P>
   With its smattering of small-town news, paid political ads and
television listings, Vybor could never be mistaken for one of the
nation's leading newspapers. A six-month subscription to the
eight-page weekly costs 36 rubles (about $1.25).
</P>
<P>
   But provincial newspapers like this have become increasingly
important because they are the only publications that millions of
Russians read.
</P>
<P>
   Major national newspapers like Izvestia may influence the
chattering classes in Moscow, seven times zones west of Artyom.
Outside Moscow, many Russians consider such papers an unnecessary
luxury.
</P>
<P>
   Izvestia, for example, had a circulation of more than 6 million
when it was a propaganda organ for the Soviet state. These days,
Izvestia's circulation is 262,000. Fewer than 2,000 of those copies
are sold here in Primorye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago, most families read two, three or four
newspapers,'' said Vladimir G. Ostrovsky, the deputy editor of
Vladivostok, the region's most established local newspaper. ``Most
families now read one newspaper at most. It has to be cheap and it
has to have the television listings.''
</P>
<P>
   With major Moscow-based advertisers reluctant to include the
poorer provinces in their publicity campaigns, and with publication
costs rising steadily, the regional press has become increasingly
dependent on the good will and financial backing of local
politicians. These patrons expect a high degree of political
loyalty in return.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the Primorye region has been no easy place to
practice journalism. After a brief moment of freedom following the
collapse of the Soviet Union, Nazdratenko came to power in 1992.
Like many other regional leaders who slipped from the Kremlin's
grasp and reached various accommodations with Moscow in exchange
for local power, he turned the region into his political fief.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are really only two political parties here: the governor
and the opposition,'' said Marina Loboda, a Vladivostok-based
reporter for Moskovsky Komsomolets, the national tabloid. ``All the
other political parties live in Moscow.''
</P>
<P>
   Editors say the authorities have several ways to keep the press
in line. They can encourage Russian and foreign companies to
advertise in their favored newspapers. They can evict news
organizations from government-owned buildings or pressure private
landlords to evict troublesome news bureaus. They can file lawsuit
after lawsuit to keep the editors in court or force them to pay
fines.
</P>
<P>
   In Vladivostok, the region's main printing press is owned by the
federal government, but Nazdratenko has been lobbying hard to gain
control. Local editors say that the governor already has
considerable influence at the plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to government regulations, we have to have a month's
reserve of paper on hand,'' Ostrovsky said. ``But nobody can afford
to do that. So it is a lever that can be used at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In extreme cases, rebellious editors or broadcasters have been
threatened or roughed up, although aides to Nazdratenko deny that
they had anything to do with such attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the press, however, needs no coercion, as Nazdratenko's
birthday bash made plain.
</P>
<P>
   After presenting the congratulatory ditty, the journalists gave
him small gifts, including a dartboard with a picture of Anatoly
Chubais, the self-styled reformer and one of the governor's
political nemeses.
</P>
<P>
   The private event was filmed by the governor's television
station, OTV PRIM, as a memento of the occasion, but a tape was
leaked to NTV, Russia's only independent television network. ``The
press really demonstrated what it has become,'' said Andrei
Kalachinsky, who runs the Vladivostok office of the National Press
Institute, a nongovernmental group that is trying to encourage a
free press. ``They came and bowed to the feet of the governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Sergei Manin, an executive at Artyom's municipal television
station, said the journalists' sentiments were heartfelt. ``The
media expressed its feelings quite sincerely,'' Manin said. ``And
the guy who leaked the tape was fired.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As in many other regions across Russia, even those local
journalists less enamored of Nazdratenko are not always
independent. Also lacking resources to publish or broadcast, they
often receive financial support from the governor's political
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, federal officials say the subservience of the
regional news media is a serious and growing problem. To combat it,
the Russian Press Ministry has already begun to carry out Putin's
decree authorizing subsidies, which officials say are intended to
defray printing and production costs and help the newspapers become
more profitable. The subsidies average $1,500 a month, a
considerable sum for a provincial newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the newspapers to reflect reality and not the point of
view of a governor,'' said Vladimir V. Grigoryev, the deputy
minister of Russia's press ministry. ``This will help develop a
real media market where newspapers can be bought and sold. It will
probably help us have a freer press.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics assert that if the Russian government wanted a free
press, it would grant new tax breaks to all news media, not
distribute subsidies to a favored group.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an attempt to influence the content of newspapers and
make them more dependent on federal authorities,'' said Andrei G.
Richter, director of the Media Law and Policy Center at Moscow
University.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Artyom, a city of 114,000 people, the editors of Vybor do not
even dream about total independence. The paper, as they see it,
needs the support of the governor to keep the city's mayor in check
and the backing of the president to counterbalance the governor. It
is a recipe for survival, not autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   But even survival is not easy. Vybor is formally owned by the
local administration, a legacy from Soviet times. The city
administration has not provided any money to the newspaper in more
than a year, and the relationship between the editors and the mayor
is sour.
</P>
<P>
   After Vybor reported about unheated apartment houses and a
paralyzing bus strike, the mayor's office demanded a letter laying
out the evidence. More worrisome, the mayor announced a plan to
take direct control of the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to survive and worried about the mayor's designs, Vybor's
editors turned to Nazdratenko, whose office already provides a
modest subsidy to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Vybor, in turn, publishes the glowing accounts that the
governor's aides prepare about his activities. To facilitate the
process, the regional government gave Vybor a fax machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We publish lots of news about the governor's good deeds,''
Vozian, the deputy editor, said brightly. ``He supports us.''
</P>
<P>
   But Vybor would embrace additional allies, particularly in the
Kremlin. The editors were pleased that their weekly is one of 19
provincial newspapers the Russian press ministry is planning to
support in Primorye.
</P>
<P>
   Vozian said that federal officials had promised the newspaper an
initial payment of 60,000 rubles (about $2,100) in exchange for
Vybor's support for Putin's election. The newspaper has not
received the money, but she remains hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, we're supporting Putin,'' she said. ``We want to be
independent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 2104EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
