<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9131 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-INDIAHOTEL-CLINTON17-     03-16 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIAHOTEL-CLINTON17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hotel readies for Clinton's visit to India
 &HT;    By Moni Basu
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Manorama Patra is worried about the
canary-yellow blooms lining the entrance to the Maurya Sheraton
hotel. The annuals are at the end of their season and she is hoping
they will hold on until Sunday when President Clinton arrives in
New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see, these flowers are at the end of their life. They are
already seeding,'' said Patra, the environmental chairwoman for the
Maurya, one of Delhi's best luxury hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Patra also has been given the task of supplying flowers for
Clinton's Maurya suite, named after a powerful fourth century Hindu
king. ``We've been told not to place flowers with a lot of
pollen,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While Patra instructs her staff of 22 gardeners on how to spruce
up the front lawns, an even bigger staff is working around the
clock to get ready for the visit by the U.S. president, the first
since Jimmy Carter's trip in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Work crews are polishing thousands of square feet of marble
floors and cleaning wall-to-wall windows.
</P>
<P>
   When an unexpected afternoon storm descends, managers start to
panic. ``Don't just stand there. Cover the glass outside,'' one
shouts to his staff.
</P>
<P>
   The Maurya is accustomed to high-powered clientele, but the
White House has booked the entire hotel for Clinton and his
traveling staff. ``Yes, that is very unusual,'' Patra said.
</P>
<P>
   One week before the president's arrival, Secret Service
personnel and U.S. Embassy staff members were milling around the
vast halls of the Maurya and meeting with hotel managers every day.
</P>
<P>
   But security is the last thing on the minds of the Maurya's many
shopkeepers, who are eager to do a lot of business next week.
</P>
<P>
   Lucrative Commercial Private Ltd. has doubled its stock of
Indian jewelry and curios and is busy installing new track lighting
so the president and his staff can see the goods better. ``We're
expecting a big business boom,'' manager Shailesh Jain said.
</P>
<P>
   But no one is more excited about Clinton's visit than Saboor
Wangnoo and his staff at National Cottage Emporium, a Kashmiri
crafts shop. It was from Wangnoo's store that Hillary Rodham
Clinton purchased a chain-stitched rug for the White House and a
gift for the president when the first lady and daughter Chelsea
visited India in 1995. Manager Abdul Majid pulls out an album
filled with pictures of that visit that he received from the White
House. He points to framed letters written by Bill and Hillary
Clinton thanking him for the purchases. The letters are Wangnoo's
pride and joy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am really looking forward to saying hello to Mr. Clinton.
Mrs. Clinton had promised he would come into my store,'' said
Wangnoo, adding that he has saved a special rug to show the
president. The chain-stitched carpet has 1290 knots per inch and
took 2 1/2 years to make, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In between talking about the lucrative business possibilities
that are ahead for his shop, Majid is asked whether all this effort
to please the American president will help bring peace to his
war-torn homeland. The territorial dispute with rival nuclear power
Pakistan over Kashmir and other tensions are high on the Clinton
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Majid, surrounded by his pashmina shawls and hand-woven carpets,
thinks for a moment and quietly says, ``God willing.''
</P>
