<HEADLINE>
THE MOVING AVERAGE RUNS INTO A WALL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 19) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic of total return on technical buy and sell signs
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By MARK HULBERT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most investors are probably unaware of one of the great unsolved
mysteries of the last decade: the breakdown of many technical
approaches to stock-picking _ strategies that had been successful
for decades.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, not all such systems stopped working in the early
'90s. After all, there are an incredibly large number of them,
since technical analysis encompasses any approach that focuses
exclusively on the price histories of stocks. But some of the
simplest, most popular varieties did fall apart.
</P>
<P>
   Among the best known is a strategy based on moving averages _
one that advises buying stocks whenever the market is trading above
its average level over the previous few weeks or months, then turns
bearish if the market starts trading below that average.
</P>
<P>
   There are many variations, depending on the period on which the
average is based. But researchers found that almost any period
between two months and a year proved equally profitable over the
long term.
</P>
<P>
   Consider how well one such strategy _ using a 150-day moving
average _ performed when applied to the Dow Jones industrials over
a very long stretch, from 1897 to 1986. According to three
professors _ William Brock of the University of Wisconsin at
Madison, Blake LeBaron of Brandeis University and Josef Lakonishok
of the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign _ the system beat
a simple investment in the Dow Jones industrials by an average of 7
percentage points a year. That difference is especially striking in
that an investor using the system would have been invested in
stocks only 60 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1990s, by contrast, this strategy's performance was,
well, awful. For the 11 years from January 1988 through February
1999, according to recent follow-up research conducted by LeBaron,
the system lagged behind the Dow by an average of 2.3 percentage
points a year.
</P>
<P>
   Newsletters that use moving average systems have seen similar
reversals. From 1980 to 1989, for example, the market-timing advice
of the Fabian Premium Investment Resource _ which uses a 39-week
moving average and is probably the best known of the lot _ beat the
Wilshire 5000 index by 2.1 percentage points annually, on average.
From 1990 to 1999, it lagged behind the market by 3.7 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   But the plot thickens. Beginning in the early 1990s, the use of
technical trading systems in other kinds of markets also began to
fail. Simple moving-average strategies had also been profitable,
for example, when applied to foreign-exchange markets for the two
decades through the late 1980s. If the dollar was trading above,
say, its 30-day moving average compared with the Japanese yen, that
amounted to a buy signal. But according to LeBaron, such systems
also stopped working in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Or consider a strategy called pairs trading, which focuses on
divergences in pairs of stocks that typically move in tandem. For
at least two decades through the late 1980s, such divergences soon
reversed themselves, making it profitable to buy the stock that
underperformed its partner while shorting the other, according to
William N. Goetzmann, a finance professor at the Yale School of
Management. Starting in the early 1990s, however, the strategy
declined in profitability and then began posting frequent losses.
</P>
<P>
   A large part of the failure of such approaches likely has to do
with increasing market efficiency. Investors in the 1990s witnessed
the growth of two important forces: personal computers and discount
brokerage commissions. The PC lets individual investors learn about
and act quickly upon statistical patterns in price and volume data
_ information that previously could have been known only by large
firms with supercomputers. Cheap trading, particularly online, has
let investors exploit technical strategies far more easily.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, as more and more investors try their hands at
technical analysis, trying to take advantage of pricing anomalies,
the anomalies evaporate and the strategy loses its advantage. That
is market efficiency at work. Think about that the next time you
read about such an approach in your favorite chat room. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hulbert is editor of The Hulbert Financial Digest, a
newsletter based in Annandale, Va. His column on investment
strategies appears every other week. E-mail:
strategy(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
