<HEADER>
A9138 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-GUNS-LAPIERRE-ART-2TA     03-16 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-LAPIERRE-ART-2TAKES(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR OF WORDS BETWEEN CLINTON AND NRA MAKES GOP LEADERS UNEASY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla., N.Y., Utah, Texas, Ill.)  (See also GORE) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By JAMES DAO and MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A growing number of prominent Republican officials
say they feel deeply uncomfortable with the harsh battle of words
pitting President Clinton against the National Rifle Association,
and, as a result, have begun urging passage of long-stalled
gun-control legislation in Congress this year.
</P>
<P>
   A number of Republicans who have strongly opposed strict
gun-control efforts in the past _ including Rep. J.C. Watts of
Oklahoma, who has appeared in ads for the National Rifle
Association, and Rep. Sue Kelly of New York _ have joined the call
for Congress to move on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   But there were no signs Thursday that either those efforts or
the statements this week by two leading Republican governors,
George W. Bush of Texas and George Pataki of New York, supporting
some gun-control measures were having any effect on Republicans who
control the fate of the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, aides to Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah, chairman of the
Judiciary Committee, and Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the House
majority whip, accused Democrats of playing politics with the
issue, adding that they saw no reason at present to move the
bottled-up bill.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the rifle association also said Thursday that they
had no plans to tone down their attacks on Clinton. They said the
fierce back-and-forth has resulted in a surge in the organization's
membership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Folks have been saying outrageous things about NRA members for
years,'' said a spokesman, Bill Powers. ``People say we're an evil
empire, and they don't bat an eye. We view this as an opportunity
to point out what we truly believe. If it requires some degree of
provocativeness, the issue is important enough for that.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the association's executive vice president, Wayne
LaPierre, said that Clinton had blood ``on his hands'' for
advocating new gun restrictions instead of enforcing existing laws.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that the president bore responsibility for the
shooting death of the former basketball coach of Northwestern
University, Ricky Byrdsong, who was killed last year with an gun
purchased from an unlicensed gun dealer.
</P>
<P>
   A White House spokesman, Joe Lockhart, called LaPierre's
comments ``sick rhetoric.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just when you think a human being couldn't go any lower, Wayne
LaPierre and the NRA found a way yesterday by saying that the blood
of Ricky Byrdsong is on the president's hands,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a number of Republican officials who have been
allies with the rifle association distanced themselves from
LaPierre's remarks, including Bush, the Republican's presumptive
nominee for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a way to debate the issue without casting aspersions
on the president like this,'' Bush said at a news conference
Thursday in Springfield, Ill. ``I think they've gone too far with
that statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Several leading Republicans in Congress also expressed dismay
with the intensity of the attacks between Clinton and the NRA. But
while they stopped short of condemning LaPierre, those Republicans
said they have begun urging their leadership to move forward with
negotiations on the stalled gun-control bill, which includes
provision requiring trigger locks on new guns and background checks
for people who buy firearms at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   A Democratic version of the gun-show bill passed in the Senate
last year as part of a broader juvenile justice bill. But the House
passed its juvenile justice bill without any gun-control
provisions. The differences must now be resolved by a joint
House-Senate conference committee, which has met only once since
last summer.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has called on Congress to pass gun-control
legislation before April 20, the one-year anniversary of the
shootings at Columbine High School outside Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clock is ticking, and America is waiting to see whether
Congress can really produce a bill that responds to the interests
of our children and not the intimidation of the NRA,'' he said
Thursday at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Watts, the House conference chairman, the No. 4 post in the
Republican leadership, said through a spokesman that he opposed the
gun measures backed by Clinton but agreed with him that the
conference committee should convene.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like for the viciousness to stop on both sides,'' said
Watts spokesman Bill Shapard. ``We want to talk about issues. We
think we will win the battle in conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Watts was one of more than 40 Republicans who voted for a
non-binding resolution on Wednesday urging the House-Senator
negotiators to meet.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, who has voted with the House Republican leadership
against gun-control bills in the past, also voted for the
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's safe to say that there is a lot of rhetoric on both sides
that we can do without,'' said Rob Ostrander, Kelly's spokesman.
``But the bottom line is, she feels that that should be set aside,
and that a middle ground can be found.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it will take considerable movement for legislation to
emerge from a conference committee, some lawmakers said they
believed a compromise could be reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a former judge that used to bring parties together in
settlement conferences, I'd say we're kind of close on this, and we
ought to be able to resolve it,'' said Rep. James Rogan, R-Calif.
``Why is there the vitriolic name-calling and bloody shirt-waving
on both sides?''
</P>
<P>
   The advisory resolution that passed the House on Wednesday took
no position on gun control. It merely urged conferees to meet
within the next two weeks to discuss the gun legislation. But the
NRA opposed the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason to force a deadline other than to allow
political grandstanding on issues that members are already trying
to resolve in good faith,'' the gun association said in a memo
circulated among lawmakers before the vote.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations have stalled over details of the measure. The House
Democratic leadership supports a version giving law enforcement
officials three business days to complete a background check; many
House Republicans support a 24-hour limit on such checks.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials asserted that Wednesday's non-binding vote
showed that Republicans are feeling pressure to enact some gun
legislation this year, whether to answer concerns from their own
constituencies or to help insulate Bush from charges that he is
beholden to the rifle association.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that that at least some Republicans feel that allowing
the gun lobby to determine the congressional schedule is too great
a burden for them to carry,'' said Sen. Patrick Leahy of Vermont,
the ranking Democrat on the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans said the vote was meaningless, and they accused
the House Democratic leader, Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, of
playing politics with the gun-show bill. They asserted that
Gephardt does not want any bill to pass so that the Democrats can
hammer Republicans with the issue in the fall elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gephardt has laid down the gauntlet,'' said Tony Rudy, a
spokesman for Rep. Tom Delay, the Republican whip. ``He's saying
there's no room for compromise. What he wants us to do is come out
with a bill that won't pass.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
