<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BUCHANAN WRAPS HIMSELF IN McCAIN'S FLAG OF REFORM  
(sw) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Grafting onto the lesson of the presidential
primary contests, Pat Buchanan on Thursday unveiled a retooled
stump speech for his lagging third-party candidacy, packing this
year's politically magic phrase ``campaign reform'' into its every
jot and tittle.
</P>
<P>
   Conceding the losing insurgent effort of Sen. John McCain had
made campaign reform ``the only real issue'' in this presidential
year, Buchanan tailored his remarks to that cause as he took his
quest for the Reform Party nomination to Harvard University and
accused the two major parties of huge fund-raising abuses in ``an
incumbents protection racket.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Beltway parties are chemically dependent on soft money,''
Buchanan told an overflow crowd of more than 300 at the John F.
Kennedy School of Government in a speech starkly different from the
``pitchfork brigade'' orations of past campaigns. ``We get no soft
money and we take no PAC money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither Beltway party is going to drain this swamp: it's a
protected wetland; they breed in it, they spawn in it,'' Buchanan
added, sparking general laughter and applause. He even updated his
stump graphics with a giant mock check at his side made out for
hundreds of millions of dollars to the major parties and endorsed
by ``Influence Peddlers.''
</P>
<P>
   With his candidacy in the doldrums for months, Buchanan, a
turncoat Republican, clearly sought to tap into the public appetite
for the campaign reform issue that McCain galvanized in his losing
challenge to Gov. George W. Bush for the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But during Buchanan's one-hour appearance, students accused him
of exploiting some controversial racial and political views in his
chronic presidential candidacy. One student accused him of
``selling out'' his one political virtue, consistency, in jumping
to the Reform line. Another, identifying himself as a rare
conservative Republican at the Kennedy school, caustically
declared, ``Thank you for leaving the party.''
</P>
<P>
   But Buchanan gave as good as he got, at one point defending his
controversial accusation that Harvard employs elitist quotas
favoring groups like Jewish- and Asian-American students at the
expense of the nation's white Christian majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply because you're at Harvard does not exempt you from the
same kind of rules and regulations that Harvard lovingly imposes
upon the rest of America,'' he shot back at one critic. ``Pat
Buchanan is not a beloved figure in America, but neither is
Harvard.''
</P>
<P>
   To another questioner, Buchanan conceded the ``risk'' that he
might ultimately succeed only in playing the spoiler's role and
drain enough votes from the Republican line to help Vice President
Al Gore be elected. In the view of some political specialists,
Buchanan's current standing of about 6 percent in the polls might
be enough in a close race to foil Bush. The Reform line created by
Ross Perot drew 19 percent of the vote in 1992 and saw President
George Bush defeated by Bill Clinton by a plurality.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his remarks, Buchanan made clear his determination to
stay in the race and fight for an equal spotlight in this fall's
televised presidential debates. He said he expected the major
parties to try to block this and that he was preparing a lawsuit to
challenge for debating time if, as he expects, he wins the Reform
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have ruined the conservative cause,'' he declared in
criticizing current Republican leaders and rebutting a questioner
who called him ``a reactionary in reformer's clothing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last seven years they conflated the conservative cause
with Clinton bashing,'' Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   Framing his speech as a detailed cry for reform, Buchanan called
for a ban on soft money and the creation of a national initiative
and referendum process to let voters directly change the system. He
also urged the imposition of term limits on Congress, a body he
described as so beholden to big-money donors that it has become the
nation's ``bellhop stand for the business roundtable.''
</P>
<P>
   In sum, Buchanan packed the Kennedy school forum with the same
heady mix of political iconoclasm and personal controversy that was
his stump signature in 1992 and 1996, when he drew early primary
support but failed to win the Republican nomination. His quest this
time, in which he has said he will fight Perot if the Texas
billionaire runs again, is complicated by the need to build
political organizations in most of the 29 states where the Reform
party does not exist.
</P>
<P>
   Students questioned how the Reform party, which in the past
shied from social and cultural issues, might ever embrace Buchanan,
whose opposition to abortion has been his political keystone. The
candidate replied that he had not altered his views but, rather
than feature them in the Reform platform, he would ``append'' them
to the platform as a personal statement.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan drew strong applause at the close of a performance in
which he handled even a lampoon touch when a young man beamed and
asked him out on a date.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shelly, would it be okay?'' Buchanan asked, turning to his
wife with a big grin. Then the candidate guffawed as he told the
audience, ``She said it would be okay!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
