<SLUG> BC-BKC-SOUTH-UCONN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S THAT TIME OF YEAR FOR BAFFLING UCONN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ The Connecticut Huskies suffer from an
identity crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The defending national champions began this season as the
country's consensus No. 1. The Huskies won 10 of their first 11
games and sent Duke and Arizona to the canvas in the process, but
``we were a team still trying to find itself,'' coach Jim Calhoun
said.
</P>
<P>
   That search continues, four months later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really hasn't been a difficult team to coach,'' said
Calhoun, whose fifth-seeded Huskies (24-9) will oppose 12th-seeded
Utah State (28-5) at 1:50 p.m. Friday at Birmingham-Jefferson Civic
Center in the NCAA South Region.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just been difficult to convince them that what you are is
really good. Accept that. Don't fight to be something you were. Try
to be what you are. That's been our biggest fight all year.''
</P>
<P>
   That conflict could be near an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have the type of all-star season that everyone
thought we were going to have or the type of season that we had
last year,'' point guard Khalid El-Amin said. ``We didn't have one
of those seasons this year. We've at times had to grind out wins,
and sometimes we've gotten beaten in games that we shouldn't have
gotten beaten.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the thing about this team now is it really knows
about this tournament, knows what to do and knows how to win. So, I
feel very good about this team and its chances.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies built much-needed momentum for their title defense
with victories in six of their final seven games. St. John's
supplied the lone blemish with an 80-70 victory Saturday during the
Big East Conference championship game, but it appears Connecticut
now realizes that it is the ``defending'' national champion and not
``the'' national champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we could be and maybe will be as good as last year's
team if we play to our strengths as opposed to try to be something
we were,'' Calhoun said. ``Please don't think I don't believe we're
a good team. I think we're a very good team.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1998-99 Huskies went beyond being very good with 34
victories and a national title with Richard Hamilton, Ricky Moore
and Rashamel Jones supplying the firepower and will.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, those Huskies struggled, too, Calhoun said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just didn't notice last year when we struggled a little
bit in February because we were so good,'' Calhoun said. ``This
year when we didn't play quite as well or those (other) teams
played well, we didn't quite get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the Huskies lost nine times this season and is
``very underrated,'' El-Amin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get beat in order for us not to be the defending
national champions, and I feel like this team really knows how to
win _ especially at this time of year,'' El-Amin said. ``This is
the time of year that really counts the most. So, I do feel like
we're the defending national champions. We just have to go out and
play like it.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 2124EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
