u s BC-HKN-DEVILS-SALE-660(2     03-16 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-SALE-660(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS SOLD FOR $175 MILLION TO YANKEENETS' UNIT
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   John McMullen's reign as the owner of the New Jersey Devils
ended Thursday with the sale of his team to a YankeeNets' affiliate
for $175 million, a nearly sixfold gain on the $30 million he paid
for the erstwhile Colorado Rockies 18 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which is set to close in July, includes a $1 million
bonus if the Devils win the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of the Devils was a crucial component in the
YankeeNets' plan to build a $295 million arena in downtown Newark
and provides additional programming for the company's proposed
regional cable sports and entertainment channel.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of the Devils leaves the Islanders and Mets as the only
local professional teams that are the subject of sales
negotiations. The Yankees and Nets merged late last year. Robert
Wood Johnson IV paid $635 million for the Jets in January.
</P>
<P>
   Cablevision remains interested in adding the Mets to its
portfolio, with the Knicks and Rangers, but talks have slowed to a
crawl. And the proposed $180 million sale of the Islanders is
stalled.
</P>
<P>
   The push to buy the Devils began soon after the Yankees-Nets
merger. The new entity, known as the YankeeNets, offered $175
million, and McMullen did not argue with its generosity.
</P>
<P>
   The definitive agreement signed Thursday was technically with
Puck Holdings, whose principal investors are Raymond Chambers and
Lewis Katz of Nets Holdings. The Nets paid $225 million to become
equal partners in YankeeNets. Chambers and Katz sit on the
YankeeNets board.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're fronting the purchase and starting the process of
bringing in other investors,'' Harvey Schiller, chairman of the
YankeeNets, said. ``Then the intent is to bring the YankeeNets in
as general partner. But right now there is no liability on the
YankeeNets' side.''
</P>
<P>
   Chambers and Katz are making the initial payments because of the
Devils' important role in building the Newark arena _ and because
the YankeeNets raised their debt load by $200 million last week
with a sale of junk bonds.
</P>
<P>
   With two teams, the Nets and Devils, playing at least 82 dates
per season, bank financing for a new arena would be easier and the
chances of profitability would increase.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman has said that state aid of about $75
million for infrastructure needed to build a new arena hinged on
the presence of two teams.
</P>
<P>
   Pete McDonough, a spokesman for Whitman, said that ``now that
the Devils and Nets are joined at the hip,'' any threat of either
team leaving New Jersey is gone and that the location they choose
for a new arena would carry a lot of weight. But he cautioned that
any state assistance would go toward bricks and mortar, ``not to
underwrite the purchase price of the two franchises.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Sharpe James of Newark said, ``We owe it to these two
teams to give them the financial support they need.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeting Whitman's mandate for two teams in a new arena doomed
McMullen's dream of building an arena for the Devils in Hoboken.
Last month, Whitman told McMullen that she would not grant him and
his partner, Cablevision Systems, the air rights to build a
proposed arena over New Jersey Transit tracks in Hoboken.
</P>
<P>
   McMullen said Whitman's lack of support for his plan made
selling the Devils unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terrible,'' he said. ``This is the 19th season. We built
an outstanding franchise for the state of New Jersey and it's so
disappointing not to be appreciated. I was offering to build an
arena without using any taxpayer money. The governor disappointed
me.''
</P>
<P>
   McMullen signed a 12-year lease in 1995 to keep the Devils at
Continental Airlines Arena, rather than move to Nashville. But he
said, ``Under the lease, there's no future. Our costs aren't going
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Schiller said one of his short-term goals is to negotiate better
terms on the Devils' and Nets' leases in the Meadowlands. The
Devils' lease expires after the 2006-07 season. The Nets' lease
ends in 2008, but they can move without penalty after the 2003-04
season.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Dan Emmer, a spokesman for the New Jersey Sports and Exposition
Authority, would not discuss a possible renegotiation. But he said
he hoped the YankeeNets would be persuaded to stay in the
Meadowlands at a proposed new arena south of Giants Stadium,
instead of moving to Newark.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase puts in doubt the future of Lou Lamoriello, the
Devils' president and general manager. One of the most respected
general managers in hockey, he has fashioned successful teams
without bankrupting McMullen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a free agent,'' McMullen said. ``He's never had a
contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Schiller said there had not been any discussions with
Lamoriello. But he added, ``Our interest is to do what we can to
keep him on board.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Lou's done a great job. He's sitting there with
salaries that are 50 percent lower than other teams. He's got a
great scouting staff and he's done it very efficiently.'' The
Devils' player payroll is $37.6 million, compared to the Rangers'
$61.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   McMullen said Lamoriello owns less than the 20 percent of the
team he has been reported to hold. ``He's in the same category with
my children, so he shares equally with them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lamoriello did not want to discuss his plans. ``I will sit down
and talk with the new owners at their discretion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would consider running the Rangers, he said,
``That's the first time I heard that. I have no comments on
anything of that nature right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The amassing of three teams is part of the YankeeNets' plan to
build a regional cable network with Cablevision, Time Warner or
other possible partners. The cable broadcasts of all three teams'
games are on Cablevision-run affiliates: the Yankees on the MSG
Network, the Devils and the Nets on Fox Sports New York.
</P>
<P>
   If the YankeeNets create a network with Cablevision, all three
teams could be on the outlet before their existing deals expire.
</P>
<P>
   But if the YankeeNets form a network with another partner, a
three-team channel would take longer to assemble. The Yankees'
cable deal ends after this season, the Nets' in 2002 and the
Devils' in 2007.
</P>
<P>
   McMullen has a history with the Yankees, one that produced a
memorable and frequently quoted line. He was once a small investor
in the Yankees, but the 81-year-old former Navy commander and
shipping magnate became frustrated in a supporting role to George
Steinbrenner, the principal owner. ``There's nothing more
limited,'' he said, ``than a limited partner of the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, when he signed a lease with an escape clause if the
Yankees moved to New Jersey, he said, ``I'll do everything I
possibly can, within the agreement, to keep the Yankees from coming
to New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees did not come to New Jersey. But the YankeeNets did.
And McMullen's team will soon belong, in part, to George
Steinbrenner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
