<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9151 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-PRIMARIES-NYT &LR;      03-16 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-PRIMARIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER VICTORIES, BUSH MUST WIN OVER THOSE WHO SEE HIM AS WEAKENED 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BUSH-MCCAIN) 
(sw) 
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, far from being
weakened by a tough primary season, was fortunate to have some
inevitable problems disclosed sooner rather than later, in the view
of Republicans who wish him well.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue now is whether Bush will be able to profit from
the opportunity to prove he is ready for the fall campaign. Some
governors before him, including Jimmy Carter and Michael Dukakis
overcame both real difficulties and Washington mockery, and then
behaved as though that proved they knew everything they needed to
know about politics.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's intermittently dismissive tone toward Sen. John McCain in
an interview on Wednesday suggested he has at least a mild dose of
that nomination hubris. But the actions of aides reaching out to
various Washington Republicans suggest a far more unifying
approach.
</P>
<P>
   Winning over McCain, and especially his followers, is only one
of the issues that Bush faces after his victories on Tuesday, when
he came well within range of having the delegates to be nominated.
</P>
<P>
   But many in the capital who once assumed his nomination and
election to be foreordained seem to see Bush's experiences in the
primaries only as problems and to conclude that the primaries
weakened Bush and strengthened Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   On one dimension, it is obviously true. Polls that showed Bush
with leads of up to 20 percentage points over Gore last fall now
show them more or less even. Some have Gore slightly ahead.
</P>
<P>
   And Gore is plainly stronger, having slimmed his campaign,
stayed on message with mind-numbing persistence and worked hard to
win every primary and caucus, defeating both Bill Bradley and
Washington's image of him as a loser.
</P>
<P>
   But the part about Bush's being weaker depends, beyond the
numbers, on some pretty facile arguments. They go this way: that
the primaries hurt Bush by opening up divisions in the Republican
Party, tying him to its right wing, denting his shiny image and
exposing him, in the word of one Gore enthusiast, as an uninformed
and inarticulate ``stumblebum.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   For example, it is clear that Bush does not have a glass jaw.
John McCain knocked him down in New Hampshire, he battered McCain
in South Carolina, then McCain slammed him in Michigan. Then Bush
won the nomination, coast to coast, on the first two Tuesdays of
March.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush had won as easily as many had expected, he would still
have been vulnerable as a candidate who was anointed by
fellow-governors and members of Congress, and then, after winning
last summer's checkbook primary, was handed the nomination. In
reality, Bush fought hard, perhaps even dirty, but got nothing on a
silver platter.
</P>
<P>
   One serious problem the primaries revealed was Bush's need, in
the words of Stuart Spencer, a veteran Republican consultant, to
``get a little more savvy on some of the issues.'' Publicly, some
Bush aides dismiss this problem as one that only reporters care
about, citing a recent Gallup Poll in which 70 percent of the
public (compared with 77 percent for Gore) said he had enough
knowledge to be president.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to imagine that the problem would have cured itself,
and the jokes from Jay Leno and David Letterman would have
disappeared if only John McCain had not been around. And the first
debate with Gore would be a poor occasion for Bush to reveal that
he did not know the name of the prime minister of Canada, or that
he wanted to ``use our technologies to enhance uncertainties
abroad.'' Or, as an advocate of improved education, to observe,
``Rarely is the question asked: Is our children learning?''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Bush and his handlers say, they now have several months
to train their candidate to avoid seeming ignorant or stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Two developments in the primaries that are widely described as
Bush setbacks were his visit to Bob Jones University and his
reliance on the help of Pat Robertson. Gore partisans chortle that
it will now be easy for them to portray Bush as a tool of the
religious right. (Not that they weren't planning to do so anyway.)
</P>
<P>
   It is an opening, to be sure. But its effectiveness will depend
on what Bush seems like in the fall; in short, on whether he can
recapture the compassionate image that was his initial emphasis in
the race. Ralph Reed, a major Bush backer, argues that polls show
that Bush is still ``viewed as a new and different kind of
Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, when Bush defended Robertson and Jerry Falwell against
McCain's attacks, he gave the Christian conservatives a reason to
vote for him. He had their leaders' endorsements early on, but
there had been serious doubts about whether he could get the rank
and file. He got them.
</P>
<P>
   As Reed said, ``In what you expect to be a very close election,
the first thing you want is to unify your party and insure that
your base is intact.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, the task is to reach out _ as Bush promised when
he started his campaign. He and his staff know it, and know they
have been diverted by the necessities of winning primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, identifying problems is not solving them. Bush's
verbal difficulties may be incurable.
</P>
<P>
   And on reaching out, there will probably be some heavy-handed,
unconvincing ``Democrats for Bush'' events. On other issues, it is
not clear that the Bush campaign has avoided that pride that has
often infected primary winners.
</P>
<P>
   But some of his perceived wounds are not real, and none are
mortal, whatever the latest public opinion surveys say. It is a
mistake, after all, to lean too much on the world of polls whose
basic question begins with a condition contrary to fact: ``If the
election were held today.''
</P>
<P>
   Those polls, nearly eight months ahead of reality, imply that if
one candidate, like Gore, gets better, Bush must be getting worse.
Both candidates can improve, or get worse, at the same time. Or one
can improve, or get worse, more than the other.
</P>
<P>
   Not until Election Day will the campaign be a zero-sum game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
