<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9153 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BMW-ROVER-OUTLOOK-NYT     03-16 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BMW-ROVER-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROVER DEAL REFLECTS DWINDLING BRITISH BRANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (with BMW-ROVER)  
(bl) 
 By ALAN COWELL with ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ For decades now, the British automotive industry has
been a story of British ownership dwindling as foreigners snapped
up the marques from the proudest Jaguars and Bentleys to the
humblest Mini. Thursday, there were a few extra twists, most
remarkably that a British venture capital company might be paid to
take over this country's most troubled auto plant.
</P>
<P>
   BMW AG, the German automaker that bought Rover Group for $1.2
billion six years ago and has plowed billions more into it since,
moved Thursday to end a disastrous investment that has turned into
a sinkhole.
</P>
<P>
   Rover's money-losing Longbridge plant outside Birmingham in
central England is to be acquired by a British venture capital
company, Alchemy Partners. Rover's sport utility vehicle division
is expected to be purchased by Ford Motor Co.
</P>
<P>
   The twist in the interlocked deal, according to an executive who
knows its broad outlines, was that BMW was ready to ``gift-wrap''
the disposal of the Longbridge plant. Alchemy Partners is pressing
for BMW to pay it up to $1 billion in net assets and a cash
sweetener to take the plant, free of debt.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Alchemy Partners, founded only three years ago by
the British venture capitalist Jon Moulton, has $1.6 billion in
assets under management on behalf of 35 institutional investors
including Goldman, Sachs and Bank of America, a spokesman for the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   Those funds will be directed in part at reducing Longbridge's
work force and possibly disposing of part of the sprawling plant
that German newspapers call ``The English Patient'' because of its
losses and low productivity.
</P>
<P>
   At present, the plant manufactures small and medium-size Rover
25 and 45 models along with a version of the Mini that was set for
replacement. But, within the next few years, Longbridge's run of
mass-market autos bearing the Rover name will end, to be replaced
by what the new owners Thursday called ``a more focused'' plant
manufacturing sporty MG compacts intended to appeal to young
families, as MG itself produced in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to reduce the cost base to a level where the
company generates cash rather than eats it,'' Moulton said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   If that turns a profit, Alchemy will look for the exits,
according to Moulton, who told reporters his investment would span
three to six years. Those exits could include a merger with another
company, a sale or a stock flotation.
</P>
<P>
   The Alchemy spokesman indicated, however, that the new owners of
Longbridge had no plans to spend the kind of money usually
associated with new car models, saying the MG successors to Rovers
would need only ``tens of millions of dollars'' to develop. That
suggested that the staff reductions at Longbridge, which employs
9,000 of Rover's 30,000 people, could be even more severe than
analysts had anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   The looming cuts have angered the government, which stands to be
accused by the opposition Conservatives and by its own supporters
of failing to secure the long-term viability of Longbridge as a
provider of jobs both at the plantt and throughout the West
Midlands region, which is dependent on the automaking industry.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Byers, the trade and industry minister, assailed BMW on
Thursday night, accusing the German company of reneging on a
commitment to maintain its investment in Longbridge in return for
more flexible working hours from auto workers and in return for the
British government's pledge to support the plant with an aid
package.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a real body blow for the people who work at Longbridge
and the people of the West Midlands,'' Byers said. Graffiti sprayed
on the plant tonight accused the German company of betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   Rover will join a tally of names like Morris, Austin, Sunbeam
and Riley winnowed over the years from Britain's showrooms. It is
the end of a long story. Once the chariot of choice for
middle-class Britons eager for leather seats and walnut dashboards
_ but not quite able to afford a Jaguar _ Rover has more recently
been the underdog of the British car market and a sinkhole for BMW
investments totaling $3.4 billion since it bought the group for
$1.2 billion six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Its owners and partners have included the British government,
British Aerospace and Honda prior to BMW. Its cars have
consistently failed to overcome the twin burdens of a strong pound,
which made Rover's exports too expensive for foreign buyers while
permitting its European rivals to import their cars into Britain
more cheaply. And BMW's $1.2 billion of losses at Rover last year
finally annulled a partnership that had once been described as the
biggest and most promising of foreign investments in British
industry.
</P>
<P>
   In extricating itself from a mess that drew in British
politicians and European regulators, BMW could barely have brought
together two more unlikely entities. Alchemy is regarded as a
fast-moving, aggressive firm that sees its niche as taking losers
and turning them into winners. It took its name to make the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's a case of proving the meaning of their name,'' said
Stephen Reitman, an auto industry analyst with Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Moulton, 49, established the company after a long career in
venture capital with firms that included Citicorp and Schroder
Venture. He has been involved in many deals, such as one that
rescued the Parker Pen company and made millions. Since its
founding, Alchemy has been linked to deals on Scottish hotels and
Britain's largest cattle-breeding concern. But it has never been
directly involved in the car business or in a deal of this
magnitude with so much capital and jobs at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Alchemy, said a spokesman for the company, plans to bring in a
management team with automotive expertise to replace the current
top management dominated by BMW executives.
</P>
<P>
   For all that, Longbridge's stubborn labor unions and political
sensitivities, its age as one of Britain's oldest auto plants
dating to 1906, and its persistent productivity problems may be
difficult to turn around. Additionally, with the pound still
strong, the new managers will face some of the same problems as BMW
did.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day,'' said Reitman at Merrill Lynch, ``the
thing that strikes me is that the things that conspired against BMW
aren't going to go away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
