<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON BALKS AT ADDING KOSOVO BATTALION 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO) 
(js) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The top NATO commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, wants
the United States to commit an additional battalion of 700 to 800
soldiers for Kosovo to prevent Albanians from raiding across the
border into Serbia, but the Pentagon has balked at the idea, NATO
and U.S. officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing an erosion of security in Kosovo, Clark has pressed the
NATO allies to increase forces. This week, France and Italy pledged
to add 1,100 soldiers to their forces. Thursday, the NATO secretary
general, George Robertson, said the allies would add troops, if
necessary, to deal with eruptions of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials, however, remain wary of committing more U.S.
troops to the 5,300 there, the officials said. Senior commanders
have asked Clark to provide a more detailed analysis to justify the
need for the added battalion, a process that could take days, a
NATO official said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's request reflects his continuing differences with senior
Pentagon officials over running an operation that has increasingly
struggled to contain clashes between the Serbs and Albanians in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   As violence has flared in the ethnically divided town of
Kosovska-Mitrovica and along Kosovo's southeastern border with
Serbia, Clark has argued for a stronger response from the 33,000
troops on the ground there. On Wednesday, U.S. soldiers raided
villages in southeastern Kosovo, seizing weapons and ammunition
that were evidently being used by Albanian fighters to strike at
Serbs across the border.
</P>
<P>
   Clark requested the added troops this week, the officials said.
One Pentagon official said Clark had not made a formal request.
</P>
<P>
   Clark wants the battalion to increase patrols along the
Kosovo-Serbia border, according to the other officials. He also
requested _ and received approval for _ 50 Army troops to operate a
Hunter unmanned aerial surveillance drone, presumably from
neighboring Macedonia, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's demands for more aggressive action, however, have met
resistance in Washington. When he first asked for up to 1,800
additional NATO troops last month, Pentagon officials said the
European allies should contribute more first.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon announced Thursday that it was sending 1,100
marines to Kosovo for a two-week exercise that will involve 2,000
allied troops. The marines, now on landing ships in the
Mediterranean, are to land in Greece this weekend before moving
overland through Macedonia and into Kosovo. They are widely
expected to stay until the first week of April.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials insisted that the exercise had been planned
months ago and was not related to the Kosovo tensions. But the
aides acknowledged that the rapid deployment of 2,000 troops, part
of the reserve for NATO operations in Kosovo, could demonstrate a
resolve to maintain a secure environment and improve the ability
for rapid reinforcements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
