<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9160 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-ASBESTOS-AGENCY-SPI &LR;      03-16 2348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASBESTOS-AGENCY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINE SAFETY CHIEF VOWS ACTION OVER ASBESTOS DISCLOSURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW SCHNEIDER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Davitt McAteer agonizes over how the federal
government's mine-safety agency failed to prevent hundreds of slow,
painful asbestos-related deaths.
</P>
<P>
   McAteer is not an outside critic. He is the boss of the Mine
Safety and Health Administration, and he backs up his anguish with
a vow: ``I will make damn sure that it doesn't happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   He has launched an aggressive examination of all the mines
across the nation that may be contaminated with asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   An investigation by the Seattle Post-Intelligencer into the
lethal legacy of a vermiculite mine owned by W.R. Grace &AMP; Co. in
Libby, Mont., moved McAteer to search his agency's archives.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper documented that almost 200 miners and members of
their families had died from diseases caused by exposure to
tremolite asbestos fibers, and hundreds more got fatal diseases _
asbestosis, lung cancer and mesothelioma _ from the mine's
asbestos-tainted ore.
</P>
<P>
   The P-I also reported that for decades, government agencies knew
the workers and their families were at risk, but did nothing to
stop it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a hard time believing what I was reading,'' McAteer
says. ``So I had all the reports pulled on Libby and found out it
was true. What I found bothered me a great deal. We could have done
more. We should have done more and we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   His agency, a branch of the Department of Labor, ``failed to
detect, failed to alert, and failed to remedy the situation,'' he
says. ``We can't bring those people back, but we can make changes
in how we operate so we don't have any revelation of preventable
deaths 20 years from now. I want to ensure that this is not still
happening today in any of the mines we're responsible for.''
</P>
<P>
   A remarkable admission
</P>
<P>
   It's extraordinary when a boss of a federal agency admits that
lives could have been saved if the government had done a better
job. There's a lot that's extraordinary about McAteer.
</P>
<P>
   He came into government from the coal fields of West Virginia,
after founding and directing the Occupational Safety and Health Law
Center and working as the Solicitor for Safety for the United Mine
Workers. Before taking over as its chief, he was one of MSHA's
fiercest critics.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders and newspapers in mining country cheered President
Clinton's appointment of McAteer in 1994 as mine-safety boss, but
the industry cringed, lamenting that putting the safety zealot in
charge of keeping miners safe would be like naming Ralph Nader to
head the Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   McAteer, who eagerly accepts responsibility for the well-being
of the nation's 365,000 miners, admits that it's a challenge to
determine how big a health hazard workers face in asbestos-tainted
mines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a hard sell with miners where the asbestos is
a contaminant to their ore,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   For years, many mine operators have told their workers that the
problem existed only at the now-closed Libby mine, that there is no
asbestos in the ore they're mining. But government and
mining-company documents _ some going back 30 years _ indicate that
this may not be true.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the real story of Libby was made public last fall, no
one understood how widespread the potential risks may be,'' McAteer
says. ``It's a difficult message to pass to miners who think
they're healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got get them to understand that just like silica and
coal dust, if asbestos is contaminating the dust that they're
breathing today, it may shorten their lives, may kill them before
they reach the age when they can play with their grandchildren,''
McAteer says.
</P>
<P>
   A career forged by tragedy
</P>
<P>
   A rumbling explosion at Consolidated Coal Company's Number 9
mine, eight miles from his home in Farmington, W. Va., in 1968
shoved McAteer into the world of mine safety.
</P>
<P>
   McAteer, then a law student at West Virginia University, stood a
somber vigil for days with the rest of the small town, watching the
rescue effort, hoping that boys he went to school with, their
fathers and grandfathers would somehow survive. Twenty-one miners
escaped, but 78 were entombed in the deep shafts as the mine was
sealed to halt continuing explosions.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, McAteer hunted down Ralph Nader, whose
reputation as a consumer advocate was spreading, and offered to run
a team of other law students to investigate mine safety in the
state. When McAteer's report was published five years later, West
Virginia passed laws that changed the way mines were regulated.
</P>
<P>
   Now, McAteer is wasting no time getting the asbestos message out
to the mining industry.
</P>
<P>
   Last week,the agency sent out a five-page bulletin to all mine
operators, miners' unions and associations in the country. It
discussed what happened at Libby, explained the hazards of asbestos
and explained how mine operators can protect workers from the
lethal fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Individual pocket safety cards are being printed now to be
distributed to every miner in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Education is vital in a situation like this, but so is
identifying precisely what the hazards are,'' McAteer says.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors dispatched to mines
</P>
<P>
   MSHA has ordered special inspections of all mines where asbestos
may be present in the ore. Testing is being done at vermiculite
mines in Enoree, S.C., Woodruff, S.C., Louisa, Va., and Dillon,
Mont.; at the nation's only two operating asbestos mines near King
City, Calif.; at rock quarries in Sparta, N.J., North Branford,
Conn., and near San Jose, Calif.; at talc mines in Ludlow, Vt., and
Governeur, N.Y.; and at taconite mines in Hoyt Lakes and Silver
Bay, Minn., and two sites in northern Michigan. Several other
operations are on the list to be inspected.
</P>
<P>
   At each mine, the inspectors attached small, portable air pumps
to the workers while they did their normal jobs. Samples of the air
they were working in was drawn through fine filters. The filters
from the vacuum pumps were examined under a microscope at OHSA's
laboratory in Salt Lake City and the fibers of asbestos were
counted.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the initial testing showed levels below MSHA's
permissible exposure limit.
</P>
<P>
   That's not a clean bill of health, as some of the mine operators
boast, McAteer says.
</P>
<P>
   ``These say that the air testing came back below our limit,''
the safety boss says, waving a stack of test results. ``But MSHA's
limit is 20 times higher than OSHA's limit. There could be 20 times
more asbestos fibers in the sample than OSHA's limit and it could
be legal under our regulations. How can we say that's safe?''
</P>
<P>
   A try for safer limits
</P>
<P>
   The exposure standard that MSHA is working under was promulgated
27 years ago. Twelve years later, in 1989, the agency tried to
bring the asbestos exposure limits down to OSHA's safer standards.
</P>
<P>
   As it does every time the government proposes to reduce exposure
to any asbestos fiber, the industry flooded MSHA with opposition to
the agency's proposal. W.R. Grace said there was no need to lower
the permissible exposure limits for vermiculite mines, because it
claimed there was no asbestos in its South Carolina mines.
</P>
<P>
   The Asbestos Information Association, an industry-funded
lobbying group, cited medical studies which they claimed showed the
risk of asbestos exposure from the mines was minimal. But almost
all the studies the association cited were done by physicians and
researchers working on industry-funded projects.
</P>
<P>
   `Our asbestos isn't bad'
</P>
<P>
   ``The efforts to prevent the new standard were pretty much made
by the same people making the same statements they made in
defending Libby,'' McAteer says. ``They said `Our asbestos isn't
bad asbestos.' And, `these fibers are too short or the wrong shape
to be harmful' and `our mining process doesn't result in the kind
of asbestos problems exposure that would cause the disease.'''
</P>
<P>
   Agency files don't show why the effort was dropped in 1989. Now,
MSHA is again developing a proposal for a health standard for
asbestos that would lower the permissible exposure to OHSA's level.
There is little doubt that the opposition will quickly muster
against it once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure we'll being hearing from the industry as soon as the
word gets out,'' says Dr. Carol Jones, director of MSHA's Office of
Standards, who helped OSHA implement its exposure level.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that the miners will be safer if we can
reduce the exposure,'' Jones says. ``When you have a carcinogen
like asbestos, you want to have no exposure at all.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Jones, McAteer and other government experts who fight
to reduce the exposure level do a delicate balancing act _ lower
the standard as far as possible, but keep it high enough so the
mines can still operate.
</P>
<P>
   OSHA's .1 fiber per cubic centimeter of air still permits
exposure that is estimated to cause three or four cases of cancer
for each 1,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go to a level which won't close the mines,'' she
says. ``So that's the reason that .1 fiber still has significant
risk, because we couldn't go any lower, because we couldn't drive
everyone out of business.''
</P>
<P>
   New samples sought
</P>
<P>
   OSHA's level of ``.1'' sounds like a minute amount, but Jones
says that's not the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's 100,000 fibers per cubic meter. We breathe 10 cubic
meters of air in a work day if we're working hard, so that's a
million fibers. And with asbestos, research shows that, in some
cases, just one fiber could get into one cell and cause it to
become a tumor cell. It multiplies and you've got cancer,'' Jones
explains.
</P>
<P>
   McAteer says that last week his inspection teams went back to
the mines to take more air samples as well as samples of ore.
</P>
<P>
   The South Carolina and Virginia vermiculite mines are owned by
Grace and Robert Sansom, a former associate EPA administrator.
Neither take kindly to government prodding too hard into their
operations.
</P>
<P>
   But McAteer says he doesn't expect any problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have authority to take samples when and where we believe
dangerous exposures might exist and that is precisely what our
inspectors will do,'' the administrator says.
</P>
<P>
   `That's why he got the job'
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first time that McAteer stood up to powerful
interests.
</P>
<P>
   The 56-year-old father of five hadn't had time to hang his
mementos of the walls of his new office in 1994 before Republicans
in Congress began clamoring for MSHA to be gutted, its staff cut by
60 percent, if not completely dismantled. But McAteer hung in, and,
in fact, strengthened the agency's watchdog actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why he got the job,'' says former Labor Secretary
Robert Reich, who brought McAteer into the agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Davitt comes from a mining family and he cares deeply and
passionately about what happens in those mines,'' Reich says. ``He
knows more about mining, the technology and the dangers than almost
anyone I've ever encountered.
</P>
<P>
   Reich, who was never shy about expressing his views when he was
labor secretary, cheers McAteer's candor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says what he believes. It's not easy in Washington to tell
it like it is, but if you are telling the truth, giving an accurate
portrayal of reality and you have technical competence on your
side, then you're unassailable. That's the way he operates and he
thrives on challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   McAteer has made the health of miners a prime focus for his
agency, something, he says, that's no easy task.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had an epidemic of safety problems the magnitude of
Libby, with hundreds of miners dying, we'd take some action and do
so immediately,'' McAteer says. ``But with health problems, it
doesn't happen right away and it gets pushed back and pushed back
and pushed back until something forces it to the front again.
Meanwhile, lives that could have been saved have been lost. We
can't let this happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Safety problems, he says, can typically be corrected with a
mechanical fix.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a conveyor belt with a guard missing, you can put the
guard back on. A broken piece of equipment causes an accident, you
can repair it, but solving health problems is nowhere as simple,''
McAteer says. ``In health problems there's a latency period where
you don't see the impact for 15 years, typically. So it's a lot
harder to get people involved, be they the miners, be they the mine
operators, be they my own agency people.''
</P>
<P>
   `A public health matter'
</P>
<P>
   He's also not shy about asking other federal agencies to get
involved in solving problems, which is what he's proposing to do
with ore tainted with asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   ``A product like asbestos has potential for injury to workers at
a mine location, to workers at milling processors, and in other
manufacturing plants. This problem is a public health matter that
needs to be seriously addressed beyond the limits of our
authority,'' McAteer says, and adds, that a team effort is needed
to see how much of a problem the asbestos in the different ore may
be causing.
</P>
<P>
   ``MSHA will take the mines, OSHA will take the milling
operations and processing plants and the EPA the production plants
that use the ore,'' he says, drawing a triangle and pointing to the
corners.
</P>
<P>
   While McAteer plans for the future, he still worries about what
happened at Libby. His examination of the old reports showed that
the field inspectors did their job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The information about the dangers the workers faced at Libby
was passed on to Grace officials,'' he says. ``It should have been
passed up the chain to the head of this agency and it was not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What worries me is that I can't tell you that that failure to
get the word to those of us who can make things happen isn't
happening today.''
</P>
<P>
   McAteer has done what he can to make sure that's not the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spoken to all of our management and met with all of our
people up and down the line to say, `If you see a problem, you'd
better tell us.'
</P>
<P>
   `` We owe it to the miner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 2143EST &QL; 
