<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9161 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     03-16 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE SHADOW THAT HAUNTS THE TOURNEY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Two thousand school children were squealing
during practice, so Shaheen Holloway, the ebullient point guard for
Seton Hall, raised his arms, encouraging them to scream even
louder.
</P>
<P>
   ``They like me because I'm the same size,'' said Holloway, all
of 5 feet 10 inches tall.
</P>
<P>
   The first round of the national basketball tournament has all
the excitement of those grade school children on a field trip. This
first round belongs to poised college stars like Speedy Claxton of
Hofstra and Shaheen Holloway of Seton Hall and _ look up there at
the tube! _ to Messiah Capers of St. Bonaventure, who made three
foul shots to extend Kentucky into double overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The Bonnies eventually lost, but all his life Messiah Capers
will remember how Tubby Smith called two separate timeouts to ice
him but could not make him miss.
</P>
<P>
   There is so much joy and anticipation in the first round. And
then there is Bobby Knight. Glowering or smiling, cursing or
praising, he is impossible to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana University has been to the national tournament 15
straight years, and he is the only active coach to have won three
championships, and here he is again, playing Pepperdine Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Knight has not thrown anybody in a garbage can or acted
boorishly on a trip to Puerto Rico or flailed at his son on the
Indiana bench in over a decade. But as anger sinks deeper into his
self-indulgent face, he is still a presence.
</P>
<P>
   This week the forces of CNN and Sports Illustrated came up with
testimony that Knight belittles his players, acts in disgusting
fashion, and once wrapped his hands around the throat of a player
during practice. Nothing against investigative journalism, but this
unsurprising view sadly served to make Bobby Knight the center of
attention here.
</P>
<P>
   Two days ago, Knight admitted he might have put his hands on a
player's neck to guide him to his proper spot on the floor.
Thursday night he declined to discuss the specifics.
</P>
<P>
   First, his two best players, A.J. Guyton and Michael Lewis,
attended the mandatory news conference and said that Neil Reed, the
player who claimed he had been choked, had been voted off the team
by an 8-0 count, and that Richard Mandeville lacked the proper work
ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Then Knight came out for his obligatory appearance and gave a
monologue of controlled fury. He talked about his admirable
graduation rate, talked about the money his team had raised for
good causes, talked about the good deeds his players did. He made
jokes about his foul language and laughed at reports that he had
ordered a president out of practice, but he never discussed the
specifics about waving used toilet paper at players or putting his
hands on his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not reaching kids to play canasta,'' Knight said.
``We're playing a sport where kids get bloody noses and broken
legs. I can't say I'm proud of everything I did to motivate them.''
</P>
<P>
   He claimed that Isaiah Thomas had recently told him to never
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't think I will,'' Knight added.
</P>
<P>
   School officials then passed out a remarkably indiscreet release
that said Reed had flatly denied the choking incident three years
ago, and that Mandeville had an ``alcohol-related incident'' in
school and ``pleaded'' to stay in school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask Buckner, ask May, ask Chaney, ask Woodson,'' Knight said,
referring to former players.
</P>
<P>
   However, there was no discussion of his public tantrums, his
private rages at players. Timid college officials have created this
monster by continually overlooking anti-social behavior that would
get an English professor fired, tenure or not. Knight is Indiana's
problem, but he is also our problem, sucking the air out of a
regional.
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody sees it this way, of course. John Chaney, age 68,
is the sentimental favorite to reach the Final Four for the first
time. Chaney goads his Temple players but does not exude the
meanness Knight does, although Thursday Chaney asserted: ``You ask
my kids. I do worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaney was standing up for his bud. But enough of Bobby Knight.
Let's talk about Speedy Claxton who honored his commitment to
Hofstra, and Friday night gets to play in the national tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Let's talk about Shaheen Holloway, whose mother and grandmother
sent him from their neighborhood in Jamaica, Queens, to a private
school in New Jersey, not only for the basketball but for the life.
They were flying up for Friday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why it's so great they had this tournament up here in
Buffalo,'' Holloway said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, the snow was sticking. Inside, the children cheered and
asked for autographs from these college players. From here on, this
weekend belongs to the young and the joyous, not the seething bully
from Indiana.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
