<HEADER>
A9163 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-IMF-KOEHLER-NYT     03-16 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMF-KOEHLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN CLEARED TO HEAD IMF AS RIVALS BOW OUT
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The contentious five-month-long scramble to find a
new leader for the International Monetary Fund came to a de facto
conclusion Thursday, as the Japanese and American rivals for the
job formally withdrew their nominations and cleared the path for a
German to take the post for the first time in the fund's history.
</P>
<P>
   Fund officials said the election of Horst Koehler, who heads the
European Bank for Reconstruction and Development, was now a
foregone conclusion. An overwhelming majority of its 182 nations
have already signaled that they will back him.
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of African and Arab countries that had backed
Stanley Fischer, the American who serves as deputy managing
director of the monetary fund, withdrew his candidacy Thursday. And
Japan said it would vote for Koehler and was no longer pushing the
candidacy of Eisuke Sakakibara, former vice finance minister for
international affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler, on a visit to Washington with Germany's finance
minister, Hans Eichel, had breakfast with Fischer Thursday and
lunch with Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers. The Clinton
administration tipped the scales in favor of Koehler this week when
it agreed to support him. He also won the backing of the 15-nation
European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer, a former Massachusetts Institute of Technology
professor who is well regarded by fund members for his day-to-day
stewardship, reaffirmed his intention of remaining in the No. 2
post.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had an excellent meeting this morning with Koehler, during
which we discussed the challenges the fund faces,'' Fischer said in
a statement. ``I am confident that under his leadership the fund
will become an even more effective institution. I look forward to
working closely with him.''
</P>
<P>
   The development ends the leadership struggle at the fund, which
has been under intense pressure to streamline even with its
increasing prominence as a sort of world central bank. The United
States rejected Germany's first choice, arguing that the candidate,
Caio Koch-Weser, a state secretary in the Finance Ministry, did not
have the financial skills or leadership experience.
</P>
<P>
   The rejection set off a feud of sorts with Germany, which had
championed Koch-Weser and lined up grudging acceptance from the
European Union. After failing to win broad support for him in a
round of voting at the fund, the Germans backed Koehler.
</P>
<P>
   Neither man tops the lists of European financial officials. But
Koehler gained relatively quick endorsement, at least in part
because the European Union and the United States had no desire to
pick another fight with Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, who had
vested prestige in winning the job for a German.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler, 57, served as a top economic aide to Schroeder's
predecessor as chancellor, Helmut Kohl. Now, as head of the
European Bank for Reconstruction and Development, he helps finance
development projects and back businesses in the former Soviet bloc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
