<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9165 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-R-BMW-ROVER-ART-430&AMP;A     03-16 1270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-BMW-ROVER-ART-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BMW WILL SHED ROVER, SELLING SPORT UTILITY VEHICLE LINE TO FORD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending to add art note)  (with ROVER-OUTLOOK) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS with ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Six years and nearly $6 billion after
buying the Rover Group, BMW of Germany abandoned the British
automaker Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   BMW essentially gave Rover's money-losing car business to a
little-known group of British investors. And it negotiated a deal
to sell the Land Rover line of sport utility vehicles to Ford Motor
Co. for just under $3 billion, an executive involved in the
transaction said.
</P>
<P>
   The giveaway of Rover's car business was stunning enough. But
the Land Rover deal with Ford, which BMW is expected to announce
Friday, raised speculation about BMW's future strategy. Friday's
moves by BMW represented a retreat from a strategy of getting
bigger and broader, at a time when worldwide rivals are merging and
forming alliances.
</P>
<P>
   The ownership upheavals came as a shock to Rover's 30,000
workers in Britain as well as to the British government, which has
been hoping to salvage one of Rover's main factories with a
taxpayer subsidy around $220 million.
</P>
<P>
   BMW of Munich bought Rover in 1994 in hopes of expanding beyond
its market for luxury vehicles and of keeping up with larger
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's action represented a reversal for BMW and it
generated more uncertainty for Rover's workers, whose new boss will
be Alchemy Partners, an investor group that includes a former Rover
executive, Kevin Morley.
</P>
<P>
   Because nearly half of BMW's shares are controlled by the Quandt
family of Germany, which has so far rejected all overtures, BMW's
independence seems assured for now. But analysts say the pressures
are increasing. Volvo of Sweden sold its car business last year to
Ford. Earlier this week, the Agnelli family of Italy agreed to sell
20 percent of Fiat to General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   Though BMW did not disclose the terms, Alchemy Partners is
expected to pay little, if any, money up front and BMW will assume
many of Rover's debts.
</P>
<P>
   BMW said the expense of shedding the Rover car business would
cost about 3.15 billion euros, or $3.06 billion. As a result, it
will report an annual loss of about $2.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   BMW was officially silent Thursday on the future of Land Rover,
the profitable and growing sport utility business. An agreement to
sell Land Rover to Ford was expected to be announced Friday at the
Munich corporate headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The jettisoning of Rover came as a relief to BMW investors, who
have viewed the British car line as a black hole for money. Rover
lost more than $1 billion in 1998 and $1.2 billion in 1999. Its car
sales plunged 24.9 percent last year, to 251,000 vehicles from
334,000 in 1998.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In further fallout from the Rover developments, BMW dismissed
three top executives, the second big boardroom shake-up in 13
months. The three executives, responsible respectively for
marketing, production, and research and development, had been named
to the board in February 1999 and were supposed to oversee the
integration of Rover and BMW.
</P>
<P>
   Joachim Millberg, who became chief executive after the ouster
last year of Bernd Pischetsrieder, appears to have been the main
architect of Thursday's moves and will remain.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Reitman, an automobile analyst in London with Merrill
Lynch, said Thursday that BMW's future would be brighter now that
it had freed itself from Rover. ``It has a massive effect on BMW,
in the sense that it removes a significant problem,'' Reitman said.
But he added, ``What it doesn't answer is the issue they themselves
have been talking about _ the need for scale.''
</P>
<P>
   Excluding Rover, BMW's profit margins are the highest of any car
manufacturer in the world except for Porsche. Reitman estimated
BMW's profit margin at 12 or 13 percent, when calculated on
American rather than German accounting standards. By contrast, he
said, the Mercedes business of DaimlerChrysler has a margin around
8.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But BMW faces assaults in the luxury market from the likes of
the Audi unit of Volkswagen AG, Volvo and the Jaguar division of
Ford, and of course, its principal German rival, DaimlerChrysler.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts are skeptical that sheer size is the basis of
success. But large size can make it easier to distribute research
and development costs over more vehicles and achieve economies of
scale.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal announced Thursday, Alchemy Partners will take
over Rover's money-losing line of midpriced sedans, including the
more expensive Rover 75, and it will acquire Rover's big factory at
Longbridge, near Birmingham, which has been in danger of closing
for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of trying to build smaller cars through Rover, BMW will
revive a strategy it discarded years ago and design a new line of
cheaper cars under the BMW brand. That is a reversal: BMW
executives had argued strenuously that they did not want ``to
stretch'' their prized brand with cars that sold too cheap.
</P>
<P>
   In an odd twist, BMW indicated that it would also give Alchemy
Partners the line of Mini subcompacts produced by Rover. Yet it
said it would retain the redesigned ``new Mini'' that is due out
later this year.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear exactly what will happen to Rover, but there were
signs Thursday that it would disappear as a brand name. In a
statement Thursday, Alchemy Partners said it would reintroduce
Rover as the MG Car Co. _ adopting the MG marque acquired years ago
by British Leyland, which owned Rover then.
</P>
<P>
   Under BMW's previous chief executive, Pischetsrieder, the
company committed itself to becoming bigger and capable of
competing in the largest and fastest-growing segment of the market
_ medium-priced mass-market cars.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan turned disastrous. The rising value of the British
pound, in relation to the falling euro, made British cars expensive
in Continental Europe and open to competition from companies like
Volkswagen and General Motors' Opel subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Rover also failed to reduce its costs and the size of its labor
force. On top of all that, its midsize car models, the R-25 and
R-45, suffered declining popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Though many experts said the sale of Rover was overdue, some
analysts contend that BMW and the Quandt family were so concerned
with protecting their independence that they missed opportunities.
``It is the Quandts' biggest mistake,'' said Markus Pluemer, an
analyst with WestLB Research in Duesseldorf. Pluemer argued that
BMW could have rescued Rover by teaming up with a bigger
manufacturer like Volkswagen or General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   ``GM or Ford would have been willing to pay an enormous premium
for Rover,'' he said. Had BMW been willing to trade off 20 percent
of its shares, he continued, it could have preserved its
independence, raised billions in extra capital and tapped the
expertise of companies already making mass-market cars.
</P>
<P>
   Georg Stuerzer, an analyst at Hypovereinsbank in Munich, said
BMW could navigate on its own. Noting that shares of
DaimlerChrysler have plunged in the last year, Stuerzer argued that
BMW might have been well advised to focus on luxury cars. ``The
experience of Porsche gives us an indication,'' he said. ``If size
were indicative of operating margins, then Porsche should have the
lowest margins in the industry. But it has the highest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
