<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9170 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-MCCAIN17-COX     03-16 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MCCAIN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush reaches out to McCain in speech
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHEATON, ILL. _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush extended an olive
branch to his former Republican primary rival Thursday,
complimenting Arizona Sen. John McCain and urging their party to
unite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud to stand before you as the nominee of our party and
I'm honored and humbled by that,'' Bush told the $1,000-a-person
crowd at the Cantigny War Museum in kicking off a series of
fund-raising events.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I appreciate the competition. John McCain waged a good
fight. He ran a good campaign. He brought some good ideas to the
surface,'' Bush said. ``We had a good debate and I think it's very
important for all of us to recognize the contribution that John
made. ... It's important for us to unite and move forward. After
all, the biggest reform of all starts with getting rid of
Clinton-Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush camp was stung by controversy over an interview
published Thursday in The New York Times in which Bush made no move
to strike a conciliatory tone toward McCain. Reminded that McCain's
candidacy motivated record turnout in the primaries, Bush told The
Times: ``Well, then, how come he didn't win?'' Bush also said he
did not feel he needs to make concessions toward McCain.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks came as intermediaries between the two camps have
been working to find a path toward a McCain endorsement of Bush.
Both Bush and Vice President Al Gore will need the independents and
Democrats who supported McCain as they battle for victory in the
Nov. 7 general election.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech Thursday before 150 people, Bush pledged to hold
fast to his $483 billion, five-year tax cut proposal. The House
Budget Committee voted this week to approve a budget plan that
calls for $150 billion and possibly $250 billion in tax cuts over
five years starting in 2001, leaving Republicans in the odd
position of backing a tax plan smaller than the one their nominee
has advanced.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was undaunted by that vote, and by polls showing that
voters are not clamoring for a big tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``The press said, `No, the polls don't say people want their
money back,''' he told the crowd. ``Well, you know, I really don't
care what the polls say. ... I come from the school of thought that
says when you reduce marginal rates on people who pay the bills in
America, it encourages growth and more growth is what our party
ought to stand for and more growth is what this campaign
represents.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spoke at the war museum, located on 500 acres in DuPage
County that once formed the estate of Col. Robert R. McCormick,
former editor and publisher of The Chicago Tribune. Wheaton, the
county seat, is 25 miles west of Chicago, but DuPage County
couldn't be farther from that Democratic stronghold when it comes
to political philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Lyn Kennelly, DuPage GOP executive director, said she can't
remember the last time a Democrat held elected office there. She
sold about 1,400 tickets at $90 apiece to the county GOP's 39th
annual Lincoln Day dinner where Bush spoke after the museum event.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will need to visit more such Republican bastions to shore
up his campaign coffers. He is reportedly down to $6 million from
his $70 million in campaign contributions and is hoping to raise $5
million to $10 million by the end of April. He has at least a dozen
fund-raising events coming up and his ``Pioneers'' _ the campaign's
name for people who have raised at least $100,000 _ are revving
their engines.
</P>
<P>
   David Miner, a North Carolina state representative and Pioneer,
said supporters are rescheduling a fund-raiser originally set for
Feb. 10 that was canceled by Austin campaign officials after Bush
lost the New Hampshire primary to McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``After having come up short in New Hampshire, some people who
had not contributed yet felt a little uneasy about the whole McCain
prospect,'' Miner said. ``Now that the die has been set, now that
it's a Bush-Gore race ... I am extremely optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
