<P>
   (NYT33) UNDATED -- March 16, 2000 -- CNBC-JOURNAL -- Steve
Frank, a reporter for the Wall Street Journal, in a photo off video
during its broadcast Tuesday. Frank was discussing a possible
merger between Internet companies Yahoo and Ebay. The next day, the
Journal played down the story despite their reporter extensively
discussing the topic on television the night before. The different
treatment between television and the paper version of the news
underscores the different demands of the two media, and what could
happen to a newspaper's information when it is conveyed in the real
time world of electronic journalism, especially in the rapid-fire
environment of business news, where minutes count and the need to
highlight breaking reports is crucial. (CNBC/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) NEW YORK -- March 16, 2000 -- NORRIS-COLUMN -- The signs
of Times Square have long been amazing. Today the most eye-catching
is the $37 million Nasdaq extravaganza at Broadway and 43rd Street.
And yet, you have to wonder whether Nasdaq is spending its money
wisely. Technological change has made it possible for new
competitors to arise, and it is at least conceivable that the
dominant markets could be eclipsed if they move too slowly to keep
up. (Steve Berman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) NEW YORK -- March 16, 2000 -- NY-TAXI-SHORTAGE -- A row
of taxis near Grand Central Terminal, most of them carrying
passengers, Thursday. It's not your imagination. Hailing a yellow
taxi really has become a lot harder. According to an analysis of a
decade of taxi meter and odometer readings, obtained recently from
New York City by a transportation consultant, the availability of
cabs over the last seven years has fallen sharply, by 13 percent --
even with an expansion of taxi medallions, two taxi fares hikes and
the introduction of subway and bus fare discounts. (Angel
Franco/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) HOPEWELL, N.J. -- March 16, 2000 -- NJ-SPRAWL -- Hungry
for space and for educated suburban workers, the region's office
developments are vaulting over the inner ring of suburbs and
landing in the outer reaches of rural countryside beyond. At upper
left, Merrill Lynch is building the equivalent of a World Trade
Center tower on an old cornfield. (Laura Pedrick/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) HALIFAX, Vt. -- March 16, 2000 -- MAPLE-SYRUP-3 --
Unlike a winery, a sugar house gets just one chance a year to prove
the mettle of its maple with fresh tastings for amateur
connoisseurs: for only about 45 days in the spring, when the nights
are cold and the days are warm enough to coax the sap to flow.
Pancakes topped with syrup at Shearer Hill Farm, above; Bill Pusey
taps one of the farm's trees, below. (Paul Boisvert/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) WHITINGHAM, Vt. -- March 16, 2000 -- MAPLE-SYRUP-2 -- In
early March, dozens of farmers in this informal pancake zone start
the annual ritual of sugaring, a craft handed down through
generations. Newt Brosius offered a ride to guests at his
Whitingham Farm Bed-and-Breakfast. (Paul Boisvert/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) HALIFAX, Vt. -- March 16, 2000 -- MAPLE-SYRUP-1 -- In
March, the 100-year-old sugar maples shadowing the Shearer Hill
Farm in rural Vermont are hung with metal sap buckets, which are
collected by Bill and Patti Pusey and an assortment of relatives
and visiting friends who come from all over the Eastern Seaboard
to, in effect, work for maple syrup. The Puseys have been operating
a combination working farm/bed-and-breakfast here for the last 30
years. (Paul Boisvert/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- March 16, 2000 -- MOMA-EXHIBIT-2 --
``Christina's World,'' Andrew Wyeth's iconic 1948 painting, from
``Making Choices'' at the Modern. The exhibit, which looks at the
next four decades, has been overseen by Peter Galassi, chief
curator of the museum's photography department, working with Robert
Storr and Anne Umland, respectively senior curator and associate
curator in the department of painting and sculpture. (Museum of
Modern Art/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- March 16, 2000 -- MOMA-EXHIBIT-1 --
``Symphony of a Big City,'' a 1928 lithograph by Vladimir and
Georgi Stenberg, from ``Making Choices'' at the Modern. The
exhibit, which looks at the next four decades, has been overseen by
Peter Galassi, chief curator of the museum's photography
department, working with Robert Storr and Anne Umland, respectively
senior curator and associate curator in the department of painting
and sculpture. (Museum of Modern Art/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- March 16, 2000 -- BUFFALO-THEATER-REVIEW --
William H. Macy, left, Mark Webber and Philip Baker Hall in
``American Buffalo,'' directed by Neal Pepe as the third offering
in the Mamet season from the Atlantic Theater Company. A
quarter-century after it was first performed, the play scarcely
seems like a fossil. The marginal urban losers of ``American
Buffalo,'' self-defined entrepreneurs, are enduring American
archetypes, dark soulmates to the day traders of today. (Sara
Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) UNDATED -- March 16, 2000 -- THEATER-NOTES -- Eric
Bogosian's latest one-man show, ``Wake Up and Smell the Coffee,''
is to open off Broadway in May. His wife, Jo Bonney, will direct;
Fred Zollo and Nick Paleologos will produce. The piece, Bogosian's
first solo show since 1994, includes an array of characters and
concepts including airlines, Jesus and overpriced java. ``I'm not
mellow,'' he said, ``I like being fierce, and what makes me laugh
is what I'm going to put onstage.'' (Ruby Washington/The New York
Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. -- March 16, 2000 --
SCI-NO-INSURANCE-DOCS-2 -- For those with insurance, or the money
to pay for health care, there is a two-tiered system evolving in
the U.S. One tier is made up of doctors who take insurance, the
other offers doctors with time and attention to give but take only
cash. Dr. Herbert Rubin, a gastroenterologist, in his office next
to signs warning patients that he does not accept insurance.
(Edward Carreon/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) HOLLYWOOD, Calif. -- March 16, 2000 --
SCI-NO-INSURANCE-DOCS-1 -- William Daniel in his home during a
recent interivew. Two years ago, Daniel's doctor accepted only cash
for his services and refused to deal with insurance companies.
Reluctantly, Daniel changed doctors only to find one that seemed
always pressed for time. So he changed back. For those with
insurance or the money to pay for health care, there is a
two-tiered system evolving. One tier is made up of doctors who take
insurance, the other offers doctors with time and attention to give
but take only cash. (Edward Carreon/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- March 16, 2000 -- CLINTON-FILES -- Nearly
four years after the Whitewater independent counsel began
investigating how the White House acquired some 900 confidential
F.B.I. files, many of them of prominent Republicans, the current
counsel, Robert W. Ray, seen in his office in December, officially
reported Thursday in a statement that there was no criminal
wrongdoing involved. The report is the first of several to be
issued over the next several months by Ray as he closes down the
independent counsel's office. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- March 16, 2000 -- TRUCKS-PROTEST-2 --
Trucks lined up along the National Mall near the Washington
Monument during a protest against higher fuel prices Wednesday. For
the second time in less than a month, a convoy of independent
truckers rolled into nation's capital, seeking relief from fuel
prices that have more than doubled in the past year. (Susana
Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- March 16, 2000 -- PEOPLES-SYMPHONY -- Eighth
Blackbird, a new-music ensemble of six young muscians, is to
perform Saturday evening in a Peoples' Symphony Concert at
Washington Irving High School. Founded in 1900, the low-cost
concert series has been managed by Frank Salomon since 1973.
Besides being one of the best bargains in New York City's concert
life, the performances are also an unusually well-kept secret.
(Aaron Lee Fineman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) UNDATED -- March 16, 2000 -- ART-NOTES -- A group of
contemporary artworks from what Sotheby's describes only as a
private European collection, are to be auctioned on May 17 in New
York at Sotheby's. The works, dating from 1965 to 1971, range from
Minimalist sculpture and painting to Conceptual photography and
neon installations. Among the most prized works is Bruce Nauman's
``Light Trap for Henry Moore, No. 1'' (1967). (Sotheby's/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- March 16, 2000 -- ANTIQUES-COLUMN -- A
pottery beaker is part of J.J. Lally's show of ancient Chinese
ceramics and tomb sculptures. ``You must realize this is before the
appearance of figural materials,'' said Jim Lally, the gallery
owner, referring to a melon-shaped vessel resting on three short
pointed feet - one of the show's neolithic items from 6000 B.C.
that look amazingly modern. ``It is one of the earliest Chinese
ceramics in America.'' (J.J. Lally &AMP; Co./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- March 16, 2000 -- RIVERDANCE-REVIEW -- The
``Riverdance on Broadway'' troupe performing at the Gershwin
Theater. Essentially there is only one thing to say about the Irish
music and dance show, which has returned to New York for a limited
run. The phenomenon rolls on, as inexorably as the sonorous voice
of Liam Neeson summons up the pounding seas and dark nights of
Ireland in the taped text that runs through the production. (Norman
Y. Lono/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) PHILADELPHIA -- March 15, 2000 -- GORE-LABOR -- Vice
President Al Gore acknowledges the crowd at a meeting of the
Pennsylvania chapter of the AFL-CIO, Wednesday. Having locked up
the Democratic nomination for president with considerable help from
organized labor, Gore now faces the tricky problem of having to
show his gratitude to the nation's trade unions, while convincing
voters that he is not in labor's pocket. (Paul Hosefros/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) LOS ANGELES -- March 16, 2000 -- MUSIC-CAROL-KAYE-LADN
-- Members of the drummerless trio ``Thumbs Up,'' from left, Ray
Pizzi (sax, flute), Carol Kaye (bass) and Mitch Holder (guitar).
Their new album documents the improvisational interplay of the trio
who has been playing together since 1998. (Phil McCarten/Los
Angeles Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) TARZANA, Calif. -- March 16, 2000 --
FASHION-BRIDAL-TRENDS-LADN -- Beaded pants and a tank top from Lili
Bridals in Tarzana, Calif. offer brides a less-formal alternative.
At right, at strapless gowns, such as this corset design by British
designer Anu Pam from Lili Bridals, are the latest look in bridal
attire. (Gus Ruelas/Los Angeles Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) LOS ANGELES -- March 16, 2000 --
LEARNING-GIANT-WOMAN-LADN -- Tess, the giant robot, is designed to
teach visitors to the California Science Center about homeostasis--
the body's remarkable, but often taken-for-granted ability to
maintain a stable internal environment despite the wildly
fluctuating conditions we expose it to, from soccer games to
mountain climbing. David Combs, physiologist and curator of the
museum's World of Life exhibit, says the $1.7 million in grant
money spent to build the model was definitely worth it. (Charlotte
Schmid-Maybach/The Los Angels Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) STUDIO CITY, Calif. -- March 16, 2000 --
KNITTING-CELEBS-2-LADN -- From left: Bettina Swan, Sandy Gonor,
Ellen Weston and Kerri Randles, at La Knitterie Parisienne where
customers help each other with knitting projects. Only now the
quips are being printed in Time magazine and Entertainment Weekly,
and they're about how many people -- young and old, male and
female, famous and infamous -- can't get their fill of this ``knit
one, purl two'' stuff. (David Sprague/The Los Angeles Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) STUDIO CITY, Calif. -- March 16, 2000 --
KNITTING-CELEBS-1-LADN -- Actress Daryl Hannah knits a scarf at La
Knitterie Parisienne. Once considered the nerdiest, most old
ladyish of crafts, knitting is the butt of jokes once again. Only
now the quips are being printed in Time magazine and Entertainment
Weekly, and they're about how many people -- young and old, male
and female, famous and infamous -- can't get their fill of this
``knit one, purl two'' stuff. (David Sprague/The Los Angeles Daily
News) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NY8) GAINESVILLE, Fla. -- March 16, 2000 -- FL-GIRL-KIDNAPPED-2
-- Alachua County Sheriff department personnel push a vehicle,
suspected of being used in the kidnapping of a girl earlier this
month, into a police garage, Wednesday. Police said the green Jeep
Cherokee, owned by James P. Johnson, matches the description of the
vehicle used in the kidnapping of Jessica Rodriguez on March 6.
Johnson, 38, was arrested Wednesday. (Kelly Gamble, Alachua County
Sheriff department/The Gainesville Sun)
</P>
<P>
   (NY7) GAINESVILLE, Fla. -- March 16, 2000 -- FL-GIRL-KIDNAPPED
-- Alachua County Detective Bobby Gaff, left, and Gilchrist County
Sheriff David Turner, right, lead kidnapping suspect James Paul
Johnson, 38, into the Alachua County Jail late Wednesday night.
Johnson is the prime suspect in the abduction of 10-year-old
Jessica Rodriguez, who was released last Thursday after being
kidnapped three days earlier. Johnson was ordered held on $1
million bail and was under a suicide watch Thursday. (Jon M.
Fletcher/The Gainesville Sun)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) LINCOLN, Mass. -- March 16, 2000 -- HOME-KITCHENS-BOS --
The kitchen in the house that Walter Gropius designed for himself
and his family in 1937. The space was a statement of the Bauhaus
style, transported to and translated for New England, after the
great architect fled Nazi Germany and arrived to teach at Harvard.
(Mark Wilson/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BOSTON -- March 16, 2000 -- AUTHOR-MACDONALD-BOS --
Michael Patrick MacDonald, author of ``All Souls: A Family Story
from Southie.'' The book, published in September by Beacon Press,
is a bittersweet coming-of-age saga set in South Boston during the
1970s and 1980s, chronicling a series of family tragedies,
including the deaths of four of MacDonald's siblings, that occurred
within a proud community besieged by social change and bedeviled by
violence and denial. (Suzanne Kreiter/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- March 16, 2000 -- TRUCKS-PROTEST -- A
convoy of trucks drive past the Capitol protesting increasing fuel
prices on Thursday. For the second time in less than a month, a
convoy of independent truckers rolled into nation's capital,
seeking relief from fuel prices that have more than doubled in the
past year. (Susana Raab/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) GRIFTON, N.C. -- March 16, 2000 -- FLOYD-FAME-COX --
Beadie Tarlton reviews a wall of cards representing flooded homes
in the area. Church volunteers have dominated relief efforts in
Grifton in the six months since the flood caused by Hurricane
Floyd. In Grifton, a town of 2,307 people and 900 houses, about 400
houses were damaged in the flood. Churches and public buildings,
including the police station and fire department, were also gutted.
Jean-Henri White/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) MOSCOW -- March 16, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 19 --
RUSSIA-YOUNGVOTER-COX -- Nadia Gorovaya at her home in northern
Moscow. On March 26, she and a generation of her peers will be
voting in a democratic election for the first time. Gorovaya, a
Russian architechture student, is worried that Russia's poor
economic situation will mean she won't be able to find a job when
she graduates from college in three years. (Margaret Coker/Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) LOS ANGELES, Calif. -- March 16, 2000 --
ONLINE-UNIVERSITY -- Michael Saylor, who plans to spend $100
million to create a university on the Web, says his goal is a
``free education for everyone on earth.'' Saylor, the chief
executive of Microstrategy, a technology company in northern
Virginia, said in an interview that he envisions his online
educational institution eventually granting degrees in countless
disciplines, based on final exams that would be administered once a
month in convention halls around the world, with grading done by
computer whenever possible. (Monica Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
