<P>
   (NYT43) FAIRFAX, Va. -- March 16, 2000 -- GUNS-LAPIERRE -- A
growing number of prominent Republican officials say they feel
deeply uncomfortable with the harsh battle of words pitting
President Clinton against the National Rifle Association, and, as a
result, have begun urging passage of long-stalled gun-control
legislation in Congress this year. On Wednesday, Wayne LaPierre,
executive vice president of the NRA, said that the president had
blood ``on his hands'' for advocating new gun restrictions instead
of enforcing existing laws. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
