<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9181 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-1STLD-WRI     03-16 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BUSH TRIES TO ALLAY NEW CRITICISMS BY McCAIN SUPPORTERS  
 (Changes dateline from Springfield to Wheaton; removes `here' from
2nd graf; subs 6th graf to note Gore is `probable' opponent; subs
11th and 12 grafs to include reference to Springfield; subs 22nd
graf to clarify that McCain has suspended, not quit, campaign) 
 (bl) 
 By FRANK BRUNI and ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHEATON, Ill. _ Gov. George W. Bush went out of his way Thursday
to demonstrate respect for Sen. John McCain, pointing to areas of
agreement between him and his vanquished rival for the Republican
presidential nomination and saying, ``I'm confident we can work
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush made his comments in two speeches Thursday and at a news
conference this afternoon, as aides and supporters of McCain
criticized Bush for remarks in an interview with The New York Times
on Wednesday. They said the Texas governor had made it more
difficult to work out a reconciliation between the two men.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Bush said McCain had made him a better
candidate, but he also said he had no intention of making
concessions to McCain and passed up several opportunities to
embrace his signature proposal to overhaul the campaign finance
laws. Bush also challenged the notion that McCain had been
responsible for the huge surge in voter turnout during the
Republican primaries, saying, ``Well, then, how come he didn't
win?''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Harris, a spokesman for McCain said, ``Obviously we're
disappointed with the governor's tone, but it doesn't change any of
our plans. Senator McCain is committed to campaigning for
reform-minded Republicans across the country.'' He sidestepped the
question of whether McCain would ultimately endorse Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But another aide to McCain said that the interview had made an
endorsement less likely. And Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., who was a
national co-chairman of the McCain campaign, said, ``I don't think
it enhances the bridge-building that needs to be done here. That
was a pretty arrogant interview and it doesn't help what we're all
trying to do here.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, Bush's probable Democratic opponent in
the general election, who is trying to win over some McCain
supporters, also jumped into the fray. He chided Bush for saying
that McCain had not changed his views on reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he should have been taking notes from John McCain,''
Gore said Thursday to a gathering in Washington of about 50 members
of the Amalgamated Transit Union.
</P>
<P>
   Taking advantage of the Republican divisions, Gore cited
McCain's criticisms of Bush's proposal to cut taxes by $483 billion
over five years. Had Bush taken notes, Gore said, ``he could have
written down the statistics that John McCain pointed out _ that his
risky tax scheme gives 60 percent of all of the benefits to the
wealthiest 10 percent of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In his interview, Bush called the tax cut ``a well-thought-out
plan backed by numbers backed by credible sources.'' He said he
believed voters are interested in tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   In the governor's public appearances and in a series of
telephone calls, the Bush camp made a concerted effort to try to
smooth relations with the McCain camp.
</P>
<P>
   The presumptive Republican presidential nominee brought up
McCain in a luncheon speech in Springfield, saying: ``I appreciate
the hard campaign that John McCain waged. He ran a good race. He
highlighted the need for reform, and I appreciate the ideas that he
brought forth in the campaign. Of course, he and I agree on a lot,
and it starts with this: the best reform for America is to end the
Clinton-Gore era in Washington, D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   Later at a news conference in Springfield, Bush referred to The
New York Times article indirectly, saying, ``There's a story out
today that doesn't characterize how I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   He directed attention instead to a interview on the front page
of The Dallas Morning News quoting him as saying he wanted to mend
fences with McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how I feel,'' he said holding up the Texas newspaper.
``I look forward to working with Senator McCain.'' He added that
the senator ``ran a good campaign. He brought forth some issues
that are important and I'm confident that we can work together.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that both men, for instance, want to change the Social
Security system to allow younger workers to have personal
investment accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides also contacted McCain's aides and supporters. Staff
members for both men said that Joe Allbaugh, the governor's
campaign manager, called John Weaver, McCain's political director.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as we saw The New York Times story, we immediately
reached out to Senator McCain's staff and advisers to tell them
that The New York Times story was not a full and fair reflection of
what the governor has said about Senator McCain,'' said Ari
Fleischer, a spokesman for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``We provided them with the quotes that were excluded
from the story, that were put at the bottom of the page of the
transcript, off the front page and out of the headlines.'' He said
Bush aides also told the McCain campaign about The Dallas Morning
News interview.
</P>
<P>
   The question of how to handle McCain has been a sensitive one
for Bush because even while the Arizona senator lost popularity
among Republicans, he attracted to his side many independent and
swing voters who could well determine which party wins the November
election.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Both Bush and Gore are already casting themselves as reformers
and vying for the allegiance of McCain;'s followers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the two men's agendas are difficult to reconcile. McCain is
particularly focused on winning a ban on the unlimited, unregulated
donations to political parties known as soft money. Yet Bush has
stopped short of endorsing such a ban and many of his staunchest
allies adamantly oppose such legislation, arguing that it would
hamper the ability of Republicans and conservatives to fight for
their causes.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who is on vacation in the South Pacific, suspended his
presidential campaign last week but stopped short of endorsing Bush
after their bitter primary struggle. He vowed to keep up a battle
for his issue agenda, ranging from overhauling the campaign finance
law to mixing moderate tax cuts with debt reduction.
</P>
<P>
   McCain made no statement himself on Bush's remarks, but Hagel
said, ``I can guarantee that he knows about it. Right next to that
grass hut, he's got his fax machine winging along.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Peter King, R-N.Y., who supported McCain, also was critical
of Bush on Thursday, saying, ``either he's arrogant or he's
politically tone deaf.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to the Arizona senator revealed this week that he was
creating his own political action committee to help him keep up a
national political presence and keep his supporters mobilized. They
said McCain planned to campaign in November for candidates who
share his views and that he also planned to stump for a ban on
unlimited unregulated donations to political parties.
</P>
<P>
   Among the activities tentatively in the planning stages, aides,
said, is a a tour of college campuses where McCain would hold the
kind of town hall meetings he popularized in New Hampshire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
