<SLUG> BC-BKC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SPORTS COLUMN: GUESS WHAT AL McGUIRE MISSES THE MOST THESE DAYS?  
(rk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Al McGuire's voice sounded as sturdy as it ever had when it was
crackling with laughter on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting a lot of sympathy,'' he was saying. ``I go to this
Manhattan bagel place down here and the guy who owns it, I guess he
read where I'm not working the NCAA this year and when I went in
there the other morning, he buys me my bagel and coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   Al McGuire laughed and said, ``If I knew the guy was reaching,
I'd have had an egg on it.'' Weakened by anemia, basketball's old
philosopher was on the telephone from his condo in Singer Island,
Fla., Thursday instead of perching where he usually has for more
than two decades when the college tournament is on: at courtside as
a television analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all right,'' he was saying, ``but the arenas, the hotels,
the airports are big places. It makes it hard to get around.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 71, he talked about how he will miss the tournament but when
he was asked what he will miss the most, he didn't laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds phony, but I'll miss the national anthem,'' he said.
``I thought about this the other day sitting on the beach. When
they play the anthem, it's the only silence you're going to have.
The players, the coaches, the students, the neurosurgeons in their
beanies. Then after the anthem, it's an explosion.''
</P>
<P>
   What he did not miss was having to learn to identify the players
when eight teams, some of which he had never seen before, practice
the day before a subregional began.
</P>
<P>
   ``One year one team came out with no names, no numbers on their
shirts,'' he said, laughing. ``You had to find out which guys were
wearing low socks or high socks.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Al McGuire needed names or numbers. All he ever needed
was his outlook on basketball and on life, an outlook developed
growing up in his family's bar in Rockaway Beach, playing for St.
John's and the Knicks, coaching at Belmont Abbey and then at
Marquette, where his 1977 team won the N CAA championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no training for analysts,'' he often said. ``You can't
prepare for it because if you prepare for it, it comes over flat.
It comes over like a charade, like watching paint dry.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years at both the CBS and NBC networks, McGuire worked
with nearly a dozen different announcers, notably Billy Packer and
Dick Enberg, but the game was always the thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the game is good, the announcers should let it be,'' he
once explained. ``An announcer should never cut into a game if the
game is in the 12-point or 18-point area. But if it goes over 18
points, you have to be more creative or do more talking to the
future and the past, or get into the hobbies and who eats Jell-O
and who doesn't eat Jell-O.''
</P>
<P>
   His words on basketball and life have endured as if chiseled in
stone, or at least in playground blacktop:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``If you haven't broken your nose in basketball, you haven't
really played. You've just tokened it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``They call me eccentric; they used to call me nuts. I haven't
changed. The only difference between being eccentric and being nuts
is the number of security boxes you have.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Sports is a coffee break. Winning is only important in war
and surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I think everyone should go to college and get a degree, then
spend six months as a bartender and six months as a cab driver.
Then they'd really be educated.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Anyone who offers to double your money, walk away. If he
offers to make you 20 percent, hear him out.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``If you're at a flea market and see something you want but
don't buy it, when you go back, it'll be gone.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Postseason tournaments'' meaning conference tournaments,
``are a waste of time. I think they should knock them all out and
put 256 teams in the NCAA tournament. It would just take one more
week. You open up at 32 sites, then the next week you're down to 64
teams, then 16, then four and out.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Pre-game meals? Give me kids who'll win on a pizza and a
Coke.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``If a guy takes off his watch before he fights, he means
business.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``If you want to determine if a guy's hanging on the rim,
electrify the rim. If a guy's hand touches it, you leave the juice
on until he turns blue.''
</P>
<P>
   As an analyst, he was different but he didn't remember ever
being critiqued by his television bosses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don Ohlmeyer,'' he was saying now, referring to his former NBC
boss, ``told me, `You're so bad, you're good.'''
</P>
<P>
   But what he called his ``finest compliment'' came after he left
Marquette with the 1977 NCAA title.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother told me, `I'm glad you left clean,''' he said, ``She
meant without having had any trouble with minorities, without being
sued, without any expense-account scheme.''
</P>
<P>
   As a television analyst, Al McGuire has left clean, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
