<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9188 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-CENSUS-AZR &LR;      03-16 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 CENSUS MANAGERS DISMISSED  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TESSIE BORDEN  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With less than three weeks left before Census Day, officials
have fired three top managers of south Phoenix's Census 2000 office
for recruiting the fewest census workers in a 10-state region.
</P>
<P>
   The office, which serves some of the hardest-to-count groups in
all of Maricopa County, needs 5,080 people by the end of the month.
So far, it has hired 3,001. Nationwide, it is in the bottom 10
percent in recruiting efforts among local offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've stressed that for a month now, and the numbers have not
come up,'' said Sam Martinez, who manages census efforts in most of
Arizona. ``That's why they were relieved of their duties.''
</P>
<P>
   Those fired this week were Al Jauregui, local census office
manager; Jim Shee, assistant manager for recruiting; and Frank
Cano, assistant manager for administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said that they weren't happy with the job we'd done,''
Shee said.
</P>
<P>
   But the move to replace the office managers could further harm
an effort that community members say has been disorganized and
slow-starting in an area often undercounted because residents are
transient, little educated or undocumented.
</P>
<P>
   The seasonal workers are needed to personally survey census
stragglers who don't fill out forms mailed out this week. That push
begins April 27.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Enriquez, director of adult education at Friendly House,
said census officials should have started recruiting weeks ago,
given the expected problems _ and the fact that prospective workers
have to take a test, go through a background check and be trained.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they knew this was a hard-to-count area, why didn't they
start earlier?'' Enriquez asked. ``It's tough to recruit in this
area, especially 2,000 people.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudolfo Perez, who had been working with census officials in
behalf of the Mexican American Legal Defense and Education fund,
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that they were concerned with the low numbers of
people that have been hired so far,'' he said. ``(But) it's pretty
shocking to make this kind of a decision so late in the ball
game.''
</P>
<P>
   If the south Phoenix office lacks workers, officials will have
to bring in workers from other areas in the Phoenix area or the
state, which Martinez said would defeat their goal of hiring local
workers with whom residents felt more comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona missed 2.4 percent of its population during the 1990
census, according to regional Census Bureau figures. Among the
invisible ones were 32,223 Hispanics and 21,570 Native Americans.
Martinez said the state is the second fastest-growing in the Union,
so the potential for an undercount becomes an even bigger problem.
</P>
<P>
   COUNTERS FACE HURDLES
</P>
<P>
   He said counters face four hurdles in Arizona: skyrocketing
growth, rivers of undocumented workers, the annual pilgrimage of
snowbirds who spend winters here, and far-flung, hard-to-find
Native Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Enriquez said his agency, which trains poor people to join the
workforce, could get stretched by an undercount because it would
get less federal grant money to serve more people.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a need,'' he said. ``This is always an
invisible population, and their needs come to us. For us, an
accurate count is vital because then we can get some proper funding
for services this community vitally needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Enriquez and other community organizers believe the Census
Bureau's efforts to get the word out in their neighborhoods has
been adequate. But that may not matter much if it doesn't have
enough people to do the counting, they say.
</P>
<P>
   MANY TO IGNORE FORMS
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey by Behavior Research Center, a Phoenix polling
firm, said 16 percent of Arizona Hispanics plan to ignore the
census forms they get in the mail and 32 percent aren't sure if
they will fill them out. Census counters could play a crucial role
in convincing them, Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez replaced the fired managers with employees from the
Mesa census office, including Manuel Trujillo, who was in charge of
recruiting in Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to get more workers, Census 2000 will hold a
recruiting fair Saturday beginning at 10 a.m. in 12 Phoenix area
locations, said Doug Wayland, regional Census 2000 spokesman. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
