<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9189 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NJ-SPRAWL-1STLD-WRITE     03-16 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-SPRAWL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG OFFICE DEVELOPMENT IN RURAL NEW JERSEY PREVAILS OVER
ANTI-SPRAWL PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs 8th graf to note construction began about 2 years ago; subs
6th graf to change `that will start' to `starting') 
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT30 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOPEWELL, N.J. _ Leslie Kramer and her husband moved into a big
Victorian house in this rural township to get away from congestion
in Westchester County, N.Y. Carol Ferry and her husband moved here
from Hamilton Township, on the other side of Trenton, for the same
reason.
</P>
<P>
   So have hundreds of their neighbors who thought that here, at
last, they would be safe from sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Gov. Christie Whitman had said that she would make
New Jersey a national model for controlling growth in ways that
would protect open space and direct growth back to urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Governors across the country, including George Pataki of New
York and John Rowland of Connecticut, have more recently done the
same.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But like forest creatures who are too slow to outrun a wildfire,
the Kramers and the Ferrys have found that the crowded old
neighborhoods they tried to flee are on their way to them, led by a
giant new development that could produce more office space than a
tower of the World Trade Center. And when new census figures this
month showed formerly rural parts of New Jersey growing faster than
anyplace in the region, it was a reminder that stopping sprawl and
talking about it are two very different things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you what I believe _ you can't stop it,'' said
Kramer, the leader of a failed effort to stop Merrill Lynch from
building a project starting at 3.5 million square feet and could
grow to 5.5 million in an old cornfield here. ``My husband hit me
over the head with that fact all along and I didn't believe him. I
kept saying, `No, this is so wrong on so many levels _ look what
it's doing to our community, look how it violates the State Plan,
look how it goes against everything the governor said she was going
to do!' But you know, he was right. You can't stop it, not if the
people with the money want it.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the existence of anti-sprawl measures like New
Jersey's state plan and the governor's fervent calls for protecting
open space may only deepen residents' sense of betrayal when a
project like the one being built by Merrill Lynch here starts
rising in a neck of the state that looks more like Vermont than New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The Hopewell project, which began construction about two years
ago, also demonstrates anew how money and jobs _ in this case the
company's threat to move 3,500 jobs to Pennsylvania _ can trump
public land preservation policy.
</P>
<P>
   So whether it is the project here, or the 1 million square feet
of laboratories that AT&AMP;T recently opened in Middletown, Monmouth
County, or the plans to develop 2,000 acres of woods near Stewart
Airport in Orange County, N.Y., sprawl continues to march on across
the region.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some figures from New Jersey: of the 9.9 million square feet of
office space authorized by local officials through November last
year, nearly two thirds is being built in an outer ring of largely
rural counties of Morris, Somerset, Hunterdon, Monmouth, Mercer and
Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Somerset, the fastest growing county in the New York
metropolitan region, added more than half a million square feet
alone, while Mercer County, home of Princeton and Hopewell and two
hours from Manhattan, leads the state with 2.1 million square feet
of office space authorized last year, much of it from the Merrill
Lynch project.
</P>
<P>
   The Regional Planning Partnership, a non-profit land-use
planning group that studies growth in Mercer, Somerset and
Middlesex counties, forecasts a 40 percent population increase by
2020 in the region. Even more striking than population growth
trends, however, are land use trends. The group said that while the
region's population grew 21 percent from 1976 to 1996, the land
area developed increased by 61 percent. And most of that came
before the area's boom began in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In her 1998 inaugural address, Whitman announced a $1 billion
open space preservation bond act, to buy up 1 million acres of open
land, and declared, ``We must do more to encourage intelligent,
responsible growth for New Jersey's future, especially in our
cities.'' The bond act was passed by the voters by a wide margin.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In January, Pataki of New York created a Quality Communities
Task Force to study ways to direct growth in ways that emphasize
redevelopment and reduce sprawl. In Connecticut, Rowland has
declared a goal of tripling the amount of land protected from
sprawl in the next 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But such pledges to stem sprawl have come too late for residents
here, who failed to follow the local planning process until it was
too late, said Samuel H. Hamill, Jr. a former local planning board
president and now senior consultant to New Jersey Future, a growth
management think tank. That aloofness from the nitty-gritty of
planning issues, he said, is now ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only did the governor's bond act pass, but there were any
number of local elections that turned on these very questions.''
Hamill said.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch had one big factor going in its favor: the land it
company chose was zoned for a big project like the one it wanted to
develop, however incongruous it might seem to someone driving
slowly by on the rural lane that bordered the site. But if the
state had any misgivings, they were erased when Merrill Lynch made
plain that it was going to be Hopewell or another state, probably
an equally rustic corner of Pennsylvania. Whitman, concerned with
the company's threat to pull 3,500 or more jobs from the state,
gave the project political and financial support.
</P>
<P>
   The state applied for and got $38.5 million in federal money to
rebuild the interchange at Interstate 95 and Scotch Road, where the
Merrill Lynch project is being built, and it has agreed to help the
company avoid $13.5 million in sales taxes. In addition, the state
said it would give the company $6.4 million to create at least
1,100 new jobs at the site, which will eventually employ 3,500.
Finally, Merrill Lynch, the country's largest brokerage house, will
get $135 million in grants for job creation at Hopewell and at its
10 other New Jersey sites.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Eileen McGinnis, the governor's chief policy adviser, lives in
Hopewell and defends the project, even as she has her own personal
misgivings about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I separate my personal feelings from my professional
feelings,'' McGinnis said. ``On a personal level I drive by it
every day and I do wish the project wasn't there. But on a
professional level I know that the State Plan is not about no
growth, it's about smart growth.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The State Plan, adopted in 1992 as guidelines for directing
growth to areas with transportation access and to already built-up
areas, is often invoked by preservationists for its goal that the
state should use its power to push some new development towards the
state's hollowed-out cities. But the plan's guidelines are
advisory, not mandatory and subject to economic and political
pressures.
</P>
<P>
   The Merrill Lynch site is designated for growth under the State
Plan as an area with public space such as retail and housing.
Critics point out, however, that there is no public component in
the 3.5 million square foot first phase.
</P>
<P>
   The site is designated as a growth area under the State Plan,
because it is adjacent to an interstate highway.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But Jeff Tittle, executive director of the New Jersey Sierra
Club, maintains that by helping Merrill Lynch build on a pristine
rural site, it was working against its own aim of buying land for a
public greenway trail from the Delaware River to Princeton through
Hopewell, since all land in the area will now be made much more
expensive by the immense new development.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Building deep in the country makes perfect sense from the
company's perspective, said Hamill, even though the state might
have wished that the project had gone go to a city like Trenton,
which has acres of unused industrial space, and which lies only a
few miles from Hopewell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cities in general, and Trenton is no exception, are much
less certain than the suburbs as planning environments,'' Hamill
said. ``Things don't happen as quickly in the cities, buildings
inspections aren't on time and policy plans are much more vague, so
anyone going there has this uncertainty in the approval process.''
</P>
<P>
   When Merrill Lynch told the state that it would build in
Hopewell or leave New Jersey, state officials gingerly raised the
idea of building in Trenton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merrill Lynch officials said very clearly that they would not
look at Trenton,'' said Tom Dalessio, an assistant in the
governor's policy office. ``They wanted a suburban style campus, so
it was either here or Pennsylvania.''
</P>
<P>
   In Hopewell, Merrill Lynch found 450 acres of open farmland that
had been owned, with development in mind, by Bristol Myers Squibb,
the pharmaceutical concern, since 1955.
</P>
<P>
   It also found a five-member all-Republican town board with
strong land-owner sympathies that welcomed the prospect of millions
of dollars in new taxes for sewers and schools. It did not hurt
that the company also bought 440 additional acres across the road
from William E. Schluter, an influential state senator who sits on
the Economic Growth, Agriculture and Tourism committee.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch has final approval to build 1.3 million square
feet of office space on the land, and has preliminary approval to
build 2.2 million more at the site. The adjacent 440 acres is zoned
for 2 million square feet of commercial development, for a total of
5.5 million square feet potential _ and probable _ construction on
both sides of the road. One World Trade Center tower contains 4
million square feet.
</P>
<P>
   Local reaction followed the now familiar arc from surprise to
anger to despair. An anti-growth coalition swept the Republicans on
the town board and replaced them with a 4-to-1 Democratic majority
that succeeded in stopping Merrill Lynch's preferred sewer option _
it has others _ but could not block the development.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Now Ferry, an office worker, has to wonder if she and her
husband Dennis, a chemist, should think of moving again, to stay
ahead of the wave. When they moved from their starter home in
Trenton to a house in Hamilton in 1978, they had fields behind.
When they left for Hopewell in 1985, she said, the fields in
Hamilton were covered with houses, and a drive that once took ten
minutes took half an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do we go next?'' Ferry wondered. `There's really no
place you can go to hide.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
