<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0397 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9191 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GENE-ALTERED-FOOD-ART     03-16 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENE-ALTERED-FOOD-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY U.S. FARMERS ARE STICKING WITH GENETICALLY ALTERED CROPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIOUX CITY, Iowa _ David Howe, a big corn and soybean farmer
near this town nestling the Nebraska border, says he is tired of
people treating his genetically engineered crops as freaks of
nature.
</P>
<P>
   To him, genetically modified seeds and the foods they produce
are entirely safe. He has been planting such seeds for three years
and expects to do so for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely bothered by what they're saying in Europe,''
Howe said, referring to the loud and growing opposition to
genetically modified food in places like France and Britain. ``I
hear it called `Frankenstein foods,' but what damage has it done?''
</P>
<P>
   Genetically modified seeds have been biologically altered to
release their own insecticide or to immunize themselves against
weed killers and other chemicals or against pests. Despite the
rancorous debate overseas and a smattering of protests in the
United States over the safety of gene-altered foods, Howe and many
other American farmers now expect to plant the crops again this
year because they are easier and cheaper to grow, and because there
is still a big market for them in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   More important, the nation's largest agricultural companies have
formed a line of defense against the opposition by promising
farmers that they will buy their gene-altered grains. Cargill Inc.
and Archer-Daniels-Midland _ two of the largest grain-handling
companies _ say they will welcome the crops at most of their grain
elevators, where they buy and store crops before shipping them to
food companies.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Major seed companies _ Monsanto, DuPont's Pioneer Hi-Bred
International unit and Novartis of Switzerland _ have held forums
around the country this winter in a bid to assure farmers that the
big grain companies will buy what they grow.
</P>
<P>
   That is comforting to farmers like Gary Dreckman in Le Mars,
Iowa, who says he was on the fence about planting gene-altered
seeds. ``Through last harvest I was very concerned,'' said
Dreckman, who now expects to plant genetically modified corn and
soybeans on 80 percent of his 1,200 acres. ``But what's changed my
mind is the elevators; if they weren't going to accept it, I
wouldn't plant it.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Scientifically altered seeds already account for huge parts of
the U.S. cotton, soybean and corn crops. But throughout the grain
belt, this year is shaping up as a test of the seed makers' resolve
to defend their products in the face of protests in Europe, where
imports of U.S. corn and soybeans have plummeted. If farmers
abandoned biotechnology seeds because of the protests, the
companies could lose billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the world's largest food producers have already shaken
things up by saying they will not use biotechnology crops this
year. McCain Foods Ltd. of Canada, a huge potato producer and a
leading supplier of French fries to Burger King, says it will steer
clear of gene-altered potatoes. The Frito-Lay unit of PepsiCo has
announced that it will not buy modified corn. And the Gerber
Products Co., going somewhat against the stance of its parent,
Novartis, has said that it will not use biotechnology crops in its
baby food.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't eliminate them out of safety concerns,'' said
Sheldon Jones, a spokesman at Gerber in Summit, N.J. ``We just
wanted to take baby food out of the debate; baby food is a very
sensitive area.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Markley, a Frito-Lay spokeswoman, added: ``It's all about
standing on the sidelines and waiting to see how consumers and the
FDA respond. Frito-Lay is not saying they are unsafe, and we are
not ruling out genetically modified products in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmers worry, however, that an increasing number of companies
will move away from genetically altered crops if fears spread among
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very concerned because the consumer is who we rely on,''
said Todd Gibson, 37, in Norborne, Mo., who was an early
biotechnology convert and says he will keep planting modified seed
as long as he can.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the technology say the regulatory approval process
is inadequate. They also question the safety of the food produced
and wonder about the effects to the environment in future
generations. The seeds are now used throughout North and South
America, China and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   No definitive studies have been done on the safety of
gene-altered foods, and protesters argue that more research is
needed.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, when American farms began shipping biotechnology crops
to Europe, exports of corn and soybeans, both genetically modified
and conventional, amounted to nearly $3 billion. But these
shipments have declined markedly, to about $1 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, the trade in genetically altered seeds or foods has
virtually stopped: farmers won't plant biotechnology crops,
consumers won't buy the foods, and stores are declining to stock
them. Regulators have approved no new seed strains for nearly two
years.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, by contrast, the growth of gene-altered
corn and soybeans has exploded; almost a third of the corn crop and
about half the soybeans are produced from genetically altered
seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Biotechnology plantings in the United States increased to 62
million acres last year, from 16 million acres in 1997. This year,
the amount is expected to stay nearly flat, with more than 60
million acres of genetically engineered corn and soybeans planted,
according to the world's largest seed companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing a very stable market,'' said Carl Casale, a
spokesman at Monsanto, which is based in St. Louis. ``There's no
major step backward; it's now a matter of how much we'll grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Planting statistics are hard to come by so early in the farming
year, and some farm groups suspect the giant seed companies of
painting a overly rosy picture because they have so much riding on
this growing season. But interviews with more than two dozen
American farmers suggest that they are not drastically retreating
from biotechnology crops, partly because their share of the
European market is relatively small.
</P>
<P>
   About 80 percent of the corn and 60 percent of the soybeans
harvested in this country are used for domestic consumption and
animal feed, according to the Agriculture Department.
</P>
<P>
   At some of the nation's largest agriculture companies,
executives say it may be too late to turn back the clock on
genetically modified, or GM, crops; agriculture in the United
States is already geared toward producing large quantities of
biotechnology crops. Providing crops that are biotechnology-free
entails creating a more costly and cumbersome system to separate
the two kinds of produce, the executives say.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, ``the likelihood of commingling, we think, is very
high,'' said Lori Johnson, a spokeswoman at Cargill in Minneapolis.
``We tell customers we cannot guarantee 100 percent GM-free.''
</P>
<P>
   Some European food companies have asked for nonbiotechnology
crops this year, and the American grain handlers say they will try
their best.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you stopped right now, it'd take two years to get purity in
the system,'' said Gerald E. Smith, who farms about 2,200 acres in
Holstein, Iowa. ``There's an elevator in Nebraska looking for
non-GM. They want 98 percent purity, and they won't get it,'' he
said, because biotechnology crops are everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Smith says he is planting half his fields with gene-altered
seeds this year, down from 60 percent last year, just in case the
food companies change their minds. But he predicts that opposition
to biotechnology crops will eventually disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Curt Mowery, a farmer in Rosharon, Texas, agrees. ``I think a
lot of the fears are exaggerated,'' he said. ``In my mind, it's not
that much different from someone who gets a flu shot. They're using
a germ to immunize the corn.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Major farm organizations disagree over the future of
biotechnology plantings. Some say the seed companies _ which are
closely guarding preliminary planting statistics _ are playing down
farmer resistance and misrepresenting planting decisions farmers
have made.
</P>
<P>
   ``The companies are deceiving farmers into thinking their
neighbors are planting GM,'' said Gary Goldberg, the president of
the American Corn Growers Association, which predicts that
biotechnology corn plantings in the United States will decline as
much as 16 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
   The National Corn Growers Association, a much larger trade
group, disputes those figures, saying that biotechnology corn
planting has slipped, but not drastically. They say the decline is
largely because of the reduced threat of the European corn borer, a
major pest of corn in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what farmers decide now, they still have a little
time to change their mind. If those who ordered biotechnology seed
get a sense that grain handlers are wavering, or major food
companies won't accept the crops, they can cancel their seed
orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole situation is in turmoil,'' said Kent Boyer, 51, a
farmer in North Platte, Neb., who says that some livestock
producers in his area are cutting back on the amounts of
gene-altered grain in what they feed their animals and that some
grain farmers are considering abandoning biotechnology seeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the Europeans continue to express their concern, that could
flow into the U.S.,'' he said. ``Ultimately, the consumer is going
to decide whether they're going to accept the technology.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
