<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9196 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AUCTION-ANTITRUST-(TR     03-16 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUCTION-ANTITRUST-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUCTION FIRMS SAID TO SHARE CLIENT LISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL and CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sotheby's and Christie's, the world's two most
powerful auction houses, swapped confidential lists of superrich
clients who were spared from paying fees charged to other sellers,
people close to the companies and to a federal antitrust
investigation of them said.
</P>
<P>
   The shared and overlapping lists of about 50 names, which
include some of the world's wealthiest families, were described as
a crucial tool for the auction houses to use in enforcing a form of
price control in which certain customers were charged lower
commissions, down to zero, that both houses honored. At the same
time, both houses charged identical rates, up to 20 percent, to
other sellers who had little chance of negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual collaboration by the two longtime archrivals,
lawyers said, could figure into a prosecution for possible
price-fixing and other collusive practices under study by the
Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called grandfathered lists, as they were known at
Christie's and Sotheby's, were compiled separately by the two
companies and closely held by top executives. But in 1995, with the
art market in the doldrums, the two hard-pressed houses set new
sellers' commissions, which were higher and identical, generating
more income and leaving customers little room for bargaining.
According to closely matching accounts, they then shared the lists
of preferred customers so that they would each respect the other's
special deals and not cut new ones with people who were not named.
Because well-heeled sellers often converse with both houses and
many dealers, a low rate that was not recorded on the list could
easily be tracked through art world gossip, providing the houses
with a check on each other. Yet the two still sometimes breached
their agreements and betrayed each other, people close to the
companies said.
</P>
<P>
   At least five people with different links to both auction houses
and the investigation confirmed the list-sharing arrangement but,
citing the investigation, spoke only on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The identities of those on the lists were not disclosed, but
generally, those familiar with the lists said, the bigger the
seller, the lower the commission, down in many cases to zero.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   One former auction house official said that just before the
higher new sellers' commission went into effect, the company asked
top experts to compile a list of preferred clients to be
``grandfathered'' with lower fees.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the same former executive said, the beneficiaries
were then pressed to sell their goods through that auction house,
as a way of guaranteeing their presence on the preferred list.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the lists were physically traded or just the names
exchanged was not spelled out.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   One person involved in a civil lawsuit against Christie's and
Sotheby's cited the account of a seller who told of approaching one
house or the other seeking, in vain, to negotiate a lower fee.
</P>
<P>
   The customer then threatened to go to the rival house, only to
be told, ``You can go but you won't get anything better.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the lists, spokesmen for Christie's and Sotheby's
said Thursday that they would have no comment during the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The existence and sharing of customer lists was not mentioned in
an expanded complaint filed late Wednesday in Federal District
Court in Manhattan on behalf of a large group of buyers and sellers
who are suing Sotheby's and Christie's claiming that collusive
practices going back to at least 1993 cheated customers of untold
sums.
</P>
<P>
   The companies have not yet responded in court but are expected
to do so in coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The amended complaint, adding new details to previous
allegations, contended that in 1995, after both companies had
already fixed buyers' premiums, Sotheby's chairman and major
stockholder, A. Alfred Taubman, sought to extend the collusion to
sellers' fees in secret meetings with Christie's chairman, Sir
Anthony Tennant, and its chief executive, Christopher M. Davidge.
The complaint also contended that Sotheby's president, Diana D.
Brooks, held secret meetings in New York with a Christie's
counterpart, whom others have identified as Davidge. Brooks, others
have said, also traveled to London to meet with Christie's
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Linklater, a Chicago lawyer representing Davidge, and
Stephen E. Kaufman, a Manhattan lawyer retained by Brooks, said
they would have no comment.
</P>
<P>
   For three years Federal antitrust prosecutors have been
questioning a wide array of art world figures about possible
price-fixing and collusion in the famously secretive multibillion
dollar art world.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   People close to the investigation said the Justice Department
has been given notes of phone conversations between Taubman of
Sotheby's and Tennant of Christie's.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the prosecutors' questions, those who have been
contacted also say, involve regular meetings that took place
between the two auction giants and whether any matters discussed
raise antitrust issues.
</P>
<P>
   At least once, sometimes twice a year, employees from Sotheby's
and Christie's met to coordinate their sales schedules. Top-level
officials also met to discuss the possibility of holding auctions
in Paris, a market that has been closed to non-French auctioneers
for hundreds of years.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The preferred customer lists were compiled in 1995 when
Christie's announced it was changing the fee it charged sellers
from a flat commission of 10 percent to a more complex,
nonnegotiable sliding scale ranging from 2 percent to 20 percent
depending on the size of the sale. Weeks later Sotheby's did the
same.
</P>
<P>
   Three years before the seller's fees were changed, Sotheby's
announced an increase in the buyer's commission, up from a flat fee
of 10 percent. Seven weeks later Christie's followed suit.
</P>
<P>
   Collusion in setting either or both of these commissions would
constitute an illegal restraint of trade under the Sherman
Antitrust Act. Penalties for violations can include substantial
fines and imprisonment of up to three years.
</P>
<P>
   The companies, which control about 95 percent of the $4 billion
worldwide auction market, are facing more than 40 class-action law
suits filed against them by disgruntled buyers and sellers who
charge that they were victimized by collusion. And because
Sotheby's is a public company, unlike Christie's, it has been hit
with several shareholder lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 24, Davidge abruptly resigned from Christie's, and
Taubman resigned as chairman and Brooks as president of Sotheby's
on Feb. 21. All three have turned away repeated requests for
interviews.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 2238EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9197 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-TRADE-TEX     03-16 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TRADE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS SEND STEVENS TO EXPOS IN THREE-WAY DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUNEDIN, Fla. _ Willing to trade power for fewer strikeouts and
a higher on-base percentage, the Rangers sent Lee Stevens to the
Montreal Expos on Thursday and acquired David Segui from the
Toronto Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   To complete the three-team deal of first basemen/designated
hitters, the Expos sent Brad Fullmer to the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Segui is a better fit for our lineup,'' Rangers general
manager Doug Melvin said. ``That's what this trade comes down to.
We just felt David's able to put the ball in play a little more and
have a little better on-base percentage.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said the trade had nothing to do with Stevens' salary
arbitration case last month, and the financial considerations of
the deal support that. Stevens is signed for $3.5 million, while
Segui is signed for $4,325,000. To make up the difference, the Blue
Jays are paying the Rangers $825,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very tough,'' said Stevens, who was told of the trade
during the Rangers' 6-2 exhibition loss to the Blue Jays on
Thursday. ``I've been with this team a long time, more than any
other place. It feels like home. I've made a lot of friends here.
It's going to be tough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers liked Stevens' power but were concerned about his
high number of strikeouts. Stevens struck out 132 times in 517
at-bats last season. Segui's career high is 80 strikeouts in 522
at-bats in 1998 while with the Seattle Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Segui, a switch hitter, has a career on-base percentage of .352
compared with .319 for Stevens. But Stevens, who hit 24 home runs
and had 81 runs batted in last year, has a .453 career slugging
percentage compared with .436 for Segui.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates said he plans to bat Segui fifth in the
lineup behind Rafael Palmeiro and ahead of Ruben Mateo and Gabe
Kapler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Batting behind Raffy, he could drive in a lot of runs,'' Oates
said. ``When Lee's in one of his streaks, he can drive in a lot of
runs. But we wanted to get away from the strikeouts and make sure
we got someone who would put the ball in play.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Oates said, ``When you trade someone like Lee Stevens,
you don't get overly excited. He was always ready to play. The way
he went about his business, it was a pleasure for a manager.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason was that Stevens accepted his role as a designated
hitter even though he wanted to play first base. Segui, 33, found
himself in a similar position when he was acquired by the Blue Jays
on July 28 last year and wasn't happy about having to DH while
Carlos Delgado played first.
</P>
<P>
   Segui, who is expected to report to the Rangers on Saturday,
could not be reached for comment Thursday. Because he was a free
agent in the off-season and free agents can't be traded until after
June 1, Segui had to give his permission to be traded to the
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Palmeiro is the Rangers' regular first baseman but is
still having occasional trouble with his right knee. Palmeiro
underwent two operations on the knee last year and was forced to
play all but 28 games at designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``David will play some first base for us,'' Oates said. ``How
much, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   But Oates insisted Palmeiro's health had nothing to do with the
trade, pointing out that both Stevens and Segui are excellent
defensive players.
</P>
<P>
   From that standpoint, Stevens comes out ahead because he'll get
a chance to be the Expos' regular first baseman. But he'll be going
from a division champion to a team that was 68-94 last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough when you go from a club like this,'' Stevens said.
``Hopefully, I can help (the Expos) win a few more ballgames.
Nobody likes to finish last. They're trying to do something about
it; maybe I can be part of something special.''
DAVID SEGUI BIO Age: 33 Height: 6-1. Weight: 202 Bats: Both Throws:
Left
</P>
<P>
   CONTRACT: Makes $4,325,000 this season and is eligible for free
agency. Was eligible after last season but, after the New York Mets
signed Todd Zeile, found that nobody needed a first baseman.
Instead he accepted the Blue Jays' offer of salary arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL: Son of former major-league pitcher Diego Segui.
Drafted by the Baltimore Orioles in the 18th round of the 1987 June
amateur draft. Played for manager Johnny Oates from 1991-93 while
with the Orioles. This is his 11th major-league season and the
Rangers will be his sixth team.
</P>
<P>
   STATISTICS: Segui, a switch hitter, has a career batting average
of .285, including .282 against left-handers and .286 against
right-handers. He has 102 career homers, including a high of 21
with Montreal in 1997. He has hit .300 or better in three of his
past five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ANALYTICAL: The Rangers like Segui because he puts the ball in
play and doesn't strike out nearly as often as Stevens. He had a
career high 80 strikeouts in 522 at-bats in 1998, a relatively low
total for a first baseman. But his career-high slugging percentage
is .505, which is low for a first baseman. Segui also prefers to
play first base but will have to adjust to being a regular
designated hitter behind Rafael Palmeiro. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
