<SLUG> BC-BKW-TEXAS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TECH GETS EARLY EDGE WITH TOP-SEED SPOILS
</HEADLINE>
 TECH-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Think of the advantage if Duke played the first two rounds of
the men's NCAA Tournament inside the crazed confines of Cameron
Indoor Stadium. North Carolina in the Dean Dome. Arizona in the
McKale Center. Syracuse in the Carrier Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Pass Go, advance to Sweet 16 Parkway, collect $200.
</P>
<P>
   That's the advantage awarded to Texas Tech and the 15 other
top-seeded teams in the women's NCAA Tournament, which starts
Friday. Devised years ago to ensure larger crowds in the early
rounds, the top 16 seeds play host to four-team subregional
tournaments. In Lubbock, same as in Knoxville, Tenn., Storrs,
Conn., and other women's basketball havens, it's similar to feeding
the visitors to the lions.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Tech will get to show off its new United Spirit Arena. Its
24 luxury skyboxes are a nice touch, but the real charm of the
place is it packs in 15,000 frenzied fans. The Lady Raiders average
nearly 13,000 fans a game for the regular season, and the school
estimates it'll have close to capacity crowds for each of the three
tournament games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you have 12,000 people rooting for you and only for
you, of course, that's going to get your adrenaline pumping,''
senior forward Aleah Johnson said. ``We just love playing at home,
we love it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mideast Region's No. 14-seed Tennessee Tech (24-8) will be
the first to find out how much at 8:30 p.m. tomorrow when it faces
the 25-4 Lady Raiders, the No. 3 seed. No. 6 Tulane will face No.
11 Vermont in the early game at 6 p.m. The winners will meet at
8:05 p.m. on Monday with the victor advancing to the Mideast
Regional _ the Sweet 16 _ at The Pyramid in Memphis, Tenn., a
neutral site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're real excited to put that kind of crowd in here and share
the first two rounds of the tournament with our fans,'' Tech coach
Marsha Sharp said. ``We're undefeated here, so we hope it can stay
that way two more games.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, Texas Tech is 11-1 in tournament games played in
Lubbock, until this year at the old Municipal Stadium. This is the
third consecutive year, and eight of nine, that Tech will have
played host to early-round tournament games.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Raiders are 14-0 at home this season, winning by an
average of 23.2 points.
</P>
<P>
   So, should the strongest teams receive home-court advantage in a
64-team tournament? The NCAA is tinkering with changes. Sharp said
a proposal has been made to have early-round games at
``predetermined sites'' with schools bidding to get the game by
guaranteeing ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   Vermont coach Mike Cieplicki, whose team will travel more than
2,000 miles and will stretch its athletic department's budget by
spending $1,943 per person for a round-trip ticket to play in
Lubbock, said he'd rather make the logistic nightmare of a trip
than have revenue potential become an influential factor in
determining host sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there is a significant advantage for the host, but
if part of that is earned, which it is in the NCAA Tournament, then
that's a little more fair,'' he said. ``If it just comes down to
which city happens to get the cheapest hotels so they can get a
better bid, then that's where I struggle more in the fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharp and Cieplicki believe eventually tournament games will be
played at neutral sites as women's basketball continues to grow.
Until then, Sharp will have her team ready to play and have fun
showing off their new arena _ and likely use it as a springboard to
the Sweet 16. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
