<SLUG> BC-GLF-BAYHILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGH IS HOPING RIVALS BRING OUT HIS BEST
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ More than a year has passed since Vijay Singh's
last victory. And for a player of Singh's caliber, a year between
victories seems like a very long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't win, then it's a disappointing season for me,''
said Singh, whose last victory was at the Honda Classic in March
1999. ``I'm eager to win again. That's my next goal, to win a golf
tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh may reach that goal this weekend if he continues to play
like he did Thursday. Overcoming bogeys on his first two holes,
Singh finished with a 4-under 68 to tie Duffy Waldorf for first
place after the opening round of the Bay Hill Invitational. Tiger
Woods was one stroke off the lead at 69, tied for third place with
Brent Geiberger, Paul Goydos, Dudley Hart, Jonathan Kaye, Mike
Nicolette and David Toms. Hart won the Honda Classic last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   For Singh, a victory this week would be the best way to prepare
for The Players Championship next week and the Masters next month.
Like all of the world's top players, Singh has reached the point
where he no longer worries about making money or finishing in the
top 10. He is ranked No. 6 in the world, he finished fourth on the
PGA Tour's money list last year and he has finished no lower than
17th on the money list in every year since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   At age 37, winning is what really matters to Singh, and he hopes
to capitalize on this week's opportunity. Singh had an excellent
chance to win last month at Pebble Beach, when he entered the final
round one stroke off the lead. But after falling five strokes
behind on the back nine, Singh lost his concentration, figuring he
had no chance to win. Instead, Matt Gogel stumbled on the back nine
and Woods made a miraculous comeback, overcoming a seven-stroke
deficit with seven holes to play to win his sixth consecutive tour
start. Singh settled for a second-place tie, and he admitted that
he learned a lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had played all the hard holes, I didn't think he was going
to mess up,'' Singh said of Gogel. ``But he came back to the field,
I made one or two bogeys and Tiger made a bunch of birdies going
in. I had a good chance if I kept playing. I gave up a little bit
when I bogeyed No. 14, but I shouldn't have stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who stops making birdies this weekend may be overtaken by
Woods again. Woods looked fresh and sharp after his two-week break,
in a round that included five birdies and two bogeys. Singh would
love to triumph over a field that includes 12 of the top 16 players
in the world rankings. With Arnold Palmer as the host, Bay Hill
always attracts a strong field. Singh hopes the competition brings
out his best. ``Before the tournament starts, you kind of look at
the list and see who's playing and who's not,'' Singh said. ``The
field is strong. But once we tee it up, we don't' worry about who's
playing. We worry about our own game.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
