<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEM ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: The (plus) and (minus) words should be replaced with the
symbol)  
 (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a Look at Low Taxes, High Marks for Wyoming &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you want to hold onto as much of your money as possible, move
to Wyoming, advises Bloomberg Personal Finance magazine, which
recently measured the tax bite of each state and the District of
Columbia for four hypothetical families.
</P>
<P>
   Wyoming took the daintiest of nibbles, and was given an A(plus)
in the survey, to be published in the April issue. The state was
ranked first, both over all and in the area of retirement taxation.
Rhode Island chowed down on taxpayers, ranking 51st in both
categories, according to the survey; its grade was F. But the state
had company in the Northeast. New York was 49th over all, Vermont
46th, Maine 45th and Washington, D.C., 42nd.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Wyoming, states in the wealth-friendly top 10 were
Nevada, Washington, Tennessee, Alaska, Florida, Louisiana, South
Dakota, Texas and Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was heading for Laramie, Steve Gittelson, the
magazine's editor, laughed. ``My sister moved out there,'' he said,
``and I think she made a smart move, but she didn't do it for that
reason.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more to life than taxes,'' added Gittelson, whose
office is in Princeton, N.J. Still, wealth-friendliness could be a
factor in deciding where to live, he said, especially as
telecommuting lets more people work wherever they choose.
</P>
<P>
   Montanans, for example, might want to move to Wyoming. Their
state ranked 50th in both categories. Other states in the bottom 10
over all were Nebraska, 43rd; Oregon, 44th; Wisconsin, 47th; and
Minnesota, 48th.
</P>
<P>
   A surprise in the survey was Massachusetts, which may be
shedding its ``Taxachusetts'' moniker. It ranked 35th overall and
41st for retirement. Its grade was C(minus). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jan M. Rosen &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
