<HEADLINE>
NASA'S RELIANCE ON RUSSIA QUESTIONED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House budget writers, who have long criticized the
Clinton administration's reliance on Russia to complete the
International Space Station, questioned Thursday whether NASA
officials have compromised the station's safety by accepting
Russia's faulty work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is NASA lowering safety standards in order for Russia to
participate?'' asked Rep. Dana Rohrabacher, R-Calif., chairman of
the House Space and Aeronautics Subcommittee. ``I am very concerned
that the administration has been bending over so far backward to
keep Russia involved that they may have jeopardized safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Rothenberg, associate administrator for NASA's human
spaceflight program, assured committee members that Russia has met
all the major safety standards and is working to fix any remaining
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not treating the Russians any differently than our own
civil servants and contractors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The questions came during a subcommittee hearing on the human
spaceflight program's $5.5 billion budget request for fiscal year
2001.
</P>
<P>
   Also testifying was Allen Li, associate director of the General
Accounting Office's National Security and International Affairs
Division, who was asked to review Russia's compliance with safety
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Li, whose final report on the issue is expected next month,
agreed that Russia has done a good job for the most part, but he
outlined some safety concerns:
</P>
<P>
   _ The station's Russian-built service module, also known as the
crew module _ which is critical to life-support, propulsion and
power generation _ does not have adequate shielding to protect it
from orbiting debris.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Zarya, a Russian component launched in 1998, and the
service module, which is to be launched this summer, will not be
able to operate if cabin pressure is lost.
</P>
<P>
   _ The service module's window design has not been approved.
</P>
<P>
   _ Excessive noise levels in Zarya and the service module could
result in permanent hearing damage to the crew.
</P>
<P>
   Li and Rothenberg said the problems can be resolved, even after
the components have been launched. For example, plans are already
under way to improve the service module's shielding in orbit
because if additional shielding were added before launch, the
module would be too heavy for lift-off.
</P>
<P>
   The most cumbersome problem, it seems, may be that the first
crew aboard the space station may have to wear some type of ear
muff to protect their hearing until they can install additional
insulation.
</P>
<P>
   NASA officials are concerned that crew members won't wear the
uncomfortable ear protection and that if they do wear them, they
might not be able to hear caution and warning signals in the event
of an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   When completed in 2005, the space station will provide research
facilities for a permanent crew of seven. The station, which
involves 16 nations, is a crucial first step in launching an
eventual human mission to Mars, and also is expected to aid medical
and scientific research on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the National Research Council urged NASA to
consider paying financially ailing Russia for equipment and
services the country had once promised to donate to the U.S.-led
international space station.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 2243EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
