<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0406 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9203 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-RAMSEY-MEDIASAGA17-CO     03-16 1346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMSEY-MEDIASAGA17-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1ST UPDATE
 &HT;    EDs: Updates first 3 grafs; DO NOT USE earlier versions
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Media blitz by Ramseys starts today
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If only Lt. Columbo were here, investigating the
murder of JonBenet Ramsey.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we are a nation of armchair Columbos, always turning
and asking just one more question, but with the truth as elusive as
ever.
</P>
<P>
   The maw of television opens wide again, the Internet
hyperventilates with invective, the whodunit rattles our national
cage.
</P>
<P>
   ``This story has moved beyond something that is merely
newsworthy to become a communal event, an experience,'' says
Matthew R. Kerbel, author of ``If It Bleeds, It Leads,'' a new book
that presents a scorching analysis of television news.
</P>
<P>
   Today marks a peak, if not in actual news, then in the communal
event that is our fascination with the Ramsey case. John and Patsy
Ramsey's book, ``The Death of Innocence'' (Thomas Nelson Inc.,
$24.99) goes on sale today, with a first printing of 300,000 copies
(several bookstores around the country jumped the gun, claiming to
be unaware of the publisher's embargo). At 10 tonight, ABC airs a
Barbara Walters interview with the Ramseys on ``20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   The publicity drumbeat continues next week with a live Internet
chat with the Ramseys at 10 p.m. Monday on the Web site ABC.com; a
five-part interview with Katie Couric on NBC's ``Today'' show; and
then a March 27 appearance on ``Larry King Live.'' The true
newsworthiness of any of these interviews is debatable; the Ramseys
say exactly what they said on CNN on Jan. 1, 1997, and on a British
documentary that ran on A&AMP;E in 1998: that they are innocent, that
they did not kill their 6-year-old daughter on Dec. 26, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``The audience loves it, and I'm curious to a point, but there's
got to be something new,'' CNN's King said in January. ``I don't
think there's been any real development in the last 12 shows we've
done.''
</P>
<P>
   The book publication and media blitz are new, but that's not
necessarily the same as being news.
</P>
<P>
   The very notion of ``news'' in the Ramsey case has been
slippery, as the level of journalism has been a shocking mixture of
laziness and aggressiveness resulting in a blur of misinformation
and misleading leaks that surpasses even Clinton-Lewinsky, along
with the usual speculation, blind alleys and ax-grinding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm amazed that the whole world doesn't think we're guilty,
given what they've been told,'' John Ramsey tells Walters in
tonight's interview. And, indeed, many do think that he, his wife
or both are guilty and see their book and the well-orchestrated TV
appearances as a cynical manipulation. But many others see the
Ramseys as innocent, unjustly persecuted by a Boulder, Colo.,
police force that rushed to judgment and by a ravenous media in
which distinctions between tabloid and mainstream journalism no
longer hold.
</P>
<P>
   The book itself, ``The Death of Innocence'' _ the 10th book
about the case _ is 396 grueling pages in which the Ramseys
describe the last three years and three months in detail, outline
the case that an intruder killed JonBenet and wreak extended
vengeance on the Boulder police and the national media. Although
the supermarket tabloid The Globe draws their strongest criticism
(Geraldo Rivera is second), they also jab at CNN, citing their
devastation when they heard former talk show host Mary Tillotson
say that JonBenet looked like ``a hooker'' when she dressed for
child beauty pageants. They refer to MSNBC (the cable venture of
NBC and Microsoft) as ``the video tabloid brought to us by Bill
Gates and GE.'' (General Electric owns NBC.)
</P>
<P>
   But frequently in ``The Death of Innocence,'' the media are just
an undifferentiated mob, a perpetual stalking machine both in
Colorado and in Atlanta, where the Ramseys now live.
</P>
<P>
   They turned down nearly all interview requests; ``we did not
feel obligated to fill their time slots with macabre
entertainment,'' they write.
</P>
<P>
   TOUGH BUT NOT VICIOUS
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, there is no other way to publicize their book
than to present themselves as ``macabre entertainment'' in the
media they despise. Thomas Nelson, a Nashville, Tenn., Christian
publishing house, set up the carefully calibrated appearances on
the couple's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted these interviews to air when the book is in
bookstores,'' says Jeff Zucker, executive producer of ``Today.''
``If we hadn't agreed, they wouldn't have taped it.'' So Couric
interviewed the Ramseys in late February, as did Walters, and their
news organizations agreed in advance not to air the interviews
until the book's release.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not unique,'' says Zucker. ``We've seen this on other
books of major interest; Colin Powell's book comes to mind.''
</P>
<P>
   If this extended dance is indeed about news, it's just as much
about promotion. But as author Kerbel notes, ``The public creates
the demand; the media feeds the demand.''
</P>
<P>
   On ``20/20'' tonight, Walters is tough but not vicious,
definitely not in her supersympathetic mode. She tells the couple
that to many people, the videos of JonBenet in beauty pageants look
``perverted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That didn't come from JonBenet; that came from the viewer,''
Patsy responds.
</P>
<P>
   Walters also reviews the evidence that an intruder killed
JonBenet (as does the current Newsweek), but the show is aimed more
at casual followers of the case than the hard-core obsessives.
</P>
<P>
   For the latter, the Internet is the medium of choice. The Ramsey
case is unmeasurably huge in cyberspace. One popular Web page lists
118 links to the case, and each link leads to countless more. Susan
Bennett, a North Carolina homemaker whose Internet site led to her
becoming friends with the Ramseys, being questioned by police and
being threatened by Internet crazies, has a time line of the case
that runs more than 3,000 printed pages. She also runs one of the
many Internet forums, where thousands of people speculate endlessly
(and sometimes mindlessly) about the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hobby for some,'' says Bennett. ``Some are there
because they really care about JonBenet; some are there because
their lives are lacking something.'' She agrees with the notion
that many, but not all, Ramsey case fanatics are armchair
detectives, sifting through the clues in an effort to solve the
case.
</P>
<P>
   A REAL-LIFE WHODUNIT NOVEL
</P>
<P>
   While Bennett's site is independent but pro-Ramsey, other sites
argue so strongly for the guilt of one or both parents that an
Internet acronym was coined, based on a ``Star Trek'' alien race:
BORG, for ``Bent On Ramsey Guilt.'' Even the sleaziest print and
broadcast media outposts have at least some standards _ fear of
libel, if nothing else _ but the Ramsey obsessives on the Net, many
of whom post using anonymous names, are completely unfettered. They
attack the Ramseys, the police, the district attorney and one
another.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Patsy and I have lived through might go down in history
as the first cyberspace lynching,'' John Ramsey declares in
``Innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have here is the blurring of the line between reality
and fiction,'' says Kerbel. ``A real murder happened. People then
latched onto the mystery of it, the celebrity, and became
captivated by it, as if it was a whodunit novel.'' This one,
though, had more clues than any self-respecting ``Columbo'' would
ever allow: the bizarre ransom note, the stun gun, the DNA, the
garotte, the duct tape, the shoeprint, the snow outside the house
(or lack of it).
</P>
<P>
   ``So we beat on, boats against the current, borne back
ceaselessly into the past.'' F. Scott Fitzgerald closed his novel
``The Great Gatsby'' with that line 75 years ago. Now it describes
us all: the media talking heads, the cybersleuths, even the Ramseys
themselves. The nature of modern news, with every day a new cycle,
makes it seem as if we're moving forward. But we really just keep
going back, and going back, trying to figure it out.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
