<HEADLINE>
A CHALLENGER FOR KENNEDY; PUSH FOR UNION CANDIDATES; BUSH
APPOINTEES AND MESSAGE WIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A CHALLENGER FOR KENNEDY
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts has accumulated a hefty
$3.6 million in his re-election fund. And that money, along with
the Kennedy name and 36 years of incumbency, were enough Thursday
to scare off one potential Republican foe, District Attorney
Michael Sullivan of Plymouth County.
</P>
<P>
   But no sooner had Sullivan said that he would not run than
another Republican, Jack E. Robinson III, announced that he would
take on the senator. In fact, Robinson, a 39-year-old cell phone
entrepreneur, said he planned to use up to $1 million of his own
money to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely a long shot,'' he conceded. ``We're the
underdog. But at the end of the day, ideas are going to win out.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, a Boston-born African-American whose father once
headed the city's NAACP chapter, is seeking to be the third
popularly elected African-American senator since the Civil War. He
has never held political office. But state Republican leaders see
him as the party's last best hope as a Kennedy challenger, in part
because the state has a strong civil rights record but also because
they believe his fiscally conservative, socially moderate approach
to politics, including support for abortion rights, will appeal to
a broad spectrum of Massachusetts voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be reaching out not only to Republicans, but to
Democrats and independents as well,'' said John Brockelman,
executive director of the Massachusetts Republican Party. ``He's
going to run under the Republican reform banner.''
</P>
<P>
   PUSH FOR UNION CANDIDATES
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John J. Sweeney, the AFL-CIO president, came to New
York Thursday to promote an ambitious effort by big labor to have
at least 2,000 union members run for office nationwide this year,
from campaigns for school boards to campaigns for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Too many of the nation's elected officials, he said, come from
big wealth, with at least 1 of every 4 members of Congress being a
millionaire. But, he declared at a news conference, big labor's
``2,000 in 2000'' program would help rectify that by ensuring that
the voices of the less well off were represented in the halls of
power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our program,'' Sweeney said, ``aims to change the face of
elected America and make sure working families' voices are heard by
running union members for office.''
</P>
<P>
   BUSH APPOINTEES AND MESSAGE WIN
</P>
<P>
   Two of Gov. George W. Bush's minority appointees won Republican
primaries in Texas on Tuesday, giving a boost to his effort to make
his party more inclusive in the Lone Star state and also providing
some underpinning to his assertion that as president he would be an
inclusive leader.
</P>
<P>
   Neither faces Democratic opposition in the fall, so both are
assured final victory.
</P>
<P>
   They are Michael Williams, who won election to the Texas
Railroad Commission in his own right, having earlier been given an
interim appointment by the governor, and Al Gonzales, who won a
seat on the state Supreme Court in his own right after an interim
appointment by the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who served earlier as Bush's secretary of state, is an
African-American, the first ever to win a nonjudicial statewide
election in Texas. Gonzales is Latino.
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, Bush appeared in television commercials
supporting both.
</P>
</TEXT>
