<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PRELUDES-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEY, MONEY, MONEY. GUILT, GUILT, GUILT.  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 19) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Colo., Calif.)   (af)  
 By ABBY ELLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every day, I thank God that I'm not an Internet billionaire,
that my last name isn't Kennedy or Rockefeller and that no one is
paying me $20 million to star in a movie. After all, if I were
worth an outrageous amount of money, who knows the trauma that
would await?
</P>
<P>
   At a minimum, I'd be paralyzed by choices, smothered by
possibilities. According to the Forum for Investor Advice, only 42
percent of people who come into large sums initially react with
happiness or excitement; one in four express anxiety or numbness,
even guilt. Emile Durkheim, the French sociologist, thought
unexpected wealth could lead to suicide.
</P>
<P>
   With luck, before I ever reached that point I'd find a fiscal
therapist, someone well-versed in the malaise that practitioners
call ``affluenza'' or ``sudden wealth syndrome.''
</P>
<P>
   Trust-fund children and lottery or game-show winners have the
hardest time; they didn't work for their money, ``so there's a
disparity between their net worth and self-worth,'' said Myra
Salzer, president of the Wealth Conservancy, a financial planning
firm in Boulder, Colo., dedicated to helping heirs ``integrate with
and take control over'' their wealth. Her fee is a percentage of
the client's assets, with a minimum of $5,000 a quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``My clients tend to be young, and they feel guilty and
undeserving,'' she said. ``They've almost been denied an
opportunity to see what they can do for themselves. So their goal
in life is not to screw up their money, as opposed to seeing what
they can build for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   To help, she conducts a four-day seminar called ``Inherited
Wealth and You'' twice a year in Aspen. Scions gather to lament
their riches in a ``safe place where it's OK to talk about money
and put it into perspective.'' Salzer is not advocating that anyone
feel sorry for young heirs, but she does think that they need an
arena where they can be who they are. For $1,475 (plus hotel and
air fare), she provides it.
</P>
<P>
   Things are a little different in Silicon Valley where more than
60 new millionaires are said to be minted each day. Because
Internet millionaires, like celebrities, tend to have worked in
some manner for their money, most feel more entitled to it than do
those who inherited their wealth. Still, many can't handle it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money used to be called the root of evil; now it's the root of
stress and confusion,'' said Dr. Stephen Goldbart, a
psychotherapist and co-founder of the Money, Meaning and Choices
Institute in San Francisco. ``Many of the dot-commers had no idea
that at such a young age they'd have enough money they'd no longer
have to work. They buy two or three houses, a car, spend money on
stuff. And when that hasn't done it for them, they become
depressed, empty and uncertain about what to do with their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldbart and his co-director, Joan DiFuria, came up with the
term ``sudden wealth syndrome'' to describe a condition in which
people with quick riches isolate themselves, become obsessed with
the stock market and feel embarrassed, scared and unable to accept
that the money is really theirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``SWS triggers a massive identity crisis, an early midlife
crisis,'' Goldbart said.
</P>
<P>
   The recovery process has three stages: recognizing the impact of
the wealth on one's life, regaining control of one's life and
coming up with a new set of priorities and goals.
</P>
<P>
   Like Salzer, Goldbart doesn't believe that we should feel sorry
for the very rich, but that we do need to acknowledge their issues.
``Think about it,'' he said. ``What would you do if you suddenly
had $35 million?''
</P>
<P>
   I didn't have an immediate answer. But after some pondering, I
decided I would dedicate the rest of my life to helping others in
similar situations. I'd open a soup kitchen for those so
immobilized by their riches that they were unable to order in. I'd
hold bake sales and give the proceeds to the ``Money Doesn't Buy
Happiness'' Foundation. It would be tough, but I'd take it one day
at a time and, somehow, find the inner strength and power to cope. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Abby Ellin is a Manhattan writer. Her column on starting out in
the world of money appears the third Sunday of each month. E-mail:
preludes(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
