<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-METEOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RARE METEORITE COULD TELL HOW SUN, PLANETS FORMED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Fragments of a rare form of meteorite that made a
spectacular landfall in the frozen wilderness of Canada's northern
Rocky Mountains earlier this year may hold important new clues
about the materials that formed the sun and the planets, scientists
at NASA's Johnson Space Center said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   There is a high likelihood the secrets locked within space rocks
have been preserved by uninterrupted cold since well before the
solar system was formed an estimated 4.5 billion years ago, said
Michael Zolensky, a NASA cosmic mineralogist.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my career this will be the only time this happens,'' said
an elated Zolensky, as he displayed a sample at the Lunar and
Planetary Science Conference under way at Johnson Space Center this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are hopeful that as the fragments are cut into
sections and examined with electron microscopes and other high-tech
instruments, they will reveal the presence of amino acids, some of
the most critical building blocks of life, and other complex
chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   The findings could help scientists determine whether the water
on the Earth and the chemical precursors for life arrived within
the meteorites and comets that theorists believe bombarded the
Earth and the other planets for hundreds of millions of years after
the formation of the solar system.
</P>
<P>
   The fragments were recovered from the snow and ice without
contamination from human touch, thanks to the efforts of alert
Canadian authorities and the scientifically minded citizen of
British Columbia who found the first charred pieces of the
meteorite.
</P>
<P>
   Carefully preserved in a freezer, a dozen small pieces of the
find were flown to the contamination-free laboratories of the Earth
Sciences and Solar System Exploration Division at JSC.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian and U.S. authorities are working out arrangements with
the unidentified owner of the meteorite. When the arrangements are
completed, they plan to slice into the meteorite and study its
contents in Houston. So far, NASA scientists have been allowed only
a cursory examination.
</P>
<P>
   However, they were able to quickly determine it is a
carbonaceous chondrite, a class of very primitive meteorite filled
with many kinds of carbon-based elements and other organic
material, some containing water bound into the molecular structure.
Carbonaceous chondrites comprise about 2 percent of the meteorites
recovered from the Earth. The most recent similar find occurred 30
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Critics will find it tough to dispute whatever scientists find
in the meteorite because of the care that was taken to prevent
terrestrial contamination. That was not the case with previous
carbonaceous chondrites found in the Antarctic and the African
desert.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might have been washed first in someone's home or passed
hand to hand before you ever saw it,'' said Zolensky. ``Here, for
the first time, we have an organically rich material which has been
kept very, very clean, about as clean as you can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The fragments at Johnson Space Center appear charred and pitted
and porous. They are light to lift and smell of sulphur, said those
who have examined them.
</P>
<P>
   The meteorite fell to Earth in northern British Columbia in the
pre-dawn hours of Jan. 18, said Richard Herd, curator of Canada's
national meteorite collection.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling at more than(60,000 mph on a south-southeasterly
trajectory, the high-velocity meteorite exploded at least twice in
spectacular fireballs as it soared above the towns of Whitehorse
and Carcross. No injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was observed by thousands of people,'' Herd said. ``It left
a very large contrail in the sky, which was seen for the better
part of an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on readings from seismic instruments that detected shock
waves from the explosions and infrared images that were detected by
U. S. military missile-warning satellites and other analyses,
experts estimate the meteorite was 50 feet across and weighed more
than 50 tons, or about the size of a bus.
</P>
<P>
   The searing heat of the high-speed entry into the Earth's
atmosphere formed a black crust on the exterior of the fragments
without heating the interior, Zolensky said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Herd, the spectacular fireball coincided with a
well-publicized test of American ballistic missile weaponry,
alarming many residents of northern British Columbia and the
southern Yukon who witnessed the contrail.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Canadian authorities issued public assurances that
there was no danger. Then they began asking the residents of the
sparsely populated region to look for signs of the fallen
meteorite.
</P>
<P>
   Zolensky mobilized a high-altitude NASA aircraft to fly along
the meteorite's path. It had special airborne collectors designed
to gather meteorite debris still in the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   By late January, Canadian authorities urged anyone who found
fragments from a meteorite not to handle the rocks. They included
instructions on how to collect the fragments with plastic bags and
to keep them in ice.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy paid off. On Feb. 3, authorities were alerted by a
Canadian citizen that he had found fragments on or near his land.
His request to remain anonymous was granted by the Canadian
government.
</P>
<P>
   By Feb. 7, a dozen fragments, the largest about the size of a
lump of charcoal and the smallest the size of a fingernail, began
arriving at Johnson Space Center, the same NASA facility that keeps
the moon rocks gathered by the Apollo astronauts in the late 1960s
and early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian authorities did not have the laboratories, equipment or
personnel with experience to analyze the rocks, Herd said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
