<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9215 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-TAXES-ART-$ADV19-     03-16 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-TAXES-ART-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET TIMING? MAYBE TAX TIMING IS BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Graphic of breaks for the self-employed is being sent to
NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 888 603-1036 or 888 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 19)  
 (af)  
 By SANA SIWOLOP   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Jacqueline Buford, 45, a real estate relocation manager,
decided late last year that her home in White Plains, N.Y., needed
some repairs, she was tempted to dip into her portfolio of taxable
mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   But selling fund shares at the time would have meant a large tax
bite this April. So Buford now plans to sell a portion of her funds
this spring, delaying the tax consequences for a year. She and her
husband, meanwhile, are also planning to make regular contributions
this year to their church's building fund, and they expect the
resulting charitable deduction to offset the capital gains tax she
expects to incur from the mutual fund sale.
</P>
<P>
   That's smart. But from a tax standpoint, an even better approach
would be to donate appreciated securities to the church or another
charity and let it sell them. The donor gets a deduction for the
full market value without having to pay capital gains tax; the
charity, of course, pays no tax, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't thought of doing this, but it is something that I
would consider,'' said Buford, who is also president of the
Hudson-Housatonic chapter of the National Association of Investors
Corp., an educational group. ``Whenever we take distributions, we
try to take them earlier in the year, so that we can balance them
against charitable contributions, as well as against our entire
income picture. We're always, always contemplating tax issues.''
</P>
<P>
   As more Americans become active market traders, investors like
Buford should be the rule, rather than the exception, financial
planners say. But many planners report that the opposite seems to
be true: Too many investors ignore the tax consequences of their
market moves, thus generating unexpected tax bills. That is
especially the case for investors who are playing the markets in a
fast and furious way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see investors paying attention to taxes at all _
they're more interested in chasing profits,'' said Valerie
Lasher-Adelman, a certified financial planner and the founder of
Chestnut Financial in Bronx, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Lasher-Adelman said many of her clients had begun to ask about
buying individual stocks; two years ago, they were happy with
mutual funds. If they buy stocks and hold onto them, that could
have the happy consequence of lowering their taxes; mutual funds,
after all, pay out taxable capital gains even if you don't sell
shares. Still, she added, ``if investors these days are paying
attention to taxes, they're not doing it in a focused way.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosilyn Overton, a certified financial planner at Mid-Atlantic
Investments in Queens, N.Y., is more blunt. ``Investors are simply
not paying attention to tax consequences whatsoever,'' she said,
adding that many even seemed unaware of the sizable tax bite that
comes from selling appreciated stocks or other securities too soon.
</P>
<P>
   When a security is held less than a year, the capital gain is
taxable at the same rate as ordinary income _ 15 percent to 39.6
percent. But there is a break for longer-term gains. Taxpayers in
the 15 percent bracket pay just 10 percent on such gains, while
investors in the 28 percent to 39.6 percent brackets pay 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
   For an investor in the 28 percent bracket who has a capital gain
of $5,000, that would amount to a tax bill of $1,000, versus $1,400
on a short-term gain. Overton, however, said that many investors
persisted in ``looking at the tax difference as an 8 percent,
rather than a 40 percent difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, she said, frequent traders also seem unaware of
so-called wash sale rules. Usually, if a stock is sold at a loss,
that loss will offset gains on other sales. If net losses exceed
net gains, up to $3,000 can be used to offset earned income, with
any excess carried forward to future years.
</P>
<P>
   But under the wash sale rules, those tax breaks are not
available to traders who buy more of the same shares during the 30
days before or after the sale that yielded the loss.
</P>
<P>
   For certain investors, active trading may pose even greater tax
risks. Consider a resident of Rockland County in New York, a widow
in her late 60s who recently entered the stock market for the first
time, enticed by its outsized returns in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The widow, who spoke on condition of anonymity because she lives
alone, said she wanted to increase the small income she had been
receiving from her late husband's sizable investment portfolio,
which had been entirely in tax-free municipal bond funds. She sold
the bond fund shares in January and put the proceeds into taxable
mutual funds, hoping that she would be able to supplement her
income by making monthly withdrawals from the funds as they grew in
value.
</P>
<P>
   ``My accountant told me not to worry, but I'm still nervous,''
she said. ``For one, I want to hold on to my principal. But I'm
also concerned about how much I have to set aside for taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Be prepared for a triple tax whammy, Lasher-Adelman advised. She
said the widow could expect to pay taxes on any dividends that were
paid by her funds, capital gains taxes on any stocks that the funds
sold at a profit and at least a 28 percent capital gains tax on any
portion of her funds that she held for less than a year before
selling.
</P>
<P>
   To play it safe, Lasher-Adelman suggested that the widow set
aside 40 percent of her capital gains for tax purposes. Longer
term, however, Lasher-Adelman is worried that if the market turns
bearish, the widow may have to dip into her principal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have preferred it if this investor had kept perhaps a
third to a half of her money in the municipal bond funds, to give
her a sense of security and to reduce the bite of what is now a
very taxable situation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Overton's advice was even more conservative. She said she would
have liked to see the widow keep at least two-thirds of her
portfolio in bonds. ``I spend a good part of my day talking retired
people out of buying the stock du jour,'' she said. ``People are
becoming more aggressive than what is appropriate for their
circumstances, and that is certainly not helping their taxes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 2249EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0411 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9216 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-LIFE-INSURANCE-AR     03-16 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-LIFE-INSURANCE-ART-2TAKES-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING FOR TERM LIFE INSURANCE AS RATES RISE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Graphic of best rates for term life insurance is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 19)  
 (af)  
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The life insurance industry is battening down its hatches _ and
consumers, it turns out, will pay the price.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, prices for term life, the most popular kind of
life insurance, had been declining for more than a decade. But new
regulations requiring insurers to set aside more money to cover
their potential payouts have caused rates for many policies to jump
20 percent to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Before the new rules started taking effect on Jan. 1, a
45-year-old Pennsylvania man in excellent health, to pick a typical
example, could get $500,000 of coverage at a guaranteed annual
premium of $690 for 20 years from Transamerica Occidental Life
Insurance, a leading seller of term life, according to
AccuQuote.com, an online insurance agency. Now, that coverage is
selling for $850, an increase of about 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The regulations, which do not affect whole life policies, are
being adopted state by state. They bring prices elsewhere in the
country closer to levels in New York, where reserve requirements _
and hence prices _ have long been the highest in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Later this year, New York is expected to ease reserve
requirements, putting its insurers on an equal footing with the
rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
   What's a consumer to do? It is more important than ever to shop
around. Rates now range more widely, and there is greater variety
in the policies being offered, most intended to save a customer
money in the short run but with the risk that costs will rise
considerably in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts advise consumers to just bite the bullet by locking
in a policy for the typical 20 years at the higher rates. There are
options, but they involve extra risk.
</P>
<P>
   If you are thinking about life insurance, of course, you must
first decide whether you need it. Most experts say that comes down
to whether your death would leave your dependents in a financial
lurch. But you may not need the typical 20-year policy; a 10-year
policy might suffice, for example, to protect a child who is now
12.
</P>
<P>
   If you decide to get life insurance, remember that postponing
the purchase is risky. Insurance costs more the older you get, and
insurers love to tell tales of customers who died while mulling
things over.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, you might qualify for a policy from a company that has
not yet raised its prices. It is also possible, experts say, that
some companies will not set higher premiums but will instead absorb
the higher expense to gain market share.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a 20-year policy essentially identical to the one
for which Transamerica is now charging $850 can be purchased for
$690 a year from John Hancock Financial Services, which has not
raised its rates.
</P>
<P>
   Other options are riskier. You could buy a less expensive
10-year policy with a guaranteed annual flat rate, betting that
premiums will drop after that period and that you can buy a new
policy at a lower rate.
</P>
<P>
   After all, many experts say the price rise may be reversed in
two or three years as the insurance industry updates the tables on
which reserves are based. If you think prices may drop sooner
rather than later, you could buy coverage year to year, with costs
rising each year. That would cost less to start, but annual
premiums would exceed those for a 10-year policy after the third
year.
</P>
<P>
   But all of that is a gamble. Even if overall rates are lower
after 10 years, you will almost certainly have to pay higher
premiums when you are a decade older. There is also the risk that
your health will have deteriorated and that you will either have to
pay much more for a new policy or even be unable to get coverage at
any price.
</P>
<P>
   Another strategy to keep initial costs down is to get a policy
in which coverage is guaranteed for 20 years, but the premium is
fixed for only a portion of that time _ and, indeed, can later rise
considerably.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies are offering such plans. The Banner Life
Insurance Co., for instance, has a 20-year policy for a healthy,
45-year-old man that costs $655 a year. But that rate is guaranteed
for only five years; afterwards, the company advises, the annual
premium could shoot up to $3,720, and it could keep rising to a
peak of $16,200 in the final year of coverage.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Insurers have never charged those worst-case premiums, but
quoting them lets the company set aside smaller reserves and shift
to customers the risk of paying more if its claims and other
expenses increase.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio National Life Insurance Co. is selling a 20-year policy
with the same initial premium _ $655 a year _ and with a similar
proviso about rates rising, but after just three years instead of
five.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts say such drastic increases would never occur.
Steven A. Smith, chief actuary of the First Colony Life Insurance
Co., another leader in term life sales, says they would be
suicidal. ``People would just stop buying your insurance,'' he
said, noting that policyholders can cancel term life coverage at
anytime without additional charges.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the risk of a price increase _ whether small or large _
falls on the customer's shoulders. Glenn S. Daily, an insurance
consultant in New York, said, ``People have no idea what risk they
are taking when they sign up for a nonguaranteed product.''
</P>
<P>
   Daily, who thinks that prices will head down in a few years,
suggests going the 10-year, fully guaranteed route. Or even
insuring year to year. If you choose a 10-year policy, he advises,
buy one that lets you convert coverage to whole life should your
health fail. Your premiums could be up to 10 times higher for the
whole life policy _ but at least you could not be denied coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has made shopping for insurance much easier than in
the old days, when consumers had to deal with company agents one at
a time or find a broker who represented at least a few companies.
Some Internet insurers, including AccuQuote and Quotesmith.com,
offer comparisons of more than 100 companies with just a few key
strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Some sell policies online; others direct customers to an agent
for a consultation by phone. Once a choice is made, documents are
mailed out for signature. Often, a blood sample is taken and a
physical given to make sure the buyer really is in excellent health
and qualifies for the best rates.
</P>
<P>
   While price is important, there are other factors. Agents can
give guidance on considerations like insurers' financial strength
and whether a person's health permits him or her to qualify for the
best prices.
</P>
<P>
   Fooling yourself that your health is good enough to qualify you
for the most favorable rates can prove expensive. Often, companies
that offer the best prices for customers in excellent health charge
more than their competitors for coverage of those whose health is
only average.
</P>
<P>
   If you indicate that you are in excellent health, hoping to get
the preferred rate, and the insurer determines that your health is
only average, a new price will be proposed. And if you just sign up
for the coverage without shopping further, as many customers do,
you will very likely wind up paying more than you might otherwise,
perhaps now more than ever.
</P>
<P>
   The turmoil in term life insurance has not caused a stampede
toward whole life, which includes an investment component with a
low rate of return. Annual premiums on term life still tend to be
one-tenth of those for whole life, or even less.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buying term life is a little more complex now,'' said J.
Robert Hunter, the director of insurance for the Consumer
Federation of America. ``But if you shop around you can still get a
pretty good price.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
