<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-SUISSE-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREDIT SUISSE UNDER SCRUTINY FOR UKRAINIAN IMF LOANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN with JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Credit Suisse Group, the European banking giant, has long plied
the unpredictable waters of overseas financial markets with elan,
earning a reputation as a swashbuckler in corners of the globe as
far afield as the former Soviet Union and East Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The bank has made lush profits in many of those markets but has
also suffered bruising losses when speculative fervor overseas
turned against it in recent years. Still, Credit Suisse remains an
important player in emerging markets, particularly in the former
Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Credit Suisse is on the hot seat. Allegations of
improprieties in the way the Ukrainian central bank managed
International Monetary Fund loans are raising serious questions
about the bank's role in the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The bank's chairman, Rainer E. Gut, has been asked to testify
before the House Banking Committee next week at a hearing examining
money laundering and the possible misuse or theft of IMF money.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF disclosed this week that the Ukrainian central bank
engineered a series of financial transactions _ some through Cyprus
_ to inflate artificially its foreign currency reserves so that the
country could obtain hundreds of millions of dollars in IMF loans
that otherwise might have been denied. Some of the transactions
were conducted with the help of Credit Suisse's investment banking
arm, Credit Suisse First Boston, according to government
investigators in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF has retained the accounting firm PricewaterhouseCoopers
to audit the transactions for any evidence of wrongdoing and a
report is expected by the end of March. The Ukrainian government
and Credit Suisse have repeatedly denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've examined all the transactions in question and we've
found nothing to cause us to believe that any of those transactions
were inappropriate or illegal,'' a Credit Suisse spokesman said in
an interview. Credit Suisse, citing bank secrecy laws in Cyprus,
declined to comment about whether it knew that transactions it
conducted for the Ukrainian central bank artificially increased
reserve levels.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Suisse was one of the first foreign companies to receive
a commercial banking license from the Ukrainian government and the
bank has conducted a wide variety of financial services for the
government. Just this week, Credit Suisse was one of several banks
that helped Ukraine repackage almost $3 billion in foreign debt to
avoid a default.
</P>
<P>
   Western financiers said that Alexander Bazarov, who runs Credit
Suisse First Boston's Kiev office, has played a key role in winning
business for Credit Suisse with the Ukrainian government. And the
authorities in the United States said that Bazarov was the banker
responsible for channeling the central bank funds in question
through Cyprus. Bazarov could not be reached for comment, and
Credit Suisse declined to comment on questions about him.
</P>
<P>
   Bazarov, a Ukrainian citizen who once worked in the Ukrainian
central bank, is said to be close to Viktor Yushchenko, Ukraine's
prime minister. Yushchenko was formerly the head of Ukraine's
central bank. Earlier this week, Yushchenko canceled a visit to the
United States after the Clinton administration told him he should
come only after ``cleaning up his government.'' Ukrainian officials
said the trip was canceled because of a mining disaster at home.
</P>
<P>
   Yushchenko's visit was discouraged soon before the Treasury
Department and the IMF disclosed the Ukrainian central bank's
financial maneuvers late Wednesday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The IMF, a public agency financed by several Western
governments, has been widely criticized for lax lending and
oversight in the former Soviet Union. But it is the private and
very profitable Western commercial and investment banks that have
provided the financial plumbing underlying many of the transactions
under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in the role played by Western financial institutions in
possibly aiding financial misdeeds in the former Soviet Union was
heightened by last year's disclosure that $7 billion in suspect
Russian money was funneled through the Bank of New York. The Bank
of New York has not been charged with wrongdoing and is cooperating
with the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Times was the first publication to report on
Credit Suisse's involvement with the Ukrainian central bank. One of
those cited by the paper as providing information about Credit
Suisse was Joel Bartow, a former FBI agent who once worked as a
member of the legal defense team for Pavlo Lazarenko, a former
Ukrainian prime minister. Bartow has been out of the country and
did not return phone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Lazarenko is being detained by the federal authorities in
California while they consider extradition requests from
Switzerland and Ukraine on charges of embezzling state funds and
money laundering. As prime minister, Lazarenko may have pocketed
millions of dollars from state programs, according to Ukrainian,
Swiss and United States authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Lazarenko has a personal interest in any stories that impugn the
integrity of Ukraine's government.
</P>
<P>
   His wealth and power were growing so briskly during 1996 and
1997, his two years as prime minister, that the situation led to a
rift with Ukraine's president, Leonid Kuchma, who dismissed
Lazarenko from his influential post. Lazarenko subsequently formed
an opposition party and planned to run for the presidency until he
fled Ukraine in late 1998, just days before prosecutors there
charged him with embezzling millions of dollars in government
funds. Lazarenko has not been charged with any crime in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Handwerker, a New York lawyer representing Lazarenko,
said that charges against his client were politically motivated and
noted that some of Lazarenko's reputed co-conspirators are now
members of Kuchma's administration.
</P>
<P>
   Handwerker would not comment on any of the issues involving the
Ukrainian central bank and the IMF, other than to point out that
Bartow is no longer a member of Lazarenko's legal team.
</P>
<P>
   Problems with the management of central bank funds in Ukraine
bear striking similarities to questions that were raised last year
about the management of Russian central bank reserves.
IMF-sponsored audits of its lending to the Russian central bank,
also conducted by PricewaterhouseCoopers, found no evidence of any
misappropriation, although the IMF said that the central bank had
misled it about the level of its foreign currency reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, questions still linger about how Russian central
bank funds were managed through an offshore entity known as Fimaco.
Hefty interest payments earned on billions of dollars invested by
Fimaco in high-yielding Russian debt still have not been entirely
accounted for _ an issue also under scrutiny in the Ukrainian
central bank matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
