<SLUG> BC-SEC-LEVITT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALL STREET IS URGED TO DISCLOSE ALL UNFILLED ORDERS FOR SHARES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.) (rk) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission called on
Wall Street Thursday to voluntarily put together a system that
would disclose all stock orders that have not yet been filled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now is the time for all market participants to move towards
open books on all markets,'' said Arthur Levitt, the SEC chairman,
in remarks prepared for a speech at Northwestern University. ``Now
is the time for a voluntary private sector initiative in this
important area _ one that does not require major systems
engineering.''
</P>
<P>
   All markets are now required to disclose any limit orders _
orders to buy or sell a stock at a particular price _ if that order
represents the best available price in the market. Levitt proposed
going further than that, but he also said that he was ``deeply
troubled'' by evidence that even the disclosures required now are
often not being made.
</P>
<P>
   ``In far too many cases,'' he said, ``limit orders are being
mishandled by market intermediaries'' and not being exposed to the
market as required. He said that an SEC examination of one regional
stock exchange, which he did not identify, showed ``at least one
out of six limit orders was not properly displayed.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the SEC staff would prepare a report on the extent of
that problem in the next 45 days. But he added that just showing
the best orders, as is now required, was not enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ability of all investors to see the depth of supply and
demand in any stock would be a giant step toward a true national
market system,'' he said. ``And it is a step that our markets
should take now, before the uncertainty of decimalization is upon
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices are now usually quoted in increments of
one-sixteenth of a dollar, or 6.25 cents. But when markets switch
to decimals, or cents, the increments could decline to a penny.
``In many respects, price transparency today is like seeing the tip
of an iceberg, and having no idea how much rests below,'' he said.
``Without more transparency, ascertaining supply and demand below
the top of the book could become more difficult in a world of
pennies.''
</P>
<P>
   Levitt said he would convene a meeting with many people from the
industry to try to encourage such disclosures, which would then be
disseminated by the companies, like Reuters and Bloomberg, that now
disseminate price quotes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
