<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING COLUMN: TWO PRODUCTS, TWO AGENCIES, IDENTICAL ADS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two beverage marketers are running television
commercials that no doubt have many viewers wondering whether they
are seeing double.
</P>
<P>
   The commercials, for Michelob Light beer and Colombian coffee,
have similar premises and resemble each other closely. The spots
also began running nationally about the same time, with Michelob
Light appearing first, in December.
</P>
<P>
   The dueling commercials are indicative of a problem that has
been vexing Madison Avenue for many years, centered on the
origination of ideas and how to properly credit the creators. That
is made difficult by the fact that advertising is a business that
borrows liberally from the popular culture, producing work meant to
capitalize on the success of the intellectual property of others
from movies to TV series to songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's seldom plagiarism,'' said Bob Garfield, ad critic for the
trade publication Advertising Age, ``especially if they are
appearing simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some cases, it really does seem as if two people are
plucking the same radio signals from the zeitgeist,'' he added.
``Or it's the same fairly obvious idea occurring to two people at
the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Garfield gave several examples of the phenomenon: a brewer and a
battery maker running commercials that parody other commercials; an
automaker and an auto-parts maker running spots that compare cars
rebuilt using parts not factory authorized to Frankenstein's
monster; and ``three commercials all on at the same time with
Morocco as their settings, all essentially ending with the same
joke.''
</P>
<P>
   There are numerous other examples. Two brands of athletic shoes
once proclaimed, ``The only competition is yourself.'' And ads for
an imported beer presented the imaginary complaints of a
make-believe protest group about a year after a campaign for a
Scotch whiskey used the same tongue-in-cheek tactic.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, duels between dual ideas are not confined to
advertising. In recent years, Hollywood studios have released pairs
of movies about volcanoes, Wyatt Earp, asteroids and missions to
Mars.
</P>
<P>
   In this instance, both the Michelob Light and Colombian coffee
commercials are set in supermarkets. They share the same plot:
store employees manhandle groceries until the product being
advertised comes down the conveyor belt.
</P>
<P>
   In the Michelob Light spot, by the Leap Partnership in Chicago,
a unit of Leapnet, a bored bag boy carelessly tosses groceries into
a bag. He jams in a plant upside down and even breaks a loaf of
bread in half.
</P>
<P>
   But when the cashier rings up a six-pack of Michelob Light, the
bag boy radically alters his routine. He enrobes the package in
bubble wrap, tapes it closed and writes ``Fragile'' on the bag. He
even says ``Have a nice day'' as the shoppers leave.
</P>
<P>
   The other commercial, for the National Federation of Coffee
Growers of Colombia, was created by DDB Worldwide Marketing in New
York, part of the DDB Worldwide Communications Group unit of the
Omnicom Group. This time, the cashier and the bag boy are both
miscreants; the cashier haphazardly tosses the groceries to the bag
boy, who then mistreats them.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the impulse to reform is generated by the product being
pitched. When the cashier and bag boy see a can of Colombian
coffee, they handle it lovingly. As he encases it in bubble wrap,
an announcer proclaims, ``The reaction when you buy 100 percent
Colombian coffee can be quite surprising.'' Only when he is done do
the employees resume their mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   Anheuser-Busch, which makes Michelob Light, had a terse response
to a question about the similarity of the two spots. Here is the
text of the brewer's statement: ``We are aware of the Colombian
coffee federation commercial in question. We are pleased with the
response our ad has received.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter le Comte, president of DDB Worldwide Marketing, was more
expansive in his reply.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very much aware'' of the Michelob Light spot, he said,
adding: ``We've been bombarded with e-mails from people asking us
what happened. That's good for us, because it means our commercial
provokes a reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have written it off as an incident of coincidence. They
will run their commercial and we will run ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he added, chuckling, ``I don't think we share the same
consumers, unless they drink too much beer and need to drink coffee
before they drive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 2252EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
