<HEADLINE>
KINGS LOSE PALFFY TO INJURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As the Kings' best player, Ziggy Palffy is a
target. Now, he is a casualty.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy, whose scoring and playmaking have helped put the Kings
on the verge of qualifying for the Stanley Cup playoffs, is
expected to miss at least the final three weeks of the regular
season with a sprained right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy, tied with teammate Luc Robitaille for 14th in the NHL in
scoring, was injured early in the third period of Wednesday's 2-2
tie with the Mighty Ducks on a vicious hit by defenseman Vitaly
Vishnevski.
</P>
<P>
   Kings coach Andy Murray said the hit was clean, but that didn't
make it any easier watching Palffy helped from the ice.
</P>
<P>
   And though the Kings (34-27-9) are fifth in the Western
Conference race with 80 points, Palffy's absence during the final
12 games could impact playoff pairings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you lose a player of that caliber, you lose a lot,''
Murray said on the eve of tonight's game against St. Louis, the
league's top team this season. ``But we've been through it before
this season and we have survived. I didn't even bring it up in the
dressing room today. We lost Luc and (Jozef Stumpel) for long
periods earlier in the year. You just have to keep moving
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   When Robitaille (six weeks), Stumpel (10 weeks) and goaltender
Stephane Fiset (six weeks) were sidelined with injuries in November
and December, the team buckled. The Kings lost six straight at one
point and had just two victories in 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy also missed six games this season with a strained lower
back.
</P>
<P>
   Before this season, he had missed just three games during his
six-year career. But through a rigorous off-ice rehabilitation
program, Palffy recovered.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Palffy was examined by team physician Ronald Kvitne
and underwent an MRI exam. In Palffy's absence, the Kings will use
rookie Jason Blake at right wing on the first unit.
</P>
<P>
   Blake, who has played every line this season, was a healthy
scratch for the Kings game in Anaheim. He has four goals and 16
assists in 54 games.
</P>
<P>
   Murray elected not to break up his second line, which added
Nelson Emerson at Tuesday's trade deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Second-unit center Bryan Smolinski scored both goals in
Wednesday's tie with Anaheim. Glen Murray had two assists and
Emerson had one.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the group that carried us when other players were
injured,'' said Andy Murray. ``They've struggled a bit lately, but
they picked it up against the Ducks and we'll need that.''
</P>
<P>
   Palffy, acquired with Smolinski last summer from the New York
Islanders, is no longer just the pure scorer that produced three
consecutive 40-goal seasons.
</P>
<P>
   In 64 games, Palffy has 27 goals and 39 assists for 66 points.
Those are hardly career numbers. He had 48 goals three seasons ago.
But he also never has been to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   However, protecting him has been difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, the Kings tried to retaliate when opposing
teams took a run at Palffy and often wound up in the penalty box.
</P>
<P>
   Murray has worked to break that habit.
</P>
<P>
   A turning point was Feb. 18 in Detroit when Palffy was flattened
by Red Wings strong man Darren McCarty. They did not retaliate and
won the game 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to see your top scorer down on the ice,'' said
enforcer Ian Laperriere.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the game is still going on and you have to be careful. You
want to take the other guy on, but you don't want to wind up in the
penalty box.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings added grit at Tuesday's trade deadline by acquiring
Kelly Buchberger, whose fights with former Kings tough guy Marty
McSorley were legendary.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the third period on Wednesday, Buchberger also was hit
by Vishnevski.
</P>
<P>
   Many thought that hit was illegal, but Buchberger kept his
distance.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Kings must keep the rest of the West at a distance
without Palffy. They are eight points ahead of Edmonton for the
eighth and final playoff spot and 10 ahead of No. 9 Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two ways to go with this,'' Murray said. ``You can
worry and complain and cry about it, but where is that going to get
you? Or you can buckle down. and do the job. We were in a battle
before we lost Ziggy and we're still in a battle.''
</P>
<P>
   KINGS vs. ST. LOUIS
</P>
<P>
   Time: 5:30 p.m., Staples Center
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: ESPN, KRLA-AM (1110)
</P>
<P>
   Matchup: The Blues have been a big help to the Kings, beating
Phoenix twice this week and helping the Kings move into second in
the Pacific Division. St. Louis had seen their seven-point lead in
the West trimmed to two before their 5-3 victory over the Coyotes.
The Kings had other injuries to report other than Ziggy Palffy, who
could miss a month with sprained right shoulder. Backup goaltender
Marcel Cousineau was teased in Thursday's practice for complaining
of a stomachache. An hour later he was being prepped for surgery to
remove his appendix. Doesn't sound like much, but with top
goaltender Stephane Fiset still out with a groin, the Kings have
had to call up goaltender Mike O'Neill from minor-league Lowell,
Mass. Aki Berg (concussion) is still out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
