<HEADLINE>
INVESTIGATION CLEARS FIRST LADY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A four-year investigation into possible misuse of
FBI files has found no criminal wrongdoing by first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton or senior White House officials, independent counsel
Robert Ray reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The special prosecutor also said no credible evidence indicates
that former White House counsel Bernard Nussbaum lied to Congress
about the hiring of a staff member who sought the confidential
background files on Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Ray, who was named in October to replace former independent
counsel Kenneth Starr, issued a statement saying the two
investigations were ending and that ``no prosecutions were
warranted.''
</P>
<P>
   Two reports outlining Ray's conclusions were submitted under
seal to a panel of three federal appellate judges who named Starr,
then Ray, to oversee what has evolved into a $50 million
investigation of President Clinton and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Yet to come are final reports on inquiries into the firings of
the White House travel staff, the Monica Lewinsky scandal and
Whitewater, an Arkansas land deal that triggered the investigation
in mid-1994.
</P>
<P>
   The reports are being kept confidential by the three-judge
panel, at least until people named in the documents have a chance
to respond. Even then, the court can decide not to release the
reports to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The sprawling investigation led to Clinton's impeachment by the
House of Representatives on charges stemming from his effort to
conceal his sexual affair with Lewinsky, a former White House
intern. Clinton was acquitted by the Senate in February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about Ray's statement, which was issued to the news
media, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart bristled. ``Well, that's
really good, since that report hasn't been provided to the White
House, and it involves the White House,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   The summary of Ray's findings echoed testimony by Starr in
November 1998, when he acknowledged to the House Judiciary
Committee that his investigation had yielded no criminal wrongdoing
by the president or first lady in either the FBI files case or the
travel office firings.
</P>
<P>
   Saying ``there shouldn't be much news in this,'' Lockhart
dismissed Ray's reports and questioned why his findings had not
been issued sooner. ``I don't know why we've continued on this
subject for another couple years and why the report's coming out
now,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI files inquiry grew out of what Clinton at the time
called ``an honest bureaucratic mess-up'' in which Anthony Marceca,
an Army detailee at the White House, in 1993 and 1994 gathered
hundreds of FBI files on Republicans, mostly workers in the Reagan
and Bush administrations.
</P>
<P>
   Marceca's boss, former White House security office chief Craig
Livingstone, resigned after a congressional committee investigation
in 1996 turned up the possible misuse of the files. Livingstone
maintained he didn't know that Marceca had collected the files.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides blamed the Secret Service for providing
Livingstone and Marceca with outdated lists of White House
passholders. Marceca used the lists to order the background files
from the FBI, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   An FBI agent reported that Nussbaum said in a 1993 interview
that Hillary Clinton had ``highly'' recommended Livingstone to run
the security office. When Nussbaum testified before the House
Government Reform Committee in 1996, he denied knowing who hired
Livingstone and specifically denied discussing the former nightclub
bouncer with the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   Ray on Thursday said his office ``determined there was no
substantial and credible evidence that Mr. Nussbaum lied'' about
his discussions with Hillary Clinton regarding Livingstone.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel also said ``there was no substantial and
credible evidence that any senior White House official, or first
lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, was involved in seeking confidential
Federal Bureau of Investigation background reports'' on Republicans
hired during the Reagan and Bush administrations.
</P>
<P>
   Ray's announcement drew criticism from at least one Republican
appointee, a former Bush speechwriter who is a figure in a lawsuit
accusing the Clinton administration of violating a federal privacy
law.
</P>
<P>
   Closing out the probe without any prosecutions is ``a
travesty,'' said Joseph Duggan, adding that he would ask the
Justice Department to investigate possible violations of the
Privacy Act of 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``These raw investigative files invariably contain material that
is not necessarily true, but almost certainly is negative and
embarrassing,'' said Duggan, who is participating in a lawsuit
filed against Clinton by Judicial Watch. ``The FBI improperly gave
our files to unauthorized and politically hostile individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray explained that his investigation did not include possible
Privacy Act abuses, which would amount to misdemeanors and would
fall outside the independent counsel's jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
