<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES DISCUSS EDMONDS DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX, Ariz. -- Yankees owner George Steinbrenner called a
``summit'' meeting Thursday night in Tampa involving his top front
office executives, the scouting staff, manager Joe Torre and his
coaches to discuss the possibility of trading for Angels center
fielder Jim Edmonds.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant in Tampa -- Malio's -- is where Steinbrenner has
conducted several top-level meetings, including one last year that
led to the trade for Roger Clemens. According to reports,
Steinbrenner has grown impatient with the Yankees poor play this
spring (5-12) and particularly their lack of production in left
field.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner is known to love action and this is the first year
since the Yankees World Series run began in 1996 that the club has
not made a major acquisition going into the season.
</P>
<P>
   Top Yankees scout Gene Michael is spearheading the effort to
acquire Edmonds. Michael believes in having two left-handed slugger
outfielders signed long-term playing in Yankee Stadium, and with
37-year-old Paul O'Neill in the final year of his contract, the
Yankees need that second lefty to complement Bernie Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all in the Yankees organization believe Edmonds will make
them a better team. Where there is debate has to do with who the
Yankees are willing to give up in return. And that's what
Thursday's meeting was about.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the organization -- including Torre -- do not want to
part with pitcher Ramiro Mendoza and would be more willing to trade
shortstop/second baseman Alfonso Soriano. Others are not as high on
Mendoza and would include him in a trade, but want to use Soriano
to acquire pitching help. No one seems to have reservations about
including outfielder Ricky Ledee in a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue is Edmonds' contract status. Edmonds is a free
agent at the end of the season and the Yankees are reluctant to
trade for him unless they are given a ``window'' -- typically 72
hours -- to sign Edmonds to a contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams would first have to agree on the players involved,
but if and when that happens, the Angels are not philosophically
opposed to granting that window to another team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You examine the circumstances and make a decision, just like
you do in any business situation,'' Angels general manager Bill
Stoneman said when asked if he would grant a signing window.
``There's no one answer for all circumstances. That would be
silly.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds would agree to negotiating with the Yankees under such
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   There are other teams still interested in Edmonds, including the
A's, Mariners and Rockies. Stoneman and A's general manager Billy
Beane sat in the seats behind homeplate of Thursday's game between
the Angels and A's and chatted for an inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' biggest need is starting pitching, and with Ramon
Ortiz's status uncertain (slight tear in labrum of right shoulder)
there is even more reason to make a deal for pitching help.
</P>
<P>
   Stoneman, though, has not buckled under the pressure and given
Edmonds or any of his other outfielders away for less than their
value. A healthy Edmonds will have a big season this year, whatever
uniform he's wearing, and Stoneman knows it.
</P>
<P>
   The question now seems to be, are the Yankees willing to pay the
price.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz will play catch today but will not throw off the mound
again until Monday. Angels manager Mike Scioscia said Ortiz will
probably throw two bullpens before pitching in a game again.
``We're very content to take a step backwards with him so it will
push us forward in the long run,'' Sciosica said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Schoeneweis took a big step towards winning a spot in the
starting rotation with his performance Thursday against the A's.
Schoeneweis went five innings -- most by an Angels pitcher this
spring -- and allowed two runs and five hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying I can't do better, but I'm doing what I expect
to at this time of the year,'' said Schoeneweis, who has a 2.25
spring ERA. ``It's only going to get better. Every spring training
I've gotten better and I will continue that going into the regular
season.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Scotty's coming on,'' Scioscia said. ``He located his pitches
and had pretty good movement. And that's a good lineup. He has the
arm and he has the stuff. Now, he has the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Left-handed veteran Greg Cadaret, vying for a spot in the
bullpen, was released after Thursday's game. Cadaret had been
battling Juan Alvarez and Mike Holtz for the left-handed reliever
spot, but Cadaret, 38, sealed his own fate in Thursday's game
against the A's. Facing four left-handed hitters, Cadaret gave up
three consecutive singles, then a hard-hit sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   The two runs off Cadaret in the eighth inning cost the Angels
the game, 4-3. But the Angels did get a home run from Mo Vaughn and
two from Scott Spiezio, a former Athletic who is the favorite to
win the starting job at second base.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
