<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PRICE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASAL STRIPS, AND RACING BRASS, HARD TO FIGURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've never taken exception to the use of nasal strips on
racehorses. As long as horse racing commissions are allowing the
use of Lasix _ which produces a measurable chemical change in a
horse _ I can't see much reason to bellyache when anyone wants to
take a strip of tape and adorn a horse's snout with it.
</P>
<P>
   There are people who aren't hip on nasal strips because they fly
in the face of tradition. But that's not the reason nasal strips
have become another sad episode in horse racing.
</P>
<P>
   Nasal strips, like the ones athletes or snorers wear across
their noses, are designed to hold a horse's upper breathing passage
open and make it easier _ or less noisy _ to breath.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison to the medication Lasix, a nasal strip is a
physical change. So are blinkers, front wraps, tongue ties, mud
caulks, D bits and body clipping.
</P>
<P>
   We know that the addition or removal of blinkers can change the
way a horse races. We know that front wraps can indicate soreness.
So we take notice when they are reported in the ``Daily Racing
Form'' or track program.
</P>
<P>
   The jury's still out on how nasal strips affect, or don't
affect, the way a horse races. There has been no independent report
from any institution of higher learning. So the horse racing
industry struggles over the question of whether to report the use
of nasal strips or whether to ignore them like tongue ties and
bits.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know whether nasal strips make much difference or not.
Personally, I don't pay much attention to them when I handicap a
race.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Cat Thief won the Breeders' Cup Classic was more
because of a speed-favoring track than the fact he wore a nasal
strip. He has won with and without them.
</P>
<P>
   Nasal strips have not proven that a horse like Cat Thief can run
better with one than he can without. The only thing nasal strips
have proven _ like this hasn't been proven before _ is that horse
racing botches anything new.
</P>
<P>
   First, state racing commissions can't agree if nasal strips
should be allowed or not. Then a place like Texas has a commission
that decides to allow them, but doesn't require that their use be
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Equibase and the ``Daily Racing Form'' are reporting
nasal-strip use. They're both partners in gathering and reporting
past performance information, yet Equibase denotes nasal-strip use
with an ``s'' in the equipment column of a past performance when it
sends the information for publication in track programs. In the
editions of its publication, the ``Daily Racing Form'' changes it
to ``n.''
</P>
<P>
   From the start, this has been a goofy, sad episode _ the
quintessence of horse racing administration.
</P>
<P>
   Because horse racing can't get it right, maybe nasal strips
should be banned.
</P>
<P>
   A TROUBLED RATE
</P>
<P>
   When Exchange Rate hung and finished fourth in last weekend's
Louisiana Derby, jockey Corey Nakatani said the colt couldn't
handle the track. He didn't seem to have trouble with it when he
won the Risen Star Stakes at Fair Grounds last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tightened down the track this time,'' Nakatani said,
``and he was bobbling on it every time he tried to pick it up and
run.''
</P>
<P>
   Exchange Rate, whose next race is expected in the Wood Memorial
on April 15 in New York, was shipped to Churchill Downs this week
and showed up with a lung infection.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING THE MERCEDES
</P>
<P>
   Elite Mercedes flipped the palate in his upper breathing passage
while finishing eighth in the Florida Derby last weekend,
part-owner Bill Casner of Southlake said. The colt is expected to
race in the $600,000 Spiral Stakes (formerly the Jim Beam Stakes)
on March 25 at Turfway Park.
</P>
<P>
   If that doesn't go well, Casner indicated Elite Mercedes could
race in the Lone Star Derby on April 22. But that might make the
Kentucky Derby unlikely because the races are two weeks apart.
</P>
<P>
   The $1 million bonus Lone Star is offering is available to the
horse that wins the Lone Star Derby and any Triple Crown race. But
if Elite Mercedes skips the Kentucky Derby and races in the
Preakness, he'll try to break a long-standing trend. A horse hasn't
won the Preakness without running in the Derby since Deputed
Testimony beat a field that included Sunny's Halo in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   WRONA'S DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Michael Wrona, who has been the toast of sports talk-radio shows
since he was named track announcer at Lone Star Park at Grand
Prairie last week, has been signed to a three-year contract. The
Australian will call the races for both the thoroughbred and
quarter-horse seasons.
</P>
<P>
   A three-year stint would be his longest with one track since
Wrona arrived in North America in 1990. He has worked at two tracks
that have experienced financial problems (Retama Park in 1995 and
Arlington International in 1997) and another that has been
controlled by volatile management (Hollywood Park and Bay Meadows).
</P>
<P>
   When he departed from his second gig at Hollywood to come to
Lone Star, new management at that track had not secured Wrona to a
contract.
</P>
<P>
   SPOTLIGHT ON ...
HEAVENS NEED TO OPEN FOR MIGHTY TO RACE HERE
</P>
<P>
   It would take an act of God The Almighty to get a horse like
Mighty to show up for the $300,000 Lone Star Derby in April. It
would sort of be like lightning striking twice, but at least
trainer Frank Brothers is willing to consider it.
</P>
<P>
   Mighty, who won the Louisiana Derby with much authority last
weekend, is scheduled to make his next race in the Blue Grass
Stakes on April 15 at Keeneland. But Brothers won't let him run if
the track comes up muddy.
</P>
<P>
   Mighty wears ``rundown'' pads to protect the backs of his front
ankles from abrasions. He ran down when he raced on the mud last
year at Keeneland. He lost that race by more than 20 lengths.
</P>
<P>
   Brothers would put Mighty in the Lexington Stakes a week later
if he misses the Blue Grass. But if _ by an unlikely circumstance _
the forecast in the days leading up to the Lexington predict rain,
Brothers said he might make arrangements to come to Lone Star. It
would have to be horrendous weather, because the Lone Star Derby
and the Lexington are on the same day (April 22) and Brothers has
Mighty stabled in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I'd consider it,'' he said. ``He is nominated to the
race, and you have to keep all your options open.''
</P>
<P>
   Lone Star director of racing Larry Craft will be at the Tampa
Bay Derby on Saturday recruiting 3-year-olds for the Lone Star
Derby. Craft indicated that the only possibles for the Derby are
Oro Negra and Ifitstobeitsuptome (seventh and eighth, respectively,
in the Louisiana Derby). nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
