<HEADLINE>
IBM ACHIEVES ADVANCE IN MEMORY FOR COMPUTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif.)  (js) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A group of IBM scientists said Thursday that they had achieved a
technological breakthrough that could result in disk drives capable
of holding more than 1 trillion bytes of data _ more than 100 times
the capacity of today's most typical hard drives.
</P>
<P>
   In an article to be published Friday in the journal Science, the
researchers say they discovered chemical reactions that cause tiny
magnetic particles, each no larger than a few thousand atoms, to
assemble themselves at precise intervals like a company of soldiers
coming to attention on a parade ground.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery was made in a cross-country collaboration of
researchers working in IBM laboratories in New York state and
California. Beyond product applications, the breakthrough is
significant for the emerging scientific field of nanotechnology,
the effort to build microscopic circuitry and even machines only a
few molecules in size.
</P>
<P>
   One obstacle has been the difficulty of manufacturing such
precise magnetic surfaces, but IBM researchers are exploring
self-assembly _ chemical or mechanical processes that can be
programmed to build these minuscule technologies without human
intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Self-replication, the holy grail of nanotechnology, is widely
viewed as the key to an entirely new industrial era that may one
day replace modern microelectronic systems.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in the past year a variety of U.S. corporate and
academic laboratories have made progress in an area of research
known as molecular electronics, using a similar chemical approach
to build simple computing components no larger than a single
molecule.
</P>
<P>
   And academic researchers have made progress with the fabrication
of nanotubes, man-made carbon molecules capable of being assembled
into exotic materials that could contain their own processing power
_ a wall that becomes an entertainment center, for example, or
clothing that changes its thermal properties to compensate for
shifts in temperature or humidity.
</P>
<P>
   The IBM scientists said they had been able to assemble arrays of
particles so tiny that it would take 20,000 to span the width of a
human hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exciting because it potentially applies to many
different types of small storage structures, not just rotating
memory,'' said Currie Munce, IBM Research's director of storage
systems and technology.
</P>
<P>
   IBM researchers in Zurich, for example, have been working on a
storage device that can read and write information to particles
that are only a few atoms wide.
</P>
<P>
   The current research was conducted by Shouheng Sun and
Christopher Murray at IBM's Thomas J. Watson Research Center in
Yorktown Heights, N.Y. and Dieter Weller, Liesl Folks and Andreas
Moser at the company's Almaden Research Center in San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   To create the new material the researchers combined iron- and
platinum-containing molecules in a heated solution.
</P>
<P>
   IBM executives cautioned that while the breakthrough is cause
for scientific excitement, it would not immediately translate into
the next generation of disk drives. It took almost a decade for IBM
to take its gigantic magneto resistive head technology from the
laboratory to the market, Munce said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   IBM has demonstrated storage densities up to 35.3 billion bits,
or gigabits, per square inch, and it is now shipping disks with
densities of 14.3 gigabits per square inch.
</P>
<P>
   The new magnetic nanoparticles could boost storage densities to
as high as 150 gigabits per square inch, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, IBM scientists have said they could continue to
improve disk densities until sometime this decade when they will
encounter a physical limit known as the ``superparamagnetic
effect'' _ a point at which the magnetic particles on the surface
of a disk will be so small that their magnetic orientation will
become unstable at room temperature. Munce said the new technology
would push disks closer to that limit.
</P>
</TEXT>
