<HEADLINE>
SMALL FIRMS EXPRESS DISMAY AT PLAN FOR NASDAQ SPINOFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After months of breezy talk about a plan by the
National Association of Securities Dealers to issue stock and spin
off the Nasdaq stock market later this year, the fine print finally
became public Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   And though NASD executives predict that the deal will pass a
membership vote easily, a handful of small brokerage firms
expressed hostility to the offering in a conference call Thursday.
Another group may file a class-action suit to stop the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The voluminous offering statement explaining the two-part deal,
which is expected to raise $1.13 billion if it is fully subscribed,
was mailed earlier this week to the 5,509 brokerage firms that
belong to the membership organization. Phase 1 of the deal will
involve selling shares in the Nasdaq stock market. The second phase
will involve the sale of shares in NASD, the stock market's parent.
The offering will be put to a vote April 14.
</P>
<P>
   The prospectus outlined how the shares in the Nasdaq market
would be divided, with the largest share _ 32 percent _ going to
130 large brokerage firms that trade and underwrite Nasdaq stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Next in line are all other NASD member firms, with 25 percent,
followed by 130 companies whose shares trade on Nasdaq, which will
receive 16 percent of the deal. An undisclosed number of
institutional investors who own large stakes in Nasdaq-traded
companies will receive less than 5 percent. The NASD will own 51
percent of Nasdaq after the first phase of the deal and 22 percent
when the second phase is completed.
</P>
<P>
   The association said it would earmark up to $500 million from
the deal to be used by its regulatory arm and $215 million for the
benefit of the American Stock Exchange, which the NASD acquired in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   In the first conference call to discuss the deal with members
Thursday, the mood was contentious. According to several people who
took part in the 45-minute call, NASD executives allowed few
questions and were vague in their answers. ``Substantive questions
weren't answered,'' said an executive at one small firm who
insisted on anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Frank G. Zarb, chairman of the association, disagreed. ``It's
been generally a good response,'' he said. ``We're going to have
numerous more calls. Getting answers to questions really is
important to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Davidson, president of the Independent Broker-Dealer
Association and a member of the association board, has recommended
that small brokerage firms vote against the deal. ``If approved,
this could be the end of one-firm, one-vote as we now know it in
the NASD,'' he said. ``As a result, large firms will be empowered,
and it will force a consolidation of small firms, which will give
investors fewer options and will create a severe imbalance in the
capital formation process for small business in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   A class-action suit against the NASD could come within a week,
said Howard Sirota, partner at Sirota &AMP; Sirota in New York. The
action would be brought by the Independent Broker-Dealer
Association on behalf of its 200-plus members, Sirota said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
