<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GUN-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPITZER TRIES TO ORGANIZE GOVERNMENT GUN BUYERS TO PRESS FOR SAFETY
FEATURES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ERIC LIPTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saying that gun-control legislation and lawsuits against gun
manufacturers are taking too long, New York state's attorney
general, Eliot L. Spitzer, proposed Thursday that federal, state
and local governments across the country band together to try to
force gun makers to add safety devices to all weapons sold to
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Gun manufacturers that did not agree to the coalition's demands
would lose their ability to sell guns to the local and state police
departments that sign on to the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said that the mayors of Buffalo, Rochester, Albany and
East Aurora, as well as the Westchester County executive, had
already signed on to the campaign. He said he had sent letters to
attorneys general and governors across the United States and to the
mayors of the nation's 100 largest cities to ask for their support.
</P>
<P>
   ``A company that will be driven into bankruptcy because we will
deny it access to its primary market will respond in ways that
nobody thought of,'' Spitzer said, noting that federal, state and
local governments bought at least 25 percent of all handguns sold.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the details in the proposal, which Spitzer said he had
been working on for several months, overlap a plan announced two
days ago by Gov. George Pataki. Both proposals, for example, would
require that guns be sold with safety locks to prevent use or
accidental firing by a child. Spitzer, a Democrat, praised the
Republican governor for the gun-control legislation, which he said
he supports.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said he was confident that within the next several
months he would have enough cities and states signed up for his
campaign to force gun manufacturers to agree to the terms. Until
then, he said, the attorney general's office would continue to buy
guns without regard to the proposed new code.
</P>
<P>
   But an industry representative said Thursday that he expected
the strategy to fail. Gun manufacturers ``absolutely will not be
forced or blackmailed into designing and marketing unsafe or
unproven firearms,'' said Bob Delfay, president of the National
Shooting Sports Foundation, a Connecticut-based organization that
represents 1,800 gun manufacturers, distributors and retailers
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Even the New York State Association of Chiefs of Police
expressed some reservations Thursday, given that the plan might
limit the ability of police departments to buy the guns they wanted
if a certain manufacturer did not agree to comply with the
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Safety of officers and the public comes first,'' said John J.
Poklemba, a lawyer for the state association and the former New
York state director of criminal justice. ``Police departments need
the flexibility to buy the equipment that is appropriate for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The so-called code of conduct that Spitzer has proposed is far
reaching. All handguns sold to civilians in the United States would
be required to have external and internal locking devices to
prevent accidental firing, as well as a device to alert a user if
there is a round in the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Gun manufacturers would have to agree to refit old guns at no
cost to the owner, adding any new safety devices as they become
available. Handguns would have to be made in a way that allowed the
ammunition magazine to be removed.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers would also have to spend an amount equal to 1
percent of their annual sales to develop technology that prevented
a gun from being fired by anyone but the owner or another
authorized user.
</P>
<P>
   The code would also prohibit manufacturers from producing guns
that resisted fingerprints or that could easily be converted to
illegal firearms. The manufacturers would have to take steps to
ensure that the gun dealers it sold to did not distribute the guns
to groups that would resell them to convicted felons. Finally, the
gun manufacturers would have to agree to open their records to an
independent monitor who, with a staff of 50 to 70 people
nationwide, would be charged with ensuring that the manufacturers
complied with the rules.
</P>
</TEXT>
