<HEADLINE>
DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 EXCERPTS FROM BUSH'S COMMENTS ABOUT McCAIN OVER THE COURSE OF TWO (Eds: please replace double parentheses (( )) with single
brackets)  
 (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following are excerpts from an interview with Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas on Wednesday and from his comments at two separate
campaign events in Illinois on Thursday, as recorded by The New
York Times:
</P>
<P>
   Comments on Wednesday
</P>
<P>
   Q. Wasn't your message lost in fighting over tactics during
primaries? Can't that happen again if Gore acts as McCain did?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: First of all, Al Gore is no John McCain. Please don't lump
John into that category. Secondly, I think John McCain is a person
that basically wanted to elevate the discourse and had a reason for
running, other than trying to tear somebody down.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Has John McCain elevated your consciousness about reform? Has
he changed your views?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: No, he didn't change my views. He made me a better
candidate. Competition made me better. It forced me to play to my
strengths better. I didn't do that good a job early on. I needed to
make it more clear that I not only believe in reform, I've got the
record as a chief executive of getting reform done. There's nothing
like the humbling experience of getting whipped pretty bad in New
Hampshire to cause a man to re-evaluate. And I re-evaluated my
message and I re-evaluated how I was conducting myself as a
candidate. I wasn't doing as good a job as I could have explaining
where my strength is. And my strength is as somebody when, giving
the chance to reform, like education, I brought both Republicans
and Democrats together. That's what this country needs, when it
comes to Social Security, for example. When it's all said and done,
I think America's going to turn to me. I've got a record of doing
it. The Vice President is extremely partisan. He's extremely
partisan.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is there anything McCain brought to light for you or changed
your opinion on in any way?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: No, not really. We agreed more than we disagreed. That's
the great irony. You know, primaries are struggles; I used to say
primaries are arguments over shades of gray. And that's what makes
primaries difficult. In my case, I've known John a long time. And
battling with John wasn't all that pleasant, because I like him.
You know the competition got tough, and there were things said
during the course of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you see the possibility of healing?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: Yes, I do.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What do you need to do to make sure that happens?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: Just remind him there's a lot of agreement. We agree on a
lot of things, starting with neither of us wants Al Gore to be the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What about Al Gore's public life do you dislike so much?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: I don't like the acrimony in Washington. I don't like the
zero-sum politics. I don't like pitting one group of people against
another. I don't like the way they've handled whether or not he
knew about raising money from the White House - you know, iced tea
and all these kinds of excuses. I think they ought to be more
forthcoming
</P>
<P>
   Q. You won the primaries and you don't have to make concessions
to McCain, but there are people out there urging it and calling for
it. . . .
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: Who's saying that?
</P>
<P>
   Q. His people are saying it, talking about intermediaries and
all that.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: Well I've talked with Fred Thompson and John Kyl for
example and they said whatever I can do to help you become the
president, I want to help you.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is there anything you need to do to win him over? Any
concessions you need to offer?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: No. I think what I need to do is explain to John that we
agree a lot more than we disagree. There's a lot of room for reform
in Washington, D.C. I look forward to working with him to achieve
the reforms. Just to remind him that we can work together to get a
lot of reform done.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Any change in your positions, though?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: No, I campaign on what I believe.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How critical to your future is it to patch things up?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: Well, I think it's important for there to be some time. I
think it's important for all of us to get some rest. I think it's
important for us to realize that there's far more we agree on than
disagree on, and I'm confident we can work things out, confident
that we will be on the same team.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What do you think John McCain's role should be in the party?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: I think that John McCain has earned the respect of a lot
of people, and it's going to be up to him to determine what course
he wants to take.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How important is it to win his enthusiastic support?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: I'm confident we'll be able to find common ground and work
together.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How important?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH It's important, and I'm confident we can work together.
</P>
<P>
   ((Later he discussed the primary turnout thus far.))
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: I'm going to repeat: I'm very optimistic. I think if you
take an honest look at where this campaign is and where the party
is, we're pretty far down the road, consider that the turnout has
been huge. And the thing about the turnout that's important, there
are people who've been lying dormant as Republicans for a while and
there hasn't been much to cheer about, there's hasn't been much to
be excited about. And they're coming out.
</P>
<P>
   Q. But weren't they coming out for John McCain?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH Well then, how come he didn't win? Let me say this: I
remember the wisdom, you remember the wisdom in South Carolina, if
the turnout is bigger than 300,000. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Comments on Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: I appreciate the hard campaign that John McCain waged. He
ran a good race. He highlighted the need for reform, and I
appreciate the ideas that he brought forth in the campaign. Of
course, he and I agree on a lot, and it starts with this: the best
reform for America is to end the Clinton/Gore in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ((At a subsequent news conference he elaborated on his
comments.))
</P>
<P>
   Q. : Would you consider the possibility of compromise with
Senator McCain?
</P>
<P>
   BUSH: It's interesting. There's a story out today that doesn't
characterize how I feel. I want to show you a different newspaper
that says `Bush says he wants to work with McCain.' ((He holds up
front page of The Dallas Morning News.)) That's how I feel. I look
forward to working with Senator McCain. As I said in my speech, he
ran a good campaign. He brought forth some issues that are
important and I'm confident we can work together.
</P>
<P>
   Let me say where. For example, Social Security reform. John and
I both agree that there needs to be personal savings accounts
available for younger workers. . . . There's a lot of areas of
agreement; I know we can work together. . . .
</P>
<P>
   People want to focus on areas where we disagree, I'm going to
focus on areas where we agree . . . There's a lot of areas where we
can work together. In terms of budget reform, for example, I know
that John wants to reform the budget. I've laid out some plans. I
want to have biennial budgeting in the United States. I have a
two-year budget, so the budget bite doesn't go on every single
year. And that's going to require a lot of work together to get
that done.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
