<SLUG> BC-CONN-CAMPFIRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT LAWMAKERS ACT TO END CAMPFIRE BAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Hold your marshmallows. Put the lid on the
lighter fluid. Connecticut, perhaps the only state where lighting a
campfire is illegal, has become a land of unhappy campers and
downright dyspeptic campground owners.
</P>
<P>
   Because of an inadvertent change in a state statute last year,
campfires have been illegal since October. And though no campfire
police are sweeping the state's backwoods, the ban has thousands of
outdoor types wondering what kind of state they live in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the advancement program of the Boy Scouts of America
is to build a fire,'' said Harry Pokorny, executive director of the
Scouts' Connecticut Rivers Council in Hartford. ``Without campfire
programs it will change the fellowship and team building of
scouting. They're going to have to use charcoal grills.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news for the Boy Scouts and others is that the ban is a
mistake, one that officials at the state's highest levels have
vowed to fix by the time guests begin to fill most campgrounds this
spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think the governor is out to stop Boy Scouts from
having campfires?'' asked state Sen. Eileen Daily, a Democrat and
co-chairman of the legislature's Environment Committee, on
Thursday. ``I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Daily's committee approved a bill that would make
campfires legal again. The legislature is expected to send it to
Gov. John G. Rowland as early as the end of the month, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The sooner the better. Asked how many complaints she has
received since the local news media have begun reporting the
glitch, Daily said, ``It would be in the hundreds.''
</P>
<P>
   Before last year, campfires, along with barbecues and other
recreational fires, were exempt from regulations requiring permits
for open fires, said Dennis Demchak, a director in the state
Department of Environmental Protection. But a change in a statute
regulating open fires eliminated the exemption, he said,
effectively removing campfires from the list of fires residents
could legally start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because they were not mentioned, they were prohibited,''
Demchak said. And, he stressed, officials ``didn't intend to do
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with the Boy Scouts, the ban has inflamed some campground
owners, many of whom count on firewood sales as a revenue source.
</P>
<P>
   ``A campfire is a part of camping,'' said John Kelsey, a manager
of the Niantic by the Atlantic campground, in Niantic. ``You can't
have one without the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelsey said the imbroglio would be a popular topic at this
year's convention of Northeastern campground owners, which he was
attending Thursday in Stockbridge, Mass. ``This is going to be a
huge topic tonight at dinner,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
