<SLUG> BC-NY-MAFIA-GOTTI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSBAND WILL BEHAVE IF FREED ON BAIL, GOTTI DAUGHTER SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Telling a federal judge that she runs ``an extremely
tight ship at home,'' Victoria Gotti promised Thursday to keep her
husband, Carmine Agnello, in line if he is released from custody on
charges of racketeering in the scrap metal industry.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing at Agnello's bail hearing in U.S. District Court in
Brooklyn, Gotti, the daughter of John J. Gotti, the former boss of
the Gambino crime family, told the court that as an author of
popular mystery novels, she works at home and would be around to
make sure Agnello abided by the terms of any bail agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, you would be on hand to act as a sort of
policeman, would you not?'' Agnello's lawyer, Jay Goldberg, asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I run an extremely tight ship at home,'' Gotti replied. ``So,
yes, I guess I would.''
</P>
<P>
   Agnello, whom prosecutors describe as a ``made member'' of the
Gambino family, was arrested in January on state charges of using
mob intimidation to attract customers to his scrap metal empire
around Shea Stadium in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   On March 6, he was accused of similar charges in a federal
indictment. He has been in jail since then.
</P>
<P>
   Bridget M. Rohde, an assistant U.S. attorney, argued that
Agnello should not be freed on bail because after his release on
the state indictment, he threatened a government witness by making
``an Italian gesture of death'' _ a hand held sideways with the
index finger and pinky extended like horns.
</P>
<P>
   Agnello took the witness stand and, in rapid, mumbling tones,
denied having made threats of any kind.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg told Magistrate Robert M. Levy that Gotti would follow
the most stringent terms of a bail agreement, saying she would
agree to an extremely narrow list of people who could visit the
couple's home because she is an author who cherishes her solitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a writer, you understand that the less people who come
to visit, the better off you are, correct?'' Goldberg asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree,'' Gotti said.
</P>
<P>
   Levy is expected to decide Friday whether to release Agnello. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 2323EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
