<DOCNO> NYT20000316.0434 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9369 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-NCAA-MIDWEST-II-N     03-16 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-MIDWEST-II-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENTRAL CONNECTICUT TESTS IOWA STATE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ They stared up at the giant scoreboard hanging
from the ceiling, still hoping. One, two, three heads popped up
from Central Connecticut State's huddle wanting to believe that
they still had a chance to shock Iowa State and the college
basketball world.
</P>
<P>
   But the chance that had been very real five and a half minutes
earlier when the score was tied had evaporated. The Blue Devils
were 30 seconds from losing to Iowa State, 88-78, in the first
round of the NCA A tournament's Midwest Regional at the Metrodome,
so looking at the scoreboard provided no hope, regardless of how
many heads popped up from the huddle.
</P>
<P>
   No one expected this game between the second-seeded Cyclones and
the 15th-seeded Blue Devils to be competitive. Central Connecticut
was behind by 19 points in the first half, and coach Howie
Dickenman warned his players that they were looking at the
possibility of a 50-point blowout. No one expected a comeback, but
it came. The comeback came because the Blue Devils (25-6) played
harder and smarter and the Cyclones (30-4), who play Auburn next,
on Saturday, relaxed too early.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had to play this game again, I wouldn't want to play
them again,'' Iowa State's Marcus Fizer said. ``They were really
anxious to beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   Iona felt the same way about Maryland. Like Central Connecticut,
the 14th-seeded Gaels were trying pull off an upset. But they were
pummeled, 74-59, to finish their season in a frustrating manner.
</P>
<P>
   When the Iowa State game was over, Fizer, the All-American who
had muscled his way to 27 points against a 2-3 matchup zone,
located the Central Connecticut starters, shook their hands and
patted them on their heads. Fizer looked exhausted with sweat
pouring off his bald head and his arms dangling by his sides. More
than exhausted, Fizer looked relieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great game,'' Fizer told the Blue Devils. ``Great game.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Central Connecticut wanted more. When Dickenman and three
players trudged into the interview area, Rick Mickens (19 points)
and Victor Payne had moist eyes and John Tice (21 points) answered
questions as if he were undergoing root canal work.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils wondered what might have happened if they had
not fallen behind by 18 points only eight minutes into the game in
their first NCAA tournament appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tied the score, 69-69, and that's all fine and dandy, but
we lost the basketball game,'' Dickenman said. ``That was a
winnable basketball game for us.''
</P>
<P>
   After Mickens streaked in for a layup to even the score, 69-69,
with 6 minutes 13 seconds left, the 50 fans who had trekked from
New Britain, Conn., to see the Blue Devils hugged and high-fived in
their seats. The Blue Devils' mascot, who was in his third game
ever because the school did not have a costume until this month,
clapped. Iowa State, not wanting to become just the fourth No.
2-seeded team to falter in the first round, frowned.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next five possessions, the Cyclones uncorked a 12-0
burst.
</P>
<P>
   Jamaal Tinsley, the Brooklyn native who did not play high school
basketball, was the reason the Cyclones prevailed, not Fizer.
</P>
<P>
   Tinsley, who slithered inside for 26 points and six assists and
also had six rebounds and four steals, started the run with a
driving layup and finished it by swishing a 3-pointer. The Cyclones
were 5 for 7 in those fateful four minutes, while the Blue Devils
were 0 for 3 with a turnover. Fizer was 0 for 0.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won the game and they kept the ball out of my hands,''
Fizer said. ``It proves it's not just me making the shots.''
</P>
<P>
   After Tomas Brookins' running 3-pointer at the buzzer sliced
Central Connecticut's deficit to nine points at halftime, Dickenman
gave an impassioned speech. He challenged his players to dive for
loose balls, to prevent transition baskets and to play defense for
35 seconds of every possession. But his team did not do enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no moral victories,'' Dickenman said. ``We came here
to win this basketball game. We didn't come to play close.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first game, Auburn built an 18-point bulge over Creighton
in the second half but then needed Mamadou N'Diaye to block Ben
Walker's 3-point attempt with 2 seconds remaining to win. The
seventh-seeded Tigers (24-9) gave the 10th-seeded Blue Jays (23-10)
a chance to even the score when Daymeon Fishback inexplicably
tossed a full-court pass to N'Diaye that sailed over the 7-footer's
head. The Blue Jays got the ball back under their basket with 3.8
seconds left. They inbounded the ball to Walker, who had to turn
and hoist up a shot that N'Diaye's long arm swatted away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game should have been over,'' Auburn coach Cliff Ellis
said. ``I'm glad that we survived.''
</P>
<P>
   Auburn played without Chris Porter, its best player, who was
suspended by the NCAA for accepting $2,500 from an agent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before the game was nine minutes old, Maryland led by 23-4. At
one point in the first half, Iona went more than nine minutes in
which the Gaels scored just one field goal. Iona shot 33.3 percent
from the field for the game, including 4 of 19 from beyond the
3-point arc. It is obvious why Maryland (25-9) romped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing the way we started,'' said coach Jeff
Ruland. ``The way we started, instead of like Cinderella, it was
more like Tinkerbell.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Gaels (20-11) chopped the deficit to nine on Tariq
Kirksay's layup with six and a half minutes remaining in the first
half, the Terrapins were never in danger of relinquishing the lead.
Maryland was bigger, quicker and more confident, which is why the
Terrapins cruised on a night when they made 21 turnovers. Terence
Morris had 22 points for Maryland, which will play the winner of
UCLA-Ball State on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   After Ruland called a timeout in the second half, he was so
disappointed that he shouted ``that's embarrassing.'' But Ruland
complimented his team after the loss for rebounding from a 6-9
start this season and praised Kirksay, who scored 24 in his final
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never gave up, we turned it around,'' said Kirksay, whose
voice choked up as he bowed his head and wept.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
