<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAY-SAINTHOOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOROTHY DAY IN FIRST STEP TO SAINTHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Vatican has approved starting the process by
which Dorothy Day, a 20th-century American pacifist and advocate
for the poor, might be canonized as a saint of the Roman Catholic
Church.
</P>
<P>
   Day, a Brooklyn native who died 20 years ago at 83, was a
founder of the Catholic Worker movement, which aided the poor and
the homeless. She lived in voluntary poverty and described herself
as a conservative in matters of the church and a radical on issues
like equal rights for blacks and opposition to war.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to begin the process toward sainthood followed a
request by Cardinal John O'Connor, archbishop of New York. It was
announced Thursday in the cardinal's column on the archdiocese's
Internet site (www.ny-archdiocese.org).
</P>
<P>
   ``With this approval comes the title Servant of God'' for Day,
he wrote. ``What a gift to the church in New York and to the church
universal this is!''
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal wrote to the Vatican on Feb. 7 to begin the lengthy
process of investigating the person's life and reviewing the
findings at the local level and in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Day converted to Catholicism in 1927, after the birth of her
daughter. Before that, in her 20s, she wrote for a Socialist
newspaper and lived a Bohemian life in New York. After her
conversion, she rejected the idea of class struggle and emphasized
the dignity of the individual.
</P>
<P>
   In 1933, with Peter Maurin, a French philosopher of peasant
background, she founded the Catholic Worker movement to aid the
poor and homeless. They opened a shelter and food distribution
center on the Lower East Side of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, O'Connor wrote that he believed Day to have been
a saint, ``a modern-day, devoted daughter of the church,'' who
wanted attention not for herself but for the work of helping the
poor. ``Much of what she spoke of in terms of social justice
anticipated the teachings of Pope John Paul II and lends support to
her cause,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal said he considered her a model for everyone, ``but
especially for women who have had or are considering abortion.''
Day had an abortion before her conversion, he wrote, adding, ``She
regretted it every day of her life.'' The conversion, he said,
demonstrated God's mercy and how one might turn from what he
described as ``the ultimate act of violence against innocent life
in the womb to a position of total holiness and pacifism.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 2334EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
