<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS BENCH WILL BE A BOOM TOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - Phil Jackson is relieved not to face a $100,000
fine for defying a league order to wear a microphone, but he's not
thrilled with the league's compromise solution - the placement of a
boom mike near the bench during timeouts.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers will have to contend with that policy Sunday, when
they play for an NBC audience against the New York Knicks at
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have gone willingly to slaughter like the rest of
these guys,'' Jackson said of refusing to wear a mike and taking
the fine, ``because it was something we had to stand up for.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson had indicated all along that he wouldn't wear a
microphone, but he hadn't faced the prospect yet. Then the league -
after heavy criticism from coaches, fans and even media - backed
off after Toronto coach Butch Carter and Seattle coach Paul
Westphal refused to wear mikes earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is wary of the boom mike but said it won't be as
effective with his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always have a mobile huddle. That's one of the things that
I've been known for,'' he said, ``so it (won't be) as intrusive in
my huddles as it has been in others, because my huddles are very
unexciting, and perhaps have the worst in the league as far as
huddles go.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson always huddles separately with his coaches - on the
floor - while the players meet near the bench, where the boom mike
would be. Then they all come together at the end of the timeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can sit with boom mikes on these players and the cameras
in their faces while they're venting or whatever's going on (among)
the teammates,'' Jackson said, ``and that's a really, pretty
private situation too, because our players are very animated to
each other, very encouraging and sometimes they're jostling with
each other or chiding each other. So I think that it still is
invasive as far as I'm concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan rules: Wizards president Michael Jordan watched his team
beat his former coach from an MCI Center luxury suite, ending a
three-week span in which he didn't attend a single game. Jordan has
endured some criticism for the absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree entirely with his position of not being here after the
(Feb. 24) trading deadline,'' Jackson said. ``He wants to see how
these players do on their own. I think him being here might
motivate them; he wants to see who's self-motivated. I can
understand that very easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Jordan: ``They all knew I was coming. If I'm here or not
here, you still got to go out and do your jobs. That's the thing
they really have to understand. If they have to wait and have me
look over their shoulders, they're not the players that I think
should represent this organization.''
</P>
<P>
   LAKERS vs. DETROIT Tipoff 5 p.m., The Palace of Auburn Hills
TV/Radio: Channel 9 (6 p.m., delay); KLAC-AM (570)
</P>
<P>
   Lakers (53-11) update: They've beaten the Pistons three times in
a row and have a six-game winning streak at Detroit. The Lakers are
17-1 on the second night of back-to-backs, winning the last 11 in a
row. Pistons (32-31) update: They've gone 6-4 over their last 10
games to creep above .500 again and are fighting for one of the
East'slast two playoff berths. Grant Hill is third in the NBA in
scoring, at 26.4 points per game, just behind Shaquille O'Neal.
-Howard Beck
</P>
</TEXT>
