<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 23:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9388 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-NCAA-MIDWEST-NYT &LR;      03-16 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-MIDWEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DEPLETED KENTUCKY TEAM GETS A BIG SCARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ With four-tenths of a second remaining in an already
improbable game stretched into one overtime, David Messiah Capers
of St. Bonaventure created an epic from that sliver of time.
</P>
<P>
   He stood alone at the line, his team trailing by three points.
Capers, a 55.6 percent free-throw shooter, had three free throws.
His Kentucky opponents threw out insults to rattle him and coach
Tubby Smith of the Wildcats called a timeout after each of his
first two shots in an attempt to ice him. But Capers calmly swished
all three to send the first-round game into double overtime. In
turn, he sent the crowd in the Cleveland State Convocation Center
into pandemonium and Kentucky's weary players searching for oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth-seeded Wildcats, making a record 41st appearance in
the N CAA men's basketball tournament, and the 12th-seeded Bonnies,
making their first trip here in 22 years, double-dared each other
all afternoon. Yet Kentucky survived the second overtime and a near
upset when the sophomore guard Tayshaun Prince, who made a
game-tying 3-pointer with eight seconds left in regulation, closed
the exhaustive contest with two free throws for an 85-80 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did not want to get out of the tournament; we did not
want to get out of the tournament,'' said Prince, who scored a
career-high 28 points. ``We just had to dig down deep and pull out
a victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky, which began the game with nine players and started the
second overtime with six players whose legs had turned to stone
pillars, leaned on its NCAA tradition to advance to the second
round against fourth-seeded Syracuse, which scored a convincing
79-65 victory over 13th-seeded Samford.
</P>
<P>
   But the day belonged to St. Bonaventure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a heck of a way to start an NCAA tournament,'' St.
Bonaventure coach Jim Baron said. ``We fought hard, we fought long
and really persevered. We're one basket away, but Kentucky made
some big, big shots.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second overtime, Jamaal Magloire hit a turnaround jumper,
Keith Bogans made a free throw and a put-back, and Prince swished
his free throws to push Kentucky past St. Bonaventure. Meanwhile,
point guard Tim Winn and his teammates came up short on their
long-range shots and J.R. Bremer missed a pair of free throws.
</P>
<P>
   But the earlier free throws from Capers captured the frantic
call and response nature of this game. ``On the foul line, we were
talking to him, saying all kinds of stuff like: `You're going to
miss this one. You don't want to win,''' Prince recalled, shaking
his head. ``We were just saying stuff to make him miss, but he
stepped up and made them all.''
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky could have prevented overtime. Five minutes into the
second half, the Wildcats held a 13-point lead before the Bonnies
launched a 23-5 run. With 1 minute 20 seconds remaining, Winn
converted a layup on a fast break following a block by his teammate
Caswell Cyrus to give the Bonnies a 63-60 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But after a missed Bonnies shot, Kentucky got the ball back and
set a double-screen for Prince. He took advantage of his wide-open
look to drain a 3-pointer with 7.1 seconds left. It was only
Kentucky's second 3-pointer of the half.
</P>
<P>
   Winn then brought the ball downcourt and drove to the basket,
but his layup just nudged off the glass, setting up the first
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky started to tire, especially when point guard Saul Smith
fouled out with less than 90 seconds remaining. Down the stretch,
the Wildcats converted just 5 of 10 free throws and allowed Winn to
convert a nifty reverse layup to bring the Bonnies within 74-73.
With eight seconds left, Magloire sank both free throws to give
Kentucky a 76-73 lead.
</P>
<P>
   St. Bonaventure inbounded the ball and got it to Capers on the
wing; with the clock running out, he launched a desperation
3-pointer as the Kentucky freshman Marvin Stone fouled him. Capers,
who had not been to the free-throw line in nine games, made the
first shot. Smith called a timeout and St. Bonaventure's players
linked arms in the huddle. Capers made the second shot and Smith
called another timeout. St. Bonaventure's players held one another
closer. ``We talked about family,'' Bonnies coach Jim Baron said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy,'' Winn said. ``You dream about situations like
that. I had that dream, only I was the one on the line. I'm glad it
was him. I was just trying to enjoy the moment, no matter what
happens, I was going to hug him the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of last season, two Kentucky players transferred,
seeking more playing time at potentially better programs. Another
player quit. Then one of Kentucky's recruits died of a heart attack
while playing in a high school game. This season, a partial
qualifier did not qualify academically, another transferred in
January, and Desmond Allison was arrested on charges of drunken
driving and possession of marijuana on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Depleted, but not defeated. ``That's been the profile of this
team,'' said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky (23-9) now gets a rematch of the 1996 national
championship game with Syracuse. The Orangemen jumped to an early
24-13 lead. After extending a seven-point halftime lead to 10
points, Samford surged back to within four. As Syracuse center Etan
Thomas sat with three quick fouls in the second half, guard Jason
Hart made up the difference.
</P>
<P>
   He gathered a steal at half court, converted the layup and
followed with a pull-up jumper that put the Orangemen up by six,
changing the momentum of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Hart sees no advantage in meeting a very tired Kentucky squad on
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only advantage that we had is that we got a victory after
a two-game losing streak,'' he said. ``I feel that everybody is
going to be emotionally high. When you're playing basketball, I
think your momentum carries you over the tiredness.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State 65, Valparaiso 38
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen minutes into its first-round game, No. 16-seeded
Valparaiso had scored just three points. Michigan State, the Big
Ten champion and a Final Four team last year, stifled the Crusaders
early with man-to-man defense and then teased them with banked-in
3-pointers and thundering alley-oop dunks. Valparaiso scored on
consecutive possessions twice all game and shot 25 percent. At
least Valparaiso beat the tournament's low scoring record by six
points.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
