<SLUG> BC-POLK-AWARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOURNALISTS IN 13 CATEGORIES ARE WINNERS OF POLK AWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By NEIL MacFARQUHAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Journalists whose work chronicled fatal medical
mistakes, pension abuse, slashed welfare rolls and death sentences
against innocent inmates were among those singled out Thursday as
recipients of the annual George Polk Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Long Island University, which administers the prize, announced
13 categories for the 1999 awards, including a career award to
Studs Terkel, 87, for his ongoing radio program and his books on
topics from the Depression to race relations.
</P>
<P>
   The National Security Archive, a private library of documents
that helps researchers in international affairs, also received a
special award for its work in obtaining documents on important
topics like Oliver North's diaries during the Iran-contra scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Among reporters, Jason DeParle of The New York Times won the
Polk Award for national reporting for his analysis of the changed
lives of welfare recipients in Wisconsin, where the rolls were
reduced 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A Polk Award for international reporting went to four
journalists at The Associated Press _ Charles J. Hanley, Martha
Mendoza, Sang-hun Choe and Randy Herschaft _ for their extensive
work unearthing a U.S. military cover-up during the Korean War.
U.S. soldiers machine-gunned hundreds of civilians under a bridge
at No Gun Ri in the war's first weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Daily News won the award for editorial writing in a
series about the grueling conditions experienced by farm laborers
cut off from the minimum wage and other benefits, and WWOR-TV in
Secaucus, N.J., better known as UPN-9 News, won the local
television reporting award for a decade of reports on racial
profiling by the police in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The Polk Awards were established in 1949 in the memory of George
W. Polk, a CBS News correspondent murdered in Greece while covering
its civil war. The formal presentation of the awards will be on
April 18 in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Winners in seven other categories were announced.
</P>
<P>
   Criminal Justice Reporting: Ken Armstrong and Steve Mills of The
Chicago Tribune, inspired by the work of Northwestern University
journalism students, reviewed every death penalty case in Illinois
and found that 12 men had been wrongly convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Medical Reporting: Andrea Gerlin of The Philadelphia Inquirer
wrote a four-part series on the thousands of deaths every year in
U.S. hospitals due to medical mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Financial Reporting: Ellen E. Schultz of The Wall Street Journal
exposed how large U.S. companies cut retirement benefits of
unsuspecting employees by altering their pension plans.
</P>
<P>
   Local Reporting: Kevin Carmody of The Daily Southtown in Tinley
Park, Ill., wrote about hundreds of people involved in developing
the A-bomb through the Manhattan Project who were exposed to a
toxic element and not alerted to its consequences for 45 years.
</P>
<P>
   Regional Reporting: Todd Richissin and Andre Chung, a
photographer, of The Baltimore Sun produced a series on the
brutality of Maryland's boot camps for juveniles convicted of
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Reporting: Paul Watson of The Los Angeles Times stayed
in Kosovo throughout the nearly three-month war there. This is the
second consecutive year The Los Angeles Times has won a foreign
reporting award for its Kosovo coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Television Foreign Reporting: A team from the British
Broadcasting Corp. in London _ Olenka Frenkiel, a reporter, Giselle
Portenier, a producer and Fiona Murch, the executive producer _
made a documentary about conservative Muslim men in rural Pakistan
who maim or kill women family members suspected of infidelity. ABC
broadcast the program in the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-16-00 2350EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
