<SLUG> BC-IRAN-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJOR OVERTURE TOWARD IRAN EXPECTED IN SPEECH BY ALBRIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will make a
major overture to Iran on Friday by announcing that the Clinton
administration will lift several sanctions on Tehran,
administration officials said Thursday night. She will also
acknowledge that the United States was shortsighted in its support
for Iraq during the Iran-Iraq war and in its involvement in a 1953
coup in Iran, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech here before a private group that seeks to promote
better ties with Iran, Albright will also announce that the United
States is ready to reach a quick agreement to unfreeze billions of
dollars in Iranian assets that have been held in the United States
since the 1979 Iranian revolution, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The speech, they said, was an effort by the administration to
promote ties with Iran after the victory last month in
parliamentary elections by moderate politicians loyal to Iran's
reformist president, Mohammad Khatami. Several of the details of
the speech were first published in The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has sought to improve relations with
Iran, which were broken off as a result of the 1979 seizure of the
U.S. Embassy in Tehran, but has been rebuffed by Khatami.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials say they hope that the recent election of so many
of Khatami's allies will offer him a new power base to stand up to
his fiercely anti-U.S. foes elsewhere in the Iranian government and
to move toward closer ties with Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a substantial speech designed to strengthen the hand of
the reformers by giving them something concrete in the form of
sanctions modification,'' said a senior administration official who
has read Albright's speech. ``I don't think we expect a quick
reaction from them. I think they'll be cautious, mild, at the
beginning. But they won't be dismissive.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials confirmed several days ago that the United States
would leave oil sanctions in place on Iran but intended to lift an
embargo on Iranian caviar, rugs, pistachio nuts and other goods.
</P>
<P>
   They said Albright's speech, which she will deliver to the
American-Iranian Council, offers a vehicle to make the announcement
and to reveal other steps intended to end two decades of hostility
between the United States and Iran.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranians may be most intrigued, they said, by Albright's
disclosure that the United States is ready to move quickly to
resolve the issue of the frozen Iranian assets, which include bank
accounts and precious metals. The United States has refused to
return the assets until there is a resolution of U.S. legal claims
made against Tehran as a result of the revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The speech is expected to review decades of U.S. involvement in
Iran. Officials said Albright would express regrets over the
involvement of the Central Intelligence Agency in the 1953 coup
that restored the monarchy.
</P>
<P>
   She will also describe U.S. support for the Iraqi government of
Saddam Hussein during the Iran-Iran war of the 1980s as
shortsighted, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
